<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SAYS MRS. CLINTON WAGES A FEAR CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio on Tuesday night accused Hillary
Rodham Clinton of waging a campaign based on fear and warned that
her latest television commercials attacking his record would
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what these attack ads are all about,'' Lazio said at a
sparsely attended fund-raiser at the Sheraton Hotel in midtown
Manhattan. ``They're about fear.'' He added, ``If these attacks
continue, my opponent will learn this about New York: Bend the
truth, and you will face the consequences. New Yorkers will not
elect a person they cannot trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's escalating attacks came in response to Clinton's
intensified criticism in recent weeks, both for his votes in
Congress and his positions on gun control, abortion and education
financing. Clinton has also released a series of television
advertisements attacking Lazio for what she says is his opposition
to legislation on hate crimes and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry to say that my opponent is now on her fifth
negative attack ad,'' Lazio said as the crowd booed the first lady.
``That makes five negative attack ads over the last 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio added that the advertisements were designed ``to fool New
Yorkers, to drag New Yorkers down.'' Then he invoked the name of
the New York senator whom he and Clinton are seeking to replace:
``You know, Pat Moynihan never needed to use attack ads like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Next he addressed his opponent: ``Maybe, Mrs. Clinton, we
shouldn't expect you to know that. Because you've never seen a New
York campaign. You've never lived here through a New York
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor in the race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, picked up
where the congressman had left off. ``I mean it really is hard when
you step back from this to completely assess the arrogance of all
this,'' Giuliani said. ``Never having lived here, never having held
public office and, `I want to be your senator?' I mean, we have to
demand more than that, don't we?'' The mayor also retooled one of
his favorite insults from his days as Clinton's opponent, aiming
again at one of Chappaqua's newest residents. ``I think what they
should do is put Rick and Hillary in an automobile at La Guardia
Airport and figure out who can actually get home on their own,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Karen Dunn, a spokeswoman for Clinton's campaign, responded:
``Rick Lazio couldn't get through his announcement speech without
attacking Hillary Clinton. It's clear that things haven't changed
much. What New Yorkers will really learn in this race is that Rick
Lazio has a voting record he can't defend.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials said the Sheraton fund-raiser and another
one for Lazio were expected to raise $1.7 million. Nonetheless, the
ballroom at the Sheraton was only a quarter full at best, and many
Republicans were asking last night whose idea it was to rent such a
large space.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton gave a detailed response to Lazio's
contention that the Clinton administration is to blame for federal
gasoline taxes that have caused higher prices at the pumps. She
argued that New York stands to lose millions of dollars in revenue
for highway construction if those taxes are suspended or repealed,
as Lazio urged by calling for the 18.3 cents per gallon federal tax
to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Buffalo it's gone up 50 cents since last year and oil
company profits have gone up almost as much as 500 percent,''
Clinton said. ``Prices are out of control for consumers and profits
are out of line for the oil companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on a campaign swing in upstate New York that also
included the Buffalo area, asked on Monday for a six-month
suspension of the 18.3 cents per gallon federal tax, and suggested
that part of it, a 4.3 cents per gallon tax enacted seven years
ago, be eliminated. He made the same suggestion at an Eastchester
gas station Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani joined the fray at a Manhattan gas station, saying a
survey of 80 city stations found an average $1.78 a gallon price
for regular.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton argued that the gas tax ``is one of the few
exceptions where we get more money back than we send to
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what New York pays in the gas tax: over $300 million
dollars a year,'' she said, holding up her charts. ``I got that
figure from my opponent's press release. And the amount that New
York state gets back from Washington in highway funding is $477
million a year. So our surplus is almost $177 million a year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
