<HEADLINE>
HIGH GAS PRICES THIS SUMMER MAY MEAN SOARING HEATING BILLS THIS
WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri is prepared to waive a rule that
prevents natural gas utilities from raising rates this summer and
is worried that a key program meant to protect consumers from price
spikes is in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   The moves _ and concerns _ are the latest sign of the trouble
that rising gas prices are beginning to play. The higher prices are
fueling increasingly gloomy predictions that consumers should
prepare for prices that could boost heating bills $200 to $300 over
the course of the upcoming winter.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators definitely are worried, said Mike Straub, assistant
manager of gas rates for the Missouri Public Service Commission,
the state's utility regulating body.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's staff told the state's gas utilities Monday
that it would accept requests to raise rates this summer to recover
unexpectedly high gas costs. Normally, the next adjustment would
not take place until November.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the commission's staff is raising questions about
the effectiveness of hedging programs used by the state's three
largest gas utilities. That includes Missouri Gas Energy, which has
484,000 customers in western Missouri, most of them in the Kansas
City area.
</P>
<P>
   The programs were expected to protect consumers from price
spikes this winter. But rising natural gas prices have played havoc
with the hedges _ a sort of ``inflation insurance'' that, for a few
dollars a customer, caps gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to buy the hedges in summer, when gas prices
usually are down. But tight supplies and utilities' increasing use
of natural gas to generate electricity have pushed wholesale prices
way up _ to about $4.50 per thousand cubic feet in the Midwest,
more than double what they were in January. So the hedges could
still cap prices, but at levels not seen since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gas Energy said Tuesday it planned to file a request to
raise its purchased gas adjustment _ the part of each customer's
bill that recovers the utility's costs for buying, storing and
transporting gas. It would be effective Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The purchased gas adjustment is at $3.91 per thousand cubic feet
but is expected to go up to about $5.50 if the Public Service
Commission approves. That would increase a customer's gas bill just
a few dollars until November. But with the heavier gas use that
comes with winter heating _ and the possibility of an even higher
purchased gas adjustment in November _ households could be out
hundreds of extra dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gas Energy said it was also considering changes in its
hedging program. The high gas prices are also raising the cost of
buying the hedges. Among the possibilities under review are
reducing the amount of gas that would be hedged _ even at higher
prices than last year _ or raising the amount of money spent on the
caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to assume is that the prices we are seeing now
are going to stay with us,'' said Rob Hack, a vice president with
Missouri Gas.
</P>
<P>
   Other Missouri utilities are also readying proposals. Laclede
Gas in St. Louis said it would request an increase in the purchased
gas adjustment this summer but was still considering the amount to
raise it.
</P>
<P>
   Rising gas prices are also forcing changes in other states,
including Kansas. Kansas Gas Service has asked that state's
regulators to boost the amount it spends on hedging from $3.5
million to $8 million. And it will also make some changes in how
the program caps prices, said Steve Johnson, a spokesman for the
Kansas utility.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Information Administration recently said it expected
natural-gas prices to remain high into next year, when more
production should ease the tight supply.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, the rising prices are putting to the test various
reforms put in place three years ago after price spikes caused
heating bills to soar.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Missouri utilities could frequently change the
purchased gas adjustment to recover the cost of gas. Missouri
limited those changes to two times a year, plus a third adjustment
that could be made in winter if prices changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Under those rules, that would have meant no more changes until
Nov. 1. But Straub said gas prices had risen so fast that utilities
would have had to recover much of their costs beginning in
November, when bills are usually going up anyway to cover heating
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The largest change was the hedging program. But now, if current
prices hold, the hedges will be above the $5.81 purchased gas
adjustment that occurred in the price spikes of early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That also poses a dilemma. Do the utilities go ahead and hedge
to protect customers from prices that could spike to $7 or $8 per
thousand cubic feet? Or do they save the estimated $5 to $10 per
customer charge of the hedging program?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' said David Sommerer, the head of the Public
Service Commission's gas procurement division. ``The question is
whether a hedge still makes sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
