<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT MARLINS, 5-2, FOR 6TH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what has become a midseason pennant race if not a
morality play, the Mets mowed down still another victim Tuesday
night and began to set the table for the four-game visit by the
Atlanta Braves that starts Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Glendon Rusch helped extend the Mets' winning streak to six
games by pitching deep into the eighth inning of a 5-2 victory over
the Florida Marlins at Shea Stadium. John Franco and Armando
Benitez finished up.
</P>
<P>
   As significant as the streak is, though, is the fact that the
Mets chopped still another game off the Braves' lead in National
League East. It is down to two games, with the Mets facing the
Marlins again Wednesday night before the theatrics start.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch allowed only five hits and no walks. But with two out in
the Florida eighth, his 5-2 lead was in jeopardy as he yielded a
single to Mark Kotsay after another Marlin reached base on an
error.
</P>
<P>
   Franco came on and handcuffed Cliff Floyd, who hit a bouncer to
first but beat the throw to Franco, who was covering the bag. Now,
with the bases loaded and the Mets leading by three runs, Preston
Wilson, the Marlins' top power hitter, took his stance.
</P>
<P>
   Franco got the count to 1-2 and then threw a fastball past the
flailing Wilson. Franco pumped his arm and dashed off the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez took over in the ninth and got the save, his 18th of the
season, as the shadow of the Braves loomed closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us,'' center fielder Jay Payton said, ``are talking
about the Braves among ourselves. It just hasn't come up in
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusch (6-5) was formidable over the first three innings. After
mowing down the first eight batters, he was touched for a single
when the opposing pitcher, Jesus Sanchez, bunted along the
third-base line and beat the throw to first.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Mora immediately produced a highlight-film dive to end
the inning. The shortstop pounced to his left to snare Luis
Castillo's sharp grounder up the middle, set himself and then
shoveled the ball to second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo for the
forceout.
</P>
<P>
   But Rusch was not so lucky in the Florida fourth. Kotsay and
Floyd got on with a single and double, and both scored on sacrifice
flies _ Wilson driving in Kotsay and Mike Lowell knocking in Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets responded with a sacrifice fly of their own in their
half of the inning. They loaded the bases on a single and two
walks. Payton lofted a fly to short right, Kotsay grabbed it and
threw home, in what appeared to be enough time to get Derek Bell,
running from third.
</P>
<P>
   But the ball died, and reached Marlins catcher Mike Redmond on a
few hops. As Redmond bent to pick it up, Bell barreled into him,
knocking the ball loose and giving the Mets their first run of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani drilled a single past short, scoring Alfonzo to
tie the game, and the Mets then took the lead on Todd Pratt's
groundout that scored Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Joe McEwing delivered the Mets' third hit of the inning, a
single that scored Agbayani for a 4-2 edge.
</P>
<P>
   The outburst made up for the Mets' frustrations the first two
innings, which ended in double plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added a fifth run in the seventh when Mora hit his
second double of the game and scored on Alfonzo's needle-threading
single to the right side off reliever Braden Looper.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine's lineup lacked his regular Nos. 4 and 5
hitters. Robin Ventura, who normally bats fifth, was on the bench
because of what was described as a sore shoulder; he hurt it diving
for a ball in Monday's game. And the Mets' cleanup hitter, Mike
Piazza, was given a rest, presumably to prepare him for the
four-game series against Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
