<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TRIES TO HEAD OFF FOREIGN SUITORS FOR SPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Sprint Corp.'s intended merger with WorldCom all
but died Tuesday in Washington, lawmakers tried to head off
potential foreign suitors for Sprint and called for hearings on the
growing complexity of communications pacts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Department of Justice lawsuit to block the merger
brought only light criticism from Kansas City region lawmakers,
with the exception of Missouri's Sen. John Ashcroft. An Ashcroft
spokesman called the government intervention ``distressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not aimed directly at Sprint, a bill sponsored by five
Democratic senators sought to keep American telecommunication firms
from being purchased by companies that have at least 25 percent
foreign government ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom, owned by German and French
governments, respectively, are looking at U.S. companies, said Sen.
Fritz Hollings of South Carolina, ranking Democrat on the Senate
Commerce Committee. Deutsche Telekom is seen as a potential bidder
for Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings said successful efforts by the U.S. government to
enhance domestic competition plays into hands of foreign interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be facilitating the ease by which foreign-protected
players may emerge with key U.S. assets,'' Hollings said in a news
release. ``While our efforts to foster competition have benefited
consumers, these efforts have depressed the earnings and stock
prices of U.S. domestic providers. However, many of our foreign
counterparts have consistently worked to provide advantages for
their government-owned companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollings also envisioned potential national security risks if
foreign powers owned U.S. telecommunications assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``To permit a foreign government to own such assets would raise
too many troubling questions,'' Hollings said.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsors of the Hollings bill are Dan Inouye of Hawaii, Jay
Rockefeller of West Virginia, John Kerry of Massachusetts and Byron
Dorgan of North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   In the House on Tuesday, a telecommunications subcommittee
recommended the Commerce Committee hold a hearing on mergers and
the role of the Justice Department, said Rep. Karen McCarthy, a
Kansas City, Mo., Democrat and subcommittee member.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just so many dramatic changes, things we couldn't
have envisioned or contemplated,'' McCarthy said, giving the growth
in broadband cable access as an example.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said the Sprint-WorldCom merger is an example of the
growing complexity of the telecommunications business in that it
encompassed phone service, Internet access and data network
services.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy did not take a position on the merger and had no
reaction Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was in the hands of the federal regulators to
decide,'' McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Moore, a Johnson County, Kan., Democrat whose 3rd
District is home to Sprint headquarters in Westwood, also hadn't
taken a position on the merger. He said Tuesday he was confident
Sprint would continue to be a strong local business.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ike Skelton, a Democrat from Lexington, Mo., whose district
is home to some Sprint employees and offices, said he favored the
merger and is disappointed it won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it probably would have been a good thing for both
Sprint and WorldCom,'' Skelton said. ``They would have been able to
touch more telecommunications bases and enlarge their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican, said in November at a Judiciary
Committee hearing that he was ``strongly inclined'' to support the
merger. He said it ``promises to be a winner for Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Harris, Ashcroft's press secretary, said Tuesday that the
merger would have strengthened Sprint's presence in Kansas City for
years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint is a cornerstone of Kansas City's economy,'' Harris
said. ``It is distressing that government lawyers in Washington
think they are better able to shape Sprint's future than (are) the
people of Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is seeking re-election and is among many candidates who
have received contributions from Sprint's political action
committee. Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican who also received
support from Sprint, took no stand on the merger but said through a
spokesman Tuesday he was confident ``Sprint will continue to be
innovative and be at the top of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican who is on the Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee, had reservations about the
merger last fall and offered no comment Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
