r b BC-CONSUMERS-SPRINT-KAN &LR;      06-28 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERS-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER GROUPS APPLAUD JUSTICE DEPARTMENT; FOES CRITICIZE
OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ To consumer groups, the Justice Department's
lawsuit to block the merger of WorldCom Inc. and Sprint Corp. was a
no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   But to critics, the Justice Department showed it lacked a brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an easy merger to say no to,'' said Mark Cooper, a
spokesman for the Consumer Federation of America, which opposed the
consolidation of the two largest long-distance companies behind
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper and other consumer group spokesmen said Tuesday the $129
billion combination would whittle competition, smother innovation
and ultimately pump up telephone service costs to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That's also how the government saw what was the largest merger
in history at the time it was announced last October.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Joel I. Klein said Tuesday if
WorldCom acquired Sprint, ``large and small businesses and millions
of individual consumers would have to pay higher prices and accept
lower service quality and innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogwash, critics of the Justice Department responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crystal-ball gazing at its worst,'' said Adam Thierer,
an economics policy fellow at the Heritage Foundation. ``One would
have thought that they'd have allowed it (the merger) to play out
and see what the results would be first.''
</P>
<P>
   The harsh differences in opinion in how consumers might be
affected turn on how one defines the future of telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates saw immediate dangers in a merger that would
reduce from three to two the number of major competitors in the
U.S. long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   They said historically it takes at least three, and probably
more, thriving competitors to keep costs low to consumers, to
prevent collusion and allow new competitors to freely enter into
the market.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, leniency by the Justice Department and the
Federal Communications Commission had prompted a juggernaut of
giant consolidations in the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T spawned seven sibling
regional Bell phone companies, they evolved into just three huge
regional Bell operating companies through an assortment of
expensive mergers, all approved by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't surprising that Sprint and WorldCom felt the need to
join the consolidation binge,'' said David Butler, a spokesman for
Consumers Union, which publishes Consumer Reports magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The action taken Tuesday by the Justice Department was ``a
signal of the beginning of stronger anti-trust enforcement,''
Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates reject the bigger-is-better argument made by
Sprint and WorldCom, that the merger was necessary to create a new
company with the muscle to battle in a new arena of behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   They also reject the notion that telecommunications is fast
becoming a one-package delivery system, rather than one that is
broken into long-distance companies and local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   A one-size-fits-all industry is a fiction, argues William G.
Shepherd, an economics professor at the University of Massachusetts
in Amherst and general editor of the Review of Industrial
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper in May for the Economic Policy Institute, Shepherd
wrote that the evidence ``to support these hyperbolic claims is
insufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, if Sprint and WorldCom were allowed to merge,
``The main competitive pressures on these two long-distance
battlers _ the rivalry between them _ will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of innovation is likely to slow, as will the decline
in costs across the variety of their activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, WorldCom and Sprint would combine their 24 percent
and 12 percent shares of the long-distance market into a 36 percent
share.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T would hold 43 percent. The remaining 21 percent, Shepherd
said, would be held by ``the scores of generic non-brand fringe
firms.''
</P>
<P>
   But the critics of the Justice Department action say consumer
groups are relying on 1960s economics to predict the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department is taking prescriptive action rather
than reacting,'' said Thierer. ``How can they predict the outcome
of this merger in today's fast-paced telecommunications industry?''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he said, the difference between long-distance and local
delivery will be meaningless to consumers. ``The relevant market is
the full market of services. It's the broadband delivery of
services.'' How, he asked, can WorldCom and Sprint compete
separately with AT&AMP;T in this new environment that was encouraged to
grow?
</P>
<P>
   John Hoffman, former legal counsel for Sprint and author of a
new book on the history of Sprint, titled Was That a Pin?, said the
action by the Justice Department is ironic.
</P>
<P>
   He said it seemed strange to halt this merger after the
government had already allowed ``the regional Bell operating
companies to re-create the Bell monopoly'' through a series of
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not looking forward. They're looking backward,'' he
said. He said the regional Bell companies are already emerging as
competitors in long distance in New York and possibly soon in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next handful of years, people won't see the difference
between local and long distance,'' he said. ``That's happening now
in the wireless industry and on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, consumer advocates say the Justice Department is
justified in slowing down the furious stampede toward mergers that
have lately typified the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reflection that the government is getting tougher on
some of these large mergers,'' said Albert Foer, president of the
American Antitrust Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a merger that probably wouldn't even have been attempted
in years past. It pushed the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some markets you have to be large,'' Foer said. ``But the
question is how large? And at what point does size benefit or harm
society?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
