<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 After merger bogs down, WorldCom Inc. could become takeover
target  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WorldCom Inc., a perennial aggressor through scores of mergers
engineered by Chief Executive Bernard J. Ebbers, suddenly looks
like a potential takeover target itself.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agreed Tuesday that with its $129 billion merger
with Sprint Corp. in trouble, WorldCom suddenly looks attractive.
Indeed, some of the same companies cited as possible suitors for
Sprint may well take a look at WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both WorldCom and Sprint would be put in play, and we believe
the large European operators which are trading at premium'' prices
would act quickly to make an offer while their stock prices are
high, Eric Strumingher, telecommunications analyst with
PaineWebber, predicted last week as trouble brewed for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, WorldCom remained mum Tuesday after the Department
of Justice announced its lawsuit to block the merger. Separately,
the two companies withdrew their merger application before the
European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``WorldCom will promptly review its options with Sprint,''
according to a statement by WorldCom General Counsel Michael
Salsbury.
</P>
<P>
   While a quick takeover of WorldCom is unlikely, some analysts
said a final collapse of the proposed merger with Sprint might make
WorldCom rethink its direction.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom must figure out if it can find another company to buy
that would provide the wireless operation it does not have. Another
option would be to back out of residential communications and
concentrate on the more lucrative corporate business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be the first to say WorldCom has been searching for a
wireless strategy and may not be able to pull that off,'' said John
Kwoka, professor of economics at George Washington University.
Having failed to earlier buy wireless provider Nextel and now
Sprint, they might give up on residential all together, Kwoka said.
</P>
<P>
   The question then becomes what would happen if WorldCom sold off
its residential long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feds wanted three viable competitors. That's why they
blocked the Sprint//WorldCom deal,'' Kwoka said. ``But would
(WorldCom's) business end up in the hands of a strong enough player
to preserve that competition?''
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent, WorldCom faces problems of its own making.
Ebbers molded the company by buying up about 75 other companies,
eliminating potential competitors in long distance and Internet
services all along the way.
</P>
<P>
   For the immediate future, the consolidation of Sprint and
WorldCom would have left business and home telephone long-distance
users with only two viable choices. It also would have given
WorldCom a huge concentration in the telephone lines carrying
Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each business sector that has featured a great deal of
consolidation, the next deal that goes through the pipeline gets a
closer look and faces greater problems,'' said William Kovacic, a
law professor at George Washington University Law School. ``That is
particularly true where the number of suppliers falls from four to
three, or three to two.''
</P>
<P>
   The WorldCom deal also was proposed at a time that regulators
have been re-evaluating some of their earlier approvals for
missteps. Regulators have been assessing whether previous efforts
to keep competition alive by making companies sell off some of
their merged operations had the intended affect.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission Chairman Robert Pitofsky made the
observation in February that the government was not justified in
repeating a mistake if an earlier restructuring failed to provide
adequate competition. Speaking about an FTC study, he said the
agency found when companies divested some of their business
operations, ostensibly to preserve competition, they sometimes
picked weak buyers and then undermined them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mario Monti, chief antitrust regulator for the European
Union, said an earlier WorldCom deal had left a sour taste in the
mouth of European regulators.
</P>
<P>
   When WorldCom and MCI merged in 1998, the merging companies
agreed to sell MCI's Internet business to Britain-based Cable &AMP;
Wireless Inc. for $1.75 billion, along with the customer contracts,
employees, assets and services that would allow it to replace MCI
as a competitor in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Cable &AMP; Wireless later sued, alleging WorldCom failed to
transfer all its customers, customer information and personnel, and
failed to provide all the services and support to operate the
business. WorldCom settled the lawsuit for $200 million in March.
</P>
<P>
   The spoiling of the Sprint and WorldCom deal also comes at a
time when the heat of enthusiasm seems to be dissipating on media
mergers. Two major media mergers now under attack are America
Online with Time Warner and AT&AMP;T with MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have urged the U.S. government and the Europeans
to investigate the deals more closely. The European Union last week
said it would spend the next four months giving the America Online
and Time Warner merger a going over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ironic that while the U.S. went twice to save the
Europeans (in the world wars) that the EU is now coming to save our
Internet,'' said Jeff Chester with the Center for Media Education,
which has urged European Union review. The center is a consumer
organization promoting competition on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the tide is turning against massive
consolidation but I think it is no longer business as usual.
Regulators realize that what they are deciding upon is the future
of the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
