<HEADLINE>
POSSIBILITY OF SHAREHOLDER LAWSUITS LOOMS FOR SPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER and DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The final collapse of WorldCom Inc.'s bid to
buy Sprint Corp., if and when it comes, could spark shareholder
lawsuits and an exodus of managers at the Westwood, Kan., company,
both linked to the accelerated vesting of employee stock options.
</P>
<P>
   When Sprint shareholders approved the WorldCom deal April 28,
they also approved a provision that immediately vested stock
options worth as much as $1.7 billion to Sprint executives and
employees, even if WorldCom never completed the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   What was unusual in Sprint's case was that the benefit, which
would have otherwise taken employees years to accrue, occurred when
shareholders approved the merger in April, rather than when the
deal actually went through.
</P>
<P>
   It was also unusual that in a deal of this magnitude and
complexity, in which regulators had obvious antitrust concerns,
shareholders voted before such concerns were resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that provision is uncommon,'' said lawyer Vickie
Westerhaus of Shook Hardy &AMP; Bacon, who deals with mergers and
acquisitions and securities law. ``It's entirely possible
shareholders would be concerned about that.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Richard Devlin, Sprint's general counsel, acknowledged
Tuesday that Sprint could face shareholder lawsuits over the issue,
but said its exposure was minimal given the disclosure of options
vesting plans in the companies' merger proxy.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for accelerating options is to give key executives
and employees _ possibly concerned about their jobs post-merger _
an incentive to help the deal proceed. Otherwise, the executives
and employees conceivably could help block a deal that benefits
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But in Sprint's case, the provision may have had the opposite
effect, turning the company's golden handcuffs into a golden
handshake.
</P>
<P>
   Already, five top managers at the company have jumped ship. They
are Kevin Brauer, president of national integrated services; Andrew
Sukawaty, president of Sprint PCS; Theodore Schell, senior vice
president of strategic planning; Thomas Weigman, senior vice
president of consumer market strategy and communications; and Paget
Alves, president of sales and sales support for Sprint Business.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer filed this week to sell about $30 million worth of Sprint
stock, much of which he accumulated as part of management stock
option plans. As much as $15 million of the value of his stock was
accelerated as a result of the merger vote by shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Chief Executive William T. Esrey addressed the departures
in a note to employees, saying: ``You must be asking yourselves,
`Do they know something I don't?' and `Should I be worried?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I am disappointed that executives have chosen to
leave. Many are longtime friends, and all have contributed to make
Sprint successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey went on to reassure employees that the company had a deep
pool of talent and was on the right path strategically. The
executives' choice to leave, he said, was driven by other
opportunities, a re-evaluation of their personal goals, and their
professional and financial success at Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, those choices, and the role of accelerated options
in them, could well become the target of shareholder lawsuits in
the wake of the merger's seeming collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If management takes the accelerated options and chooses to
walk away, that obviously could hurt the future and the value of
the company,'' Westerhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what shareholders of Northrop Grumman charged
when the company's proposed merger with Lockheed was scuttled after
regulators threatened to block the deal on antitrust grounds. Like
Sprint's, Northrop's stock options accelerated when shareholders
approved that merger, triggering $150 million to $160 million in
stock awards and payments to company executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We claimed they were unjustly enriched,'' said San Diego
lawyer Randall Baron, who represented the shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Wrobley, a corporate lawyer with Blackwell Sanders Peper
Martin, said he didn't think a shareholder suit alleging Sprint
failed to get the best possible deal for shareholders would get
very far. But Wrobley said the stock option provision might present
``a clear opportunity to question the economics of the vesting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's billions of dollars of options, obviously that's a
target,'' Wrobley said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger has already attracted lawsuits alleging that
shareholders had not been sufficiently informed about the deal ``in
a timely manner'' and that its terms had discouraged bidding by
other possible buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine the millions of dollars that were spent here _ on
investment bankers, lawyers, accountants and the like _ and
obviously if they couldn't even get past the staff report at the
Justice Department, you've got to think it was an ill-conceived
deal,'' said lawyer T. Bradley Manson, who represented plaintiffs
in one of the earlier lawsuits seeking to block the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Whether shareholders find the stock option provision another
reason to sue remains an open question. But given the amount of
money at issue and the litigious atmosphere that often surrounds
big mergers, experts say they'd be surprised if no lawsuits were
filed over the provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line in this case,'' Westerhaus said, ``is that you
had two major players here, operating in the same market, offering
many of the same products. So from the start everyone there had to
know they would be testing the limits with this merger. It's the
same type of situation as the Northrop case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
