<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ACTION DERAILS SPRINT-WORLDCOM MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER and KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending months of speculation that the largest telecommunication
merger in history would fail regulatory scrutiny, the Department of
Justice on Tuesday sued to block WorldCom Inc.'s proposed $129
billion buyout of Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno and Joel I. Klein, assistant
attorney general of the Justice Department's antitrust division,
announced the lawsuit Tuesday morning in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Digging in their department's heels, Reno and Klein charged that
the merger would lead to diminished service, less innovation and
higher prices for millions of consumers and businesses, undermining
the competitive gains achieved since the breakup of the AT&AMP;T's
telephone monopoly in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   If the combination of the nation's second and third biggest long
distance companies was allowed to go forward, Reno said,
``consumers and businesses would pay the price because competition
would be reduced in many important telecommunications markets.''
</P>
<P>
   She cited a laundry list of examples in a 65-page lawsuit filed
Tuesday, including the prospect of higher prices for domestic and
international long distance, Internet services, private line, data
and custom network services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from the Big Three telecom companies _ WorldCom, Sprint
and AT&AMP;T _ to the Big Two would be like giving customers the wrong
number,'' Reno said. ``We must continue to go forward toward
greater competition and greater innovation, not backward toward the
telecom monopoly of yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Though widely expected, the scope and vigor of regulators'
objections revealed the gaping chasm between the companies' public
statements that the deal was on track for regulatory approval by
fall, and regulators' less sanguine analysis of the deal's
implications.
</P>
<P>
   Based on statements Tuesday, the companies have made no headway
in convincing regulators that the deal was pro-competitive, or
necessary to head off emerging competitive forces in the cable and
local telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement, as well as the stances and actions taken by
Justice throughout the merger process, has left me frustrated and
disappointed,'' wrote Sprint Chairman William T. Esrey, in a letter
to employees. He was not available for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is by far the largest that Justice has sought to
block, and the decision to go forward with a suit stands in
contrast to the other telecommunications mega-mergers that have
passed muster in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint, the largest private-sector employer in the
Kansas City, Mo., area, said they would be reviewing their options
with Justice over the next few days. But they withdrew their merger
application in Europe on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies can fight Justice's suit, and under their merger
agreement they are obligated to do so unless they mutually agree to
terminate the deal. Given the time and uncertain outcome of
fighting the case, handling appeals, then getting necessary
approvals from the European Commission and the Federal
Communications Commission, most observers think the likelihood of
resurrecting this merger in another form is almost nil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely this merger is over,'' said Mel Marten, a
telecommunications analyst with Edward Jones in St. Louis. ``Both
companies will be seeking other alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   William E. Kennard, who is chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, backed Justice's lawsuit Tuesday in a
two-paragraph statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud today's action by the Department of Justice to
preserve competition and protect consumers,'' Kennard said. ``In my
view, American consumers are better served if these companies
continue to compete rather than combine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of the WorldCom merger, Sprint will likely be
looking to fill the void in its available services through another
merger, adding international reach through a combination with a
foreign carrier like Deutsche Telekom, or connections to local
consumers through a domestic partner like BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the company will be trying to stem the
defection of senior managers, who have already seen their stock
options vest as a result of the shareholder vote approving the
merger, and have little incentive to stay with the company in a
period of upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint has a telecom headhunter bulls-eye all over it,'' said
Scott Cleland, an analyst with the Precursor Group in Washington,
D.C. ``Every telecom headhunter has Sprint as target one.''
</P>
<P>
   While WorldCom officials refused to comment in detail on
Justice's suit, senior executives at Sprint expressed amazement
with regulators' inflexibility and lack of responsiveness during
their nearly nine-month investigation.
</P>
<P>
   They also professed to be astonished with the concessions
regulators reportedly demanded to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did regulators insist that Sprint sell its entire long
distance and Internet businesses to assuage competitive concerns,
but also its local telephone business, which operates in 18 states
across the country, Sprint said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why,'' said J. Richard Devlin, Sprint's general
counsel. ``The DOJ has always asserted that stand-alone long
distance is a discrete antitrust market. All of the sudden
requiring us to sell local implies they don't even believe their
own theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Devlin said the problem all along was getting feedback from
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very much a one way process,'' he said. ``Despite
efforts to draw the department out, we were in the dark trying to
understand body language and signals, and frankly, the appearance
of caring.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey, in his letter to employees, said that the divestitures
required ``were clearly unacceptable and not in our best
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said he was vexed MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
