<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6888 &Cx1f; kan-z
r b BC-SPRINT-MERGER-2NDTAKE     06-28 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ACTION DERAILS SPRINT-WORLDCOM MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER and KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ...not in our best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said he was vexed by regulators' apparent fixation on
market share information from 1998, and lack of focus on where the
industry was headed in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only draw the conclusion that the Justice Department has
either missed or discounted the changes occurring in the
communications industry,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the investigation the companies said they
provided more than 3,670 boxes of documents, numerous CD-ROMs and
4,209 pages of answers and responses to more than 10 informal
requests for information from regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives, including Esrey, also made more than 25
detailed presentations to regulators in an effort to explain their
business.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, they said the Department of Justice declined to
engage in any discussion of the basis for its conclusions, refusing
even to share the economic models it used to calculate the mergers
effect on long distance pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Klein declined to discuss any talks the companies had with the
department to resolve the competitive concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my position has always been that a negotiated
resolution, a settlement between the parties in all matters, is
preferable to litigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' he said, ``there is no resolution that the parties
have proposed to us that addresses the full range of competitive
concerns at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein said the lawsuit does not signal similar reluctance to
approve other mergers down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it signals is what it's always signaled _ that the
department takes these cases one at a time...,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Devlin called the Justice's lawsuit ``a kitchen sink kind of
complaint'' that left the impression of a complex and convoluted
case that would take a judge forever to work through.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality it's a pretty simple case,'' Devlin said. ``It's
about three things: recognizing marketplace realities, looking
forward instead of backwards and protecting consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a tactical issue, it was a strategic mistake of
thinking long-standing antitrust boundaries no longer applied in
the new economy,'' said Cleland, the analyst. ``When you go from
three to two competitors in a market, the government is more
concerned about consumers than shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the mergers apparent demise met with mixed reaction
among Sprint's roughly 20,000 employees in the Kansas City area.
Some were concerned that it would lead to further uncertainty, and
undermine the price of Sprint shares, lowering their net worth.
</P>
<P>
   Other employees, many of whom uncomfortable with WorldCom as a
new parent from day one, felt like shouting for joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, it's quite a sight to see people popping up out
of their cubicles and giving high fives over the top of them,''
said one Sprint employee, who asked not to be identified for
reasons of job security.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's stock was down slightly in trading Tuesday. Most
analysts think it will drop into the mid 50s in the wake of a
failed merger.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Maria Kovacs, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott LLC,
downgraded Sprint's FON stock from ``accumulate'' to ``hold'' on
Tuesday, saying ``it's reasonable to expect a period of uncertainty
for Sprint in its entirety and for FON Group in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   Marten, the analyst at Edward Jones, said Sprint is likely to be
bought by another company, but questioned whether any company would
be willing to pay the $76 a share that WorldCom offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one else would have as great a cost savings and revenue
synergies,'' Marten said. ``Any new offers will be above the
current price but not as high as WorldCom's offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ferrugia, an analyst with A.G. Edwards in St. Louis,
concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have been one of the best possible transactions
that Sprint could have negotiated, which is why Bill Esrey chose it
in the first place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he feels Sprint is probably worth $70 a share and
will eventually wind up being part of a larger entity.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, most analysts point to Deutsche Telekom, Sprint's
former partner in the failed international venture, Global One, as
its most likely partner. The German giant is flush with cash from
recent asset sales, debt and stock offerings, and is intent on
acquiring a presence in the U.S. that includes an Internet and
wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Sprint, which owns the fastest-growing wireless
business in the U.S. and one of the top four Internet backbones in
the world, an appetizing target. Deutsche Telekom already owns 10
percent of the company dating from the Global One deal, and may be
ready to expand that stake.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sommer, chief executive of Deutsche Telekom, recently left
no doubt about his company's interest in global expansion.
</P>
<P>
   A global telecommunications company ``needs to be equally footed
in Europe and the United States,'' Sommer said. ``If you look at
the market capitalization of Deutsche Telekom today versus any
American potential acquisition candidate, nobody is out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Other potential international suitors include France Telekom and
Nippon Telephone &AMP; Telegraph, although they are considered less
likely partners; the French because they are wrapped up in other
deals, the Japanese company because there are legal limits on its
ability to issue shares in an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic front runner is BellSouth, whose $100 billion offer
for Sprint in October was topped by WorldCom. Buying Sprint would
add needed competitive muscle for the Atlanta-based regional bell
company, which has been absent from the acquisition spree among
fellow Ma Bell offspring Bell Atlantic and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth might need to outbid European suitors and would
face regulatory scrutiny, as it is still banned from offering long
distance services to its own customers.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts think a foreign buyer would be the best scenario
for local employees, as the new owner would have no presence in the
U.S. and little incentive to cut jobs. Still, analysts say the only
certainty for the time being is uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent telecommunications analyst in
Atlanta, ``Bill Esrey better put his fishing pole back in the
closet because he's going to be at the helm of Sprint for a while
longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
