r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-28 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHT RAIL WOULD HURT BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The forgotten constituency in the debate over
whether a light-rail mass transit system is a good idea for Kansas
City involves those whose livelihoods would be most affected by the
project.
</P>
<P>
   What of the Kansas Citians whose businesses would be adjacent to
a light-rail link's right of way?
</P>
<P>
   This question is rarely addressed, but always much on the minds
of community members such as Gregory B. Allen. Nearly four years
ago, when Allen was president of the Broadway Area Association, his
group issued a position paper questioning the wisdom of pursuing a
light-rail vision for Kansas City. Its thrust tried to focus
community attention on the discombobulation that construction and
operation would wreak on the affected business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughfares that are home to many businesses, the position
paper warned, ``would be drastically transformed by rail transit to
a use never before contemplated.'' Not only would the capacity for
vehicle traffic become drastically limited, but access to the
businesses and parking would be diminished.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, governments routinely pursue projects that
discombobulate neighborhoods in the name of progress and serving a
greater community good. In this case, however, it's difficult to
make the greater-good case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk to existing assets must be justified by benefits,''
the Broadway Area Association's brief noted, ``and the benefits
must be demonstrated with convincing and detailed data.''
</P>
<P>
   The association has since merged with the Westport Improvement
Association to form the Broadway-Westport Council, Allen said, but
the ``risk to existing assets'' is as significant a concern today
as it was in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When the latest initiative to revive the light-rail dream
surfaced, Allen was prompted to ask, ``How much tax base must we
isolate from left turns, convenient parking and reasonable access
before the would-be straphangers are satisfied? ... How much more
business will we run off to the suburbs before our urban hormones
are sated?''
</P>
<P>
   What is most remarkable about local light-rail advocates is
their willingness to concede to themselves the all-encompassing
rightness of their cause. It's as if no other interests exist
except those served by pursuit of their goal.
</P>
<P>
   Economic considerations are of no apparent concern, and the huge
amounts of money involved seem an abstraction. Cost-benefit
relationships, therefore, are unimportant. Nor do facts seem to
matter. While mass transit may serve a critical role in a few of
America's larger cities, it certainly seems a stretch to pretend
its expansion in scope here is vital to Kansas City's future
well-being. As one observer asked me recently: If justifiable
demand is there, why aren't local transit operations ordering more
buses?
</P>
<P>
   Advocates, nevertheless, rule the debate because they are vocal
and dedicated. Meanwhile, the voices of stakeholders such as Allen,
who has owned a business in midtown for 20 years, get drowned out,
which isn't a healthy thing. This column is an effort to balance
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anything more dangerous to the health of this
community,'' Allen recently wrote, ``than building two-track
railroads in exclusive rights of way down our leading commercial
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
