</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS NIP YANKEES, 7-6 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The New York Yankees were considered a great team the
last time David Cone won a game, on April 28. They could enter
Chicago's Comiskey Park or play the Tigers, or just about any
American League team, and they were feared.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Cone won a game, the Yankees had a .650 winning
percentage. No one thought they would need Juan Gonzalez or Sammy
Sosa. They were favorites to repeat as World Series champions.
Chuck Knoblauch's throwing problems were dormant, their pitching
rotation was deep, the lineup considered potent.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been two months since Cone's last victory and the
Yankees are just three games over .500, after Cone collapsed in the
fifth inning, allowed five runs and blew a lead. The Yankees
(37-34) came back from a three-run deficit to tie the game in the
eighth, but lost to the Tigers, 7-6, in 11 innings, when Derek
Jeter's error set up the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera came out of the bullpen to pitch the 11th inning
for the Yankees, and Bobby Higginson led off with a single for
Detroit. Bernie Williams made a sliding catch on a looping fly ball
hit by Gonzalez, but when Shane Halter hit a ground ball to Jeter
at short with Higginson moving, the grounder skipped off Jeter's
glove, his 10th error this year. The ball rolled into short left
field, and Higginson took third.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees elected to play their middle infield back and try
for the double play, and when Robert Fick rolled a grounder toward
shortstop, Higginson hustled for the plate. Jeter threw home, to
catcher Chris Turner, who tried blocking Higginson but dropped the
ball. For an instant, the ball sat on the ground and Higginson
stood next to the plate, neither he nor Turner realizing the umpire
was waiting to make the call. Higginson jabbed a foot on the plate
quickly, barely beating Turner and ending the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are unconfident, nagged by injuries, playing badly.
They need a stimulant _ perhaps an emotional victory or a
regenerated rotation, or Sosa. In the last quarter of the season,
the Yankees are 15-25, a performance level that would translate
into 100 defeats over a full season.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez went hitless in four at-bats and was booed thickly in
his first game since the proposed trade that would have sent him to
the Yankees fell through. Cone made the All-Star team last year and
with two starts remaining before the All-Star break, his record is
1-6, and hasn't won in his last 10 starts. He had a great chance to
snap that streak on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored three runs in the fourth inning, the last two
runs on singles by Jose Vizcaino and Jeter. Cone had a good slider
and a decent fastball, 86-88 miles an hour, and although Tony Clark
homered to lead off the fourth, Cone pitched out of further trouble
in that inning. The Tigers were hitless in seven at-bats with
runners in scoring position in the first four innings, the
continuation of a recent trend for Cone; to that point, he had
allowed just two hits in opponents' last 23 at-bats with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees filled the bases in the fifth inning with two hits
and a walk, and there was nobody out, before Ricky Ledee whiffed.
Then Turner, who has become Cone's personal catcher, hit a grounder
up the middle. Damion Easley dove to his right to intercept the
ball, flipped to shortstop Deivi Cruz for a force at second, and
Cruz turned and threw to first. It was easy to see, from a
distance, that Turner crossed first base before the ball arrived at
the bag. Television replays confirmed that he had clearly beaten
the throw, and the Yankees should have had another run.
</P>
<P>
   Except that Jeff Kellogg, the first base umpire, called Turner
out.
</P>
<P>
   Turner spun to the ground in disgust. Lee Mazzilli, the first
base coach, immediately charged Kellogg. Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager, bumped through some irate players in his dugout and rushed
onto the field, arguing at length.
</P>
<P>
   Torre turned to leave, but as he did so, Coach Don Zimmer might
have yelled something from the bench, for Zimmer was ejected and
Torre resumed the quarrel, challenging Kellogg until he was
ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Four Yankees have been ejected this season _ all in the last
eight days _ as they have plummeted toward .500 and their
frustration has grown.
</P>
<P>
   But the lead was still two runs. Cone still was in control of
this game, at least until Luis Polonia, Brad Ausmus and Higginson
hit consecutive singles to open the fifth inning, Polonia scoring.
Jason Grimsley quickly jumped to his feet to warm up in the
Yankees' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Cone used his slider to whiff Gonzalez for the first out. But
after a walk to Tony Clark, Cone appeared to hang a split-fingered
fastball to Dean Palmer, who waited for it and destroyed it, far
over the wall, a grand slam. Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching
coach, threw a sunflower seed to the ground, frustrated, and he
went to the mound to end Cone's night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
