<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FACE FAMILIAR DECISIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers are in a familiar position in late
June _ holding a top-five draft pick, entertaining trade offers and
waiting for a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into today's NBA Draft in Minneapolis, the Clippers
still had the third overall pick. But vice president of operations
Elgin Baylor spent most of Tuesday talking with several teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our phone lines have all been burning up in both directions
and we are taking a hard look at every angle,'' said Baylor. ``But
it would be completely premature to say any serious discussions
have taken place concerning a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have the third, 18th and 30th picks in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that they were interested in getting a point
guard to replace Derek Anderson, a free agent, and a big forward to
replace Maurice Taylor, also a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   However, it appears unlikely they will make any deals prior to
the draft, thus leaving them to decide between Marcus Fizer or
Darius Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Miles is the most intriguing player available. He is lean and
agile at 6-foot-9 and 220 pounds, with good jumping ability and
quickness. Last year, he worked as a counselor at Michael Jordan's
summer camp in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a little counselor game every night and he picked me
to be on his team every night,'' Miles said of Jordan, who has
publicly stated he would take Miles if Washington had the No.1
pick. He truly liked the kid's precocious behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ```Sometimes I'd probably just put my warm-up suit on, and not
even my jersey. Low teams need the lottery pick. They need players
that are going to make a difference. Like Vince Carter. He came in,
and three years later they made the playoffs. If you get a player
with a whole lot of potential, he can turn your franchise around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls have the No.4, 7 and 24 picks and the Orlando
Magic have No.5, 10 and 13. As an extra benefit, all three teams
have room to make a personnel move under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Reports had the Magic looking to trade up to the Clippers' No.3
spot to Miles, who was projected to go to the Bulls with the fourth
pick. The Magic would miss out on Miles at five.
</P>
<P>
   Even with most trade scenarios, the Clippers should end up with
Fizer, the 6-foot-8, 250-pound power forward from Iowa State. Fizer
would give the Clippers a lottery front line with center Michael
Olowokandi, 1998's top choice overall, and small forward Lamar
Odom, 1999's fourth overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been lukewarm about playing for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Playing an undersized center much of the time at Iowa State,
Fizer averaged 22.8 points and 7.7 rebounds a game last year as a
junior.
</P>
<P>
   In workouts, Fizer felt he was able to better show his shooting
range and dribbling skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed them my ability to dribble and things I can do like
shoot an NBA 3-pointer,'' Fizer said.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has not ruled out taking Miles with the third pick, but
the selection of the 6-foot-9 forward from East St. Louis High in
Illinois could mean a trade for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some players with good upside but it will take some
time before you get these players where we want them to be,''
Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The one spot the Clippers won't be drafting today is head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor wanted a coach before the draft but that won't happen.
The Nets hired former Laker Byron Scott on Tuesday, leaving the
Clippers and the Indiana Pacer as the only teams without a coach.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second time in three years the Clippers are drafting
without a coach. In 1998, the Clippers drafted Olowokandi before
hiring Chris Ford. The top candidates are assistant coach Dennis
Johnson and Denver Nuggets assistant John Lucas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
