<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-940     06-28 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-940&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BACKS BILL TO OPEN CAMPAIGN RECORDS OF POLICY GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: The following is now the lead story on The New York Times
front page) 
By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted on Wednesday morning to require a
growing number of shadowy tax-exempt groups that raise and spend
unlimited amounts on political advocacy to disclose their donors
and spending, opening the way for the first major change in
campaign finance law in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising reversal, lawmakers approved a bill, 385-39,
that mirrors an amendment sponsored by Sen. John McCain that the
Senate endorsed this month. On substance and the numbers, there is
scant difference between the House and Senate versions, and
President Clinton supports the legislation. But the Senate must
still give the measure final approval, and the question remains
whether Senate Republican foes will try to block or postpone action
on the measure.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks ago, the House narrowly defeated virtually the
same bill after Republican leaders bowed to pressure from party
moderates and promised to bring an even broader campaign disclosure
bill to the floor by the July 4 recess if they voted against the
more narrow legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy backfired when organizations on the left and
right, from Common Cause to the National Right to Life Committee,
strongly objected to provisions in the leadership-backed bill that
would have forced them to disclose their contributors and
nonpolitical activities.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican leaders and their allies conceded they had
overreached and only reluctantly voted for the more targeted
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a C-minus, not an A,'' said Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y.,
who wrote the leadership-backed bill. ``We just couldn't get it. It
had too many people with too many pieces that they hated.''
</P>
<P>
   But champions of tightening the nation's campaign finance laws,
who criticized the larger bill as unconstitutional and deliberately
punitive toward unions, hailed Wednesday morning's outcome as a
victory in closing a loophole created by elected officials and
interest groups under Section 527 of the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents one small triumph of democracy over secrecy,''
said Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, who sponsored the measure that
the House rejected on June 9. ``Disclosure by secret 527 political
organizations is one modest reform we can still enact before this
year's election.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday morning's vote, 205 Democrats, 178 Republicans and
two independents voted for the measure; 39 Republicans voted
against.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert supported the bill, but Tom DeLay, the
House majority whip, opposed it, saying it violated First Amendment
free speech rights.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This so-called `reform' bill is in reality nothing more than a
last-ditch effort by the Democrats to protect their vulnerable
incumbent members from valid attacks on their positions and
beliefs,'' DeLay said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the campaign disclosure measure would be the first
change to campaign finance law since technical changes were made in
1979 to the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1974, which was passed
after the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's measure was adopted, 57-42, as an amendment to a
military budget bill. But the measure immediately faced a
constitutional challenge because experts said the amendment
amounted to a revenue measure because it involved possible changes
in the tax status of political groups. Under the Constitution, all
revenue bills must originate in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measure say the question now is whether the
Senate Republican leadership, specifically Trent Lott, the majority
leader, will try to stall or block McCain's measure. The Senate
Finance Committee is to hold hearings on 527 groups on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the momentum, we have the policy, we have the votes,''
said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a group that
supports overhauling campaign finance law.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., expressed optimism that the House
and Senate votes on campaign disclosure could enhance prospects for
a ban that he and McCain support on unrestricted donations, called
soft money. But many political analysts say that clamping down on
527 groups does not translate into support for limits on soft
money.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of the new tax-exempt groups have cropped up in recent
years, exploited by nonprofit political organizations seeking to
avoid the donor disclosure rules and the contribution limits of
federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   These secretive groups are affiliated with causes across the
political spectrum, from the Sierra Club to groups with close ties
to Representative DeLay. They are allowed to raise money, buy
television and radio advertisements, conduct polling and other
political activities, without disclosure, so long as they do not
expressly advocate voting for a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure requires the 527 political organizations to follow
federal campaign law and file tax returns. They would have to
disclose any contributors who give more than $200, and report any
expenditures more than $500. Violators would have to pay a 35
percent tax on all contributions and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican aides said that the measure would take effect
upon enactment, meaning it would cover at least part of this
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased the House today voted to close the 527 loophole in
the tax code that allows money from any source to be spent in
American political campaigns without being disclosed to public
scrutiny,'' McCain said in a statement. ``I am very proud of the
members of the House who rejected partisan appeals to support a
sham reform.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wednesday morning's vote capped several days of contentious
meetings between House Republican leaders, Republican moderates and
McCain to reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders had sought to win approval for a bill that
passed the House Ways and Means Committee last week on a party-line
vote. Under that bill, organizations that spend more than $10,000
on political activities would have to disclose contributions of
$1,000 or more. Currently, there is no such requirement. The
legislation covered all Section 527 organizations.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and other opponents of revamping campaign finance law have
argued for years that what is needed is more disclosure, not more
limits on fund-raising. But Democrats and many moderate Republicans
complained that the leadership's bill would apply to all sorts of
activities, not just those in election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   With bipartisan opposition growing to the broader bill,
Republican leaders conceded defeat and agreed to bring up the
measure dealing only with 527 groups. But they moved the bill to
the floor under procedures designed to speed along uncontentious
bills, like renaming post offices.
</P>
<P>
   The process, called the suspension calendar, allows for only 40
minutes of debate, no amendments and requires two-thirds vote for
approval, rather than a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some House conservatives threatened to vote against a
top priority of their leaders _ a separate bill to expand Medicare
to provide coverage for prescription drugs _ if Republican leaders
allowed the 527 bill to come to the floor at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
