r a BC-MEXICO-STABILITY-SFCH     06-28 1992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-STABILITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREATER STABILITY BRINGS TEST OF POLITICAL STATUS QUO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  OAXACA, Mexico _ Romualdo Sanchez and his classmates are
sitting under a tree outside their college classroom, chatting
about everyday things _ graduation, jobs, romance, the hotly
contested national election.
<P>
   What's unusual is what they're not talking about _ guerrilla
warfare, assassinations, financial panic. Unusual because until
just a few years ago, masked guerrillas prowled the campus of the
Benito Juarez Autonomous University of Oaxaca, holding rallies and
recruiting members for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Oaxaca was then a revolutionary hotbed in the midst
of a crisis-ridden country. The national economy was near collapse.
Ruling-party infighting left a trail of victims, with each scandal
more bizarre than the last. Mexico, in short, seemed ready to
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Mexico still has plenty of problems that make the
issues in the U.S. election seem tame by comparison. But the
convulsions that provoked headlines worldwide are fading memories.
The economy is booming, guerrilla movements have all but
disappeared and, except for drug-related killings on the U.S.
border, assassinations are rare.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, fear of change, the glue that has helped hold
together the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), is
diminishing throughout Mexico, and the party is facing the stiffest
challenge of its 71-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   The shift is especially clear in Oaxaca, and calls for change
can be heard on the streets and on the university's leafy plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is corrupt; it never follows through on its
promises,'' says Sanchez's girlfriend, Anita Leon, biting into
another stick of gum. ``There's too much injustice and poverty. We
need a change. It's been way too long. We're no longer afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign leading up to Sunday's elections for president,
Congress and many local offices, ``change'' has become the
watchword nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge is Vicente Fox of an alliance headed by the
National Action Party (PAN). ``The choice is to continue with a
monopoly of power _ the longest-reigning one-party system on Earth
_ or achieve the much-awaited transition to democracy,'' he has
said over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the Democratic Party of the Revolution
(PRD) is carrying the banner of change too. But Cardenas, whose
platform of leftist reform in two previous unsuccessful bids for
president sent shivers down the spines of bureaucrats and investors
from Mexico to Wall Street, is far behind in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Even Francisco Labastida, the PRI standard-bearer, has taken up
the cause, casting the party as the ``new PRI,'' a more democratic
version of itself, and promising that ``after the election we are
going to continue to transform the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in previous campaigns, the desire for change this year is
propelled more by pragmatism than by ideology, and the contest is
over power more than policy. In general, the platforms of Labastida
and Fox differ merely in their details. Both candidates are
middle-of-the-road politicians who promise a more prosperous future
and a bigger piece of the pie for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida and Fox are in a statistical dead heat in most opinion
polls, with about one-fifth of the electorate still undecided. Many
of those still wavering, pollsters say, will make up their minds
based on how safe they feel.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, by U.S. standards, Oaxaca is still a turbulent
place. Sit-ins, taking local officials hostage, strikes _ all are
part of the in-your-face style of local politics. Compared to a
just few years ago, however, it has settled down enough to let more
voters feel safe.
</P>
<P>
   At the Oaxaca university campus and throughout Mexico, young
people are leaning toward the opposition, with their votes split
between Fox and Cardenas. Most polls show that among voters age 18
to 24, Fox has a double-digit lead over Cardenas, with Labastida
trailing in third place. Among those 26 to 30, Cardenas leads Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez says he'll vote for Cardenas; Leon, with an affectionate
pat on her boyfriend's arm, says she'll probably vote for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Young people form a crucial swing vote in what appears to be the
fairest and most competitive presidential race in Mexican history.
Nearly one-third of the country's voters are in their 20s, and
almost half are younger than 35.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox campaign has put young people in top roles and is
aggressively courting young voters. It has sponsored concerts with
the popular rock band Tri, while Fox himself, one of Mexico's most
eligible bachelors, often dresses in jeans and cowboy boots,
seeming much more vigorous than Labastida. Cardenas, while
remarkably wooden as a candidate, has added to his traditional
support from left-of-center students by featuring &LR;   &LR; using TV ads
and posters showing a young couple in a passionate, open-mouthed
kiss under the slogan, ``We want to dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people ``are a key factor that is moving the election
toward the opposition,'' said Daniel Lund, president of the polling
firm MUND. ``They are the first group to break with the PRI's
traditional methods of guaranteeing control, so they are less
afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the status quo looks solid indeed:
</P>
<P>
   -- The economy has recovered dramatically after the 1994-97
economic crisis, which required a $50 billion, U.S.-led financial
package to save Mexico from collapse. Economic growth is now
averaging 5 percent, inflation has dropped to less than 10 percent,
government finances are healthy, and the peso is solid.
</P>
<P>
   -- Guerrilla warfare is virtually a thing of the past. The
Zapatistas in Chiapas state, to the east of Oaxaca, have been
bottled up in their jungle hideouts by the Mexican army since their
1994 uprising. The People's Revolutionary Army (EPR), which stunned
Oaxaca and other southern states with a bloody series of attacks in
1997, has divided into factions, and many of its members have
silently abandoned armed struggle and joined the PRD.
</P>
<P>
   -- Unrest by students and teachers has fizzled. A chaotic,
10-month strike at the National University in Mexico City initially
enjoyed wide support but lost steam and was crushed by police in
February after the strike leadership was taken over by a tiny group
of ultraradicals. Earlier this month, schoolteachers gave up a
nationwide strike when public opinion swung heavily against them.
</P>
<P>
   -- Although discontent among indigenous groups simmers
elsewhere, it has been reduced in Oaxaca because of reforms by the
PRI-run state government in 1995 and 1998 that allow
Indian-dominated towns to operate their local governments with
``uses and customs,'' a consensus-oriented, traditional Indian
system of governing.
</P>
<P>
   -- The political process has been reformed, opposition parties
have more public funds and, for the first time, federal elections
will be run by an independent body, the Federal Electoral
Institute, rather than by the PRI-dominated government.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Improvements Aid Opposition
</P>
<P>
   For poll-takers and election watchers in Mexico and the United
States, the opposition's rise at this juncture is ironic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is suffering from the Al Gore problem,'' said Eric
Olson, a Mexico policy expert at the Washington Office on Latin
America, a liberal think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy looks to be doing well, the guerrillas are off the
map, yet polls say 60 percent don't support the PRI. It's the same
as with Gore _ considering the economy, they should be 20 points
ahead. But Fox and Cardenas have tapped into the public's desire
for change and have succeeded in making this election a referendum
on 71 years of power, not about what's going on today.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet because Fox and Cardenas are splitting the opposition vote,
the PRI still could eke out a victory with little more than 40
percent of the tally. For an answer to why the PRI remains strong
despite the desire for change sweeping the nation, take a stroll
into the bustling public market in downtown Oaxaca, and talk with
Romualdo Sanchez's mother, Gabriela.
</P>
<P>
   She and most of the market vendors are firm PRI supporters. They
are guided by the PRI-controlled union of vendors, which controls
nearly every aspect of the market's operations. The union is part
of the party's huge, well-oiled machinery that doles out favors
large and small to millions of Mexicans nationwide, guaranteeing a
steady flow of votes for PRI candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm loyal to the PRI because it's changing things for the
better,'' she said as she weighed vegetables for a customer. ``It
helps me and my family. Why should I turn my back on it?''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the PAN has won municipal elections in the
state capital and several other major cities in Oaxaca, but the
PRI's strong support among rural voters, union members and people
who receive government benefits _ such as the Progresa fund for
poor families or the Procampo subsidy program for farmers _ has
allowed the party to maintain power at the state government level.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders complain of a stacked deck. ``The PRI has
very strong control over lots of people because of its resources in
government,'' said Luis Andres Esteva, president of the Oaxaca PAN
chapter. ``The PRI's message is: `The PRI gives you all this, all
these government benefits, and what has the PAN or PRD given you?'
People feel like they owe the PRI their vote. Loyalty is a
deep-rooted trait among Oaxacans.''
</P>
<P>
   For these voters, Labastida's vision of safe change is
reassuring. ``Other candidates are advocating change without
strategy,'' he said at a recent rally in Oaxaca. ``They say that
everything that has been done in the past 70 years (under PRI rule)
is bad and must be thrown out. We will carry out change with
direction, change with strategy, change to improve conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of populist  &LR; rhetoric is a hit with many Oaxaca
residents. Like many Mexicans, Oaxacans say the country's good
times are less than advertised. Their complaints include:
</P>
<P>
   -- The nation's economic boom has largely sidestepped Oaxaca.
Most new jobs are found in the  &UR; maquiladoras,  &LR; or assembly plants,
in northern and central states. The Oaxaca state government has
tried to coax export firms to set up  &UR; maquiladoras &LR;  in Oaxaca, but
with little luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We complain, we complain, we tear our hair, but the Oaxaca
economy remains marginalized from macroeconomic growth,'' said
Carlos Guzman, president of the state chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   -- Many smaller businesses have been hurt by cheaper foreign
goods flowing into Mexico from the United States under the North
American Free Trade Agreement, and laid-off workers have little
choice but to emigrate northward to survive. In a nationwide survey
in May  &LR; last month by the GEA polling firm, only 18 percent of
respondents said their wages had improved since 1994 when President
Ernesto Zedillo took office, 56 percent said they were unchanged
and 26 percent said their wages had worsened.
</P>
<P>
   -- In remote rural areas, heavy-handed tactics by PRI strongmen,
the police and the army have maintained an atmosphere of fear and
coercion, human-rights groups say. Even in Oaxaca's charming
central square, dozens of Indians from the southern mountains have
created a squatter camp since 1997 to protest the jailing of at
least 86 peasants on subversion charges.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this is the new face of Mexico _ still full of
grievances but more stable and more democratic than ever. Oaxaca is
willing to flex its political muscle, but, like an adolescent, it
is still a little unsure of itself and looking for a safe way to
leave the past behind.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who wins Sunday's election, ``everything is changing,
mostly for the better,'' said Gabriela Sanchez in the marketplace.
``It's for my son, you know, for all our children, and he wouldn't
have it any other way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
