r a BC-EROSION-THREAT-SFCHRO     06-28 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EROSION-THREAT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COASTAL HOMES ON SHAKY GROUND SAYS U.S. REPORT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One in four of the nation's homes situated within 500 feet of
the ocean could be lost to erosion in the next 60 years, a
congressionally mandated report released Tuesday concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the H. John Heinz III Center for Science,
Economics and the Environment, estimates that approximately 1,500
homes and the land that surrounds them will be lost to coastal
erosion each year for the next six decades.
</P>
<P>
   Although areas along the Atlantic and the Gulf of Mexico coast
are expected to be hardest hit, California accounts for a large
portion of the total property loss to erosion because of the high
value of coastal property.
</P>
<P>
   The center recommended that the Federal Emergency Management
Agency (FEMA) produce maps detailing erosion risk so homeowners and
community officials could make sound zoning and development
decisions. FEMA already produces similar maps for flood risks.
</P>
<P>
   The result of a 1994 Congressional directive to FEMA to fund an
erosion-risk study, the report is based on a nationwide sampling of
11,000 buildings in 18 counties that are located within 500 feet of
the shore.
</P>
<P>
   The study concludes that property damage could be minimized and
coastal environmental quality improved by, among other options,
establishing development-free zones in areas prone to erosion.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that coastal properties face as much risk from
erosion damage _ caused by rising sea level, storms and large waves
_ as they do from flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report was based on data collected during the past 150
years,'' said Mary Margaret Walker, a spokeswoman for FEMA. ``So
given the dramatic predictions on sea level rise that we're seeing,
these (conclusions) are pretty conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the high-risk areas are on the Eastern Seaboard,
particularly the coastal zones of the southeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   But parts of California are also at high risk, particularly
Santa Cruz, San Mateo and San Diego counties. All have erodible
bluffs that support homes and commercial buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Monterey, San Luis Obispo and Ventura counties are also
contending with accelerating coastal erosion problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total estimated annual property loss (from erosion) for
the country is $530 million,'' said Bill Merrell, the president of
the Heinz Center and the project manager for the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``And California accounts for about $110 million of that
total,'' said Merrell. ``The problem is that you have very
expensive properties in coastal California, many of them located on
bluffs that are subjected to heavy surf.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell also noted that erosion concerns in California have
resulted in an acceleration of ``armoring'' along the coast:
covering bluff faces with concrete, gunnite or rip-rap, a process
that can destroy beaches and block coastal access.
</P>
<P>
   Armoring has been attacked by the Sierra Club's coastal program
as one of the worst crises facing California's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to mapping erosion zones, the report also recommends
doubling federally subsidized flood-insurance rates for the
highest-risk zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Flood Insurance Program is supposed to be
self-supporting for homeowners, but it doesn't address damage to
community infrastructure that can occur (during erosion
incidents),'' said Merrell.
</P>
<P>
   And even homes covered by national flood insurance are not fully
protected, said Merrell. Of the $530 million in losses that are
claimed every year because of erosion, federal flood insurance
would pay only about $80 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the onus of protecting coastal residents from
erosion is falling on all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is paying for this,'' she said. ``The fact is that
the erosion problem can't be solved by FEMA and the insurance
program alone. Coastal residents have to take some of the
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the Heinz report is important `'because it gets the
information out there. It indicates (the limits) of responsible
development.''
</P>
<P>
   The report struck a sour chord with some groups, particularly
advocates of private property rights and local zoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't dispute that there should be smart development, and
we don't oppose buyouts for set-back zones as long as they're
voluntary,'' said Andy Lacy, the executive director of the American
Coastal Coalition, a lobbying group for coastal communities and
property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the people who already live along the coasts aren't going
anywhere,'' Lacy said. ``This report is trying to scare them into
retreating, and that's not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacy also opposes raising insurance rates in high-risk zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coastal property owners pay far more into the National Flood
Insurance Program than is paid out in claims,'' he said. ``The
insinuation that this is a subsidy to coastal residents is false.''
</P>
<P>
   The report may be viewed on the Heinz center's web site at
 &UR; www.heinzcenter.org. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
