   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ A terrifying surge of
communal violence, apparently fueled by anti-government agitators
in Jakarta, is tearing apart the remote and beautiful islands of
Maluku, once known as the Spice Islands, raising fears of
destabilization throughout Indonesia's ailing archipelago. More
than 200 people have reportedly been killed in the past week in
village massacres and in street fighting in the small city of
Ambon, pushing the death toll during the last 18 months to more
than 2,500. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTIONS (Mexico City) _ Authorities have promised that
Mexico's presidential election this Sunday will be the cleanest in
history, but recent events suggest that at least some hard-liners
in the governing party still believe that electoral chicanery can
help them triumph. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-JEWS (Rome) _ Jewish groups are mounting a campaign against
the beatification of Pius IX, the 19th-century pope who kidnapped a
Jewish child and raised him as a Catholic. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AFRICA-AIDS (Undated) _ At least half of all 15-year-olds in
the African countries worst affected by AIDS will die of the
disease even if the rates drop substantially in the next few years,
the United Nations reported Tuesday. And if infection rates remain
high, the odds are that more than two-thirds of 15-year-olds will
die from AIDS in countries like Botswana, according to projections
from Unaids, a joint U.N.'s program in Geneva. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SCHOOL-UNIFORMS (Undated) _ San Diego, Calif., is the only
major U.S. city where all children are required to wear school
uniforms. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-LOBBY _ With a congressional debate planned for this week
on competing Republican and Democratic Medicare drug proposals, a
look at the intense lobbying effort against the Clinton plan. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   FDA-OVER-THE-COUNTER _ Spurred by two pharmaceutical companies
that want to take their cholesterol-lowering medications over the
counter, the FDA is considering whether many more medicines should
be made available without a doctor's prescription. Beginning with
public hearings on Wednesday and Thursday, the drug agency will
begin a re-examination of the way it regulates over-the-counter
drugs, the first such review in nearly three decades. The last one,
in 1972, created a new system for approving over-the-counter drugs
that enabled more than 600 drugs to switch from prescription to
nonprescription status. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA-ASSESS _ Timing, in constitutional law no less
than in life or love, can mean everything, and when it came to
timing, the opponents of the Miranda decision who finally managed
to push the Supreme Court into revisiting the case after 34 years
turned out to have been spectacularly unlucky. A news analysis by
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-DETECTIVES (San Francisco) _ Oracle Corp. acknowledged
Tuesday that it had hired a prominent Washington detective firm to
investigate groups sympathetic to its archrival, Microsoft Corp.,
an effort that yielded documents embarrassing to Microsoft in the
midst of its antitrust battle with the government. By John Markoff
and Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The SEC proposes new rules to
tighten standards on what other services accounting firms can sell
to companies whose books they audit. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-PATENTS (Undated) _ Even though the unraveling of the
human genome is only now being completed, much of the genetic code
has already been claimed for commerce. In what has often been
compared to a land grab, companies and universities have filed for
patents on hundreds of thousands of genes and gene fragments. By
Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-DATA (Undated) _ New government data shows just how
far prosperity has spread across America, with stock options,
two-career couples and capital gains helping to lift a record
number of families to six-figure annual incomes. One taxpayer in 15
resided in this economic realm in 1998, the government reported
Tuesday _ an increase of 1.1 million over 1997. The number of
taxpayers with incomes of $100,000 or more soared in 1998 to 8.3
million, up 15 percent from the 7.2 million in 1997, preliminary
figures from 1998 income tax returns showed. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-INVESTORS (Undated) _ Having mapped the human genome at a
speed that doubters had said was impossible, Celera Genomics must
defy the skeptics who say it will not be able to make money by
selling information about the genome. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FORECAST-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A leading forecaster of
advertising spending has raised his estimates for 2000, citing
economic conditions that are more robust than he expected and
strong spending by marketers in major categories from automobiles
to computers to drugs. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-EDUC (Undated) _ Competing for the smallest pool of
college graduates of accounting programs in more than a decade,
many of the nation's largest accounting firms and associations have
begun promoting their profession in high schools. With scholarships
and internships in hand, they are hoping to resuscitate a field
that is rapidly losing recruits to the wonders of technology and
the glamour of being entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDLYINVESTOR (Undated) _ Lewis Gersh, the 32-year-old chief
executive of worldlyinvestor.com.
