<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-28 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOUGH TO WATCH HERSHISER, GWYNN AT END OF LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And so, Orel Hershiser faces the end. Sooner or
later it happens to all of them, to the best of them. Careers take
different twists and turns, find their own peaks and valleys, carve
unique paths through baseball history, but inevitably they all come
together in the same sad place.
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove the universality of it all, on the day Hershiser
was released by the Dodgers and resisted suggestions he retire,
fellow 40-something Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres underwent a
sixth knee surgery in a bid to prolong his career.
</P>
<P>
   At such moments you try to remember the good times.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in a dog-eared scorebook marked ``1985,'' are some of the
earliest and best of times. And here, on yellowing Daily News
sports pages from your first month on the Dodgers beat, pages your
mother saved.
</P>
<P>
   One week in April, 15 years ago now, Orel Hershiser faced the
Padres in consecutive starts. He pitched a two-hitter and a
one-hitter. Each time the no-hitter was broken up by Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday afternoon in San Diego, Gwynn sliced a 2-and-1
curveball double down the right-field line leading off the seventh
inning. A good pitch, Hershiser said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the guy you want to break up a no-hitter _ the best
hitter in baseball,'' Hershiser said.
</P>
<P>
   On a Friday night at Dodger Stadium, Hershiser tried to jam his
nemesis with a fastball in the fourth inning but Gwynn got the
barrel of the bat on the pitch and grounded it into right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the guy's name that got the hit?'' Hershiser joked
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was 26 years old then, working on a breakthrough, 19-3
season. Gwynn was 24, coming off the first of his eight batting
championships.
</P>
<P>
   The sports pages in those days were full of news of USC
basketball's signing of Hank Gathers and Bo Kimball, of the USFL's
fight for survival, of Rod Carew closing in on 3,000 hits, of the
Rams' efforts to trade Vince Ferragamo, and of the Lakers on their
way to an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Of the players in those games, only Hershiser and Gwynn remain.
Steve Garvey and Graig Nettles were Padres. Dave Dravecky was the
losing pitcher in both games. Mariano Duncan and Candy Maldonado
homered to account for the Dodgers' runs in the first game. Pedro
Guerrero doubled home Bill Russell and Al Oliver for the Dodgers'
runs in the second (though he might now claim not to have known
what he was doing).
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Gwynn was barely one-tenth of the way to 3,000
hits. In those days, Hershiser was not yet a Cy Young Award
pitcher, a World Series hero or a 200-game winner; it was still
vogue to joke about his wimpy name _ Orel Leonard Hershiser IV _
and physique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of Poindexter-looking,'' as Dodgers coach Rick Dempsey, a
player then, described him Tuesday. ``You looked at Orel, and you
didn't see `athlete' in him. Until he got out there on the mound.
Then you'd see what he can do with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hershiser, the round-shouldered pitcher, and Gwynn, the
round-bellied hitter, the trips to the final crossroads have been
different indeed. Hershiser starred in the baseball towns of Los
Angeles, New York, San Francisco and Cleveland, made it to three
World Series, recorded the final out when the Dodgers beat the
Oakland Athletics in 1988. Gwynn played for one team, largely
wasted in the darkest corner of the baseball nation, batted .371 in
two World Series but never came close to a championship.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way they would be connected as two sides of the
same coin, their generation's leading craftsmen of the mound and
the batter's box. George Will would examine their preparations at
length and write in ``Men at Work'' that if everybody played the
game like Hershiser and Gwynn, nobody would be saying that its best
days are past.
</P>
<P>
   Will noted that on the night in September 1988 when Hershiser
ran his shutout-innings streak to 59, the ultimate measure of his
dominance was the fact he got Gwynn to ground to second four times.
</P>
<P>
   Now they cross paths again. Just not at Dodger Stadium, where
their teams were facing each other Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser had been at the stadium in the morning with his wife
Jamie, received the news of his release from Dodgers chairman Bob
Daly, and departed. Gwynn was in San Diego, undergoing arthroscopic
surgery on the left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Their immediate circumstances are different. Hershiser, 41,
apparently is healthy, yet he pitches as if he's washed up. Eight
Padres runs in the second inning Monday night left him 1-5 with a
13.14 ERA. Gwynn, 40, can still hit (.323 this season), yet the
knee wouldn't let him run the bases and play the outfield every
day. He is expected to be out until September.
</P>
<P>
   This brings them to same place, facing the same grim certainty:
Gwynn admitting last week that along with exploring medical
options, he is ``forced to think about retirement.'' Hershiser
hearing Daly implore him to retire and responding, ``I want to
think about what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point you are supposed to plead with them to end the
agony and just retire. You are supposed to remind them of Willie
Mays at the end, hanging on too long and hitting .211 for the 1973
New York Mets. You are supposed to suggest that each creaky step
somehow stomps out an ember of their glory days.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't work that way. The good times still exist in the
scorebook and on newsprint _ the days when Hershiser was becoming a
star although few thought he would, and Gwynn was hitting him
although nobody else could.
</P>
<P>
   If you remember them then, you think maybe these are the men who
can stare at retirement and make retirement blink. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
