<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SIMMONS-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S SIMMONS FEELING BETTER AFTER SURGERY TO REMOVE TUMOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC defensive back Antuan Simmons is not expected
to play this season following severe complications from surgery to
remove a stomach tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, who is a preseason All-American and three-year starter,
has drifted in and out of intensive care following the operation at
USC's Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center on May 16, and has lost
approximately 40 pounds from his listed playing weight of 190. The
growth in his stomach was benign, but was lodged between his left
kidney and behind the abdominal lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very difficult six-week period where Antuan
has undergone major surgery and we're proud of how he's battled it
and fought through it,'' said USC coach Paul Hackett. ``He's been
an inspiration. Thank God, he's coming out of it. They feel the
worst is behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been scheduled to leave the hospital on several
occasions, Simmons' physical condition has at times deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last weekend, Simmons was back in intensive care.
He needed a respirator to assist his breathing and had fluid in his
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons is expected to remain hospitalized at least through the
end of this week, barring any unforeseen problems.
</P>
<P>
   Donald G. Skinner, the doctor who performed the surgery, has
told USC officials that Simmons should eventually play football
again.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10 Simmons, who is a senior, has a redshirt year
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe he can recover in time,'' Hackett said. ``He's
young and strong and will rebound. This is why you have the
redshirt year.''
</P>
<P>
   His absence opens up the left cornerback position, which is
considered the toughest in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said junior starter Kris Richard may move over to left
cornerback, or junior-college transfer Chris Cash and sophomore
Darrell Rideaux could have a chance to start at the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the role of Cash or Rideaux is expected to increase
significantly, as one will be starting when USC opens its season
Aug. 27 against Penn State in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a three or four way battle for two spots,''
Hackett said. ``You can't replace (Antuan). We just have other guys
that will step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons was recently named a preseason All-American by Street
and Smith's magazine. Last season, he had 49 tackle, 10 pass
deflections, three interceptions, three blocked kicks, two fumble
recoveries and a forced fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons missed the final two games of the 1999 season after
undergoing surgery for a herniated disc in his back. That operation
also caused him to miss this year's spring practice. The stomach
tumor was detected after a follow-up exam on his back.
</P>
<P>
   In other football news, freshman offensive lineman Lucais MacKay
has decided to quit playing and concentrate on track, where he is a
discus thrower. MacKay, who finished sixth at the Pacific-10
Conference championships, will be placed on a track scholarship. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
