u k BC-EDIT-GUN-SUIT-NYT &LR;      06-28 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK JOINS THE GUN SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesay, June 28:
</P>
<P>
   In two important new cases, New York state and New York City
have filed lawsuits against gun manufacturers for injuries to their
citizens from unsafe and illegal weapons. Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer filed the first state lawsuit in the country on Monday with
a forceful new argument that gun makers are contributing to a
public nuisance by flooding the state with illegal firearms. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's lawsuit against gun makers last week also lends
a powerful political voice to the gun control debate, since he is
the first Republican mayor to join more than 30 communities taking
the manufacturers to court. For that reason, Giuliani helps rob the
nation's gun makers of their expectation that the issue will go
away if more Republicans are elected this November.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawsuit, unlike the state's, raises some concerns by
including the nation's largest handgun manufacturer, Smith &AMP;
Wesson, the only gun maker that has negotiated an important gun
control deal with the Clinton administration. The Smith &AMP; Wesson
settlement is not perfect, but it represents a brave move against
gun violence. The National Rifle Association has organized a
boycott against the company, and Smith &AMP; Wesson has tried to back
out of parts of its original agreement. But by lumping Smith &AMP;
Wesson with other gun makers, the city could inadvertently
discourage similar settlements by other manufacturers that might
conclude that there is no point in compromising if they are going
to be sued anyway. The city should work quickly to settle with
Smith &AMP; Wesson, making sure that the company honors the terms of
its original agreement with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Filed in conjunction with the Center to Prevent Handgun
Violence, in Washington, the city's suit argues correctly that the
manufacturers have been negligent in marketing and distribution,
often saturating markets in states with weaker gun controls so that
weapons can more easily move into New York City, which has tougher
gun laws. The suit also accuses the gun makers of producing a
defective product missing crucial safety mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   The state's suit does not ask for damages, a good way of putting
extra pressure on other gun makers to negotiate a deal like Smith &AMP;
Wesson's with the federal government. Spitzer argues that the state
should be working more to change behavior than to collect dollars
and that his method would bring a speedier resolution. But these
bullies may not listen to reason unless they are threatened with
paying a hefty price.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits appear at an important time, when most
manufacturers are trying to get the courts and Congress to stop
local and state governments from rewarding Smith &AMP; Wesson with
contracts to provide guns for law enforcement. The state should
consider adding damages to its case. The city needs to subtract
Smith &AMP; Wesson from its case. Then both can focus more heat on the
less responsible gun makers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
