<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS KEEP COOL, BEAT ANAHEIM FOR SEVENTH WIN IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The temperature at game time was 89 degrees, so a
meltdown at Safeco Field wasn't out of the question Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The second-inning line: two run (RUN IS CQ), two snits, untold
glares.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim starting pitcher Tim Belcher was the first to let his
graying hair down. He lasted just 47 minutes and 47 pitches,
drawing an ejection after fiercely arguing a balk call. Initially a
peacemaker, Angels manager Mike Scioscia wasn't far behind, getting
tossed himself when all else failed.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Mariners kept their cool.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the uncommon Seattle heat wave and all the
theatrics, the home club beat Anaheim 5-3 for its seventh
consecutive victory _ its longest such streak at Safeco and a
season-best by three games.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele, who exactly a year earlier lost the last game played
in the Kingdome while with Texas, won the 79th hosted at Safeco.
The Mariners' off-season acquisition permitted three runs and five
hits in 61/3 innings, good enough for his team-high ninth victory
in 12 decisions. It was also the Poulsbo product's fifth victory in
six decisions at his new home park.
</P>
<P>
   Sele got plenty of backing from home runs by David Bell and Mike
Cameron, both leading off innings. Belcher's balk didn't hurt
either, plating a third run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I love about that guy,'' Jay Buhner said of
Belcher, a former Mariners teammate. ``Right or wrong, Belch was a
pretty solid dude. He's got that fire. Sometimes it gets the best
of him. But I love to see that, letting people know what he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm curious to see what that locker looks like _ probably a
war zone. I'll get a damage report.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally a feisty type, Belcher came unglued in the second
inning after falling behind 3-0 and finding himself in a
first-and-third jam. In mid-windup, the pitcher faked a pickoff
move to third, then to first. Umpire Mike DiMuro signaled balk.
Belcher lost it.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander got in DiMuro's face. Scioscia, the former
Dodgers catcher, rushed onto the field and pushed his way between
the overheated Belcher and the arbiter. Belcher got tossed anyway _
obviously it was something he said. Not finished, the pitcher ran
around Scioscia and bumped the umpire from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Several nasty words later, Belcher and Scioscia retired to the
comfort of the visitors clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Television replays appeared to show the pitcher, with his first
move, step toward home rather than toward the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the replay and it was close,'' a contrite Belcher
said in front of his locker cubicle, which was still in one piece.
``It's something you don't see called very often. You don't get it
called by the home-plate umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cameron, at the plate at the time of the histrionics, ``It
was a balk. It's the first time I've even seen a balk. I don't know
what he got tossed for. I wasn't concerned. It was between him and
the umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher admitted using a few expletives, but insisted that he
was a charmer otherwise with DiMuro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted an explanation. I came down off the mound and said I
wanted an explanation,'' he said. ``I said, `Let's go out to the
mound and show me where I stepped.' The next thing I know I was
thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who played for Seattle's pennant-winning club in 1995,
wasn't long for this game from the start. He gave up a run in the
first inning on John Olerud's two-out single into the left-field
corner. Belcher allowed another on Bell's leadoff homer in the
second. The long ball was followed by a single, walk, fielder's
choice and the hotly debated balk.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners pushed across another run on Mark McLemore's
double-play grounder in the fourth and their final score on
Cameron's inning-opening homer in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim chipped away with Tim Salmon's RBI single in the third,
Mo Vaughn's thundering homer leading off the sixth and Darin
Erstad's RBI groundout in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn launched one with a thud off a window of the Hit It Here
Cafe in right field, freezing everyone and drawing quiet after he
made contact.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners got spotless relief. Arthur Rhodes retired all five
batters he faced and Kazuhiro Sasaki went 1-2-3 in the ninth for
his 15th save.
</P>
<P>
   By now, there was peace at Safeco.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
