<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LA     06-28 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS COME BACK TO BEAT PADRES, 5-4
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At 11 p.m. Tuesday night, Eric Gagne still didn't
know what happened to Orel Hershiser. All he knew was that the
Dodgers had come from behind to beat San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It took home runs by Eric Karros, Dave Hansen and Todd Hundley,
plus Karros' RBI single in the 10th inning, to give the Dodgers a
5-4 victory in front of what was left of the 41,897 beach
towel-waving Dodger Stadium fans. The win snapped a five-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne was recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque before Tuesday's
game to replace Hershiser, who had been waived earlier in the day.
He gave up three runs and three hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sadness,'' Gagne said. ``I still don't know what
happened. What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   When told, Gagne said, ``Really? He's one of the greatest
pitchers I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers had to go about business and did so, but it took
until the seventh inning, and by then, San Diego had a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still sluggish with the bats,'' said Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson. ``With Hershiser and that whole thing, it's been a
grind. This really picked the whole team up.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros started the rally with a seventh-inning home run off
Padres starter Will Cunnane, himself having been recalled from
Triple-A Las Vegas on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley followed with a double, and Carlos Reyes relieved and
got two outs before giving up Hansen's game-tying pinch homer.
</P>
<P>
   This was Hansen's fourth homer of the season. All have come via
pinch-hits, and it was the 10th pinch homer of Hansen's career. He
has nine as a Dodger, tying him with John Frederick for the most in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   After San Diego regained the lead off Matt Herges in the bottom
of the eighth, Hundley tied the game in the bottom of the ninth
with a home run just inside the right-field foul pole off closer
Trevor Hoffman. It was Hoffman's third blown save this season.
</P>
<P>
   Karros finally won it in the 10th with a single to left off Matt
Whiteside (2-1) that scored Mark Grudzielanek, who doubled with one
out.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters (3-0) pitched a scoreless 10th for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty interesting here in the Dodger locker room
through the years,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hope Gagne can provide more interest, since he's the
one the Dodgers want to establish.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed Ryan Klesko's first-inning home run to left and Kevin
Nicholson's two-run broken-bat single to right in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In every other inning, he pitched like the Dodgers hoped,
retiring seven straight in one stretch and the final six batters he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had, in my opinion, his best outing of the season,''
Hundley said. ``The home run was his only bad pitch. The two-run
single was a good pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Cunnane threw plenty of good pitches, too.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first start since May 20 at Atlanta and just his
second start since 1997, Cunnane had a three-hitter through six
innings, having pitched his way out of two jams.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up consecutive singles to Grudzielanek and Gary
Sheffield, but got Shawn Green to ground into a force play and
Karros to ground into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Cunnane put the same two batters on base with two
out but again got Green to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   But he lost his shutout bid when he gave up Karros' 22nd home
run of the season in the seventh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
