<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-L     06-28 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE TEMPERS, GAME TO MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Angels will go sweepless in Seattle, their 5-3
loss to the Mariners on Tuesday night in front of 32,051 at Safeco
Field in the series-opener ruining any hopes they might have had of
taking the first three games in a critical 10-game stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of getting a hot streak started, the Angels were just
hot, period, when emotions boiled over in the first of 10 games
against the Mariners and Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Tim Belcher and manager Mike Scioscia were
ejected during a heated exchange with home-plate umpire Mike DiMuro
over a disputed balk call in the second inning. The Angels were
never able to recover and lost for the third time in their past
four games.
</P>
<P>
   They also fell a season-worst 6 games behind the AL West-leading
A's, and six games behind the second-place Mariners, who have won
seven in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher had already given up a run in the second inning on David
Bell's leadoff homer, and the Mariners had runners on first and
third with one out with Mike Cameron coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher went into his stretch, set, faked to third, then whirled
and faked to first. DiMuro immediately called a balk, allowing Joe
Oliver to score from third and Rickey Henderson to take second
base.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed DiMuro's ruling was correct _ Belcher stepped
more toward home than third during his fake pickoff throw, going
beyond the imaginary 45-degree line between home and third. But
Belcher charged DiMuro, who ejected Belcher almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   That got Belcher even more upset, and he was stopped by Scioscia
and first baseman Mo Vaughn from going after DiMuro. Belcher, from
a safe distance, continued to berate DiMuro while Scioscia did the
same. Scioscia eventually got tossed long after Belcher returned to
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted an explanation,'' Belcher said. ``I even went so far
as to put my arm around him and say `You show me where I stepped.'
The next thing I know I'm getting thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably one job in baseball that's tougher than being a
pitcher, and that's an umpire. I respect the ones who do a good job
and have control of the game. Unfortunately, the ones who don't
have control have the thinnest skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia and Belcher both dispute the balk call, saying many
lefties cross that imaginary 45-degree line on their pickoff move
to first yet don't get called for a balk. But the balk call became
secondary to the ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's really troubling,'' Scioscia said. ``I never got
an explanation why Tim Belcher got tossed from the ballgame.
Obviously there's a line you cross for getting tossed out of a
ballgame. Tim Belcher never crossed the line. It was very
disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMuro and the rest of the umpiring crew refused to comment
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   While having your starting pitcher thrown out in the second
inning normally isn't a good thing, Belcher certainly wasn't
pitching as well as he did in winning his previous two starts.
</P>
<P>
   He walked two and gave up an RBI single to John Olerud in the
first inning and was in trouble before being ejected in the second.
In 1 1/3 innings, he made 47 pitches and gave up three runs on
three hits with three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fyhrie replaced Belcher (2-1) and retired the first five
batters he faced, including Cameron, Edgar Martinez and Jay Buhner
on strikeouts. But the Mariners got a couple of hits and a run in
the fourth inning, then got a home run from Cameron in the fifth to
take a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fyrhie gave up two runs in 3 2/3 innings, and Lou Pote (two
innings) and Mark Petkovsek (one inning) combined to shut down the
Mariners for the final three innings. After the game, Pote was sent
to Triple-A Edmonton to make room on the roster for Ken Hill, who
will start tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen did a great job of picking me up,'' Belcher said.
``We're starting probably one of the biggest stretches of games,
one thing you don't want to have happen is lose your starting
pitcher in the second inning, no matter what the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had trouble mounting much offense against Mariners
starter Aaron Sele. They got three consecutive two-out singles _
including Tim Salmon's RBI single _ in the third inning, and a solo
homer by Vaughn (No.21) in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sele left the game with Adam Kennedy on second and one out in
the seventh. Kennedy scored later in the inning on Darin Erstad's
RBI groundout. Sele (9-3) gave up three runs and five hits in 6 1/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the second in a row for the Angels, who have not
lost more than three in a row all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to stay away from any prolonged losing streak or
any losing streak at all is a big plus, it's a sign of a good
team,'' Angels general manager Bill Stoneman said before the game.
``But another sign of a good team is putting a win streak together,
and we haven't done it yet.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
