<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV02-COX     06-28 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT'S FUTURE WILL MOVE TO THE WEB
 &HT;    Moving in (a) national and (f) financial categories for release
Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The Microsoft programmers butted each other
with their black plastic helmets, molded to look like the hair of
Japanese sumo wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in rubberized suits that made them look like jumbo pink
Michelin men, the programmers clashed, fell down and rolled around,
unable to get up again without help.
</P>
<P>
   The immobilized wrestlers symbolized Microsoft today _ its
powerful programming skills and enormous market power in danger of
being toppled and left helpless by a government antitrust action.
</P>
<P>
   But the court battle back in Washington hardly seems to have
registered here in the Seattle suburbs. Pressing ahead to make its
products more all-encompassing than ever, the company's high
command has adopted a vision built upon the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That approach is leaving the work of the Windows programmers
writhing on the outdoor mat a vestige of a passing era.
</P>
<P>
   In a stretch of 72-hour work weeks, the code writers had just
put the finishing touches on Windows Me, for ``millennial edition''
_ likely the last consumer product from the world's largest
software firm to regard the personal computer as largely a
stand-alone machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent work,'' a team leader said into a mike as the sumo
wrestlers' straw-hatted colleagues sipped beers to the music of a
steel band. ``Let's go party!''
</P>
<P>
   But the company's top brass shows scant enthusiasm for Windows
Me, a direct successor to DOS, which led Microsoft on a 25-year
march to riches. In a June 22 briefing for reporters and analysts
here, which focused on how Microsoft intends to reinvent itself as
an Internet powerhouse, Windows Me went unmentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows isn't going away,'' Steve Ballmer, Microsoft's chief
executive, told the gathering at the company's conference center.
But ``to take advantage of this future trend in technology, we need
this new 'dot-Net' platform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's new business model remains a work in progress, but
the core idea is to view software as a service rather than as a
product, to be stored not on millions of personal computers but on
a Web server.
</P>
<P>
   The new platform relies on an open programming language known as
XML. It runs on any operating system and on any robust hardware
platform. It can be accessed by a host of devices, including
Web-enabled TV sets and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is no pioneer in pursuing a service-based,
multi-device, Web-centric model for its software. Hewlett-Packard
began marketing its own Internet services platform, known as
e-speak, last December. IBM, Oracle and Sun Microsystems are also
players in this league, as well as host of smaller firms.
</P>
<P>
   But assuming the courts to do not raise insurmountable
roadblocks, Microsoft possesses potent assets to comete in this
market, including long-standing relationships with such key
business partners as Dell Computer Corp., 40,000 worldwide
employees and a $20 billion cash hoard.
</P>
<P>
   And software developers still recall how WordPerfect and Lotus
lost their onetime top billing in the word processor and
spreadsheet charts to Microsoft when they failed to adapt quickly
to the Windows standard.
</P>
<P>
   Another key facet of the makeover moves revenues from software
royalties and licenses to subscription fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at this,'' Microsoft chairman and co-founder Bill
Gates said in an interview, ``it's clear to me that 'p' (price)
cannot be the answer. The entire upside must be in 'v' (volume).''
</P>
<P>
   Gates's economic shorthand reflects less on his aborted Harvard
education than on the June 7 decision by U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson to split Microsoft's Windows monopoly from its Web
sites and from its software applications business, such as Office.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the company has argued that it could not go
forward with the ``dot-Net'' initiative if Jackson's ruling stands.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews on the Microsoft campus with programmers and
mid-level managers, Jackson's draconian remedy also scarcely caused
a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I don't think about the case at all,''
said Jonathan Weinstein, who devises computing strategies for small
businesses aimed at dovetailing with the new ``dot-net'' agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
