<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-FAMILY0627-COX     06-28 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAMILY0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cybercafes, Internet kiosks keep travelers connected
 &HT;    By Anne Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My husband enjoys the ability to disconnect during a
vacation. Work and home are left behind so he can indulge in the
sheer enjoyment of the places we visit. The only exception is the
daily phone call to our kids.
</P>
<P>
   I like to vacation, but I never completely disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, our flight to Dublin, Ireland, stopped for a
two-hour layover in Shannon. The stopover was little more than an
invitation to spend our Irish currency.
</P>
<P>
   The terminal offered some food and a lot of tourist-friendly
merchandise. Green was the dominant color in the gift shop, but
across the hallway I could see a welcoming PINK.
</P>
<P>
   I had been away from my kids for less than 24 hours, and it was
1 a.m. where they were. I still felt the need to send them a note,
and there in the corner was PINK _ a public Internet kiosk
(www.isltd.com/pink.html). At the PINK machine, you can surf the
Internet and send and receive e-mail on its 14-inch LCD
touch-screen computer. The box is coin-operated.
</P>
<P>
   I bought a diet cola to break the paper money into coin and
headed for the PINK machine. Just as I approached, another traveler
informed us that the box was broken. I was disappointed, but knew
that I would soon find an old-fashioned cybercafe in Dublin with
plenty of working computers.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed since the days I called my parents' house
from the road and hung up after the first ring just to let them
know I was still alive. When I traveled 20 years ago, phone calls
cost over $1.50 per minute between the United Kingdom and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a prepaid calling card from a major long-distance
provider, I paid 18 cents per minute from London and 24 cents per
minute from Dublin. The card was purchased from Costco and may be
precharged with a credit card number via telephone. (The same card
purchased direct from the telephone company is nearly four times
the cost.)
</P>
<P>
   Since its introduction, public Internet access has also dropped
in cost. Three years ago, I paid approximately $5 per half-hour in
cybercafes and more at Internet kiosks. On this trip to Ireland,
England and Switzerland, we paid no more than $3.50 an hour.
Internet use was free with the purchase of a drink at some
cybercafes.
</P>
<P>
   This technology kept me in touch with family, friends and work.
With the ease of communication, I was able to enjoy my trip more. I
sent a few e-mails and never bothered with postcards.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I met up with friends from Atlanta while we were
in London. While the men made a stop at a local pub, my friend
Debbie and her kids joined me at a favorite cybercafe called
Webshack (www.webshack-cafe.com).
</P>
<P>
   Debbie's family shares an America Online account, and each of
them has a screen name. Webshack computers have AOL's software and
Instant Messenger. Katie, who is in high school, exchanged instant
messages with friends, while Joey, a middle-schooler, logged on via
AOL's Web site and checked his e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   They enjoyed the opportunity to connect with their friends. When
the men arrived from their taste of the local culture, Debbie's
husband Jim quickly checked his e-mail, and we ventured back into
London's trendy Soho. Jim regularly checked his work e-mail during
their trip.
</P>
<P>
   Webshack offers a high-speed connection so I can check mail,
read an online newspaper and surf miscellaneous Web sites at
lightning speed.
</P>
<P>
   New cybercafes are emerging regularly, and information is
available online. The Web site, www.netcafeguide.com
</P>
<P>
   /frames.html, offers information about 3,000 cybercafes in 139
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who are computer-equipped need to know a different set
of rules. Check the Web site www.roadnews.com/ for important
information for laptop users who travel abroad. The site will help
with everything from finding a roaming Internet access provider and
resolving hardware and software issues to guarding against computer
theft.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
