r s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-AGSSI28     06-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-AGSSI28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spadea: At 21, skid was getting old
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ His parents had gone home to Boca Raton two
days earlier, probably in despair, Vince Spadea joked later.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent had virtually guaranteed his British fans a win in
the well-read pages of The Sun _ London's tabloid featuring
bare-topped Page3 girls and lots of Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   And few others had given him much chance to end his ATP
Tour-record 21-match losing streak against big-serving Greg
Rusedski, the 14th seed and a grass-court lover.
</P>
<P>
   But at 9p.m. Monday in London (4 p.m. EDT), Spadea lifted his
arms in victory to the few friends in his supporters box and to
himself. He had finally won.
</P>
<P>
   The streak was over, after months of losing, of working when it
seemed hopeless, of close losses and horrible losses, of injury, of
scrutiny. It was over, after three hours, 56 minutes of play and
nearly two hours of rain delay Monday at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm popping champagne like I won the tournament,'' Spadea said
later. ``I'm going to enjoy it, because that's what it's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Spadea defeated Rusedski 6-3, 6-7 (5-7), 6-3, 6-7 (8-10), 9-7 on
Court1, which seats 11,429 and was filled with passionate British
fans waving signs and flags for Rusedski.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Spadea urged a partially booing crowd to give him
credit for a hard-fought match, even though he'd been a bit testy
during play. He won them over with a broad grin once they began
applauding. Davis Cup captain John McEnroe hugged him too _ so hard
Spadea said he felt ``like my kid was born or something. That was a
great feeling, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, he entered a near-empty interview room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am. Six months,'' Spadea said. ``It was worth the wait,
huh people?''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was his first since reaching the semifinals at Lyon
in October. He defeated Jim Courier, then Yevgeny Kafelnikov,
before losing to Lleyton Hewitt. Spadea tried not to lose faith in
himself during the streak, but the number finally got to him last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some girl in a bar asked me how old I was and I told her 21
because I've got that number in my mind, all over my brain,'' said
Spadea, 25, laughing after finishing most of his media obligations
at about 11p.m. He hadn't yet called his parents but wished they
had been here after all they've put into his career over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one became his number after Spadea lost to Sebastien
Grosjean last week. That loss broke an ATP record held by Gary
Donnelly, a Phoenix doubles specialist who lost 20 straight from
November 1996 to September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Spadea said he thought about his streak just once while playing
Rusedski and admitted to himself then that losing this match _
after failing to convert two set points in the second set and two
match points in both the fourth and fifth sets _ would be ``very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But the streak hasn't haunted him daily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough patch in my life in tennis,'' Spadea said.
``It didn't really faze me so much. I was trying to enjoy my life a
little more, trying to improve my tennis game. Everything wasn't
clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   He kept going to the gym, brought on former Australian star Pat
Cash to help his game, kept playing and kept trying to improve upon
his career-high No.19 ranking, where he finished 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't playing poorly,'' he said. ``I had a great year last
year, but I needed to add some things to get to even a further
level. I just wasn't sure how to do it. I wasn't that organized.
It's hard to improve, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   And when he saw his Wimbledon draw, he wasn't encouraged,
despite his usual good results against top players in big
tournaments. He suspected television and fans would be watching
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to put a microscope on me,'' Spadea said.
``With a guy who is a great grass-court player, and my record on
grass, it just made it so much more adverse.''
</P>
<P>
   But he endured, after he and Rusedski fought like gladiators, as
he put it.
</P>
<P>
   Spadea credited Cash, who has been helping him informally since
his first-round loss at the French Open. Spadea came straight to
London and started working on grass, particularly on approaching
the net, playing more aggressively and believing in himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very generous,'' Spadea said. ``It's been an amazing
experience to work with someone of that stature. He's definitely
changed my outlook on grass-court tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   And the victory can't hurt any of that, particularly the way it
came.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski, despite his column in The Sun, hinted at a foot injury
that has been hampering him but wouldn't elaborate and credited
Spadea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played well,'' said Rusedski, adding that he plans to
escape tennis for several days now. ``I didn't take my
opportunities when I had them. He's too good a player to lose as
many matches as he lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Spadea couldn't agree more and said he's curious to see how a
victory feels this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even analyzing the monkey that I had on my back,'' he
said. ``I'm just focused on the fact that this will be a great
memory, no matter what happened to me this year.''
</P>
<P>
   elizabethclarke(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
