<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concrete gorilla boasts face of George W. Bush, moves of Al Gore
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently it's just a silly coincidence that the 3,600-pound
concrete gorilla made and marketed by Double D Statuary looks like
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody who had access to do something like that
is that artistically inclined,'' said Kevin Barker, manager of
Double D's outlet yard on Interstate 35 between Temple and Waco,
Texas. He said the gorilla is made from a mold, so there may be
countless concrete gorillas out there from Double D that look like
the governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the gorillas come out of the exact same mold, so they're
all going to have to look very, very similar,'' he said. Barker
added he was not aware that the $660 gorilla looks like Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A reader of my book ``Texas Curiosities'' pointed out the eerie
resemblance between Bush and the life-size yard gorilla. The
concrete gorilla on Page 20 of the book is the spitting image of
the Republican presidential candidate, the reader noticed. I took
the picture of the gorilla, and I hadn't even notice-- .
</P>
<P>
   If Bush gets a presidential library, I wonder how long it'll be
before some wise guy leaves one of these gorillas on the front lawn
at night. Let me add that although the gorilla does not look like
Al Gore, it has Gore's moves. Actually, it may be a little quicker
than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the gorilla really does look like Bush. Don't take my word
for it. Check out the pictures of these two characters who appear
to have been separated at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Really, the look on the gorilla's face is the same one you get
when you ask Bush to name the capital of Outer Slobovia.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's the eyes that make them look so much alike. There
is that intensity in the gorilla's eyes that you see on Bush when
he appears to be deep in thought, assuming this occurs. It's the
pre-smirk look that the gorilla is giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I going to get national attention out of this?'' Barker
asked. ``Maybe I can be vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Kevin. The gorilla gets to be vice president, and you're
chairman of the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Double D also makes hippos, rhinos and gnomes. I wonder if it
has a troll that looks like Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   I saw a bumper sticker on the back of a truck in South Austin a
few months back that said ``George W. Bush for Lawn Ornament.'' I
wonder if this gorilla has anything to do with that? Maybe these
gorillas will end up taking the place of ice carvings at Republican
functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not familiar with it,'' Bush presidential campaign spokesman
Scott McClellan said of the concrete gorilla. ``It sounds like a
lot of political monkey business.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that Democrats always come up with funnier quotes?
Maybe it's because they drink more beer.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that George and George of the Jungle look the same
is just pure dumb luck. This is not, apparently, something that
came out of the Dirty Tricks Department at Democratic National
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gorilla's been out probably as long as he (Bush) has,''
said David Reyckert, owner of the Double D Statuary factory in San
Patricio County, about 25 miles northwest of Corpus Christi. That
gorilla, he said, has been manufactured for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we just came out with a 15-foot, 10,000-pound
alligator,'' Reyckert said. ``I don't know how close it looks to
Gore, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it sounds more like Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
