<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History reweaved still fabric
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A young friend became terribly enthused about a religion-class
assignment that challenged her to come up with the top five
questions she would pose to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the question for me!'' exclaimed the Inquisitive
One, furiously jotting down her questions: ``God, why, are you
important?'' ``Why do we have to die?'' and the ultimate
unfathomable: ``Why is it so weird to be alive?''
</P>
<P>
   Some questions _ in this life, at any rate _ are destined to
remain unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   With DNA literally rewriting history, however, many of our
unanswered questions are being answered.
</P>
<P>
   Did Thomas Jefferson father some of Sally Hemmings' children?
Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Shawnee warrior Blue Jacket and a white man named
Marmaduke Van Swearingen one and the same? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   DNA's usefulness as a historical tool is undeniable. It puts to
rest centuries of speculation about Jefferson, and challenges
centuries of denial about the realities of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Yet are we learning more than we need to know? Could literal
truth undercut the power of legend?
</P>
<P>
   Pure legends can spring purely from our cultural hunger. Legends
based on history, however, perch on that treacherous precipice
between fact and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   We always knew that the Blue Jacket story, as presented every
summer in a Greene County amphitheater, is larger than life. But we
were prepared to believe that Blue Jacket might have been Van
Swearingen, a white man raised by the Shawnee tribe, until DNA
testing at Wright State University cast doubt on the legend.
</P>
<P>
   How much does historical accuracy matter when a legend comes to
life on stage?
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Blue Jacket not being related to the Van Swearingens,
it is not really that important to anyone but the family that
claimed him,'' said Brian Hackett, director of the Montgomery
County (Ohio) Historical Society. ``He still did what he did. The
tests did not prove he was not a white man, just not a Van
Swearingen. The story is still strong.''
</P>
<P>
   And myth? ``It is very important for the understanding of
history,'' Hackett said. ``It helps define who we are. It draws us
into a community and makes us whole. There are countless examples
where the myth is more powerful than the truth. It is part of our
makeup. Myth is the fabric of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   With Blue Jacket, we're dealing with both historical fact and
family legend. What becomes tricky is which branch of the family is
telling the story. Who's writing the legend?
</P>
<P>
   ``The story comes through white records and not native
stories,'' noted Gaelann AllCorn, marketing manager for Cityfolk.
``I do know some of the Blue Jacket family believe the story, but
other descendants believe their ancestor was always native.''
</P>
<P>
   AllCorn, a native American, is a strong believer in
storytelling: ``I teach my daughter through things that are passed
down as stories. Our stories always contain kernels of truth or
moral lessons that are important to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   AllCorn calls the Blue Jacket production ``wonderful,'' but
thinks the story line should be altered to reflect the new facts.
``I think there are a lot of things that need to be set straight as
far as native people are concerned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Must all of our cultural myths now pass through technology's
crucible? Will time travel ultimately prove that George Washington
never whacked that cherry tree?
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope not. As Hackett observed, ``Storytellers have always
had a revered place in our world, from the cave man campfire to
Steven Spielberg.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one truth no amount of DNA testing can ever challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
