r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX     06-28 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cracking the genetic code has opened a whole new can of worms
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he was introduced by President Clinton as one of the men
responsible for mapping the human genome, Dr. Craig Venter wrote
about the possibility of genetically engineering a man with bird
wings.
</P>
<P>
   That's the image most people have of angels.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a scientific breakthrough that can put God out of
business has to disturb some people.
</P>
<P>
   On a morning television network news show following Monday's
White House announcement that scientists completed a first draft of
the human book of life, Venter, who runs for-profit Celera
Genomics, and Dr. Francis Collins, head of the government-sponsored
Human Genome Research Institute, were asked if they believed in
God.
</P>
<P>
   Collins quickly and easily answered yes. He felt his scientific
research bolstered his religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   Venter began his answer by recounting his extensive research in
various scientific endeavors. He concluded by saying that he is
convinced that what he has seen is not man-made.
</P>
<P>
   To say that the blueprint of human life is not man-made is not
the same as professing a belief in God.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps aliens from an undiscovered dimension seeded this Petri
dish of a universe with a bit of DNA to see what would grow. At
this point, humans are the dominant life culture in this remote
section of the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   It may be considered rude to ask a scientist if he believes in
God, but the question has relevance for people who think that
humans are getting to the point where they are playing God. The
question sheds more light on the questioner than on the person
asked to reveal private beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, if scientists like Dr. Venter will be able to
splice the genetic instructions for a bird's wings into a human and
create a man who can fly, that would be unnatural meddling with
life.
</P>
<P>
   If the new genetic maps can be used to cure diseases such as
AIDS, Alzheimer's, malaria, cholera and cancer, then people will be
inclined to say the scientists are doing God's work.
</P>
<P>
   Curing diseases has theological and moral consequences. Venter
says 50 diseases are responsible for 90 percent of human death and
illness.
</P>
<P>
   If genetic advances overcame these diseases, the resulting
population explosion could spell disaster for the planet.
Disease-free people with twice the current life-span would quickly
strip the planet of its remaining natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic scientists would have to hold a few incurable diseases
in reserve so they could initiate occasional epidemics to bring the
population back into balance. War is another way to reduce surplus
population.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are working on genetically engineered food that will
better feed all the extra people saved by science from premature
death. Transgenic food already is causing a rebellion in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be right for people who refuse to eat genetically
engineered food that can save the planet from starvation to take
advantage of genetic engineering that will extend their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where people can be engineered to be healthy,
intelligent and vigorous, discrimination against disabled people
will increase in insurance, employment and other aspects of life.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to reduce bad genetic predispositions will
accelerate the pressure to enhance good genetic predispositions.
China, India and several other na- tions now have distressingly
high abortion rates for female fetuses. Abortions should go up when
parents can learn that an unborn child is likely to be homosexual
or at risk for certain diseases.
</P>
<P>
   When science can create perfect babies, few pa- rents would
accept a baby less than perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps science can create a perfect theologian to solve these
riddles.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
