<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SYRIA-CLASSICCARS-062     06-28 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-CLASSICCARS-0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLASSIC CARS, ANCIENT CITY: CHROME, FINS GIVE DAMASCUS CHARM
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ The names come out a little differently in
Arabic. DeSoto becomes something like ``Tozata'' and Chrysler
sounds like ``Kleezler.''
</P>
<P>
   But those old bombs you might find in an auto collector's garage
in America make for colorful and practical transportation in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The country's streets are flush with fins and crawling with
chrome. Stroll the centuries-old bazaars and you're likely to be
passed not only your father's Oldsmobile, but his father's before
him.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Malik Sheikho has a 1951 DeSoto powered by a hefty 1987
Caprice motor. Pictures of the late President Hafez Assad in the
windows make it clear that this cherry-red hybrid is pure Syrian.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikho, a 37-year-old auto parts dealer, says his car is both
sensible and sensational. It's sensible because his extended family
fits inside. It's sensational for the tire-screeching fun he has
taking the corners in this ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's striking,'' he says. ``I drove it to Beirut once and
everyone stared at me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, new cars are the norm. But in Damascus and other
Syrian cities, cars of yesterday are as common as the spices and
mother-of-pearl furniture in the markets.
</P>
<P>
   The affinity for retro cars is not entirely by choice. Syria's
closed economy is still mired in socialist strictures set down more
than 30 years ago. The streets of Cuba, for example, have a
similarly antiquated fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Under the socialist code, cars are a luxury and not necessary
for people meant to focus on their country's industry and defense.
In Syria, new-car buyers can be slapped with a 300(CQ) percent tax
levy and must buy registrations costing thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   While there are still some new cars on the road, many Syrians
turn to miracle-working mechanics to keep the old cars running. It
makes for an old car craze born out of necessity as well as style.
</P>
<P>
   On the style side is car collector Bashar Assad. The 34-year-old
eye doctor tapped to be the successor to his father, President
Hafez Assad, who died June 10.
</P>
<P>
   But, he's also chairman of the Classic Car Club of Syria. He
counts two vintage Cadillac El Dorados _ early '50s and early '60s
_ among his collection.
</P>
<P>
   Samir Darwish, president of the club and a friend of the Assad
family, said the younger Assad still drives himself and is very
safe, fitting for soft-spoken leader originally trained as an
ophthalmologist.
</P>
<P>
   Darwish, a wealthy Syrian businessman, owns several classics
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Among his fleet are a 1950 Fiat Ciento with ``woodie'' sidings
and a 1963 Pontiac Parisian convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian roads are Darwish's primary auto show room. On the
streets, he finds old cars, usually motley combinations of
different motors and chassis, and rebuilds them with the original
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It's the restrictions on imports that keep the old cars on the
road. Darwish said there is only about one car for every 17
Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't buy a new shirt, you at least wash the shirt you
have,'' he says. ``You keep it looking good until you can get a new
one.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Hosh Blass(CQ) industrial zone on the edge of Damascus, a
stroll amid the rows of auto shops finds bug-eyed headlights,
airplane-wing hood ornaments, metal dashboards and few seatbelts.
</P>
<P>
   Here, motorists say they have old cars because they are cheap
and big, which is helpful for families with just one car. Some
owners do not even know the particular make of their car, except
that it is a Buick or Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Lotfik, owns an elegant 1951 Austin with an Opel engine
and BMW wheels. He understands a foreigner's admiration for his
wheels, but says he would rather have something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's history. A lot of people like it, but not here in our
country,'' he says. He would rather have a new Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more enthusiastic, even for cars that would be
considered clunkers in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's American. It's strong and powerful,'' mechanic Kiork(CQ)
Sarkisian, 60, says of his vinyl-topped, white 1976 Buick Century.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics get the job done by reworking old parts and
subbing in newer ones. Sheikho's 1951 DeSoto, for example, has
Cadillac dome lights inside, electric windows and even a
remote-control starter.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic Samer Najjar, 28, said he's been working on cars since
his teens and has always been able to find the right parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is possible, especially in this country,'' he says.
``Thanks to God, there is always something available.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For promotional information about Syria:
</P>
<P>
   www.cafe-syria.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
