<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENTRAPMENT (San Francisco) _ Mark Poehlman was trolling the
Internet for someone to share his passions for cross-dressing and
foot fetishism. He answered an ad placed by ``Sharon,'' who
expressed interest but said she was really seeking a ``special
teacher'' for her three young daughters. He eventually traveled
from his Florida home to Long Beach, Calif., where Sharon showed
him some child pornography and then delivered him into the waiting
arms of state and federal agents. On Tuesday, the U.S. 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals ruled that Poehlman had been entrapped, and
overturned his 10-year federal prison sentence for crossing state
lines to engage in sex with a minor. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   MIRANDA-CALIF (San Francisco) _ The U.S. Supreme Court's
unexpectedly strong affirmation of its famous Miranda rule _ that
police advise suspects of their right to remain silent before
interrogations _ will likely stem a statewide California practice
in which officers had deliberately violated it, lawyers said. By
SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-INSURANCE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Insurance
Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush's political future has grown even
darker after a dramatic Assembly hearing that included allegations
of document shredding, back-door coercion and abuse of power.
Quackenbush has been accused of coddling insurance companies after
the 1994 Northridge earthquake. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-HISPANICS (Undated) _ Showtime's ``Resurrection Blvd.''
should be judged as it is: a solid family drama with the potential
to get even better. But because its cast and crew are almost
entirely Hispanic _ a group grossly underrepresented on television
_ the program takes on greater symbolism and meaning: This show has
to make it. It can't be just OK; it must be a trailblazer. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-PATRIOT (Undated) _ Mel Gibson's new movie goes
where most vanity projects fear to tread: 1776. But that's all
right; he's gone there with sci-fi action director Roland Emmerich
calling the shots. So the result _ in spite of the puffy white
shirts, mussed ponytails, 13-starred American flags and nameless
slaves _ feels more like 1996. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RETINA-DISEASE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Macular degeneration, a disease
that affects the light-sensitive cells that line the back of the
eye, affects up to 30 million people worldwide and is the leading
cause of blindness in the United States in adults older than 60.
Although no one knows what causes it, a new treatment is providing
patients some relief. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   PT-BOAT (San Antonio) _ After toiling six years to restore a
rare World War II combat boat, a group of Galveston, Texas,
volunteers isn't ready to surrender PT-309 so it can be displayed
outside the Nimitz Museum in Fredericksburg, Texas. The craft is
the only existing torpedo boat known to have seen combat in World
War II. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-GROUP (San Francisco) _ Partners in The Welcomed Consensus
describe themselves as one man and several women living together in
sexual harmony, offering classes that teach everything from
seduction methods to a one-hour orgasm. But Erwan Davon has other
names for the group and its ``training programs,'' which have been
going on for years in San Francisco and other Bay Area cities:
Pimping. Prostitution. Pandering. He claims he gave The Welcomed
Consensus more than $136,000 in cash and stock options and sued the
group in San Francisco this month, asking for his money back. By
PETER HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BERRIES (San Antonio) _ Before the world shrank, allowing fresh
fruits and vegetables from once-distant continents to fill grocery
shelves year-round, anticipation grew as the seasonal arrival of
old favorites approached. Now we take it for granted that we can
get any foods whenever we want, courtesy of overnight shipping and
greenhouses in places like Chile and Costa Rica. Yet somehow
berries have survived produce's endless summer. By JOHN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-WINERY (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ Cooperstown, one of
upstate New York's hottest tourist draws thanks to the Baseball
Hall of Fame, has a new attraction: Bear Pond Winery. Located a
dozen miles south of Cooperstown in the hamlet of Milford Center,
Bear Pond is attempting to make the most of its connection to the
national pastime. The wines include All Star Chardonnay, Grand Slam
Champagne and Fielder's Choice Rosario. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PESO-ELECTION (San Antonio) _ For the first time since the
1970s, the Mexican presidential election may not wreak its
election-year havoc on the peso. Border banks and cross-border
trade-related businesses that would feel the pinch of a plummet
have seen few signs that Mexico's election Sunday will send the
peso into a free fall. This time around, a stronger Mexican
economy, a more stable political climate and the fact that more
business in Mexico is conducted in dollars bolster the peso. By
ASSATOU SIDIM and BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (Undated) _ All right, so watching people eat raw
bugs and barbecued rats may not meet your definition of
entertainment. It doesn't matter. You still have to watch
``Survivor'' on CBS. It's the most educational workplace-related
television show since ``Roller Derby.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ We started almost reverently,
carefully negotiating which family photograph should go to which
brother or sister. But four days into cleaning out our parents'
house, my brother Jamie was passing out old family photographs like
a blackjack dealer. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
