<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-FILE     06-28 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDS: FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: In connection with high fuel prices, I keep reading about
this nation's strategic oil reserves. How much oil is there, and
where are these reserves?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Strategic Petroleum Reserve is estimated to be 570
million barrels (enough to last about two months at normal
nationwide consumption levels).
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy oversees the reserve, which is stored
in underground salt caverns along the Gulf Coast of Louisiana and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was announced recently that 25 people won MacArthur
Foundation ``genius grants'' of $500,000. The article stated there
were no strings attached, and the money would be paid over five
years. Are the winners required to pay income taxes on these
awards, or are the taxes prepaid?
</P>
<P>
   A: The fellowships are taxable to the recipients, said Elizabeth
Kennedy at the MacArthur Fellows Program.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting: Although the term ``genius'' is commonly used in
news articles about the fellowship grants and their recipients, the
MacArthur Foundation doesn't use that word. Why? Because, as the
foundation explains, it ``connotes a singular characteristic of
intellectual prowess . . . The people we seek to support express
many other important qualities: ability to transcend traditional
boundaries, willingness to take risks, persistence in the face of
personal and conceptual obstacles, capacity to synthesize disparate
ideas and approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A lawyer on TV stated that in order to assign the death
penalty in Texas, jurors must answer three questions. Can you tell
me what these question are, and their exact wording?
</P>
<P>
   A: Heather Browne of the Texas attorney general's office
explained that for offenses committed on or after Sept. 1, 1991,
the questions _ as stipulated in Article 37.071 of the Texas Code
of Criminal Procedure _ are these:
</P>
<P>
   (1) whether there is a probability that the defendant would
commit criminal acts of violence that would constitute a continuing
threat to society; and
</P>
<P>
   (2) in cases in which the jury charge at the guilt-innocence
phase permitted the jury to find the defendant guilty as a party
under Sections 7.01 and 7.02 of the Penal Code, whether the
defendant actually caused the death of the deceased or did not
actually cause the death of the deceased but intended to kill the
deceased or another or anticipated that a human life would be
taken.
</P>
<P>
   If both (1) and (2) are answered affirmatively, then the jury is
asked the following question: Whether, taking into consideration
all of the evidence, including the circumstances of the offense,
the defendant's character and background, and the personal moral
culpability of the defendant, there is a sufficient mitigating
circumstance or circumstances to warrant that a sentence of life
imprisonment rather than a death sentence be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury answers the questions ``yes,'' ``yes'' and ``no,''
the death penalty is imposed automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since we've just had the longest day of the year, how much
time do we lose each day until we reach Dec. 21, the shortest day?
Is it a few seconds, a minute, a couple of minutes?
</P>
<P>
   A: How much daylight is ``lost'' from June 21 to Dec. 21 _ the
summer and winter solstices _ depends a lot on where you live on
the Earth. A person at the North Pole wouldn't even see the sun set
until September. But for an example, let's use Atlanta. There, June
21 has about 14 hours and 25 minutes between sunrise and sunset. By
Dec. 21, that has dwindled to about 9 hours and 55 minutes _ a
total loss of 4 1/2 hours in six months. That's an average of
nearly 1 1/2 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   In actuality, the daily loss is slower near the solstices in
June and December and faster in late September, near the autumnal
equinox.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall that relatives of John Wilkes Booth wanted to exhume
his body several years ago because they suspected it wasn't the
real Booth buried in the grave. Whatever became of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: A Maryland appeals court refused in June 1996 to let Booth's
relatives open his grave to determine if soldiers who tracked down
President Abraham Lincoln's assassin had shot the wrong man.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Booth's distant relatives wanted the body exhumed from
the grave to test a persistent theory that he escaped after the
assassination and lived for years under aliases while someone else
was buried in his grave.
</P>
<P>
   Green Mount Cemetery in Baltimore refused their request, and a
lower court upheld its right to control the grave site. That ruling
was affirmed by a three-judge panel of the Court of Special
Appeals, Maryland's second-highest court.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you identify a bothersome insect that has a small, black
body and a red head? When it bites, it feels like a pinch, and it
often leaves a red welt that lasts for days. Also, is there a
recommended repellant?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be dealing with the azalea plant bug Rhinocapsis
vanduzeei, said Beverly Sparks of the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   These plant bugs are a predator of the azalea lace bug, so they
actually are beneficial to have around, because they can keep
azalea lace bug populations at low levels. However, as you perhaps
painfully noted, they can deliver a bite to humans. They have
piercing mouth parts and, if exposed to a human arm or neck, for
example, will ``test'' to see if they're a suitable food.
</P>
<P>
   Control of these insects isn't necessary, Sparks explained. What
you should do is avoid close contact with azalea plants that are
infested. Once populations of lace bugs are not available, these
bugs usually will leave in search of other prey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I received an e-mail saying that as part of the settlement of
a lawsuit, Gerber Foods is awarding a $550 savings bond to children
born between 1985 and 1997. The messages says we're supposed to
forward the e-mail to churches, relatives and friends. Is there any
validity to this?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is the Hoax That Will Not Die. It's hard to believe it's
making the rounds once again.
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A first reported on it in October 1997. As Gerber Products Co.
stated at the time _ and continues to say even now _ the so-called
settlement is ``completely inaccurate and false.''
</P>
<P>
   This misinformation appears to have started circulating after a
1996 settlement involving Enfamil and Similac infant formula and
pricing issues, but Gerber was not connected with that litigation.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Gerber says, the deadline for filing claims in that
1996 settlement expired Jan. 31, 1997. The company also says a
Minneapolis post office box listed in the e-mail for sending
documentation to Gerber for the ``claims'' has been closed by
Minneapolis postal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   More information can be found online at
www.gerber.com/contactus/faq.asp?faqcatid &QC; 6.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Detroit is the 10th-largest city in the United
States. Can you list all the top 10?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the top 10 most populous U.S cities, by estimate,
as of July 1, 1998, according to the Census Bureau: New York, 7.4
million; Los Angeles, 3.6 million; Chicago, 2.8 million; Houston,
1.8 million; Philadelphia, 1.4 million; San Diego, 1.22 million;
Phoenix, 1.2 million; San Antonio, 1.11 million; Dallas, 1.1
million; and Detroit, 970,000.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the last census whose statistics are available, Detroit
ranked No. 7 with 1.03 million people. These statistics are for
city limits, not metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
