 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDS: FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported on how you can obtain a replacement
Social Security card. But tell me, if someone mails in their
driver's license or work ID, how do they go around without them
until the Social Security Administration returns them?
</P>
<P>
   A: While the Social Security Administration requires proof of
identity in an application for a replacement card, the applicant
isn't required to mail the documents. An applicant can present them
in person at their nearest Social Security office, said agency
spokeswoman Patti Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are a driver's license or work ID the only acceptable
documents. Others _ which an applicant might be better able to do
without temporarily _ include passport, marriage or divorce record,
adoption record, health insurance card, military records, insurance
policy or school ID card.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the documents will be returned, Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Tiger Woods finish his college education, or did he leave
early to turn pro?
</P>
<P>
   A: The latter. In the fall of 1994, Woods, who had been playing
golf since early childhood, entered Stanford University in
California on a full scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   For some time a debate raged in the media over whether he should
drop out of college to turn pro or complete his degree first. At
16, he already had become the youngest person ever to play on the
PGA Tour, in the 1992 L.A. Open.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after winning the NCAA Division 1 championship
individual title for the first time, and after making history with
his unprecedented third U.S. Amateur title that August, Woods chose
to leave school and play golf as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can fans write to Phil Jackson, coach of the Los Angeles
Lakers, to congratulate him and his team on winning the NBA title?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mail can be addressed to him in care of Los Angeles Lakers,
Staples Center, 1111 S. Figueroa St., Los Angeles, CA 90015.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several articles about a museum dinosaur being reconstructed
say the bones were found in Argentina. Isn't it true that no human
has ever seen a dinose actual bone has long been replaced by
minerals during the fossilization process,'' Bean explained. ``Very
little of the original bone material still remains in what we
usually find.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some exceptions, although not in this case. An article
in Earth magazine reports discoveries in South Dakota's Hell Creek
formation of fossilized intact sections of bone that contain
original proteins from the bones. They were documented by the
Museum of the Rockies in Montana, Bean said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We know why actor Christopher Reeve publicly supports
research into curing spinal injuries, and Michael J. Fox does for
Parkinson's disease. But does anyone know why Jerry Lewis has been
so involved in muscular dystrophy research? When did his interest
begin?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although people have speculated that he might have known
someone, perhaps a relative, who was stricken with a neuromuscular
disease, Lewis has never disclosed a specific reason for his
interest and involvement, according to the Muscular Dystrophy
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and then-partner Dean Martin became involved with MDA in
the 1950s, said association spokesman Jim Brown, doing three
fund-raising TV campaigns around Thanksgiving. Lewis started his
solo Labor Day telethons for MDA in 1966 ``and works for us
tirelessly year-round,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Q : What sort of salary or compensation does Jerry Lewis receive
for the work he does on behalf of the Muscular Dystrophy
Association?
</P>
<P>
   A: He donates his services and receives no compensation of any
kind, MDA says.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a computer illiterate, I'm curious: How big are the two
hard drives with secret information that were missing and then
found at Los Alamos? Are they like the tower on a computer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The hard drives, which disappeared from the weapons lab in
early May and then reappeared last week inside the lab's secure
area, are about the size of a deck of cards.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI continues to investigate the circumstances of the
disappearance and the authenticity and condition of the hard drives
that were found behind a copying machine in an area that had
previously been searched.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about the two Florida schools that finally got off
the state education department's ``F'' list included part of a
poem, ``The Man Who Thinks He Can.'' I'm not familiar with that.
Can you print the entire poem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Waler D. Wintle's ``The Man Who Thinks He Can'':
</P>
<P>
   If you think you are beaten, you are/ If you think you dare not,
you don't/ If you would like to win but you think you can't/ It's
almost a cinch you won't./
</P>
<P>
   If you think you'll lose, you're lost/ For out in the world we
find,/ Success begins with a fellow's will,/ It's all in the state
of mind./
</P>
<P>
   If you think you're outclassed, you are/ You've got to think
high to rise/ You've got to be sure of yourself/ Before you can
ever win a prize./
</P>
<P>
   Life's bsattles don't always go to the stronger or the faster
man,/ But sooner or later, the man who wins/ Is the man who thinks
he can.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to have ice cubes that are clear, not clouded.
What's the secret so I can do this with my home freezer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Connie Crawley of the University of Georgia Extension Service
suggests boiling the water and letting it cool slightly. Then pour
it into ice cube trays and let it cool some more.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a bit of experimenting at each stage to see if the
water has cooled sufficiently before being frozen to achieve the
desired clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
