<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-DIALECT     06-28 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-DIALECT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILLY WEB SITE CAUGHT IN SERIOUS FREE-SPEECH FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers 
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or
888-603-1036.) 
 By RICHARD HIGGINS   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silly, you say, a free Web site that can turn the lyrics of the
Marine Corps Hymn into a dialect called Swedish Chef: ``Frum zee
hells ooff Muntezooma tu zee shures ooff Treepuli.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, to render it in Elmer Fuddese: ``. . . to the shaws of
Twipowi.''
</P>
<P>
   And being silly was all a New Hampshire man was aiming for when
he created the Dialectizer page two years ago. It will turn any
text, including Web pages, into one of seven pseudo dialects.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Samuel Stoddard has become enmeshed in an Internet
free-speech battle. Last month, he shut down the Dialectizer page
after corporate lawyers raised the threat of a copyright lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an outpouring of support from around the country and
offers of donations for legal fees, Stoddard, who lives in
Somersworth, N.H., has reopened an altered version of Dialectizer
on his entertainment Web site, Rinkworks.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started doing this because I thought it was pretty
amusing,'' said Stoddard, 26, a software engineer for a computer
networking company in Durham, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intended to tackle the First Amendment. I'm glad I'm
in this, though, because it's interesting. It just wasn't the fight
I counted on having.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoddard started Dialectizer two years ago as a parody of
legitimate Web translation sites. It is one page on Rinkworks.com,
which includes film reviews, science fiction features, and lots of
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can type in text or an entire Web page to be translated
into seven fake dialects: Redneck, Cockney, Elmer Fudd, Swedish
Chef, Pig Latin, Moron, and Jive.
</P>
<P>
   The page became more popular than Stoddard imagined, with 7,000
to 8,000 hits a day and as many as 10,000 hits on peak use days.
The traffic jammed his servers. Overall, Rinkworks.com has about
100,000 visitors a day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dialectizer relies on basic programming, performing ``search and
replace'' functions according to translation rules that Stoddard
developed and occasionally refines for an extra ounce of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dialects are works in progress,'' said Stoddard, whose
``office'' is no more than a Pentium Pro desktop computer in the
family room of his house in Somersworth, just north of Portsmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote Redneck and Moron from scratch, but the others I
picked up and modified from the Web,'' who gets part-time help from
a friend, Dave Parker. ``They were thrown out there as freeware.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble began when people started translating entire Web pages
into the dialects. Some Web site developers and companies were not
only not amused, but they began protesting.
</P>
<P>
   Stoddard agreed to block the translation of any Web sites that
complained. By April, he had done so for 10 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in early May, he got a letter from a lawyer for the Bank
of America. Not only did the lawyer, Larry Jones, want the
translation of the bank's Web site blocked, but he raised the
possibility that Stoddard was committing copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their threat was the last straw for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stoddard said he is confident that he was not breaking
any law, proving himself right could be expensive, and on May 10 he
shut down Dialectizer.
</P>
<P>
   That proved equally unpopular _ but to a different crowd.
Outraged techies and other supporters of Dialectizer, alerted by a
piece on Slashdot, a Web site created by anticopyright computer
programmers, responded by attacking the ``corporate bullies'' who
saw copyright problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of this e-rage, he was getting one e-mail a
minute. Several of those e-mails are in the Slashdot archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that corporations are using the threat of a lawsuit
to force individuals to conform to their dictates just frosts my
butt,'' wrote ``Geekbird'' on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time for a round of Lawyer Skeet Shooting,'' said another
message.
</P>
<P>
   Others described how much fun they had had translating documents
like Microsoft copyright announcements into Redneck.
</P>
<P>
   Yet others attacked Stoddard for closing down the site, with one
person saying someone should ``shoot the loser wimp who runs the
Dialectizer for caving in to folks at Bank of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was overwhelmed by the response,'' said Stoddard.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stoddard said he had been gradually losing interest in
Dialectizer, the response ``fired me up.'' On June 5, he brought
the page back up _ this time with an expanded legal defense of
Dialectizer and a prominent notice that any Web site can be
blocked. The revised site also includes a link allowing
organizations to block their own site.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the Bank of America attorney, said through a spokeswoman
that he was satisfied with the fact that the company was able to
block its site from being parodied.
</P>
<P>
   But the threatened suit might have been hard for the bank to
win. Jon Grossman, a lawyer in Washington who specializes in
copyright law, said the Dialectizer probably would fall under
protection from copyright law offered to parody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems clear to me that what we are offering is protected by
law,'' said Stoddard, noting that courts have not found
``derivative parodies of works'' to be copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the people who are objecting are taking
themselves and their work a little too seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since reopening the site with instructions about blocking,
things have become more civil, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he received a request for a site to be blocked, and
``it was refreshing to see it worded in a civil, professional
manner. The requests for site blocks I got before had a much
angrier tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that only gives Stoddard more time to fend off
another controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of Dialectizer, he said he has received e-mail
from people who find the translations into Jive to be racist and
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Stoddard disagrees and has put a lengthy disclaimer on the Web
page stating that acknowledging ``cultural differences'' does not
mean discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we will ever conquer racism,'' it states, ``is
not by suppressing those differences but by cherishing them,
bringing them out into the open in such a comfortable and
nonthreatening way that we become at ease enough with them . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Angry e-mails and letters from lawyers aside, the support he has
received _ and the higher profile his Web site has gained _ have
encouraged Stoddard, who nurtures hopes of being a filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The increased popularity has also brought offers to buy
Rinkworks.com, but Stoddard is not interested in selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life's passion is here,'' he said. ``I've really tried
to harness everything I care about. So I'm not going to sell. It's
a lot of work, but I'd rather keep doing it as a passionate
hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-00 1316EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
