<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES BRITISH TELECOM OWN HYPERLINKS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lads at British Telecom finally cleaned out their closets
the other day. And there, amid old biscuit tins and burnt-out
vacuum tubes, they stumbled across a chunk of solid gold. Or fool's
gold. Time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   If you're reading this on the World Wide Web, you probably got
here by clicking a hyperlink, a spot on the Web page that lets you
hop to some other spot on the Internet just by clicking a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperlinks are vital to the working of the Web. We could make do
without them; there are lots of other ways to find stuff on the
Internet. But it was the application of hyperlinks that made
Internet use simple enough for 5-year-olds and journalists. It was
the hyperlink that transformed the Internet from a geeky curiosity
to a prime mover of the world's economy.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? British Telecom owns the hyperlink, or thinks it
does. During a recent search through its 15,000 or so patents,
company lawyers came across US Patent Number 4,873,662, applied for
in 1980, granted in 1989. It's a patent for an ``information
handling system and terminal apparatus therefor,'' and I've got to
admit that the system sounds quite a bit like hyperlinking.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody at BT noticed the same thing. Now the company has begun
contacting American Internet providers, to discuss the size of the
royalty checks. Ironically, only American companies are targeted,
because similar BT patents in other lands have all expired. The US
patent was issued much later than the others, and will remain in
effect until 2009.
</P>
<P>
   The news has a lot of Web site owners planning a reenactment of
the Boston Tea Party, and vowing never to pay the British company a
dime. But BT's royalty raid will likely have no effect on Internet
commoners. BT has no intention of seeking cash from people with
hyperlinks inside their Web pages. ``That would be nonsensical,''
said BT spokesman Simon Craven.
</P>
<P>
   Not very lucrative either. But America Online, Earthlink,
Microsoft Network _ those are companies with real money. BT may
also try to collect fees from makers of the software people use to
design their hyperlinked Web pages. ``What we're looking for,''
says Craven, ``is a reasonable royalty based on revenues that
others enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   They might be looking for quite some time, if American firms dig
in and fight. ``I think British Telecom has some serious explaining
to do,'' said Colorado patent attorney Carl Oppedahl.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, why did the company wait so long before asserting
its patent rights? Craven says that it really wasn't worth
bothering about until 1996 or so, when the Internet began to put on
weight. But that's still four years ago. ``Laches'' is a Latin word
meaning ``use it or lose it.'' It's also a principle of patent law,
says Oppedahl. Hold off too long on enforcing your patent, and it
dies.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another bit of legal jargon: ``prior art.'' This refers
to whether a technology really is original. A live patent dies fast
and hard if it turns out that others had previously come up with
the idea, and put it to use. It took only a few minutes' scouring
of the Internet to find evidence that BT was late to the concept of
hyperlinking.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Engelbart always was quick on the uptake. He's credited
as the inventor of the computer mouse. In the 1960s he was also
tinkering with a data management system he called NLS.
</P>
<P>
   If you drop in at Engelbart's Web site at www.bootstrap.org,
you'll see that NLS seems to embody the basic ideas found in the BT
patent. Sure looks like prior art to me. Then there's Engelbart's
pal Andries van Dam, a professor at Brown University. He and
Engelbart were shopping hyperlinked databases to companies like IBM
in the late 1960s, according to a document on display at the Brown
University Web site. Van Dam went on to a similar system of his own
called FRESS that was humming away at Brown during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. van Dam is traveling and hasn't reviewed the BT patent, but
he declares: ``I would be amazed if they had come up with something
sufficiently unique to support a patent claim.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing will likely be settled by the true masters of
the Internet _ lawyers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Internet service providers may just shrug and pay up.
What do they care? They'll pay serious cash before this case is
closed.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is whether it'll go to their legal teams, or
our cousins across the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-00 1312EDT &QL;
</P>
