<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-B0MBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAG AND ... IT'S JUST A DRAG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am in dire need of your perspicacity. My
current system is disgusting (a Pentium II with Windows 98 Second
Edition). The clock will lose a full day in about two weeks. Also,
when you click the mouse pointer on something, there is a delay,
and when I type, there is a delay before the letters show up. I
call the hardware manufacturer, and he blames the software or the
operating system. I call the software company, and they blame the
hardware or the OS. I have never been able to talk to a real person
at Microsoft, so I am unsure who they'd blame.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slow Motion
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SLOW: There are no real people at Microsoft. I mean, have
you ever actually seen anyone who works there, other than Big Bill
or Steve Ballmer? Or maybe the're all just hiding in their
windowless little offices, eating aerosol cheese and sardines,
hoping nobody asks them why their products are so full of bugs.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I really hate about trying to run down a problem with
no clear solution is trying to get a straight answer out of a
support technician. I wish they'd just say they don't have a clue
instead of pointing a finger at somebody else. And before you say
it, yes, I've done the same thing when I've wanted to get rid of a
particularly annoying user and get back to playing Unreal
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, since I know I'll get the run-around from three or four
different help desks, I generally start looking for the answer
myself somewhere out there on the Internet. Try the Knowledge Base
at Microsoft (support.microsoft.com) first, although ``knowledge''
is a bit of a stretch. Maybe ``Stuff We Figured Out For Whiny
Users'' didn't sound so hot to the Marketing Department.
</P>
<P>
   Most software and hardware companies have similar collections of
fixes and suggestions on their Web sites. Just look for ``support''
links.
</P>
<P>
   The best places to find an answer, however, are news groups,
where you post a message and hopefully get an answer. When the
Internet was more text-based, these groups were fabulous places for
finding people with similar interests and problems, software,
little-known tips and, of course, dirty pictures. New Internet
users often pass the groups by, probably because the dirty pictures
are easier to see using a browser.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising the groups, I learned that you're not the only one out
there losing time and putting up with a jerky mouse and keyboard.
Most PC clocks are about as accurate as my SATs, plus a flaky
battery will exacerbate the problem. But there's something else
afoot here, a conspiracy of major proportions. OK, maybe not a
conspiracy and maybe not major, but let me point a few fingers
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Many people report the slowdowns happen after installing Win98
Second Edition or Microsoft's Y2K patches. Others complain that it
all started after installing Norton AntiVirus 5.0 with
Auto-Protect, which runs all the time. And even Microsoft says that
your system can slow down when running stuff like a virus checker
in the background. No definitive answer, but there are a few clues.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs just don't play well with Win98, so turn off your
virus checker and see if things speed up. No? Try this: Shut down
everything else that's going on behind the scenes. If you hit
Control-Alt-Delete, you'll get a dialogue box that lets you end
individual tasks. You can safely knock out everything but Explorer
and Systray. If that doesn't work, go back to the Microsoft support
site and look for document Q259161 for some other suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay says his editors are to blame for any
misinformation or outright lies that may appear in his columns.
Write him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-23-00 1154EDT &QL;
</P>
