<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-XML-WEB-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XML USHERS IN NEW WAVE OF WEB PAGE DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID SIMS   The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A potential successor to HTML, the computer language that tells
your browser how to display Web pages, could be a boon to small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It's called XML _ the Extensible Markup Language _ and it's a
bit like the story of the blind man and the elephant: depending on
where he approached it, he thought it was a snake, a rope, or a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that XML does do is allow you to create new markup
languages unique to a certain task.
</P>
<P>
   A markup language is a system of tags that lets you tell a
computer what certain content is or means. If you've ever looked at
the underlying code of a Web page (you can do this by pulling down
the View menu on your browser, and choosing Source), you'll see the
HTML (hypertext markup language) that makes the page show up in
your browser. Headlines are marked with an H1, italics are marked
with an ``i,'' and so on.
</P>
<P>
   HTML has a limited number of tags. But the ``extensible''
aspects of XML offer a way to create new tags for different uses.
So, for example, someone doing business in the wine industry could
create a markup language that included tags for things such as
vintage year, type of grape, winery, appellation, price, and so on.
They could call it the VML, the vintners' markup language, and it
would be just one of many XML languages.
</P>
<P>
   Why would they bother to do this? One advantage is that if
everyone in an industry can get together and agree that they will
use that markup language, then their Web servers can easily
exchange information about the goods they're buying and selling.
So, for example, I could do a search for all zinfandels from the
Alexander Valley, and ask my computer to list only those with
bottle prices between $10 and $30.
</P>
<P>
   That would be interesting, but more interesting would be if my
computer and the winery's computer could complete the transaction
on their own. So that if I were a reseller looking for a certain
price on a type of wine, I could set my machine to look for that,
and buy it when it found it. The winery's machine and mine could
complete the sale, I would get a confirmation from the winery's XML
server, and the wine would arrive at my store in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 30 years, some companies have been working on
systems like this to make computers do much of this work by talking
to each other. Collectively, they have been called EDI, or
electronic data interchange.
</P>
<P>
   But these systems have been expensive to implement and have been
limited to companies that can afford them.
</P>
<P>
   One of XML's promises is to bring EDI-like services to
companies, especially those in developing countries, that have been
unable to afford EDI _ which can cost millions of dollars to
implement.
</P>
<P>
   XML makes it possible to do this relatively cheaply, so that a
desktop machine running at a small shop in Thailand can communicate
over the Web with computers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Mac made everyone a desktop publisher, and as the
Web made everyone a global publisher, so might XML make every
business able to communicate electronically with every other
business _ all for pennies per transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups are contending to be the main repository for
these XML classifications, called schemas. Microsoft is sponsoring
one called BizTalk. Another group, called Oasis, is working with
the United Nations on a strategy called ebXML, which hopes to make
one global repository of this type of business information.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is still mostly wealthy companies that are working
to build this repository, a trickle-down effect may follow. Once
standards are defined, and vendors build tools to work with them,
these tools may become as inexpensive as Web development tools _ a
few hundred dollars or less. If that happens, it could be just one
more way that the Web levels the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-00 1711EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
