<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-WINDOWS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STRATEGY WILL MOVE MICROSOFT AWAY FROM PERSONAL COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Embracing an approach to computing it once
scoffed at, Microsoft unveiled a strategy Thursday that will
increasingly move its business away from the personal computer the
company has championed since the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would retool its product line to shift the
very focus of computing away from hardware devices and toward a new
generation of Internet-based software allowing people to interact
with data and one another whether they are using computers, digital
cell phones or interactive televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman, portrayed the long-awaited
initiative as ``more ambitious than anything we've done,'' adding,
``There is no Microsoft product that isn't touched by this
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The fanfare surrounding the announcement and demonstrations here
Thursday signaled that Microsoft considered the move as momentous
as its decision in December 1995 to ``embrace and extend'' the
Internet after being caught flatfooted by the rise of the World
Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's subsequent integration of a Web browser directly
into its Windows operating systems led to the antitrust case in
which a federal judge has ordered the company split in two and
imposed severe restrictions on its business practices.
</P>
<P>
   But those restrictions have now been suspended while appeals
proceed, probably for a year or more, lifting what Microsoft said
would be a serious impediment to the strategy it announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gates showed no signs Thursday of being intimidated by the
antitrust case, saying the browser, which he called a ``universal
canvas,'' would become the principal user interface for all
interaction with a variety of new services.
</P>
<P>
   In demonstrations and videos, Gates and his top executives
introduced what they portrayed as a vision of a new software
platform _ called .NET _ in which users will be surrounded by a
range of devices providing access to a universe of information,
including business and personal data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite like the past where there was a single device
that defines all of this,'' Gates said. ``There will be many
different devices.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy will involve repackaging some of the company's core
products, like its Office software, as subscription-based services
obtained over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said the new products would be introduced in increments
beginning next year, when Microsoft plans to introduce a version of
its Windows operating system to be called Windows.Net 1.0.
</P>
<P>
   He also demonstrated a natural language interface that would
permit people to interact with a machine via voice, handwriting or
commands entered in natural human language.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maritz, a Microsoft group vice president, said the overall
initiative would be ``a long march'' that could take a decade or
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft emphasized that the centerpiece of its new approach
would be an increasingly popular Internet standard, XML, that
facilitates the automatic interchange of information.
</P>
<P>
   In each example the company tried to show how the data-sharing
facility of XML would allow people who work and play together to
share information like scheduling, homework, music and videos to
collaborate seamlessly whether they were connected by PCs, cell
phones or tablet computers _ notebook-sized devices that can be
activated by pen, voice or keyboard, or read as books.
</P>
<P>
   One example of the power promised by the .NET world was a video
scenario in which a family posed for a digital portrait while on a
trip to the zoo. A child then transmitted the photo via his cell
phone to his grandparents, who were watching television. Without
leaving their couch they were able to view the image on the
television set, and then, with a simple command using the remote
control, they transferred the image to a nearby digital picture
frame.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy is striking because Microsoft's executives once
strongly resisted the notion that the personal computer might be
supplanted by competing products, from handheld devices to set-top
boxes to cell phones. In the mid-1990s the company was under
assault from competitors like Sun Microsystems, Netscape
Communications and the Oracle Corp., which were advocating an
approach called network computing that would have moved processing
power from the desktop to a centralized computer.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Microsoft's new view of computing calls for
processing to be done everywhere, from the desktop to the cell
phone to powerful network computers somewhere on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft took pains Thursday to make the case that the new .NET
strategy would be inclusive rather than exclusive and that it would
offer the new .NET services on competing platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we a company that is going to suck everything up into
itself?'' said Steven Ballmer, Microsoft's president, rhetorically
defending himself against critics who have challenged the company's
strategy as being proprietary. ``Because of XML you can have a
device on the Internet that does not run .NET software but through
XML it can participate in .NET services.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he and Gates insisted that those services would be
based on an open Internet standard, enabling users with
non-Windows-based platforms like the Palm computer and the
Macintosh to take advantage of them, the two executives
acknowledged that such users would be second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said the ``richest'' interactions with the new .NET
services would require the new Windows.NET operating system.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the vision the company sketched with videotaped
endorsements from executives of hardware and software companies
like Compaq, Dell Computer, Arriba, Loudcloud and others, there was
skepticism among some industry analysts that Microsoft would be
able to rapidly attract other software developers to its vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're leading a parade and asking developers to come with
them, but what happens if nobody joins?'' said David Readerman, a
managing director at Thomas Weisel &AMP; Partners, a San Francisco
investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   But other industry analysts said they were impressed with the
vision the company articulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that despite all the problems they're dealing with
in the courts they still have a vision of the future,'' said Walter
J. Casey, a technol0gy analyst at Banc One Investment Advisors
Corp. in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday, Ballmer occupied himself with making the case that
there is a workable business strategy in the array of new products
he said the company would introduce as part of the .NET strategy.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the company would increasingly try to move to a
subscription basis for selling its products but that the existing
packaged software and royalty and licensing schemes would continue
for the forseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   He outlined a series of Internet-based services the company is
creating, including its MSN online service; a version of its Office
software to be called Office.NET; bCentral, a Web portal offering
services to small business, and a version of its Visual Studio
development environment for software developers.
</P>
<P>
   The company hedged its bets only slightly during the day. Gates
said that the bet on the .NET was equivalent to the 100 percent bet
the company placed on its shift to the Internet strategy in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer said he was confident but he realized that the strategy
was still a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bet I feel very confident about,'' he said. ``But it's
a bet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-00 2149EDT &QL;
</P>
