 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    News for kids
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   abcnews4kids.com _ This brand new interactive news site offers
important world and national news with animated graphics, audio and
text. It repackages the news in a way that is meant to be appealing
to children. The language isn't watered down, but the material is
presented in short bursts, to hold a short attention span. Each
news story includes a search box that enables users to search the
Web site of Encyclopedia Britannica.
</P>
<P>
   www.barbie.com _ Barbie isn't just about a plastic doll anymore.
The timeless girls' toy has a Web site that includes a daily poll
(recent questions: ``Boy bands: how do they rate?'' and ``Pokemon:
your favorite is:'') a Barbie postcard messenger service and
personality quiz, not to mention several pages that feature Barbies
to order online. There is even a product line called Barbie
Software for Girls. Check out the feature Barbie for President.
This Barbiell Husted
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Driving to work, I often make mental lists of all my
mistakes. I could drive to Oregon and back and still not get bored.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there was the time, at 23, when I bought a $29.95
wig at J.C. Penney with the conviction it would forever change my
life. It did. I looked so weird _ very much like I was wearing a
dead possum _ that I had to move from my native Arkansas in shame.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't done much better with my high-tech predictions.
</P>
<P>
   There was my fearless pronouncement, years ago, that AOL would
soon bite the dust. AOL not only stayed around, it's the world's
largest ISP. Then there was the column in which I explained in
great and logical detail how the telephone companies such as AT&AMP;T
would soon domin
</P>
<P>
