 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Fast, furious fun with ``Street Fighter''
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of gamers _ those who still love ``Street
Fighter,'' and those who have long abandoned it to play more modern
3-D fighting games or who never liked the series in the first
place. For the former, there is Street FighterAlpha 3 ($30 for
Playstation, $50 for Dreamcast; www. capcom.com), a jam-packed game
with 33 characters from all the original games, including your old
favorites Chun Li, Ken and Ryu. Both games are extremely playable
old-school fighters. Advantage goes to the Playstation version for
game control (nothing short of an arcade stick beats Sony's Dual
Shock controller), but the Sega Dreamcast version lets you download
and unlock characters, choose character development modes and use
up to three players in a two-on-one match. Whichever version is
chosen, the game, like most of the Street Fighter titles, is fast,
furious action in 2-D cartoon style. Invite some friends over and
start a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Banging one's head against a brick wall and then using the
scattered chunks of mortar to file one's teeth without anaesthetic
is about as much fun as installing Microprose's Gunship! ($50; www.
hasbro-inter-active.com; for Windows). Third in a venerable series
of helicopter sims, the glitchy, buggy, prone-to-freeze Gunship
makes an effort to appeal to action fans and forgoes its roots
entirely. Variable complexity and options ranging from improbably
``realistic'' to aggressively exaggerated effects merely make this
game a gloriously graphic blow'em-up festival, not an aficionado's
technically immersive simulator. Gunship! is a lot of fun when it
is up and running, but getting there is half the problem _ the
other half being the fact that arcade-style flying firefight games
are a dime a dozen.
</P>
