 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    AOL's instant messaging can mangle one's privacy
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When does instant messaging stop being a useful tool
for keeping up with your online pals and become one big pain in the
neck _ or even an invasion of privacy?
</P>
<P>
   With so much discussion of privacy on the Net and the potential
of e-commerce sites to take our credit card numbers and pass them
out to every con artist from here to Singapore, the fact that
almost all of America Online's 25 million members can find out if
you're online and send you all kinds of messages for all kinds of
things should be equally disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a user logs on to AOL, he or she sees a Buddy List in
the right-hand corner of the screen. Users set up these lists so
they'll know when their friends, family and co-workers are online.
That way you can send them instant messages, real-time notes that
pop up on the left side of your screen.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging is very popular with teenagers who love
chatting online with their friends, and in many households it has
replaced the telephone as the teen communication method of choice.
Teens can talk to each other via ``IMs'' or invite all their
friends to a chat room for a virtual gab session. It's also handy
for companies with far-flung employees to message each other or
hold impromptu meetings when employees are online but not
necessarily in the same city or even the same state.
</P>
<P>
   I have friends who have IM chats with faraway relatives for
hours and rave about the joys of real-time contact with loved ones
that would cost a small fortune if they used the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messages and real-time chat have always been the
``secret sauce'' that separates AOL from other online services,
some of which no longer exist. The minute you log on to AOL, you
most likely will get a perky message telling you that ``you've got
mail'' and, even better, a look at all the people you know who are
online right there with you.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the knee-jerk reaction to seeing that a friend or
colleague is online is to send him or her a chirpy note to say
hello. Just because your friends are online, however, doesn't
necessarily mean they want to talk to you. There's a story that
Charles DeGaulle, the late president of France, had a telephone in
his home that did not accept incoming calls. He reasoned that just
because people wanted to talk to him, it didn't necessarily follow
that he wanted to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Apply this to the concept of the instant message. Your best
friend may be online, but he or she may be busy talking with
someone else or engaged in some online task, lacking the time to
trade hellos with you.
</P>
<P>
   I send few, if any, IMs these days, and let me tell you why. A
friend of mine tells an embarrassing story about being online with
her boss and a co-worker doing research for a project when her
boyfriend sent her an IM that, from what I understand, isn't the
kind of thing you need your boss to see and probably violated at
least six points of AOL's infamous terms of service. She was
mortified and closed the window as soon as she could, but it was
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Another less dramatic story is the time I came to work one day
to be greeted by a co-worker who said, ``Boy, you were online for a
long time last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I was online for a long time, doing a variety of things,
some work-related, some not. But what really bothered me was that
the co-worker _ not an especially close friend _ had added me to
his buddy list and knew I was online every time he was online. It
felt like an invasion of privacy and of my right to spend as much
time as I want on the Backstreets Web site reading articles about
Bruce Springsteen, without the whole world _ or just one annoying
colleague _ watching.
</P>
<P>
   Several of my friends lend their screen names to family members,
who are often bewildered by the range of people and messages that
pop up while they're using AOL. I once sent a very chatty, personal
message to a friend and after a while I got a short one-line reply:
``This isn't Linda. This is her mother.'' Oops.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you are tempted to dash off a quick note to
someone, remember that it might not be your buddy you are
messaging. As the old saying goes: ``On the Internet, no one knows
if you're a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because you've logged on and discovered all your friends
are online, try to resist the urge to send them an IM. Give your
friends a little space and fight the urge to watch them by closing
the Buddy List ``peephole'' when it pops up. You can also go to the
Buddy List preferences and select how public you wat your online
presence to be. I found that button right after my workplace
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that buddy lists can't be a fun way to keep
up with your friends and family, but remember, even if it's
somebody you know, you're still being watched, and you can _ and
sometimes should _ control who knows when you're online.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
