 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    E-mail service dishes out pearls to make you appear cultured
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Dear Jack,'' the e-mail press release begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``How great would it feel to be surrounded by a group of
intellectual people and impress them with a magnificent fact about
Mozart?''
</P>
<P>
   The mind reels, then conjures a scene at a cocktail party.
Dressed as usual in rumpled sports shirt, patched twill pants and
sock-eating shoes, I casually join a group in evening wear. It's
clear they're already impressed; they're just trying to hide it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's obvious to me,'' a lady in a black dress is saying.
``That particular verse refers to the Beatles in Shea Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps,'' muses a guy in a cummerbund, ``but what do all
those football references mean? I've listened to `American Pie' 200
times, and I've consulted every source I can find, and I still
don't have a handle on that.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, time to drop the bomb on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' I say, cunningly catching their intention. ``Didja know
that Mozart once fainted dead away when he heard an off-key
trumpet? Magnificent, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God,'' sighs black dress. She drifts away. Cummerbund
follows. I'm left with a sharp-faced girl in a black pantsuit and
rimless glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got that from Zooba, didn't you?'' she sneers. ``H.C. Robbins
Landon says that little trumpet story is almost certainly
apocryphal. Who let you in here, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Zooba (www.zooba.com), according to my breathless ``Dear Jack''
e-mail, ``is the revolutionary link to being a smarter, more
cultured person. It's the online destination when you want to know
more about a particular subject, but you don't have the time to sit
and read a book. Once you become a member of Zooba, it creates and
delivers personalized e-mails, containing rich content based on the
topics that you choose. ... It's a great way to brush up on any
subject and to appear worldly.''
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that anyone who doesn't have time to sit and read a
book could still find time to read one standing up, or is probably
so busy making wheelbarrows full of money that he could afford to
hire a lackey to follow him around, reading a book aloud.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly is easy to do, anyway. I used to do worldly pretty well,
back when I smoked. Worldly people always smoke. French cigarettes
are best, or Picayunes. Do they still make Picayunes? Probably not
since they invented marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Any rate, all you do is put on a trench coat and sit around with
a sullen look and a lit cigarette hanging out of the corner of your
mouth. It takes some practice not to let the smoke make your eye
water, unless you're doing brokenhearted worldly.
</P>
<P>
   And keep your mouth shut. The minute you start blabbering
magnificent facts, you're revealed for what you are _ an unworldly
geek who subscribes to Zooba.
</P>
<P>
   Zooba's press release concludes with this grand aphorism:
</P>
<P>
   ``NO MATTER WHO YOU ARE, YOU CAN ALWAYS BE SMARTER.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You got that right, baby,'' I muttered as I hit the delete
key.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-26-00 1100EDT &QL;
