<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WINDOWS ME? WE CAN WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN    c.2000 Houston Chronicle   Bill Gates
<TEXT>
must be a little short on pocket change, because a new issue of the
consumer version of Windows is on its way, and you have to decide
whether to pony up the bucks for an upgrade.
<P>
   Windows Millennium Edition _ cloyingly nicknamed Windows Me _ is
actually the third version of the Windows 98 operating system. It
also supposedly is the last Windows release that uses the so-called
9x architecture that began with Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime next year, if all goes well, Microsoft will offer a
consumer operating system built around Windows 2000, currently
code-named Whistler. That means the software that will render
Windows Me obsolete is already in development.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes Windows Me the least compelling upgrade for many
Windows 98 users. I've been playing with test versions of the
operating system for months, and with a couple of exceptions, I
don't think there's much here that most folks will find crucial. I
have yet to get my hands on the finished code, but I'll follow up
once I do.
</P>
<P>
   However, Windows Me may be attractive to users who have found
Windows 95 or 98 to be trouble-prone. It has some interesting
features for fixing and, even more importantly, preventing
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Work was completed on Windows Me last week, and it is due in
stores in mid-September. It may find its way onto new PCs before
that. And that's probably the best circumstance in which to get
Windows Me. The operating system's biggest strength is that it has
support for many of the latest hardware components that computer
manufacturers will be offering soon.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has had two main goals for its Windows Me upgrade.
First, it wanted to make it easier to use, and there have been
interface and design changes in that direction. But frankly, some
of the changes make Windows Me harder to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Dial-up Networking folder icon is now gone by
default from the My Computer window. Instead, there's a Web-like
text link to it in small type in the folder. (There's also a text
link in My Network Places, which is the new name for Network
Neighborhood.) But that link is visible only if you have your
folders set to be viewed as Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   So where is Dial-up Networking actually stored? In the Control
Panel _ a bizarre change, since most folks are used to finding it
in My Computer.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, when you first open the Control Panel, most of the
modules there are hidden from you. Again, there's a text link that
reveals all.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also sought to make Windows Me more reliable than
Windows 98 Second Edition. Of course, Windows 98 SE was supposed to
be more crash-proof than Windows 98, which was supposed to be more
stable than Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Users who've religiously followed the upgrade path know that
this has not always been the case. While each successive version
does contain bug fixes and feature improvements, Microsoft also has
added features and thus increased complexity. A clean, simple
installation of Windows 98 is pretty reliable. But once you start
adding things _ like, uh, new software _ this house of cards can
come tumbling down.
</P>
<P>
   However, Windows Me may have an edge here. While the versions
I've been using have been pre-release ones with their share of
bugs, Microsoft argues that Windows Me is going to be more stable
because the company has removed some of the things that could cause
problems in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   There is less support for older MS-DOS programs in Windows Me,
which should raise a warning flag to anyone who still relies on
that type of software. While many DOS programs may still work,
there is less of an emphasis on DOS compatibility in Windows Me.
Whether that translates into increased reliability is something
that will be determined over time.
</P>
<P>
   There are other Windows Me features, though, aimed at helping
users. The built-in help files have been expanded dramatically,
with more automated troubleshooters and links to Microsoft's
support Web site. If the documents on your PC can't help you, you
can easily go online for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 has a little-documented but lifesaving feature that
lets you recover from catastrophic problems. If you do something
that hoses your operating system, but you can still get to a DOS
prompt, you can type scanreg /restore, then choose from several
days' worth of backed-up Windows Registry files. This takes your
Registry back to a point before the damage was done - almost like
traveling back in time.
</P>
<P>
   Windows Me takes this one step further with a feature called
System Restore. It notes changes made to your system over time and
creates so-called Restore Points. You can choose one of the Restore
Points from a calendar. You can go back for days, weeks or even
months.
</P>
<P>
   The operating system also brings over a useful feature from
Microsoft's Office productivity suite. Windows Me has the ability
to replace crucial files that have been either accidentally deleted
or overwritten with older versions. This ``self-healing''
capability seeks to fix one of the biggest causes of program
crashes _ incompatible versions of system files. How well this
works is something that only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   As with all versions of Windows, there are new features built
in.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, after all, has to do something to keep the Justice
Department busy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you'll find a built-in desktop video editor that
makes it easy to bring in movies from a videocamera and manipulate
them. I spoke with several companies that make and sell software
programs that do this, and they didn't seem worried about Microsoft
adding this new capability to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just calls attention to the category,'' said one company's
spokesman, who apparently wasn't feeling like his firm might be the
next Netscape Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Windows Me wouldn't be a new version of Windows
without at least one feature suffering a solid case of hyperbloat.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows Media Player, once a simple and speedy way to play
media files, has ballooned into a lumbering application that takes
twice as long to load and bristles with unnecessary bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it now has a Media Guide that helps you ``find
entertaining and informative content on the Internet.'' The last
time we saw a description like that, it was on the Channel Bar on
Internet Explorer 4, which was partially to blame for that
program's bloat. And it went largely unused.
</P>
<P>
   Since an upgrade will cost around $100 _ and since the consumer
version of the more robust Windows 2000 is just around the corner _
chances are many users will take a pass on Windows Me. Gates may
end up a little poorer, but you may be better off waiting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-26-00 1411EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
