<HEADLINE>
VERY DEEP POCKETS BACKING MIT PROJECT 
 BY ANY OTHER NAME, IS IT SPAM? 
ROYALTIES SOUGHT ON FORGOTTEN PATENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   After dinner was served to the
elite group of computer scientists assembled at Boston's sumptuous
Bay Tower Room last Tuesday night, professor Juhani Kuusi, chief of
the Nokia Research Center in Finland, made a toast.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We have taken on a great challenge,'' Kuusi said in his
lilting accent. ``Let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge Kuusi referred to was Oxygen, a five-year project
headed by Michael Dertouzos, the director of the Laboratory for
Computer Science at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. The
dinner was the first meeting of Oxygen's corporate underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   At $1 million a year for five years, the price of admission to
Oxygen is unusually high, particularly because MIT's computer
laboratory and its sister Artificial Intelligence Laboratory have
long relied almost exclusively on government financing. Those
ponying up are the Acer Group, Delta Electronics, Hewlett-Packard,
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, Nokia and Royal Philips
Electronics. The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency will
supply an additional $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Oxygen software itself will be in the public
domain, each company hopes to get something different from the
deal. Several officials said they were particularly interested in
MIT's work on computers that respond to human speech. All intend to
work closely with MIT's researchers, and under the deal, will own
the intellectual property rights to anything they invent.
</P>
<P>
   While few would articulate it, beyond a general support for
``open systems,'' one other principle seemed to unite the Oxygen
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   `'Microsoft is too strong,'' said Kenichiro Ishii, deputy
director of NTT's Communication Science Laboratories in Kyoto,
Japan. ``So if the Oxygen project is a strong competitor to
Microsoft, it's exciting to us.''
</P>
<P>
   BY ANY OTHER NAME, IS IT SPAM?
</P>
<P>
   So if you give merchants a green light to spam you, and they do,
have you been spammed?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, those who make their livings from junk _ or,
in their words, promotional e-mail _ answer with a resounding no.
Now, they say they can prove they are right.
</P>
<P>
   FloNetwork of Toronto, a company that handles promotional e-mail
for merchants, sent e-mail messages to about 1,000 people who
regularly buy things on the Internet to ask their feelings about
spam vs. so-called permission-based e-mail _ messages that go only
to consumers who have clicked the button on a Web page indicating
that they would welcome updates, promotional material and such.
</P>
<P>
   FloNetwork's conclusion? ``People hate spam, but they love
permission-based e-mail,'' said Regina A. Brady, a FloNetwork vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that is overstating it on both sides. Most of the
respondents said they got about 10 pieces of unsolicited
promotional material a week, and only a third of them saw it as a
major invasion of privacy. Two percent actually liked it. But a
majority _ 65 percent _ did not care about it one way or the other;
they just deleted it upon arrival. By contrast, 94 percent of those
responding said they occasionally gave permission to merchants to
send them e-mail. And 58 percent said they thought permission-based
e-mail was an excellent way to learn about products, services and
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Tempting as it might be to think of the surveys themselves as
spam, they were in a sense permission-based e-mail. Those surveyed
were already volunteer members of an online panel that National
Family Opinion uses to gauge the popularity of various internet
sites and methods.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALTIES SOUGHT ON FORGOTTEN PATENT
</P>
<P>
   Dusting off a 14-year-old patent, British Telecommunications is
claiming ownership of the linking technology that lets Web users
move around the Internet by clicking on text and pictures. The
company has begun sending letters to Internet service providers in
the United States asking them to pay royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Patent specialists say British Telecommunications has a
difficult case to prove. But they expect the number of such cases
to rise as people try to apply old and new patents to broad areas
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications did not respond to requests for an
interview. The claim was reported last Monday in The Financial
Times, which said the patent was found two years ago buried among
15,000 other patents owned by the company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-25-00 2011EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
