<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MICROSOFT JUDGE SEEKS RATIFICATION IN LATEST RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The unexpected order last week to suspend
restrictions on Microsoft Corp.'s business practices until appeals
of its antitrust case are complete held some good news for every
party to the suit. But the true winner was the trial judge who made
the decision, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   For months Jackson had been expressing discomfort at the fact
that he alone was making all the judgments in this important case.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I am the one decision maker,'' he said in a
late-February interview. ``I would derive some comfort if I could
call on someone else's intellect to assist me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, on April 4, the day after he found Microsoft in
broad violation of state and federal antitrust laws, the judge told
the litigants that he intended to ``sever the liability and the
remedy'' and encourage appeal of his verdict before imposing a
remedy. But both Microsoft and the government told him they did not
think that was allowed under the law, so Jackson backed down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with his decision on Tuesday he accomplished something
similar. Now a higher court will have the opportunity to rule on
the merits of the case, ``the liability,'' as Jackson had put it,
before even thinking about the remedy. Sometime in the early fall,
the Supreme Court is likely to decide whether to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing his remedy ruling on June 7, Jackson had immediately
stayed his order breaking up the company. Had he not decided last
week to suspend a long list of restrictions on the company's
conduct as well, the Supreme Court would quickly have had to wade
into a Microsoft request for a stay, ``and make an immediate
decision on a very complicated subject, drawing them immediately
into the thick of the whole case,'' said Robert Litan, a former
senior Justice Department official now with the Brookings
Institution, a research and policy analysis organization.
</P>
<P>
   And that raises another benefit for the judge. Microsoft has
argued that Jackson made a serious procedural error in failing to
give the company a full hearing before imposing his remedy. Even
some of the plaintiffs think that a higher court might side with
Microsoft on this question. But now the court will have no reason
to consider this issue until the end, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes all the steam out of Microsoft's due-process
argument,'' said Richard Blumenthal, attorney general of
Connecticut, a leader of the states joining the Justice Department
as plaintiffs in the case. ``Now Microsoft will have a full
opportunity to present their views on remedies'' to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, Litan added, ``looks more evenhanded, and now there's
no need for a higher court to admonish him over the remedy-hearing
question.''
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft and the government, however, the results from the
judge's order are more mixed. Microsoft had maneuvered to avoid
having its appeal sent directly to the Supreme Court, where the
company had thought it might have a less favorable audience than
before the U.S. Court of appeals. At that Microsoft failed; Jackson
certified the case for direct appeal in the same order.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft also vociferously opposed imposition of the
constraints on its business that were to go effect in the fall.
They varied from marketing restrictions to product-development
limits. Now these limits are on indefinite hold, and the company
can go about its business.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, most notably, Microsoft announced a major retooling
of its product line to emphasize Internet-based software powering a
variety of devices. Microsoft had postponed the announcement while
Jackson's remedy decision was pending, and said before he granted
the stay that the restrictions he had imposed would be a major
impediment to the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   For the Justice Department and the 19 state attorneys general,
though, Microsoft's ability to go about its business unhindered is
exactly the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really worry about what they are going to do now with nobody
watching,'' said one senior government official.
</P>
<P>
   But several officials, and others, also said that given the
judge's freezing of the remedy the Supreme Court might be more
likely to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes it easier for them to take it,'' said Tom
Miller, attorney general of Iowa, another leader of the states'
efforts. ``The focus goes much more to liability questions, which
they are probably more comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   Without this order, said another official with knowledge of the
government's case, ``there would have had to be a lot of summertime
activity on the stay request, and that might have prompted them to
buck the whole thing back down'' to the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even without the need to deal with a stay request, the
judge's order ``underscores the need for the Supreme Court to act
quickly, now that Microsoft is not under any sort of conduct
decree,'' said Kevin O'Connor, the assistant attorney general from
Wisconsin who represents the states in court.
</P>
<P>
   But the court can move only so fast under its own rules and is
unlikely to make a decision, even on whether to take the case,
before late summer.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the Justice Department announced that the litigants
had agreed to complete briefings on that question by Aug. 22. After
that, the Supreme Court can decide whether to keep the case or send
it to the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as O'Connor noted, ``in court time, the schedule is
short, but in the market we're talking about, that's a very long
time.''
</P>
<P>
