<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-28 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF POLLS MEAN MUCH, GORE NEEDS TO FIND A NEW HOUSE SOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore must be due for another political makeover. It's been
days since the Democratic presidential candidate reinvented
himself.
</P>
<P>
   And look what happened in the meantime: The Republicans'
nominee-to-be, George W. Bush, surged ahead of Gore by 13 points in
the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Bush racked up that lead among ``likely voters,'' according to
USA Today's report on the poll. Likely voters, the paper said, are
those ``whose past voting behavior indicates they are most likely
to go to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the choice of 52 percent of likely voters, while 39
percent preferred Gore. And there was more good news for Bush:
Independent voters responding to the poll favored Bush over Gore by
a margin of 57 percent to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Bush outpolled Gore by ``26 points'' in the
crucial category of independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it just a few months ago that John McCain was running
around the country trying to convince Republicans that only he
could lure independent voters to the Grand Old Party's cause and
defeat Gore in the general election?
</P>
<P>
   But look who's beating Gore like a drum these days. It's not
John McCain; it's George W. Bush, making fools of McCain and others
who insisted that Bush would be hopelessly overmatched by Gore in
the battle for independents.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at the number again: Bush 57, Gore 31.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another amazing number: The poll showed Bush with a
6-point lead over Gore ``among female voters.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not a misprint. Bush is ahead of Gore in the
all-important women's vote.
</P>
<P>
   If this poll reflects anything even remotely resembling reality
_ and there's every reason to assume that it does _ Bush has
effectively erased the Democrats' cherished ``gender gap'' and
created a gender gap of his own.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, that's even worse news than the recent headlines about
his fund-raising shenanigans during the 1996 presidential campaign.
If a Democratic presidential candidate can't carry the women's
vote, he's in big trouble _ especially considering that the poll
gave Bush an eye-popping 20-point lead among male voters.
</P>
<P>
   With every silver lining there's a cloud, of course, so it's
only fair to stop drooling over the poll results for a moment and
consider USA Today's suggestion that Gore might have fared better
if not for the bad publicity about fund-raising. The newspaper
quoted one expert as saying that the fund-raising flap is a
temporary problem for Gore that will quickly evaporate unless
Attorney General Janet Reno appoints a special prosecutor to
investigate _ which she is not expected to do.
</P>
<P>
   The expert also downplayed the value of June polls in predicting
the results of November elections, noting that voters aren't really
paying attention yet. One of CNN's polling wizards made a similar
observation, explaining that polls taken on or around Labor Day are
more likely to reveal the eventual winner.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I can wait.
</P>
<P>
   It's entirely possible that the polls could fluctuate wildly
between now and Nov. 7, leaving us in suspense until the very last
vote is counted. That's not what usually happens, but it's
possible.
</P>
<P>
   A more probable scenario is that both of the major party
candidates will get a ``bounce'' from the upcoming nominating
conventions and that the race will tighten during August and early
September. Then one of the candidates will surge to a significant
lead and hold that lead _ or widen it _ as the election approaches.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days before the voters go to the polls, the
candidate who's behind will edge closer to the leader _ and then
fall back again as undecideds swing to the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Being a Bush-backer, I'm guessing that his summer lead will hold
up and that Gore will be the one giving futile chase in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is ahead in the final days, of course, then my whole
scenario is out the window, and Bush comes from behind to snatch
victory from the jaws of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It's the one thing I'm sure about: Bush wins.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
