<P>
   THE WORLD'S MOST POWERFUL COMPUTERS
</P>
<P>
   The new IBM supercomputer will be more powerful than the world's
next four fastest computers combined. The new computer and the four
fastest current machines are listed below with the performance
rating, location, use, maker, and year put into service.
</P>
<P>
   1. ASCI White; 12.300 teraflops (trillions of operations per
second); Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, Calif.;
nuclear research; IBM; 2000.
</P>
<P>
   2. ASCI Blue-Pacific; 3.868 teraflops; Livermore; nuclear
research; IBM; 1999.
</P>
<P>
   3. ASCI Red; 3.268 teraflops; Sandia National Laboratories,
Albuquerque, N.M.; nuclear research; Intel; 1999.
</P>
<P>
   4. ASCI Blue-Mountain; 3.072 teraflops, Los Alamos National
Laboratory, Los Alamos, N.M.; nuclear research; SGI; 1998.
</P>
<P>
   5. SP Power3, 2.004 teraflops; IBM/Naval Oceanographic Office,
Poughkeepsie, N.Y.; aerospace research; IBM; 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: IBM; University of Mannheim, Germany
</P>
