<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-PATRIOT-H     06-28 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PATRIOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `PATRIOT' GAMES CREATE A REVOLUTIONARY BORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mel Gibson's new movie goes where most vanity projects fear to
tread: 1776.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all right; he's gone there with sci-fi action
director Roland Emmerich calling the shots. So the result, despite
the puffy white shirts, mussed ponytails, 13-starred American flags
and nameless slaves, feels more like 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot'' makes the Revolutionary War look like
super-produced studio footage of the Los Angeles riots made
suitable for broadcast on VH-1: a cacophony of THX-level stabbing,
shooting and shrieking too arbitrary, too anonymous to be visceral,
though the dusks, the dawns and billowing puffs of gunsmoke seem
designed to complement the azure in Gibson's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The film's would-be money shot stars a cannonball swiping a head
clean off a Yank's body. But that's the kind of special-effects
crotch-grabbing that's good only in hindsight (or DVD) when you can
replay it at an eighth the speed like a megaplex Zapruder film.
Most of the battle sequences are about as hard to figure as the
``Soul Train'' scramble board, and less suspenseful, too.
</P>
<P>
   Easier to keep track of is Gibson, particularly in full
slow-motion gallop, bringing his usual frighteningly intense
horsepower to the character of Benjamin Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Widower, plantation owner, amateur home craftsman, staunch
pacifist, this American and proud father of seven finds himself
caught in the madness of war and the cross hairs of principle when
one of his boys is shot in the back by a simpering, glacial,
blood-lusting British colonel named William Tavington (Jason
Isaacs). Tavington descended upon the Martin property, flanked by a
small army of redcoats, to seize his oldest son, Gabriel (Heath
Ledger), a Yankee soldier who's been pegged as a spy.
</P>
<P>
   A child murdered, another kidnapped, his house torched, his
slaves pocketed, Benjamin sheds his conscientious-objector status
and reacquaints himself with his violent French-and-Indian-War
days, electing to go medieval in order to get Gabriel back and
avenge his dead son. The film gives up on being a war epic and
turns instead into a long evocation of Mel Gibson titles like
``Lethal Weapon,'' ``Ransom,'' ``Braveheart,'' ``Payback,'' ones
that Gibson is eagerly willing to personify. But the script holds
no challenging obstacles for him to overcome to get to Tavington;
it protracts the inevitable with queasy weddings and militiamen
camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a trace of elegant filmmaking in ``The Patriot'' _
that fuses historical fiction and pulsing drama with a competent
vision and moral resonance _ it's the rescue sequence, in which Ben
instills his two other sons with the right to bear arms. It's a
challenge the boys fulfill with nervous mettle, heeding dad's motto
(``Aim small, miss small,'' kind of a ``keep it simple, stupid''
for the junior marksmen set). They're naturals, taking out redcoats
with a sharply shot devotion. But it's only here, as extras fall to
the ground, that you are compelled to question the consequence of
two kids and their dad knocking off 20 men.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the only passage in ``The Patriot'' where the
choreography of chaos is comfortably wedded to technique. It's
ugly, it's raw, it's charged. Otherwise, we get a degree of
jingoism unseen since ``Armageddon'' or Emmerich's ``Independence
Day,'' a piece of toy-cinema that was having fun in the wrong
places. The ``Patriot'' script, by ``Saving Private Ryan'' writer
Robert Rodat, is a curiously timid, vapid comic strip, which leaves
Emmerich ample room to bombard us with a bevy of boldly unsubtle
images that make Armageddon's ``America Rules!'' message seem
subliminal.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, a loud stink has already been made of how the
historical inaccuracies in the script make the British into inhuman
figments of terrorism, not unlike portrayals of Arabs. What with
the characterization of Lord Cornwallis (Tom Wilkinson), who rivals
Liberace in his love of primping, preening and florid housecoats,
plus a host of fey-accented people saying things you'd expect to
read in inter-titles of King Vidor silent films, they have a case.
</P>
<P>
   But in a Revolutionary War flick with nary a revolution, where's
the news? When it comes to nationalism and racist caricatures, is
there any better colonizer than Hollywood? Should you expect more
from a director whose last film was ``Godzilla''?
</P>
<P>
   I had a better time at ``The Patriot'' imagining that while
Gibson sits in front of what looks like Yoda's swamp and talks
about his massacre of French troops, the British have returned to
their Industrial Light and Magic space pods for an evening of
glowing green tea.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the ``Who's the biggest victim sweepstakes,'' the
British in the film are going to have to stand behind the African
slaves. Since the death of her mother, Susan, the youngest Martin
child hasn't spoken. That loss must have had a worse effect on the
slaves, who are so cordial and upbeat about having their lives and
property gentrified in 1776 that you fear for the entire future of
the blues. After the British burn Benjamin's sister-in-law's (Joely
Richardson) house, she and the kids move into the escaped slave's
beach haven, where the intruded-upon say nothing but do host
weddings, dance and house and feed them. They're a compliant
wallpaper background. But then, so is the war.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
