<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-HISPANICS-HNS &LR;      06-28 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HISPANICS FINALLY GET SOME AIR TIME, ON CABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television has the capacity to be important. At times, that
capability rises to the level of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   But not like this. It shouldn't be like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.'' has more pressure on it than any show
deserves. Television shows should worry about merely surviving,
preferably while being entertaining, amusing and/or
thought-provoking. Television shows should worry about attracting
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   What television shows should not have to worry about is carrying
the hopes and expectations of an entire culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.,'' which debuted Monday on Showtime, should
be judged as it is: a solid family drama with the potential to get
even better.
</P>
<P>
   But because its cast and crew are almost entirely Hispanic _ a
group grossly underrepresented on television _ ``Resurrection
Blvd.'' takes on greater symbolism and meaning: This show has to
make it. It can't be just OK; it must be a trailblazer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute that a Latino show fails, it has to withstand
greater scrutiny and go through greater challenges, unlike
(predominantly white shows) ... because we are so far back,'' said
Felix Sanchez, president and co-founder of the National Hispanic
Foundation for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time last year, various protests surged together
into a howl when African-Americans decried their
underrepresentation on television. Network and studio executives
had no choice but to listen, and scrambled to add blacks to their
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   A happy ending? Not for Hispanics, whose calls for more roles
and behind-the-scenes jobs went largely unheard. While Hispanics
comprise 12 percent of the population _ a percentage growing
rapidly _ they make up about 1 percent of the faces seen on
television, Sanchez said. Hispanics can literally count the
characters on one hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Latino community, this is our Selma; this is our
moment to take the seat at the front of the bus,'' Sanchez said.
``This is a civil-rights issue in the media age. Whether people
like it or not, we are in a segregated media world, completely
impenetrable to Latino actors and behind-the-camera talent.''
</P>
<P>
   It's getting better. Then again, how could it get any worse?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Resurrection,'' Nickelodeon introduces ``The
Brothers Garcia'' on July 23; the show is being billed as the first
English-language sitcom with an all-Hispanic cast and team of
writers, directors and producers. (Showtime introduced another
minority family drama, ``Soul Food,'' on Wednesday. Based on the
1997 Vanessa L. Williams feature film by the same title, the drama
tracks a multi-generational black family in Chicago.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the most part the networks have not opened many doors
for Hispanics. (One notable exception this fall is Ruben Blades on
ABC's ``Gideon's Crossing.'') ``An American Family,'' a Hispanic
family drama, did not make the final cut for CBS' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.'' falls into the tradition of ``Price of
Glory,'' a feature film released earlier this year starring Jimmy
Smits as an ex-boxer trying to capture the title that eluded him as
he trains three young men. (It was a box-office bust.)
</P>
<P>
   Like that movie, the new series delves into the Hispanic family
structure, and how boxing is revered within that minority
community. The series focuses on the Santiagos of East Los Angeles,
and particularly Carlos (Michael DeLorenzo, ``New York
Undercover''), a middleweight contender. Cheech Marin and Paul
Rodriguez also star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.'' will be met with some jabs from within
the Latino community for perceived stereotypes of its own, from the
patriarchal family structures to the presence of gangs and guns and
the clan that looks to boxing as the primary path out of the
barrio.
</P>
<P>
   When you get one shot, why not present nothing but the best of
your community? The answer, of course, is when you get one shot,
the first order is to make it as compelling and as realistic as
possible. And guess what: The stereotypes are sometimes _ but only
sometimes _ true.
</P>
<P>
   While the presence of African-Americans on television is
comparable to their percentage of the population, many are
segregated into a few ``black'' shows. Similarly for Hispanics, a
true sign of change will come when more Hispanics appear as
regulars in shows like ``ER,'' ``The Practice'' or _ say it ain't
so _ ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   And that day will come, not because it is the right thing to do,
but because it is the wisest business move. There's a huge market
that is waiting, no, begging to be tapped. And some new stories
couldn't hurt the rest of us, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very soon, we will have a fierce bidding war to bring on new
Hispanics images on every level,'' Sanchez said. ``The biggest
issue is no one knows how to successfully tap into this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, someone will figure it out _ and the pressure will be
off.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
