<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-GOALIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TEAM MISSES INJURED GOALIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ No one on the US team is happy to be playing
the Gold Cup without Briana Scurry, its No. 1 goalkeeper. You don't
lose your Olympic gold medalist and World Cup winner to a severe
case of shin splints and smile about it.
</P>
<P>
   But if there's a bright side, it was on glowing display Tueday
night as stand-in Siri Mullinix got another chance to show why she
should join Scurry on the 2000 Olympic team, shutting out the
Olympic bronze-medalist Brazilians, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's always there,'' said Mullinix, a 22-year-old
who helped the University of North Carolina to a pair of NCAA
championships and was one of the last cuts going into the World
Cup. ``You just kind of take it day by day and play; that's all you
can do. Today was a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would disagree. By night's end, Mullinix _ whose only
failure was trying to suppress her delighted grin after the game _
had notched five saves and a lot of miles with her aggressive,
out-of-the-goal, fear-no-enemy-foot style. What some see as risky
business, she sees as shot prevention, refusing to hang back and
let the team take shots anywhere in the vague neighborhood of the
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball's going back there, you're not worried about
what's going to happen,'' said veteran teammate Kristine Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   It is, Mullinix said, exactly the way she played in college,
when she started for three years before graduating last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just takes time to get back in the groove,'' explained
Mullinix, once again getting used to going out for a ball and being
two inches away from an attacker before kicking it under her foot,
something she knew from watching film would be needed against the
Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing in goal is games. The more games you play,
the better your timing is going to be. Playing one game a month
doesn't help; playing 12 games in three months does. I think (this)
was my best performance yet. I felt confident in every decision I
made.''
</P>
<P>
   April Heinrichs, the first-year US head coach, obviously feels
that same delighted confidence. ``It gives me goosebumps to look at
her little face over there because she's so happy,'' said
Heinrichs. ``She knows she played well. She knows she played high
behind our defense and she knows she had a critical impact on
tonight's outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the 12th cap for Mullinix, who made her first
international appearance May 2, 1999, in a 7-0 win against Japan.
Although she earned a spot in residency camp before the World Cup
after her stellar career at powerhouse UNC and has played for four
years on the US Under-20 team, she had to watch the World Cup from
the stands after barely missing the squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, but I think it paid off,'' she said. ``I knew
that I was young. I think the timing is perfect right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, Heinrichs hinted at agreement. ``She has stepped through
the door,'' said the coach, asked about her young keeper's bid for
Olympus. ``In some ways, she is kicking the door wide open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
