u w BC-SCOTUS-GAY-SCOUTS-NYT     06-28 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GAY-SCOUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY SCOUTS CAN BAR GAY MEN FROM BEING TROOP LEADERS, HIGH COURT
RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday narrowly upheld the
right of the Boy Scouts to bar gay men from becoming scout leaders
and, by extension, barred gay boys from joining the scouting ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision reversed a ruling by the New Jersey Supreme
Court that arose from Monmouth County, where James Dale was
expelled from the Scouts a decade ago after his troop learned from
a newspaper article that he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's opinion by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist held
that requiring the Scouts to have Dale in their ranks would violate
the organization's First Amendment right of ``expressive
association.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By all accounts, Dale was an exemplary Scout,'' the opinion
noted. ``In 1988, he achieved the rank of Eagle Scout, one of
Scouting's highest honors.''
</P>
<P>
   After entering Rutgers University, Dale participated in
gay-rights activities, and soon thereafter Scout officials revoked
his adult membership. At the time of his expulsion, he was an Eagle
Scout assistant scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not, as we must not be, guided by our views of whether
the Boy Scouts' teachings with respect to homosexual conduct are
right or wrong,'' the court said Wednesday. But, it continued,
``Public or judicial disapproval of a tenet of an organization's
expression does not justify the state's effort to compel the
organization to accept members where such acceptance would derogate
from the organization's expressive message.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy
and Clarence Thomas were also in the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. In his opinion, Stevens
focused on the scouting precepts of being ``morally straight and
clean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain as the light of day that neither one of these
principles...says the slightest thing about homosexuality,''
Stevens wrote. ``Indeed, neither term in the Boy Scouts' law and
oath expresses any position whatsoever on sexual matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absence of explicit wording on sexual matters, Scout
officials have argued all along that gay people have no place in
their membership.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia seemed to signal his view when the arguments in Boy
Scouts vs. Dale, No. 99-669, were heard on April 26. ``To require
the Boy Scouts to have as a scoutmaster someone who embodies a
contradiction of their message _ how can that be?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the New Jersey Supreme Court ruled that the Boy
Scouts were a ``public accommodation'' and thus not protected by
the First Amendment's guarantee of freedom of association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
