u s BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-BOS &LR;      06-28 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DOESN'T SELL BRAZIL SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The road to world soccer supremacy doesn't
have a ``No Passing'' sign.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, the US women will win the 2000
Gold Cup when they return to Foxboro Stadium for the tournament
final July 3. Then the defending world champions will go to Sydney
and bring home the Olympic gold medal, just as they did four
summers ago in Atlanta. Once again they'll be on top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that way for much of the past decade, the US setting
the pace while the rest of the world reluctantly follows. In recent
years, however, the Norways, Chinas, and Brazils of the world have
been flashing their high beams, showing they're ready for the US to
get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   But the world champs aren't quite ready to oblige. Heading into
Tuesday's Gold Cup match at Foxboro Stadium, the US had beaten
Brazil five straight times by a combined 18-2. Of their previous 13
meetings, Brazil had been shut out six times.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled, because the Americans aren't. They know that
the Brazilians made it to the semifinals in Atlanta, then lost in
the bronze-medal match. They remember how Brazil finished third in
last summer's World Cup, how it gave the US all it could handle in
the semifinal. And, most importantly, the Americans realize that
with continued improvement and more national support, Brazil could
become one of the world's truly elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   The hierarchy of world soccer could be very different by the
time the 2003 World Cup rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is interesting, because they've always been a country
that's been in the background until recent years,'' veteran US
midfielder Julie Foudy said Monday. ``And they've really emerged
since the last Olympics. They're getting better, and when they get
really organized _ and they're starting to; (the country is)
putting more money into the women's side _ we're going be screwed,
because they're going to be so good.''
</P>
<P>
   They're good now. Very good. They've already got the players, so
all they need is more international experience. The 25 players on
Brazil's preliminary Gold Cup roster had a combined 250 caps. US
midfielder Kristine Lilly has 205.
</P>
<P>
   Before this tournament, Brazil had played only four
international matches since the World Cup, none since a 4-2 loss in
October to the host team in the US Cup. The Americans played 18
matches during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is short on experience, not talent. Katia has 23 goals in
only 16 international matches. She scored seven Sunday against
Trinidad and Tobago. Her front-line mate Pretinha has 24 goals in
23 matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer a time when you can step on the field against
Brazil and know you're going to get a win,'' US forward Tiffeny
Milbrett said Monday. ``And you know that against Brazil it's going
to be a top-level, world-class game.''
</P>
<P>
   Foudy called the Brazilian forwards ``lethal'' players who could
``score at will.'' And they should be doing so for a long time,
considering that Katia is only 23 years old and Pretinha 25. The
team's star player, midfielder Sissi, is 33 but has only 40 caps.
Six of Brazil's players had no caps coming into the Gold Cup, and
19 players are 25 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   China's already proven to be a strong adversary for the US, and
Brazil is poised to join them. Soon.
</P>
<P>
   The US knows it, which is why head coach April Heinrichs has
been preparing for the future. She's playing her younger players
like Nikki Serlenga (hat trick vs. Costa Rica), Christie Welch, and
Susan Bush, affording them valuable experience.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Foudy, Milbrett, Mia Hamm, Joy Fawcett, and the rest of
the World Cup veterans can still carry the US, but they've played a
lot in their careers. They can't do it forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been real conscious about the old ladies and the
veterans,'' Foudy said Monday. ``And having a good mix of the old
ladies and the young guns. And always you have to have that
combination . . . One of the things April did when she came in this
year after the World Cup was keep the core of the veterans but also
really experiment with some new younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was decided that these were the players (we) were going to
invest in for the future. Especially when some of us retire, these
are some of the players that are going to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And keep teams like Brazil in the Americans' rearview mirror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-STATESTREET-SPINA-ART     06-28 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATESTREET-SPINA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SPINA SPENT 31 YEARS GETTING TO THE TOP OF STATE STREET BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ David Spina was 33 years old, a smart young banker with
a used VW Beetle, a Harvard MBA, and an urge to leave Vietnam
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1976. He'd been working at State Street Bank for seven
years _ first as a credit analyst and then, after getting his MBA,
as a commercial loan officer _ when he got the call. The chief
executive, William Edgerly, had told his lieutenants to scour the
bank's ranks for the smartest up-and-comers they could find; he was
looking for an assistant, a right-hand man. Edgerly liked what he
saw in Spina _ bright, hard-working, a potential leader with his
military training _ and offered him the job.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't at all what Spina had planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been totally focused on my banking career,'' says the man
who is now CEO himself. ``I did not know Bill personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Spina, colleagues and family members prodded him to
take the job. He's been showing up for work at 225 Franklin St.
ever since, beating a patient path to the top of a company that has
become one of the world's financial giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the way to the office,'' he jokes. After 31 years at
the asset servicing and investment firm, in roles from financial
chief to president, there is perhaps no one more suited than Spina
to lead State Street into the next decade. Yet few envy the
challenge he faces.
</P>
<P>
   Spina takes the baton from Marshall Carter, a man who is
something of a legend everywhere from Wall Street to Boston's city
streets. Part war hero, part philanthropist, Carter, who stepped
down May 18, made success look easy, overseeing eight years of
double-digit earnings growth and a sevenfold jump in State Street's
market value, to $17.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a sense of comfort and status quo in Spina's
appointment to the number one post, there is also hushed
uncertainty. For one, Carter is a tough act to follow. Can Spina _
or anyone, for that matter _ keep State Street on this steady
growth track for yet another seven to nine years?
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the leadership factor. Does Spina, a loyal
number two for so long, have what it takes to step into the top
job? Soon after being spotted by Edgerly, Spina became chief
financial officer; more duties were gradually added to his
portfolio through the years. But always he was Mr. Inside, running
the operations for someone else rather than leading his own
department. With his new posting, Spina is moving out of the very
long shadows cast by the two men who preceded him and into the
spotlight on a very large stage.
</P>
<P>
   State Street handles recordkeeping and accounting on $6.2
trillion of assets for mutual funds and large institutional
investors. It is the nation's second-biggest pension manager, with
$720 billion under its watch.
</P>
<P>
   To a person, analysts say Carter will be missed. But investors
are optimistic about Spina so far. Boston investment manager Lee
Forker asserted recently, ``There will be no diminution of the
momentum.'' He predicts, ``I think we will be pleasantly surprised
when we look back in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who steps down as chairman at year end, is firmly behind
his pick. He says Spina, 57, has been in training for this job for
4 1/2 years. Carter, 60, put him in charge of growing the company's
European business two years ago. That meant being abroad one-third
of the time, an assignment Spina didn't mind, he says, as his
children were nearly grown. He is blessed with the ability to sleep
on planes. And he kept up his rigorous workout schedule by joining
a gym in London (he belongs to two Boston-area gyms as well).
</P>
<P>
   In October, Carter asked Spina to form a task force and develop
an Internet strategy. A skeptic at first, Spina vows he's now a
convert. Not surprisingly, Europe and Web projects top Spina's list
of priorities today.
</P>
<P>
   It was important for Spina to take on big projects, to raise his
profile, Carter says. ``We wanted people to stop thinking of him as
the CFO.''
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker who's made Boston his home, Spina studied
history as an undergraduate at the College of the Holy Cross in
Worcester and then joined the Navy. He captained a swift boat in
the war, a post he describes as ``98 percent boredom, 2 percent
terror.'' He served his last two years of duty at a desk job in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy to be in a military uniform stateside in 1968 and
1969, Spina says. ``It took me a long time to understand the amount
of social change that went on in the US while I was (in Vietnam)
growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was with a deep yearning to move beyond those lost war years
that Spina tackled his career. ``The strong urge was to get on with
my life,'' he says. A voice in his head kept asking, ``When was I
going to catch up?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Spina finished his MBA, got married, and moved into a
full-time loan officer's job at State Street, turning down other
offers in Manhattan. He took up skiing to survive New England
winters and is an avid tennis player, step-aerobics fanantic
(``front row,'' he says), and wine lover. He reads five newspapers
a day.
</P>
<P>
   A man with less patience and control over his ego could never
have thrived in Carter's shadow. Spina was considered a contender
for the corner office back in 1992, but Edgerly brought Carter in
from Chase Manhattan. Spina was disappointed, he admits, and
getting a new boss after 16 years was ``very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Carter did was remodel the offices and cut a
door in the wall between his office and Spina's. It was usually
closed but always unlocked, Spina says. The one time cleaning
people locked the door by mistake, Carter stormed around to the
entrance everyone else used. ``It added three seconds to his trip.
He wasn't happy,'' Spina jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Spina said, ``My first personal agenda was for Marsh to
trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. While Spina is clearly glad to be able to stretch
his own wings at last, he says he's grateful to Carter for handing
him major responsibilities. He needed to spend time with customers
and executives in Europe and elsewhere, because, ``In many ways, I
was perceived as an inside person.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was hired to take the company global. Spina must now work
to penetrate markets more deeply and keep State Street at the crux
of big investors' needs, from settling stock purchases and handling
currency trades to helping clients develop better tools for their
portfolio managers.
</P>
<P>
   With humility rarely seen in the financial district, Spina now
says Edgerly picked the right guy for the time. ``I'm a different
person today,'' he says, ``and a lot more ready today than I was in
1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgerly recalls that Spina took the news well at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``His character is to be zealous about opportunity,'' Edgerly
says. ``He is invigorated by challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Spina is liked and respected throughout the
company. If his manner is more formal than Carter's _ Spina is
bow-tied, polite, almost professorial when he speaks _ he has
managed to forge more allies than enemies in his long tenure at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   But Spina has wasted no time in reaching out to build a new
inner circle. On the day he was promoted, he announced the creation
of an office of the CEO, which includes Nicholas Lopardo, chief of
investment arm State Street Global Advisors, chief operating
officer Ronald Logue, and administrative chief John Towers.
</P>
<P>
   Spina also intends to carry on State Street's reputation as a
good corporate citizen. He is steeped in a culture established by
Edgerly in the early 1980s, when State Street first reached out
aggressively as a contributor to charities and a partner with local
government in providing subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Grogan, chief of government and public affairs at Harvard
University and a former staff member for mayors Kevin H. White and
Raymond Flynn, has worked with Spina over the years on many public
projects, including what's now the Metropolitan Boston Housing
Partnership. He believes Spina will keep State Street involved _
and perhaps write his own chapter in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is not a grandstander,'' Grogan says. ``but very steady
and very committed to the things he cares about.'' Furthermore, he
adds, ``He is not an off-putting type. He is someone who could
really bring people together.''
</P>
<P>
   If Spina can bring that trait to his new job, he'll be off to a
running start. Even as he spins the globe for growth, he says, he
won't forget the people who work quietly here at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pretty good sense of the whole,'' he says. ``It takes
a lot of people to make a company like this work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
