<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-28 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNS FOR THE DIGITAL AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beware of all enterprises that require new clothes,'' Henry
David Thoreau once advised. Not that the retail industry pays any
attention. Instead, it has seized on this statistic: There are
approximately 100 million cellular phone users in this country who
spend about 6 minutes a day on their phones and hours toting them
in pockets, purses, backpacks, or briefcases.
</P>
<P>
   So for fall, designers are combining the practical with the
gimmicky. For the first time, clothiers from Brooks Brothers to
Levi's to Fubu are designing clothes for the information age.
They're incorporating pockets perfectly sized for cell phones in
blazers, jeans, tuxedo jackets, and skirts. Some of the garments
feature hidden pouches while others flaunt the phone as an
accessory on a lapel, leg, or arm.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to accommodate all manner of portable electronics is
on. In the coming weeks, retailers will also be offering a rash of
pullovers and pants with built-in spaces for Palm Pilots, MP3 and
CD players, and beepers. And new clothing companies are setting up
shop to cater to a nation of gadget users.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last December, the www.ufunction.com website was
born to sell moderately priced womenswear with outer pockets to
hold cell phones and music players, making the electronics both
accessible and decorative.
</P>
<P>
   Another young clothier, B. Lucid, will be selling a jacket at
Nordstrom and Express as of next month that holds a beeper on the
sleeve, which lights up a strobe from wrist to shoulder when the
wearer is paged.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the only wires touching clothing were
those sewn into brassieres and the only directions needed were
about how to launder. That was before a Houston radiologist and a
NASA engineer applied their knowledge to create the New York
company's microstretch slicker, retailing for less than $80.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pager is set on vibrate, the vibration sets off the
light. It's a patented electronic device,'' says Steven Zellman,
who runs the New York-based B. Lucid. ``Let's say you don't have a
pager. You hate pagers. But you want the jacket to go clubbing. You
can hit the switch inside the jacket and it will light up.'' The
jacket, powered with a 9-volt battery, can flash for about six days
nonstop and works with any pager, although the company has a
marketing agreement with Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Even the conservative end of the business is plugging into the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Brothers is incorporating a lower cell-phone pocket
inside some suit jackets and blazers and all of its outerwear for
men this fall. Palm Pilots also slip easily into the inner jacket
pocket designed for wallets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the trend, I think, of the whole industry,'' said
Brooks Brothers spokeswoman Geri Corrigan. ``With people dressing
more casually, you can't carry around a big briefcase when you're
wearing chinos and a button-down shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on consumer reaction, the cell-phone pocket may be
extended to some women's outerwear as well. But Corrigan said women
may be harder to convince because they're accustomed to carrying
small electronics in their purses and may not want their
silhouettes marred by a protruding Nokia.
</P>
<P>
   Where some see a marketing problem, others see an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ufunction is offering a crinkled nylon stretch
blouse (in white, lemon, and orange) with Velcro closures up the
front and an outer cell-phone pocket that runs down toward the
waist. The phone, on display at the rib cage, is meant to be the
focal point.
</P>
<P>
   The company also makes a black nylon stretch skirt with a phone
pocket strategically placed just below the thigh, a stylish black
sheath to be worn with a belt that has a cell-phone pouch as well
as jeans, cropped pants, fleece pullovers, and brushed cotton
trenchcoats with the same outer compartments.
</P>
<P>
   For MP3 and CD players, Ufunction has designed pockets in nylon
windbreakers and vests and plans on rolling out a men's line in
late autumn. A spokeswoman said the company is so new it won't have
hard sales data until the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Tommy Jeans is introducing its cotton laminate
Tection jacket that has a cell-phone pocket on its front lapel. The
fall line also includes a flight jacket, retailing for $179, with a
CD player pocket on the arm and loose-fitting jeans with phone
compartments above or below the knee, selling for between $69 and
$79, depending on the style.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Cole is including cell-phone pockets inside some men's
suits and outerwear pieces that are part of the urban-oriented
Reaction collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``An accessory pocket like that is an added novelty,'' said
Kenneth Cole Productions spokesman David Stewart. ``It's a
development because of need. You walk down the street in any large
city and people are on cell phones nonstop. It's just a convenience
that we recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. has begun working cell-phone slots into its
Red Tab, Silver Tab, and the youth-focused L2 brands, as well as
some styles of shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the most basic pocket is large enough to hold a zip
disk,'' said L2 designer Thom Massat. ``That's our gold standard.
No pocket smaller than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dockers, the unofficial uniform of Kendall Square, will be
offering its so-called Hands Free khakis with cell and Palm Pilot
pockets in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would look fine empty. But you can tell looking at it that
it's designed for a gadget,'' said Dockers spokeswoman Amy
Gemellaro. The pants come in ``chalk,'' ``new khaki,'' and
``burl,'' part of the green family, and will retail for $52.
</P>
<P>
   For dressier _ and more expensive _ casual clothing, menswear
designer Wilke-Rodriguez put cell-phone pockets on the sleeve of
its cotton/rayon crewneck sweater and inside a charcoal stretch
flannel jacket with concealed snap closures. The pieces will be
available at Bloomingdale's in Chestnut Hill, Jasmine in Boston,
and Casablanca in Lenox.
</P>
<P>
   The concept has even trickled down to the rental tuxedo market.
</P>
<P>
   Fubu the Collection sports a pouch for a cell phone in its
formal wear jackets as a novelty selling point for prom-goers or
groomsmen. One can only hope the groom remembers to shut off the
phone during the vows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
