<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING MUCH OF A DISSING MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cartoony celebrity deathmatch of the month is between Eminem
and Christina Aguilera. She's the co-queen (with Britney Spears) of
the carefully choreographed teen music scene, he's the hate-filled
white rapper whose new album is becoming the soundtrack of summer
2000. She's all high-school tease and exposed bellybutton; he's
sloppy rage and a fully extended middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   The fight kicked up when Aguilera ragged on Eminem's domestic
violence song ``'97 Bonnie and Clyde'' on MTV. His revenge was to
rap about her all-purpose skankiness on his latest hit, ``The Real
Slim Shady,'' including the image of the Real Slim Blondy spreading
venereal disease. Now, in the cover story for the double issue of
Rolling Stone, Aguilera is suitably teed off about the insult, even
if it helped her win the magazine's cover story. ``I was offended
and really disgusted by it,'' she says, adding more
philosophically: ``I see where he's coming from, in the sense that
you take this guy who wants to be respected as a serious rap
artist, and all of a sudden he is in the world of MTV and `TRL.' I
can see where he would get a little mad and want to rebel against
the Britney Spears, 'N Sync, Backstreet Boys world of teen music.''
</P>
<P>
   And not only does the little dissing contest draw the battle
lines in today's best-selling music world, but it serves as a
reminder of the way Rolling Stone manages to embody the two sides
without appearing totally ridiculous. (Imagine the Monkees on the
cover of Rolling Stone 30 years ago, with Mick Jagger and Peter
Tork in a duel.) You can't go 10 pages in this issue without
tripping over a mention of Eminem and a mention of Aguilera, from
Random Notes and Tour Report to Recordings, and yet the whole
things hangs together in some kind of weird, fractured,
peroxide-drenched way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Eminem and Aguilera aren't so different after all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Perfect Storm'' isn't a massive box office hit, it
won't be from imperfect George Clooney hype. The man with the
bobbing head has nailed more magazine covers than his defunct
``ER'' doctor performed intubations. And entertainment junkies
don't seem to tire of his always stubbly mug, even if the July
Men's Journal cover photo of Clooney floating on a piece of
wreckage is just a little bit tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney is a curious celebrity, in that he seems to have it both
ways. He's passionately critical of the gossip press, but he is
charming and endlessly accessible with writers from the glossier
outlets. He's a guy's guy who attracts straight male fans,
evidenced by his Men's Journal front, but then he's a romantic
hero, too, which means Vogue felt comfortable putting him on its
recent cover.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, writer Doug Stanton visits Clooney at the home
he bought from Stevie Nicks _ ``think of a posh fishing lodge
mounted on a wooded hill and you're there'' _ and Clooney supplies
Stanton with basketball tips. Much is made of Clooney's attachment
to ``the Boys,'' eight friends who hang out together to heal their
marital wounds, as well as his concern with his own work ethic.
Indeed, the 39-year-old star says he will never marry again, that
instead of family he will leave a legacy of movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the Readings section of the July issue of
Harper's Magazine there's a blue two-page spread with white
dropped-out type that looks like either an ad for Absolut vodka or
a short story by Mary McGarry Morris. Turns out it's a merger of
both brands: fiction as commerical tool, author as ad-copywriter,
literary reader as bait. Apparently the ad series, yet another
clever grabber from the agents of Absolut, has been around for a
few years, so I am behind in my observation of the blurring of
church and state boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Does it help that Morris's story is critical of our ad-driven
culture, ending with the image of a publically worshipped junk-yard
sign reading ``Absolut''? Or is one man's protective irony another
man's sales spin?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
