<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. NEIGHBORHOOD ADJUSTS TO LIFE WITH ELIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After spending 35 days in an upscale neighborhood
in northwest Washington, Elian Gonzalez may be going home, leaving
behind residents whose initial alarm over the attention their new
neighbor would bring turned into a feeling that his presence was in
some ways a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 58 federal marshals move into the neighborhood, well,
we've felt pretty safe lately,'' said Chris Buckley, who lives
across the street from the Rosedale estate, which is owned by the
Youth for Understanding International Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley's children even made some extra cash from the reporters
and photographers staking out the scene when Elian first moved in
May 25 from the Eastern Shore of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold lemonade for 25 cents and homemade cookies for 25
cents,'' said Buckley's 8-year-old son Conor, who made $7.50 that
day off the thirsty media. ``They said it was good and they also
said, `I want some more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Cleveland Park neighborhood said the biggest
problem has been limited access to the grounds around the estate,
which usually is a hot spot for dog walkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When word first went out `guess who's coming to dinner,' I'm
ashamed to say I thought, `What about the dogs,' '' Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Valdalsum normally lets her dog, Holly, run free on the
fenced grounds that are open to the public. But heightened security
because of Elian has forced dog owners to keep their pets on a
leash and use only a roped-off part of the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have the freedom to walk around,'' Vandalsum
said. ``She wants to go there and run.''
</P>
<P>
   But without the constant trampling of walkers, what once looked
like desert land is now lush green grass, Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   The media, which has spent hours, even days, staking out the
complex trying to capture a story or photo of the young Cuban,
hasn't ruined the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day he (Elian) was coming, the neighbors and the
media were just hanging out together,'' said Ruthanne Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen J. Boitano, a stringer for the Associated Press and
often the only member of the media at the estate, developed a good
relationship with area residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really 98 percent of the neighbors are friendly. One old lady
is crotchety and was snapping at us,'' Boitano said. ``They'll be
happy to get their park back.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents several times invited the Gonzalezes and their friends
to potluck dinners at their $750,000-plus homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very down-to-earth regular people that seemed to be
in limbo and caught up in this political drama that are just
wanting to go home,'' said Miller, who attended one of the dinners.
``The kids are more oblivious. The adults seemed to be carrying the
burden of this political drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political drama emerges from time to time outside of the
estate with protesters carrying signs or yelling through
megaphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few protesters but they've been very well
behaved,'' said Miller, who originally envisioned a chaotic scene
similar to the ones outside Elian's home in Miami's Little Havana.
``It was a small price to have to pay to provide a nice place for
this family that's in limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all the residents agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait until this kid goes back because he's given us a
lot of problems,'' said Margaret Thompson, a 10-year resident. ``I
need to worry about my sewer. I need to worry about my water. I
don't need to worry about this little kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
