<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW WAYS TO LESSEN TAX LIABILITY ON CAPITAL GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Shortly after our son was born we began to make $600
quarterly contributions to a mutual fund account in his name. Since
we now expect he will begin college in four years, we feel it is
time to begin gradually moving money from Magellan to a more
conservative investment. We have transferred $15,000 to the CD. We
plan to make similar transfers each year until his senior year or
until we deplete the account. Our current concern is with respect
to taxes. For several years now Magellan has reported substantial
capital gains, creating an income tax liability. By selling some
shares to purchase the CD, he will be realizing additional capital
gains liabilities this year. When we file his tax return, we may
report that the shares sold were the ones most recently purchased.
This transaction would minimize the capital gain, although a
portion will be treated as a short-term gain and will be taxed at a
higher rate. Is there any way to minimize his tax obligation on the
capital gain? Is there any way to avoid paying taxes on the
interest on the CD?
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Sudbury, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The situation is probably even darker than you think. Unless
you specified in writing to Fidelity which shares were being sold a
few months ago when you sold them to purchase the CD, you will have
to compute the capital gain using either the average cost per share
for all of the Magellan shares your son holds or the
first-in-first-out method. Since the latter would doubtless create
the highest tax liability, the average cost method will probably be
your best choice this year. J.K. Lasser's ``Your Income Tax'' is
emphatic on this point: You cannot wait until you file your
(income) tax return to allot specific sales to gain a tax
advantage, it says.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if you did not make written specifications of the
shares sold and if you choose the average cost method, you will
have to stick with that method when you make subsequent sales.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I can think of to improve the overall tax
position is a fairly meager tactic at this point, which is to
transfer $500 a year from the taxable Magellan account to an
Education IRA in the same fund. You will still have to pay capital
gains taxes on those sales, but if the money is withdrawn for
educational expenses, the withdrawals, including any investment
returns that have been produced, will be tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   The only consolation prize I can give you is to say I think you
are making the right move, slowly transferring the money to
conservative assets as college time draws closer. In fact, I think
I would favor a more aggressive course, moving about $20,000 a year
into the CD accounts, thus having all of the money invested in
short-term instruments by the time your son starts college and
begins the process of paying the bills. From an investment point of
view, the cost of a college education is a short-term liability,
and thus it should be funded with short-term assets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently sold some real estate and have $500,000 available
for investment. I have purchased a new home, mortgage-free, and
have no outstanding debts. My goal is to establish a conservative
investment plan for growth and income, with the income starting
after two years, for I don't know how much longer I will be
actively employed. I have contacted some financial advisers and
have been recommended a number of plans _ some good, some
confusing, some contradictory. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   G.C., Southborough, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In all candor, I think the reason you're having trouble
sorting through the various suggestions that have been made to you
is that you are probably looking for more than you can reasonably
expect. If your entire $500,000 were invested for income through a
five-year CD, after two years you would have $583,630, using the
highest national rate of 7.74 percent entering this week. At that
point, it would produce an annual income stream of $45,172. That
seems to fill the bill with a few thousand to spare. But it would
leave you little protection against inflation during your
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate how serious the threat of inflation is, consider
that 10 years from now you will need $59,245 to buy what $42,000
now buys, so the entire amount of your anticipated Social Security
benefit will simply go to offset the effect of inflation during
that first decade. And after that. . .
</P>
<P>
   Here's my suggestion: Divide the money into two equal pools,
with $250,000 going into the five-year CD and the remaining
invested in a good balanced fund, such as Fidelity Puritan or
Vanguard Balanced Index. After the two years you anticipate
working, the CD account would have grown to $291,680. At that
point, you could withdraw the actual yield, which would be $22,576
a year. In all likelihood, that figure would be inadequate for your
needs, so you would have to supplement that income with earnings
from a part-time job or some other kind of employment.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other $250,000, if your balanced fund produced
average annual returns of 9 percent and you reinvested all
distributions, you would accumulate $612,762 in that account by the
time you are 65. At that stage, you could divert $250,000 of those
funds from the balanced fund into your CD account, which would mean
that between the CD yield and Social Security you would have
sufficient funds to maintain your current standard of living. And
you would also have $362,762 remaining in the balanced fund, a pool
that should, in the long run, protect you against the ravages of
subsequent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, if you could save a bit of your earnings during
the next couple of years _ say, enough to fully fund IRA accounts _
that certainly wouldn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am recently retired and my wife expects to retire later
this year. My 401(k) money is still with my employer, but I plan to
put it in the same fund as the IRAs are in. In addition, I have a
military pension and my wife and I both plan to draw Social
Security at the earliest date. What do you recommend I invest in to
produce $1,500 a month without touching the principal?
</P>
<P>
   D.B., Escondido, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two ways you can go with this, in my opinion. One
is precisely what you suggest _ adding the 401(k) money to the
Vanguard LifeStrategy Conservative Growth position and simply
establishing a program for monthly withdrawals of $1,500. Regular
readers of this column, I hope, are aware that I am skeptical about
withdrawing money from stock funds, effectively anticipating
capital gains and setting up a schedule for spending them whether
or not they have been realized. But since LifeStrategy Conservative
Growth is a balanced fund, with only 35.6 percent of its portfolio
in stocks, that schedule would entail withdrawals that represent
less than the yield, which is currently 4.24 percent, according to
Morningstar Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   However, such a plan would not guarantee that you would not be
touching your principal. For example, so far this year the fund has
produced only a 1.7 percent total return. Had you invested $504,000
in the fund at the start of this year and withdrawn $1,500 a month,
you would have seen an erosion of nearly $5,000 of your capital by
now.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the second idea. As discussed in the letter above,
long-term CD rates are currently quite attractive, and an
investment of $235,000 in a five-year jumbo CD would supply you
with the desired income stream, leaving you with $89,000 to add to
your Vanguard accounts that are designed to protect you against the
inflation of the later years of your retirement. If you took that
course, in order to offset the fact that you can expect no growth
from the CD accounts, I would be slightly more aggressive, putting
the $89,000 in Vanguard LifeStrategy Moderate Growth fund, which is
similar to the fund you already hold, but allocating 54 percent of
its assets on the stock side.
</P>
<P>
   I have been writing about CDs a good deal in recent months, and
my mailbag is stuffed with letters from people inquiring where they
can find the rates I quote in my columns _ usually complaining the
rates offered locally are much lower. CD rates have ticked down a
bit in recent weeks but are still attractive. You can find a list
of institutions with the nation's best CD rates on the Data Bank
page of the Sunday New York Times or by going online to one of the
many Web sites that track interest rates
(www.bankrate.com/brm/rate/dep(long dash)home.asp is the one I
use).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
