<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-LINCOLN-RENEWAL-BOS &LR;      06-28 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-RENEWAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN'S GETAWAY TOPS RESTORATION LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Lincoln's summer getaway, just 3 miles
and a short horse ride from the White House, was an escape not just
from the heat of the city but also from the day-to-day stresses of
office.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson Cottage, in northwest Washington, is where Lincoln
wrote his second draft of the Emancipation Proclamation. The
cottage desperately needs interior renovation, which is why the
structure tops this year's list of most endangered historic places.
The annual list, put together by the National Trust for Historic
Preservation, identifies historical sites in danger of demolition
or deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a call to all Americans that some of our most precious
treasures are at risk,'' Richard Moe, president of the trust, says.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1862 and 1864, while battles loomed in the distance,
Lincoln's son Tad climbed the trees outside Anderson Cottage and
was scolded in the family dining room when his pet goat ate flowers
from the garden. Lincoln's wife, Mary, stayed in the second-floor
dressing room during her recovery from a head injury she suffered
in a carriage accident. Some historians believe the mishap was a
sabotage attempt intended for the president.
</P>
<P>
   These days the dining room houses a copy machine and the
dressing room's hardwood floor is covered with Army-green carpet,
while the light-blue paint is peeling and the ceiling shows water
damage. The spot where Lincoln worked on his famous document is
practically bare, with the view from an old window once overlooking
the Capitol blocked by a new building.
</P>
<P>
   The only clues that the president spent about a quarter of his
term here are the few portraits and mementos displayed by workers
using the cottage, which sits on the grounds of the US Soldiers'
and Airmen's Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too important of a place to be largely unknown,'' Moe
said. ``This is one of the city's greatest hidden treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust hopes to turn the building into an education center,
restoring its interior and furnishing it from the era. Although the
cost to restore the building was not disclosed, officials estimate
it would require several million dollars in public and private
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Funds were also scarce during the Civil War, which was why
Lincoln furnished the house seasonally, moving the family's
belongings to the cottage in May and taking them back to the White
House in November. The cottage, in essence, served as Lincoln's
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge procession of carriages that would carry the
president's goods, and in the fall it would go in the other
direction,'' said Nick Minecci, a spokesman for the Armed Forces
Retirement Home whose office is in the cottage.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen strides from the back door is a copper beech
tree where Lincoln would spend time playing with his son, reading,
or writing correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last living link to President Lincoln,'' Minecci
said. ``If trees could talk, I'd like to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tree branches form a trailing canopy surrounding the trunk,
creating a nook that is seven degrees cooler than the rest of the
lawn, Minecci said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president would bring his desk and chair,'' he said. ``If
this place was where he came to get away from it all, the copper
beech tree was the getaway from the getaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on this year's list are the Dwight D. Eisenhower Veterans
Affair Medical Center in Leavenworth, Kan.; historic neighborhood
schools around the country; the Hudson River Valley in New York;
5th and Forbes Historic Retail area in Pittsburgh; Nantucket;
Okeechobee battlefield in Florida; Red Mountain Mining District in
Colorado; Santa Anita Racetrack in California; Valley Forge
National Historical Park in Pennsylvania; and Wheelock Academy in
Oklahoma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
