<SLUG> BC-SOC-GOLDCUP-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ALL COMES DOWN TO A COIN FLIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Heads I win, tails you lose. Only in soccer
do 22 people play for 90 minutes and have something important
decided by a toss of a coin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's weird, huh?'' US midfielder Julie Foudy said Tuesday
night after her team had won its Gold Cup group by drawing, 0-0,
with Brazil at Foxboro Stadium and then winning the tie-breaking
coin flip. ``The team was high-fiving me like I won. I said, `I
didn't do a thing.' I just stood there.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in soccer. No overtime. No penalty-kick shootout. Just the
simplest game of chance. The Americans prevailed _ and probably
ducked a date with nemesis China in Saturday's semifinals in
Louisville, Ky. _ because Sissi, Brazil's designated numismatist,
called tails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have called tails, too,'' said Foudy.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever thought it would come down to random chance, not in
a group that was so one-sided that the Americans and Brazilians had
been able to name their margins in their previous two matches. The
US hammered Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, 11-0, and Costa Rica, 8-0. So,
incredibly, did Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing, that two teams both did 19-0,'' said US coach April
Heinrichs.
</P>
<P>
   Under tournament rules, it meant that if the two teams played to
a tie in the group finale, they would go to a coin flip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew about the goal differential,'' said Heinrichs. ``We
knew exactly what the criteria were. We understood that. I told the
team, `There's no overtime. Get the business done here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Americans didn't try. They outshot the Brazilians,
18-8. They had a 13-3 edge in corner kicks. And when Foudy was
low-bridged in the penalty area by Formiga in the closing moments,
they had a golden chance to win the game. But Kristine Lilly
decided in mid-stride to go right instead of left with her kick,
keeper Andreia smothered the ball, and it was spare-change time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never saw a coin flip,'' said Heinrichs, who played half a
dozen years with the national team. ``We've heard of it. Everyone
always talked about what a disaster it was to have a game decided
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes always want to decide their own fate, and most sports
allow for it. Extra innings. Double, triple, quadruple overtime.
Playoff holes. Swimoffs. Pistols, blindfolded, at 30 paces.
Anything but Lady Luck.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer players would rather play until they seize up like the
Tin Man than go the spare-change route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather play overtime,'' said Foudy. ``We had 'em, too. I
was like, `Man, just give us another 15 minutes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even penalty kicks (which is how the 1999 women's and 1994 men's
World Cups were decided) are preferable. At least someone gets to
put a foot to a ball in some format. Or a thumb-wrestling contest.
A three-legged race? Pie-eating? Naming world capitals?
</P>
<P>
   But a coin in the air?
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it isn't the best way to do it, but there's no
other way,'' said Brazilian coach Jose Duarte. ``So we have to
agree with it.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, nobody knew how to do it. After Canadian
referee Sonia Denoncourt blew the final whistle, the teams shook
hands and waved to their fans. Then they milled around, waiting for
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `What the heck are we doing?' '' Foudy said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16,000 customers weren't sure, either. Some tournament
matches do go to overtime. ``Some go right to penalty kicks,'' said
Heinrichs. Most draws end in draws, though, with the teams walking
off. But nobody was leaving. And nobody was moving.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, tournament official Jill Fracisco summoned Foudy and
Sissi to midfield and produced a coin. She pointed out one side,
then the other. And because the Brazilians were visitors, Sissi got
to choose. Fracisco tossed, caught, put one hand atop the other,
and showed the coin to both players.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody moved. Nobody pumped a fist. Nobody slumped a shoulder.
Was it a practice toss? Was it the real deal? Nobody knew. Finally,
Foudy turned to her teammates. ``We won,'' she informed them.
</P>
<P>
   Won what, other than the group? Not the game, which goes into
the books as 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you tie a team,'' Foudy mused, ``you walk away as if
you lost.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Chinese don't beat Mexico in their group finale, the
Americans will end up playing them in the semis anyway.
</P>
<P>
   What they won was a game of chance, and they weren't quite sure
how to behave. So Foudy's teammates high-fived her because they
figured they had to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you celebrate a coin toss?'' Foudy wondered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
