<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LATINO-CHEFS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 RESTAURANTS' LATINO FLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cafe Louis, an upscale eatery on Newbury Street, is
known for clams al forno and oven-poached cod. Specializing in
Northern Italian cuisine, the menu conjures images of hefty Italian
cooks. But the chef de cuisine is Mexican. And with the exception
of the sous chef, the rest of the cooks hail from Latin America:
two Peruvians, a Mexican, six Salvadorans and a Colombian.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same at Giacomo's Ristorante in the North End. Their
three cooks are Latino. Patrons peer through the open-air kitchen
and often ask the waiters: Where are the Italians?
</P>
<P>
   ``They wonder because they see only Hispanic guys,'' said chef
Richard Talieri, who creates the daily specials menu but leaves the
cooking to his staff.
</P>
<P>
   At dining spots across Boston, and in big cities across the
country, Latinos have worked their way up from jobs as dishwashers
and busboys to more prestigious work. Now, in Boston, New York, Los
Angeles and Chicago, Latin American immigrants can easily account
for more than half of the cooking staff at any given restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a comparative basis they're better cooks,'' said Anthony
Bourdain, chef of Les Halles, a Park Avenue brasserie. ``The best
French cooks, the best Italian cooks in New York are Mexican and
Ecuadoran.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the majority of line cooks at many restaurants are
Latino, the person at the head of the line _ the chef de cuisine _
is usually Caucasian. It has become, say many in the business, an
unspoken rule: Put an Italian, French person or American in charge
of the kitchen, someone who can charm diners. Keep the Latinos, and
other immigrants, in the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some Americans who don't like seeing me in charge,''
said Simon Restrepo, a Colombian immigrant who is the evening sous
chef at Biba. ``They are jealous because they went to culinary
school and I didn't. They have a lot of pride and can't accept
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diners expect the affable Italian speaking with a lilting
accent, or the ebullient American, or the French chef who speaks
with a raised eyebrow. Those stereotypes clash against the reality
of the quiet, meticulous Brazilian searing steak and reducing
sauces _ unseen by the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restaurantgoers don't see them,'' said Jaime Mammano, the chef
at Mistral, whose cooking staff of 25 includes 15 Latinos. Mammano
calls them ``fantastic cooks.'' They learn quickly, and they don't
have attitudes, like Americans who graduate from culinary arts
schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids coming out of culinary schools are a little too big
for their britches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs say that once Latinos proved they could outshine culinary
school-trained cooks, the chefs began promoting them.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Latino chefs, Restrepo, 29, began as a dishwasher and
worked his way up over 10 years. Susan Regis, co-chef at Biba,
calls Restrepo her ``amazing right-hand man.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many chefs, Regis said she prefers hiring Latino immigrants
over culinary arts-educated cooks. Many chefs say Latinos are
better cooks, and they all have their theories as to why.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grow up in the culture of cooking, and we grow up in the
culture of frozen TV dinners and fast food,'' Regis said. ``They
watched their moms coming home from the market with fresh-killed
chickens, with the head and feet still on . . . so imagine the kind
of heartfelt, tangible feeling that they can bring to food.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Davis, the chef at Henrietta's Table in Harvard Square,
attributes it to how Latinos _ and Asians _ are brought up. ``Their
food comes from the garden, or farm, whereas growing up in America,
food comes off supermarket shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kingsford, chef de cuisine at Al Forno, said the
Guatemalans who work for him know how to balance flavors better _
an art that can make or break a dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine times out of ten, the Guatemalan cook is right on the
money, whereas the American will ask me, `How's this?' And it's
like, `Man, this needs salt.' '' Kingsford said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Johnson, chef of The Blue Room in Kendall Square, agrees,
saying Latinos have ``sharper palates'' because they were raised on
home cooking, unlike Americans raised on a lot of processed foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in a lot of restaurant cooking is often adding
the right amount of seasoning,'' he said. ``You know how in
cookbooks it says `salt to taste'? That's where a lot of people
screw up. The same is true in restaurant cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from tastebud aptitude, there's an attitude difference,
many said. Americans who attend cooking school tend to get
frustrated more easily, and are overwhelmed by the pace of
kitchens. They quit more often, and get bored preparing the same
dish over and over _ a necessary part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   They require a lot of ``psychological maintenance'' for their
fragile egos, said Bourdain, of Les Halles.
</P>
<P>
   But many Latin American immigrants, who tend to come up through
the dishwashing ranks and who have held grueling jobs back home,
see cooking as an easy job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather work with a Mexican who worked his way up from
dishwasher than the kids graduating from culinary arts schools
today,'' Bourdain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
