<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB RETAILERS STILL WAITING FOR THE REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it too soon to say the retail side of electronic commerce was
wildly oversold in the first place and is now turning out to be a
major disappointment?
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just that the e-tailing world is starting to resemble
an episode of the hit show ``Survivor.'' Each week another company
bites the dust.
</P>
<P>
   It is that many of the assumptions that seemed to underly the
whole industry are crumbling, along with the stock prices. Chief
among them: that e-tailers enjoy a critical cost advantage over
traditional retailers.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the argument: How could anyone compete with the big
e-tailers, who didn't need to build stores and didn't need to pay a
huge work force to staff those stores?
</P>
<P>
   So how do you reconcile that with the latest news, reported in
Sunday's New York Times, that most e-tailers are raising their
prices and shipping costs in a bid to become profitable?
</P>
<P>
   Or a hypercritical report on Amazon.com, issued by Lehman
Brothers last week, which says Amazon can't find a way to make a
profit on the items it sells, and that as a result the company
suffers from a ``weak balance sheet, poor working capital
management and massive negative operating cash flow?''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Haverty has an answer. ``People forgot that what the
Internet does is deliver bits,'' said Haverty, a senior vice
president at State Street Research. ``You need people to deliver
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   And it turns out that delivering stuff is not easy _ or cheap.
The Internet may be new economy, but getting someone in a van to
schlep something to your house is decidedly old economy. It can
also be expensive, especially at a time of rising wages and
gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the retail side, the Internet is not something that is
going to revolutionize everything that came before it,'' said Rick
Wise, an e-commerce specialist at Mercer Management Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Compare e-commerce to an innovation in retailing that truly was
revolutionary: the rise of the superstore.
</P>
<P>
   When Tom Stemberg, the founder of Staples, launched his chain in
1986, the typical local stationery store sold a dozen yellow legal
pads for $10 or $11. The first Staples sold the same pads for
$3.99.
</P>
<P>
   With a price advantage like that, was it any wonder that Staples
and its fellow superstores became huge hits, or that they quickly
vanquished their mom-and-pop competitors?
</P>
<P>
   When e-tailers have boasted big price advantages, those
advantages have been illusory. Thanks to a big infusion of money
from venture capital and initial public offerings, the e-stores
were able, for a time, to charge artificially low prices and
subsidize their shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone. With the new push for profitability and the
drying up of Wall Street money, prices must now reflect economic
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When companies are forced to charge appropriate prices, we
will find out which Internet categories are truly mass markets and
which ones are luxury markets,'' said Nick Moore, a money manager
with Jurika &AMP; Voyles in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Groceries may fall into the latter category. So far, none of the
Internet grocery companies has figured out how to make a buck. Two
of the major players, Webvan and HomeGrocer,com, this week
announced a merger. Webvan lost $57 million in its most recent
quarter; HomeGrocer lost $43 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the two boost prices to cover their costs, will there still
be enough customers left to make this a big company? Analysts
aren't sure. They also have their doubts whether other categories _
pet food and electronic equipment _ will ever succeed on the Web.
The former is too cheap; the latter requires too much selling and
explaining. Books, records, and videotapes are a better fit, say
money managers, although it remains unclear whether they will ever
generate significant profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an equity investor, I find it hard to believe that
e-commerce companies are going to be very attractive,'' said
Haverty of State Street Research.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Wise, the Mercer consultant, is more optimistic. He expects
the next generation of e-tailers to add value by focusing on the
Web's true strengths: providing information and convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Put us down in the skeptics' camp. We don't doubt that e-tailing
is here to stay, or that it will take a chunk of the retail dollar,
over time. But we suspect it will never be the revolutionary
development it was supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't have a closed mind on the subject. If some wizard
like Harry Potter comes along one day and finds a way to send
books, records, pet food, and televisions over the Internet and
have them pop out, fully formed, in your house, then we may be
prepared to change our minds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
