<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AMAZON-VIABILITY-BOS &LR;      06-28 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-VIABILITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN STORE FOR AMAZON.COM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, Jeff Bezos sat on top of the e-commerce world. The
cheery founder of Amazon.com Inc. had delivered on his promise to
get big fast, pushing beyond his initial mission of selling books
online to offer CDs, toys, and even power tools. Investors made him
a billionaire, on paper at least, and Time magazine made him its
Person of the Year for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Then came April's punishing market correction.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, it seemed, Wall Street decided the dot-com business
model was overhyped and exceedingly risky, with too many companies
emphasizing rapid growth over profits.
</P>
<P>
   As impatient investors abandoned e-commerce stocks and venture
capital money dried up, the list of former Internet retailers began
to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Boo.com, a British clothing e-tailer, went out with a splash
just six months after its flashy debut.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com slammed its online doors shut after being jilted by
a major investor, Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Still others, like the gift site Violent.com, quietly faded away
from the online marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even the mighty seem vulnerable. Last week, Amazon.com, the
king of electronic commerce, was forced to defend itself against a
highly critical analyst's report that questioned whether the
e-tailer could survive in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, a Lehman Brothers analyst, Ravi Suria, drew harsh
conclusions after comparing money-losing Amazon.com to
bricks-and-mortar retailers, which have long been judged on their
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com's weak balance sheet and inability to turn a profit
on each item sold were ``financial characteristics that have driven
innumerable retailers to disaster throughout history,'' Suria
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Suria said Amazon.com's mounting debt and negative cash flow
posed a large risk for investors buying its convertible bonds _
debt that can be turned into common stock. And he warned that the
company will be under more pressure this Christmas selling season,
with cash-flush traditional retailers like Wal-Mart Stores and
Kmart Corp. spending big bucks to improve their online stores.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com spokeswoman Patty Smith called the Lehman Brothers
report ``ridiculous'' and said the Seattle-based Amazon.com had $1
billion in cash at the end of March, more than enough to finance
its business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to generate positive cash flow from operations over
the rest of the year,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Amazon.com's dominance in the online marketplace
had helped the company escape much of the dot-com backlash that saw
other Internet stores laying off employees, slashing advertising
costs, eliminating freebies and closing their doors.
</P>
<P>
   But now, it's clear that profits really do matter _ and even the
Web's biggest store is being punished for failing to comply with
Old Economy rules. Since December, Amazon.com's stock price has
plunged 68 percent, including a 19 percent drop last Friday
following the release of the Lehman Brothers report.
</P>
<P>
   Lackluster comments from other analysts, including influential
Merrill Lynch analyst Henry Blodget, haven't helped Amazon.com.
While maintaining a strong buy rating on Amazon.com, Blodget has
predicted smaller gains in the company's second-quarter sales due
to slowdowns in the nation's economy and online retailing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone believes that Amazon.com's situation is so dire.
Many analysts point to the company's successes in attracting tens
of millions of customers by expanding into new markets such as
music, furniture, household appliances and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Amazon.com boasts one of the highest buyer conversion
rates in the industry. About 10 percent of Amazon.com browsers
turned into buyers last month, while the industry average is less
than 5 percent, according to PC Data, a technology research firm in
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   And in spite of its recent struggles, Amazon.com's market value
of $11.9 billion is 12 times the size that of rival
Barnesandnoble.com. Even Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., a traditional
retailing pioneer with a market capitalization of $11.6 billion,
lags slightly behind Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the sky is falling,'' said Scott Van Winkle, an
analyst with the investment firm Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill in Boston.
``We thought (Amazon.com's stock) was overvalued at $50 to $100.
But I like the company. I like the business model.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Amazon.com began recovering this week, rising $2.5625
on Nasdaq Tuesday to close at $36.50.
</P>
<P>
   Some dot-com executives complain that Wall Street has added to
the turmoil by providing its share of misdirection. Last year, a
joke made the rounds that the best way to lose analysts' interest
was to mention a path to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, an analyst angered Edward Albertian, chief executive
of online grocer Streamline.com, by telling him to focus on
``selling his space'' rather than planning a path to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was in left field,'' said Albertian, who
previously worked for Staples Inc. and Star Markets Co. ``It's
always about profits.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that few Internet players _ with the possible
exception of barnesandnoble.com _ will take any pleasure in
Amazon.com's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Already, America Online, Yahoo and other portals that rely
heavily on advertising revenue have been hard hit by online
retailers' penny-pinching. And this week, share prices of big
technology consultants like Scient Corp. and Viant Corp. fell on
concerns that a Web shakeout will hurt their revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Small online retailers say Amazon.com's troubles are bad news
for anyone who's trying to lay the foundation for a successful Web
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to build a category together,'' said Michael
Lannon, chief executive of Send.com, a Waltham-based online
retailer of gifts. ``If Amazon.com succeeds _ or anyone that I
compete against succeeds _ that's one more piece of evidence that
the whole market is viable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
