<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-ALVAREZ-ART-BO     06-28 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ALVAREZ-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WRITING HER BOOK OF HIGH GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ Julia Alvarez has just sat through a culinary
celebration of the Dominican Republic roots she explores in her
novels ``How the Garcia Girls Lost Their Accents,'' ``Yo!'' and
``In the Time of the Butterflies.'' So after a meal of bean soup,
rice casserole, and bread pudding, what does Alvarez decide to read
to an audience of 40 fans?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not an excerpt from her historical work of fiction,
``In the Name of Salome,'' published this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like reading from a novel,'' says Alvarez, her large
eyes, the color of a rich cup of coffee, brimming with
mischievousness. ``I've always done it because people have told me
that I have to do it. I turned 50 this year and I figured I'm not
going to do anything I don't want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right?'' she asks, her moment of defiance crumbling into the
politeness expected of traditional Dominican women.
</P>
<P>
   Right, murmurs the audience at the New England Culinary
Institute, encouraging Alvarez to be like the independent,
strong-willed Latinas they read about in her novels. And so the
diners get to hear something more relevant: a piece about the
eating habits of her characters in ``In the Name of Salome.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez has carved out a successful career doing the unexpected.
She spent her early years as a migrant professor/writer, jumping
from one adjunct teaching job to another. Three years ago, after
producing three novels, one book of essays, and four works of
poetry, she gave up a tenured teaching position at Vermont's
Middlebury College to devote herself to writing full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez also defies expectations with ``In the Name of Salome.''
The novel follows the lives of Salome Urena, a poor, Dominican
woman of color who overcomes her circumstances to become the
country's national poet and her daughter, Camila, who at the ripe
age of 65 left a Vassar College teaching job to preach the
revolution in Fidel Castro's Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find any reveries here about assimilation and accents
that Americans have come to expect from Hispanic writers, says Ilan
Stavans, a Spanish professor at Amherst College who has edited many
anthologies of Latino literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julia is one that doesn't give the audience what the audience
wants,'' he says, ``but I think in some ways, teaches the audience
to want something different.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ask Alvarez, she'll simply say she's writing the books
she's compelled to write. The subjects reflect the bicultural
heritage of a woman who immigrated from the DR with her family when
she was 10 years old. But the stories have an added complexity.
They're tales of Dominican life told by a writer raised in the
United States who's part of an American literary tradition
(although when Alvarez says ``America'' she's referring to the
entire hemisphere, not just the US).
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think of myself as a hybrid,'' explains Alvarez,
``and there's still that pressure: You're American. You're
Dominican. What is it to be a Dominican? What is it to be an
American? What you should you do if you're either one?
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think the world is becoming more multicultural,''
Alvarez continues. ``It's going to be impossible to keep these
kinds of borders into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Alvarez didn't really know much about Salome Urena.
It was the name of a street in her hometown of Santo Domingo. Words
emblazoned on a school Alvarez often passed by. Writing the novel
helped Alvarez learn more about the birth of the nation she came
from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go back and read the literature,'' says Alvarez.
``Understand what was happening in the other half of the
hemisphere. Try to understand what it is that happened that created
such a different America.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, she discovered some lingering phobias. In
``Salome,'' Alvarez hints that Camila may have been a lesbian, a
lifestyle choice that people hid then and one that remains somewhat
controversial now in Latin communities. (``Ay Dios mio,'' Alvarez's
mother responded when Alvarez revealed Camila's sexual preference,
``you're going to get into touble with that.'')
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was also disturbed by the specter of racism in the
country. Salome, a mulatto woman, was made ``whiter and whiter'' in
her official portraits, she says. ``I was just alarmed, alarmed.
This sense that out of respecto, she has to be lightened up.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez makes these comments while driving from her Weymouth,
Vt., home to Burlington, where the culinary institute event took
place. She manages to make significant eye contact, touch a leg,
and gesticulate often with her hands, while smoothly maneuvering
through traffic on Vermont's country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Warm and talkative, Alvarez has a voice that barely contains
traces of her Dominican roots. But she often speckles her speech
with Spanish words like analfabeto (illiterate) and companero
(companion).
</P>
<P>
   A gray top and loose black pants cover her petite, almost gaunt
figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of that was getting sick in Alta Gracia,'' Alvarez says
of her skinniness, referring to the organic coffee farm she and her
husband, Bill Eichner, own in the Dominican Republic. ``And being
on this damn book tour. It's just grinding, you know. Sometimes you
get to a place, then you have an interview, you go on to give the
reading, and you get back to the hotel at 11, and all you want to
do is crash.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Alvarez got to the point of promoting her books
on two-month tours is the stuff of legend. Her father, a physician,
had plotted to overthrow the Dominican dictator Rafael Trujillo.
When the coup failed, he fled to America with his wife and four
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez lost her homeland, her relatives, and her culture, but
the loss gave her the fuel she needed to become a writer. Now
Alvarez spends her days producing prose in the upstairs study of a
Vermont house she and Eichner built from wood found on his parents'
farm.
</P>
<P>
   She reclaims what was lost when she became an immigrant by
visiting the Dominican Republic four or five times a year and
working on projects like Alta Gracia. The name literally means
``high grace,'' but it's also what Dominicans call their patron
virgin, Altagracia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I wouldn't have felt so compelled if I were, say, living
in a community like Boston,'' says Alvarez of her work at Alta
Gracia. ``I live in Vermont. I mean, the Latino population here is
. . .,'' she scrunches her body into a ball, ``very small. It's the
calling and the yearning for what I left behind there.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to sell organic coffee. (Bags of the beans are
available at the Middlebury Food Co-op and womenshands.com for $10
to $12.) The money raised will fund a literacy and art center on
the farm, which hugs a mountain in the Dominican interior.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, who still occassionally teaches at Middlebury, brought
12 college students to Alta Gracia for a course last winter. The
pupils worked the land, taught locals how to read, and wrote about
their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room of her home, which is silent except for the
tweeting of birds, Alvarez thumbs through a thick binder of those
Alta Gracia memories: photographs, writing, and drawings the
students made to record the class. Her pride and excitement is
palpable as she turns each page.
</P>
<P>
   There's Carmen, the wife of Alta Gracia's caretaker, who
literally let down her hair under the influence of the Americans.
Another photograph shows the golden-ponytailed Lupe, who taught the
students cooking and gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lupe, my dear, is a man,'' Alvarez announces with a flourish.
``The kids were intrigued with her/him. She dresses like you would
not believe. She's a glamour girl.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove the point Alvarez starts turning the pages faster.
``I'm trying to see if I can find another picture of Lupe,'' she
says, before finally locating a photo of a reclining Lupe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult for Alvarez to stop teaching. She had been an
educator since getting her masters in creative writing at Syracuse
University. Three years ago, she decided it was finally time to
focus completely on the writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really strongly love the classroom,'' says Alvarez. ``But,
you know, I used to tell my students this: `Only the empty hand is
free to hold.' You've got to let it go so it fills up with
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   She speaks from experience. In 1988, when Alvarez's
undergraduate alma mater Middlebury College offered her a tenure
track teaching job, she let go of her peripatetic writing life. At
the time, she worried about being a single woman in Vermont. She
wondered if she would find a companero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was a woman in my late 30s, in a small town,'' Alvarez
says. ``I thought, `Well, this is it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A chance visit to the local ophthalmologist wiped away the
pessimism. The doctor was Eichner, who'd just returned from the
Dominican Republic after a stint volunteering at a charity hospital
run by Alvarez's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez calls Eichner a ``doer,'' and the difference between the
two is obvious. It's Eichner who easily recites hard facts about
Alta Gracia: 200 acres that produced 2,000 pounds of coffee its
first harvest, he says. From Alvarez you hear romantic notions
about Alta Gracia's possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Eichner, who was raised on a Nebraska farm and grows vegetables
on the couple's 10 acres of land, is also responsible for the
subject Alvarez is chewing on at the culinary institute: her
introduction to the culinary world. As Alvarez explains it, she
didn't know her pots from her pans before marrying Eichner. Now
food is an integral part of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course,'' Alvarez reads to the audience, ``the changes
in my life trickle down into the lives of my characters. Now my
characters eat more than before. Or, let's put it this way, I think
a lot more about what they might eat, something I never used to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
