<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA LAW BANNING ABORTION PROCEDURE OVERTURNED BY HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday handed down its most
important abortion-related decision in years, overturning a
Nebraska law that had banned a procedure that abortion foes find
especially objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 ruling declared the law an unconstitutional ``undue
burden'' on a woman's right to choose. As important as the ruling
is, no one expects it to settle the nationwide debate over abortion
that has been fought for years in the arenas of politics, law and
ordinary conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nebraska is one of 30 states that have banned
``partial-birth abortion,'' a term that abortion opponents embrace
but that the medical profession does not recognize, the Nebraska
law went further than most statutes because it did not contain an
exception for the woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Wednesday, while not automatically invalidating the
laws in other states, made it unmistakably clear that they cannot
stand if they do not contain such an exception.
</P>
<P>
   The majority decision was written by Justice Stephen G. Breyer
and joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor,
David H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia,
Clarence Thomas and Anthony M. Kennedy dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ruling was the first on an abortion-related issue
for Ginsburg and Breyer, who joined the tribunal after a 1992
decision in which the court upheld the right to choose abortion in
a 5-4 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the 1997 Nebraska law had argued that it applied
only to a method known as dilation and extraction, used for some
abortions close to the 24-week point of viability outside the womb.
In this operation the fetus is removed intact after the doctor
collapses the skull by suctioning out its contents.
</P>
<P>
   But the court majority Wednesday was not persuaded by that
reasoning. It said the Nebraska law's language was so broad that it
might be used by abortion foes to outlaw another procedure, in
which a pre-viable fetus is dismembered as the doctor extracts it
from the uterus. The latter method is commonly used to end
pregnancies in the second trimester, during which the high court
has already held that a woman's right to choose outweighs the
state's interest in fetal life.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's ruling Wednesday upheld the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the Eighth Circuit, in St. Louis, which struck down the
Nebraska law last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court had emphasized beforehand that it would not
reconsider the basic right of a woman to choose abortion, as set
down in the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision of 1973. And it was very
clear to anyone who had paid attention to the Nebraska case that
there were many paths the justices could choose.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even so, as the first abortion issue to go before the tribunal
since 1992, the Nebraska case, Stenberg vs. Carhart, No. 99-830,
had stirred great interest.
</P>
<P>
   When the case was argued before a packed courtroom on April 25,
only Scalia seemed sympathetic to the Nebraska law. ``The state is
worried about rendering society callous to infanticide,'' said
Scalia, the court's most outspoken abortion opponent. ``Why is that
not a valid state interest?''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor asked why the Nebraska law contained no exception on
use of the procedure for the woman's health. Donald B. Stenberg,
the Nebraska attorney general, contended an exception was
unnecessary since another procedure, dilation and evacuation, was
available.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Breyer said, some medical briefs maintained that the
other procedure was more risky for some women. Stenberg insisted
that the justices were obliged to defer to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision may be viewed on the Supreme Court's website,
www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
