<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MARX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRIUMPHS AND STRUGGLES OF KARL MARX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
KARL MARX 
A Life 
By Francis Wheen 
Norton, 448 pp., $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Soviet Union has evaporated. Communism in China has taken on
a distinct capitalist sheen. And the last remaining countries still
firmly embracing communism, Cuba and North Korea, are economic
basket cases. Little more than 100 years after predicting
capitalism's demise in his magnum opus ``Das Kapital,'' Karl Marx
would seem to enjoy little appeal outside university walls or a
shrinking circle of ardent believers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Marx remains a seminal figure in intellectual history. So
now comes Francis Wheen, a columnist for The Guardian in London and
writer for the British humor magazine Private Eye, with a witty,
sometimes hilarious, sometimes pathetic portrait of the man. In
``Karl Marx: A Life,'' Wheen is largely sympathetic to Marx's
economic and political ideology, but what he does most effectively
is provide a compelling and detailed portrait of Marx's humanity,
his triumphs as well as his many struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is Marx's ideology rather than his life that have
echoed across time. Wheen excoriates political leaders for
perverting Marx's ideas to justify their oppressive regimes,
comparing them to those who interpret the Bible to buttress their
intolerance. Marx ``would have been appalled by the crimes
committed in his name,'' Wheen writes. ``The bastard creeds
espoused by Stalin, Mao, or Kim Il Sung treated his work rather as
modern Christians use the Old Testament: much of it simply ignored
or discarded, while a few resonant slogans (`opium of the people,'
`dictatorship of the proletariat') are wrenched out of context,
turned upside down, and then cited as apparently divine
justification.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wheen spends less time on Marx's philosophy than on his
turbulent personal life. The portrait is that of a brilliant
thinker who did a fairly miserable job of handling his private
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Marx was born in 1818 in the Rhineland. His father was a
religious and social liberal whose forebears included prominent
Dutch and German rabbis. Feeling trapped in his hometown, the young
Marx was happy to leave for college, and by the time he was 19, his
father had recognized the son's intellectual gifts and conceded
that Marx had ``outgrown him.'' When his father died, a year later,
Marx did not even bother to attend the funeral: He said he was too
busy.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing college, Marx left Prussia for France, where he
met his intellectual soulmate, Friedrich Engels. Marx was expelled
from France for his political views and moved to Brussels; he lived
there until he was forced to flee after the failure of various
European uprisings in 1848 _ the revolutionary year that also saw
Marx and Engels publish their ``Communist Manifesto.'' Marx
decamped to London, where he spent a great deal of time in pubs and
in the reading room of the British Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Marx lived the rest of his life in a perpetual state of poverty,
dodging creditors and depending on the generosity of Engels, who
raided the petty cash box of his father's firm to support his
friend and mentor. As Wheen acidly describes, Marx aspired to
maintain a bourgeois lifestyle; in spite of his family's financial
misfortune, the champion of the proletariat insisted on keeping a
personal secretary _ despite his incompetence _ because not having
one would tarnish his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Marx was a thin-skinned thinker who raged against critics,
usually in the form of book-length rebuttals filled with lacerating
opinions. As Wheen notes, Marx was a ``sadistic intellectual
thug.'' And he was regularly beset by physical ailments, especially
when deadlines loomed. ``At all events, I hope the bourgeoisie will
remember my carbuncles until their dying day,'' Marx said as he
rushed to put the finishing touches on ``Das Kapital.'' ``What
swine they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheen's otherwise excellent work is marred by a weak section
defending ``Das Kapital.'' Dismissing Marx's critics as either
having never read the tome or else having misunderstood it, Wheen
claims Marx's predictions about capitalism's implosion have been
largely borne out by time. That would come as a surprise to most of
the world, where American-style capitalism is not only alive but
dominant. And where exactly have communist societies thrived?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, this section takes up only a dozen or so pages of a
fine book that provides a fresh perspective on one of history's
towering figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-28 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE TINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeing Tina Turner changes your life. My wife and I saw the
60-year-old soul rocker this month at the Fleet Center. Since then,
I cannot stand it when young people say they are tired.
</P>
<P>
   We had an 18-year-old stay with us recently for a week. He is a
typical teenager. He stays up late, he gets up late and then when
you stop by the house for an errand in the middle of the afternoon
and say ``How's it going?'' he says, ``I'm tired.''
</P>
<P>
   This reminds me of some of my college students. I really do not
want to sound like a 44-year-old crank, yapping about falling
standards (one standard has not fallen: Forty-four is still old to
young adults), but it seems as if all it takes to turn them into
Rip Van Winkle is a mere half-hour of research in the library. My
students have no idea how much entertainment they provide me on
Mondays when they come into class bedraggled, almost limping from
the titanic struggle of balancing studies with parties.
</P>
<P>
   My own kids crack me up, too. If you choose to believe this,
because this is entirely too convenient to believe, I have started
this column in an auto repair shop. My 9-year-old son is sitting
next to me. He was reading a book. About two minutes ago, he put
the book down and dropped his head down long enough for me to ask
him, ``Everything all right?''
</P>
<P>
   He stretched and responded with one word: ``Tired.'' Funny, I
thought I was the one who had just driven nearly three hours.
</P>
<P>
   This has been enough to drive me to the phone to get more Tina
Turner tickets when she returns to Boston in September. This time,
we are taking the boys.
</P>
<P>
   Since my 14-year-old happens to like Tina Turner and my
9-year-old has started playing the saxophone, no arm twisting will
be needed. But Mom and Dad do have ulterior motives. We want them
to see a liberated woman in a inspiring display of energy and
optimism. We want them to see so much energy that when they come
home, the word ``tired'' will be retired.
</P>
<P>
   Turner has said, ``I don't feel 60.'' She has said, ``My entire
life has been like one long aerobics class.'' She has said, ``My
figure comes from my work, from all those years of dancing. My
lifestyle has been my exercise, all that sweating onstage and the
singing and the yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Cher once said of Turner, ``Sometimes when I'm tired or feeling
like `Oh God, I just can't make it,' I think, I bet Tina could do
this. She's like a hurricane.'' Just to get in shape to even play
Turner in the movie version of Turner's autobiography, Angela
Bassett said, ``I had a dialect coach, a singing coach, a
choreographer and a personal trainer for 30 days before the filming
began. I lifted weights and went on a high-protein, no sweets diet
_ egg whites, tuna without mayo, vegetables _ to get Tina's
incredible muscular physique.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew! As there will never be another hurricane like Tina Turner,
I am declaring her farewell tour a national treasure for parents.
Remember, children hate to be shown up by old farts. When they are
trailing the rear on hikes up mountains, you can almost see the
afterburners blaze from the soles of their feet if you drop back,
poke them in the side and say, ``You mean you're going to let your
old man beat you up to the top?''
</P>
<P>
   So I figure Tina Turner can assist us all in achieving greatness
as parents, or at least the great, rare act of rendering your
children speechless. The bargain is simple. OK kids, we'll take you
out to see Tina sing ``What's Love Got to Do With It.'' After that,
the new song of the house is:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You must understand, how the sleight of your hand,
</P>
<P>
   Makes my pulse react,
</P>
<P>
   You say you can't see, that dirt at your knee,
</P>
<P>
   You got cataracts?
</P>
<P>
   It's miserable, and intolerable
</P>
<P>
   And now you tell me you need even more sleep
</P>
<P>
   Oh, oh, oh, what's ``tired'' got to do, got to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   What's ``tired,'' but a second-hand emotion?
</P>
<P>
   What's ``tired'' got do do, got to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a nap, when Tina's still smokin'?
</P>
<P>
   It may seem to you, that I'm acting confused,
</P>
<P>
   You have not made a dent.
</P>
<P>
   If I tend to look dazed, it's cause I'm amazed,
</P>
<P>
   At your entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   There's a name for it, call it laziness,
</P>
<P>
   Get up off your seat, cause life is not free.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, oh, oh, what's ``tired'' got to do, got to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   What's ``tired,'' but a second-hand emotion?
</P>
<P>
   What's ``tired'' got do do, got to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a nap, when Tina's still smokin'?
</P>
<P>
