<HEADER>
A7218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PATRIOT-BOS &LR;      06-28 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PATRIOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIBSON SHOWS A BRAVE HEART IN `THE PATRIOT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE PATRIOT 
Directed by: Roland Emmerich 
Screenplay by: Robert Rodat 
Starring: Mel Gibson, Heath Ledger, Joely Richardson, Jason Isaacs,
Chris Cooper, Tcheky Karyo, Rene Auberjonois, Lisa Brenner, Tom
Wilkinson 
Running time: 158 minutes 
Rated: R (strong war violence) 
Stars: 3 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be easy to be cynical about ``The Patriot.'' It is,
after all, history according to Hollywood. Charlton Heston led the
Jews to the Promised Land. Mel Gibson wins the American Revolution.
It's hard to resist dismissing ``The Patriot'' as ``Braveheart'' in
a three-cornered hat. But just as ``Braveheart'' was overrated,
``The Patriot'' is likely to be underrated. To my surprise, it won
me over despite its excesses. It's possible to forgive ``The
Patriot'' its Hollywood heroics _ right down to Gibson charging up
over a hill just before what we are told is the decisive battle,
bearing the Stars and Stripes from the saddlebag of a dead soldier,
just in time to rally his ragtag troops.
</P>
<P>
   If the battlefield gestures are pure Hollywood, they at least
have the courage to throw in our faces the butchery of war. This
perhaps is not a surprise, since the script was written by ``Saving
Private Ryan'' screenwriter Robert Rodat. But I wish the film
hadn't reduced the Revolution to a mutual vendetta, as it does,
between Gibson's Benjamin Martin and Jason Isaacs' sadistic British
colonel, responsible for the death of someone close to Martin. It
was a good choice on Gibson's part to mostly turn his face into a
mask of anguish. Although he gets down and dirty as any action hero
in any film this year, he goes the same route as ``Gladiator'' did
a few weeks ago in that he's a farmer who's a reluctant warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson plays Martin as a man conscience-stricken by his own
savagery when he fought in the French and Indian war, afraid of
reaping a harvest of bad karma. There's something dark and reined
in about Gibson's Martin. He's afraid of his own capacity for
violence. When he does go to war, and his weapon of choice turns
out to be the tomahawk, we're not surprised by his proficiency with
it _ or by the frequency with which he's drenched in his enemies'
blood. What is surprising is the film's way of making the carnage
intimate. Resourcefully utilizing its South Carolina locations, it
persuasively conveys the war's impact on a specific community.
</P>
<P>
   While his eldest teenaged son (Heath Ledger) can't wait to fight
the British, Gibson's veteran of the French and Indian War knows
his son's idealism will be eroded pretty quickly by the grim
realities of war. He doesn't want his son to go. One reason the
film is so long (more than 2 1/2 hours), and takes as long to
achieve liftoff as it does, is the time it takes establishing
Martin's reluctance. But once his son plunges into the war, he
follows. By that time, the war has literally spilled onto the front
lawn of his South Carolina plantation.
</P>
<P>
   The colonial rebels are being shredded by the better-equipped,
better-trained British army. Gibson's character is modeled on,
among others, Francis Marion, known as ``The Swamp Fox.'' The
real-life Marion, who kept slaves (he reportedly raped more than
one of them) and hunted Indians for sport, wouldn't have been a
presentable 21st century movie hero. But he also was a pioneer of
guerrilla warfare. Realizing that it would be suicide to try to
defeat the redcoats at their game of disciplined formations firing
away in open fields, Marion employed surprise attacks, then quickly
withdrew into the swamps.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's patriot (his lifestyle has been sanitized _ the workers
on his plantation are freed slaves who at one point return the
flavor and hide him) retains this tactic. Eventually, he diverts
enough of General Cornwallis' troops to put a dent in the British
ability to fight the war in Virginia. Tom Wilkinson is an amusing
Cornwallis, an aristocrat annoyed that Martin won't fight by the
rules. He isn't a fool. He admonishes his cruel subordinate,
pointing out that the British will want to trade with the Americans
after the war and that it's bad business to antagonize the future
customers any more than necessary. The film also makes clear the
British officers' motivation _ they've been promised large land
grants by King George III. Cornwallis makes only one error, the
classic error of generals, who go into each new war with everything
they needed to win the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   The sterling Chris Cooper is another plus as the Revolutionary
general under no illusions about the difficulties the Americans are
facing. There's a lift, too, from the believably contagious
idealism we're persuaded is animating Ledger's young hothead and
Lisa Brenner, as the spirited young woman he loves. You can feel
the film yielding to market pressures and throwing credibility to
the winds as Gibson launches one of his Mad Mel numbers in the big
showdown we're told is the war's pivotal battle. But there are
trenchant and even moving aspects of ``The Patriot,'' not the least
of which is the unflinching clarity with which it reminds us of
war's horrific costs. It's often corny, but it's never boring, and
it'll sweep you up in its momentum if you give it a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
