<HEADER>
A7219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SEX-GROUP-HNS &LR;      06-28 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-GROUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEX EDUCATION GROUP FACES LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Partners in the Welcomed Consensus describe
themselves as one man and several women living together in sexual
harmony, offering classes that teach everything from seduction
methods to a one-hour orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this culture there are very few places where people can go
to be trained to expand their orgasm,'' the group explains on its
Web site (www.welcomed.com). ``We are that kind of place.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erwan Davon has other names for the group and its ``training
programs,'' which have been going on for years in San Francisco and
other nearby cities: Pimping. Prostitution. Pandering.
</P>
<P>
   Davon, who said he gave the Welcomed Consensus more than
$136,000 in cash and stock options, sued the group in San Francisco
this month, asking for his money back plus a court order that would
force the group out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The Welcomed Consensus instructors acknowledge open sexual
relations with each other as part of their ``research.'' Davon
contends that they also illegally engage in sex acts with their
clients during sessions, some of which cost thousands of dollars
and involve living with the instructors.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Welcomed Consensus denied that the group had
sex with its students.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' attorney Mark Divelbiss said, declining to
comment further on the nature of the classes.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the court battle, Davon's lawsuit and
the group's Web site offer an often explicitly detailed look into
what has to be one of the most unusual educational opportunities in
the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Courses are described as labs, with tuition and programs for
graduate students. Most upper-level courses have prerequisites,
although there are no course credits or degrees at the Welcomed
Consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent heart of the Welcomed Consensus is ``R.J.,'' the
only man in the group. He is identified as Robert Testerman in the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Five women listed as general partners also were sued, although
only three of the women are listed on the Web site's biographies
page.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says they all live in Shasta County. The group's Web
site says they started having sex in San Francisco but now reside
at their ranch, called Eagle's Nest, in Shasta County. They still
receive their mail at a San Francisco post office box and host many
of their sessions in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls and an e-mail to members of the Welcomed Consensus
were not returned. The group's lawyer said he did not plan to fight
the legal battle in the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit, at least in our perspective, is unfounded,''
Divelbiss said. ``It doesn't have any legal or factual support.''
</P>
<P>
   Divelbiss said Davon was a former student who might have had
some interest in investing with the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes it's just an attempt to use a public forum to
obtain a settlement,'' Divelbiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit does not say what Davon spent the money on, or if he
ever was a student with the group.
</P>
<P>
   Davon's lawyer did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. and the current instructors acknowledge in their Web site
biographies that he has sex with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are my best friends, my salvation, my reason for
being,'' R.J. says in his biography. ``One thing I know for sure is
women want action, and three of them want a lot of it, and living
with all these people and teaching courses on sex and relationships
supplies a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's Web site also acknowledges the sexual nature of the
courses that are offered, including more than one that allows
students to live with the group.
</P>
<P>
   For $450 tuition, a student can take ``Adventures in
Sensuality,'' described as an ``advanced sensuality laboratory''
designed for partners.
</P>
<P>
   For $19,000, a student can take the two-week, full-time
``Confirmation Intensive Course.''
</P>
<P>
   The group also offers ``Private Hours,'' at $200 per hour,
giving the buyer a one-on-one ``conversation with a member or
members of Welcomed Consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive course, called the ``Validation Program,''
costs $310,000, although no specifics are listed for the class on
the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Davon's lawsuit accuses the group of violating California laws
that prohibit prostitution, pimping, pandering and keeping a house
of ill fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
