<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7222 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-RETINA-DISEASE-HNS &LR;      06-28 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETINA-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TREATMENT RAISES HOPE FOR SENIORS WITH RETINAL DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Of all the losses associated with aging, Florence
Kaplan most fears losing her sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blindness is a terrifying, terrifying thought,'' said the
80-year-old resident of Amsterdam, N.Y. But Kaplan came close to
losing the vision in her right eye earlier this year when she was
diagnosed with macular degeneration, a disease that affects the
light-sensitive cells that line the back of the eye, known as the
retina.
</P>
<P>
   The condition affects up to 30 million people worldwide and is
the leading cause of blindness in the United States in adults older
than 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was horrified and shocked,'' Kaplan said after learning her
diagnosis in April. To add to her worries, Kaplan was diagnosed
with ``wet'' macular degeneration, a less common form of the
disease affecting some 200,000 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one knows what causes macular degeneration, the wet
form tends to deteriorate the vision more rapidly than the dry. In
both cases, ophthalmologists have been unable to offer their
patients much hope. ``We don't have a cure for either form of
macular degeneration,'' said Dr. Charles D. Mayron of the Retina
Office in Slingerlands, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians and senior citizens across the country have been
keeping abreast of Visudyne therapy, the newest treatment for wet
macular degeneration, approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration in April. ``This is the first pharmacological
treatment that has proven efficacious,'' said Mayron, who has
treated approximately two dozen patients so far.
</P>
<P>
   In clinical studies of 243 patients with wet macular
degeneration, vision improved or remained stable in 67 percent of
patients treated with Visudyne, compared to 39 patients on a
placebo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a high level of desperation,'' said Edmund J.
Aleksandrovich, president of the Macular Degeneration Foundation in
San Jose, Calif. ``People say, `if there is any chance of getting
my sight back, I want to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Visudyne, manufactured by CIBA Vision, is not a cure.
Scientists believe any such breakthrough is years away. ``It's
somewhat of a milestone, but nowhere like we have a solution,''
Mayron said.
</P>
<P>
   Wet macular degeneration is caused by the abnormal proliferation
of blood vessels beneath the retina. The growth of those blood
vessels eventually damages the retina, which is that part of the
eye that enables us to read and see fine detail.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say women tend to get the disease more often, perhaps
because they live longer. And people with lighter eyes tend to have
a slightly greater risk of developing the condition, according to
Don Anderson, director of the Center for the Study of Macular
Degeneration at the University of California in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   He expects research over the next five years to reveal a
significant genetic link to the disease, which is already known to
run in families. In the past, the only weapon against wet macular
degeneration was laser therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But using a hot laser on the surface of the eye carried its own
risk. ``In the process of burning the blood vessels, we were
destroying the retina,'' Mayron said. ``The treatment was almost as
worse as the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Visudyne also uses a laser, but a cold one. The treatment is
two-step. First, a physician injects the drug into the bloodstream,
which then binds to the abnormal blood vessels in the eye. Once
activated by the laser, the drug shrinks the blood vessels. But
while Visudyne has helped some patients, it seems to be a temporary
fix. The therapy, in most people, has to be repeated every three
months.
</P>
<P>
   And that can be expensive. A single treatment of Visudyne can
cost as much as $1,500. Medicare, in most cases, is expected to
pick up the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan believes the treatment is worth it. ``My sight is nowhere
near normal but it's much better than it had been,'' she said.
``It's like a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
