<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PT BOAT CAUGHT IN NEW BATTLE OVER ITS FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEMAH, Texas _ After toiling six years to restore a rare World
War II combat boat, a group of volunteers is not ready to surrender
PT-309 so it can be displayed outside the Nimitz Museum in
Fredericksburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a travesty to take a perfectly good, seaworthy boat and
stick her in a hole in the ground,'' said Tim Kelley, skipper of
the 78-foot boat now docked at Clear Lake, southeast of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they take her up there, she will rot and decay,'' Kelley
said.
</P>
<P>
   But concern about dry rot was dismissed as a red herring by
Charles Grojean of the Admiral Nimitz Foundation, which spent
$80,000 in 1994 to buy the boat, which was being used for charter
fishing trips.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which gave the boat to the Texas Department of
Parks and Wildlife, planned for it to become part of its Pacific
Combat Zone display this November.
</P>
<P>
   With time and money invested by both groups, emotions are
heating up over the future of the only remaining torpedo boat known
to have seen combat in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that a bona fide artifact like that ought to be
preserved for future generations,'' Grojean said Tuesday. ``Running
it around in water like that is not preserving it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kelley's group has launched a publicity campaign to convince
state officials to display the boat in Kemah, a town on Galveston
Bay south of Clear Lake.
</P>
<P>
   More than $750,000 has gone into restoring the boat. The
volunteers say they were told they could have some time to display
the restored boat there, and the city of Kemah has passed a
resolution pledging to spend $55,000 to build a dock and visitor
center for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Parks and Wildlife and the museum have taken advantage
of the entire system down here,'' said Mike Frye, an assistant to
Kemah City Councilman Bill King.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volunteers put it back together and got it back in the
water,'' he said. ``Now, it appears that based on the taxpayers
doing all of this work, they've decided that our timetable has been
pushed up so we really can't allow it to be put on display for any
period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   State and foundation officials said they were open to a 1998
request from the city of Kemah to display the boat there two years,
but the time has come to move it.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to keep it in Kemah is supported by former wartime
crewmen of the boat that was named ``Oh Frankie'' after a chance
meeting between its first skipper and singer Frank Sinatra in a New
York nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the boat should remain a viable living example of a
naval vessel, and should remain in the water,'' said Bob Pleasants,
who was second in command on the boat during combat tours in the
Mediterranean Sea more than a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though PT boats gained fame in the Pacific theater of World War
II, PT-309 was used to attack German vessels in the Mediterranean.
Its crew sank five enemy vessels in 75 missions.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1944, the 50-ton vessel featured a double-planked
mahogany hull, and was among about 300 motor patrol torpedo boats
built for the Navy by the Higgins Co. in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the war, PT-309 sold as war surplus for $3,500.
When bought by the foundation, it was a fishing boat called ``Brand
X.''
</P>
<P>
   A bid to keep the boat in Kemah was rejected in May by Parks and
Wildlife Executive Director Andy Sansom, who nevertheless applauded
the volunteers' work.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said he offered to reimburse the Nimitz Foundation for
its outlay on the restoration project, or to restore the exterior
of another old torpedo boat, PT-305, for display in Fredericksburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're open-minded to some extent,'' Kelley said. ``They want
to see our plans for it. They are not saying yes. They opened the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposals outlining the options will be presented to state
officials by July 17, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
