<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN MAY BE WINNING BATTLE TO PRAY AT THE WAILING WALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bonna D. Haberman has a simple dream: One day she wants to be
able to pray at the Western Wall in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch. She wants to wear a prayer shawl and read
from the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   That behavior doesn't raise an eyebrow in Haberman's adopted
hometown of Cambridge, Mass., where as a Jew who is at the same
time radical and orthodox, egalitarian and traditional, she is
welcome in many circles.
</P>
<P>
   But in Jerusalem, where public officials have ceded control of
behavior at the wall to the ultra-Orthodox, Haberman's wearing of
religious clothing and her reading from religious texts
traditionally reserved for men has triggered a violent reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 12 years, Orthodox men have threatened, cursed,
and attacked women praying in groups in the women's section of the
Wall. On occasion, men have hurled excrement or furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Now Haberman, a scholar in the women's studies program at
Brandeis University, thinks her 12-year struggle may be nearing
success in the effort to win equal access for women to one of the
most important sites in Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Supreme Court ruled last month that women should be
allowed to have group services, to wear prayer shawls, and to read
from the Torah at the wall, and the court gave the government six
months to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are furious, and Israel's parliament is considering
legislation that would overturn the Supreme Court decision and
allow jail sentences of up to seven years for women who read from
the Torah at the Western Wall. The wall, also known as the Wailing
Wall, is the last remaining piece of the Second Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Haberman, a 40-year-old mother of five who helped found a group
called Women of the Wall in 1989, heads to Jerusalem this week, and
she hopes to celebrate the Supreme Court victory at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the area considered to be, for the Jewish people, one
of the most significant and sacred places,'' she said. ``For women
to be present in the sacred space is a fundamental part of the
fixing of the undignified part of human relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   But Haberman is under no illusion that it will be easy to
translate the Supreme Court decision into public policy. Israel's
government could collapse, the parliament could overturn the
decision, or the police could fail to protect women who pray.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-Orthodox Jews argue that women praying from the Torah
violate the roles assigned to men and women by God.
</P>
<P>
   Haberman spent about five years living in Israel and during that
time prayed at the wall every Friday. On the occasions when her
group had a Torah, Orthodox women would try to tear it away or men
would attack verbally or physically, at times calling the praying
women whores, witches, or Nazis and even praying for their death.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be assaulted at any time is an awful violation, but, in the
middle of prayer, there's a special vulnerability,'' she said.
``Our opponents have been brutal, violent, and have broken so many
of the codes of civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade of hearings by various government commissions
attempting to work out a compromise solution were disastrous,
Haberman said. ``They were extraordinarily degrading and
humiliating events.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she recoils at the proposal that women be jailed for
praying, even though the measure is not expected to pass.
Preliminary approval of the measure by the Knesset caused the
American Jewish Congress to compare Israel to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an appalling situation,'' Haberman said. ``It's
intolerable. To name that prayer by women as a criminal offense is
difficult to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Haberman said she and other women of varying denominations and
nationalities have tried to be patient as they push for change, but
that their patience is running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter had her bat mitzvah, and she wasn't able to do it
at the Wall, whereas every Jewish boy can do it at his will,''
Haberman said. ``It's time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
