<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BAPTISTS-WOMEN-ART-BO     06-28 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-WOMEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PREACHER PERSISTS DESPITE OPPOSITION BY DENOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tina T. Saxon was just 18 when she announced to her
family that she wanted to be a Baptist preacher.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was swift, she recalls: the fist of her uncle, a
leading deacon at the local church, came slamming down against the
dining room table. ``You show me in the Bible where God told a
woman to preach!'' she remembers him shouting.
</P>
<P>
   It took Saxon decades to answer that question to her own
satisfaction. Today, at age 61, she is the pastor of a small church
she founded six years ago in a rundown and abandoned building in a
public housing development.
</P>
<P>
   But now she finds herself once again defending her right to be a
preacher.
</P>
<P>
   On June 14, the Southern Baptist Convention, the nation's
largest Protestant denomination, voted to declare that women should
not be pastors.
</P>
<P>
   That poses at least a symbolic problem for Saxon. Though she
grew up in a black Baptist church and was ordained as an American
Baptist minister, she chose years ago to affiliate her church with
the Southern Baptist Convention after she was recruited by a
retired black male pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Saxon is the only woman pastor of a Southern Baptist church in
Massachusetts, and she views her denomination's action with a
combination of indifference and anger. At times she says she
doesn't have time or energy to worry about votes like this; at
other times, she is irate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't back off because a bunch of powerful white whatevers
feel I should not be trying to make this a better world, also,''
she said. ``This really is about economics and sexism _ it's about
power _ and they have to come up with God talk to explain it out of
ignorance or sexism or greed.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote does not mean that Saxon or the estimated 35 to 100
other women heading Southern Baptist churches will lose their
posts. The Southern Baptist Convention is decentralized, so the
vote is not binding on individual churches, and the denomination is
also facing a possible schism over its rightward tilt.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also does not mean that Saxon will leave the Southern
Baptist Convention; Saxon said that even today she would encourage
a young woman who felt a call to the ministry to consider a
Southern Baptist church.
</P>
<P>
   Saxon said the denomination's historic opposition to civil
rights for blacks and its current opposition to equality for women
are outweighed by the support she has enjoyed from the New England
leadership of the Southern Baptist Convention, from her fellow
pastors, and even from college-age Southern Baptists from Kentucky
and Texas who have traveled to Boston to help repair her church.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have proved to be very sincere and loving people when it
comes to the work of the kingdom, and that's what it's all about,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention, which reports nearly 16 million
members in 40,000 churches, is theologically conservative and
evangelical. Founded in a break over the issue of slavery with
predominantly Northern churches now represented by the American
Baptist Churches, the Southern Baptist Convention has now
repudiated that position and formally denounced racism in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, where an estimated 15,000 Southern Baptists
represent a tiny percentage of the region's Christians, most
Baptist churches are affiliated with one of several black Baptist
bodies or with the American Baptist Churches. American Baptists
have been ordaining women since 1890, and a majority of the
ministers now being ordained by the denomination in Massachusetts
are female.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 220 Southern Baptist pastors in New England, some
support the denomination's rightward tilt, while others do not.
But, like other evangelical churches in New England, the Southern
Baptists here tend to be far less engaged in denominational
politics than their counterparts in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the South, those people are arguing about the icing on the
cake, but up here we're trying to deal with whether or not there's
going to be a cake,'' said the Rev. Mark D. Acuff, senior pastor of
Grace Baptist Church in Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Acuff said his church would not ordain a woman pastor. But he
wishes the denomination had not codified such a position, and he
said he recoiled when the denomination tried to organize a boycott
of the Walt Disney Co. over the company's support for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my pulpit, `Follow Jesus' and `Ban Mickey' do not fit in
the same paragraph,'' Acuff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nicolas S. Zaccardi, pastor of First Baptist Church in
Watertown, said he has no problem with the leadership of women. He
grew up in Pentecostal churches, which are generally more
hospitable to women pastors. But Zaccardi also said he pays no
attention to denominational politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know about the decision,'' Zaccardi said. ``Down
South, it's a whole different climate, where it's much more
Christianized, and they can sit back and talk about things like
that. Up in New England, we're more like missionaries, and we're
just trying to have a growing congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in a region where evangelicals avoid political battles
to focus on evangelization, Saxon's position is filled with irony.
</P>
<P>
   She is a black woman who heads a church in a denomination that
was created to support slavery and that just two years ago declared
that women should ``submit graciously to their husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Saxon also has much more pressing problems to worry
about. The future of her church is in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   She is essentially a squatter. Her congregation holds services
on the first three floors of an abandoned nine-story building at
the Bromley-Heath housing project. Saxon has no lease on the
property, so last year the Boston Housing Authority decided to
evict her, contending that running a church in an abandoned
apartment building violates the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Saxon said the BHA has since promised to let her stay, but she
has nothing in writing. BHA spokeswoman Lydia Agro said only that
``we're trying to work out a solution.'' But pending a definite
decision, Saxon continues to conduct church services, offer an AIDS
ministry, and plan for Bible camp and school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Her makeshift church is marked with a spray-painted white cross
over the door. As she entered the makeshift church one recent day,
she paused to rue the beer bottle and the Devil Creme snack cake
wrapper amid the carefully tended flowers behind a chain-link
fence. Once inside, she ignored the peeling paint and
malfunctioning plumbing, heating, and wiring and focused instead on
the pews her congregants made and the faux stained-glass windows
she created, using decals on frosted glass.
</P>
<P>
   Without a hint of irony, she stepped onto the cracked pavement
of a courtyard once overrun with drug dealers, looked past the
giant brick planters filled with dry dirt and the dandelions
springing up through the asphalt, and said, ``Isn't this beautiful?
Imagine kids and balloons and ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in black Baptist churches in Tampa, Fla., and Washington,
D.C., Saxon became an increasingly fervent believer. At 17, she was
jokingly called an evangelist, and at 18 she claimed a miraculous
healing; one morning she woke up and, she says, the stub of a sixth
finger on her hand since birth had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Saxon has worked or worshiped in a variety of Christian
churches: American Baptist, black Baptist, Nazarene, United Church
of Christ, Unitarian Universalist, even Swedenborgian societies and
Christian Science. And she has moved between predominantly black
and white worlds.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, she left a black Baptist church over its
indifference to drug abuse and pursued political activism through
the League of Women Voters before running unsuccessfully as a
Republican candidate for school board. In Massachusetts she worked
in a number of affluent white suburban churches before deciding to
found Disciples Baptist Church in an effort to minister to a
low-income black population plagued by drugs and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Saxon remembers even at age 6 noticing the inequality faced by
women in church life. Her grandmother would iron and starch the
altar cloth and bake the unleavened bread for communion, but then
had to step aside to let the men perform the ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she has little patience for the argument that the New
Testament prohibits women pastors. She says the apostle Paul, an
opponent of women pastors, ``was a product of his culture, of his
kind, of his tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are all in Christ, we can all do whatever the heck we
want to do with our gifts and our talents,'' she said. ``I follow
Jesus Christ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
