<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-BASEBALL-WINERY-HNS &LR;      06-28 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-WINERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK WINERY THROWS A SOFT PITCH TO BASEBALL FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Cooperstown, one of upstate New York's
hottest tourist draws thanks to the Baseball Hall of Fame, has a
new attraction: Bear Pond Winery.
</P>
<P>
   Located a dozen miles south of Cooperstown in the hamlet of
Milford Center, Bear Pond is attempting to make the most of its
connection to the national pastime. The wines include All Star
Chardonnay, Grand Slam Champagne and Fielder's Choice Rosario.
</P>
<P>
   Owned and operated by Hank and Joan Nicols, who for a number of
years have grown grapes on their property in Cooperstown, which
includes a small lake named Bear Pond, the winery has formed an
unofficial partnership with Brotherhood Winery in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   While Bear Pond waits for the grapes the Nicols planted earlier
this year on their five-acre winery to mature, many of its wines
are being bottled at Brotherhood using that winery's grapes. The
Nicols are also buying grape juice from various Finger Lakes
wineries, allowing them to age a burgundy and chardonnay in oak
barrels at the Bear Pond winery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first wines we made on site to sell sold out almost
immediately,'' said Hank Nicols, whose full-time job is director of
system support at Bassett Hospital in Cooperstown. ``Our production
probably will never be able to keep up with demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Bear Pond wines sell for between $7 (Grizzly Red Burgundy) and
$12 (Castle Cabernet Sauvignon). There are 15 varieties available,
including an alcohol-free grape juice called Goldilocks' Favorite
($4). The labels have a distinctive bear paw print, the signature
sign at the winery.
</P>
<P>
   The winery opened Memorial Day weekend and held its grand
opening June 17-18. It is so new that James Tresize, president of
the New York State Wine &AMP; Grape Foundation, had not heard of Bear
Pond when he was reached at his office in the Finger Lakes. There
were 140 wineries operating in New York as of Jan. 1, according to
Tresize.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For more information, call 607-643-0294 or visit the winery's
Web site: www.bearpondwines.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
