<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT'S A BERRY NICE SEASON FOR SUCCULENT FRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GRIFFIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Before the world shrank, allowing fresh fruits and
vegetables from once-distant continents to fill grocery shelves
year-round, anticipation grew as the seasonal arrival of old
favorites approached.
</P>
<P>
   April brought the first asparagus, crisp and green as an apple.
Late May or early June meant vine-ripened tomatoes, blood-red and
bursting with flavor. Pumpkins, of course, seemed to grow on
schedule in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Now we take it for granted that we can get these and all other
foods whenever we want, courtesy of overnight shipping and
greenhouses in places like Chile and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow berries have survived produce's endless summer.
Sure, you can find strawberries in mid-December, but we all know
they are going to be hard, white and a pale imitation of what comes
fresh and locally.
</P>
<P>
   Raspberries picked in spring are a deep, almost purple red,
their drupelets _ the individual sections, each containing its own
seed _ filled with an irresistible sweet-tart nature that sends
paroxysms of pleasure across your taste buds. I can remember as a
child fighting off the birds to gather a few handfuls from the
bushes in our back yard. No matter how successful I was, there were
never enough of those amazing morsels. Certainly there were never
enough to share with the rest of my family or even to make it from
the bushes to the house not 25 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   It is too hot in South Texas to grow flavorful raspberries, says
Baxter Adams, owner of Love Creek Orchards. But the region produces
boysenberries, a cross among a raspberry, a blackberry and a
loganberry. And blackberry season has just come to a close at his
Devine farm.
</P>
<P>
   The blackberry season was a bit longer than usual this year,
thanks to the rains and to new varieties, such as the Kiowa, which
will ``produce berries for nearly two months, instead of two
weeks,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also boasts the dewberry, which is smaller, tarter and
wilder than the blackberries found elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This is prime blueberry picking season for Texas, and farms to
the east are harvesting the bushels of blue gold, perfect for pies,
cobblers, muffins and more. Blueberries also have garnered a great
deal of press lately because they have been found to be a major
source of antioxidants that fight cancer, heart disease and other
degenerative conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Berries as a whole have captured our fancy because they are much
more flavorful than other big fruit, says Damien Watel, chef and
owner of Bistro Vatel. So much so, in fact, that Watel uses them in
salads, with foie gras and in desserts, including a blueberry tart
with an almond crust.
</P>
<P>
   Given the short season in which truly fresh berries are
available, it's no surprise that people develop a craving for them,
Watel says. Certainly, their fragile nature and their rarity
combine to make them more expensive than apples or oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Once the berries have been harvested, they are refrigerated
immediately in an attempt to extract a longer shelf life. This also
means that if you can't pick your own, you should buy only those
that are refrigerated at the grocery, unless you plan to use them
immediately, Adams says. Otherwise, refrigerate them at home and
use them within a day or two at the most because mold will likely
form.
</P>
<P>
   Berries shouldn't be washed until immediately before using as
the water can damage the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   If fresh berries in season are not available, opt for frozen.
Just remember to drain the juice before measuring.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, freeze your own. ``As long as the fruit is freshly
picked and tightly wrapped to prevent freezer burn, it defrosts
with much of its original sparkle intact,'' according to
``Gardener's Community Cookbook'' (Workman Publishing, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Griffin by e-mail at jgriffin &LR; express-news.net)
</P>
