<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ABORTION (Washington) _ A divided Supreme Court strikes
down a Nebraska law banning ``partial-birth'' abortions, ruling
that the statute imposes an ``undue burden'' on a woman's right to
end her pregnancy. The 5-4 decision _ the court's most important
ruling on abortion in eight years _ is rekindling debate on the
landmark Roe v. Wade ruling of 1973 that legalized the procedure.
In another abortion-related decision, the court gives states
greater leeway to restrict anti-abortion protests outside health
clinics. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SCOUTS (Washington) _ The Boy Scouts of America may bar
homosexuals from becoming troop leaders, the Supreme Court says. In
a 5-4 decision the court rules that the Scouts are a private
organization and thus have a right to exclude people that don't
share their values. Forcing the Scouts to accept openly gay troop
leaders would violate the group's First Amendment right to free
association, the court holds. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-COURT (Blacklick, Ohio) _ Vice President Al Gore lambastes
Supreme Court Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia for their
dissents in two abortion rights cases. Gore says those justices
would be the ``model'' for the kind of judges Texas Gov. George W.
Bush would name to the court if he were elected president. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-JEWS (Havana) _ According to the Bible, it took Moses 40
years to lead the ancient Hebrews out of the desert and into the
promised land _ about the same amount of time it has taken Cuba's
small Jewish community to get back on its feet under Communist
rule. Depleted by departures since Fidel Castro seized power in
1959, Cuba's Jewish community of 1,500 is rebuilding itself. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ For Al Gore, this is the best of
times and the worst of times. The best because two months from now
he will be anointed as the Democratic Party's first presidential
nominee of the new millennium. The worst because Gore has been
steadily sinking behind Bush in the public opinion polls. By ROBERT
E. THOMPSON.
</P>
