   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHESAPEAKE-COMPACT (Rose Haven, Md.) _ Three states sign a new
compact to repair the tattered ecology of the Chesapeake Bay, the
vast resource of 64,000 square miles and a watershed population of
15 million that has slowly been on the mend. It has been 18 years
since the first compact, now considered a model for
intergovernmental cooperation, and the new pact sets such ambitious
standards as a 10-fold increase in oysters, the restoration of blue
crabs and a 30 percent cut in suburban sprawl development that is
the latest threat undermining the bay. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACE SERIES &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   This story, for Thursday papers, was filed Tuesday evening:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PAPER (Akron, Ohio) _ In New York in 1994, Carl Chancellor
and Bob Dyer looked like tourists, snapping pictures at the Statue
of Liberty, savoring Jamaican food at a trendy restaurant, clinking
beer bottles and wineglasses in heady toasts back at their hotel.
More than tourists, they were colleagues out on the town
celebrating. Chancellor and Dyer were part of a team of reporters
for The Akron Beacon Journal that had explored the racial attitudes
of this city of 215,000 people. Their series earned the paper
journalism's big award, the Pulitzer Prize. In Akron, there were
congratulatory speeches for a staff that had united behind the
series and gloried in having been a healing force in the city. The
Beacon Journal also tried to lead by example. Shortly after the
series ended, it introduced a lineup of columnists reflecting ``the
perfect demographic,'' as Dyer put it. They included a black woman
and a white woman as well as Chancellor, who is black, and Dyer,
who is white. The paper, it seemed, had become a proud model of
racial enlightenment. Which made it all the more startling when,
just a year later, the jubilation began to fade _ for the men and
the newsroom. Troubled by the state of race relations, The Beacon
Journal had gone further than most newspapers to investigate the
gap between blacks and whites and to understand why it had not
closed. It found mistrust and misperceptions, frustrations and
tensions; it even looked inward, discovering much the same in its
own newsroom. It had found, it seemed, a way to talk about race.
And yet even here, in a place where men and women make a living
seeking answers to questions and using words well, communication
can break down. And race still seeps back in. Many among the 157
people on the news staff _ 15 percent of whom are black and 4
percent other minorities _ say that although the city's racial
climate may have improved because of the series, seven years later,
the newspaper itself has shown less progress. By Dana Canedy. (6240
words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT110-116 have been sent to NYT photo clients. For a
special price, nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST (Jerusalem) _ Prospects for a Mideast summit
meeting in early July faded Wednesday as Palestinian and Israeli
leaders advised Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that they
were too far apart on the key issues. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-KILLING (United Nations) _ A gunman demanding an end to
sanctions on Iraq forced his way into the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization building in Baghdad Wednesday and opened fire, killing
a Somali and an Iraqi worker and wounding two Iraqi citizens,
according to the U.N. agency. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ARRESTS (Tehran) _ With the first anniversary of the
pro-democracy student riots at Tehran University approaching,
Iranian authorities took several contradictory actions Wednesday
that could both provoke and placate the reformers who have been
under severe attack over the past three months by hardline clergy.
By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ On political and economic
developments as the upper house of parliament on Wednesday rejected
President Vladimir Putin's plan to weaken the powers of the 89
regions and the Kremlin presented a broad and vague economic plan.
By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-POLITICS (Kampala) _ Once there were few places in Africa
as grim as Uganda; now there are few as hopeful. And the man who
claims the credit is campaigning hard for voters to reward him on
Thursday in perhaps an odd way: He wants them to admit that Uganda
is still backward and not yet ready to open up to political
parties. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT9,10,11, sent June 27.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-POLITICS (Dateline to come) _ Developments following
the weekend parliamentary elections. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-REDCROSS (Geneva) _ In its annual World Disasters Report,
the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies on Wednesday said that while natural disasters accounted
for some 80,000 deaths last year, that paled into insignificance
compared with the huge loss of life from preventable disease. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Beijing, China) _ Taiwan's new president said the
magic words more clearly than ever before Wednesday, telling
visitors that his government could agree with Beijing that there is
only ``one China.'' But he added a condition that Beijing has said
it cannot accept: that Taipei and Beijing must be able to interpret
those words in different ways. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ As was widely expected, Federal Reserve
policy makers decide to leave interest rates unchanged. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-INVEST (New York) _ For all its success in commercial
banking on a global scale, Chase Manhattan Bank has had an image
problem in the clubby precincts of Wall Street. When Chase agreed
last month to buy the Beacon Group _ an investment banking boutique
started by Geoffrey T. Boisi, a former star at Goldman Sachs _ for
an estimated $450 million, it looked to some like yet another
expensive acquisition in a piecemeal attempt at building an
investment banking presence. But it actually signals a big change
of direction by Chase, which has announced that Jimmy Lee, one of
its most prominent executives, would spend more time with clients
and that Boisi would become his boss. By Laura Holson.
</P>
<P>
   PROVIDIAN-FRAUD (Washington) _ The government announces a $350
million fine against Providian Financial in credit card fraud case.
By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-DETECTIVES (Redwood Shores, Calif.) _ Larry Ellison,
head of Oracle, will hold a news conference in the wake of the
disclosure that his company commissioned an investigation of
Microsoft. Other developments. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow Jones industrial average was up 41
points, or 0.4 percent, at noon, and the Nasdaq index was up 77
points, or 2 percent. The 30-year Treasury bond was down 17/32, to
yield 5.97 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-GENES-FOODS (Sao Paul) _ In a widely awaited decision
that could have a profound impact on the global food industry, a
Brazilian court is to decide today whether to permit farmers to
grow genetically modified soybeans. By Jennifer L. Rich.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVESTORS (Moscow) _ Foreign investors in Unified Energy
Systems, Russia's power monopoly and most widely held stock, are
intensifying their efforts to stop a restructuring proposal that
they fear will destroy the value of their holdings. By Sabrina
Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By Hal
R. Varian.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
<P>
   William Safire is on vacation.
