<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, June 29:
</P>
<P>
   SEA-SHELLS (New York) _ The lowly mollusk should rightly be
credited with creating the world's first beach house in the
brilliant form of the sea shell, those Cambrian-era dwellings that
today are sometimes prized and polished, and sometimes trampled
underfoot. Christopher Gow, importer, creator of objets, and
consummate handyman, would probably live in a sea shell if he could
figure out how. A longtime fan and student of whelks, conchs,
periwinkles, murexes, et al, he is also the founder of Ruzzetti &AMP;
Gow, a Manhattan-based company that gathers shells around the
world, silver-coats them in Rome, and uses them to adorn antique
and contemporary frames, chandeliers and mirrors. He sells sea
shells far from the sea shore. By David Colman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLYNESIAN-REVIVAL (Undated) _ After a decade of bubbling under
pop culture's crust like a subterranean lava pool, tiki is back.
It's all happening now: surfing, the revival of Polynesian and
Hawaiian shirts, lounge music and tropical merchandise that Trader
Vic would have adored. By Frank DeCaro.
</P>
<P>
   WEST-PALM-LIVING (West Palm Beach, Fla.) _ ``The best thing
about this neighborhood is you can step outside to get the paper
and not see anybody you know,'' said Mario Nievera. Which can be a
blessing, he added, ``because we live pretty public lives here.''
Here is Palm Beach, a posh playground for Vanderbilts, Astors and
their ilk since the 1920s, and Nievera is not being boastful about
the high-profile existence shared by him and his partner, Robert
Janjigian. A gregarious, notebook-wielding presence at cocktail
parties and charity events, Janjigian, 42, is the fashion editor of
the Palm Beach Daily News, known as The Shiny Sheet for the paper's
slick finish. The gardens that Nievera, 35, creates for members of
the local fete set show up in Architectural Digest. Yet their
primary residence is comfortably modest. So is its location.
Sixty-seven miles north of Miami, West Palm is Palm Beach's
renegade mainland sister, the grinning tomboy who married the
family chauffeur and settled down to carpool-and-lunchbox bliss. By
Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   MINORITIES-HOME-OWNERS (Undated) _ As the United States roars
through the year 2000 still in the midst of the longest housing
boom on record, there are disturbing signs that minorities remain
on the bottom end of the home-ownership gap, according to a report
issued this week by the Joint Center for Housing Studies of Harvard
University. By Tracie Rozhon. (Will move in `l' category)
</P>
<P>
   HARDY-PLANTS (Undated) One morning in early June, Dr. Peter del
Tredici led the way around the Arnold Arboretum at Harvard to some
of the beautiful old plants he says are tough enough to ride the
roller coaster of recent climate changes. Among them is the Chinese
fringe tree (Chionanthus retusas), with its masses of little white
blossoms covering its broad branches like a silken shawl. The
fragrance was so intoxicating I wanted to open my arms and walk
right into it. The arboretum, founded in 1872 and designed by
Frederick Law Olmsted, rambles for 265 acres over the hills of
Jamaica Plain, Mass. As plant explorers continue to add to the
collection of 7,000 woody plants, it stands as a vast repository of
the temperate world's hardiest specimens. It's Del Tredici's living
laboratory, where he observes, almost daily, which plants survive
the ups and downs of contemporary weather. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
