<SLUG> BC-FOOD-VANITYPLATES-950(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REASONS CHEFS NAME THEIR CREATIONS AFTER THE PEOPLE THEY LOVE _
AND HATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's called kissing up.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the dishes we know as ``classics'' today are the results
of old-time chefs toadying up to their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Take beef Stroganoff, a dish so familiar that there are even
frozen containers of it in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Beef Stroganoff was named for Count Pavel Stroganoff, a bon
vivant of the Gay Nineties. A noted gourmet, as well as a dignitary
at the court of Czar Alexander III and a member of the Imperial
Academy of Arts in St. Petersburg, Stroganoff lives in our hearts
as a combination of sour cream and beef to ladle over noodles.
</P>
<P>
   And the list goes on. Auguste Escoffier, THE celebrity chef at
the turn of the century, came up with peach Melba to honor opera
singer Nellie Melba. Melba toast, the thin toast/cracker familiar
to legions of dieters, was also created by Escoffier for the divine
Miss M.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Tetrazzini was created for another opera singer who
loved her food, the Italian coloratura soprano Luisa Tetrazzini,
although the chef of note has never been noted.
</P>
<P>
   Even ballerinas got their due from the kitchen. Russian
ballerina Anna Pavlova was honored in Australia with the creation
of a dessert made of meringue to resemble a tutu.
</P>
<P>
   These dishes named for women also marked another trend of the
time: It was beginning to be acceptable for proper women to eat in
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Then you've got the dishes awarded to conquering heroes _ a
smart move by chefs with a strong sense of self-preservation.
There's chicken Marengo, served to Napoleon after he won the battle
of the same name. And then there's beef Wellington, named for the
Iron Duke who met Napoleon at Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Shirley Temple, the darling of midcentury cinema.
It was the Brown Derby Restaurant in Hollywood, knowing on which
side its bread was buttered, that came up with that nonalcoholic
tribute to innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Not so innocent was the kiss-up to John D. Rockefeller by the
owner of Antoine's Restaurant in New Orleans. Due to a shortage of
snails at the turn of the century, restaurants turned to the native
oyster as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, though, oysters were rarely consumed heated. Jules
Alciatore concocted oysters baked and served on a bed of greens _
the color of money.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the naming thing causes indigestion for the creator.
The chef at Delmonico's in New York City was brought a recipe in
1876 by sea captain Ben Wenberg. The recipe was a big hit with
diners, and restaurant owner Charles Delmonico honored the captain
by naming the dish lobster a la Wenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Delmonico and the captain had a disagreement, and
Delmonico switched around the letters to make lobster a la Newberg.
Eventually, the spelling changed, but we still have lobster Newburg
with us today.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BEEF STROGANOFF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 pounds beef sirloin, cut into strips 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 green onions, white part only, chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 beef bouillon cube, dissolved in 1 cup hot water
</P>
<P>
   10-ounce can beef consomme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce can mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sauterne wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Remove all fat from the beef. Cut the beef into 2-inch strips
across the grain of the meat. Salt and pepper the strips. Heat the
butter in a Dutch oven and brown the beef, turning frequently to
brown evenly. Set the meat aside and cook the onions until they are
transparent. Set the onions aside. Add the flour to the drippings
and mix well. Return the meat and onions to the Dutch oven, and add
beef bouillon cube, water and beef consomme. Stir the mixture until
it is smooth. Add mustard, cover and cook very slowly for 1 hour or
until the meat is tender. Add the undrained mushrooms, sauterne and
sour cream. Serve over rice or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 582 calories, 39 grams fat, 11
grams carbohydrates, 45 grams protein, 191 milligrams cholesterol,
764 milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.CopyKat.com
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
