<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV19  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: LAMB CARNITAS; POTATO AND TOMATO SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, July 19, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carnitas are little cubes of meat, usually pork, roasted until
they are fairly crisp. Generally the cooking process is quite long
because large chunks of meat are roasted. Here we've speeded up the
process using small pieces of meat. They have been seasoned with
the appropriate spices of Mexico, the home of carnitas, which means
little meats.
</P>
<P>
   While potato salad is probably not an authentic dish, the
seasonings in this version with tomatoes makes it an appropriate
and complementary dish to the spicy carnitas. Cumin and cilantro,
an herb I love, but some love to hate, give the potatoes and
tomatoes the Mexican touch. Toasting the cumin enhances its flavor
and its aroma.
</P>
<P>
   Local tomatoes should be coming to market soon in your
neighborhood, if they are not there already. During their fabulous
short season you ought to give up on what the local supermarket is
offering from far away and stick with the farmers' market near you,
the roadside stand, or if you are lucky and industrious, your own
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   You can never have too many local tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   LAMB CARNITAS
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces boneless leg of lamb
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1/2 serrano chile
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces whole onion or 3 ounces chopped, ready cut
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon hot chile powder
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Trim fat from lamb and cut lamb into 1/2-inch cubes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Crush garlic; wash, trim, seed and finely chop the chile;
chop the onion. Combine the lamb with the oil, garlic, chile,
onion, hot chile powder and pepper to taste. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   4. Spread the ingredients on a baking sheet and roast for 15
minutes, until well browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   TOASTED CUMIN POTATO AND TOMATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Scrub the potatoes but do not peel. If they are large, cut
into 1-inch cubes. If they are very small, do not cut.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cook the potatoes in water to cover until they are tender but
still firm, 10 to 17 minutes, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   3. Toast the cumin seeds in toaster oven.
</P>
<P>
   4. Wash, dry and chop the cilantro; wash, trim and chop green
onions; wash trim and cut the tomatoes in small dice. Combine these
ingredients in serving bowl. Add the toasted cumin seeds.
</P>
<P>
   5. When potatoes are cooked, drain and stir into bowl; season
with salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare potatoes through step 1.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare meat through step 4
</P>
<P>
   Finish potatoes
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Hot chile powder
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   YOUR SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces boneless leg of lamb
</P>
<P>
   Serrano or jalapeno chile
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces whole onion or 3 ounces chopped, ready-cut
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces new potatoes (smallest possible)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch cilantro (1/2 cup packed)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch green onions (2)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 500 calories, 16 grams total
fat, 3.8 grams saturated fat, 80 miligrams cholesterol, 195
milligrams sodium, 60 grams carbohydrate, 8.5 grams fiber, 30 grams
protein.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
