<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7297 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-STUDENTS-ABROAD-ART-B     06-28 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-ABROAD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUOYED BY DOLLAR'S STRENGTH, MORE STUDENTS ARE STUDYING ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a fortunate coincidence that Sara David picked this
summer to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since her freshman year at Brandeis University, she wanted
to study overseas. But the 19-year-old junior was tentative about
the cost. And when she decided earlier this year to study politics
at Boston University's program in London, she knew the price would
be more than a typical semester in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what turned out to be good luck for David has served as a
stimulus for thousands of students signing up to study abroad,
especially in Europe, this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar, cresting at a 15-year peak against European
currencies, has helped create a surge of students enrolling in
study-abroad programs. Local universities and national study-abroad
organizations are reporting significant enrollment increases, some
with 30 percent more students than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes it so much easier to travel and buy things,''
said David in a phone interview from London. ``I'm now traveling
every weekend. I don't know if I would have been able to if the
dollar wasn't so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The crush of students studying abroad this summer is part of a
larger trend of Americans studying overseas. Although still only 9
percent of US college students study abroad, the numbers have
doubled in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1987-1988 academic year, about 60,000 US students studied
abroad; between 1998 and 1999 an estimated 122,000 undergraduates
took classes overseas, according to the latest data from the
Institute of International Education, an umbrella organization for
such programs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Without accounting for the dollar's 12 percent climb against the
Euro in the past six months, the number of students studying abroad
has jumped by more than 20 percent since the academic years
1996-1997, according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
   The main factors influencing the steady increase over recent
years include the roaring US economy _ making it possible for more
students to afford studying outside the country _ and a rising
awareness among students that a global economy requires an
understanding of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that a favorable exchange rate helps, but
that's only part of the most recent story,'' said Todd Davis,
director of the institute's higher education resource group.
``Study abroad is increasingly an integral part of a college
student's education. And international experience is a major plus
in differentiating students when they enter the job market.''
</P>
<P>
   Many study-abroad programs in Massachusetts have also benefited
from the boom.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston University, which has one of the nation's largest
programs with about 1,600 students studying in 13 countries,
enrollment in this summer's programs is up by nearly 30 percent
from last year.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a lack of student interest nearly led officials
at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst to scrap their
study-abroad programs. Now, they have more applications than spots
for classes in countries ranging from Israel to India.
</P>
<P>
   And at Boston College, enrollment for the school's international
programs has grown by almost 20 percent every year since the early
part of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the interesting things we've noticed is that people
aren't complaining about how much they have to pay, like they used
to do,'' said Marian St. Onge, director of Boston College's Center
for International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   While studying overseas is easier when salaries at home are high
and a strong dollar reduces the cost of everything from food to
rent, studying abroad is not cheap. On average, when plane tickets,
required travel, and long-distance phone calls are factored in,
studying overseas is almost always more expensive than a typical
college semester in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Nicole Portley, a 19-year-old junior at Boston
College, said she'll be able to afford studying in Senegal this
fall is because of a government grant. But thanks to the dollar,
assuming it holds its strength through the next academic year, she
should have some petty cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great if the dollar stays at its current level,''
she said. ``I'm hoping to hit a lot of other countries in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   While students may be less concerned about the cost, not every
study-abroad program has benefited from the boom. As demand has
increased, so has the competition. Now, some 1,000 universities and
colleges offer about 5,000 study-abroad programs, according to the
Institute of International Education.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one longtime player in the field concedes the
squeeze effect. Unlike many other schools, Syracuse University
hasn't reaped the benefits of higher enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our programs are more expensive compared to others,''
explained Jon Booth, deputy director of Syracuse's International
Programs Aboard. ``And there's a negative side of the good economy:
People are going to work rather than going to school. That hurts
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as more students realize the benefits of studying abroad,
Syracuse expects to join in the industrywide gains. Until then,
however, the program's officials are resigned to watch as a
resurgent dollar lifts many of their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Beaver College in Glenside, Pa., one of the dominant players in
the field of international studies with more than 2,000 students in
its far-flung programs, has seen enrollment double since the 1991
Gulf War, when many students decided to stay home. And this summer,
the college has registered 12 percent more students to study abroad
than last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment at the Chicago-based Institute for the International
Education of Students has risen by 31 percent this year in its
eight summer programs. In 17 other summer programs it organizes for
various US universities in Europe, the number of students is up 26
percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is having an effect beyond the general growth in the
market,'' said Carla Slawson, IES's vice president of marketing and
recruitment. ``The most obvious explanation is the strength of the
dollar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
