<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ARRESTS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION BETWEEN TOP IRANIAN AUTHORITIES EVIDENT IN LATEST MOVES  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ With the first anniversary of pro-democracy
student riots at Tehran University approaching, the Iranian
authorities took several actions Wednesday that could both provoke
and placate the reformers who have been under severe attack over
the past three months by hard-line clergymen.
</P>
<P>
   In one move, a court here in the capital sent two well-known
reformist lawyers to jail without trials, accusing them of
insulting public officials. One, Mohsen Rahami, represented the
students who were injured last July 8 by police officers and
right-wing vigilantes who attacked their dormitory. The other,
Shirin Ebadi, is a prominent human rights lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the country's supreme
leader, abruptly fired the commander of the national police, who
was blamed by the student protesters for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei gave no reason for the dismissal of the commander,
Brigadier Gen. Hedayatollah Loftian. Twenty police officers,
including Loftian's deputy, have been on trial for their actions in
the campus assault, but no verdict has been announced. Several
students were tried last year _ in secret _ and sentenced to death
for their role in riots that followed the dormitory attack.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly paradoxical actions Wednesday reflect a tug-of-war
in the highest reaches of the Iranian government between
conservatives who fear the growing power of reformers and the
liberal activists who want to wrest the judiciary and security
forces from the hands of religious hardliners.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the forces could also be seen in other
pronouncements Wednesday by the country's top two leaders, who have
rarely taken such diametrically opposing public views.
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammad Khatami, a moderate cleric who has promoted
the rule of law and freedom of expression, said in a speech that
individual rights should not be trampled in the pursuit of law and
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a system creates peace in a society by using force,
violence and intimidation, it has secured a temporary peace in a
cemetery in which people are nothing more than animated corpses,''
said Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   He also made one of his strongest defenses to date of press
freedom, calling on the judiciary to resist political pressure and
to clearly define what constitutes an offense against the system by
writers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement broadcast on state radio, Khamenei, who
holds ultimate political and religious authority, called on the
courts to resist attempts to ``undermine the authority and dignity
of the judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the president swept elections earlier this year
and now control the Iranian parliament. They have launched an
attack on the court system over the past three weeks and pledged to
loosen restrictions on the press and political parties.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservatives who lost control of the parliament have
rallied against their opponents, largely through the court system
and through their influence over Khamenei.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since late May, judges have summarily closed 20 newspapers and
magazines associated with the pro-Khatami forces, with the latest
closure this week. Courts have also jailed five reformist writers
and ordered the arrest of all the Iranian participants at a
conference on democracy that took place in Berlin in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The judges have accused all those arrested of violating Islamic
principles, a criticism also made by Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
   The coming anniversary of the Tehran University disturbances has
added tension to the conflict. A student group has announced that
it intends to hold a demonstration to mark the date. A right-wing
militia that reports, ultimately, to the supreme leader, has asked
for permission to hold a counter-demonstration at the gates to the
university.
</P>
</TEXT>
