<HEADER>
A7306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-PESO-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      06-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PESO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HUGE DROP IN PESO NOT EXPECTED AFTER MEXICAN ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AISSATOU SIDIME and BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ For the first time since the 1970s, the Mexican
presidential election may not wreak havoc on the peso.
</P>
<P>
   Border banks and trade-related businesses that would feel the
pinch of a plummet have seen few signs that the election on Sunday
will send the peso into a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, a stronger economy, a more stable political
climate and the fact that more business in Mexico is conducted in
dollars bolster the peso.
</P>
<P>
   When experts on Mexico look for warning signs of a looming
economic dip, they first look at banks. But there is no sign of
trouble at border banks this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican nationals typically juggle their deposits in American
banks during Easter visits, at the end of each year and just before
a presidential election. So border banks that are at the center of
U.S.-Mexico trade ``live and die on what's happening in Mexico,
just like we live and die with what's happening in the U.S.,'' said
Dennis Nixon, chairman of International Bancshares Corp., the
parent of International Bank of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, just before the peso plummeted 50 percent, banks
shipped only one-tenth of the dollars to U.S. banks that they
normally would send. This trickle was offset by Mexicans' spending
more dollars in stores before the devaluation, according to Keith
Phillips, a senior economist at the San Antonio branch of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, net currency deposits dropped 15 percent in 1994, an
indication that Mexicans hoarded dollars to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as of the end of May, ``we have not seen in overall
dollars that receipts are down,'' Phillips said. ``There's not been
a big hoarding of dollars this year.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the 2000 data are skewed a bit because people hoarded
money due to fears about the year 2000 computer bug, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   But a look at another important clue _ how many pesos are being
converted into dollars and left in U.S. accounts _ shows that
increases are ``less than in 1994,'' said Gerry Schwebel, executive
vice president for international business at IBC, which far
outpaces other border banks in the value of its Mexican accounts.
</P>
<P>
   IBC, the Laredo-based bank that long has aggressively marketed
to Mexican nationals looking for stable places to stash currency or
to borrow for trade-oriented businesses, has seen a slight bump in
the past 90 days in the number of Mexican customers converting
pesos, Schwebel said.
</P>
<P>
   Just days away from what could potentially be a history-making
change in government, Mexico's political climate is much calmer
than in 1994, so investments have not stalled, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, fear over a new floating peso, unrest in Chiapas and
loans that listed interest payments in dollars undermined investor
confidence, said James Giermanski, former regents professor at
Texas A&AMP;M International University.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Mexican businesses and consumers have acclimated to
a floating peso that periodically adjusts downward. The peso fell
in gradual bumps of 10 percent to 15 percent each year between 1996
and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This time, political change is being welcomed. The presidential
election pits Francisco Labastida of the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) against Vicente Fox of the National
Action Party. Polls show that Fox has a strong change of ending 70
years of dominance by the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think change is good,'' said Daniel B. Hastings Jr.,
third-generation owner of a biggest Texas-based customs brokerage
house in Laredo. ``We may need one more PRI term to strengthen
state and local administrations, but Vicente Fox is very pro-trade
and export-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who holds a Harvard business degree and who has led
Coca-Cola operations in Mexico and Central America, ``has a good
business sense that not everybody has had before,'' Hastings said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the peso will probably make its familiar 5 percent to
10 percent drop and settle at about 10.25 to 10.5 for every dollar,
Schwebel said.
</P>
<P>
   If the markets react as they did after the last presidential
election, 2001 will be the year to watch. Even if the 2001 dip is
more substantial, ``it shouldn't hit us that hard because many
export businesses tie their contracts and leases firmly to the
dollar,'' said Nicholas Ferrara, president of Nuevo Laredo's
Industrial Development Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
