<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7331 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEARNING TO BE A SURVIVOR ON CUBICLE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All right, so watching people eat raw bugs and
barbecued rats may not meet your definition of entertainment. It
doesn't matter. You still have to watch ``Survivor'' on CBS. It's
the most educational workplace-related television show since
``Roller Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: Fifteen people are pushing themselves to
the limits of human endurance for mere peanuts, just so that one
greedy soul can walk away a millionaire. Now does it remind you of
work?
</P>
<P>
   In case you've been lost on a cubicle farm the last few weeks,
``Survivor'' is the hot show about being stranded on a deserted
island. Sixteen real people signed up for the 39-day ordeal on
Pulau Tiga in the South China Sea, and one of them gets voted off
the island every episode. The one who remains at the end of the
series wins $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you consider ``Survivor'' honest entertainment or
made-for-TV drivel doesn't really matter. It will teach you about
people, office politics and working relationships, crucial lessons
if you want to be a workplace manager or a survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things to chew on:
</P>
<P>
   _ The inmates do run the asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is officially the leader of either ``Survivor'' tribe,
but people with certain skills have tried to appoint themselves as
bosses. Sometimes it backfires.
</P>
<P>
   B.B. Andersen, a 64-year-old retired contractor, found the
watering hole for his tribe and built its shelter. He also built up
a lot of resentment. ``I've been working my ass off,'' he told his
teammates, ``while a lot of you've been lying on your asses
watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   His leadership didn't last long. He was the first person voted
out of his tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly companies do appoint leaders. But if you are a
manager, ask yourself a question: How long would you last before
being voted off your tribe? If you don't like your answer, having
all the authority in the world won't help.
</P>
<P>
   Every good worker has certain skills. One of the most crucial
skills a manager can have is the ability to bring out the best in
other people. Setting a good example is important, but you also
have to realize that not everyone will approach work the way you
do. Others have to succeed on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   The most important workplace skill was, is and always will be
the ability to get along with people. If you don't have that skill,
any success you have will be only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diversity is crucial, except when it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Different contests in ``Survivor'' reward different skills, so
sometimes the wispiest woman is more valuable than the most
muscular man. If you picked a team in your own image, you would
probably be in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Managers often pick people like themselves: same age, same sex,
same background, same skin color. You have things in common, and
that can make for a comfortable workplace. But it can also limit
creativity, because people with different backgrounds will approach
situations in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, diversity isn't always the answer. The first
person voted off the island was Sonja Christopher, 63. The others
in her tribe felt that although she might add wisdom and a good
perspective, she could drag the team down in physical contests.
</P>
<P>
   If you bring diversity to a group, you have to make it clear how
that will help, such as by using an unusual approach or attracting
new clients. If you lack some fundamental talent and you can't make
others understand how your diversity makes up for it, you won't
survive.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you teach a man to fish, he won't have to eat barbecued
rats.
</P>
<P>
   One tribe earned a snorkel and spear, helping its members to
catch a few fish. Meanwhile, the other tribe got its protein by
eating barbecued rats.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how productive workers can be if you provide them
with the right tools. If you don't, they'll swallow something less
appealing, but that doesn't mean they'll enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   If a competitor is offering fish and you're offering barbecued
rats, your employees may do a little island-hopping.
</P>
<P>
   _ Denial even flows through the island.
</P>
<P>
   The third ousted castaway was Stacey Stillman, a lawyer who was
up a creek without a paddle when she unsuccessfully tried to oust
another tribe member: Rudy Boesch, a retired Navy Seal.
</P>
<P>
   Stillman may be a wonderful attorney, but she made a classic
employee mistake: overestimating your own value. If you're going to
raise a divisive issue, you run the risk of doing irreparable harm
to your reputation unless you already command respect.
</P>
<P>
   Even after being ousted, Stillman was pleading her case to the
camera, saying that the tribe had gotten rid of its ``bug-eating
hero.'' In the previous episode, tribe members from both sides had
to eat bugs or lose a contest, then a tiebreaker was held, where
the most squeamish person from each tribe had to eat two bugs as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Stillman did win that contest, but basically all that did
was save her. If she hadn't been her tribe's most squeamish link,
she wouldn't have been in the tiebreaker in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   She said the men basically just all stuck together behind
Boesch. ``I was more productive than the four guys,'' she
harrumphed. Yet even her two female tribe-mates weren't solidly
behind her; one voted to oust Boesch, the other Stillman.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Stillman was lucky. Circumstances gave her a lesson
that some workers never learn: Office politics are always part of
the game, even when you don't have an office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7334 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     06-28 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICNIC-PACKERS, LIBERATE YOUR POTATO SALAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's only a few day until the Fourth of July, the first real
opportunity for most of us to go on an actual picnic. It will be
our initial chance to get a true sunburn. Once more, we'll feel
that little sting of sparkler embers cascading down our bare arms.
</P>
<P>
   And we'll eat potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   We always eat potato salad on picnic holidays. No one seems to
know why, exactly. It's just that you bring green-bean casseroles
to inside, sit-down suppers; you bring potato salad to picnics.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rule, especially on Independence Day. It must have been
one of the things our forefathers fought for.
</P>
<P>
   The potato salad can be made with mustard or mayonnaise, or
both. Generally, if there are a lot of kids at the picnic, German
potato salad doesn't work well. It's too sweet/sour, and it doesn't
have the right kind of mushy texture that kids enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can overdo the mush. Since most kids now get
their potato salad from the supermarket deli counters, they are
used to the neatly squared little chunks of potato. They don't like
the mashed kind that some home cooks prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Just how potato salad first came about seems a mystery to me. No
one could accidentally drop some hard-boiled eggs and cooked
potatoes into a vat of mayonnaise and sweet pickles. Those items
don't generally sit together on the shelf. Someone had to unify
them on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   I did find a lengthy history of the french fry on the internet,
but it doesn't speak to potato salad. It does say that potatoes
were discovered by the Incas in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no discussion of potato salad, the story goes
on to say the Incas used potatoes for ``telling time, treating
illness and injury, and divination.''
</P>
<P>
   They used spuds to foretell the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish found out about the potatoes and the English got
them from the Spanish, then the English gave them to the colonists
in America. It was unclear how the potatoes got over to Ireland, or
why the Germans make their potato salad with so much vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Texas, where the University of Texas Institute of Texan
Cultures says that Texans of German descent comprise the state's
fourth-largest ethnic group, we get a lot of tangy potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't a lot of variations on the basic potato salad
recipe. There are potatoes _ either white or red _ eggs, sometimes
celery or celery seed, and mustard and mayonnaise. If you want to
get real fancy, it is acceptable to toss in a handful of chopped
dill.
</P>
<P>
   It is also allowable to mix in chopped pickles or even pickle
relish.
</P>
<P>
   The strict recipes are generally easy to follow, but provide
kind of a boring product. Potato salad needs a little spicing up,
it seems, and no one spices up better than Paul Prudhomme,
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Chef Paul Prudhomme's Louisiana Kitchen'' (Morrow,
$19.95), he offers potato salad with a twist. Instead of regular
mayo, Prudhomme suggests a green-onion salad dressing that is
different and full of flavor. With all the bottled salad dressings
on the market today, the idea of using different-flavored dressings
opens up a whole new opportunity for potato salad. I can see it
made with ranch, creamy garlic or Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one caveat: Prudhomme's recipe is pretty spicy,
with two teaspoons of cayenne. Just to be safe, the first time out,
cut the cayenne in half.
</P>
<P>
   POTATO SALAD WITH GREEN-ONION SALAD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6-8 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 medium-size white potatoes, cooked, peeled and coarsely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 hard-boiled eggs, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground red pepper (preferably cayenne)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Green-onion salad dressing (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine all the ingredients, mixing well.
Refrigerate until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-ONION SALAD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 egg plus 1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/8 cups vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoon Creole mustard (preferred) or brown mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Blend the egg and egg yolk in a food processor or blender until
frothy, about 2 minutes. With the machine on, gradually add the oil
in a thin stream. When the mixture is thick and creamy, add the
remaining ingredients and blend thoroughly. Refrigerate until ready
to use.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 415 calories, 36 grams fat, 16
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 212 milligrams cholesterol,
537 milligrams sodium, 78 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
