<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-28 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VACATION WITHOUT A CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We started almost reverently, carefully
negotiating which family photograph should go to which brother or
sister. But four days into cleaning out our parents' house, my
brother Jamie was passing out old family photographs like a
blackjack dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa with a fish,'' Jamie said, tossing a picture of our
grandfather holding a salmon onto my sister Pam's pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa with two fish, Papa with a string of fish, Papa in a
boat,'' he said as he dealt more photographs to the three of us.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one thing my grandfather Cooper loved, it was
fishing. If there was one thing my entire family loved, it was
taking pictures of each other. My late mother kept every one of
those pictures, and as an only child and blond beauty of the Ingrid
Bergman type, she was in a good many of them.
</P>
<P>
   My parents' old house on Cape Cod was filled with hundreds of
photographs, dating back to tintypes of relatives who fought in the
Civil War, all covered with dust that seemingly dated back to when
the house was built in 1776. George Washington coughed here.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother Morse was quite the young Victorian in her
graduation photo from Boston's Franklin Grammar School in 1900.
There were quite a few African-American girls in her class. Boston
schools were better integrated then than in my day. That's the kind
of thing you learn from old photographs.
</P>
<P>
   I learned from my father that his mother got to Boston because
her mother was a daring woman who amicably deserted her husband in
Maine and, after a time, sent for her children.
</P>
<P>
   My brother learned he's half Catholic on both sides, leading to
half-hearted jokes about going to confession and telling half-lies.
He never knew that grandfather Morse was an Irish Catholic who
renounced his religion before marrying a Yankee, or that
grandmother Cooper grew up in a Catholic orphanage in England.
</P>
<P>
   We found an old box containing the rosaries she brought to this
country on the Aquitania. I told the story my mother told me, about
how her mother became an Anglican because Catholic churches in New
Bedford divided up by ethnicity, with none for the English.
</P>
<P>
   American family histories are so complicated compared to the
myths of melting pot or multiculturalism. My mother is gone, and
she was the family historian. We never thought to get the full
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing you learn: Every house is a dump, a memory dump,
but it has to be cleaned out sooner or later. It's always later,
and the pictures never have names on the back.
</P>
<P>
   As the first born in my generation, there were hundreds of
photos of me in my first few years. I tried to explain to my sister
and brother that mom and dad had run out of film by the time they
were born. They were a little hurt anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was the favored child, as my brother and sister always
claimed. Unfortunately, it means I had all the more photos to ship
to California.
</P>
<P>
   Once the six boxes of photographs and papers arrive by UPS, I'm
cleaning out my house. I'm not leaving the kind of archaeological
dig my folks did. I don't even have room for my measly old photos,
and now I have boxes of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The days of being able to afford a house big enough to hold a
family's precious junk are gone. But we can't throw out the
photographs of our great-grandparents' fish-and-chips shop in
Manchester, our grandfather Cooper's working papers that allowed
him to labor as a child in an English mill, or the ships' logs and
portraits from the faintly respectable Maine side of the family.
</P>
<P>
   We await the arrival of my mother's capacious old bureau after
her house sells, and Lord knows where the bureau will go.
</P>
<P>
   We buried my mother at sea after a week of sorting the
photographs and papers she had saved. My father chartered a boat,
and on a bright morning in a gray week we slipped the paper
container of her ashes and some flowers from her garden onto the
unusually glassy waters of Vineyard Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Her father had pulled plenty of flatfish and stripers out of
those waters, and some may not even be in photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Past Woods Hole we could see as far as New Bedford and Fall
River, where my mother lived as a child. In the other direction was
Chatham, where she once had a house and a garden she loved, and
turning north around the Cape you could sail to Maine, where she
went to high school and fell in love with my father.
</P>
<P>
   On the Cape shore near Nobska Light were fancy homes she had
sold as a real estate agent. Sailing out of Woods Hole was the
Martha's Vineyard ferry we took so often to the island Bill Clinton
has helped ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, our family's little boat had been passed by President
John F. Kennedy in the Honey Fitz near the spot we placed my
mother's ashes. The late president's late son, a favorite of my
discerning mother, was buried at sea just a couple of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   This was navigation from the heart by my father the former naval
officer. He didn't realize the full significance of the spot until
we were there, looking past the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution, where he had worked, toward New Bedford, where two
young immigrants met long ago, got married and had a special
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   My mother might have liked this, even though she was as far from
a sentimentalist as a person can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just cremate me, and throw me away,'' were the burial
instructions of this hard-working New England lady. We didn't
follow her instructions exactly.
</P>
<P>
   We each said a few things. We floated her on the water. We
didn't find that famous thing called closure, but we opened to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't take a camera.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
