<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR GORE IT'S THE BEST OF TIMES, THE WORST OF TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 2   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Al Gore _ as for the heroic Sidney Carton and
his friends in Charles Dickens' ``A Tale of Two Cities,'' this is
the best of times and the worst of times.
</P>
<P>
   It is the best of times because two months from now Gore will be
anointed as the Democratic Party's first presidential nominee of
the new millennium. He will be the warrior who will carry the
banner once hoisted aloft by such Democratic presidents and
presidential candidates as Thomas Jefferson, Andrew Jackson,
Woodrow Wilson, Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman, John F. Kennedy,
Lyndon Johnson, Bill Clinton, Jimmy Carter, Adlai Stevenson and
Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   He also will be the candidate of the party that can point with
great satisfaction to the facts that the horrendous federal deficit
ended during its watch and that Bill Clinton will be leaving office
with a budget surplus now estimated a $1.9 trillion over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   It is the worst of times because Gore has been steadily sinking
behind his Republican rival, George W. Bush in the opinion polls
and because Bush has taken the initiative on key issues _ such as
Social Security, Medicare and education _ that once provided
formidable campaign weapons for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the vice president faces the possibility that his
veracity will be eroded if investigators probing his 1996
fund-raising activities find that he was deceptive in order to hide
the true nature of those activities. At issue is his claim that he
did not know that his appearance at the Hsi Lai Buddhist temple
near Los Angeles was a fund-raising event that added an estimated
$140,000 to Democratic coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is the question of whether he understood that some
of the campaign contributions he solicited by telephone in 1996
were ``hard money'' that would benefit his and Clinton's campaign
and not just ``soft money'' for the party.
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., revealed that Robert J. Conrad
Jr., a top Justice Department investigator, had urged Attorney
General Janet Reno to name a special prosecutor to probe Gore's
fund-raising activities more fully, the vice president replied
heatedly and hastily.
</P>
<P>
   He released a 123-page transcript of the four-hour interview
that he had on April 18 with federal investigators on those very
issues. Gore's answers to questions posed in that interview form
the basis for Conrad's call for the appointment of a special
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore told reporters, ``I think the truth is my friend in
this,'' and he added that they could read the transcript and
``judge it for yourselves.'' He asserted that he ``sure as hell''
did not know that the Buddhist temple event was a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Bush apparently already had made a judgment about Gore's
honesty. He chortled when he declared that the demand for a further
investigation of Gore reinforces his own call for ``a new tone in
Washington, which is going to require a new administration.'' That,
the Texas governor added, means turning back Gore's quest for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial question, however, is not what Gore knew when
visited the Buddhist temple or when he made telephone calls to
raise campaign funds. The question is: Did he tell the truth about
his role in those activities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is suffering from his close relationship with Clinton who
lied under oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. No
matter where he goes or what he does, Gore is haunted by the
Clinton stigma at the same time that he is helped by Clinton's
record of achievement and Clinton's continued popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton connection is important to Gore when he cites the
economic gains made by Americans. His ties to the president also
are helpful in his bid for votes among African Americans, Hispanics
and union members. But the ties tarnish Gore's image when his
truthfulness is said to parallel that of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Reno will not bow to Republican pressure and
name a special counsel to probe Gore's conduct. Following an
earlier look into his fund-raising activities four years ago, Reno
rejected suggestions then that she appoint a special counsel to
investigate him. She is a strong woman, who does not readily take
actions that contradict her earlier decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Several individuals and newspapers have suggested that the
voters, rather than a special counsel, should make the decision on
Gore's credibility. By Election Day, Bush and his GOP surrogates
will have filled the atmosphere with charges that Gore cannot be
trusted. At the same time, Gore and his Democratic backers will
have asserted over and over that the vice president's behavior is
above suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Debate over Gore's honesty during the presidential campaign
should provide voters with enough information to determine whether
the vice president is, or is not, the right man to move into the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is not without his problems. They include his seeming
indifference to the death penalty in Texas, where 135 people have
been put to death during his governorship. The problems also
include the possibility that some of oil barons who have done
business with Bush and who have supported his political ambitions
could be found guilty of jacking up the price of gasoline in this
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Bush was late in proposing campaign fund-raising
reform. Under pressure from Arizona Senator John McCain during the
primaries, he unveiled a plan that would place a lid on
contributions from corporations and labor unions but would allow
wealthy individuals, a majority of whom are Republicans, to spend
as much as they desired on political campaigns. His proposed
reform, therefore, would weaken the Democrats while strengthening
the Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
