<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of THURSDAY, June
29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WEB-SEARCH (Undated) _ Five years ago, search engines seemed
like the Web's salvation. Today, they need some saviors of their
own. When search engines first appeared, they were hailed for
accomplishing two things that could not possibly be done by people
on any large scale: search engines could find and index Web sites
almost as soon as they appeared. And they could almost
instantaneously match a page with a single keyword. But today, the
promise of automation has been tempered by the Web's success. There
are now more than one billion Web pages, and doubling every eight
months. Keeping up with that growth has been nearly impossible. To
cope, many search engines have concluded that simply indexing more
pages is not the answer. Instead, they have decided to rely on the
one resource that was once considered a cop-out: human judgment.
Search engines have become more like cyborgs, part human, part
machine. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CHINA-GAMES (Beijing) _ Three a.m. on a summer Friday in
Beijing. A smoke-filled room is packed with men, faces lighted by
computer monitors, adrenaline running from online combat. Bicycles
clutter the alley outside the door under the sign that reads NG
Cafe. The men are muttering into their headsets, discussing attack
strategies with teammates seated only a few computers away. NG Cafe
is a net cafe or a wangba, which serve as late-night entertainment
venues for hundreds of Beijing residents. The putative reason the
wangbas operate is to provide online access. But the global scope
of the Internet seemed mostly an afterthought in a room where 18 of
the 20 computers are engaged in electronic warfare with opponents
sitting nearby. The fact that the government considers the playing
of computer games in wangbas illegal has not stopped thousands of
them, and their cousins, game parlors, (which typically do not
provide Internet access, just locally networked computers) from
springing up across China. But the proliferation of wangbas and
game parlors in the last three years has vexed a government that
aspires to monitor social, political and economic trends. Wangbas,
the government believes, have the potential to alter all three. By
Jennifer 8. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The computer column: A look at
programs like Napster, Gnutella, Freezone and Hotline, which allow
users to trade files PC to PC, bypassing servers. By Peter H.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Techno news and notes: Online photo
albums; Sony PDA using Palm OS and memory stick storage; new
antivirus software.
