<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ENTRAPMENT-HNS &LR;      06-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTRAPMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT RULES AGENTS IMPROPERLY SNARED MAN WITH CYBERSEX AD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ His marriage and military career both over, Mark
Poehlman was trolling the Internet for someone to share his
passions for cross-dressing and foot fetishism. He answered an ad
placed by ``Sharon,'' who expressed interest but said she was
really seeking a ``special teacher'' for her three young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The more that Poehlman wooed Sharon by e-mail, the more she
brought up her daughters, saying she preferred to watch. After two
weeks, he took the hint, sent a series of messages about sex with
the children, and finally traveled from his Florida home to Long
Beach, Calif., where Sharon showed him some child pornography and
then delivered him into the waiting arms of state and federal
agents.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that
Poehlman, 40, had been entrapped, and overturned his 10-year
federal prison sentence for crossing state lines to engage in sex
with a minor. He had served about 19 months of the sentence, and
previously served part of a one-year state prison term for the same
conduct, a conviction not affected by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 decision, the court said federal agents conceived of
the crime and recruited Poehlman, who was looking only for legal,
adult companionship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is surely enough real crime in our society that it is
unnecessary for our law enforcement officials to spend months
luring an obviously lonely and confused individual to cross the
line between fantasy and criminality,'' said the opinion by
appellate Judge Alex Kozinski.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting Judge David Thompson said there was enough evidence
to support the jury's conclusion that Poehlman was the one who
proposed sex with the children.
</P>
<P>
   Entrapment has become a common defense to the increasing number
of sex crime prosecutions resulting from government sting
operations on the Internet, where agents typically pose as
children.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants have to prove that they were induced to commit the
crime. But in cases like Poehlman's, the government has argued,
usually with success, that the defendant was already predisposed to
commit the crime and was merely given an opportunity by an
undercover agent. Defendants have a better chance in California
courts, which consider predisposition irrelevant and define
entrapment as police conduct that would induce a normally
law-abiding person to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Lon Ramlan, who investigates cyber crimes for the San
Francisco police, said undercover officers are careful to avoid
entrapment but are encountering new definitions in the Internet
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is public and anonymous,'' he said. ``I don't
have to announce I'm a police officer. But it's a very complicated
area. When you develop these relationships on the Internet, logging
all the conversations, it's very difficult at times to know how far
you should or shouldn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Poehlman's lawyer, Edward M. Robinson, said there was no
evidence that Poehlman was predisposed to have sex with children.
He said the ``alternative lifestyle'' Internet discussion group,
which Poehlman was frequenting when he saw ``Sharon's'' ad, focused
on sexual behavior among adults, not children.
</P>
<P>
   Posting that ad reflected a misplaced belief by federal law
enforcement authorities ``that people who are not just straight
heterosexuals are automatically interested in children,'' Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Los Angeles was disappointed by
the ruling, said spokeswoman Adriene Hill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case dates from 1995, when Poehlman had just been divorced
by his wife after about 12 years of marriage and had been pushed
into early retirement after nearly 17 years in the Air Force. Both
separations resulted from his inability to control his impulse to
cross-dress, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   In her first e-mail, Sharon told Poehlman that she and her
children were ``looking for someone who understands us and does not
let society's views stand in the way.'' She said she especially
wanted someone to help with the children's ``special education,''
and referred in later messages to a ``man teacher'' and ``special
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Poehlman replied that he would be happy to teach the children
``proper morals'' but said he was interested in a relationship,
leading to marriage, with Sharon. She turned him down; said she
wanted only someone for her daughters, and described having ``goose
bumps'' when recalling her own ``special teacher.'' She also asked
him to describe plans for their ``first lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   She never mentioned child sex, but her meaning was clear, the
court said: Poehlman could stay in contact with her only if he
agreed to have sex with her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government . . . played on Poehlman's obvious need for an
adult relationship, for acceptance of his sexual proclivities and
for a family, to draw him ever deeper into a sexual fantasy
world,'' wrote Kozinski, joined by Judge Betty Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   In dissent, Thompson said the government's messages were
``purposely vague'' and gave Poehlman the chance to back out if he
wanted only an adult relationship.
</P>
</TEXT>
