<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      06-28 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW, FOR $500, CAESAR WILL EAT A POISON-IVY SALAD
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm probably a little too young to begin grumbling wth any real
authority about the world going to hell in a handbasket, but I
swear I'm getting pretty steady whiffs of singed wicker these days.
Some mornings after I read the paper, I just want to stay home in
my slippers and bathrobe and grouse to the cat about how much more
sensible people used to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten so bad I've actually begun reflecting on the roughly
eight years of first-year Latin I took in high school and college
to try to recall what comparable stage of the decline and fall of
the Roman Empire we're now living through.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm not remembering it clearly, but didn't folks entertain
themselves back then by watching people nibble on rat hors
d'oeuvres, like we're now doing with the insanely popular game show
``Survivor''?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't the Roman senators do stuff like eliminate taxes that
affected only the nation's wealthiest citizens, while fiddling
endlessly over how to help the elderly pay for the medicine they
need to stay alive?
</P>
<P>
   Weren't there a couple of ambitious praetors named Jebbus and
Georgius Dubyus who duked it out over who could send more people
down the River Styx? At one point, didn't an inexplicably
influential windbag like Rush Limbaugh audition for ``Monday Night
Gladiators''?
</P>
<P>
   If I can find a company that manufactures togas, I think I'll
invest. The way things are going, it'll be the next big fashion
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I read a story in The Village Voice about young
entrepreneurs creating ``reality-based'' shows on the Internet. One
site features a game show called ``I Bet You Will.'' People are
given wads of cash to perform degrading stunts.
</P>
<P>
   The show's host, Morgan Spurlock, led a camera crew into
Manhattan recently. He had a very busy day, it appears. A fellow
ate a whole jar of mayonnaise for 50 bucks. Another guy gnawed on
dog feces for $400. Two women accepted $200 each to walk around
town topless, with bull's-eyes on their breasts and the words
``Follow Me 2 Free Money,'' scrawled on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not exploiting people,'' Spurlock told The Village
Voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving them an experience that they will joke about with
their friends for the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Yuh. I can imagine regaling friends years from now with tales of
the time I ate doggie doo to pay off my Mastercard. Ooh, the
memories. Another Internet site offers ``Dare for Dollars,'' which
asks ``desperate people'' to send them details of degrading things
they'd do for cash. The ``winners'' get filmed in action.
</P>
<P>
   Some entries would cause Caligula to flinch. A college student
who says his parents have cut him off financially -- and no wonder
-- offers to lick a public urinal for $2,000. Another fellow, who
describes himself as an unemployed diabetic with no health
insurance, offered to run barefoot across a greased basketball
court while people throw oranges at him. His asking price: $3,750.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes this abusive form of ``charity.'' At the
filming of ``I Bet You Will,'' bystanders began hollering at the
camera crew to stop. ``Welcome, welcome, welcome to the Roman
festivities,'' one guy shouted. ``Decadence! Decadence!'' Someone
promptly spit on him.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff like this has been going on for centuries, of course. We
just have more ways to beam the frivolity around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect there's a correlation, though, between our booming
economy and the popularity of these programs. So many people are
getting stinking rich for doing little or nothing, and it's
frustrating some folks so much that they're willing to go to
extremes to get a piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   And then, blessedly, there's Anne Lydiat of Nottingham, England,
who's enjoying modest success with her new book, ``At a Loss for
Words.'' It's 52 pages long, and each and every page is blank. She
says she was inspired to ``write'' it after visiting several
Belgian convents where talking is forbidden. ``I wanted a book that
dealt with silent spaces,'' she said. ``You open it and there's
nothing to read. But maybe nothing is something.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I've inhaled too much handbasket smoke, but that halfway
makes sense. I look forward to seeing a game show based on her
book.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
