<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WOMENS-RESIDENCES-     06-28 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMENS-RESIDENCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTANT NOSTALGIA, AS TWO HAVENS FOR YOUNG WOMEN CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MONTE WILLIAMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The young women will pine for the maid service and
the two meals a day, and some will even miss the fact that suitors
were not allowed in their rooms, only in the elegantly appointed
``beau parlors.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, in this market of cloud-scaling housing costs,
they will miss the rent: $600 to $700 a month, breakfast and dinner
and maid service included.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, Katharine House and Roberts House _ Manhattan's last
two residential hotels for young women _ will be vacant, except for
staff members who have until July 14 to leave. The closing of the
residences will end an era when dozens of long-term hotels housed
dewy-eyed women from all over the world. The most famous was the
Barbizon Hotel for Women, which became a spa in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The young residents of these hotels were an ambitious lot:
Aspiring models, actresses, dancers, writers and students. They had
come to take on New York, hunting fame and fortune and, yes,
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Not just anyone could stay at these residences. At Roberts
House, at 151 E. 36th St., and Katharine House, at 118 W. 13th St.,
the women had to be between 18 and 25 years old and could not earn
more than $25,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great entree into the city,'' said George Liu, one of
the 25 to 30 young women at Roberts House who were still looking
for new places to live last week. ``It's a great place to start.
We've made great friends.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Liu found a room on the Upper West Side. By Tuesday,
the 14 women remaining at Roberts House and the 13 at Katharine
House were packing, some of them to return home, others to stay
with friends.
</P>
<P>
   The two houses, each more than 70 years old and with 80 rooms,
are owned by the Ladies Christian Union, a nonprofit organization
founded before the Civil War. The organization has listed the
buildings with Sotheby's International Realty Co., which estimates
they will fetch just under $10 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Yeshiva University is seriously interested in Roberts House as a
women's dormitory, said Dolly Lenz, executive vice president of
Sotheby's. And Katharine House has caught the eye of a developer
who wants to turn it into a condominium.
</P>
<P>
   The Ladies Christian Union once ran six such residences for
women. ``Our goal is to promote the temporal, moral and religious
welfare of women _ particularly young women _ who are dependent
upon their own exertions for support,'' said Noelle Mills Adler,
the organization's president.
</P>
<P>
   That mission has not changed, Adler said, but the group's
methods will. ``We feel there are more effective ways of fulfilling
our purpose and reaching more needy young women by becoming a
grant-making organization,'' she said, adding that the group would
contribute to hardship cases at colleges, universities and
performing arts and vocational schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the young women who have yet to find a new place to live in
New York, or who have all but given up trying, are skeptical. ``I
think they're sort of selling out,'' said Bonnie Freestone, a
23-year-old teacher at a Roman Catholic high school on the Upper
East Side and a resident of Katharine House for more than a year.
``This is the last bit of affordable housing in the West Village,
and now it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Freestone, who plans to go to graduate school in New Jersey
after Katharine House closes, said that certain rules at the
residence were a bit anachronistic. For example, she laughed when
showing a visitor the beau parlor, a chintz-filled room with
flowers, and laughed again when asked if any men might have found
their way into the women's rooms without the knowledge of the
resident director, who functions in many ways like a dorm mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place isn't even in the 20th century,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that Victorian ethos comforted the parents of the young
women from far-flung places who moved into the residences. At both
houses, visitors are not allowed above the first floor without
permission. At Katharine House receptionists buzz the young women
in their rooms _ twice for a guest and once for a phone call. (The
rooms at Roberts House have telephones.) At both buildings, the
rules required suitors to leave by 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1950s, there was even a curfew for residents: 11 p.m.
on weekdays, midnight on weekends. ``There was a Salvation Army
residence on 38th Street, and the girls who didn't meet the curfew
used to go around there and spend the night,'' Adler said. ``Well,
the Salvation Army complained so bitterly, we dropped the curfew.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Mae Crawford, a 21-year-old resident of Roberts House
and an aspiring artist, recalled that when her boyfriend came to
install a stereo system in her room, a chaperon came, too.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, a native of Lake Charles, La., recently found an
apartment in Queens to share with two other women. But the landlord
has not finished renovating the place, ``so for two months we will
be homeless,'' she said, glumly.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Dawe, a dancer, has been looking for rooms in other
long-term Manhattan hotels, a few of which started out as
residences for young women but have since opened their doors to men
and older women. Those moves changed the character of the
residences. But that is not her chief concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't seem to be as clean as this place,'' Dawe said
last week as she ate a chili sandwich in the dining room of Roberts
House. ``They just don't seem to be as nice, and they're more
expensive. Here there are no ants, no roaches, no rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff members have been looking for new jobs, and in some cases,
homes too. Alexandra Polychronopoulou, a residence co-director at
Roberts House for the last four years, said that she would have to
give up her own one-bedroom apartment there. Some days, she
recalled, she could hear the sound of music coming from the baby
grand piano in the living room whenever the women decided to throw
an impromptu concert. Her eyes sparkled at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``On many days, there were French girls eating in the garden,
just chirping away,'' she said. ``In the winter, the girls would
have hot chocolate, in their pajamas. And we would have the biggest
Christmas tree and menorah.''
</P>
<P>
   Few residents or employees have been feeling festive lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't reached the weeping stage yet,'' said Nikki Hinds,
25, a resident of Katharine House for a year and a half. ``But I've
heard lots of weeping.'' Hinds, a part-time research assistant who
has just completed a graduate program in public policy at New
School University, is searching for an apartment with a friend. So
far, they have come up empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Both buildings had been fully occupied until it was announced
six months ago that they were being sold. ``A lot of girls just
gave up and went back home,'' Hinds said.
</P>
<P>
   Dina Vickermann, a 21-year-old from Germany who came to study
acting at the Lee Strasberg Institute, said last week that she
would return to Germany to study medicine. ``I'd like to try
acting, but I need something where I can support myself,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Becky Peterson, a 24-year-old editorial assistant at a
publishing company, plans to leave Manhattan and live with
relatives in the San Francisco Bay area after Katharine House
closes. She has dreams of being a writer. ``I can't afford to live
here anymore,'' she said. ``If I can't live in Manhattan, then I
don't want to be here. Getting a share with someone in the outer
boroughs is not what I came here for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
