<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-STORM0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Imperfect `Storm' logs great effects but so-so plot
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There could have been a tragic dimension to
``The Perfect Storm,'' the man-against-nature epic that leads to
needless fishing-community deaths. But the Wolfgang Petersen movie
based on Sebastian Junger's nonfiction bestseller is content to
reduce the sea saga to a water-park thrill ride.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you like raging ocean foam, torrential rains and surging
walls of water, you will probably note the imperfections in
Petersen's ``Storm.'' If you prefer flesh-and-blood to H2O, you are
really in for a disappointing voyage, for the crew of the
commercial fishing boat Andrea Gail is made up of hollow, stock
characters whose actions keep defying rational thought.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they are no worse than the tornado-trackers who
headed toward _ not away from _ the deadly funnel of ``Twister,'' a
movie that shares special-effects supervisor John Frazier with
``The Perfect Storm.'' They at least were compelled to record data
for scientific study.
</P>
<P>
   Here, once Capt. Billy Tyne (George Clooney) hauls in a
lucrative catch of swordfish, and his boat's ice machine happens to
stop functioning, he heads directly into the path of three
converging weather fronts. It is a foolhardy decision made for
mercenary motives, hardly a move calculated to involve an audience
in the crew's waterlogged struggle for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Petersen and screenwriter Bill Witliff (''Lonesome
Dove'') want us to care about these folks. After all, they spend
the first half-hour of ``The Perfect Storm `` sketching them in as
they get sloshed and pour out their pipe dreams to one another at
Gloucester's nautical hangout, the Crow's Nest.
</P>
<P>
   There is Tyne, whose streak of bad luck at sea is preying on his
sense of judgment and will lead him to take out the Andrea Gail
again on the cusp of the risky fall weather season. There is Bobby
Shatford (Mark Wahlberg), strapped for cash since his divorce and
eager to start a new life with steamy Chris Cotter (Diane Lane),
whom he promises _ Cliche warning! Cliche warning! _ that this will
be his last trip to sea. Dale Murphy (John C. Reilly) also has
money woes over his estranged family; scruffy Bugsy (John Hawkes)
cruises the bar for some human contact; and Jamaican Alfred Pierre
(Allen Payne) is ill-defined except for his extreme sexual prowess.
Add in last-minute crew replacement Sully (William Fitcher), a
sullen bloke whose sole purpose is extra dramatic friction, and we
are ready to hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   It is getting tiresome to report it, but ``The Perfect Storm''
is just one more big-budget movie that cares far more about its
visual effects than its story. Yes, the Industrial Light &AMP; Magic
computer-simulated squalls are impressive, and the towering waves
are awesome. Once the storm builds to full force, though, even the
shouted dialogue is difficult to understand.
</P>
<P>
   There are exciting rescue attempts by an Air Force helicopter,
but the evident peril to the military Samaritans underlines how
selfish the Gail's actions are. That also goes for a trio of yacht
cruisers (Bob Gunton, Cherry Jones and Karen Allen) whose purpose
must be to make the fishermen seem sane by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that Petersen once made ``Das Boot'' (''The
Boat''), perhaps the most gripping nautical action picture ever,
his efforts this time seem perfunctory. James Horner's music
indicates that we are supposed to feel that the ship's crew is up
to something heroic and noble. Apparently, he was short on melodies
for the greedy and foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there were pithier messages intended for ``The Perfect
Storm,'' but they have been drowned out by the deluge. A movie like
this should leave us with a more profound moral than ``Check your
ice maker before heading out to fish,'' don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
