r e BC-PIANIST-SUCCESS-TEX     06-28 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANIST-SUCCESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANIST'S CUP OF JOE BRIMMING WITH POSSIBILITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ He isn't pouring as many grande coffees
these days. Christopher Basso says he has cut back his hours as
assistant manager at a New York City Starbucks to explore his
new-found _ and completely unexpected _ celebrity and ponder
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Basso, 41, a conservatory-trained pianist, won the International
Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs in Fort Worth earlier
this month. The competition, however, wasn't supposed to change
anyone's life.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Cliburn Foundation, the same organization that
presents the quadrennial Van Cliburn International Piano
Competition for professionals, the amateur was supposed to be a fun
``little brother'' version of the main event, aimed at accomplished
amateur pianists over age 35 who have careers in other fields.
</P>
<P>
   But Basso, who gives New Yorkers their daily joe at a Starbucks
in Manhattan's East Village, received a great deal of attention for
his win at the increasingly competitive Fort Worth event, and has
already played two recitals at professional venues. And, although
he doesn't have a manager at the moment, he has had serious concert
inquiries, forcing him to reduce his work schedule from full time
to 20 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, I wouldn't have even considered it,'' Basso says,
in a telephone interview from the coffee shop. ``I've never been
the type to take risks like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Basso says he will use the extra time to practice, and will fall
back on savings, if necessary. ``If it doesn't work out, I can
always get more hours back,'' he says. ``I haven't burned any
bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Basso's big break came on June 10, the day of the amateur
competition finals. Part of first prize was the opportunity to play
a recital eight days later at the Hirshhorn Museum in Washington.
His performance received a favorable review in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of the Rockport Chamber Music Festival, north of
Boston, got wind of Basso's success in Washington, and, when
pianist Helen Grimaud canceled her scheduled appearance last
Friday, they called Basso and asked him to fill in with only two
days' notice. His second solo recital resulted in an even more
favorable review in the Boston Globe, in which critic Ellen Pfeifer
predicted that ``Basso's simple life may soon see dramatic
change.''
</P>
<P>
   While this isn't the objective of the amateur competition, which
is dedicated to promoting the piano as a lifelong avocation, Maria
Guralnik, general manager of the Cliburn Foundation, says the
foundation is pleased to see Basso succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of exciting from the point of view of the Cliburn,''
Guralnik says. ``He didn't expect it, we didn't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also points out that the professional ranks offer
intense competition, and it's yet to be seen whether Basso's window
of opportunity will close quickly or open to a new career path.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see if this sustains,'' Guralnik
says. ``We hope he has his eyes open, and doesn't rush out and quit
his day job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of amateurs have done performances for which they get
paid,'' adds Cliburn Foundation President Richard Rodzinski.
``That's OK. In fact, it's proper that they get paid.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rodzinski says that creating professional pianists ``is not
what the amateur competition is about.''
</P>
<P>
   It has, however, been Basso's dream for much of his life. Basso,
a native of New Jersey, studied piano at the San Francisco
Conservatory, then settled in New York, where he worked at various
cafes and bars to support himself while continuing piano studies
with renowned instructor Nina Svetlanova and waiting for his big
break.
</P>
<P>
   Rodzinski says that Basso's circumstances raise some interesting
questions.
</P>
<P>
   For one, ``How many people of that caliber are working full-time
jobs (outside the music profession)?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Morgan Shafer, the operations manager for Starbucks
in Manhattan, heard about Basso's victory in Fort Worth and went to
meet his newly famous employee, who was back at work the Tuesday
after the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one of our associates wins a great achievement,'' Shafer
says, ``we like to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   There are even discussions among Shafer, Basso and Allan
Hilowitz, Northeast regional spokesman for Starbucks, about
producing a CD of Basso performing, which would be played in
Starbucks stores and also be available for purchase, with prime
shelf space next to the coffeemakers, exotic blends, mugs and
flavorings.
</P>
<P>
   Basso's cup indeed is running over. Not only will his music
possibly be available in Starbucks across the country, but
presenters in Palm Springs and of an upcoming tour of the Russian
National Orchestra have expressed interest in Basso playing some
dates next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These opportunities don't come along often,'' Basso says. ``My
idea is to just say yes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is music critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7756, or e-mail:
wlgay(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
