<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BLACKS-POLL-NYT &LR;      06-28 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACKS-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS NEW YORK CITY'S BLACKS FEARING BIAS BUT OPTIMISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By BLAINE HARDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Black residents of New York City are afraid of being
brutalized by the police, but they welcome and appreciate officers
who keep criminals out of their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   At all income levels, blacks in the city are convinced that
racial discrimination limits their income and holds back job
advancement. Yet they also believe that the major reason that young
black men have troubled lives is not discrimination, but the
breakdown of black families and a lack of personal motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Amid New York's economic boom, with overall unemployment at a
12-year low, blacks in the city say their most important problem is
a lack of jobs. But they are convinced that their children will be
more successful than they have been.
</P>
<P>
   These ambivalent attitudes are part of a wide-ranging State of
Black New York poll conducted this month for the New York Urban
League. Based on random telephone interviews with 801 blacks across
the city, the survey paints a portrait of a community on edge, one
that feels victimized by unemployment, police brutality and racial
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But it also shows that most blacks are optimistic about the
future, deeply committed to their churches and introspective about
a breakdown in black family life, which they link to the poor
performance of many young blacks in schools and the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there would be more consistency,'' said Dennis
Walcott, president of the New York Urban League, who helped write
the questions in the poll. ``The relationship between the local cop
and the black community is not as strained or as simple as has been
portrayed in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Another polling surprise was the relative lack of support among
New York blacks for school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   While blacks had serious concerns about the quality of public
schools, only 41 percent of those polled supported using tax money
for vouchers. Fifty-three percent said tax money should be used
only for public education.
</P>
<P>
   The findings differ from most nationwide polls of blacks, which
have found support for vouchers running about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Support for vouchers, as measured by the poll, increased sharply
among New York blacks as income decreased. A narrow majority of
households with yearly incomes under $10,000 supported vouchers.
But at income levels above $50,000, there was strong opposition to
shifting public money to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Income made little difference, though, in the perception among
blacks in New York that racial discrimination stains nearly every
aspect of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This survey shows that no matter how successful black people
become, they still suffer the slings and arrows of racism,''
Walcott said. ``Whether it is engagement with the police department
or issues involving promotion or disparity in wages, the figures
show that people feel that racism has touched their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name places where racial discrimination was most
common, the greatest proportion of those polled, 30 percent,
mentioned stores, where blacks have long complained about being
followed by clerks and security officers.
</P>
<P>
   Based on their perception of discrimination, more than four out
of five respondents said that affirmative action was still needed
in jobs and schools. Support for affirmative action was strongest
in households earning more than $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What jumps out at me from this survey is the emphasis on jobs
and economic development,'' said Walter Stafford, a professor of
public policy and urban planning at New York University who
analyzed the poll for the Urban League. ``Across the board, people
tend to perceive discrimination in access to jobs and mobility _
even at high income levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's unemployment rate in 1999 was 11.8 percent for black
men and 10.4 percent for women, compared with a citywide average of
6.7 percent last year. Black men and women had nearly double the
unemployment rates of whites in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``What also strikes me is that this is not a secure group,''
Stafford said, pointing to results showing that 53 percent of
respondents said they had no pensions other than Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, from June 5-16, was done for the New York Urban
League by Blum &AMP; Weprin Associates, a New York polling firm. About
70 percent of the respondents identified themselves as black or
African-American; about 30 percent said they were Caribbean or West
Indian blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the poll's findings, particularly those concerning black
attitudes toward the police, echo some results of two recent polls
by New York Times and CBS News. Those polls were conducted after
the police shooting of Amadou Diallo in February 1999 and the
shooting of Patrick M. Dorismond this March.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with The Times' polls, which surveyed New Yorkers of
all races, the Urban League survey contacted three to five times as
many black respondents in the city, making it relatively more
precise in assessing black views. The poll's margin of error is
plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The Urban League survey found a deep and pervasive ambivalence
among black New Yorkers in their attitudes toward the police. While
they feel that the police disproportionately victimize them because
they are black, they also want police protection against crime, the
poll found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like straddling a fence,'' said Lileathea Grays-Wallace,
44, a divorced mother of three who lives in the South Bronx and who
participated in the poll. ``I am worried about the police on one
side and the criminals on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Like 45 percent of those polled in the survey, Grays-Wallace
said that she believed that the police in her immediate
neighborhood (she lives a block from a police station) did a
good-to-excellent job of being helpful and friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But four blocks down, I don't know,'' said Grays-Wallace, who,
like nearly nine of out 10 respondents in the survey, said police
brutality was a ``serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Her oldest daughter works as a dispatcher for the police
department, she said. Still, she said she was afraid that her
younger daughters, who are 13 and 8, would say the wrong thing to
the police on the street and be arrested or abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a miscommunication thing,'' she said. ``I tell my
daughters they will be judged by what they look like. I explain to
them to keep their senses up and show respect.''
</P>
<P>
   This simultaneous need for and fear of the police has
overwhelmed the life of Daisy Boyd, 77, who lives in the
Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood of Brooklyn and also participated
in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, her son, Daniel Lee, then 30, was shot to death
in front of her apartment when he tried to chase away gang members
selling drugs, Boyd said. Last week, she said that another son,
Jasper, 33, was arrested by the police and was forced to spend a
night in jail after he tried to stop a fight outside a homeless
shelter in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt my son so bad to be arrested that he just cried, and
he is a college graduate,'' Boyd said. ``Some of the police are
just mean. They don't like the black man, no way. The police seem
to be pretty nice to me, but they are not so nice to the young
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Urban League poll avoided questions about politics and
politicians, other than to ask if the withdrawal of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani from the Senate race would make black residents more or
less likely to vote in November. About three-quarters of those
polled said the withdrawal of the mayor, who is widely blamed by
blacks for worsening racial tensions in the city, would not affect
their interest in voting.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the longstanding importance of the church in black
communities, the poll found religion plays a significant role in
the lives of an overwhelming majority of black New Yorkers. Nearly
four out of five respondents said that religion is either extremely
or very important, while 61 percent said they attended church at
least once a month and 35 percent said that they volunteer at least
five hours a month at their church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across all income levels, the church is important,'' said
Walcott of the New York Urban League.
</P>
<P>
   Walcott said that high levels of religious involvement are
connected to what he described as the poll's findings of
``introspection on the part of the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The poll got at the issue of family structure and how it
contributes to a lack of success for young black men,'' he said.
``It also talked about family dysfunction as a reason for poor
performance in school. The black community isn't solely dealing
with external conditions such as racism. It is also aware of the
internal issues that need to be addressed for equal opportunity to
be achieved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
