<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: AIR TRAFFIC DELAYS PILING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also moving in `t' news file.) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer's here, business travelers! Time to glare at those
airport tote boards and boil.
</P>
<P>
   Summertime flight delays are starting to pile up as traffic
increases at domestic airports. And despite new strategies for
better-coordinated air traffic control responses to weather-related
delays that cause most of the problems in an overtaxed system, the
industry is worried that this summer is going to be a lot like last
summer, the worst period ever for domestic flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer was an unmitigated disaster,'' said David Fuscus,
the vice president for communications at the Air Transport
Association, the airline industry's main trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Fuscus didn't want to specifically predict another unmitigated
disaster. ``This summer it looks like we'll have the same type of
record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, federal records so far indicate a slight improvement
in the situation this year. In April, the airline industry and the
Federal Aviation Administration put into place a new program called
the Spring/Summer 2000 Severe Weather Plan. Among its provisions,
Fuscus said, is a procedure that gives a ``more robust role'' to
the main federal air traffic control center in Virginia. This
enables controllers there to do central monitoring and adjusting of
traffic in every segment of the domestic system during those times
when bad weather in various places starts those airport tote boards
blinking.
</P>
<P>
   In May, flight delays dropped by 7 percent, the FAA said. But
the industry isn't exactly breaking out the Champagne over that.
``On the surface, it may sound good, and the FAA may tell you that
it's good _ until you consider that we've had a flight-delay crisis
over the last three summers, including this summer,'' Fuscus said.
``If you go back to May of 1997, though, you actually see an
increase in delays of 90 percent this May.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating another summer of snarled skies, some airlines are
even reducing flight schedules in advance. ``No one is more
frustrated by it than the airlines,'' Fuscus said. ``I mean, United
Airlines just canceled 4,500 flights throughout the summer because
there is no confidence they wouldn't be delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall problem is an out-of-date air traffic control
system. ``It can't move enough planes through the sky quickly
enough under the present safety parameters, which are, of course,
correct,'' said Fuscus, whose organization has been assiduously
lobbying Congress to put a lot more money than it has so far into
modernizing the aged aviation infrastructure, which the airline
industry contends will take another seven to 10 years to bring
fully up to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, delays in the summer are here to stay until
that air traffic control system is fixed,'' Fuscus said. ``It gets
our customers screaming mad. And they don't get mad at the FAA,
they get mad at us.''
</P>
<P>
   But hey, it could be worse. For example, we could be stuck with
a system like the one in Europe, where antiquated technology
combines with nationalistic chauvinism to create an air traffic
network so fragile that some indignant Frenchmen can basically shut
it down like dairy farmers railing against European Union cheese
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to the situation in France this week. French air traffic
controllers, incensed at the European Union for discussing the idea
of a central, and perhaps partially privately owned, air traffic
system for all of Europe, walked off the job on for 24 hours on
Monday in a wildcat strike. The action grounded 90 percent of the
flights within France and caused backups and cancellations
throughout the Western European air system. About half of the
international flights that pass through French airspace were also
canceled, and stranded business travelers in France had to
commandeer space on busses and trains to get to neighboring
countries like Belgium to try to pick up flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our traffic is back to normal today, and we don't see any
other problems in the near future,'' a spokeswoman for Air France
said Tuesday afternoon. British Airways, which canceled 37 flights
to and from France on Monday, also said that its operations had
returned to normal. But the French protest spread Tuesday to
Greece, where air traffic controllers, demanding assurance that the
Greek system won't be privatized, began a four-day strike during
prime flight hours to make their feelings known about control-tower
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Jeanniot, the director general of the International Air
Transport Association, predicted a summer of major delays in the
European air system. ``The situation is totally unacceptable,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fuscus said: ``If there's an example of something that works
worse than our system, it's the European system. We've got a delay
crisis; they've got a delay calamity brewing. It's absolutely
abysmal. I can't imagine there could be anything worse than our
system in the summertime in terms of delays, but there it is:
Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
