<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-PALM-LIVING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARTS OF PALM: A SUGAR CUBE OF STUCCO 
</HEADLINE>
   By MITCHELL OWENS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The best thing about this neighborhood
is you can step outside to get the paper and not see anybody you
know,'' Mario Nievera said. Which can be a blessing, he added,
``because we live pretty public lives here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is Palm Beach, a posh playground for Vanderbilts,
Astors and their ilk since the 1920s, and Nievera is not being
boastful about the high-profile existence shared by him and his
partner, Robert Janjigian. A gregarious, notebook-wielding presence
at cocktail parties and charity events, Janjigian, 42, is the
fashion editor of The Palm Beach Daily News, known as The Shiny
Sheet for its slick finish. The gardens Nievera, 35, creates for
members of the local fete set show up in Architectural Digest. Yet,
their primary residence is comfortably modest. So is its location.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-seven miles north of Miami, West Palm is Palm Beach's
renegade mainland sister, the grinning tomboy who married the
family chauffeur and settled down to car pool and lunchbox bliss.
Pockmarked with strip malls and laced with freeway asphalt, the
city was founded in 1894 as the railroad stop for moneyed New
Yorkers escaping harsh winters, so its landscape is nowhere as
grand as that found across the bay bridge in Palm Beach. There the
shady streets are lined with Norma Desmond Spanish villas designed
in the 1920s by Addison Mizner, a theatrical architect and flimflam
man.
</P>
<P>
   Nievera and Janjigian's house, on the other hand, is an
Eisenhower-era relic, which they bought for $80,000 four years ago.
A tidy sugar cube of pale beige stucco smoothly troweled over
concrete blocks, its mass-market modernism shelters two bedrooms
and one bath. The front door is tucked inside the carport and leads
directly into the kitchen. ``I couldn't do anything about the
placement of the front door, so this part of the garden is designed
like a vestibule,'' Nievera said, opening a gate cut into a thick
viburnum hedge alongside the house.
</P>
<P>
   Their slim-jim trunks standing at attention like green
sculptures in a pale marble room, a formal allee of Alexander
coconut palms sprouts from a carpet of glistening white pebbles.
``It's very easy to maintain,'' Nievera said. ``You see every leaf
that falls, so you have to pick it up.'' Soft mounds of Mexican
heather and butterfly bush soften the edges of the formal
French-influenced layout, and funky metal and wire chairs painted
white or delicate hydrangea blue peek through the tropical
greenery.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seems peaceful now, traffic goes by all the time, ``so
it was on the market for a while,'' Nievera said. (High-profile
additions to the city like the Raymond F. Kravis Center for the
Performing Arts, the prestigious Palm Beach Antiques Show and the
CityPlace housing development have sent real estate prices
skyrocketing.)
</P>
<P>
   As for their house, there were myriad drawbacks. Crank-out
jalousie windows, for instance, were once the last word in
low-maintenance chic, but half the panes had fallen out. Indoors
was an air-conditioner free zone of white and teal blue. And the
flat wood roof, he recalled with a shudder, leaked. ``At first, I
thought I would just fix it up and sell it,'' Nievera said, adding
that the house was built in 1957 as a retirement home for its
previous owner, a librarian.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it sat in the front half of a 25-by-100-foot lot
that was a blank horticultural slate. There was nary a shrub,
Nievera recalled. He threw himself into basic improvements.
``Robert was still living in New York, and he would not move in
without air-conditioning,'' he said. Nor was Janjigian thrilled
with the kitchen's worn Formica countertops and outmoded
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Nievera changed the windows, too, replacing most with
aluminum-frame French doors that opened the house's 1,200 square
feet to the surrounding gardens, a space-enhancement underscored by
new Italian-tile floors whose worn-white color blends with the
outdoor gravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've made even $20,000 worth of improvements,''
Nievera said. Indeed, like his partner, Nievera is a devotee of
cheap chic. ``Those came from Pier 1,'' he said, pointing out the
galvanized tin lanterns that punctuate the corners of the thin
white swimming pool out back.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   White chaise lounges, vintage Knoll, were castoffs from a
landscape client, and the cedar-walled outdoor shower was built
from a kit ordered from Walpole Woodworkers in Maine. Thanks to the
no-winter climate, ``we have yet to use the shower inside the
house,'' Nievera said.
</P>
<P>
   When the house had been upgraded, he gratefully handed over the
decorating reins to Janjigian, who was formerly an editor at
Rizzoli and wrote a book about yacht interiors. Still, Nievera was
momentarily worried. Living in a small house requires a certain
amount of restraint, and ``Robert has a tendency to overcollect,''
he said. ``We have a garage sale twice a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Janjigian, whose black-frame glasses and firm jaw give him a
Cary Grant-like suavity, laughed. ``OK, so I'm a scavenger,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his primary sites for shopping is the nearby town of Lake
Worth, where stylish vintage furniture often goes for prices that
make out-of-town friends jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was $300,'' he said of one of his Lake Worth finds, a
1940s chest, its sides paved with smoked mirror (it opens to reveal
cocktail equipment). A pair of sleek Danish Modern chairs from the
1960s cost $30 from the Goodwill thrift shop in West Palm. The big
square ottoman in the combination guest room and office was rescued
from a Manhattan sidewalk and snappily recovered in white patent
leather.
</P>
<P>
   As for the artwork, it is a motley array, ranging from two dozen
Russel Wright wall clocks in the kitchen _ one for every hour of
the day, said Janjigian, who bought them on eBay _ to three
hypnotic photographs of rippling blue water snapped by the makeup
maven Evelyn Lauder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried a million things up there,'' Janjigian said of a long
narrow bit of wall above a built-in shelving unit that his partner
designed for the dining area. After a while, he settled on a bad
1960s painting of skyscrapers, as seen from the Statue of Liberty.
``Of course, it would be ideal to have a Rothko,'' he said with a
grin. ``But we're not quite there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he wanted to respect its architecture, Janjigian also
wanted to avoid transforming the house into a picture-perfect paean
to mid-century modernism. ``And I didn't want to get too fussy,''
he said. ``When you have a small space, you have to pick things
that don't fill it up.'' Which explains why the furnishings are few
but juxtaposed with spirit, creating uncomplicated but visually
stimulating roomscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The chaise lounge in the living area is classic Le Corbusier,
but the exuberant gilt sconce hanging nearby is pure Palm Beach
baroque, circa 1962. A bedspread printed with big tropical leaves
gives a Heywood-Wakefield side table a funky South Beach look. And
even though the couple try to keep Palm Beach at a distance in
their private life, a bit of it remains in view: A little
Torquemada-style carved wood stool that once graced mansions across
the bay. ``Yeah, it's Mizner,'' Janjigian admitted, adding added,
diplomatically: ``I mean, I had to buy it. After all, we do live
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Budget-conscious tastemakers favor consignment and secondhand
shops on South County Road in Palm Beach and Lake Avenue and Dixie
Highway in Lake Worth filled with ``very 1940s and 1950s glamorous
kinds of stuff, things you know once lived in a great house, with
people with style,'' said Mish Tworkowski, a Manhattan jeweler and
Sotheby's expert _ like red metal chandeliers in the shape of coral
branches and fiercely button-tufted sofas a la Syrie Maugham. Margo
de Peyster, a leader of Palm Beach's young social set, recommended
the Church Mouse thrift shop at 374 S. County Rd. in Palm Beach,
(561) 659-2154. Other excellent sources are the Goodwill shop (561)
832-8893 and the dealer Peter Werner (561) 832-0428.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
