<SLUG> BC-NUTSANDBOLTS0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to restain a stained deck
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ D.D. sent an e-mail message saying his 4-year-old
deck originally was sealed with a semi-transparent brown finish,
then resealed two years ago with a semi-transparent redwood finish.
He doesn't like the redwood finish and now wants to refinish the
deck to match a nearby fence that was coated with a solid stain in
a light color called pecan tan. He wanted to know if he can use the
light-colored solid stain over the old redwood finish. He also
wanted to know how to clean the deck without harming nearby foliage
with deck-cleaning chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suggestion: I talked to L.J. Murphy of Centerville Deck
Services and Rick Weese of Deck and Fence Renewal Systems, also in
Centerville, and the short answer is that you can use a solid-color
stain on a deck that was previously treated with a semi-transparent
stain and get good coverage. But there are a few other issues you
need to be aware of. Before you use the solid-color stain, you must
be sure that the old sealer has stopped repelling water. Wait until
the deck is completely dry _ no rain for at least two days _ and
splash some water on the deck in various spots, including spots
that get little foot traffic. If the water quickly soaks in,
darkening the wood where it lands, the deck is ready for resealing.
If the water just beads up, you're better off waiting until next
year to do the solid stain.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to proceed, clean the deck before staining. The
concern about damaging plants near the deck with cleaning chemicals
is a legitimate one. Avoid products with bleach. Look on the label,
usually in the ``Warning'' label area, for the ingredient sodium
hypochlorite; this is bleach. Some products say ``no bleach'' on
the label, but they don't list their active ingredients. Powdered
cleaners that mix with water, such as Wolman's Deck and Fence
Brightener, are a good choice for cleaning decks. The cleaning
solution has a foaming action and is less toxic to plants than
bleach. Wolman's is hard to find, but Sears Hardware stores and
Meijer usually have it. Whatever deck wash you use, follow the
directions on the container. Use a garden hose to soak the plants
surrounding the deck before cleaning; this will dilute any cleaner
that gets on the plants. And clean the deck on a day with little
wind.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaning process will remove any dirt from the deck, and it
will also remove much of the remains of the semi-transparent stain
you applied two years ago. Wait at least two days after cleaning to
apply the new stain. A solid-color stain colors like a paint, but,
unlike a paint, it sinks into the surface of the wood. Because the
color is solid, it will completely cover any previous color.
</P>
<P>
   Before staining, you might want to test the stain in an
inconspicuous spot to see the effect it has on the wood. Once a
stain is in place, it's difficult or impossible to remove it
without sanding away the top layers of the boards or replacing
boards altogether. A solid-color stain should last four or five
years on upright deck posts, but it will wear out on the floor
boards in about two years. You should reseal when the floorboards
show obvious signs of wear. In the future, you should use the same
color stain or a darker stain. It's hard to cover a dark
solid-color stain with a lighter one.
</P>
<P>
   VENT DRYER OUTDOORS IF AT ALL POSSIBLE
</P>
<P>
   P.D. has a clothes dryer in her basement, and she has used it
for years without a vent attached to the hot-air outlet at the back
of the dryer. She said the nearest obvious spot where the vent
could be placed is a window 12 to 15 feet from the dryer. She can't
move the dryer under the window because that would take it too far
from its heavy-duty plug. That would also make transferring clothes
from the washer to the dryer difficult. Can a vent pipe be run from
the dryer to the window?
</P>
<P>
   _ Suggestion: The first thing P.D. should do is check her
laundry room, especially the area behind the dryer, for accumulated
lint and clean up any she finds. Lint is flammable, and one thing a
vent pipe does is carry the potential fire fuel away from the heat
of the dryer. The other thing a vent pipe does is take heat and
moisture outside the house, and that is critical in hot months.
</P>
<P>
   Both a product technician from Frigidaire, the manufacturer of
P.D.'s dryer, and Bill Davidson, vice president of Authorized
Service in Dayton, said a vent pipe connecting the dryer to the
window across the room should work fine. The owner's manual that
comes with each type of dryer will give specific directions for
venting, but most of them are similar. Davidson said the maximum
length for an exhaust pipe for a standard home dryer is about 50
feet, and each bend in the pipe counts as 8 feet. In other words, a
pipe with no bends can run 50 feet, but a pipe that has two bends
in it can only run about 34 feet. The whole assembly to vent the
dryer in question _ flexible aluminum pipe, fasteners, connectors,
the vent itself and a piece of plywood to replace a basement window
pane _ should cost less than $50.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where there is no outlet for the dryer, use a
bucket-type vent-trap kit, which sells at home-improvement stores
for about $9. With a vent trap, a piece of flexible vent hose is
connected to the top of a small plastic container with water at the
bottom. Hot air from the dryer blows into the container, and the
lint is caught in the water to prevent a fire hazard. Water in the
trap has to be changed regularly, and the trap does nothing to cut
down on the heat and humidity the dryer will pump into your living
space all summer. On a related topic, home-improvement stores also
sell inexpensive diverter boxes that can be spliced into the middle
of flexible vent pipes so some of the dryer's heat and moisture
stay indoors in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
