u w BC-COURT-SCOUTS-HNS &LR;      06-28 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SCOUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT SAYS BOY SCOUTS MAY EXCLUDE GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Boy Scouts of America may prevent homosexuals
from becoming troop leaders, a sharply divided Supreme Court said
Wednesday, ruling that the Scouts are a private organization and as
such have a right to exclude people who don't share their values.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision, the court also said that forcing the Boy
Scouts to accept openly gay troop leaders would violate the group's
First Amendment right to free association.
</P>
<P>
   While the court did not address the ramifications of its ruling,
some lawyers said it may allow the 6.2-million-member organization
to bar homosexual boys from membership.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, writing for the court, noted
that the organization ``asserts that homosexual conduct is
inconsistent with the values it seeks to instill.'' He added that
the state of New Jersey's effort to require it to accept a gay
scoutmaster ``would significantly burden the organization's right
to oppose or disfavor homosexual conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's opinion was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting, Justice John Paul Stevens argued that the New Jersey
law could not ``burden'' the Scouts' message because the group has
no specific ban on homosexuality in its literature, only references
to being ``morally straight'' and ``clean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To assert the right to association, the organization must at
least show it has adopted and advocated an unequivocal position
inconsistent with a position advocated by the person whom the
organization seeks to exclude,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' dissent was joined by Justices David H. Souter, Ruth
Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Roy L. Williams, who heads the Boy Scouts of America, said the
court's decision will allow his group to continue its ``mission of
providing character-building experiences for young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added, ``The Boy Scouts of America, as a private
organization, must have the right to establish its own standards of
membership if it is to continue to instill the values of the Scout
Oath and Law in boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Other supporters of the decision hailed it as a victory for
private organizations that want to run their groups without
government interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision will have a dramatic impact on all private
organizations _ including religious groups _ to define their own
mission and set their own criteria for leadership,'' said Vincent
P. McCarthy, senior counsel for the American Center for Law and
Justice here, a conservative group that filed a friend-of-the-court
brief for the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   But James Dale, the New Jersey assistant scoutmaster ousted when
the organization learned he is gay, said he was ``definitely
saddened by the decision. People don't join the Boy Scouts because
they're anti-gay. People join the Boy Scouts because they want
acceptance, they want community.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale's lawyer, Evan Wolfson, said he thinks the high court
ruling ``suggests that homosexual boys may be barred from becoming
Scouts. ``They won the right to declare themselves an anti-gay
group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   University of Southern California law professor Erwin
</P>
<P>
   Chemerinsky agreed, saying, ``I don't see any basis for drawing
a
</P>
<P>
   distinction between Scout leaders and Scouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Varona, legal director of the Human Rights Campaign, the
nation's largest gay rights group, said, ``We are gravely
disappointed with a ruling that gives the Boy Scouts of America the
ability to discriminate with impunity. Is this any way to teach
youth about fairness, honesty and justice?''
</P>
<P>
   The case began in 1989 when Dale, then 19, applied to be an
adult Scout leader of a troop in Matawan, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he had been an exemplary Boy Scout and had earned the
Eagle Scout Badge _ Scouting's highest award _ when he was a member
of a troop in Middletown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   His application for a leadership role was accepted, and he
served 16 months as an assistant scoutmaster for the Matawan troop.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was attending Rutgers University, where he was
co-president of the university's Lesbian/Gay Alliance. In July 1990
he acknowledged his homosexuality in a speech dealing with the
needs of lesbian and gay teenagers. The speech was reported in a
local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Later that month, the Boy Scouts sent him a letter severing
their relationship with him. When he sought an explanation, the
Scouts replied that his acknowledged homosexuality was ``contrary
to the values of the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Dale sued the Scouts for reinstatement under a New
Jersey law that forbids discrimination in ``public accommodations''
on the basis of race, gender, religion or sexual orientation. Dale
claimed that the Boy Scouts of America, which often works with
schools and other government institutions and has chapters in every
state, is a public accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   A state trial court, however, ruled that it is not and that
forcing the group to accept a gay scout leader would be
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Dale appealed the decision and last year, the New Jersey Supreme
Court ruled that the Boy Scouts organization is a ``public
accommodation,'' to which the state law applies.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the New Jersey
appellate decision. It added that since the Scouts are a private
organization, the state may not ``interfere'' with its message to
its members.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice emphasized, however, that the court's decision
was ``not guided by its view of whether the Boy Scouts' teachings
with respect to homosexual conduct are right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomas Baker, a law professor at Drake University
in Des Moines, Iowa, the court was forced to choose between two
competing constitutional issues _ fighting discrimination and
preserving the right of groups to choose their own members.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the court decided this case was not about gay
rights but about free association,'' Baker said. ``The decision
definitely will put some limits on how far courts can go in forcing
private groups to open their admissions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
