 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, June 29. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST (Jerusalem) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright failed Wednesday to win Palestinian agreement for a
U.S.-Israeli-PLO summit which Washington hopes will lead to a peace
treaty by a September target date. Palestinian officials said a
decision on whether to hold a summit sought by Israel and hosted by
the United States must await the outcome of further
Israeli-Palestinian talks in Washington after U.S. Independence Day
on July 4. (Summary from wires) By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-POLITICS (Kampala) _ Once there were few places in Africa
as grim as Uganda; now there are few as hopeful. And the man who
claims the credit is campaigning hard for voters to reward him on
Thursday in perhaps an odd way: He wants them to admit that Uganda
is still backward and not yet ready to open up to political
parties. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT9,10,11, sent June 27.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday
by a 5-4 vote that because the procedure widely known as ``partial
birth abortion'' may be the most medically appropriate way of
terminating some pregnancies, the government cannot prohibit
doctors from performing it. The decision declared unconstitutional
the Nebraska law before the court, as well as, in effect, the laws
of 30 other states. In addition, the bill to create a federal ban
on the procedure, which President Clinton has vetoed twice and
which may reach his desk again this year, would also be
unconstitutional under the court's analysis: Like all the other
laws, it does not contain an exception for the health of the
pregnant woman. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAY-SCOUTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday by a 5-4 vote that the Boy Scouts have a constitutional
right to exclude gay members because opposition to homosexuality
was part of the organization's ``expressive message.'' Writing for
the court Wednesday, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said the
court intended neither to approve nor disapprove the Boy Scouts'
views on the subject, but that the First Amendment's protection for
freedom of association meant that the state could not compel the
Boy Scouts ``to accept members where such acceptance would derogate
from the organization's expressive message.'' By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SCHOOLS (Washington) _ Taxpayer money can be used to buy
computers and other instructional materials for religious schools,
the Supreme Court ruled Wednesday as it lowered the figurative wall
of separation between church and state. The 6-3 ruling should speed
federal efforts to connect every American classroom to the
Internet. The decision also is sure to be cited as a big victory
for proponents of using public money for tuition aid to families
who send their children to religious schools. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-MEDICARE (Washington) _ The House is expected to pass a
bill offering prescription drug benefits to 39 million elderly and
disabled people on Medicare, but only after Democrats walked off
the floor of the House to express their frustration at being unable
to get a full debate on a proposal to establish much more extensive
drug coverage. Developing. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Congress moved decisively
Wednesday toward enacting the first major change in the nation's
campaign finance law since 1979, closing a loophole through which
millions of dollars have secretly flowed. President Clinton
strongly supports the bill. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline to kum) _ Ledeall: Elian Gonzalez, after the
Supreme Court rejected the last legal challenge, is returning to
Cuba. Developing. With feeds from Lizette Alvarez in Washington and
David Gonzalez in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
