<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton turned an hourlong news
conference Wednesday into an effort to both bolster Vice President
Gore's campaign and to defend him from charges of campaign finance
irregularities, saying Gore made ``a compelling case'' that he did
nothing wrong and arguing that the ``so called scandals'' of the
past eight years ``were bogus.'' In a wide-ranging discussion that
ran the gamut from rising gasoline prices to the death penalty to
missile defense and how much brain power it takes to handle the
challenges of the presidency, Clinton invoked Gore's name more than
20 times. By Marc Lacey and David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
