(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following book excerpt must be purchased to
be published. For purchase information, see end of text.)  
 LOOK BEFORE YOU LEAP: HOW TO SURVIVE A JUMP INTO WATER FROM A
BRIDGE OR CLIFF 
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Harrison Ford did it in ``The Fugitive.'' So did
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid. OK, unless you're a movie hero,
you'll probably never be forced to leap from a cliff or bridge into
water. But, hey, you never know. And if you should one day find
yourself perched on the edge, with nowhere else to go, wouldn't you
like to be prepared? The following excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE
SCENARIO SURVIVAL Handbook'' offers tips that can raise your
chances of surviving such a leap.)  
 (Includes B&AMP;W illustration of a man jumping into water. CREDIT:
ILLUSTRATION BY BRENDA BROWN.) 
 By JOSHUA PIVEN and DAVID BORGENICHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When attempting a high fall (more than 20 feet) into water in an
emergency situation, you will not know much about your
surroundings, specifically the depth of the water. This makes
jumping particularly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   If you must jump from a bridge into a river or other body of
water with boat traffic, try to land in the channel _ the
deep-water area where boats go under the bridge. This area is
generally in the center, away from the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Stay away from any area with pylons that are supporting the
bridge. Debris can collect in these areas and you can hit it when
you enter the water.
</P>
<P>
   Swim to shore immediately after surfacing.
 &UR; HOW TO JUMP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Jump feet first.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your body completely vertical.
</P>
<P>
   _ Squeeze your feet together.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enter the water feet first, and clench your buttocks together.
If you do not, water may rush in and cause severe internal damage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Protect your crotch area by covering it with your hands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Immediately after you hit the water, spread your arms and legs
wide and move them back and forth to generate resistance, which
will slow your plunge to the bottom. Always assume the water is not
deep enough to keep you from hitting bottom.
 &UR; REMAIN AWARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hitting the water as described above could save your life,
although it may break your legs.
</P>
<P>
   _ If your body is not straight, you can break your back upon
entry. Keep yourself vertical until you hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not even think about going in headfirst unless you are
absolutely sure that the water is at least 20 feet deep. If your
legs hit the bottom, they will break. If your head hits, your skull
will break.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The publisher and authors of ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival
Handbook'' disclaim any liability from any injury that may result
from the use, proper or improper, of the information contained in
this excerpt. All the information in this excerpt comes directly
from experts in the situation at hand, but we do not guarantee that
the information is complete, safe or accurate, nor should it be
considered a substitute for your good judgment and common sense.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
