<HEADLINE>
(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following book excerpt must be purchased to
be published. For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 THEY SHOOT HORSES, DON'T THEY? WHAT TO DO IF YOU BREAK YOUR LEG 
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: OK, Weekend Warrior. Summer is here, and that means
it's time to be out playing basketball, softball, tennis, soccer or
whatever sport you're into this year. It also means your chances of
getting injured are pretty good. What if you _ or one of your
buddies _ breaks a leg while sliding into first or trying to jump
over the net? Be prepared. This excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE
SCENARIO Survival Guide'' explains what to do _ and what not to do
_ to treat a leg fracture.)  
 (Includes B&AMP;W illustration of an injured leg being tied onto a
splint. CREDIT: ILLUSTRATION BY BRENDA BROWN.) 
 By JOSHUA PIVEN and DAVID BORGENICHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most leg injuries are only sprains, but the treatment for both
sprains and fractures is the same.
 &UR; SYMPTOMS OF A FRACTURE, SPRAIN OR DISLOCATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Difficult or limited movement
</P>
<P>
   _ Swelling of the affected area
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruising
</P>
<P>
   _ Numbness
</P>
<P>
   _ Severe bleeding
</P>
<P>
   _ A visible break of bone through the skin
 &UR; HOW TO TREAT A LEG FRACTURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ If skin is broken, do not touch or put anything on the wound.
You must avoid infection. If the wound is bleeding severely, try to
stop the flow of blood by applying steady pressure to the affected
area with sterile bandages or clean clothes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not move the injured leg _ you need to splint the wound to
stabilize the injured area. Find two stiff objects of the same
length _ wood, plastic or folded cardboard _ for the splints.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put the splints above and below the injured area _ under the
leg (or on the side if moving the leg is too painful).
</P>
<P>
   _ Tie the splints with string, rope or belts _ whatever is
available. Alternatively, use clothing torn into strips. Make sure
the splint extends beyond the injured area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not tie the splints too tightly; this may cut off
circulation. You should be able to slip a finger under the rope or
fabric. If the splinted area becomes pale or white, loosen the
ties.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have the injured person lie flat on his or her back. This
helps blood continue to circulate and many prevent shock.
 &UR; WHAT TO AVOID &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not push at, probe or attempt to clean an injury; this can
cause infection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not move the injured person unless absolutely necessary.
Treat the fracture and then go get help.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the person must be moved, be sure the injury is completely
immobilized first.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not elevate the injured leg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not attempt to move or reset a broken bone; this will cause
severe pain and may complicate the injury.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; The publisher and authors of ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival
Handbook'' disclaim any liability from any injury that my result
from the use, proper or improper, of the information contained in
this excerpt. All the information in this excerpt comes directly
from experts in the situation at hand, but we do not guarantee that
the information is complete, safe or accurate, nor should it be
considered a substitute for your good judgment and common sense. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Books &QL; 
 &UR; Reprinted from ``The Worst Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' by
Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this ``separate-buy'' book excerpt contact New York
Times Syndicate salesperson DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697. Or e-mail her at: weyded &LR; nytimes.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
