<HEADLINE>
(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following book excerpt must be purchased to
be published. For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 CAN IT STRIKE TWICE? WHY YOU SHOULD WATCH OUT FOR LIGHTNING 
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Summer is the season for thunderstorms _ complete
with dangerous lightning. Lightning causes more casualties annually
in the United States than any other storm-related phenomenon except
floods. No place is completely safe from lightning, but some are
more dangerous than others. This excerpt from ``The Worst-Case
Scenario Survival Handbook'' explains how to avoid being struck.) 
 (Includes B&AMP;W illustrations of a man kneeling on the ground and of
a man standing under a tree. CREDIT: ILLUSTRATIONS BY BRENDA
BROWN.) 
 By JOSHUA PIVEN and DAVID BORGENICHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lightning causes more casualties annually in the United States
than any other storm-related phenomenon except floods. No place is
completely safe from lightning. However, some places are more
dangerous than others.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to avoid being struck:
</P>
<P>
   _ Loud or frequent thunder indicates that lightning activity is
approaching. If you can see lightning and/or hear thunder, you are
at risk. High winds, rainfall and cloud cover often act as
precursors to actual cloud-to-ground strikes. Thunderstorms
generally move west to east and occur late in the day or in early
evening when humidity is highest.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you see lightning, count the number of seconds until
thunder is heard and then divide by five. This will indicate how
far the storm is from you in miles. If the time delay between
seeing the flash (lightning) and hearing the boom (thunder) is
fewer than 30 seconds, seek a safer location immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid high places, open fields and ridges above the
timberline. If in an open area, do not lie flat; kneel with your
hands on the ground and your head low.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid isolated trees, unprotected gazebos and rain or picnic
shelters, as well as shallow depressions in the earth. Current
traveling through the ground may use you to bridge the depression.
Also avoid baseball dugouts, communications towers, flagpoles,
light poles, metal and wood bleachers and metal fences. If you are
camping, avoid your tent if it is in an open area or under a large
tree.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay away from oceans, lakes, swimming pools, rivers and other
bodies of water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Large enclosed buildings tend to be much safer than smaller or
open structures. The risk for lightning injury depends on whether
the structure incorporates lightning protection, the construction
materials used and the size of the structure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fully enclosed metal vehicles such as cars, trucks, buses and
vans, with the windows rolled up, provide good shelter from
lightning. Avoid contact with metal or conducting surfaces outside
or inside the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   _ When inside, avoid contact with conductive surfaces with
exposure to the outside, including the sink, plumbing fixtures, and
metal door and window frames.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid outlets, electrical cords and wired electrical devices,
including telephones.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wait for the storm to pass. The lightning threat generally
diminishes with time after the last sound of thunder, but may
persist for more than 30 minutes. When thunderstorms are in the
area but not overhead, the lightning threat can exist even when it
is sunny, not raining, or when clear sky is visible.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; OPTIONAL SIDEBAR: HOW TO TREAT SOMEONE STRUCK BY LIGHTNING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Call 911 to report the strike and give directions to emergency
personnel. With immediate medical treatment, victims can survive an
encounter with lightning. If multiple people have been struck,
treat the apparently ``dead'' first. People who are unconscious but
still breathing will probably recover on their own.
</P>
<P>
   _ Move to a safer location to avoid getting struck yourself. It
is unusual for victims who survive a lightning strike to have major
fractures that would cause paralysis or major bleeding
complications unless they have suffered a fall or been thrown a
distance. Do not be afraid to move the victim rapidly if necessary;
individuals struck by lightning do not carry a charge and it is
safe to touch them to give medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ In cold and wet environments, put a protective layer between
the victim and the ground to decrease the chance of hypothermia,
which can further complicate resuscitation. Check for burns,
especially around jewelry and watches.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the victim is not breathing, start mouth-to mouth
resuscitation. Give one breath every 5 seconds. If moving the
victim, give a few quick breaths prior to moving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Determine if the victim has a pulse. Check the pulse at the
carotid artery (side of the neck) or femoral artery (groin) for at
least 20 to 30 seconds. If no pulse is detected, start cardiac
compressions. If the pulse returns, continue ventilation with
rescue breathing as needed for as long as practical in a wilderness
situation.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a pulse does not return after 20 to 30 minutes of good
effort, stop resuscitation efforts. In wilderness areas far from
medical care, prolonged basic CPR is of little use _ the victim is
unlikely to recover if they do not respond within the first few
minutes.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The publisher and authors of ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival
Handbook'' disclaim any liability from any injury that my result
from the use, proper or improper, of the information contained in
this excerpt. All the information in this excerpt comes directly
from experts in the situation at hand, but we do not guarantee that
the information is complete, safe or accurate, nor should it be
considered a substitute for your good judgment and common sense. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Books &QL; 
 &UR; Reprinted from ``The Worst Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' by
Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this ``separate-buy'' book excerpt contact New York
Times Syndicate salesperson DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697. Or e-mail her at: weyded &LR; nytimes.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
