<HEADLINE>
(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following book excerpt must be purchased to
be published. For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 CAUGHT IN A `TITANIC' SITUATION? HOW TO SURVIVE ADRIFT AT SEA 
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: It happened to Elian Gonzalez, and it could happen
to you. You're far from shore when suddenly the boat you are in
capsizes and sinks _ and you find yourself adrift at sea. How do
you stay alive? This excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO
Survival Handbook'' offers tips that can help you save yourself.) 
 (Includes B&AMP;W illustration of objects that can be used to signal
for help. CREDIT: ILLLUSTRATION BY BRENDA BROWN.) 
 By JOSHUA PIVEN and DAVID BORGENICHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Stay aboard your boat as long as possible before you get into
a life raft. In a maritime emergency, the rule of thumb is that you
should step up into your raft, meaning you should be up to your
waist in water before you get into the raft.
</P>
<P>
   Your best chance of survival is on a boat _ even a disabled one
_ not on a life raft. But if the boat is sinking, know how to use a
life raft.
</P>
<P>
   Any craft that sails in open water (a boat larger than 14 feet)
should have at least one life raft. Smaller boats may only have
life jackets, so these vessels should stay within easy swimming
distance of land.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the boat is sinking, get in the life raft _ and take
whatever supplies you can carry. Most importantly, take fresh
water. Do not drink seawater. A person can last for several days
without food at sea, but without clean water to drink, death is a
virtual certainty within several days.
</P>
<P>
   Many canned foods, particularly vegetables, are packed in water,
so take those with you if you can. Do not ration water; drink it as
needed _ but don't drink more than is necessary. A half-gallon a
day should be sufficient if you limit your activity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prolonged exposure to saltwater can damage your skin and cause
lesions, which are prone to infection. Stay covered. Modern life
rafts have canopies, which protect passengers from sun, wind and
rain. If the canopy is missing or damaged, wear a hat, long sleeves
and pants to protect yourself from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find food, if you can. Life rafts include fishing hooks in
their survival kit. If no hook is available you can fashion one
using wire or even shards of aluminum from an empty can.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to get to land, if you know where it is. Most rafts
include small paddles, but life rafts are not very maneuverable,
especially in any wind above 3 knots. Do not exhaust yourself _ you
won't be able to move any significant distance without great
effort.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you see a plane or boat nearby, try to signal it. Use a VHF
radio or a handheld flare kit. A small mirror can also be used for
signaling.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; OPTIONAL SIDEBAR: HOW TO PREPARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never go out on a boat unprepared. Most boats should have at
least one type of emergency signaling device, which is called an
Emergency Position Radio Beacon, or EPiRB. These devices send out
global marine distress signals and come in two forms: 406 MHz and
125 MHz. Both will send your boat identification and position, but
the 406 goes to other ships, passing airplanes and satellites,
while the 125 only goes to ships and planes. People without one of
these devices can drift for months before they are found.
</P>
<P>
   Always carry a ``go bag'' that contains:
</P>
<P>
   _ Warm, dry clothes and blanket
</P>
<P>
   _ A hat
</P>
<P>
   _ Food (canned goods, backpacking foods, dried fruit)
</P>
<P>
   _ A handheld VHF radio
</P>
<P>
   _ A small, handheld GPS (Global Positioning Satellite) tracking
unit
</P>
<P>
   _ Drinking water in portable jugs
</P>
<P>
   _ A compass
</P>
<P>
   _ A flashlight with extra batteries
</P>
<P>
   _ Handheld flares
</P>
<P>
   _ A handheld watermaker
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; The publisher and authors of ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival
Handbook'' disclaim any liability from any injury that may result
from the use, proper or improper, of the information contained in
this excerpt. All the information in this excerpt comes directly
from experts in the situation at hand, but we do not guarantee that
the information is complete, safe or accurate, nor should it be
considered a substitute for your good judgment and common sense. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Books &QL; 
 &UR; Reprinted from ``The Worst Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' by
Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this ``separate-buy'' book excerpt contact New York
Times Syndicate salesperson DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697. Or e-mail her at: weyded &LR; nytimes.com.) &QL;
</P>
