<HEADLINE>
(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following book excerpt must be purchased to
be published. For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 DIDN'T ENJOY `JAWS'? HERE'S HOW TO FEND OFF A SHARK 
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: The movie ``Jaws'' made scores of beach-goers
afraid to dip even a big toe into the water. If you're among the
leery, you'll want to read this guide to avoiding sharks _ and what
to do if you are attacked. Even if you're not afraid, you may want
to take a peek at this excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO
Survival Handbook'' before diving into the waves _ because, hey,
you just never know.)  
 (Includes B&AMP;W illustration of a shark. CREDIT: ILLUSTRATION BY
BRENDA BROWN.) 
 By JOSHUA PIVEN and DAVID BORGENICHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most shark attacks occur in waters near the shore, typically
inshore of a sandbar or between sandbars where sharks feed and can
become trapped at low tide. Areas with steep drop-offs are also
likely attack sites. Sharks congregate in these areas, because
their natural prey congregates there.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any large shark, roughly 6 feet or longer, is a potential
threat to humans. But three species in particular have repeatedly
attacked man: the white shark, the tiger shark and the bull shark.
All are cosmopolitan in distribution, reach large sizes and
regularly consume large prey such as marine mammals, sea turtles
and fish.
 &UR; HOW TO AVOlD AN ATTACK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Always stay in groups. Sharks are more likely to attack an
individual.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't wander too far from shore. This isolates you and creates
the additional danger of being too far from assistance. Avoid being
in the water during darkness or twilight hours, when sharks are
most active and have a competitive sensory advantage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't enter the water if you are bleeding from an open wound
or if you are menstruating. A shark is drawn to blood and its sense
of smell is acute.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try not to wear shiny jewelry, because the reflected light
resembles the sheen of fish scales.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid waters being used by sport or commercial fishermen,
especially if there are signs of bait fish or feeding activity.
Diving seabirds are good indicators of such activity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use extra caution when waters are murky, and avoid showing
uneven tan lines or wearing brightly colored clothing. Sharks see
contrast particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a shark shows itself to you, it may be curious rather than
predatory and will probably swim on and leave you alone. If you are
under the surface and lucky enough to see an attacking shark, you
have a good chance of defending yourself if the shark is not too
large.
 &UR; WHAT TO DO IF YOU ARE ATTACKED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hit back. If a shark attacks you, use anything you have in
your possession _ a camera, probe, your fist _ to hit the shark's
eyes or gills, which are the areas most sensitive to pain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make quick, sharp, repeated jabs in these areas. Sharks are
predators and will usually only follow through on an attack if they
have the advantage, so making the shark unsure of its advantage in
any way possible will increase your chances of survival. Contrary
to popular opinion, the shark's nose is not the area to attack,
unless you cannot reach the eyes or gills.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; OPTIONAL SIDEBAR: THREE KINDS OF SHARK ATTACKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``HIT AND RUN'' &LR;  attacks are by far the most common. These
typically occur in the surf zone, where swimmers and surfers are
the targets. The victim seldom sees its attacker, and the shark
does not return after inflicting a single bite or slash wound.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``BUMP AND BITE'' &LR;  attacks are characterized by the shark
initially circling and often bumping the victim prior to the actual
attack. These types of attacks usually involve divers or swimmers
in deeper waters, but also occur in near shore shallows in some
areas of the world.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``SNEAK'' &LR;  attacks differ: The strike can occur without
warning. With both ``bump and bite'' and ``sneak'' attacks, repeat
attacks are common and multiple and sustained bites are the norm.
Injuries incurred during this type of attack are usually quite
severe, frequently resulting in death
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The publisher and authors of ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival
Handbook'' disclaim any liability from any injury that may result
from the use, proper or improper, of the information contained in
this excerpt. All the information in this excerpt comes directly
from experts in the situation at hand, but we do not guarantee that
the information is complete, safe or accurate, nor should it be
considered a substitute for your good judgment and common sense. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Books &QL; 
 &UR; Reprinted from ``The Worst Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' by
Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this ``separate-buy'' book excerpt contact New York
Times Syndicate salesperson DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697. Or e-mail her at: weyded &LR; nytimes.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
