<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0629-COX     06-28 1793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Low-flying 527s shot down
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate have acted on the notion that those
newly popular but secretive groups known as 527s should be forced
to say who is paying for their TV spots and other political
activities. The House voted 385-39 early today to require
disclosure of groups that organize under section 527 of the tax
code, which allows nonprofit groups to run campaign-style ads as
long as they don't directly advocate the election or defeat of any
candidate. The Senate passed a similar measure earlier this month,
and the two chambers now must work out the differences
</P>
<P>
   THESE DONORS AREN'T 527S
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush knows how to throw a breakfast. By offering
scrambled eggs at the River Club overlooking the East River in
Manhattan, he was able to extract $3 million from about 55 donors
for the Republican National Committee. Neither the campaign nor the
committee would identify any of the people at the event. The
location was kept secret from reporters until the event was over.
Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said private events were, well,
private. This also applied to a lunch for Bush in Cleveland today,
where each couple paid $25,000 and the RNC raised about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   TO ENABLE THE DISABLED
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush proposed today $145 million in federal spending
to help local governments and community groups make it easier for
people with disabilities to find jobs and travel to them. ``It's
one thing to have technologies to help people help themselves,'' he
said at Vocational Guidance Services in Cleveland, a nonprofit
organization that helps disabled people find work. ``But sometimes
people have trouble getting from one place to the other.'' Bush
said his proposal would better enable the disabled to live
independently and hold jobs.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKS FOR `GREEN' DRIVING AND LIVING
</P>
<P>
   Consumers would get tax credits of up to $6,000 for buying
electric cars and $2,000 for energy-efficient new homes under a
campaign proposal today by Al Gore. He outlined his proposals,
which would cost more than $48 billion over 10 years, at a home in
Columbus, Ohio, featuring the newest energy-saving technologies.
``The best innovations are of little use if they are stuck in a lab
_ unaffordable and unattainable to you, your family or your
business,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   WITH A SMILE AND A HANDSHAKE AND A SHINE ON HIS SHOES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush accused Al Gore today of coddling big oil
companies by proposing that deep-water drillers continue to get a
break on fees despite soaring fuel prices. Gore, who often
criticizes Bush as a friend of big oil, had called for an extension
of the royalty moratorium as part of his 10-year plan for nurturing
new energy technologies. A day earlier in Michigan, Bush said that
as president he would bring down gasoline prices through sheer
force of personality, by creating enough political good will with
oil-producing nations that they would increase their supply of
crude: ``I would work with our friends in OPEC to convince them to
open up the spigot, to increase the supply.''
</P>
<P>
   A GORE WARNING TO WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said the ``razor-thin'' majority in today's Supreme
Court decision affirming abortion rights shows what is at stake for
women in the presidential election. Gore pointed to the 5-4
decision, noted that his opponent, George W. Bush, opposes abortion
rights _ with a reminder: ``Now here's the point: The next
president will nominate at least three and probably four _ perhaps
four _ justices to the Supreme Court. One extra vote on the wrong
side of those two issues would change the outcome and a woman's
right to choose would be taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTARIAN CONVENTION GOING LIVE
</P>
<P>
   Some 14,000 delegates from all 50 states are expected at the
Libertarian National Convention this weekend in Anaheim, Calif.
C-SPAN will cover it live, beginning at noon both Saturday and
Sunday. Saturday night's coverage includes a presidential debate
with candidates Harry Browne, Dave Hollist, Don Gorman and Barry
Hess. The convention's opening remarks will be delivered by
nationally syndicated radio talk show host Neil Boortz.
</P>
<P>
   INCUMBENT GOES DOWN IN UTAH
</P>
<P>
   Dogged by accusations about his temper and alleged delusional
behavior, Utah Rep. Merrill Cook lost his bid for a third House
term. He's just the second incumbent _ and first Republican _ to
lose in a primary this year. Political newcomer Derek Smith, a
computer company founder, easily won the primary. Smith faces
Democrat Jim Matheson in November. The only other incumbent to lose
in a primary this year was nine-term Democratic Rep. Matthew
Martinez of California.
</P>
<P>
   AGGRIEVED WIFE TRIUMPHS
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, two-term Republican state Rep. Shirley Hinson
captured 52 percent of the vote to win a bitter race against her
estranged husband, retired school principal Jimmy Hinson. She has
no Democratic opposition in November. The race was steeped in the
details of the Hinsons' troubled marriage, including allegations of
death threats and infidelity. In the race for retiring GOP Rep.
Mark Sanford's House seat, state Rep. Henry Brown beat former state
Transportation Chairman H.B. ``Buck'' Limehouse for the right to
face Democrat Andy Brack.
</P>
<P>
   PEROT _ YES, HE'S STILL AROUND
</P>
<P>
   Salon, the online magazine, reports that ``allies''of Reform
Party candidate Pat Buchanan ``were scrambling amid growing
speculation'' that party founder Ross Perot, who just turned 70,
would allow his name to be entered as a candidate for the party's
presidential nomination just before the deadline this Saturday.
Perot spokeswoman Donna Donovan said an announcement would be
coming soon, and ``the Buchanans are right to be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   EXCEPTION TAKEN TO SPOKESMAN'S SPEAKING
</P>
<P>
   Top Republicans criticized Al Gore's campaign spokesman for
comparing a GOP senator's decision to release Justice Department
information about the vice president to ``McCarthyite tactics.''
George W. Bush said it appeared the aide, Chris Lehane, ``got a
little carried away,'' and Arlen Specter, the senator in question,
sent a terse letter to Gore seeking an explanation and ``prompt
apology.''
</P>
<P>
   STICKING WITH THE EMBARGO
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush rejected an effort by House Republicans to allow
American food into Cuba for the first time since the economic
embargo began four decades ago, saying that Fidel Castro might
block it from reaching those who need it. His comments came after
House Republicans _ who Bush said had ``good intentions'' _ cut a
deal to permit direct sales of U.S. food to Cuba as hard-line
anti-communists yielded to pressure from the farm and business
lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   THE LONG-TERM SOLUTION
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is offering what he hopes will be a balm to drivers
pinched by steep gas prices: a ``no new taxes, no new
bureaucracies'' energy policy that does nothing about today's
prices but aims to cut oil dependence in the long term. The 10-year
package Gore outlined centered on $75 billion in tax incentives for
the development and use of fuel-efficient and nonpolluting
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC CLOUT IN BIG STATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore leads George W. Bush by 22 points among Hispanic voters,
says a survey taken by Miami pollster Sergio Bendixen. But Bush is
running about even with Gore in the South, based largely on the
Republican sentiments of Cuban-Americans in Florida and the Texas
governor's appeal to Mexican-Americans in his home state. Hispanic
voters are more heavily concentrated in the four biggest states:
California (13 percent), Texas (20 percent), New York (9 percent)
and Florida (12 percent).
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING TO FEAR BUT _
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Hillary Clinton's intensified criticism in recent
weeks, Rick Lazio accused her of waging a campaign based on fear
and warned that her latest TV spots attacking his record would
backfire. ``I know what these attack ads are all about,'' Lazio
said in Manhattan. ``They're about fear.'' He added, ``If these
attacks continue, my opponent will learn this about New York: Bend
the truth, and you will face the consequences. New Yorkers will not
elect a person they cannot trust.'' Clinton had been criticizing
Lazio's votes in Congress and his positions on guns, abortion and
education financing.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE TWO AND HIT TO RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton has taken a lot of flack over her claim to be a
lifelong New York Yankee fan _ and now, even her past rooting for
her native state's Chicago Cubs is costing her. The New York Post
reports that Jerry Reinsdorf, owner of the White Sox _ Chicago's
other team _ will host a fund-raiser for Rick Lazio on Friday in
his Comiskey Park skybox _ a payback for Clinton's Cubs allegiance.
In case anyone's wondering, Lazio's a Mets fan.
</P>
<P>
   WAITING _ LIKE THE MAYTAG REPAIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   It's far from clear just how much of a role President Clinton
will get to play in coming months. Senior campaign strategists have
made known their desire to limit Clinton's public role at the
August convention, so as not to steal the spotlight from Al Gore.
But Clinton seems to be waiting for the phone to ring. He has even
cleared his official calendar for that entire week _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   PREPPING FOR THE CONFRONTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Some advance anxiety is on display in Philadelphia, five weeks
before the Republican convention, as organizers of a protest march
are saying that police are tracking their plans and photographing
them. Some groups have promised extensive protests and possible
civil disobedience, while police officials have promised to keep
the city orderly for the conventioneers. ``The Secret Service, the
FBI, the Justice Department and the Philadelphia police have all
videotaped our news conferences,'' said Mike Morrill, one of the
organizers of the Unity 2000 protest march planned for July 31, the
eve of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   CARVILLE KENTUCKY WINDAGE
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, the former campaign adviser and chief defender
of President Clinton, will be advising Kentucky Democrats on how to
regain the state Senate, according to the Lexington Herald-Leader.
Carville will be holding a seminar for Kentucky Democratic senators
and candidates at the party's state headquarters in what state
Democratic Chairman David Boswell called a ``one-day private
briefing and critique, and not a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
