<HEADER>
A7440 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-BOOKS-POTTER-SPI &LR;      06-28 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POTTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING DOWN FOR THE RELEASE OF THE NEW HARRY POTTER BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Security guards. Slumber parties. Lightning-bolts. Threats.
</P>
<P>
   They're all part of the fever building to July 8 when ``Harry
Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' the latest in the madly popular
Harry Potter series of children's books, goes on sale.
</P>
<P>
   In a mix of fun, hype and Windows 95-type marketing, bookstores
are holding midnight Potter parties and other celebrations to kick
off the latest in the young orphan's adventures at the Hogwarts
School of Witchcraft and Wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   To date, we've seen Harry freed from the beastly grip of his
Muggle (non-magical) relatives to discover friendships, final exams
in classes like ``Defense Against the Dark Arts,'' and nail-biting
battles between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the anticipation. I think it's great,'' said Christy
McDanold, owner of Secret Garden Bookshop in Seattle, which will
open at midnight July 7 to break out Book Four. ``I'm so glad that
kids are so excited about a book.''
</P>
<P>
   To get their shipments in time for H-Day, bookstore owners had
to sign affidavits pledging they wouldn't sell the book any earlier
than 12:01 a.m. July 8. Kiddie book publisher Scholastic Inc.
threatened to cut off future Potter shipments to anyone who sells
the book early.
</P>
<P>
   Security is so tight that online bookseller Amazon.com, which
already has the books in its warehouses, has hired extra guards to
protect them. And the limited number of employees selected to
package the books were told to divulge no details about the book to
co-workers and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a need-to-know, need-to-see basis,'' said Lyn Blake,
general manager of the Amazon.com bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   (If you really do need to know, though, check out the latest
tidbits at www.harrypotterfans.net, a comprehensive Potterania
source that learned and posted the title when it was still
officially top secret. The Webmaster promises that no major plot
spoilers will be posted.)
</P>
<P>
   The widespread anticipation _ not to mention the record-setting
3.8 million print run _ is an exponential jump from even the hotly
awaited third book by author J.K. Rowling, which was released last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The first three books were published in Britain first, then the
United States. Determined fans ordered foreign editions and diluted
the mass hunger for the books here. To even the playing field,
Scholastic decided to release Book Four on the same day in both
countries. It has been a best-seller even in pre-orders for the
past few months.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare for bookstores to have such a marquee release, one
whose appeal crosses generations and genres. Though technically a
children's fantasy, booksellers report legions of fans of all ages
and types.
</P>
<P>
   The first three books have hogged The New York Times best-seller
list so long _ rankling the literary lions of Serious Fiction _
that the paper announced plans last week to create a separate
children's best-seller list in anticipation of Book Four.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on whether they'll create a separate Harry Potter
best-seller list when all seven books planned for the series are
published.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of so many book sales has also fueled the feud
between independent booksellers and online giant Amazon, reaching
intense Gryffindor vs. Slytherin levels.
</P>
<P>
   The bookstores initially thought they had the edge in the Potter
Wars, saying they would be the first to provide Book Four to
customers, even if they couldn't match Amazon's 40 percent discount
off the book's hefty $25.95 cover price.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a move that infuriated several independents, Amazon
announced it had worked out deals with Scholastic and Federal
Express to get the book early enough to package its massive
pre-orders in envelopes that would be ready to go at 12:01 a.m.
July 8. Furthermore, it announced a free upgrade to same-day
Saturday deliveries for the first 250,000 books ordered, a goal it
reached earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's Blake won't say how much the free upgrades cost the
company, but she said the customer goodwill it has generated is
more than worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken all kinds of e-mail (saying) `You don't know what
this means to our family,''' she said. ``I'm also sure we're
getting new customers in by making this an easy-to-purchase book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
