<HEADER>
A7450 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     06-28 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV16-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 16, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I have to hang several new custom-made wood doors.
 &HT;    Previously, I have had trouble using a wood chisel to cut the
shallow mortises needed for installing the door hinges. My chisel
blade always seemed to dig in too deeply and sometimes split the
wood.
 &HT;    Can you offer some tips on the correct way to use a wood chisel
for shallow cuts?
 &HT;    A: The most important point to remember is that the chisel must
be very sharp, with a blade that is not nicked or otherwise
damaged.
 &HT;    Draw the outline of the mortise onto the edge of the door with a
sharp pencil then use the chisel to cut around this outline by
tapping it with a mallet to make vertical cuts down into the wood.
 &HT;    Start removing the wood inside this outline by forcing the
chisel in from the side (as shown in the illustration). You can
also do this by working from the center of the outline out toward
the cuts just made.
 &HT;    If possible, push the chisel by hand without using a mallet and
cut with the grain (so that the grain slopes up toward the cutting
end of the blade).
 &HT;    Hold the chisel with the bevel side down, not up, and remove
only a small layer at a time to avoid gouging.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: When I tried to replace the handle on my old sink faucet, the
screw that held the handle in place refused to budge.
 &HT;    I used a wrench on my screwdriver to apply added leverage, and
the end of the screw broke off, leaving only a short stub sticking
up.
 &HT;    What can I do to fix this without having to replace the entire
faucet?
 &HT;    A: Try applying a penetrating oil around the screw threads to
help free it up.
 &HT;    Wait a few minutes to let it penetrate and tap on the end of the
stub rapidly with the handle of your screwdriver. This will help
the oil penetrate further.
 &HT;    Wait 10 or 15 minutes, then firmly grip the stub that sticks up
with a Vise Grip or similar type of locking pliers and use this to
slowly unscrew and twist the rest of the screw out.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our house has steam heat with old fashioned cast iron steam
radiators.
 &HT;    The radiators in our dining room are covered with decorative
wood covers that were installed by the previous owner and we want
to do the same for the radiators in the living room and bedroom.
 &HT;    Do you know where we can buy them?
 &HT;    A: Depending on the area where you live, radiator covers are
sometimes sold by lumber yards and home centers, as well by dealers
who sell unfinished furniture.
 &HT;    However, if you cannot find a local dealer who carries them,
then you should be able to have them made to order by any
woodworking shop or cabinet manufacturer who makes custom cabinets.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The 100-year-old house we recently bought has a brick
foundation that was painted on the inside of the basement.
 &HT;    There is a white powder that seems to be working its way out
through the paint in many places where the paint has flaked off,
and there are even small layers of brick coming off in some spots.
 &HT;    What should we do about halting this damage and repairing the
brick?
 &HT;    A. The white powder you see is undoubtedly efflorescence, a
frequent problem on brick and masonry walls.
 &HT;    Although not a serious problem in most cases, this will depend
on how extensive the condition is.
 &HT;    I recommend calling in an experienced mason to examine the
foundation and determine just how extensive the damage really is _
and what repairs, if any, are needed.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``CUTTING A MORTISE'' goes with this
column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Chisel is used with bevel side down when making shallow
cuts to keep the blade from digging too deeply into the wood with
each pass.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
