u p BC-GORE-COURT-HNS &LR;      06-28 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COURT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE ATTACKS BUSH ON CHOICES FOR SUPREME COURT  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKLICK, Ohio _ Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday lambasted
Supreme Court justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas for their
opinions against abortion rights and claimed that George W. Bush
would use them as the ``model'' to fill any high court vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   The two justices were among dissenters in the 5-to-4 high court
decision striking down Nebraska's ban on a late-term surgical
abortion procedure dubbed ``partial-birth abortion'' by opponents.
Scalia and Thomas also dissented on a 6-to-3-decision in a Colorado
case where the majority gave states wide leeway to limit
anti-abortion demonstrations near clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, touring the Midwest to pitch his energy policies, said the
dissent by Scalia and Thomas in the Nebraska case was ``very bitter
in tone and divisive in nature.'' Gore said Scalia's dissent in the
Colorado case was ``a particularly convoluted bit of logic.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving to make the direction of the Supreme Court a top issue in
the presidential campaign, Gore said the nation's next president
may be called upon to nominate three or four justices to replace
members of the present court who may retire.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the high court's ``razor thin'' decisions on
hot-button social issues such as abortion rights could be reversed
if Bush won the presidency and could nominate new justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Gov. Bush has said his models for future nominations
would be Justices Scalia and Thomas, it is obvious that he intends
_ if he ever gets the chance _ to try to change the court's opinion
on a woman's right to choose,'' Gore warned. ``The presidential
election will decide the future of the Supreme Court and that in
turn will decide whether or not we keep a woman's right to choose _
or see it taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush last November told interviewers that he would use the two
justices as models for any nominations for the court that he would
make as president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, also campaigning Wednesday in the swing state of Ohio with
appearances in Cleveland, said through spokeswoman Karen Hughes
that he was ``disappointed'' that the high court had overturned
Nebraska's ban on late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``States should have the right to enact reasonable laws and
restrictions, particularly concerning the brutal practice of
partial-birth abortion,'' Hughes said, adding: ``Unlike Al Gore, I
pledge to fight for a ban on partial-birth abortion.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush has taken two different positions, both of them in the
anti-abortion mode. He has voiced support for a GOP platform that
calls for a constitutional amendment to ban all abortions and he
has specifically endorsed a constitutional amendment to outlaw
abortion except in cases of rape, incest and to protect the life of
the mother.
</P>
<P>
   But the two-term Texas governor has rejected religious
conservatives' demands that he weed out prospective judicial
nominees by imposing a so-called ``litmus test'' on abortion,
vowing only that he will appoint judges ``who strictly interpret
the Constitution and who will not use the bench to legislate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who also rules out a ``litmus test'' for choosing judges,
told an audience here that he would appoint judges such as the late
Thurgood Marshall and William Brennan who view the Constitution as
a changing document and ``are not locked in the narrow meaning of
words as they were used 200 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Court scholars speculate that the next president may be handed
the opportunity to shape the high court in a way that hasn't been
matched since Republican Richard Nixon appointed four justices at
the outset of the 1970s and Republican Herbert Hoover named three
in the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The four leading retirement candidates on the present court
during the term of the next president are: John Paul Stevens, 80,
appointed by Gerald Ford; Chief Justice William Rehnquist, 75,
nominated by Richard Nixon and elevated by Ronald Reagan; Sandra
Day O'Connor, 70, named by Reagan, and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, 67,
appointed by appointed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The latest national survey, released Monday by CNN/USA Today,
showed Bush leading Gore 52 percent to 39 percent in a two-way
race. The survey had a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Americans remain strongly supportive of a woman's
right to choose. An NBC/ Wall Street Journal survey completed June
18, found 57 percent favored a woman's right to choose, 32 percent
favored legalized abortion only in cases where the pregnancy
stemmed from rape, incest or imperiled the life of the mother. Nine
percent favored a total ban on abortion. The survey had a margin of
error of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore injected his reaction to Supreme Court rulings while
visiting this rural community east of Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In a region where gasoline prices have soared, Gore proposed
providing consumers tax credits of up to $6,000 to buy energy
efficient hybrid electric- and-gas-powered cars and up to $2,000
for energy-efficient new homes, in addition to other steps to boost
the nation's energy efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Chapman, whose six-member family recently bought a new
energy efficient home in a neighborhood of $140,000 homes, said he
had cut family energy costs by 40 percent by upgrading to the kinds
of energy-efficient equipment that would qualify for the tax credit
outlined by Gore, if approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this stuff really does work?'' asked Gore, wearing an olive
sport shirt and slacks and seated on a stack of plywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it does,'' said Chapman, a father of four boys seated
adjacent to the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wirth, 43, a father of three who used to sell homes in the
area, said local residents are not blaming Gore for skyrocketing
gasoline prices that have driven up the cost of refilling his
Cadillac to $32.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton and Gore ought to be doing more to cut
gasoline and energy prices,'' said Wirth, who said he was a
Democrat. ``But people around here understand that the problem goes
deeper than the White House. Life has been good for most of us. If
somebody's not working nowadays, there's something wrong with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
