<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-28 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BORROWING' FAMILY RECIPES BURNS SOME COOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time honored among amateur cooks that if a friend is
excellently skilled in the creation of a peach cobbler, for
instance, to say between swallows, ``Oh, I love that; can I have
the recipe?'' At such moments of conviviality, it is proudly given
and gratefully received.
</P>
<P>
   But things are very different in the fraternity of professional
chefs and cookbook authors, where jealousies and passions are as
plentiful as stuffed artichokes, and charges of plagiarism of
recipes at times seem almost pandemic. Of course, the better
practitioners of the art of borrowing are generally smart enough at
least to alter the amounts of the ingredients: i.e., make it 6
ounces of shredded caciocavallo cheese rather than 3{ and change
the wording of the instructions. Still, an astute food person knows
who created which recipe, absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   This season's accusation of recipe plundering was made by Mimi
Sheraton, a prolific author of food books, against David Ruggerio,
once chef at La Caravelle and Le Chantilly, past celebrity
television cook and currently author of ``David Ruggerio's Italian
Kitchen: Family Recipes From the Old Country'' (Artisan).
</P>
<P>
   Ruggerio's recipe for roasted shoulder of veal with herbs set
off Sheraton's memory buds, she said, having remembered making the
same dish herself ``exactly as he described it'' from ``Marcella's
Italian Kitchen'' (Knopf, 1986) by Marcella Hazan.
</P>
<P>
   So after some research Sheraton, who used to be a restaurant
critic of The New York Times, accused Ruggerio of using 10 recipes
from four cookbooks ``that appear in almost identical form in
Ruggerio's new book.'' They ranged from luganega sausage with
black-eyed peas and tomatoes to charcoal grilled deviled chicken,
although she said that Ruggerio added garlic to the chicken dish,
``perhaps indicating a burst of creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Her allegations appeared in an article on the Web site of
Brill's Content (www.brillscontent.com), to be updated and
reprinted in the magazine in September. Ruggerio, who declined to
speak to me for this column, told Sheraton that the 150 recipes in
his book came from himself, his family and friends. She said he
explained the 10 recipe look-alikes to her this way: ``They are
very simple standards with just a few ingredients, and they are
always made the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Great chefs and cookbook authors have a protocol, an honor
system, about using recipes not their own. The author either
directly attributes the recipe to another chef or in an equally
acceptable but more informal way introduces it something like this:
I had dinner recently at X's house (or restaurant) and asked her
for the fine version of the stuffed meat roll she served.
</P>
<P>
   The line between originality and pastiche is fine indeed in
cookbooks, and what constitutes plagiarism is harder to define than
in a poetry book. Judith Jones, a legendary Knopf editor who has
edited many cookbooks, said: ``You cannot actually plagiarize
ingredients. Old-fashioned baking-powder biscuits: how many ways
can you change it? If you try too hard you'll ruin it. It's usually
in the explaining, the writing of the instructions.'' It's also in
the philosophical approach.
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``It's hard to plagiarize classic dishes, but its
another thing for the unusual recipes, the greatest dish of tripe.
You look at that recipe side by side with another: the same
ingredients, the same technique. It's not fair play, but it happens
a lot, and every 10 years or so there's a scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggerio's recipe for ``Baked Shrimp, Potatoes and Tomatoes''
was almost identical to the recipe created by Giuliano Bugialli for
his book, ``Foods of Sicily and Sardinia and the Smaller Islands''
(Rizzoli, 1996), according to both Sheraton and Bugialli.
</P>
<P>
   ``To add insult to injury, he took another of my recipes from a
different book, a Sicilian recipe, and made it a Tuscan recipe
without changing it,'' Bugialli said. Which gives you a flavor of
the seriousness and territorial imperatives in the writing of the
books. Still, Bugialli said, even this indignity was topped when he
went into a bookstore recently and found his latest book, ``On
Pasta'' (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang), on the shelf right next to
Ruggerio's.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of Ruggerio's book, Ann Bramson, said on Tuesday:
``I can say I am very uncomfortable with the similarity. I've been
obsessing about it and discussing it.'' She said that she didn't
intend to pull it from distribution. ``But I'm looking into
reprinting,'' she said. ``Coming from a personal and moral point of
view, if I had known, I would have not gone to press with these
recipes in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 25,000 copies are in print.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most notable recent cookbook scandal occurred in
1984, when Richard Nelson was accused of stealing recipes from
Richard Olney's ``Simple French Food'' (Atheneum, 1974) for his
book ``Richard Nelson's American Cooking'' (New American Library).
Nelson had been president of the International Association of
Culinary Professionals. He and his publisher settled out of court,
but it was as if a bank president had been charged with bouncing
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Malloy, senior editor at Warner Books, is trying to take
the company into cookbooks in a substantial way next year. Is he
worried about plagiarism? Not really. He said: ``There are only so
many ways to roast a piece of veal shoulder. If you picked up 10
cookbooks, you would find a lot of the procedure and the
ingredients are the same. Like any writer, the cookbook writer
should develop a personal style. So the plagiarism usually comes
down to the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right way to use another person's recipe is to say `I've
been influenced by my colleague Julia Child,' or `I had this
marvelous meal at a farmhouse in Tuscany.' People who cook and eat
and taste for a living are like a business writer or a golf writer
_ they know what's going on and will catch you.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Child said that stealing recipes ``is so stupid a thing
to do that I can only wonder if someone else didn't put the book
together for him, and he didn't read over.'' She continued:
``That's happened before. It's so stupid I can't think of any other
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   She has just finished her 11th cookbook. ``I wouldn't pay too
much attention if someone stole a recipe of mine. I guess it would
be a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Only an author of who is to cookbooks what Katharine Hepburn is
to the movies would be that confident. She knows everybody would
know a Julia Child recipe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
