<HEADER>
A7472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-RATES-NYT &LR;      06-28 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED DECIDES TO LEAVE INTEREST RATES UNCHANGED, AT LEAST FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve on Wednesday voted to leave
interest rates unchanged, giving itself more time to determine
whether the series of rate hikes it has imposed over the last year
are slowing the economy sufficiently to avoid an upturn in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank warned that it could start raising rates
again as soon as its next meeting, on Aug. 22, unless economic
indicators in coming weeks provide assurance that the red-hot pace
of economic growth earlier this year has given way to a more
sustainable level that reduces the threat of an inflationary spiral
in wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's decision had been widely anticipated by economists and
investors, and Wall Street took the news in stride.
</P>
<P>
   In calling a time out Wednesday in its campaign of rate
increases _ six over the last year, pushing its benchmark federal
funds target rate up by 1.75 percentage points to 6.5 percent _ the
Fed acknowledged said there was some evidence that the economy is
cooling off. And the central bank noted that while inflation by
some measures has been accelerating, price pressures are being held
down by continuing improvements in productivity, a measure of the
economy's ability to produce more for less.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank's policy-making Federal Open Market
Committee suggested that it remains unconvinced that the economic
slowdown is for real. It stressed its continuing concern that the
current low rate of unemployment could lead wages to rise so fast
that companies would be forced to jack up their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of moderating growth ``are still tentative and
preliminary, and the utilization of the pool of available workers
remains at an unusually high level,'' the committee said in a
statement released at the conclusion of a two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, the statement said, ``the committee
believes the risks continue to be weighted mainly toward conditions
that may generate heightened inflation pressures in the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
