<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SHURCLIFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICE SHURCLIFF, 84; MANPOWER PLANNING SPECIALIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alice Warburton Shurcliff, an international manpower planning
specialist who worked for the United Nations and International
Labor Organization, died of a brain tumor Friday at home in
Ipswich, Mass. She was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Shurcliff was a lifelong resident of Ipswich. She graduated
from Bryn Mawr College and earned a master's degree at New York
School of Social Work.
</P>
<P>
   She was employed by the War Department during World War II and
worked briefly for the State Department before joining the United
National Relief and Rehabilitation Agency.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, she spent two years in Japan before returning to
Washington, where she worked for the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist on manpower planning and economic development, she
later worked for the International Labor Organization and traveled
widely.
</P>
<P>
   After her retirement, she was a member of the Ipswich Finance
Committee for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves two sisters, Sarah Shurcliff Ingelfinger and
Elizabeth Shurcliff Lowell; and a brother, William.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
