<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ATTEMPT TO ARRANGE MIDEAST SUMMIT FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration's shot at brokering a
Palestinian-Israeli peace deal just became even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright failed Wednesday in
Jerusalem to persuade Palestinian negotiators to attend a summit
akin to the Camp David proceeedings a generation ago because of the
vast gulf between the Israeli and Palestinian positions.
</P>
<P>
   The US administration has long privately calculated that it has
until mid-September to bring about an Israeli-Palestinian deal
because of the time needed to shepherd through Congress a
multibillion-dollar aid package for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday, the already dim prospects looked far bleaker.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating President Clinton's appetite to go down in history
as a peacemaker in the Holy Land, all sides publicly said it was
now up to Clinton to decide when to hold a summit in the Washington
area. Clinton himself said so at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make a judgment about whether the time is right to ask
them to come here,'' he said. ``But I have not made that decision
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned that the difficult issues will not become any
easier in months or years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that some foreign policy problems, the answer is to
kick the can down the road and . . . hope time takes care of
them,'' he said. ``My own instinct is that the cluster of problems
here would be better off being resolved sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian leaders indicated, as they have for weeks, that
the decision on a summit was ultimately up to them. They indicated
a summitcould be counterproductive because the two sides have not
come closer on the knotty issues of borders, settlers, Palestinian
refugees, water rights and the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't bridge oceans,'' Nabil Shaath, a key Arafat
adviser, told reporters in Jerusalem. ``It's much easier to bridge
rivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who has had serious
difficulties in holding together his fragile coalition in the
Knesset, had pinned much hope on a White House-convened summit,
which Israeli officials were saying quietly could be held as early
as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Barak declared that Israel ``will not return to the borders of
1967,'' when it seized the West Bank and Gaza Strip and where about
170,000 Jewish settlers now live. Some Israeli officials have said
they were willing to give 92 percent of the territory, and accept
the declaration of Palestinian statehood with borders to be decided
at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli prime minister also said negotiations would not
advance substantially unless he and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat sat down, with Clinton prodding them along. ``The real
negotiations will open only if there's a summit,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year in office, Barak has successfully withdrawn
Israeli troops from Lebanon, but he has failed to make inroads on
his ambitious agenda to seal peace deals with Syria and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, he boldly predicted that he and Arafat would
agree by February to a framework on how to tackle the most serious
issues, and they would nail down the final deal by September. But
still no framework agreement has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happened with Albright's visit is that with all
of the final status issues _ border, settlement, refugees,
Jerusalem _ they were too far apart to come to Washington,'' said
Richard W. Murphy, director of the Middle East Studies at the
Council on Foreign Relations and former US ambassador to Syria and
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Murphy said, the focus turns to Arafat and whether he will
unilaterally declare a Palestinian state this fall, as he has
promised to do. ``On one hand, that is heard in Israel with less
anxiety than in the past,'' he said. ``But there is a growing
concern that could trigger violence as well.''
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Crowley, spokesman for the National Security Council, said
the deadline for reaching a peace deal was not the end of Clinton's
term in seven months. ``This is not about our timetable. This is
about their timetable,'' Crowley said. ``And they have set a very
aggressive timetable to make an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton clearly will push both sides for a deal soon, and if
he fails, the peace process could slip into hibernation. Recent
history indicates that it takes at least two years for a new
president to become engaged fully in Middle Eastern issues. It
takes time for the new president and his aides to understand and
become engaged with the issues as well as develop trust with all
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Clinton becoming active in negotiations in coming
weeks, however, there is no guarantee of a positive outcome,
something that the world learned this year after a failed meeting
in Geneva between Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad, who
died this month.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some observers said an Israeli-Palestinian summit could
be regarded as a Clinton high-wire act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily, you would think a summit would be fixed in
advance, more or less,'' said Geoffrey Aronson, head of the
Foundation for Middle East Peace, a Washington think tank. ``But
the experience we've had with the Clinton administration is that
they leap into these things, without a script in hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
