u i BC-HEALTH-REDCROSS-NYT &LR;      06-28 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-REDCROSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFECTIOUS DISEASES CAUSE MORE DEATHS THAN NATURAL DISASTERS,
REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Although earthquakes and floods usually receive the
most prominent news coverage, infectious diseases are claiming far
more lives than natural disasters, according to a report released
Wednesday by the Red Cross. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from infectious diseases like AIDS, tuberculosis
and malaria is 160 times greater than the number of people killed
in last year's massive earthquakes in Turkey, cyclones in India and
floods in Venezuela, said the International Federation of Red Cross
and Red Crescent Societies, which assists countries suffering from
natural disasters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 150 million people have died from those three
diseases alone since 1945 compared with 23 million in wars during
the same period, according to the Federation's World Disasters
Report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings have caused the federation to re-examine
its work, according to its author, Peter Walker, head of disaster
policy. ``Everywhere we do disaster relief, we found the disaster
was built on the shaky bedrock of poor public health,'' he said.
``While we will still respond to disasters, we've got to
reinvigorate the second string in our bow _ long-term assistance.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross said that such aid is needed to combat increasing
health risks that result from climate change, growing urbanization
and environmental damage. Yet governments are lagging behind on
preventive health care. ``There has been a real change in the last
ten years. In almost every country, there is a facade of a health
system, but away from the city centers, there is nothing,'' Walker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said this problem enables diseases that were once
under control to re-emerge _ like malaria in Azerbaijan and
Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 13 million people died from such diseases, which the
report said could have been prevented by spending as little as $5
per person in health care. ``Governments are slipping on their
responsibilities for immunization and basic health care,'' said Dr.
Hakan Sandbladh, a Red Cross health officer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, public spending on health in poorer
countries averages only 1 percent of gross domestic product,
compared to the 6 percent that wealthier countries spend.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report's authors said that money spent on changing people's
behavior saves more lives than money for expensive facilities like
hospitals and high-tech equipment. Sandbladh warned that money
meant for national health systems was not cost-effective because
most of it goes to big hospitals and not to preventive health
programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
