<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _ MIAMI _ The U.S. Supreme Court has decided not to
extend the stay keeping 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez from
leaving the United States, or hear the Miami relatives appeal.
Barring some desparate last-minute attempt in another federal
court, at 4 p.m. EDT, his father Juan Miguel Gonzalez may finally
return with his son and family to Cuba _ which they apparently plan
to do on a 5 p.m. EDT chartered flight out of Washington Dulles
International Airport. What will be the reaction in the
Cuban-American community, and in Havana? Developing.
(MWilliams/Lipman, Cox News Service). 30. WITH RICK MCKAY PHOTOS
FROM WASHINGTON.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 7 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire in (i)
International and (w) Washington categories; with updates to follow
on the family landing in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   BATAAN-POW _ WASHINGTON _ Maurice Mazer, a former POW and
surivior of the Bataan Death March who lives in Boca Raton, Fla.,
recieved a Purple Heart for his service during World War II.
(O'Dell, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-CLASSICCARS _ DAMASCUS, Syria _ Between the centuries old
mosques and the Roman ruins, Syrians like Abdel Malek Sheikho keep
history rolling down the street. Sheikho screeches the tires of his
bright red 1951 DeSoto Delux as he weaves through the crowded
streets. It's powered by a Chevy engine and has the occasional
Cadillac part inside. And, he's got a large poster of the late
Syrian President Hafez Assad in the windshield. At the garage zone
on the edge of the capital, workers hammer the chrome trim around
the fins of a 1959 Buick. They scramble for parts to fit the motley
fleet brought in for repairs. They polish up a Bel Air station
wagon, a 1963 Mercedes, old Skoda's and Fiats. A closed economy and
high taxes make it hard to get cars in Syria, so drivers and
mechanics keep the old ones running. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Will move on the NYT wire in (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA _ HONG KONG _ The first person I met in Hong Kong was
named Mao. But Elley Mao is no Maoist. The message from the
government economist for the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region of China was the same one that came from nearly everyone
here. The third anniversary of Hong Kong's return to Chinese
control comes Saturday. But the former British colony is still very
much open for business, Mao says, and delighted to embrace any
capitalist imperialists who might come calling. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   ARCHBISHOP _ SAN ANTONIO _ Archbishop Patrick Flores and his
secretary being held hostage in his office at the Chancellory near
St. Mary's Cathedral in central San Antonio. Kidnapper, supposedly
a Mexican national, said something about a passport as he met
Flores in the parking lot Wednesday morning. Later it turned ugly
in the office and about 100 employees were evacuated. Following
events. Scheibal, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ARCHIBISHOP-FLORES _ SAN ANTONIO _ Profile of Archbishop Patrick
Flores, 70, a high school dropout from South Texas tiny town of
Ganado who got back his feet with the counsel of a priest, then
became a priest at 27. Was priest in Houston, first Hispanic bishop
in Texas (or U.S.?) when became auxiliary bishop in San Antonio,
later bishop in El Paso then became Archbishop. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman). 18. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRI _ Gov. George W. Bush touts his good relationship with
Mexican officials as proof of his international abilities. But the
governor's in is with officials from the ruling PRI party, which is
facing serious election challenges this year. What happens to Bush
if the PRI loses the July 2 election? (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
