<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SEXY-MEX-ELECTION-RES     06-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXY-MEX-ELECTION-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FULL MONTEZUMA: PRI STRIPS DOWN FOR MEXICO'S FEMALE VOTE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from June 22 for Mexico's JULY 2 election)   (This colorful 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JAN MCGIRK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With less than a week left before Mexico's
closest-ever presidential election, the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party is stripping down for action and going after
the female vote.
</P>
<P>
   A quintet of buff male dancers pranced in cowboy boots,
strutting their stuff and snapping their thongs for 15,000
shrieking women at a recent political rally on the outskirts of the
capital. The organizers had enticed poor urban housewives out in
record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes were on the message spelled out on the backsides of the
tight boxer shorts worn by ``The Sexy Boys'': VOTE FOR PRI! When
these, too, were cheekily flung away, the screams were almost
supersonic.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these women from the PRI stronghold of Mexico state,
which has 7.5 million potential voters, arrived six hours early to
secure an unobstructed view of the stage.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the dull PRI campaigns of the past. There
was no brass band wheezing tunes while a rent-a-crowd of day
laborers cheered the candidate's stilted speech, then waved his
convoy of flashy cars off to the next fly-blown town.
</P>
<P>
   A big banner for the PRI's presidential candidate, Francisco
Labastida, was prominently displayed as a backdrop while the
entertainers did their bumps and grinds. However, the silver-haired
technocrat did not attend as a speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it in a Mexican political
campaign,'' said Josefina Franzoni, an analyst at the Mexican
Institute of Political Studies.
</P>
<P>
   When male strip shows first took Mexico by storm last summer,
National Action Party (PAN) stalwarts and right-wing Catholic
clergyman often were tempted to score political points by revoking
permits at the last minute in the name of public decency.
</P>
<P>
   This only added to the show's mystique, and one touring stud
cabaret, ``Solo Para Mujeres,'' set box-office records. In less
than a year, the ruling party has seized on the gimmick as a crowd
puller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that we can see nude men, but I would like to see
more political proposals,'' said Franzoni.
</P>
<P>
   Comprising 51 percent of Mexico's 59 million registered voters,
women can swing this tight election and they are being courted by
all candidates. Some four million households are headed by single
women, and they are changing the dynamics of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's wife even went on a walkabout in one of Mexico
City's tough neighborhoods to speak on crime. ``She's the first
wife of a candidate with her own personality,'' said Miguel Acosta
of the Mexican Human-Rights Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls waver, but for the first time the authoritarian
PRI is facing a viable challenge in a transparent election process.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, conservative candidate for an alliance of the PAN
and the Mexican Green Ecologists, has been riding high with his
appeal to young professionals. He even led by five percentage
points in one recent poll.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the left-wing spoiler from the Democratic
Revolution Party, gained support following a television debate in
which he appeared statesmanlike, but his electoral chances are
slim. Some of his party have defected, but he refuses to join Fox
in his alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Spin and image have been greater factors in this campaign than
in previous elections where a PRI victory was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   An American political consultant, James Carville, helped to
devise Labastida's campaign slogan, ``Change with a course,'' as an
antidote to the corrupt image the PRI acquired during seven decades
in power.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive, is more succinct: ``Enough!''
is his rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a backlash from women's groups, offended by the
PRI's spectacle. A full-page advertisement in a leading daily
newspaper recently denounced the skin show, but reproduced raunchy
images from it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Movement to Fight for Human Rights and the Equality
of Women said: ``No, Mr. Labastida, Mexico is grander than this.
You are not able to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they would have been satisfied had female strippers
received equal time is unclear. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this lively 675-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SEXY-MEX-ELECTION-RES     06-28 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXY-MEX-ELECTION-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FULL MONTEZUMA: PRI STRIPS DOWN FOR MEXICO'S FEMALE VOTE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
