<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN SUGGESTS IT COULD ACCEPT `ONE CHINA' POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Taiwan's new president this week said the magic words
more clearly than ever before, telling visitors that his government
could agree with China's government that there is only ``one
China.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added a condition that Beijing has said it cannot accept:
that Taiwan and China must each be able to interpret those words in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   With his latest statement, President Chen Shui-bian, the former
opposition candidate and independence advocate who took office in
May, came tantalizingly close to a formula that might draw Beijing
into peace talks with the island it considers a breakaway province.
</P>
<P>
   A senior security aide in Taipei, Taiwan's capital, told
reporters that the statement, made Tuesday to visiting Americans
and reported in Wednesday's papers, was ``the new government's most
authoritative, sincere and goodwill policy statement.''
</P>
<P>
   What Chen said clearly for the first time is that his
administration could accept an approach that was successfully used
in 1992 to defuse the core dispute over Taiwan's political
relationship to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new government is willing to accept a consensus that there
is one China but each side could have its own interpretation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, with a similar ambiguous oral agreement about
Taiwan's political status, the two sides began fitful talks between
semi-official representatives. These were angrily ended by Beijing
last year when Taiwan's president at the time, Lee Teng-hui,
provocatively asserted that Taiwan and China had a ``state-to-state
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the charged atmosphere after the election victory by
Chen, each side claims to have a different memory of how the
sovereignty issue was finessed in 1992. While Beijing did not
immediately respond to Chen's latest remarks, Chinese officials
have said in recent weeks that they could never agree to multiple
interpretations of ``one China.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the word games is a fundamental chasm: most residents of
Taiwan want the island to keep its de facto independent status
while China insists, on threat of war, that Taiwan must agree to
rejoin the motherland, though it says it could do so with great
autonomy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
