<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SEA-SHELLS-ART-2TAKES     06-28 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-SHELLS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE SELLS SEASHELLS BY THE SUBWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Britain, France, Italy)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT7, 8 and 9, have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The history of architecture reaches back past the
palazzi and pyramids to the dawn of the lean-to. But humankind was
bested in its attempts to create a stylish habitat 500 million
years earlier by, of all things, an invertebrate. The lowly mollusk
should be credited with creating the world's first beach house in
the brilliant form of the seashell.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Gow, importer, creator of objets and consummate
handyman, would probably live in a seashell if he could. Long a fan
and student of whelks, conchs, periwinkles et al., he is also a
founder of Ruzzetti &AMP; Gow, a Manhattan company that gathers shells
around the world, silver-coats them in Rome and uses them to adorn
antique and contemporary chandeliers and furniture. Gow, 37, sells
seashells far from the seashore: this week, he is opening his first
boutique, at 162 East 74th Street in Manhattan. But he has also
converted a small apartment above a busy Midtown street into a
combination living space, atelier and beach house.
</P>
<P>
   While others take citified polish to the seaside, Gow, who grew
up in English coastal towns, made the reverse commute: he used the
rudest of materials _ castoff fabric, flea-market finds, staples,
glue and lots of shells _ to fashion an apartment that feels more
like a getaway than many Hamptons retreats. ``It's outrageous, some
of these places,'' he said. ``If you couldn't see the ocean, you'd
think you were in the middle of the city. The antiques hail from
18th-century royal palaces.'' The standard for beach-house decor,
he added, ``should be that if waves washed it all away, there
should be nothing lost where the financial value is greater than
the emotional value.''
</P>
<P>
   His own silver products are as polished as his own decor gets.
Even his walls are relaxed. Gow, a specialist in 19th-century
European sculpture at Sotheby's for the last decade, amassed
auction catalog after catalog, finally finding himself with a
mountain of records. In a simple, bold step, he stacked them above
a bookcase in his apartment, without aid of shelves. Eventually an
adjoining wall started to buckle, and the catalogs all shifted
precariously sideways. In design terms, his ``nonfunctional
library'' is a stunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more structurally unsound it is the better, because it
enhances the herringbone effect,'' he said of his Leaning Tower of
Sotheby's. ``It really is moving, though, and I have a feeling
something is going to go bump in the night soon.'' In hopes of
forestalling the inevitable, he placed one of his heaviest
shell-encrusted mirrors on an ornate console table against the
great wall.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is his ingenious answer to the small, dreary terrace
off a studio apartment Gow also rents one floor up. ``I was at a
cocktail party at Princess Marina Pignatelli's,'' he explained,
``and I met this Australian man named Fabian Compton, and he told
me how he painted these trompe l'oeil rugs on people's floors. And
I told him I'd love to have a trompe l'oeil swimming pool.'' Now he
has one, with a ``deep end'' painted a deeper blue.
</P>
<P>
   Gow (rhymes with wow) studied art history and decorative arts in
France, but his is an Englishman's home, cozily filled with
furniture and bric-a-brac. Over 10 years, he has steadily brought
in all manner of furniture finds from street and flea market. He
asked Compton to stencil a trompe l'oeil kilim onto the sea grass
matting in his living room, which adds to the cozy sense of
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings am aspect of whimsy to decor,'' Gow said. It even
fooled his mother, Joan Gow, who during a recent visit from Kent,
England, tried to kick aside the ``rug'' to vacuum underneath.
</P>
<P>
   He installed an antique mantelpiece to create the illusion of a
fireplace. No problem was so big that it couldn't be covered up.
``That is some nasty thing covered with a drop cloth,'' he said,
pointing to the white living room sofa strewn with Moroccan
cushions.
</P>
<P>
   For his small study, Gow took a large piece of green silk he
found in the rubbish at Sotheby's _ it had been used to wrap a
sculpture from Japan _ and fashioned a harem-style ceiling with
nothing more than a wire hanger and a stapler. ``There's not one
terribly expensive thing in here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Except the silvered fruits de mer, which range from $50 for a
starfish to $1,300 for a 22-inch-long conch.
</P>
<P>
   Gow's love affair with water fauna dates at least to the time
when, at 13, he won a marine biology prize for a paper on limpets.
Now, shells fill jars in the kitchen, instead of food staples; they
pile up in dresser drawers, where linens and clothes would be; they
spill into the filing cabinet in the study. What was once the
dining room, and has been for five years the showroom, should
rightly be called the grotto. On almost every surface sit silvered
shells, sea urchins, starfish, pomegranates, ears of corn,
asparagus, apples.
</P>
<P>
   Artisans have been practicing this kind of craftsmanship on the
Italian peninsula since the days of the Roman Empire. The workshop
used by Gow has been operated by the same family for generations
and has for decades done restoration work on silver pieces for the
Vatican. In the last two years, following the tradition of the
Italian shell grottoes of the Baroque era, he began to decorate
furnishings, and has designed some wrought-iron tables and light
fixtures to resemble coral.
</P>
<P>
   All told, it's a transformation for a loft space that was
formerly a Korean massage parlor, complete with bulletproof door.
Before Gow started his renovation, the space had been divided only
by several rudimentary walls (by an artist named Peanut Butter).
More improvements were made by Gow's next roommate, an artist named
Herbert Hoover, who made kitchen chandeliers out of conduit and
bits of hardware. (His designs had a starring role in the film
``Runaway Bride,'' where they appeared as creations by Julia
Roberts' character.)
</P>
<P>
   Gow moved to New York after a stint working in Dallas as the
curator of the private art collection of the developer Trammell
Crow. He got an MBA at Southern Methodist University, and, in 1989,
began working at Sotheby's. In 1995, his good friend Giampiero
Ruzzetti came to town with a few seashells that had been silvered
in Rome and proposed that they begin selling the shells as a
sideline. The business took off, and Gow, who had studied
malacology _ the branch of zoology dealing with mollusks _ while
taking a degree in botany at Durham University in northern England,
now found himself in a crash course in international shell buying:
he wanted to take care, he said, to avoid trafficking in any shells
from endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   He was happier with his free-lance success than Sotheby's was.
``I remember I was up for my performance review, and they asked me
how I thought my sideline was going,'' he said. ``And I said, `Oh,
the shells?' And they said, `No, your work here at Sotheby's.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gow left the company, having bought out Ruzzetti, who
kept the team's Miami apartment in exchange for his part of the
business. Gow began working from his West 37th Street apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He is flattered by the suggestion that he appears to share the
mollusk's talent for creating a comfortable, compelling environment
with what is more or less readily at hand. ``Except that a
mollusk's shell increases in size, and mine hasn't,'' he said.
``It's just grown inside with objects that have come and gone.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many of those objects are going to the new Ruzzetti &AMP; Gow store
and showroom, but enough arrangements will remain to form an
octopus's garden. His idea of home is a place where ``everything is
chosen to be stimulating to the eye, but also for comfort factor,''
he said, displaying an attitude toward decor that many English
people share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far less studied than many American rooms _ and far cozier
than European ones,'' David Hicks, the interior designer, wrote in
``The Englishman's Room'' of his countrymen's fondness for a
cosmopolitan collection of furniture, books and objects ``somehow
sympathetic to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gow agrees. ``That's the beauty of English decorating: the
stylishness and comfort,'' he said. ``Too many American interiors
are too contrived and put together purely for aesthetic criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   While his precious shells have an almost kitschy element of
ostentation, Gow says they are not intended as such.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about bringing nature back into the environment,'' he
said. ``The silver heightens the contrasts, and it enhances the
texture of the outside, while the inside stays intact.''
</P>
<P>
   The silver is not meant to one-up nature, he said, but ``to
ennoble it.'`
</P>
<P>
   Knowing when to stop is important. ``Barbra Streisand wanted a
rose,'' Gow said. ``We had a courier hand-carry it back from Italy,
but it didn't pass quality control. We never even showed it to her.
There are very few cases in which we can improve on nature. Most
things are better left and appreciated as they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7496 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-MUSIC-$ADV02-NYT     06-28 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUSIC-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GODARD'S MIX OF MOVIES AND MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The history of cinema parallels the history of recorded music in
that both have been concerned, since the necessary technical
discoveries were made at the end of the 19th century, with
composing in time: composing images, and later sounds, in film;
composing sounds alone where music is concerned. With a grand
inevitability, therefore, Jean-Luc Godard's four-and-a-half-hour
video ``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' presents itself also as, one might
say, ``Histoire(s) de la Musique,'' and it is fitting that the
soundtrack alone should be available. It comes from ECM (whose
moving spirit, Manfred Eicher, has long been a friend and
collaborator of the distinguished director) in the form of a
smartly packaged set, purchasable online through Barnes &AMP; Noble
(www.bn.com, $180). Five CD's are accompanied by four hardcover
volumes presenting Godard's text, in English and German as well as
the original French, with stills from the video.
</P>
<P>
   So persuasive is ``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' as a purely auditory,
musical phenomenon that these pictures prove curiously redundant,
though sometimes striking in themselves. Certainly, one does not
feel that anything is missing, for there is so much that is not.
The recording presents Godard's poetic narration _ nearly always
delivered in his own richly inflected voice, bronchial yet robust,
a musical instrument itself _ interspersed and overlapping with
snatches from movie soundtracks and musical recordings. Sometimes
there is, too, the sound of a manual typewriter: a nicely
old-fashioned touch, and useful in enhancing the effect of a
present time in which Godard is composing his text, while all
around him, on monitors and CD players in his studio, the history
of 20th-century culture is playing over. (The textual repetitions,
too, make it seem that one is hearing the conceiving rather than
the achieved conception.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet heard another way, the movies and the music come from an
eternal present, the land of Oz, while Godard's is the fragile
voice of the temporary. The voices of the Hollywood actors of the
1930s and '40s are forever young _ even Alfred Hitchcock, heard in
an interview, is not getting any older _ and the wordless voices
heard in Liszt's ``Faust Symphony'' or Schubert's ``Unfinished''
will never age. Godard's voice, though, comes from a particular
moment: a moment when joy at the ending of an old era in Europe,
that of the Cold War, had swiftly been replaced by anxieties as to
what sort of age was coming next.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust, in fact, rustles all through Godard's history or
histories, made over a 10-year period beginning in 1988. Speaking
of the birth of film, he tells how ``in the early morning of the
20th century, technologies decided to reproduce life ... but as
morality was still strong ... they wore mourning for this putting
to death, and it was in the colors of mourning, in black and white,
that the cinema came into existence.'' Nor does he become any more
sanguine about the later development of the genre to which he has
devoted his life, and in which, here, he is so much absorbed. There
are, he says at one point, only 10 films that make the grade. And
most of those would probably be French.
</P>
<P>
   Further on, in the last two of the four chapters into which
``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' is divided, Godard's pessimism seeps out
far beyond the bounds of the movie theater. ``Nations have
something over them that is beneath them,'' he says: governments.
He goes on to accuse governments of responsibility for letting
loose hatred in Europe, though his malaise is not just political
but, at root, philosophical. Yet at the end comes a straw of hope:
``If a man wandered through paradise in his dreams, and kept a
flower to remind him where he'd been, and on waking found that
flower in his hands _ so what can I say? I was that man.''
</P>
<P>
   Godard's despair is moderated by the care and urgency with which
he speaks: the sense in everything he says that cinema matters, but
people matter more, and cinema matters at all only in that it
creates moments that, because of how much and how intensely they
mean, one has to call real.
</P>
<P>
   Talking of Hitchcock in the spaced-out fourth chapter, where the
froth of film and music clips has largely subsided, Godard says
``we've forgotten why Joan Fontaine leans over the edge of the
cliff and what it was that Joel McCrea was going to do in
Holland,'' and so on, ``but we remember a handbag, but we remember
a bus in the desert, but we remember a glass of milk.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' special, though, is not so
much the substance of Godard's eulogy-diatribe, nor even its poetic
fireworks, but rather the beautifully produced and edited flux of
words and music. Right at the start, an enigmatic utterance by
Godard _ ``Change nothing, so that all can be different'' _ makes
perfect sense as a verbal equivalent to a quotation from a
Hindemith piano piece in which a simple phrase is varied and
extended but always comes back to the same emphasized note. Later,
but still within the first chapter, ``Le Sacre du Printemps'' is
tellingly intercut with Looney Tunes music, and the heroic ring of
a movie actor is matched by that of a Puccini tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Godard and Eicher provide only the skimpiest indication of the
music included and no key to the films, presumably because they
want ``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' to be heard not as a compendium but
as itself, a composition in sound, where speaking voice folds into
orchestra, movie into music, creating an aural river one can enjoy
as it comes and remember, like those Hitchcock films, for its
instants of illumination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7498 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PATRIOTISM0629-COX     06-28 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTISM0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patriotic times are a changin'
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If today was a cold December day in 1941, Henry
Flores III might be at the Army recruiting offices in Waco for
another reason.
</P>
<P>
   But today is a hot June afternoon in 2000. At the Texas Army
National Guard headquarters, Flores signs up to be an American
soldier one weekend a month and two weeks a year. The 23-year-old
native of Waco says he is proud to be serving his country, but the
main reasons for becoming a citizen soldier have little to do with
battlefield glory or defending American Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great deal,'' Flores said of the Army's tuition
reimbursement plan for college students. ``It'll help me pay for
school and I can be a positive role model for my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   At previous times in American history, like the war years of the
early 1940s, Flores' decision to serve his country likely would
have been made for another reason: to defend the United States.
Without question, his decision would have been considered
patriotic, a measure of what it truly means to be American.
</P>
<P>
   But much like the reasons many young men and women join the
military today, patriotic times are changing.
</P>
<P>
   Things that have traditionally defined patriotism seem to be
second thoughts in the 21st century. Cynicism about government is
at an all-time high. Voter turnout remains historically low. Flag
Day gets about as much attention as national bottled-water week.
And getting out of jury duty is practically a national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what you mean by patriotism _ how pleased you are
with the direction of the country and how much you participate in
the political process _ then you have to say it's going down,''
said Donald Greco, director of the American Studies Program at
Baylor University. ``And if you define it by what people are
willing to do to express their love for America, like raising a
flag, that's probably down, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Other scholars agree: These commonly accepted signs of
patriotism have declined since the war years of the mid-20th
century. Many of those same experts, however, say that things like
flag waving, fervor for American military might, and participation
in the political process don't always tell the whole story.
Patriotism comes in different forms these days.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Brinkley, director of the Eisenhower Center for American
Studies at the University of New Orleans, said today's America is
much different and more complex than the America of the 1700s,
1800s and early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that patriotism simply means waving the flag is
inherently flawed, Brinkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriotism is in your heart, not on your sleeve,'' Brinkley
said. ``Some of the greatest patriots have been those who challenge
the government, the direction the country is going. Our founding
fathers were dissidents. There were the flies in the ointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a good American is to put the interest of the country
first _ even if your viewpoint is unpopular, he said. Protests
during the Vietnam War, for example, were seen as unpatriotic to
many Americans, but pushing for change in hopes of making the
country a better place is every bit as American and every bit as
patriotic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no more unpatriotic act than to call someone
unpatriotic for expressing their beliefs,'' Brinkley said. ``Some
kid with long hair who's trying to save the great red woods is
someone who wants them to be around for future generations. He
cares about the country, but he's not more or less patriotic than
someone who works at a lumber mill and has a bumper sticker that
says, 'America: love it or leave it.' They're expressing their love
for the country in different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   If Americans truly are less boastful about being American these
days, some scholars say that's because the U.S. is stable
politically, militarily and economically. Competing super powers in
previous times now seem to work more in concert with each other,
argues University of Georgia professor Betty Jean Craige, author of
``American Patriotism in a Global Society.'' That has put the
concept of patriotism in transition, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional concept of patriotism meant the promotion of
your country in competition with other countries,'' said Craige,
who directs the university's Center for Humanities and Arts. ``The
old definition was militaristic and bellicose. The best thing to do
as an American was to die for your country. The emerging concept _
and one I would encourage people to embrace _ is to make your
country a good country in the community of nations. I think we're
now moving into this wholistic understanding of the interdependence
of countries throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   With a larger sense of concern for the entire global community,
flag waving isn't as common as it once was, Craige said. Parading
the Stars and Stripes, in many respects, is a tribalistic ritual,
reflecting a belief in America vs. the world. But many Americans
today, while still proud of their heritage, understand that the
U.S. is part of a larger picture, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to some people flying the flag is a sign. It indicates
a kind of belief that our nation is over others,'' she said. ``I
think now at the turn of the 21st century, we can see a tension
between the political right, in which patriotism is defined as
loyalty to the U.S. and in opposition of other countries, and the
more globally oriented side.''
</P>
<P>
   But a declining sense of national pride to make way for this
globalism also has its negative side effects, according to some
historians. A portion of American society has embraced the
individual about the collective good of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of ``my rights before the greater good'' has to
do, in part, with the declining sense that all Americans are on the
same team in a monumental struggle against outside evils. Experts
also point to a modern culture that fosters consumerism before
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to say that it's right or wrong, but Americans
don't seem to identify with their larger community like they did in
the past,'' said Greco, of Baylor's center for American studies.
``It's an attitude that says, 'As long as it doesn't affect me, who
cares.' That could lead to individual rights destroying the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Armistead, a professor of American history at Baylor, said
previous generations could easily see the need to come together
because American life was at stake. What it meant to be patriotic
was simpler, said Armistead, who served in the U.S. Navy during the
Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   His father served on the Western Front in World War I and was
awarded three battle stars for heroics during World War II.
Armistead's brother was captured by Nazis during the Battle of the
Bulge and served four months as a prisoner of war in 1945 before
being freed.
</P>
<P>
   After the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor in 1941, lines at
military recruiting offices went on for miles. Business owners
proudly converted their factories to make war materials. Stateside
Americans rationed everything from food to rubber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any great lack of patriotism today,'' Armistead
said. ``I think you might see a more sophisticated view of it all.
In the early days of the Republic, the saying was, 'My country
right or wrong.' It's much different now.''
</P>
<P>
   Armistead supports the view that Americans should see themselves
as part of a larger whole, but embracing this new form of
patriotism should not replace the pride and respect people have for
those things uniquely American.
</P>
<P>
   Flag waving, going to Fourth of July parades and singing the
national anthem should remain a rich part of life in America,
Armistead and others said. Citizens also should exercise the rights
_ like voting, jury duty, civic involvement _ that make the United
States the most free country in the world, said Joe Cavanaugh,
director of the Admiral Nimitz Museum in Fredericksburg.
</P>
<P>
   Being patriotic also encompasses being aware of the country's
history and remembering the people who sacrificed to preserve those
rights for today's America and the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people no longer pay attention to history we lose sight
of the past. When that happens we lose sight of ourselves,''
Cavanaugh said. ``To 'stop and remember' is part of our patriotic
duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
