<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7500 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BEGGARS-TV-$ADV2-2TAK     06-28 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEGGARS-TV-$ADV2-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAKERS OF TV ARE HAPPY TO MINE THEIR OWN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By HILARY DE VRIES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, Brandon Tartikoff, the legendary NBC programming
chief, proposed the Hollywood equivalent of building oneself a
pyramid: A television series based on his own life. The former
network president, who had overseen such hits as ``Cheers,''
``Seinfeld'' and ``Law and Order'' during his decade-long tenure at
NBC, felt the time was right for a prime-time version of
``Network,'' the 1976 Oscar-nominated satire of the television news
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandon realized people were spending more time watching TV
than any other single activity with the exception of doing their
own jobs,'' says Jerry Offsay, president of programming at Showtime
Networks, which bought Tartikoff's proposal. ``He felt audiences
had a new interest in the twists and turns behind running a
network.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tartikoff, who died of Hodgkin's disease in 1997, did
not live to see his series reach the air, Showtime's ``Beggars and
Choosers,'' an hour comedy about the embattled president of a
fictional flagging network, reflects his vision. When the series
(which began its second season this past week) had its premiere
last year, critics hailed it as an intelligent, smartly written
adult ``dramedy'' _ the first series since HBO's comedy ``The Larry
Sanders Show'' to take a satirical behind-the-scenes look at the
television industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandon wanted to go beyond `Larry Sanders,''' says the
executive producer of ``Beggars and Choosers,'' Peter Lefcourt, who
developed the series with Tartikoff. ``He wanted to do `Network'
for the '90s and examine the whole landscape of TV programming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beggars and Choosers'' _ the title refers to the buyers and
sellers in the television market _ is the story of Rob Malone
(Brian Kerwin), an earnest if beleaguered network president not
unlike Tartikoff. In charge of programming for the faltering
fourth-place LGT network, Malone has a glamorous socialite wife,
Cecile (Isabella Hoffman), not unlike Tartikoff's widow, Lily, who
serves as a producer on the series; two precocious children and a
pressure-cooker job where he battles doublecrossing agents,
demanding stars and egotistical producers as well as his own
not-to-be-trusted staff, headed by his back-stabbing development
head, Lori Volpone (Charlotte Ross), modeled on the exploitive
programmer played by Faye Dunaway in ``Network.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Malone fought off sagging ratings by airing the
controversial ``Mountainmen,'' a ``Survivor''-like smash about a
group of vigilante wilderness-dwellers that stirred protest among
African-Americans and feminists demanding the inclusion of
Mountainblackmen and Mountainwomen. This season, Malone confronts
the network's eccentric new owners, a brash dot-com billionaire,
played by Beau Bridges, and his hard-partying nephew, played by Jim
Belushi.
</P>
<P>
   If these sound like plot lines ripped from the headlines, the
dialogue on the series is equally up to the minute. Episodes are
rife with offhand references to the overnights _ Malone wakes every
day to hear the overnight Nielsen ratings _ option year, MOW and
22-episode guarantee. Such inside-baseball terms would have been
beyond the understanding of viewers of ``The Dick Van Dyke Show''
40 years ago, when TV-industry verisimilitude extended only as far
as a late-night sketch-writing session or a trip to the woodshed
with the dyspeptic producer, Alan Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only series I've worked on where we don't need a
technical adviser,'' says Lefcourt, a novelist (his works include
``The Deal,'' a black comedy about Hollywood that he referred to as
a ``cult hit'') and an Emmy-award winning producer whose credits
include ``Cagney and Lacey'' and ``Our Family Honor.'' ``Not only
do we all know this world, but we don't have to explain things like
Nielsen ratings for the audience. Everyone just gets it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombarded by entertainment news, viewers today are increasingly
hip to Hollywood's ways, and box-office grosses, Nielsen ratings
and even the ``Friends'' contract renegotiation are water-cooler
topics. Now, prime-time producers are getting in on the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences are much more media savvy today,'' Lefcourt said.
``We've also reached the saturation point with medical and legal
shows. The television industry offers a rich body of new stories
that have so far been untapped because of a fear that audiences
don't want to demythologize Hollywood. But that's changing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, TV series about TV have been around since the industry
began. From ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' in the 1960s to ``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show'' in the 1970s to ``Murphy Brown'' in the 1980s,
such series have been a consistent if lesser part of the prime-time
landscape. Now, fueled by the newly media-savvy audiences as well
as the explosive growth of the cable industry, the genre seems to
be picking up steam. From ``Beggars and Choosers'' to NBC's new
teen drama, ``MYOB'' which is rife with insider references to
series like ``Friends'' and ``Law and Order'') as well as the
recently canceled comedy ``Sports Night'' and last season's
``Action,'' the number of series set in the entertainment industry
is increasing. The trend even extends to children's programming,
with the Disney Channel drama ``The Famous Jett Jackson,'' about a
15-year-old TV star who leaves Hollywood and moves to rural North
Carolina in order to lead a normal life. This fall ``Grosse
Pointe'' will have its debut on the fledgling WB network. A parody
of the long-running teen soap ``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' it is
expected to be the most visible of these entertainment-based shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea was to do a teen-aged `Larry Sanders,' because there's
a level of subversive humor that audiences will understand today,''
said Darren Star, the creator of ``Grosse Pointe'' as well as
``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of being in on it, of offering viewers a
behind-the-scenes look at these entertainment worlds, is very
popular now,'' added Stacey Lynn Koerner, vice president for
broadcast research at TN Media, the media-buying arm of True North
Communications. ``Whether it's `Murphy Brown' or `Sports Night' or
`Grosse Pointe,' audiences like to feel they're on the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   With its topicality and insider's tone, ``Beggars and Choosers''
has helped lead the charge. Already it's become the flagship series
for Showtime, as ``The Larry Sanders Show'' did at HBO in 1992.
``It's the best series we've put on the air,'' said Offsay, who
adds that the show has earned the cable channel new respect within
the Hollywood community. ``Agents are now sending us producers and
series that they never would have sent us before.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its success with critics, ``Beggars and Choosers,'' like
the majority of series about television, has yet to become a
break-out hit. ``The Larry Sanders Show'' never lured significant
audiences to HBO notwithstanding its critical accolades and
numerous Emmy nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Hiller and Diller,'' a 1997 sitcom about sitcom writers
played by Kevin Nealon and Richard Lewis, was shortlived. Last
season, two acclaimed, high-profile comedies about the
entertainment industry, ABC's ``Sports Night'' and Fox's
``Action,'' also failed in the ratings. ``Beggars and Choosers''
has generated plenty of buzz but not many viewers. ``It's still a
loss leader for Showtime,'' said Lefcourt, who suggests the series'
new time period, on Tuesday evenings, should improve viewership.
``We're getting a lot of attention in the big cities, but we've yet
to penetrate the podunks.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sharpened appetite for all things pertaining to
Hollywood, questions persist about the broad, popular appeal of
series set in the entertainment industry. With their cynical
attitudes and frequently disagreeable characters _ epitomized by
the narcissistic, egocentric Larry Sanders of Gary Shandling _ such
series are still considered risky when it comes to wooing
mainstream viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences are different today, and because we are a young, new
network with primarily a young viewership, we can take these kind
of programming risks,'' said Suzanne Daniels, president of
entertainment for WB, which will show ``Grosse Pointe.'' ``But even
so, I was initially very skeptical about this kind of satirical
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Offsay of Showtime said: ``Shows about cops, doctors and lawyers
still have one big advantage over shows about television: They deal
with real life-and-death issues. You only have to compare Jimmy
Smits dying on `NYPD Blue' with a story line about an actress who
might not get a role to understand why traditional dramas still
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7502 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-$ADV0     06-28 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULT OF COMPARISON AND A MUSICAL GLUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the news is true, the record business is not being nice to
classical music. The Washington Post reports that such respected
labels as RCA Red Seal, Deutsche Harmonia Mundi and Melodiya, all
owned or distributed by the international giant BMG, will be either
shunted aside as minor activities of the American, pop-oriented RCA
label or put out of business altogether.
</P>
<P>
   We do know that two of BMG Classics' busiest stars have been
left dangling. Evelyn Glennie, the Scottish percussionist,
generates enormous amounts of publicity because of her prowess and
her struggles against deafness; James Galway, the Irish flutist,
has ravished the sensible-shoe set for a generation. Yet Glennie
has had her contract cut off without warning, and Galway's will not
be renewed. The New York Times offers the further news (disputed by
BMG Entertainment) that BMG Classics will not be recording at all
outside this country.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the hand-wringing has stirred up a breeze, and
fingers are pointing every which way, often down in the direction
of the bottom line. Never or rarely moneymakers, classical
recordings have, quite frankly, been an object of charity in the
marketplace. If pop-music profits made the cup run over, the
producers of Beethoven and Brahms were there to catch the runoff.
Record companies are no longer as responsive, and it is easy and
sometimes proper to censure their crassness.
</P>
<P>
   Those not overburdened with culture have a hard time
understanding why their increasingly hard-earned net income should
be squandered on enterprises that sell 15,000 to 20,000 copies at
most, as against the millions generated by Ricky Martin. But shake
your fists at record companies all you want; they are reacting
indirectly to a bigger problem: The nature of classical music as it
has come to be.
</P>
<P>
   Popular music is predicated on the attractions of newness, the
current classical business on the attractions of oldness. Taken at
face value, the comparison is unfair. The newness of the Ricky
Martin single has planned obsolescence _ a short, fast-moving shelf
life _ built in. And although many of the world's interesting new
musical impulses are coming from anywhere but high-art sources, the
broad floods of pop releases are as quick and forgettable as summer
fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   New classical composers aspire to music that is built to last.
They are the inheritors of a 19th-century masterpiece syndrome that
linked quality with permanence and durability. And maybe their
products have both. But the problem is the public, which is not
buying their records.
</P>
<P>
   It is admirable and necessary that foundations of one kind or
other are helping to commit living composers to compact disc. The
fact that the general public isn't rushing to buy books on the
latest archaeological dig or genome discovery, or, for that matter,
recordings of the latest chamber music of Wayne Peterson, doesn't
mean that essential artifacts to a continuing culture shouldn't be
propped up by donors and universities.
</P>
<P>
   But in the record business, philanthropy and industry have
become hopelessly confused. With pop-music income under threat,
corporate high-mindedness toward releases that people buy only in
pitiful numbers has understandably weakened.
</P>
<P>
   The classical end has managed up to now by recording the
standard repertory and then recording it again. If the recordings
are old enough, they qualify as mythical voices from a distant
past. The technical imperfections are cleaned up, and releases are
repackaged and set out in bins next to the standard repertory
freshly recorded and the standard repertory recorded not so long
ago. They add up.
</P>
<P>
   Classical music on records is in trouble not because the BMG
labels are being martyred by bad guys in fancy offices; it is the
victim of a self-induced glut. In the early LP days, the
proliferation of recordings created healthy competition among
performances of the same piece. This stimulated listeners up to a
point. But faced now with 50 choices of the Beethoven Seventh
Symphony, customers _ even those who might want to own 5 to 10
versions _ are terminally embarrassed by such riches and walk away
in despair.
</P>
<P>
   And the question lurks: After all the great orchestras and
conductors of recent times have recorded their deathless
interpretations of the Beethoven Seventh Symphony, what more is
there to say about this piece? Ardent connoisseurs will argue for
the great new revelation to come and keep on listening and
comparing. Frankly, I know how the Beethoven Seventh goes, and the
ideal performance of it is in my head.
</P>
<P>
   If one good thing comes out of this worrisome affair, it may be
a forced re-examination of classical music's cult of comparison.
The explosion of information produced by the long-playing record
and the compact disc is of infinite value, but with it has come a
new and, for me, unsettling way of listening.
</P>
<P>
   My latest information on the BMG ruckus comes from a summary
report in the front pages of a new magazine, International Record
Review. Thumbing through its subsequent pages, one discovers
potential contributors to the problems the front of the magazine
reports on.
</P>
<P>
   I am in awe of these writers as they juggle 50 years or more of
recorded history, weighing the sound of versions A to Y against
version Z, noting timings, bristling at cuts in the score or
failures to make them. The knowledge of past performances and the
energy with which it is pursued paints pictures for me of people at
home in the midst of vast electrical apparatuses _ stopwatch in one
hand, urtext in the other _ endlessly crisscrossing between the
Mengelberg and the Furtwaengler tempo, or the Heifitz and the Elman
rubato.
</P>
<P>
   What a horrifying way to listen to music. Necessary, perhaps, in
that publications like this are a kind of Consumer Reports, aimed
at setting the potential buyer on the right course, but horrifying
nonetheless. I also suspect that the erudite justifications for
opinions arrived at are in fact unwitting responses to personal
instinct. And why shouldn't they be? Neither critics nor the
performers we write about are persuaded in the end by scholarly
proof; we manipulate proofs to accommodate what is in our hearts,
and that was often fixed inside us by our earliest experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Comparison, of course, is part of the process. Every new thing
that enters our heads collides with what is already there. Yet the
comparisons bred of 50 recordings of the Beethoven Seventh poison
the listening experience. Those who come away from Carnegie Hall
grumbling that they heard the Beethoven Seventh conducted at better
tempos in 1954 and with better brass playing a few years later have
wasted their evening.
</P>
<P>
   This is a plea not for recorded music, which will find its way,
but for the unencumbered ear, cleaned out for every night in the
concert hall or in front of the record player. Give your favorite
interpretation from the past an evening off. Compare as little as
you can. Make this experience as new as possible. If we don't get
back to hearing freshly, we shall soon find ourselves never hearing
the Beethoven Seventh Symphony again, only performances of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
