<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7503 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHAUTAUQUA-DANCE-$ADV     06-28 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAUTAUQUA-DANCE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUMMERTIME SUCCESS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By ROSLYN SULCAS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1983, Jean-Pierre Bonnefoux, recently retired as a principal
dancer with the New York City Ballet, was asked to take charge of
the summer ballet school at the Chautauqua Institution, a gated
community of 225 acres along the shore of Chautauqua Lake, in the
northwest corner of New York State. The oldest summer arts festival
in America _ last year its 125th anniversary was commemorated in
``Chautauqua: An American Utopia,'' published by Harry N. Abrams _
Chautauqua was founded as an educational center in 1874 and soon
incorporated musical and dramatic performances. It boasted a
resident symphony orchestra, opera and drama companies, attendant
music, theater and art schools, but almost no dance, apart from the
fledgling school that catered mostly to the children of festival
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnefoux and his wife, the celebrated Balanchine ballerina
Patricia McBride, had made guest appearances at Chautauqua in the
'70s and remembered the idyllic lakeside setting and wonderful
atmosphere as they performed to a rapt crowd in an enormous
open-air amphitheater. Bonnefoux accepted the offer and, 18 years
later, can be justly proud of his achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Summer by summer, he has transformed the school into one that
attracts some of the country's best ballet students, with alumni
like Alexandra Ansanelli and Sebastian Marcovici, now soloists at
New York City Ballet. He has also made dance an integral part of
Chautauqua's artistic program by forming a professional summer
company that presents both new choreography and work from the
classical repertory _ thus extending his activities as artistic
director of the North Carolina Dance Theater in Charlotte, where he
and McBride spend the other 10 months of the year. This year, the
Chautauqua dance program (which started June 29 and ends on Aug.
12) offers eight performances in the 5,000-seat amphitheater,
accompanied by the Chautauqua Symphony, conducted by Akira Endo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dance program has come on light years,'' said Chautauqua's
president, Daniel Bratton, who began his tenure in 1984. ``It's
incredible to have people of the caliber of Jean-Pierre, Patty and
Violette Verdy working here, and it's through their sheer
determination that it has happened.'' Bonnefoux's enthusiasm and
ambitions must have been clear from the outset: In his first year
running the summer school, he took along two former New York City
Ballet principals and colleagues, Verdy and Helgi Tomasson, as well
as the School of American Ballet's Andre Kramarevsky, to teach with
him.
</P>
<P>
   He also immediately began to present work in public. ``From the
outset, I wanted to groom the dancers to perform, to be seen on
stage,'' he said. ``You can't wait for them to be `ready.''' A
donation, two years later, that enabled the building of the new
Carnahan-Jackson studios, which incorporated a performance space,
gave an additional boost to student presentations, often
choreographed by Bonnefoux, ``because I couldn't afford anyone
else!''
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, the success of the dance school was such that he was
able to convince the institution that it wouldn't cost a great deal
of money to establish a small professional company. (``I'm not sure
how I did that,'' he said, wryly.) Since then, every year 14 to 20
dancers, some of them former students, some selected by audition or
word of mouth, have come from all over the United States to form a
temporary troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean-Pierre's idea was that we could employ dancers who are
laid off over the summer,'' McBride said, ``and it has worked
beautifully. They are paid, their housing and food taken care of,
and they have the chance to work with wonderful teachers,
choreographers and musicians.''
</P>
<P>
   One of these teachers is Verdy (now head of the dance department
at Indiana University), who has returned to Chautauqua every year
since 1983 and works with both the professional company and the
students. ``If one believes that art is excellence and leads to
spiritual understanding, then that's what you have in Chautauqua,''
she said. ``It's a cultural oasis; there are people who have been
going for generations.'' (In fact, the return rate at Chautauqua,
according to Marty Merkley, the director of programming, is around
80 percent, and the institution does little aggressive
self-promotion, which explains how a festival attracting 140,000
people annually remains so little known.)
</P>
<P>
   Verdy said that although the caliber of the students has
improved greatly, the emphasis has always been on ``giving the
students a sense of what it is like to perform, how to give
something an audience wants to buy a ticket for.''
</P>
<P>
   This accent on performing makes Chautauqua somewhat different
from most summer schools: Although the students (divided into two
groups: The advanced ``festival'' level, 14 to 17 years old, and
the ``workshop'' level, 11 to 13 years old) have a full program of
daily ballet, jazz and modern classes _ with an extra point work
and variation class in the afternoon for the older girls _ the
focus of their stay in Chautauqua is learning and rehearsing the
ballets that they will perform before an audience. W E always try
to do Balanchine with both the students and the company,'' McBride
said, ``because it's the best way for them to progress; it really
takes them a step higher. The Balanchine Trust has been wonderful
about granting permission: We've done `Stars and Stripes,' `The
Four Temperaments,' `Rubies,' `Western Symphony,' `Donizetti
Variations' and `Valse Fantasie,' and this year we're doing
`Allegro Brillante' for the company and `Raymonda Variations' for
the older students.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to learning the Balanchine repertory from firsthand
sources, both the students and professional dancers work with
invited choreographers on entirely new pieces. Over the years,
Bonnefoux has invited a broad range of choreographers to
Chautauqua, including Peter Pucci, Alonso King, Graham Lustig, Lynn
Taylor-Corbett and John Clifford, who has returned 10 times and has
created some 20 ballets there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful place to work,'' Clifford said. ``Everything
is completely open, so people watch rehearsals, you see them the
morning after the performance, and you get a lot of feedback.
Balanchine always said that ballet is a craft as well as an art,
and Chautauqua is a place to really work on your craft. You usually
have one week to choreograph, one week to rehearse, and then
they're onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, Bonnefoux has also invited the former
Martha Graham principals Terese Capucilli, Donlin Foreman and
Jacqulyn Buglisi, of the Buglisi/Foreman Dance Company, to teach
and present their own work in studio performances. ``We work our
schedules around getting to Chautauqua,'' Buglisi said. ``For us,
there is an incredible connection to the audience there, and it's
very satisfying to try to bring aspects of physicality to the
students that ballet coaching doesn't cover.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bonnefoux has also invited a number of dancers and
musicians from India, Africa, China and the Caribbean to take part
in an evening of world dance, ``to really show people what
diversity exists.'' The rest of the program includes a piece by
Bonnefoux and premieres by Christian Holder, Mark Goddon and the
resident choreographer, Mark Diamond in a salon evening set to
chamber music pieces, a pas de deux program of mostly new works
(one of these by an 18-year-old former student, Jessica Miller),
the Balanchine ballets, and a full-length ``Cyrano de Bergerac'' by
Diamond, who is also on the faculty of the North Carolina Dance
School.
</P>
<P>
   A full-evening work with 14 dancers and students? ``We've done
`Swan Lake,' `Sleeping Beauty' and `Coppelia' in the past,''
Bonnefoux said. ``We have no fear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
