<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     06-28 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTENTIONS ARE GOOD, BUT PAYMENTS ARE EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have never been one to flirt with the pleasures of
self-denial. If I gave up something, it was usually someone else's
idea. Saying goodbye to a favorite doll whose chemically treated,
artificial hair gave me a rash was my mother's idea. Come to think
of it, that woman also masterminded the campaigns to purge
chocolate, nail biting and no-handed wheelies from my life.
</P>
<P>
   But I made my own decision to bid farewell to eBay a few months
ago. Maybe it was because I caught myself cutting back on groceries
to pay for such purchases as salt and pepper shakers shaped like
ears of corn. Or maybe it was because I realized that the (other)
bidders resembled characters in a Joseph Heller novel, obsessed
shoppers doomed to sell the same Hummel figurines and Squealer
beanie babies to one another for the rest of their lives. If you
think about it, how many Seals and Crofts songbooks could have been
printed in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   So when bad publicity hit eBay, the online auction house, last
spring and forced it to suspend the sale of a painting whose price
may have been inflated by shill bidding, I knew that I was clean. I
felt smug knowing I would never again bid, and never again have to
wait 20 minutes in a post office line to purchase a $21.17 money
order to pay for Fire King dinner plates.
</P>
<P>
   I have no theories about why certain people have addictive
personalities or what sets them off. But if you do, I would like to
hear them because last week I broke my vows. Well, partly. Although
it may be true that I (1) bid on eBay and (2) bought Fire King
dinner plates, I would like to point out that I did not (3) stand
in line at the post office to get a money order.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I paid for my fix instantly, using a new online payment
system called PayPal, a free service from X.com. It enabled me to
send a $26 credit card payment via e-mail to the seller. (For
sellers who do not have an account, PayPal opens one for them and
deposits the money. Then the sellers visit PayPal.com to complete a
simple registration process.)
</P>
<P>
   That same day the plate seller informed me that my order was in
the mail. There would be no weeklong delay waiting for a check to
clear or for a money order to navigate the postal system.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty is that you can send money _ real money, not one of
those gimmicky Internet currencies that can be spent only at a few
partners' sites _ to anyone with an e-mail address. You pay either
by credit card or from a bank account, which you register when you
open an account. The payment is credited to the seller's account,
and the seller can leave it there or withdraw it by requesting
either a check or bank transfer.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal is especially popular for online auction purchases but is
equally useful for other payments. My husband, for instance, used
PayPal to send $15 for a shareware program directly to the author.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, PayPal resembles an electronic wallet because it
stores personal data to enable you to buy things without revealing
private information to merchants. But unlike wallets that accompany
you online, your PayPal account information is stored on the
company's servers. To make payments, you must visit the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal's success in opening more than 2 million accounts since
it opened last year has emboldened a growing number of online
payment competitors, including PayPlace.com, payMe.com and eBay's
own Billpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is really nothing else like Paypal because it's
incredibly easy and has removed a lot of barriers to making online
payments,'' said Avivah Litan, research director for payment
systems at the Gartner Group, a research firm. ``It's easy, free
and convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for impulse bidders like me, those advantages are
also flaws. Have I mentioned that I was so inspired that I also bid
on six yards of vintage fabric for kitchen curtains ($27, via
PayPal), an egg cup (outbid, luckily), a patterned tablecloth
(ditto) and a little vase (pending)?
</P>
<P>
   To distract myself from the lure of two Kraft Kiddie Kup Swanky
Swig glasses, I phoned Vince Sollitto, an X.com spokesman, to
complain that it was PayPal's fault that I was spending so much.
</P>
<P>
   Sollitto seemed unmoved. ``That's not a bad thing in our
business,'' he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, my bad habits are at the heart of his business. The
more payments I make, the more money Paypal earns. Paypal, which
doesn't pay interest on the accounts, makes money by investing the
account balances.
</P>
<P>
   That brings me to another shortcoming: PayPal earns more
interest the longer the money is left in the accounts, so the
company would love it if buyers and sellers would make their
transactions from one PayPal account to another. But if an account
holder requests a withdrawal, it can take up to 48 hours for an
electronic bank transfer to be made and a week or for a paper check
to be received.
</P>
<P>
   Sollitto said the delays were inevitable. ``When you request a
paper check, the bulk of the delay is Uncle Sam,'' he said,
invoking the check-is-in-the-mail defense. One eBay seller I
queried via e-mail last week _ OK, I bid on his plates, which I am
happy to say went to someone else _ told me that he does not accept
PayPal payments because it takes too long to get the money out of
an account.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest drawback to PayPal is that you have no
protection if you pay a fraudulent seller. Unlike credit card
companies, who limit liability to $50, PayPal will not help you get
your money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole goal and job is to help you make payments quickly,''
Sollitto said. ``It's the same as if you would write a check and
mail it.''
</P>
<P>
   So don't go crazy and authorize a $2,000 credit card payment,
the maximum that PayPal allows in a six-month period, to someone
you don't know. You'll limit your risk by using PayPal to make
smaller payments; 1 cent is the minimum amount.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could say that was the sale price of the three juice
glasses with oranges painted on them that I bought on eBay. But
even at $9.99, I can still afford (some) groceries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
