<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL FILES MISSING
</P>
<P>
   Most of the computer files in the Chancellery of the former
leader, Helmut Kohl, were destroyed after his election defeat in
1998. Buckhard Hirsch, who has led a parliamentary inquiry into
financial wrongdoings by Kohl, told Parliament two-thirds of the
files were deleted. All files linked to the 1992 sale to France's
Elf Aquitaine of an east German oil refinery are missing, Hirsch
said. Prosecutors in Germany, France and Switzerland are
investigating the payments of tens of millions of dollars in
kickbacks on this sale.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: DOG BREEDING BAN
</P>
<P>
   Politicians agreed on a nationwide ban on the breeding of
so-called attack dogs after public protests set off by the fatal
mauling of a 6-year-old boy in Hamburg. A statement said the ban
would apply to pit bulls, Staffordshire bull terriers and bull
terriers ``as well as other individual dog breeds and cross-breeds
deemed dangerous.'' The German railways announced an immediate ban
on allowing fighting breeds on its trains and in railway stations.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MINISTER APOLOGIZES
</P>
<P>
   After drawing widespread criticism when she was quoted as saying
Queen Elizabeth II should vacate her royal palaces, Mo Mowlam, the
Cabinet Office minister, apologized and added that the comments
were merely confirmation of something she had said six years ago.
``I apologize if I have caused any upset, but it was six years
ago,'' Mowlam told Sky Television. ``It was not anti-monarchist. It
was an attempt to ask, in the 21st century, what about a modern
palace?''
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PRINCELY WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Britain's media watchdog warned that Prince William, 18, has a
right to some degree of privacy even after he leaves high school
this week. ``Now he is leaving school it is certainly not a
free-for-all,'' said Lord Wakeham, chairman of the Press Complaints
Commission. Among other things, the news media should be sure its
articles are accurate, he said, and should not harass the prince
for the sake of articles or photographs.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: MOBSTER'S CONFESSION
</P>
<P>
   Vatican television said it planned a live broadcast on Saturday
of a confession by Salvatore Grigoli, a Sicilian mobster convicted
of murdering an anti-Mafia priest, Giuseppe Puglisi, in 1993. The
Justice Ministry agreed to transfer the prisoner to the Paul VI
auditorium in the Vatican for the broadcast. Grigoli, whose topic
will be ``spilling innocent blood,'' is part of a Jubilee Day
dedicated to the Union of the Blood of Christ, a Catholic
association.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: CHAPTER CLOSES
</P>
<P>
   Italy closed a chapter of its modern history by shutting down
IRI, the Institute for Industrial Reconstruction, a state holding
company founded under Mussolini. At its peak in the 1960s, IRI
employed 600,000 people and controlled, among other assets, the
airline Alitalia, RAI, the state television company, and major
shipping lines. By 1997, IRI carried a $12 billion debt and was
given three years by the treasury to sell off its holdings and go
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: FALUN GONG
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese Army officer, Lt. Col. Zhao Xinli, has been committed
to a psychiatric hospital for refusing to renounce the practice of
Falun Gong, the exercise and meditation group banned last year,
according to a Hong Kong rights group. Detentions of Falun Gong
members in a number of cities have increased in the last week, the
Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy said. Most
practitioners are briefly detained, but officials have sent more
recalcitrant members to prisons, labor camps or psychiatric
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   MYANMAR: U.N. ENVOY IN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   A new United Nations envoy will go to Myanmar for three days of
talks with the military rulers and Aung San Suu Kyi's National
League for Democracy, an elected government still in waiting
because its victory in 1990 was never acknowledged by the junta.
The envoy, Razali Ismail of Malaysia, is a former ambassador to the
United Nations who was known for his forthright style. The junta,
which calls itself the State Peace and Development Council, has
said it hoped for more sympathy from an Asian. The former envoy was
a Peruvian.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN: PALESTINIAN DIES
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian police officer, Yousef Mahmoud Abu Nahel, who was
critically injured in mid-May in an exchange of fire between
Palestinian officers and Israeli soldiers in Ramallah, died in a
hospital in Jordan. There will be a military funeral for him in
Gaza on Thursday; he is the seventh Palestinian to die as a result
of last month's violence.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: SENATOR EXPELLED
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its history, the Brazilian Senate has
expelled a member. The senator, Luiz Estevao, a prominent real
estate developer and member of the ruling coalition, was accused of
having siphoned off more than $100 million in government funds
intended for the construction of a federal courthouse in Sao Paulo.
With the impeachment, Estevao, who denied the charges, also loses
his parliamentary immunity and is expected to be arrested shortly.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN: U.N. CURBS STAY
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the United States, the Security Council
postponed until mid-November _ after the American presidential
election _ a decision on whether to lift sanctions on Sudan. It has
now met all the requirements imposed on its government in 1996,
after the Sudanese were accused of harboring several suspects in
the attempted assassination of the Egyptian president, Hosni
Mubarak. Diplomats say all other 14 council members want sanctions
lifted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
