<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7508 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ABT-DANCE-ART-$ADV02-     06-28 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABT-DANCE-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON OF SURPRISES, MOSTLY HAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 15 of 6/27 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hats off, gentlemen, to American Ballet Theater for a
heroic season. The repertory looked better on stage than on paper
and a clever Band-Aid approach kept performances at a high standard
despite an inordinate amount of illness and injury among the
dancers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the season of the unexpected. Damian Woetzel from New
York City Ballet and William Marrie from the National Ballet of
Canada parachuted in for single performances to relieve the
company's overworked male principals. Much of the burden had to do
with the technique required in the full-evening works that dominate
Ballet Theater's seasons at the Metropolitan Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   The happiest surprise in this category was John Cranko's 1969
``Taming of the Shrew,'' a comic ballet low on choreographic
interest but powerfully put across by Ballet Theater's casts in a
company premiere. The major new production was by Kevin McKenzie,
Ballet Theater's artistic director: A ``Swan Lake'' successfully
staged along more or less traditional lines.
</P>
<P>
   The only original work came from Twyla Tharp. Her one-act
``Variations on a Theme by Haydn,'' later retitled ``The
Brahms-Haydn Variations,'' needed three performances for its rich
intricacies to build to a grand climax. The premiere was part of
the opening gala celebrating the company's 60th anniversary _ which
was quickly forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this was because the good old days do not speak to the
new audience Ballet Theater has had to attract with full-evening
spectacles to fill the Met. But thanks to this season's revival of
Antony Tudor's ``Jardin aux Lilas,'' and to ``Theme and
Variations,'' created for Ballet Theater in 1947 by George
Balanchine, McKenzie maintained a link with the great 20th-century
choreographers associated with the troupe. The return of Erik
Bruhn's 1964 staging of ``La Sylphide,'' in August Bournonville's
19th-century Danish version, was another reminder of a more
eclectic past.
</P>
<P>
   What has gone more or less unnoticed is that each season at the
Met is increasingly devoted to full-evening works influenced by
Soviet ballet's aesthetics. This is neither good nor bad but a
fact, evident even in the British ballets of Kenneth MacMillan and
Cranko.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet Theater's production of MacMillan's 1965 ``Romeo and
Juliet'' derives directly from Leonid Lavrovsky's 1940 Soviet
ballet to the Prokofiev score. Cranko's duets in ``The Taming of
the Shrew'' owe much to the highly physical partnering, including
overhead lifts and tosses, that Soviet ballet made famous.
</P>
<P>
   Among the company's 19th-century Russian classics originally
choreographed by Marius Petipa (in part or entirely), ``Swan Lake''
has some antecedents in pre-Soviet versions that Nicholas Sergeyev,
a Petipa regisseur, staged in Britain. But ``La Bayadere,'' ``Le
Corsaire'' and ``Don Quixote'' have come down from Soviet
productions. The bravura solos that Vakhtang Chabukiani of the
Kirov Ballet added to ``Bayadere'' and ``Corsaire'' would have been
technically impossible in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   It is this virtuosity that has brought so much attention to the
brilliant male dancers McKenzie has recruited. But 19th-century
ballets are built around ballerinas, and they offered a showcase
for Irina Dvorovenko, who had a breakthrough season, usually in
tandem with her husband, Maxim Belotserkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Once with the Kiev Ballet in Ukraine, both have refashioned
themselves into new kinds of dancers. He has added virtuosity to
his pure classical style. She has added refinement to her
virtuosity.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the injured or ill included Ethan Stiefel and
Giuseppe Picone (both absent all season), Susan Jaffe, Jose Manuel
Carreno, Ashley Tuttle and Belotserkovsky. Julio Bocca, Angel
Corella, Vladimir Malakhov and Joaquin De Luz had extra duty while
corps members like Marcelo Gomes, Herman Cornejo and Carlos Molina
(an admirable Petruchio to Jaffe's Katherina in ``Shrew'')
distinguished themselves in major roles.
</P>
<P>
   The question is where Ballet Theater will find new full-evening
works. MacMillan's ``Romeo'' needs a rest. Ballets like ``Shrew''
are only as good as their performance. The company's ``Don
Quixote'' looks pale compared to the version the Bolshoi Ballet has
just performed in the United States. The solutions are elsewhere.
The audience, looking for tricks and turns, may have been less
enthusiastic about ``La Sylphide'' and ``Jardin aux Lilas.'' Yet
the first is the epitome of Romantic ballet and the other is a
neo-Romantic masterpiece with a Proustian perfume. Both are
exquisite works: One should not lose them. Like carrots, they are
good for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
