<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOULDER-DANCE-$ADV2-2     06-28 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOULDER-DANCE-$ADV2-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COLORADO FESTIVALS,   MILE-HIGH CHALLENGES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Colo., Mass., Calif., Wash., Ohio, Spain, Britain,
Canada)  (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By DANIEL GESMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Far from the Eastern shores of the American
Dance Festival and Jacob's Pillow, summer dance gatherings in
Colorado illustrate the surprising cultural vitality of the Rocky
Mountain state as well as tensions, both financial and
paradigmatic, affecting arts presenters nationwide. Three festivals
in Boulder and one each in Aspen and Vail run the gamut of
programming styles and means.
</P>
<P>
   Blazing a trail along a risky frontier is Boulder's Colorado
Dance Festival, one of America's few dance-only presenters and
widely considered one of its top three dance festivals. Despite
drawing 400 students and 5,000 spectators, last season ended with
significant debts and an inadequate operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   A chronic shortage of suitable dance spaces pushed 1999
performances into the expensive Boulder Theater, where attendance
was undermined by high ticket prices and increased competition from
the city's Shakespeare Festival, Music Festival and Chautauqua
series and statewide events like the Telluride Bluegrass Festival.
As problems that afflicted the festival, Dr. Michelle Heffner
Hayes, Colorado Dance Festival's 1997-99 director and now head of
Cultural Affairs for Miami-Dade Community College, also cited a
shrinking federal arts budget, declining corporate and individual
donations, cyclical shifts in private foundations' financing
policies and the lack of a permanent endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Dance Umbrella, for nearly 20 years Boston's leading showcase
for diverse contemporary performers, underwent a similar crisis
last January that its director-producer, Jeremy Alliger, referred
to as ``a wake-up call'' for those who give and raise money. The
organization is now advancing behind a rally of corporate and
municipal support and major grants from the Doris Duke Charitable
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Dance Festival nearly went on hiatus this summer to
focus on restructuring before grants arrived from the Lila Wallace
Reader's Digest Fund, the National Endowment for the Arts and state
and local organizations. The Glenwood Springs Dance Festival,
active since 1992, was less fortunate. It folded following the 1998
season, a year after the 29-year-old DanceAspen shut down.
</P>
<P>
   A global sweep distinguishes the Colorado Dance Festival, which
Marda Kirn founded in 1982 and Heffner Hayes compared to the
Sundance Film Festival. While providing a showcase for
international stars and emerging artists, the festival has also
given rare emphasis to non-Western dance, reflecting Boulder's
interest in diverse artistic and spiritual traditions. The 1996-99
``Let's Dance Together! The Americas'' series concentrated
primarily on popular African Diaspora forms of North, Central and
South America and their underappreciated connections with
contemporary Western concert dance.
</P>
<P>
   Boulder's support for multicultural art and dance in general,
whether home-grown or imported, has been eroding amid rapid growth,
spiraling rents and real estate prices, and an accelerating influx
of affluent young white residents who favor outdoor recreation and
mainstream entertainment. Space for Dance, a part of the nonprofit
Boulder Dance Alliance, was a recent casualty. It provided support
and affordable space to Boulder County dance groups, which
multiplied from three in 1990 to at least 25 today. After shuffling
among temporary locations for several years, last summer Space for
Dance could not find an affordable, properly zoned home.
Negotiations also failed to land it civic-use space alongside other
cultural service groups within a downtown development project.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Colorado Dance Festival will distribute city
money originally budgeted for Space for Dance in a dance-space
subsidy program. Moreover, its world-beat programming is on the
rebound under the curatorship of Kirn and the direction of
Katherine MacDiarmid, previously head of Florida's Mount Dora
Center for the Arts, whose annual arts festival grew into one of
the nation's best in two years under her administration.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Dance Festival, running from Thursday through July 23
on the University of Colorado campus, highlights emerging groups
that integrate culturally specific traditions into a modern dance
framework: Robert Moses' Kin, Rosanna Gamson/World Wide and
Compagnie Nakissa. A faculty from the five continents will offer
some 400 students a stunning array of classes, including West
African, Afro-Cuban, Sufi, Persian, Kurdish, Middle Eastern folk,
Bharata Natyam, Capoeira, Hip-Hop, Flamenco, Latin- and
Euro-American-based modern and postmodern.
</P>
<P>
   Not every Colorado State dance festival organizer accepts a
multicultural mandate to the same degree. Local standards and
tastes should be the primary guide, according to Jean-Philippe
Malaty, who, with the former Joffrey Ballet principal dancer Tom
Mossbrucker, directs the four-year-old Aspen Ballet Company and the
Aspen Dance Festival. Running from July 12 through Aug. 5 at the
Aspen District Theater, Aspen Dance Festival emerged in the
aftermath of DanceAspen, which the City of Aspen presented once in
1998 after the founding organization went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom and I have very eclectic tastes, and we want to present
things that we ourselves enjoy,'' said Malaty. ``But you can't
dictate what you think people should see. You have to be in touch
with your community and appeal to all sides of it with
high-quality, well-marketed programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaty's and Mossbrucker's formula for broad appeal includes
something classical, something modern, something ethnic and
something up-and-coming. The programs include the Joffrey Ballet of
Chicago, La Tania Flamenco Music and Dance, and the Aspen Ballet
Company in David Taylor's ``Children's Rainforest Odyssey,'' as
well as a mixed repertory featuring San Francisco Ballet guests and
a world premiere by Nicolo Fonte. The Paul Taylor Dance Company
closes the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Most dance festivals, Colorado Dance included, must pay for a
year-round office for main seasons that last only a few weeks. In
addition to marketing savvy, Aspen Dance Festival enjoys the
administration of the Aspen Ballet Company, which in September will
merge with Santa Fe Festival Ballet to become the Aspen Santa Fe
Ballet. While Malaty and Mossbrucker like taking creative risks
with their dance group, they are satisfied with tried-and-true
festival programming. Furthermore, anything that the festival might
lose on misfires, the Aspen Ballet Company can recoup with a
wintertime ``Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   But raising money has its challenges even in Aspen, said Malaty.
Its wealthy residents, who typically make primary donations in
first homes elsewhere, don't always give generously to Aspen's
165-odd competing nonprofit groups Aspen Dance Festival keeps its
lowest tickets at $18 for the 50 percent of its audience that
consists of full-time residents.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Vail International Dance Festival, in similar
environs, seems most securely financed. Its parent organization,
the nonprofit Vail Valley Foundation, produces major international
sports events and the annual American Enterprise Institute World
Forum, headed by former President Gerald R. Ford, who lives in
nearby Beaver Creek. Ford and his wife, Betty, a former dancer with
and board member of the now-distressed Martha Graham Dance Company,
are honorary directors of the Vail festival, which also benefits
from the largesse of private donors like the philanthropist and
arts patron Judy Alexander and the investment banker, lawyer and
real estate developer Gilbert Giordano and his wife, Donna.
</P>
<P>
   Under its producing artistic director, Katherine C. Kersten, a
former dancer and teacher, the Vail festival emphasizes world-class
ballet but also presents culturally specific genres that are
familiar and accessible to resort habitues, like Irish step and
Slavic folk, seen last summer. It also offers free lectures by
festival artists, a conference for ballet teachers and intensive
ballet training for 80 students and pre-professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The Vail festival performances, which run from July 20 through
Aug. 12, include the Spanish classical company Ballet Victor Ullate
de Madrid; the Spanish Gypsy flamenco artist Manolete and La Rosa
Flamenco Theater; the Washington Ballet, dancing choreography by
the San Francisco Ballet artist Val Caniparoli; and the Paul
Mitchell International Evenings of Dance, which feature principal
couples from Pilobolus, the National Ballet of China, American
Ballet Theater, the Boston Ballet, the Royal Winnipeg Ballet,
London's Royal Ballet and the Cleveland-San Jose Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Two smaller gatherings suggest that, on one scale or another,
Colorado festivals as daring as the Colorado Dance Festival can
thrive without the security and glamour of an upscale resort
setting. The Boulder Jazz Dance Workshop, attracting nearly 150
professional and amateur dancers from around the world for 14 days
of intensive study with master teachers, celebrates its 22nd year
from July 30 through Aug. 12 on the University of Colorado campus
with a comprehensive jazz-based curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   From July 23 through 30, the Boulder campus will be host to the
second annual Aerial Dance Festival, created by the 11-year-old
Boulder company, Frequent Flyers Productions. A workshop for 80-odd
dancers features daily classes that include low-flying trapeze,
upside-down movement, bungee and aerial hoop, fabric, pole and
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Jazz Dance Workshop, the Aerial Dance Festival is
financed largely by student tuition and ticket sales. But if the
past is any indication, cozy and inventive gatherings like these
can give birth to larger-scale developments in dance performance,
programming and public support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0629-COX     06-28 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN, FAMILY RETURN TO CUBA FOLLOWING MONTHS-LONG AMERICAN
ODYSSEY
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: The story will be updated upon Elian's arrival in
Havana, expected around 8:15 p.m. ET.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Nearly seven months to the day after he was plucked from
the sea, 6-year-old rafter Elian Gonzalez jetted home toward Cuba
with his family Wednesday, ending a remarkable saga that tugged at
heartstrings and stirred intense political debate the world over.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear a legal
appeal by his Miami relatives who wanted to keep him in the United
States, Elian and his immediate family climbed aboard a small
chartered jet at Dulles International Airport outside Washington,
D.C. for their flight to Havana. The plane took off at about 4:42
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to be going home,'' Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, told reporters in broken English shortly before boarding
the jet with his second wife, infant son and Elian. ``I'd like to
thank the North American government for finally giving me my son
back after all my family's suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government _ which discouraged many U.S. journalists
from traveling to Havana to cover the homecoming _ insisted there
would be no large public celebrations, although a small welcoming
ceremony was planned at Jose Marti International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that the family would stay for several weeks
at a secluded diplomatic compound in the Havana suburb of Miramar.
Later in the summer, they will take a vacation and then return
their home in Cardenas, about a two hours from Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives made no public appearances Wednesday,
and angrily confronted a Miami television reporter who filmed them
outside a Coconut Grove Church shortly after the Supreme Court
decision was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are devastated that at this very moment, Elian is going
back to a country where he'll never be free,'' family spokesman
Armando Gutierrez said. ``This is a very rough time for us, but we
must obey the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian leaves behind a tangled legacy of warring lawyers, feuding
family members and hard feelings among Cuban exiles here, who
adopted his case as a symbol of their bitter hatred for Castro's
communist dictatorship. As Elian boarded the jet in Washington, a
few dozen somber Cuban exiles gathered outside the Little Havana
home where the boy lived for five months with his Miami relatives.
Many had tears streaming down their faces, while others held up
their hands in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came for the boy at gunpoint, that's the scary part,''
said Ruth Dupree, 27, a second-generation Cuban-American. ``This
family that did so much for him never got to say good-bye. It's
shaken my faith in America.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press briefing in Washington, President Clinton said he
regretted that the case became so politically charged, although he
said it would have been fine if Elian and his father had decided to
stay in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno _ who became a lightning rod of
criticism for her handling of the case _ applauded the Supreme
Court's decision not to hear the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All involved have had an opportunity to make their case _ all
the way to the highest court in the land,'' Reno said. ``I hope
that everyone will accept the Supreme Court's decision and join me
in wishing this family, and this special little boy, well.''
</P>
<P>
   With his impish grin and photogenic face, Elian captured the
hearts of millions, especially after they heard the harrowing story
of how his mother and 10 others drowned while trying to escape from
Cuba. Elian was found alone, floating in an inner-tube a few miles
offshore the Florida coast on Thanksgiving Day last year.
</P>
<P>
   With the initial blessing of his father and the U.S. government,
Elian was taken in by his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, a Little
Havana mechanic who left Cuba more than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the family's early relief that Elian had survived quickly
dissolved into acrimony over where the boy should live.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials took until early January to rule that Elian
should be returned to his father in Cuba, a decision that sparked a
day of angry protests in Miami. The Miami family quickly filed a
federal lawsuit aimed at winning Elian an asylum hearing and the
right to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, the boy's two Cuban grandmothers traveled to
the United States _ and briefly to Miami to see the boy _ in an
unsuccessful bid to take Elian home. Their visit only seemed to
feed the rancorous debate over the boy's future.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, Castro turned Elian into a cause celebre, staging
massive public rallies and marches that attracted hundreds of
thousands who chanted and sang for his return.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a Miami federal judge ruled that Elian should go home
with his father, triggering the Miami family's immediate appeal to
the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dramatic arrival of Juan Miguel Gonzalez from Cuba
in early April, sparking a new round of demands _ and a wave of
support from the American public _ that the boy be turned over to
his father pending the court appeal. After several weeks of
frustrating negotiations, Reno ordered a pre-dawn raid on April 22
to forcibly take the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The raid triggered outrage and a day of angry protests in Miami,
along with uneasiness among many Americans shocked by a news photo
of a terrified Elian being snatched by a gun-wielding agent.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling soon subsided, however, after Elian was reunited
with his father in the Washington area and subsequent photos of the
smiling boy were released. He spent the next two months living
mostly in seclusion, awaiting the outcome of the court case.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, the Atlanta appeals court ruled against the Miami
relatives; then reaffirmed its decision on June 23.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort, the Miami relatives asked the Supreme
Court to hear the case, but were rebuffed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the case that captured the attention of U.S. presidential
candidates and is cited as a factor in an apparent deal in Congress
to ease the embargo against Cuba is finally over.
</P>
<P>
   But it will clearly never be forgotten in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' said Ana Vega, 27, a Cuban-American
schoolteacher. ``It's just publicity for Castro. In his eyes, he
beat the American government. They gave in to that evil, horrible
man.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.canf.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0629-COX     06-28 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN, FAMILY RETURN TO CUBA FOLLOWING MONTHS-LONG AMERICAN
ODYSSEY
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: The story will be updated upon Elian's arrival in
Havana, expected around 8:15 p.m. ET.
