<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST-ART-     06-28 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST-ART-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND PALESTINIANS SEEM FAR FROM MEETING U.S. TERMS FOR SUMMIT
PARLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israelis and Palestinians on Wednesday appeared
to remain far from meeting the conditions set down by the Clinton
administration for an early summit meeting in Washington. But
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who came here to assess the
two sides' readiness, said that President Clinton would make a
decision in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and her aides left open the possibility that Clinton
might decide that now was the time to seize the moment and go an
for immediate summit meeting. Palestinian officials, however,
suggested that they would prefer more negotiations over the next
two weeks so they could improve their positions for a meeting a bit
later.
</P>
<P>
   Albright on Wednesday refused to concede that an immediate
summit meeting was unlikely, even though she has said in the past
that it would not be fruitful to call one unless the two sides had
significantly narrowed their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking at a news conference at the White House on
Wednesday, said that nothing had been scheduled. But he added that
he did not think the final, most difficult issues could be resolved
unless the Israeli and Palestinian leaders ``get together in some
isolated setting and make the last tough decisions, or decide not
to make them, as the case may be.''
</P>
<P>
   A top aide to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Nabil Shaath,
who took part in Wednesday's talks between Arafat and Albright in
Ramallah, ruled out the possibility of a summit meeting in the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He said that major differences persisted on the key issues of
Israel's withdrawal from the West Bank, the status of Jerusalem and
the fate of Palestinian refugees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see a summit held in the White House presided
over by President Clinton to be successful,'' Shaath said,
indicating that it was still too soon. ``You can't bridge oceans,
it's much easier to bridge rivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel has been eager for a summit
meeting, even as early as next week, in part because his
parliamentary coalition has been roiled by contention over the
terms of a peace with the Palestinians. Barak has calculated,
Israeli analysts say, that the sooner he can get a peace agreement,
one that he insists will ``strengthen'' Israel, the better it will
be for his political survival.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a sharp reversal from when he came to power 18 months ago,
Barak is now anxious for U.S. involvement to prod the peace effort
along.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, who has already invested considerable time coaxing
Barak and Arafat toward the finish line, time is running out. But
Albright declined to rule out a summit meeting during the
Democratic and Republican conventions in late July and August.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday with Albright, Barak said that
calling a summit was the prerogative of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to the president to make up his mind,'' Barak said.
``We will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Until now we have no agreement. The substantial
negotiation will begin only if and when there will be a summit
meeting and we will negotiate only an agreement that will
strengthen Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, on a second visit here in a month to set the stage for
a summit that Clinton hopes will be a crowning achievement of his
presidency, arrived as the administration's senior Middle East
envoy, Dennis Ross, completed a week of intense negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   There was serious activity on all fronts in the last week,
including a briefing by Ross of Barak's shaky coalition partners in
an effort to assuage them about the details of the negotiations.
There was also an unusually long, five-hour session last Sunday
between Arafat and Barak's chief negotiator, Shlomo Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Israel's justice minister, Yossi Beilin, flew to
Cairo to brief President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, who is seen as an
important link to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, the Israeli press has been deluged with
leaks in the Israeli press about the possible contours of a peace
agreement. These have included the notion of the Palestinians
receiving more than 90 percent of the West Bank, considerably more
than previously contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the key elements of the territorial issue, according
to knowledgeable officials, is that Arafat is demanding that if the
Palestinians do not receive 100 percent of the West Bank, they must
be compensated with Israeli land elsewhere, possibly in the Negev
near the Gaza strip. This sort of ``land swap'' has not been
discussed much in public and according to officials will be a
crucial ingredient of a summit.
</P>
<P>
   A common interpretation of the events of the past week was that
Arafat, emboldened by what he perceives as Barak's political need
for a quick summit, was holding out for as much as possible before
sitting down at the table.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader has been insisting that Barak must agree
to go ahead with the third further redeployment of the Israeli
military on the West Bank before a summit meeting is held. A new
delay until July 7 has been set for that.
</P>
<P>
   According to the second round of Oslo accords and its
amendments, the redeployment would leave Israel in control of only
Jerusalem, settlements and specified military zones. Barak, fearful
that such a concession could trigger the collapse of his
government, wants the redeployment folded into the final round of
talks.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official who has been here in the past
week said the Palestinians feel ``entitled'' to the further
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not something that I think they are going to change
their attitude on, but they also are prepared to accept the
president's decision on the timing of the summit,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever Clinton's decision on the timing of a summit,
Arafat and Barak had agreed to comply, the official said. ``If he
says: `Now is the time,' okay. If he says `I want to do something
else before proceeding to that,' okay,'' the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
