<SLUG> BC-GLF-UGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia lures golf coach from NCAA champion Arizona
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athens, Ga. _ When Arizona women's golf coach Todd McCorkle
contacted Georgia assistant athletics director Craig White nearly
two weeks ago, he was calling to recommend a friend for UGA's
vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, McCorkle became only the third coach in the 34-year
history of the Georgia women's golf program. McCorkle, 37, leaves
an Arizona team that this year produced one of the most successful
seasons in history, winning the NCAA title along with nine
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle replaces Beans Kelly, who retired last month after 15
seasons . Kelly led the Lady Dogs to seven Southeastern Conference
titles and was chosen 1998 coach of the year by Golfweek magazine
and the National Golf Coaches Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I contacted Georgia to recommend someone and they asked if I
was interested. Originally, I was fighting that because of the team
I had coming back to Arizona. But I came here for the interview and
saw how special this place and the people are. It really turned my
head,'' McCorkle said.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle, a 1986 graduate of UNC-Charlotte, played on the Ben
Hogan Tour in 1991-92. He began coaching in 1993 at Florida, where
he served as assistant men's coach from 1993-96 and also interim
women's head coach in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996-97, McCorkle was the men's and women's coach at Coastal
Carolina, before leaving for Arizona. He spent his first season at
Arizona as associate coach for both the men's and women's teams,
and then was named women's head coach in 1998. The Lady Wildcats
finished third and fourth at the 1998 and '99 NCAA Championships.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle said he was attracted to Georgia because of the
school's Boyd Golf Center, which includes a $1.2 million practice
facility and a $600,000 clubhouse completed last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the thing that impressed me the most. It just
shows the commitment Georgia has to golf,'' McCorkle said.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle inherits three players from a team that finished
seventh in this year's NCAAs. The Lady Dogs should also have back
sophomores Reilley Rankin and Summer Sirmons, who missed last
season because of injuries. Rankin was the 1998 SEC player of the
year and national freshman of the year.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle said he hopes to retain Georgia assistant coach Kelly
Hester, who also was a candidate to replace Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
