<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORAY-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL OSCARS GET ANIMATED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Goes with June Foray story) 
By RODNEY RICHEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While she still loves doing voices for animation, one of June
Foray's most passionate drives these days is regarding animation.
</P>
<P>
   As a longtime member of the Board of Governors for the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, she is advocating a new
category for the Academy Awards: Best Animated Motion Picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although animated films do qualify for the Best Picture
category, it is very unlikely that one could win against, say,
`American Beauty,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Foray adds that such a category, if approved, would be an
occasional one, brought out only when a sufficient number of strong
animated features had been released.
</P>
<P>
   That is a sticking point with the board, says John Pavlik,
director of communications for the academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have 10 animated feature films in a year, but none of
them is any good, and yet the number 10 triggers an automatic
nomination for two or three of them, that doesn't seem quite
fair,'' Pavlik says.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, if you go much beyond that, you're sort of
making a nomination impossible (given the number of animated films
released).''
</P>
<P>
   That the academy would be recognizing feature animation,
however, might spur increased production, Pavlik adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the goals in coming up with the Academy Awards
in the first place: trying to get producers to really think about
coming up with a quality product.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sticking point is a complex one: What constitutes an
``animated'' feature? Foray's ``The Adventures of Rocky and
Bullwinkle'' contains both animation and live action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a question that the board will have to address,''
Pavlik says. ``How much (animation) has to be in a film before we
call it an 'animated' film?''
</P>
<P>
   The absolute earliest such an award could be instituted would be
for the awards given out in 2002. The last new category added was
Best Makeup in 1964 (as an occasional award). The periodic award
for Best Visual Effects, established in 1936, was made an annual
award in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the academy, Pavlik says, does not like to add categories
and dilute the value of the Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think it would be a popular award,'' Pavlik says
of the proposal. ``The audience would enjoy it, and I think the
industry would enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a revered veteran of animation, from its Golden Age to the
present, Foray feels a sense of duty in pushing this cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an art form,'' she says. ``It used to be that Disney
was the only one making these, because ... Disney was the only one
with the wherewithal and the money. But there's been such an
explosion of interest in animation from DreamWorks, 20th Century
Fox, Warner Bros., and even foreign films,'' Foray says, citing
Japan's recent ``Princess Mononoke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People love animated films, and they do make money. At least
there would be a category for them, and they would have the
opportunity of winning.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      06-28 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON ENDORSES FOOD AND MEDICAL SALES TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday said he will likely
sign legislation allowing food and medical sales to Cuba because it
would help the Cuban people but not help the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   He also said a further thaw in U.S.-Cuba relations would await
steps by the Cuban government ``to reach out to us as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not specify what steps Cuban leader Fidel Castro
would have to take before better relations could be achieved
between the Communist island nation and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But he did say Castro has to do more to make amends for the 1996
incident in which Cuban fighter planes killed four anti-Castro
Cuban-Americans by shooting down two planes they were in. Cuba
claimed the planes were in Cuban air space, a charge the victims'
relatives and the Clinton administration denied.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation sponsored by Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.,
and agreed to Tuesday by House Republican leaders, the 40-year-old
U.S. trade embargo would be eased to allow sales of U.S. food,
medicine and medical products to Cuba, Sudan, Iran, Afghanistan and
Libya. However, Cuba could not buy other U.S. products and Cuba
could not sell its cigars, rum, sugar or other goods in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that while he favored selling food and medicine to
Cuba, he had questions about whether the Nethercutt proposal would
impede travel to Cuba. The president supports more travel between
the United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he prefers language in the already-passed Senate
version that would allow full sanctions to be reimposed, if needed,
to punish Cuba for bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would sign the Nethercutt legislation if these
questions can be answered, and he is convinced it ``will be a net
plus in terms of our strategy, which is to reach out to the Cuban
people without supporting the Cuban government.''
</P>
<P>
   Normal relations with Cuba cannot be achieved ``until there is a
bipartisan majority (that) believes that there has been some effort
on the part of the Cuban government to reach out to us as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking at a news conference, praised Vice President
Al Gore, saying: ``No person in the history of the republic has
ever had the positive impact on this country as vice president that
Al Gore has had. That is a historical fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said Gore's economic proposals are the best ones
for maintaining prosperity and that he better understands complex
technological problems facing the nation in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if (voters) know those three things about Al Gore,
it's still more likely than not that he will win,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   And he predicted Gore would defeat Texas Gov. George W. Bush
this fall, even though Bush is leading Gore by five points or more
in most polls. Gore has been dogged by reports of conflict within
the Justice Department over appointing a special prosecutor to
investigate Gore's involvement in possibly illegal campaign
fundraising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno rejected the latest call from
Justice Department task force chief Robert Conrad for an
independent probe of Gore, and on Tuesday told Congress she had
received no White House pressure to block the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has ``made a very compelling case'' in dealing with
campaign finance questions, ``and certainly demonstrated that a lot
of the accusations against him ... are not so,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately ``the best thing to do is for the American people
to make their own judgments about it,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   On Gore, Clinton said voters were ``still trying to figure out
what they think about this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to navigate his way through what he termed a ``dead-bang
loser'' question on whether Bush is intelligent enough to run the
nation, Clinton said a president must combine intelligence with
curiosity, broad experience and ability to sort out the important
from the not-so-important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for a president not to try to micromanage
the presidency,'' he said. ``It's a `deciding' job.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his plans after leaving the White House, Clinton
joked: ``Maybe I'll run for the school board someday. That's about
the only thing I can imagine doing. I don't have any other plans. I
just want to be a good citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments on Cuba came just hours before a jet took
six-year-old Elian Gonzalez and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
home to Cuba after a seven-month battle with the Gonzalez family's
Miami relatives over whether the boy would stay in the United
States or return to Cuba. The U.S. Supreme Court declined to act on
the Miami family's final petition to obtain asylum for the boy,
clearing the way for the departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he and his father decided they wanted to stay here, it
would be fine with me,'' Clinton said. ``Do I wish it had unfolded
in a less dramatic, less traumatic way for all concerned? Of
course, I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also warned the oil industry that ``we're running a
serious investigation'' into soaring gasoline prices. He noted pump
prices have dropped by about 8 cents a gallon in the Midwest since
the Federal Trade Commission ordered an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a long term energy policy'' to avoid abrupt gas-price
hikes in the future, the president said. ``Inherently there's
nothing wrong'' with suspending all of part of the federal gasoline
tax to ease prices, but that Congress would have to examine the
possibility of losing revenues on highway construction projects
funded through those taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
