A7534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-VOLUME0629-COX     06-28 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-VOLUME0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sales projections ignite Coke stock
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola shares closed at their highest level in five
months Wednesday after the company said stronger markets around the
world are boosting sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based beverage giant said it expects case sales in
the second quarter to increase 5 percent to 6 percent. That
compared with a lackluster 3.5 percent in the first quarter and a
decline of 2 percent in last year's second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus on a localized marketing strategy is allowing us to
strengthen our relationships with consumers around the world,''
Chairman Doug Daft said in a prepared statement. ``This approach,
along with increasing economic stability in most regions of the
world, is resulting in improving volume trends during the second
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Case volume _ the amount of product moved _ is a key indicator
of the company's financial health.
</P>
<P>
   The company's announcement propelled its shares to $60, up
$2.13, on almost double the normal trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the stock is likely to trade in the low $60s,
predicted Sanford Bernstein analyst Bill Pecoriello. He expects it
to hit $70 within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Already, investors have been warming up to the stock. So far
this quarter, Coke shares have climbed nearly 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several important new things going on at Coke _ new
management, a new focus and a new global marketing and ad campaign
for brand Coke,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of
Beverage Digest. ``The company's turnaround has clearly begun and
is gaining momentum. It's clear that healthier and more prosperous
times lie ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the recently acquired Cadbury Schweppes brands in 161
nations outside the United States, case sales are still expected to
grow 3.5 percent to 4.5 percent in the second quarter. That
compared with 2 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   UBS Warburg analyst Caroline Levy was not impressed with the
announcement, downgrading the stock to a ``hold'' from a ``strong
buy.'' But other analysts viewed it more positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged,'' said Goldman Sachs analyst Marc Cohen.
``This is probably the first time in 12 quarters that they seem to
be on the mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who currently recommends the stock, said he expects
``even more acceleration in the second half of the year. The
indications that they're at or modestly ahead of what we
anticipated for the second quarter makes us more comfortable that
they're on their way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst Andrew Conway, who has a
``neutral'' rating on the stock, said anticipated volume growth in
the second half of the year of 5.5 percent to 6 percent ``is not a
slam dunk.'' Still, Conway added, ``Coke is poised to experience
earnings-per-share growth in fiscal years 2000 and 2001 for the
first time in several years.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, Daft said the company remains
comfortable with analysts' earnings estimates averaging 41 cents a
share, compared with 38 cents a year ago, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, Daft said the company is confident that it
will hit its previously announced target of 5 percent to 6 percent
volume growth, including the Schweppes brands. That would still,
however, be under Coca-Cola's long-term goal of growing case sales
at 7 percent to 8 percent a year. But it would considerably
overshadow last year's growth of only 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of work to do to bring the company back to
full stride,'' Cohen said. Next year, he predicts case sales will
rise 6 percent to 7 percent before returning to the long-term
target of 7 percent to 8 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Europe and Eurasia, where market
conditions had been dragging down the company's sales recently, are
expected to post the best volume results because of strong gains in
Germany, Spain and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Case sales for the region are expected to grow a robust 11
percent to 12 percent. Those figures are getting a partial boost
because of the comeback from last June's recall of company
beverages in Belgium that depressed sales there and in several
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, volume is expected to increase 2 percent in
the quarter, partly because of the prize-winning promotion on Coke
Classic cans, said company spokesman Robert Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Africa and the Middle East region is the only
place where case sales are expected to decline, excluding the
Schweppes brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more volatility than normal in Africa due to floods,
wars and other unfortunate incidents,'' Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
