<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-COX     06-28 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A headline would go in here jj like so for story
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Her name might be Mao, but she is no Maoist.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a Marxist, heaven forbid.
</P>
<P>
   As she sat in an office tower, gleaming in the sun above her
native Hong Kong's busy but picturesque harbor, Elley Mao sounded
far more like the capitalist imperialists who put her city on the
map of commerce in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The impeccably tailored Mao is an economist for the government
of Hong Kong and a life-long resident of the former British crown
colony that reverted to China at the stroke of midnight three years
ago July 1.
</P>
<P>
   As the whole world knows, many anticipated the change with
trepidation. Fearing the potentially heavy hand of communist rule,
thousands of Hong Kong's 6.7 million residents fled in the decade
before the handover _ if they were lucky enough to land passports
allowing their departure. Many of the overseas companies who do
business here _ now numbering more than 5,600, including 1,100 U.S.
businesses _ devised quick exit strategies to exercise if the rule
of law under which they had operated collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But three years later, people have become accustomed to seeing
China's red flag flying where the Union Jack once flapped in the
uncertain breezes. And so far, Mao said, unification has brought
more symbolic than substantive changes. The fears were unfounded
and the message from the mainland has been a reassuring one, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the Beijing government said it would not
interfere with capitalism as usual in the area now designated a
Special Administrative Region of China. To this point, it has been
good to its word. And _ as Hong Kong begins its fourth year under
the Chinese flag _ the commercial outpost on the South China Sea
remains as eagerly open for business as ever. Commercials running
on local television even claim it is ``the best place in the world
for business.''
</P>
<P>
   The transfer of power, in fact, may have had less impact on Hong
Kong's economy than the Asian economic crisis that rippled through
the region's tiger economies soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   With the relatively quick recoveries in neighboring nations,
however, the world's ninth largest trading economy has been
rebounding since last year, Mao said. Today, both trade and
domestic retail demand are on the upswing, and Hong Kong has moved
onto the fast-track in adjusting to the new global era of a
knowledge-based high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even tourism, which hit a low of 9.5 million visitors in 1998,
the year after the handover, is again on the upswing. Hong Kong
expects 11.4 million visitors this year, just off the 11.7 million
of 1996, and it is moving full swing to develop new attractions,
including a Disney amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   If some people feared change after the British left, others as
eagerly welcomed the end of the colonial era. And they, too, seem
relatively pleased at the way events have unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``From China's angle, the return of Hong Kong to China is a very
important milestone in China's history,'' said Bassanio So, acting
Deputy Secretary for Constitutional Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   It was a milestone for Hong Kong residents, too, most of whom
think of themselves as Chinese, culturally and historically, said
Chu Wing-yin, a tour guide who urges English speakers to call her
``Winnie, as in Winnie the Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's school children may know little of contemporary
Chinese history or politics, but they grow up taking pride in
China's ancient dynasties, she said. And Chinese traditions have
always flourished here despite the city's cosmopolitan and outward
-looking lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, differences between Hong Kong and Beijing persist _
even in language.
</P>
<P>
   Though children are now being taught Mandarin _ the prevailing
dialect on the mainland _ many older Hong Kong residents speak only
Cantonese, Chu said. If she traveled to Beijing, she said, ``I do
not speak the language there so I would need a tour guide.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though half of Hong Kong's people live in public housing
and only a tiny percentage are among the super rich living in the
elegant mansions pointed out to tourists, Hong Kong residents often
speak with pride about ``our capitalist way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   And, even though only a limited form of democracy has been
developed to date, the people are committed to such ideas as
universal suffrage and human rights, So said.
</P>
<P>
   Free speech and public dissent are well-entrenched traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, Hong Kong police scuffled with dozens of
protestors who had moved here from the mainland but were being
denied the right to stay. That same day, disgruntled home owners
demonstrated against falling property prices and government doctors
publically protested against reductions in starting salaries.
Social workers, meanwhile, were marching to protest changes in
welfare funding.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the annual anniversary of the massacre of democracy
protestors in Beijing's Tiananmen Square always brings a major
protest _ one that would be instantly snuffed out by the
authorities in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, not all the legal aspects of having ``one country, two
systems,'' as the glib phrase goes, have been ironed out, So
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Fengchao, deputy director of China's liaison office in Hong
Kong, set off a furor in April when he told journalists to stop
reporting views that diverge from Beijing's official line on the
future of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   And thorny conflicts likely will continue to arise. The migrants
from the mainland who were protesting Sunday, for instance, were
granted residency rights in a Hong Kong that were effectively
revoked when Beijing lawmakers declared the ruling wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hong Kong was granted full autonomy for 50 years
except in defense and foreign affairs, ``there must be some
interface'' in its relations with China and Chinese law, So said.
</P>
<P>
   In issues that do not directly involve relations between Hong
Kong and China, also, the former colony's government remains a work
in progress. While activists are pushing to expand self-government,
the makeup and scope of the legislature long-term are of the New
York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
