u w BC-COX-AIRLINE-COMPLAINT     06-28 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS-0629 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIRLINES: TRAFFIC CONTROL SYSTEM TO BLAME FOR MANY DELAYS
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airline representatives told the Senate Commerce
Committee Wednesday they have improved customer service but said
they're not entirely to blame for an increase in flight delays,
cancellations and missed connections.
</P>
<P>
   Aging air traffic control equipment has left planes on the
runways too long, backing up traffic and contributing to delays and
missed connections, said representatives from Continental and Delta
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some would blame the FAA for most of the delays, but the fact
is that they are doing the very best to keep up by managing our
aging and overburdened traffic control system with inadequate
resources and equipment,'' said Mary Jopplin, senior director for
customer service at Continental.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Congress considered enacting a ``passenger bill of
rights'' after a flood of complaints about delays and
cancellations. In one January 1999 incident, hundreds of passengers
were stuck in planes on runways in Detroit for up to eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines avoided the legislation after pledging to provide
better service. Instead, the Air Transportation Association of
America and 14 of its member airlines adopted a 12-point Customer
Service Commitment, which pledged to offer the lowest fares
available, provide prompt ticket refunds, and be more responsive to
customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing was to review the airlines' efforts to
improve service. The Inspector General's office for the U.S.
Department of Transportation has completed an interim review and
will issue a final report at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., challenged the
airlines to implement air traffic control reform if they are sure
that is the root of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge them to throw their weight and momentum behind a
serious, realistic plan for air traffic control reform. Otherwise
they will be accused of trying to shift the blame,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said delays have increased by more than 50 percent
and cancellations by 68 percent in the last five years. Most of the
delays occur after planes leave the gate. At the 28 largest U.S.
airports, the number of flights having delays of an hour or more
during taxi out times _ the time between leaving the gate and
taking off _ increased 130 percent between 1995 and 1999, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite an enormous effort, we are still not getting the
results that either you or we would like,'' Don Carty, the ATAA's
executive committee chairman, told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   One possible remedy is three years away. When it is completed,
the fifth runway at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport will
significantly decrease traffic at one of the country's busiest
airports, said Vicki Escarra, executive vice president for customer
service at Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland D-Ga., said the additional runway is key to
improving service in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The report) will provide us and the carriers with a good
yardstick by which to measure the industry's performance and
indicate areas for improvement,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   The report found some airlines have invested in advanced baggage
scanning technologies to speed up the claims process for delayed
baggage. Other airlines were not consistent at returning baggage
within the 24 hours agreed to by the airlines, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, customers can often obtain cheaper fares on the
Internet than over the telephone, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Mead, DOT's inspector general, said the industry has a
long way to go to fix all the problems.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the airlines do, ``there will still be delays
next summer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.oig.dot.gov/newwhatnew.htm
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
