<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ELIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN-FRIENDLY POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez went home Wednesday to a grateful Fidel Castro,
who with the help of Castro's Cuban-American enemies in Miami, used
the boy's plight in his decades-long effort to mask a failed
revolution. Cuban-Americans pursued their own failed policies this
week by toughening an innocuous bill to permit US agricultural
exports to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Elian ought to heve been returned to his father a
week or two after he was found off Florida in November. Now that
he's finally back home, the key question becomes what happens to
him and all the other Cubans once Castro, now 73, dies or otherwise
leaves power.
</P>
<P>
   The US economic embargo and political pressure have failed for
40 years to topple the Castro regime. It makes better sense to
engage the Cuban government and people with economic and
person-to-person contacts in the hope that Americans can influence
the Cubans toward political and economic freedom without
diminishing the gains made by the revolution in health and
education.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders of the House, in league with two
Cuban-American representatives from Florida, want no part of this.
They toughened a bill allowing agricultural sales so that Cuba
would not be able to get US loans and sought to codify into law the
presidential restrictions on Americans visiting the island.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans were unlikely to get many loans, and the travel language
allows the president to continue to show some discretion. So the
bill ought to be passed, despite these provisions. However, the
attitude behind the stronger wording suggests an inflexibility that
will make it harder for the United States to influence Cuban policy
whenever Castro goes.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is unfazed by the future. ``When a true revolution is
consolidated,'' he said last week, ``. . . no man, no matter how
important his personal contribution might have been, is
indispensable.''
</P>
<P>
   Change is inevitable, however. The United States has enormous
interests in making sure Cuba becomes democratic and prosperous
enough to discourage mass flight from the island. Cuban-Americans
will help Elian best by encouraging peaceful change, even if they
have to endure their bearded nemesis for a few years longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7539 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SCOTUS-BOS &LR;      06-28 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SCOTUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO CLOSE FOR COMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most unsettling about the Supreme Court term that ended with a
flurry Wednesday is the number of important cases decided by close
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Women have the right to choose a rare abortion procedure, the
Boy Scouts have the right to reject gay troop leaders, and persons
convicted of hate crimes have the right to sentences set by juries
as a result of decisions handed down this week. But all these
rights are guaranteed by the slimmest of margins _ 5-4 divisions of
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Only a slighter wider margin, 6-3, allows government to send
educational materials to religious schools and guarantees an
eight-foot buffer to persons entering an abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars like to say that the law is a living body, always
evolving. But this court is forcing too many people to live too
close to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   The most troubling of Wednesday's decisions was the one
legitimizing the unconscionable homophobic bias of the Boy Scouts.
James Dale, a Cub Scout at 8 and Boy Scout at 11, made Eagle Scout
at age 17 and the following year was named assistant scoutmaster of
Troop 73 in Matawan, N.J. Sixteen months later, local Scout
officials saw a newspaper story quoting Dale, then a student at
Rutgers, about a conference on gay and lesbian adolescents. The
officials dumped Dale, and he sued.
</P>
<P>
   To Dale, the Scout admonition to be ``morally straight'' meant
``to respect and defend the rights of all people.'' But the court
ruled that the Scouts are a private group entitled to restrict its
message rather than a public accommodation like the Jaycees, which
was forced to admit women under a 1984 ruling. No matter that Dale
made no effort to send a gay message. In its contorted decision,
the five-person court majority prevailed over the four dissenters
and a unanimous New Jersey Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Close court decisions can become solid law. The 1966 Miranda
ruling, requiring police to inform suspects of their rights, came
on a contentious 5-4 vote but was affirmed this week by a
comfortable 7-2 opinion. More often, 5-4 votes make all parties
nervous that the decisions themselves are fragile.
</P>
<P>
   These narrow majorities should send a clear message to voters to
consider the future of the court when they choose a president in
November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-VIDEO-INDEPENDENCE-LA     06-28 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-INDEPENDENCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATE `INDEPENDENCE DAY'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year during the Fourth of July celebration, Americans show
their independence (at least from critical demands) by cramming
themselves in multiplexes to gawk at Hollywood's latest blockbuster
offerings rife with expensive action and special-effect sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do any of these films make critics' top-10 lists, but,
hey, so what? In 1996, the team of Roland Emmerich and Dean Devlin
rolled out ``Independence Day,'' a story of locust-like aliens that
invade Earth. The plot, many critics thought, resembled a bad '50s
sci-fi film. But Emmerich and Devlin, who are currently responsible
for turning Mel Gibson into a Mad Max-like ``Patriot,'' charged
ahead with so much panache that the ``biggest B movie of all
time,'' as Variety called it, turned out to be a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week _ in true blockbuster fashion _ Fox released
the ``Five Star Collection Independence Day,'' a two-disc DVD. The
first disc includes a special edition of the film with nine
additional minutes of footage.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the scenes help clarify the relationship between Randy
Quaid, a drunken crop duster and former Vietnam War pilot who had
been abducted by aliens (that description alone is enough to make
most critics cringe). While they fit fairly seamlessly into the
film, they don't really add much to it, either. The scene where a
crazed scientist (Brent Spiner) shows off the inner workings of the
alien spacecraft to computer scientist David (Jeff Goldblum) does
have some wit to it, though. Disc 1 also includes scene commentary
from Devlin and Emmerich, as well as special-effects wizards Volker
Engel and Doug Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting stuff is on Disc 2, which includes the original
ending, where Quaid's character destroys the alien spacecraft while
flying a biplane instead of a jet fighter. Even Devlin and Emmerich
found this too ludicrous, but it's a hoot to watch. The disc also
includes a 30-minute making of-documentary, which explains the wide
range of the special effects used in the movie, an alien invasion
``mockumentary'' and HBO's ``First Look'' featurette. Some of this
is overkill; we learn in minute detail how they blow up the White
House (it was a miniature).
</P>
<P>
   What comes through is just how much effort and thought was put
into creating this film. Makes you glad they weren't trying to take
over the world. Mmmm, maybe they were.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Speaking of Mel: Though George Miller's ``The Road
Warrior'' (1981) _ the second part of the Mad Max trilogy _ made
Mel Gibson a star in America, it was Richard Donner's ``Lethal
Weapon'' in 1987 that made him a superstar. Earlier in the month,
Warners released the director's cut of the first three films in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   As Martin Riggs, the suicidal ex-Vietnam War special-service vet
turn L.A. detective, Gibson is a hero with an edge _ cool but
vulnerable. Danny Glover as his older partner makes a nice
counterpoint. As they chase after the bad guys, their buddy
relationship develops giving what would be a might have been just a
run-of-the-mill action picture an emotional underpinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``LW2'' (1989) is the best of the four films and introduces Joe
Pesci as an accountant on the run from the mob who the boys have to
guard, and in doing so, Donner cranked up the humor also using it
to take advantage of Gibson and Glover's onscreen chemistry. All
three DVDs, as expected, contain additional scenes.
</P>
<P>
   OK, ``Independence Day'' and ``Lethal Weapon'' aren't new, but
they're still fun and you won't have to wait in line at your local
cineplex. &QL; 
----- &QL; 
The ```Independence Day: Special Edition'' is $34.98. The price of
the ``Director's Cut'' DVD of the first three ``Lethal Weapon''
films is $24.90 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
