<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-STORM-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECT STORM, IMPERFECT MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm'' lives up to its title. But that doesn't
mean its a good movie. While the technicians at Industrial Light &AMP;
Magic have worked overtime to create a roiling squall that will
have you reaching for some Dramamine, the film rarely manages to
generate much in the way of suspense or terror. You might as well
stay home and watch the Weather Channel; at least then, you wont
have to suffer through the godawful dialogue here.
</P>
<P>
   This is a movie that's great as long as nobody talks.
Unfortunately, there's a lot of yakking in Bill Wittliff's witless
adaptation of Sebastian Junger's best-seller, not to mention
shallow characterizations and trumped- up drama. Director Wolfgang
Petersen, who knows a thing or two about water with ``Das Boot'' on
his resume, doesn't help matters much, either, clumsily cutting
from story to story without genuinely conveying the horror of the
films events.
</P>
<P>
   Junger's book certainly offered plenty of rich detail, but,
typically, the film version has discarded anything approaching
complexity, instead throwing out by-the-numbers chum, thinking the
audience will bite. In fact, the condescending writing here seems
to assume most moviegoers area bunch of dolts since it has the
characters spell out in bland detail exactly what's happening at
any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   The most annoying example of this patronizing approach occurs
during the movie's initial set-up, which is all about conveying the
hardships and dangers of a fisherman's life. Watching the movie,
you'd think these guys were going to the moon or Omaha Beach during
D-Day instead of trolling for swordfish off the local coast. And
did we really need Chris McDonald's boorish weatherman to stupidly
explain the storms ferocity? Wouldn't a snippet from a local
newscast have sufficed?
</P>
<P>
   The film's central characters are the crew of the Andrea Gail, a
group of Gloucester, Mass., fishermen who, after a string of
disappointing catches, venture out into the North Atlantic looking
for one last haul. Their timing couldn't have been worse, with
three storms _ a hurricane moving up the coast from Bermuda, a cold
front sweeping down from Canada and a North Atlantic gale _
converging at once, creating massive waves and a mountain of water
that's swallowing everything in its path.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's captain (George Clooney) must decide whether to stay
in safe waters and lose his precious cargo of swordfish (the boat's
ice machine has broken, so the fish don't have a long shelf life)
or brave the storm and head back to harbor. Complicating matters is
the loss of the ship's radio antennae, which limits the captain's
knowledge about the weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A parallel story involving a Coast Guard rescue of a sailboat
takes up much of the latter half of the film and is often more
interesting than the events surrounding the fishermen. But then,
once the movie lands in the heart of the storm, it becomes vastly
more entertaining anyway, even if Petersen can't quite figure out a
way to move between the two tales, which is partially due to the
unpredictability of the story's events.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, John C. Reilly are among the actors who
try to flesh out characters that are as wooden as an old seafarer's
peg leg; Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio plays a rival fishing captain
trying to warn the Gail of the severity of the storm. The waves, of
course, are the real stars of the movie, and they're rendered
convincingly, even as the rest of ``The Perfect Storm'' is
submerged in stupidity. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``The Perfect Storm''; (PG-13; language and scenes of
peril). &QL; 
The stars: George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio, John C. Reilly. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Wolfgang Petersen; screenplay by
Bill Wittliff, based on the book by Sebastian Junger. Released by
Warner Bros. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 9 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
