<SLUG> BC-GENUITY-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET COOL TO GENUITY IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genuity Inc.'s initial stock sale _ one of the year's biggest
public offerings _ received an unenthusiastic reception on Wall
Street Wednesday amid concerns over the Internet company's massive
losses and future ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet-infrastructure firm, based in
Burlington, &UR;  &LR; Mass., still managed to end the day as one of
Massachusetts's corporate giants. With a market capitalization of
about $9 billion, Genuity joins the same league that counts as its
members Raytheon Co., Gillette Co., EMC Corp., and CMGI Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Genuity dropped $1.59375 on the Nasdaq to close at
$9.40625, even as technology stocks rallied following the Federal
Reserve's decision to leave interest rates untouched. The company's
173.9 million shares were initially priced at $11 _ short of the
anticipated range of $12 to $15.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the IPO's underwriters misjudged the demand
for such a large offering. Genuity spooked investors who have grown
wary of money-losing Internet firms. Since April, a cruel month for
technology stocks, the markets have become kinder _ but not to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of coming back,'' said Mary Lupo, an analyst with
Renaissance Capital IPO Aftermarket Fund in Greenwich, Conn. ``But
it also depends on what kind of company it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, investors warmly greeted microchip maker Marvell
Technology Group Ltd. and software firm Click Commerce Inc.,
turning their IPOs this week into successes. But these companies
have turned a profit. Genuity, on the other hand, lost $626.7
million on revenue of $750.4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are showing tremendous losses at a time when losses are
no longer fashionable,'' said Pascal Aguirre, vice president of
Renaissance Strategy, a Boston-based consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also may be leery of paying top dollar for shares in a
firm that could eventually be controlled by the nation's largest
local telephone company, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   GTE is spinning off Genuity so it can satisfy federal regulators
and merge with Bell Atlantic Corp., creating telephone service
giant Verizon Communications. As part of the deal, which is
expected to close by the end of the month, Verizon is being forced
to divest all but 9.5 percent of Genuity.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the catch: Verizon could repurchase up to 82 percent
of Genuity if local telephone service in the 13 states covered by
Bell Atlantic is successfully opened to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it's a Bell Atlantic company,'' said Drake
Johnstone, an analyst with the investment firm Davenport &AMP; Co. in
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as GTE Internetworking, Genuity can trace its
lineage back to the Web's Wild West days. Its predecessor, Bolt,
Beranek &AMP; Newman, designed the foundation for today's Internet and
pioneered the use of the (at) symbol so widely used in e-mail
messaging.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Genuity is one of the largest Internet backbone companies
in the nation, operating more than 17,000 miles of fiber-optic
cables carrying and directing Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity gets most of its revenue from Internet access charges,
with its biggest customer, America Online, making up 52 percent of
its sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity plans to use much of the $1.9 billion raised in its
initial public offering to better position to expand its
fiber-optic network and expand its Web-site hosting business and
other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot of positives going for it,'' said Steve Tuen, an
analyst with IPO Value Monitor. ``Bell Atlantic and GTE should be
big backers of Genuity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Genuity will face strong competition from a host of
companies, including Sprint and Cable &AMP; Wireless. Its strongest
rival is WorldCom's UUNet Technologies division, which has the
largest piece of the Internet access business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genuity is losing a pot-load of money, while I think most
people in this marketplace realize that UUNet is a cash cow for
WorldCom,'' analyst Johnstone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
