<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7552 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FED-RATES-BOS &LR;      06-28 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASED WITH `MODERATING' GROWTH, FED STANDS PAT ON RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a summer respite after a series of interest-rate
increases, the Federal Reserve Board voted Wednesday against
raising rates further amid signs US economic growth may be
``moderating.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed's decision was widely expected and caused barely a
ripple on Wall Street, what was not expected was so explicit a
statement by the Fed sizing up the status of the nation's
unprecedented economic expansion. ``Recent data suggests that the
expansion of aggregate demand may be moderating toward a pace
closer to the rate of growth of the economy's potential to
produce,'' the Fed said in a policy statement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite encouraging signs of a slowdown, the Fed adopted an
official ``bias'' toward further rate hikes in the future if
inflationary pressures do not ease.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee, which has added 1.75
percentage points to the federal funds rate since last June in six
rounds of tightening, voted to leave the rate unchanged at 6.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's statement, which left plenty of room to
boost rates, possibly at their next meeting August 22, also
contained striking contrasts _ noting signs of slowdown and a
potential easing of inflationary pressures while remaining on alert
about inflation. This was read by some analysts as an indication of
spirited debate among Fed members in reaching the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was obviously a good deal of debate, particularly about
whether this slowdown is temporary or could be more permanent,''
said David Jones, a veteran Fed watcher for Aubrey Lanston &AMP; Co. in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The US economy in the fourth quarter of last year posted 7.3
percent growth in real gross domestic product, a pace more typical
of a developing economy than the world's biggest industrial
producer. In the first quarter, growth slowed to a
still-breathtaking 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Fed implied the economy, in the second quarter, may be
shifting to a lower gear. This marked a change from past policy
statements in which members indicated growth was far outpacing
available supply, putting a strain on resources and the pool of
workers and stoking inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the Fed's primary evidence of a slowdown were
federal data showing the private sector shrank its payrolls by
116,000 in June _ a report economists view as inconclusive _ and
more compelling data showing sales of automobiles and homes were
slowing.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of softening retail sales, the Conference
Board in New York reported just hours prior to the FOMC meeting
that its widely watched index of consumer confidence slid nearly
six points in June. Consumers, which account for about two-thirds
of total US demand, have been a powerful engine of the nation's
growth during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is nevertheless far from conclusive, and there are
other indicators _ durable goods orders, for example _ that show
growth continues at a breakneck pace, offering no assurance that a
``soft landing'' is in the works as a result of the Fed's actions
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market had little reaction to the Fed action and ended
the day at nearly the same levels reached prior to the
late-afternoon decision. The Dow Jones industrial stock average
gained 23.33 points Wednesday, closing at 10,527.79, while the
technology-dominated Nasdaq rose 81.38 points to 3940.34.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Sinai, president of Primark Decision Economics in Boston,
noted the FOMC when it sits down to debate policy again in August
will have the advantage of two more months of data, on prices,
wages and second-quarter growth on which to base a decision.
</P>
<P>
   At the June meeting, Fed members faced more questions than they
had answers, highlighting the difficulty of fine-tuning the US
economy. ``A slowdown is there, but is it for real. And if it's for
real, what is its pace? And beyond that, what would be the response
of inflation?'' Sinai said. ``The bottom line for the Fed is
containing inflation risk. There's a long way to go to concluding
the future risk on inflation is diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's remarks about inflation acknowledged ``core''
inflation _ the consumer price index minus energy and housing _ has
accelerated slightly over the past year. That seemed a nod to
arguments made publicly by Laurence Meyer, a vocal inflation hawk
on the FOMC.
</P>
<P>
   But, the committee, bowing to more dovish sentiments of its
chairman, Alan Greenspan, said inflation seems to have a
counterbalance in the high levels of productivity of US workers,
which ``have been containing costs and holding down inflationary
pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever vigilant about inflation, the Fed said it would continue to
hold a bias in favor of tightening in the future, repeating a
stance in the May meeting and using language that has become
boilerplate in recent months. The FOMC ``believes the risks
continue to be weighted mainly toward conditions that may generate
heightened inflation pressures in the foreseeable future,'' the Fed
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's view on inflation ``is bi-polar,'' said Richard
Yamarone, chief economist for Argus Research Corp., a New York
research company. ``On the one hand, their statement implies
inflationary pressures have not subsided,'' he said, yet ``they
refrained from raising rates. What's the real answer?''
</P>
<P>
   John Zaehringer, chief economist in the Boston office of Loomis
Sayles &AMP; Co., predicted the Fed would raise rates by 25 basis
points in August. The central bank, in choosing not to tighten, has
accepted the risk it may be opening a door to inflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed has accepted that risk several times in the past few
years'' and its success in reading inflation signals and reacting
prudently to them has been ``one of Greenspan's triumphs as
chairman of the Fed,'' Zaehringer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
