<P>
   SCOTUS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday
by a 5-4 vote that because the procedure widely known as ``partial
birth abortion'' may be the most medically appropriate way of
terminating some pregnancies, the government cannot prohibit
doctors from performing it. The decision declared unconstitutional
the Nebraska law before the court, as well as, in effect, the laws
of 30 other states. In addition, the bill to create a federal ban
on the procedure, which President Clinton has vetoed twice and
which may reach his desk again this year, would also be
unconstitutional under the court's analysis: Like all the other
laws, it does not contain an exception for the health of the
pregnant woman. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAY-SCOUTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday by a 5-4 vote that the Boy Scouts have a constitutional
right to exclude gay members because opposition to homosexuality
was part of the organization's ``expressive message.'' Writing for
the court Wednesday, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said the
court intended neither to approve nor disapprove the Boy Scouts'
views on the subject, but that the First Amendment's protection for
freedom of association meant that the state could not compel the
Boy Scouts ``to accept members where such acceptance would derogate
from the organization's expressive message.'' By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
