<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECHWORKS-PORTAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEECHWORKS TO OFFER PORTAL LINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speech technology start-up SpeechWorks International of Boston
is moving to grab a leadership position in the emerging Web ``voice
portal'' business, announcing it is offering a new open-source
software to link speech portals to each other.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that resembles the Linux open-source software
programming code movement, SpeechWorks is making public a system
companies could use to develop and interconnect sites on which
people call in by phone and use their voice to request news
information that is then read back to them, or conduct transactions
such as buying stocks and airplane tickets.
</P>
<P>
   With open-source programming, instead of being able to reach
only individual companies or sites linked to services such as
TellMe, people might be able to call one number and reach hundreds
of different sites, using their voices to skip among them as they
would a mouse to click among Web pages on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   As the start-up gears up for an initial public offering this
summer, SpeechWorks officials are gambling that by giving away
their so-called voice XML code, they can fuel faster growth in the
voice portal business and take a big piece of a more quickly
growing pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today there are really no standards for linking'' voice
portals ``and no standards for browsing,'' said Steve Chambers,
SpeechWorks marketing vice president. ``We really want to offer
this as our version of the hypertext link in the Web world.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the technology fueling products SpeechWorks is rolling
out, including a SpeechBrowser and an internetworking system called
SpeechLinks, comes from AT&AMP;T Labs, in particular its vocabulary of
1 million words that can be interpreted through speech recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The phone giant earlier this month took an unspecified stake in
SpeechWorks as part of a deal giving the company access to vast
troves of AT&AMP;T speech technology.
</P>
<P>
   An example of how the new technology might work would be someone
calling an airline voice portal to hear times for a flight to New
York, book the flight, then ask to be transferred to a hotel
booking speech site, make a reservation, and ask to be transferred
to a restaurant search service and a Broadway show ticket agency.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of those businesses do not have speech-activated Web
portals. And if they do, there normally is no easy way to go from
one to the next without starting a new phone call.
</P>
<P>
   SpeechWorks, California-based Nuance, Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, and
other companies have developed to date about 300 speech sites in
the United States, according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   With Americans buying wireless phones at the rate of one every
2.5 seconds and early versions of wireless Net access over phones
showing severe limitations, many industry analysts think Web-based
sites that respond to spoken commands will prove far more popular
with people than using the phone keypad to have information
displayed on the phone screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
