<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-INVEST-ART-1     06-28 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-INVEST-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN VETERAN LEADING CHASE'S AMBITIOUS EFFORT IN INVESTMENT
BANKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is Chase Manhattan Bank ready, finally, to join the
big leagues of investment banking?
</P>
<P>
   This is the bank, after all, that was practically a laughing
stock on Wall Street a couple of years ago when it so visibly
failed to persuade Merrill Lynch or any other big-name brokerage
firm to accept a takeover bid. Instead, it settled for consolation
prizes, agreeing to pay billions of dollars to acquire the
much-smaller Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, which specializes in technology,
and Robert Fleming Holdings, a venerable London merchant banking
firm.
</P>
<P>
   So when Chase announced in late May that it had agreed to buy
the obscure Beacon Group for an estimated $450 million _ an
investment banking boutique started by Geoffrey T. Boisi, a former
star at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. _ it looked to some like yet another
expensive acquisition in a piecemeal attempt at building an
investment banking presence.
</P>
<P>
   For years Chase has been the place corporations turned to when
they needed money to finance their own acquisitions, a business
synonymous with the hostile takeovers of the 1980s. But to compete
with Morgan Stanley, Goldman, Merrill Lynch and the like _ all of
which excel not only in finance but also in the much more
prestigious and lucrative specialities of providing merger advice
and offering new stock to the public _ Chase needed to look and act
more like them.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, for all its success in commercial banking on a global
scale, has an image problem in the clubbier precincts of Wall
Street. And that was only reinforced earlier this year when James
B. Lee Jr., the 18-year veteran head of investment banking at
Chase, was championed on the cover of Forbes magazine, complete
with a list of takeover targets and this message to Chase clients:
``We'll write you a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street insiders were struck by how Lee (universally called
Jimmy within the business) appeared as a promotional, highly
aggressive '80s-style power broker. So much so, claimed Michael
Mayo, a senior bank analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston, a
competitor, that institutional shareholders he talked to ``actually
sold shares based on that Forbes story.'' He added, ``It was
arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a shock when Chase announced, as part of the
Beacon acquisition, that Lee, 47, would spend more time with
clients and that Boisi would become his boss. The not-so-subtle
signal, analysts said, was that Chase was willing to go to any
lengths to join the inner circle, even at the risk of alienating
Lee, one of the most powerful executives at Chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy did a fantastic job building Chase's business,'' Mayo
said. ``But this shows how much the bank is committed to going to
the next level. There are different personalities needed for
different times in a company's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Boisi, 53, is indeed a different personality, a well-regarded
adviser who for 21 years thrived in the intense but self-effacing
business atmosphere at Goldman. He reached the third most powerful
spot there before leaving in the early 1990s after failing to be
named to the top position at the firm that was taken by senior
partners Robert Rubin and Stephen Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   His comeback was engineered by William Harrison, Chase's chief
executive, who surprised Boisi during a routine strategy session in
early May when he asked him to join the company. For more than two
years Boisi had been advising Chase's top echelon, first Walter
Shipley and then, after he retired as chief executive, Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt they had similar fundamental values,'' said Boisi, who
will become Chase's head of investment banking in July. ``Right at
the top there was a collegial partnership and that felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison insisted that the Forbes article about Lee ``had
nothing to do with the changes at Chase.'' Lee, he said, had been
looking to spend less time on administration and Chase needed a
skilled manager, having gained more than 200 new professionals with
the recent acquisitions. The bank also expanded its venture capital
operations, Chase Capital Partners, which invests in emerging
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But other Chase executives said that Harrison was not pleased
with Lee's portrayal in the story and wanted to move quickly to
shake things up. Negotiations between Boisi and Harrison lasted
less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And even the day before the announcement, one executive said, it
was not clear whether Lee would stay. A former executive said that
Lee described the management shuffle to some friends and colleagues
as getting ``whacked.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Lee said he welcomes the change.
Earlier this year he cut the number of people who report to him,
voluntarily sharing the responsibility with other Chase executives,
so that he could spend more time with clients. And, so far, the
talk about him leaving is untrue. ``I just got off the phone with a
senior person at a competitor and I told him I was happy,'' Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boisi's return to a big institution striving to get
ahead sets up a powerful personal drama with Chase's Wall Street
rivals. Not only will he be going head-to-head against his former
colleagues at Goldman, Boisi also faces a formidable competitor at
Citigroup, where Rubin, the former U.S. Treasury secretary who once
shared the top spot at Goldman, is now Citi's co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was prepared for the contest, Boisi did not
answer directly, instead offering an anecdote to make his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years and years ago I used to ask young recruits, `What do you
want on your tombstone?''' he said. One day one of the recruits
turned the question on him. He thought about it, he said, and
replied, ``To be a successful, respected competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he relishes the challenge. And challenge it will
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of cultural meshing to be done,'' said Judah
Krushaar, a bank analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``The question is how do
they take all these capabilities and drive them into Chase's bigger
customer base.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Boisi was born in 1947, the second of six children and raised in
a devout Catholic home in Westbury, on Long Island. His father,
James, was a vice chairman at J.P. Morgan; his mother Edith, a
homemaker. He attended Boston College where, on the last day of his
freshman year, he met his wife, Rene.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1969 with a degree in English, Boisi
immediately went to the Wharton School of Business at the
University of Pennsylvania, where he got his M.B.A. in 1971. He was
recruited by Goldman, becoming just the fourth person in what was
then a fledgling mergers and acquisitions practice.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for the ambitious young Boisi to become a
star. Mergers-and-acquisitions was once a genteel business, but as
the new era of hostile takeovers was born, Goldman moved from
insisting on only representing corporations seeking to fend off a
takeover to a being a full participant on all sides. Boisi was soon
involved in nearly every major takeover battle of the 1980s _
including advising buyout firm Forstmann Little &AMP; Co. in the epic
1988 battle for RJR Nabisco that Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.
ultimately won.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, Boisi became Goldman's youngest partner. In 1980 he
became head of the mergers-and-acquisitions department and in 1986,
he took sole responsibility for running the investment banking
division, where he spent four years at the helm, helping to create
Goldman's now formidable global finance presence.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, he still bursts with pride over what his old firm has
accomplished: ``Goldman Sachs is considered to be a pretty good
place,'' he says, ``and I had something to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have made few enemies in his rise, a rarity in the
backstabbing world of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geoff was very well-organized, disciplined and exceedingly
focused,'' Rubin says. ``He is a very decent guy.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, former colleagues say, what distinguished Boisi at
Goldman, which prides itself on collegiality, was his zeal for
argument. ``His personality fills a room,'' said Robin Neustein, a
managing director at Goldman who worked with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Boisi also took time to attract and shelter new talent. ``I
was always a believer in giving opportunities to the younger
people,'' he said. At Goldman, he even played football with junior
analysts on weekends, and trolled university campuses looking for
promising undergraduates. ``I was trying to identify who the
leaders were and talk to them and get them on board,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boisi brought that same intensity to his activities off Wall
Street. Richard Syron, the former president of the American Stock
Exchange who served as vice chairman for Boston College's board of
trustees when Boisi was chairman, recalled one spring in the early
1990s when they were responsible for finding a new president for
the college.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had constructed this extraordinary process, a two-week
schedule for gathering information,'' Syron said. ``We talked to
the dean of every school, every member of the board, past and
present, every department head and a lot of alumni.'' And the was
before the search began. All told the two spent 100 hours _ working
late into the evenings _ listening to every important person
affected by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quite cerebral in a way that does not come across as
purely intellectual,'' Syron said. ``Geoff is someone who starts
looking at something at a macro level and drills down to the
details to see how they fit in a larger picture.''
</P>
<P>
   So why didn't Boisi end up running Goldman? Wall Street
executives where surprised when he resigned in 1991. But he would
have had to wait a considerable time until Rubin and Friedman, who
had recently been named co-chairmen, left their posts. The irony
is, had Boisi stayed, he would most likely have been named their
successor in 1994, less time then he expected to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what I was giving up,'' he said of that time. He was
silent for a moment, before recounting the moment he made up his
mind to leave. It was early 1991, and he had taken a business trip
to Australia to make a three hour-presentation to a client. After
the meeting, he caught a flight to Rome, where he spent half a day
recruiting a potential Goldman board member.
</P>
<P>
   All told, he said, he spent more than 24 hours on planes _ plus
the time in meetings _ away from his wife and four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Thursday was completely obliterated from my life,'' he
said. ``Given what I wanted to do with the kids and my life I
thought it was healthy to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years after that he devoted his efforts to the National
Mentoring Partnership, an organization he co-founded in 1989 which
matches up students with corporate mentors. And in 1993, he started
the investment advisory firm Beacon, which would become a
collection of friends and former Goldman colleagues, including
David Coulter, the former chairman of BankAmerica Corp. and Richard
Herbst, a former Goldman banker.
</P>
<P>
   Boisi now says that he is not daunted that at an age when many
Wall Street executives are looking to spend more time in the
Hamptons or other leisurely pursuits, he will be starting over,
again logging long hours at the office, on planes and in meetings
hoping to create at Chase the successful atmosphere that made
Goldman what it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be building, person by person,'' he said. ``We are
going to be guerrilla warriors. That is going to be instilled.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
