<HEADER>
A7563 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-DINGLE-IRELAND-LADN &LR;      06-28 2017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINGLE-IRELAND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FORGOTTEN IRELAND
</HEADLINE>
  Hospitality beckons from the Dingle Peninsula 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box and captions below. Art available.) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (TRVL IRELAND3)
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Whipp/Staff Photographer &QL; 
The Blasket Islands are the peninsula's most famous attraction,
located three miles off Dunmore Head, Ireland's westernmost point.
The largest of the group, the Great Blasket Island, was home in the
1920s and '30s to a thriving literary community that produced some
of Ireland's best-loved works.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO &QL; 
GETTING THERE: Ireland isn't a big country, so your best (and most
cost-effective) bet is to fly into Dublin and rent a car. If you're
going in the summer, make sure you make reservations well in
advance. And go with a manual transmission; cars with automatic
transmissions cost two to three times as much to rent because of
their relative scarcity.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: Doyle's Townhouse, 5 John St., Dingle. Phone: (800)
223-6510 or (011) 353-66-9151174. Rooms are available in the
three-story main guest house as well as an annex a short walk up
John Street. Rates, depending on the strength of the dollar, come
to about $125 a night for two people. The suites at the annex are
lovely, featuring a downstairs sitting area and comfortable
sleeping quarters upstairs. Prices include full breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: If you stayed at Doyle's and enjoyed the full Irish
breakfast, you won't be all that hungry until dinner. Stave off any
midday hunger pains with a pub lunch, which is uniformly decent.
And, since the area has no shortage of choices, you won't have any
trouble locating a place that serves sandwiches, soups and, yes,
the obligatory fish and chips. Returning to town, have dinner at
Doyle's, enjoying whatever fresh seafood is on the menu that day.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: For general tourist information on Ireland, call
(800) 223-6470. Web: www.irelandvacations.com. The tourist office
in Killarney can provide specific information on the Dingle
Peninsula. Phone: (011) 353-6431633. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
By Glenn Whipp &QL; 
Staff Writer &QL; 
DINGLE, Ireland _ When most people visit Ireland, they arrive in
Dublin and spend a few days immersed in the city's cosmopolitan
conviviality. Then, once the head has cleared from the immersion of
one too many nights spent in the city's Temple Bar pub district,
they decide to venture out into the real Ireland, the Emerald Isle
of rolling hills, rocky coastlines and a hundred shades of green.
</P>
<P>
   The question confronting the visitor at this point is: Where to
go? From the guidebooks and the travel planners, you're going to
hear a lot of noise about the sunny Southeast, a fair amount of
blarney about the Cork region and high praise for Limerick (usually
coming from people who regard Frank McCourt's works as the second
coming of the Book of Kells). Galway, Killarney and the Lower
Shannon region? All have their advocates, too, and quite
justifiably so.
</P>
<P>
   One place you're not going to hear too much about is the Dingle
Peninsula, which is Reason No. 1 you should go there. Here in
southwestern Ireland, you won't find any tacky souvenir shops
selling leprechaun figures, shamrocks and post cards picturing the
seven-course Irish dinner (it's a six-pack of Guinness and a
potato, for those who've never heard the old joke). You won't find
long lines of people waiting to kiss a stone or tour a brewery for
a free pint of beer. You won't find long lines of people, period _
just the most spectacular scenery anywhere in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Dingle's biggest tourist attraction _ a playful bottle-nose
dolphin named Fungie, who has made the harbor town his home since
1984 _ tells you a lot about the place. This is Ireland at its most
charming, a town with 1,200 residents and 52 pubs, which means
there's plenty of room for anyone looking for an enjoyable evening
out.
</P>
<P>
   Music and conversation are treasured. An expression of praise on
the peninsula _ which still has a fair number of Gaelic-speaking
residents _ is ``Mo cheol thu.'' Translation: ``You are my music.''
(Maybe that's where Barry Manilow cribbed the idea for ``I Write
the Songs''; if so, don't hold that against these dear people.)
</P>
<P>
   In Gaelic, Dingle means ``fortress,'' appropriate enough given
how the town is sheltered by the mountains on one side and the
Atlantic on the other. During medieval times, Dingle was the
primary harbor for County Kerry. Now it's a thriving fishing port,
and many of the anglers earn a decent living taking tourists on bay
excursions to see the mischievous Fungie. At any one time, there
might be six ships in the harbor whose sole purpose is to coax the
dolphin into view. (The voyages also provide you with a great view
of the bay, the surrounding hills and the occasional castle ruin.)
</P>
<P>
   The boats' motion is all Fungie usually needs to appear. He'll
often follow a fishing vessel during its entire seaward or homeward
voyage. Sometimes, though, when he's being a little coy, sightseers
will try almost anything to lure him to the surface. One boy
dangled a candy bar from the side of the boat, pleading, ``C'mon
Fungie, c'mon! I've got a Mars bar fer ye if you'll just show
yerself!''
</P>
<P>
   The other wonders of the region are never hidden. National
Geographic magazine called the Dingle Peninsula ``the most
beautiful place on Earth,'' which is certainly open to debate, but
no visitor will question the grandeur of its visual pleasures. This
is the isolated part of Ireland where the 1970 melodrama ``Ryan's
Daughter'' was shot. The film won an Oscar for its cinematography,
which probably had more to do with the dramatic scenery than any
filmmaking prowess.
</P>
<P>
   The peninsula reaches about 40 miles out to sea, making it the
westernmost part of Ireland (and of Europe, for that matter). If
you wanted to drive the entire area, you'd have a little more than
100 miles to traverse and, given the windy roads and the number of
stops you'd undoubtedly want to make, the trip would require the
better part of the day. Starting from Dingle, however, you can
reduce the loop to 25 miles, making it a half-day excursion. This
leaves you with more time to explore the town, not to mention those
52 pubs.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged Dingle Peninsula isn't as heavily traveled as
Ireland's famed Ring of Kerry, which is the region just south of
Dingle. This seclusion gives the land an almost otherworldly sense
of calm and peacefulness. The views are spectacular. The verdant
hills dotted with sheep, the turquoise water and the white sands
combine to produce a compelling array of colors that pleases the
eye and soothes the mind. This is land that cries out for
contemplation, and its isolation affords visitors that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such contemplation can be difficult when driving
roads barely wide enough for your compact rental car, never mind
the oncoming traffic. Winding around the tight curves of Route 559
can be an alarming experience for anyone not used to driving narrow
lanes bracketed by stone walls (the brightly blooming fuchsia
plants nicely disguise the barriers in the summer). There's also
the fact that if you're an American, you're motoring on the
``wrong'' side of the road. But with roads this constricted, you
can throw the concept of ``sides'' out the window. Whoever hits the
bend first has the right of way.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, even during the height of tourist season, you'll
probably never run into another car _ and that is meant both in the
literal and figurative sense. So the rules of the road, while
important, aren't exactly going to be paramount here. And that's
even taking into account all the neck-craning you'll be doing.
</P>
<P>
   The peninsula's most famous scenic attractions are the seven
Blasket Islands, located three miles off Dunmore Head, Ireland's
westernmost point. The largest of the group, the Great Blasket
Island, was home in the 1920s and '30s to a thriving literary
community that produced some of Ireland's best-loved works.
Emigration and the harshness of the remote island life caused the
population to dwindle to the point where it was abandoned in 1953
when only 22 inhabitants remained. Ferries still take visitors to
the Great Blasket, and the Blasket Centre, located just north of
Dunmore Head, provides guided tours and historical exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrated sites can be reached a little more easily, such
as the Dunbeg Fort, a well-preserved Iron Age stronghold that
dramatically overlooks the Atlantic. Nearby, in the hills along
Slea Head Road, sit dozens of beehive huts that date back to the
12th century. Then, the Irish used the drystone, corbelled
dwellings as homes after the Normans had driven them from the prime
real estate; as recently as a century ago, the huts remained in use
for storage purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby Gallarus Oratory, a miniature Christian church built
some time between the sixth and ninth centuries, is also worth a
look. Shaped like an upturned boat, this place, like the peninsula
itself, remains a haven for quiet reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Children, though, have never been too big on quiet reflection,
so anyone with kids might also want to mix in a trip or two to the
peninsula's many family-friendly attractions. There's the Enchanted
Forest, a fairy-tale museum with its own pub (naturally) and
Farmworld, a wildlife petting zoo featuring Angora goats, Galway
lambs and assorted rare Irish animal breeds. Scanlon's Pet Farm is
another like-minded conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the harbor, near Fungie territory, is the Oceanworld
Aquarium, a sea sanctuary spotlighting the sea culture of the
region, along with artifacts from the Spanish Armada and St.
Brendan the Navigator's Atlantic voyages. None of these places
remotely resembles Disneyland, but then there are fewer people,
better food and no price gouging here. And Disneyland doesn't have
Guinness on draft for the adults, either.
</P>
<P>
   That latter distinction is an important one. Contemplating
natural wonders and playful dolphins may be good for the soul, but
the stomach has its needs, too. Fortunately, Irish cuisine has come
a long way since the days when overcooked meats and vegetables and
a profusion of potatoes frightened visitors into adopting a steady
diet of fish and chips. Dingle, being a thriving seaport, is a
seafood lover's paradise, with several excellent restaurants
offering fresh fish straight from the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the lot is Doyle's Seafood Bar, located on John
Street, right in the center of this lovely little town. Everything
here is fresh, either straight off the boat or from a neighboring
farm or from Stella Doyle's backyard garden.
</P>
<P>
   Owners John and Stella also smoke their own salmon, which is
excellent, as is poached lobster, grilled mussels with garlic, and
a fisherman's pie, with chunks of fresh seafood combined with a
creamy sauce served in a pastry crust. (Note for fish haters: The
lamb and steaks are great, too. Vegetarians, though, might want to
pick a different country to visit.)
</P>
<P>
   The town comes alive at night, particularly in the summer, with
pubs such as An Droichead Beag (The Small Bridge), Mac Carthaigh's,
Flaherty's and An Chonair all featuring singing, dancing and lively
traditional music. Being a tourist doesn't matter in the least when
it comes to participating; the Irish aren't exactly standoffish
when it comes to welcoming guests. You may, however, wish to
observe a jig or two before wheeling yourself out to the dance
floor, particularly if you've had a pint or two.
</P>
<P>
   But then, everyone else in the place has enjoyed a pint or two
as well, and, anyway, no one is keeping score on how much you've
drunk or how well you dance. A little too much enthusiasm in either
arena will just make for some good ``craic,'' which, translated
from the Gaelic, means either ``good conversation'' or ``wud yeh
look at tha' fool oveh ther.''
</P>
<P>
   Always remember, though, they're laughing with you, not at you.
You'll be laughing, too, because you'll be having the time of your
life.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to bring a Mars bar for Fungie. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
