look. Shaped like an upturned boat, this place, like the peninsula
itself, remains a haven for quiet reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Children, though, have never been too big on quiet reflection,
so anyone with kids might also want to mix in a trip or two to the
peninsula's many family-friendly attractions. There's the Enchanted
Forest, a fairy-tale museum with its own pub (naturally) and
Farmworld, a wildlife petting zoo featuring Angora goats, Galway
lambs and assorted rare Irish animal breeds. Scanlon's Pet Farm is
another like-minded conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the harbor, near Fungie territory, is the Oceanworld
Aquarium, a sea sanctuary spotlighting the sea culture of the
region, along with artifacts from the Spanish Armada and St.
Brendan the Navigator's Atlantic voyages. None of these places
remotely resembles Disneyland, but then there are fewer people,
better food and no price gouging here. And Disneyland doesn't have
Guinness on draft for the adults, either.
</P>
<P>
   That latter distinction is an important one. Contemplating
natural wonders and playful dolphins may be good for the soul, but
the stomach has its needs, too. Fortunately, Irish cuisine has come
a long way since the days when overcooked meats and vegetables and
a profusion of potatoes frightened visitors into adopting a steady
diet of fish and chips. Dingle, being a thriving seaport, is a
seafood lover's paradise, with several excellent restaurants
offering fresh fish straight from the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the lot is Doyle's Seafood Bar, located on John
Street, right in the center of this lovely little town. Everything
here is fresh, either straight off the boat or from a neighboring
farm or from Stella Doyle's backyard garden.
</P>
<P>
   Owners John and Stella also smoke their own salmon, which is
excellent, as is poached lobster, grilled mussels with garlic, and
a fisherman's pie, with chunks of fresh seafood combined with a
creamy sauce served in a pastry crust. (Note for fish haters: The
lamb and steaks are great, too. Vegetarians, though, might want to
pick a different country to visit.)
</P>
<P>
   The town comes alive at night, particularly in the summer, with
pubs such as An Droichead Beag (The Small Bridge), Mac Carthaigh's,
Flaherty's and An Chonair all featuring singing, dancing and lively
traditional music. Being a tourist doesn't matter in the least when
it comes to participating; the Irish aren't exactly standoffish
when it comes to welcoming guests. You may, however, wish to
observe a jig or two before wheeling yourself out to the dance
floor, particularly if you've had a pint or two.
</P>
<P>
   But then, everyone else in the place has enjoyed a pint or two
as well, and, anyway, no one is keeping score on how much you've
drunk or how well you dance. A little too much enthusiasm in either
arena will just make for some good ``craic,'' which, translated
from the Gaelic, means either ``good conversation'' or ``wud yeh
look at tha' fool oveh ther.''
</P>
<P>
   Always remember, though, they're laughing with you, not at you.
You'll be laughing, too, because you'll be having the time of your
life.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to bring a Mars bar for Fungie. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
