<HEADER>
A7567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BELARUS-SCULPTOR-NYT &LR;      06-28 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-SCULPTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLETED OPPOSITION IN BELARUS SEARCHES FOR A NEW LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ For months, Ivan Misko scraped, spackled and
molded until he had properly endowed his bust of Gennady Karpenko
with the mountainous brow of a scholar, the sturdy jaw of a leader
and, above all, the forward gaze of a charismatic politician
peering into the Belarussian future.
</P>
<P>
   As a devoted friend to the late Karpenko, a physicist and
politician, Misko this spring cast his work in plaster and
supervised its transformation into bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is almost ready for unveiling at Karpenko's tomb, a
ceremony that when it takes place sometime in July will be a
significant political act in this authoritarian state that lies
between Russia and the West.
</P>
<P>
   For Karpenko was, until his death on April 6, 1999, one of the
most dangerous men in Belarus as the leader of the opposition
forces seeking to oust President Aleksandr Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
   Karpenko, a deputy speaker of the Parliament disbanded by
Lukashenko in 1996, died abruptly at age 49 of what the medical
authorities here said was a brain hemorrhage. Though there is no
proof of foul play, the circumstances surrounding Karpenko's final
hours _ he received no serious medical attention for 24 hours after
he collapsed and entered a state medical center _ have caused his
family to doubt that he died of natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning I suspected that he was murdered
somehow,'' said his wife, Lyudmila. ``And when other opposition
leaders started disappearing months later, it confirmed my
suspicions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture of respect for Karpenko's advocacy of democracy,
the U.S. ambassador, Daniel Speckhard, made a private visit to the
grave site last year accompanied by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Since the funeral, the pressure on the family has not eased.
Karpenko's son, Dimitri, has been driven from his job in a state
enterprise, and his family remains under surveillance and
harassment from Lukashenko's security forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid for my children,'' Lyudmila Karpenko said. ``They
don't have a future in this country. We are going to open the
monument to Gennady, and then we are going to leave the country. It
is just too hard to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   As a state artist of the Soviet Union, Misko spent much of his
life lionizing astronauts and other heroes of socialist labor. His
studio, at the edge of a leafy courtyard near the center of the
capital, is an untidy museum of the socialist realism that
flourished under Communism, and that Stalin saw as the best means
to bend art to the service of the totalitarian state. It became
state policy in 1932, the year Misko was born.
</P>
<P>
   A barrel-chested sculptor who chiseled President Clinton's
profile on a commemorative medallion for his visit here in 1994,
Misko would be the last person to say he is engaging in politics
with his art. But the Karpenko bust is unmistakably an act of
rebellion against the authoritarianism that exists under
Lukashenko, an admirer of Stalin and the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am doing it for free,'' said Misko, whose shock of white
hair and mischievous eyes always seem to convey more than he says.
``I am not doing it for money _ in fact, no one wants to pay for
it. The family does not have the money, and there is no one else to
place the order, especially not the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my friend for a long time,'' Misko said of Karpenko.
</P>
<P>
   As the bronze was being cast last week, the visage of Karpenko
in clay still dominated Misko's studio, capturing what friends say
was the quiet resolve of the man who unified the country's
opposition parties little more than a year ago, and prepared them
to stage a mock presidential election that challenged Lukashenko's
legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko's presidential term expired last July, though he
continues to rule after rewriting the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The unveiling of the Karpenko memorial is scheduled for sometime
after the Congress of Democratic Forces, a grouping of opposition
parties, convenes on July 2 here in the capital. Unless Lukashenko
bans it, the congress aims once again to unite all opposition
parties in a new challenge to the president.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The congress, its organizers say, will demand fair elections
this fall for a new Parliament and next year for a new president,
and it will insist that Lukashenko re-establish the rule of
parliamentary law that has been replaced in recent years by
presidential decrees.
</P>
<P>
   Were Karpenko still alive, he would certainly have been the
leading candidate to challenge Lukashenko, in the view of most
political analysts here. Karpenko would have been able to unite the
opposition, but without him the opposition cannot offer a broadly
acceptable leader, said Yevgeny Ogurtsov, a member of the United
Civic Party and an editor whose newspaper, The Citizen, was shut
down by Lukashenko in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Karpenko's death was deeply disturbing to many
here, and in the months that followed, Belarussians were all the
more stunned by the assault on most of the remaining opposition
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the political landscape has been wiped clean,
says Irina Khalip, an independent journalist who has been arrested
and harassed for her coverage of corruption and political abuse
under Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``All political leaders who might have laid claim to the
presidency have either died under suspicious circumstances, like
Karpenko, or they have fled in fear of their lives or
disappeared,'' she said. ``The remaining ones have been convicted
of political crimes with conditions that they cannot participate in
the elections, and so today there is almost no opposition figure
who could run against Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless,'' Khalip added, ``it is a big mistake for
Lukashenko to feel safe, because a new leader will appear.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Karpenko did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
