<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7568 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ROCKER-NEWYORK-COX     06-28 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-NEWYORK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Usually blase' Big Apple riveted by Rocker's return to city
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Say what you want about John Rocker, the
controversial Braves pitcher who pretty much says whatever he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Call him a loudmouth. Say his fastball's been as unpredictably
loopy as his recent behavior. Even mock him for looking ``like
Bullwinkle when he runs,'' as one Mets fan did Tuesday night at
Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But don't for one moment suggest that this city that supposedly
has seen it all _ twice _ isn't utterly and completely obsessed
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore was appearing over at the ABC studios the other day,
and there was nobody there waiting to see him, but here we all are
talking about John Rocker, who's somewhere up in Canada right
now,'' Izzy Orloff practically moaned on a midtown Manhattan
sidewalk Tuesday afternoon. ``Who's more important, the vice
president or John Rocker?''
</P>
<P>
   Important, nuthin', as they say in New York. What matters more
is that Rocker's on everybody's radar screen here as tonight's
showdown series with the Mets begins. He also is on theater
marquees (``John Rocker Stay Home!'' was the message outside one
establishment near Times Square the other day), on newspaper front
pages and local TV news (``When `Live At Five' continues, `The
Rocker Report!''' the NBC affiliate's anchor boomed Tuesday) and on
virtually everyone's lips.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they claim to be heartily sick of this whole
controversy, sparked by Rocker's derogatory comments about New York
and its inhabitants in a Sports Illustrated article last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a news creation, a media thing,'' griped Jim Kupcho
of nearby Woodbridge, N.J., who was strolling in Central Park.
Then, Kupcho spent the next 10 minutes analyzing the Rocker
situation from every angle.
</P>
<P>
   And even when they're not exactly sure what to make of the guy.
Whereas New York City Police Commissioner Howard Safir has likened
guarding Rocker this weekend to ``protecting the Ku Klux Klan,''
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has said the issue of the big lefty's
security is being treated ``as if it were a head of state coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach might sound schizophrenic, but it actually is
pretty simple: more cops, less booze. As many as 700 New York
police officers could be deployed to Shea, Giuliani said; that
number is more than 10 times for a normal regular-season game. And
the Mets are erecting a plywood roof over the visiting bullpen to
protect Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   A shadowy group of fans has designated Friday's game as
``Battery Night,'' a reference to what they want people to bring to
fling at the Braves reliever; meanwhile, a sporting goods store
near Shea is hawking hard hats in Mets' orange and blue and
emblazoned with ``Don't Hit Me, I'm Not John Rocker.''
</P>
<P>
   A check with several dozen fans at Tuesday's game turned up no
one planning to throw batteries themselves; but everyone at least
knew someone who knew someone who supposedly would be packing size
D's at Shea. The extra security alone is estimated to cost the city
several hundred thousand dollars. Some taxpayers here are pretty
steamed about that, including Mets reliever and Queens resident
John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not half as steamed as Shea Stadium regulars are
about a plan to limit beer consumption. During Tuesday night's game
against the Florida Marlins, normal policy was in place, and adult
fans could buy as many as four beers at once. During the Braves
series they will be able to buy only two beers at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to reduce the tension level in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone got any other good ideas?
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, now I'm mad,'' Brooklyn resident Joseph Iovelli said as he
headed into Shea on Tuesday. ``You can come in here and say New
York is a cesspool, that all Mets fans are morons, and that's one
thing. But don't come in here and affect how many beers I can buy!
That's when I really start to hate John Rocker!''
</P>
<P>
   Iovelli had taken the No. 7 subway to Shea, the same train
derided by Rocker in December as being full of criminals,
foreigners and ``some kid with purple hair, next to some queer with
AIDS.'' On this particular Tuesday, the train's passengers included
one tattooed, spiky-haired kid with a nickel-sized hole pierced in
his ear, lots of people speaking foreign languages and dozens of
Mets fans speculating on whether Rocker really would make good on
his pledge to ride the No. 7 to tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Giuliani and others have begged him not to do it.
Meanwhile, the police have drawn up plans to surround him with nine
officers and turn his train into an express making only a few stops
instead of the usual 21from midtown Manhattan to Shea. Yet one more
reason for the average New Yorker to despise Rocker, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sure like to be able to summon an express train whenever I
need one,'' Angela Harrison grumbled Wednesday morning, weaving
through the throngs to make a transfer inside the vast Times Square
subway station. ``What's this guy's power, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it's having a strange effect on New York, a
usually cocky city that, for once, seems a little bit unsure of
itself - or how to behave around Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   One group of fans, noting his comment last week that booing
inspires him to pitch better, is urging everyone to stand and
silently turn their backs on Rocker when he enters games this
weekend. But others want nothing to do with such dignified
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is New York,'' Elliot Auerbacher snorted on his cellular
telephone. Auerbacher, who started the Web site
www.rockersucks.com, was doing a brisk business selling his
anti-Rocker T-shirts earlier this week near Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York style is not to politely turn your back on
someone,'' he said. ``It's to get in your face and say, `We don't
like you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But it's also the New York style to attract lots of attention to
oneself. Whatever else happens this weekend, a lot of people here
say, John Rocker already has pretty much beaten this city at its
own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must be loving this,'' Iovelli, the Mets fan from Brooklyn,
said Tuesday night as he continued his trek from the subway stop
into Shea. ``'Cause we hate him and we're all bending over
backwards for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
