<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-UTAH-REPUBS-630&AMP;ADD-N     06-28 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-REPUBS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE INCUMBENT LOSES IN REPUBLICAN PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Texas, Va.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Scarcely two hours after the polls closed on
Tuesday night, Rep. Merrill Cook acknowledged the inevitable. His
turbulent four years representing Utah's 2nd Congressional District
had caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than half the votes counted, Cook conceded to Derek
Smith, a business owner and political newcomer who went on to win
nearly 59 percent of the vote, making Cook the first Republican
incumbent to lose in a primary this year. One incumbent Democrat
has fallen, Rep. Matthew Martinez of California's 31st District,
who lost to state Sen. Hilda Solis.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Solis, who has no opponent in November, Smith will
face a formidable challenger, Jim Matheson, a political neophyte,
as well, but also the son of an immensely popular former governor,
the late Scott Matheson. With Democrats needing a swing of six
seats to regain the House majority they lost in 1994, this is one
seat they believe they have a strong chance to win back.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah's other major Republican primary on Tuesday, Gov.
Michael Leavitt withstood a spirited challenge from the right and
defeated Glen Davis with 61 percent of the vote. Leavitt, who is
seeking a third four-year term, will face Bill Orton, a former
Democratic congressman, in the general election, a contest that
could be competitive because of the high profiles of both
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The victory by Smith ended a seven-week campaign that turned
from nasty to nastier, reaching a climax of sorts on a Salt Lake
City street last Wednesday, when he and Cook stood for 45 minutes
arguing as reporters looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Their confrontation was a continuation of verbal assaults over
personal finances, voting habits and prospects for success in
November. Yet for Cook, it was just the latest chapter in a brief
congressional career that was never short of distractions. More
than for any notable legislation, he brought attention to himself
here and in Washington for public temper tantrums, staff turnover
and a recent trial in which a jury found that he had not paid a
former consultant almost $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief concession speech, Cook accused reporters of
blowing his past out of proportion and denounced the Republican
leadership in Washington for withholding full support, saying,
``You can't win when the party big shots won't stand up for you.''
And Wednesday, he expanded the blame to include Democrats who had
voted in the open primary solely to drive him out of office and
disgruntled former employees.
</P>
<P>
   He also broadened his criticism of party leaders, accusing them
of following ``two sets of rules, one for incumbents, one for
Merrill Cook.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, he did receive considerable help from many leading
Republicans. Speaker Dennis Hastert, and the House majority leader,
Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, and the majority whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas, all traveled to Utah to raise money for Cook.
</P>
<P>
   But some other House Republicans, including Rep. Christopher
Cannon, who represents Utah's 3rd Congressional District, supported
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who became wealthy as the owner of an explosives company,
vowed that his political career would not end after November,
hinting that he might return as an independent, which he has done
before. In eight years as an independent before he won the
congressional seat, he ran twice for governor and once for mayor of
Salt Lake City, the congressional seat, the school board and the
Salt Lake County Commission _ losing all six times.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was disheartened that so many Republican leaders
had backed Cook, which, he said, ``drove home a point: If you're
challenging an incumbent, you better be prepared to stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's their job,'' he added. ``If I'm the incumbent in
two years, I would expect them to support me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still wide-eyed after a sleepless night, much of it spent
celebrating, Smith said he felt relieved that he could now look
forward to a campaign against Matheson that he predicted would
focus more on issues than personality. He said a barrage of attacks
by Cook had forced him to spend time defending himself, rather than
discussing issues like education reform, tax cuts, job creation and
expanding voter participation through use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was eager to bring stability to the seat, which
represents parts of Salt Lake City and several adjacent counties.
The winner in November will become the district's fifth
representative in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Rep. Thomas Davis III, chairman of the National
Republican Congressional Committee, said in a statement that the
party would now throw its full support behind Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is a Republican incumbent lost,'' Davis, of
Virginia, said. ``The good news is we have a strong nominee in this
seat for the fall. Merrill Cook has been a fine representative for
the citizens of Utah, working tirelessly on their behalf. His
presence will be missed here in Washington after November. I wish
him all the best, and I am confident he will join us in supporting
Derek Smith this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said he would have to think about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
