<HEADER>
A7576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUMOR-MARKETPLACE-NYT     06-28 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUMOR-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NYSE PENALIZES WELL-KNOWN ANALYST AND FIRM FOR FALSE
RUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An analyst spreads a rumor that one company is about
to buy another one, and the stock of the target company soars. The
rumor proves to be false, and the stock price falls back.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of events has occurred countless times. But now
something different has happened. The analyst _ a well-known Wall
Street veteran _ and the brokerage firm that employed him have been
censured and fined by the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange announced Wednesday that Thomas H. Hanley, 56,
formerly the lead banking analyst for UBS Securities, had been
censured and fined $75,000. The exchange said he ``circulated a
rumor regarding an exchange- listed security for which he lacked a
reasonable basis and which might reasonably be expected to affect
market conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   UBS, now called Warburg Dillon Read, was censured and fined
$60,000 for failing to prevent Hanley from circulating the rumor.
</P>
<P>
   A Big Board official said that the exchange has previously taken
action against at least seven other people for circulating false
rumors, but that this one appears to be the first against an
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred on Sept. 18, 1997, when Hanley spoke to
UBS's sales force via what the exchange called the firm's
``hoot-n-holler system'' that connected all of the firm's offices
in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Bankers Trust was ``indeed gone'' and would be
acquired by Travelers Corp. at a price of $162 to $167 a share. The
stock was then trading at about $120.
</P>
<P>
   The stock soared, reaching a peak of $133.625, and Bankers Trust
soon issued a denial. But Hanley, who also appeared on CNBC,
continued to say he thought the deal would happen. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, however, Travelers did announce a deal to buy
Salomon Inc., the parent of Salomon Brothers, and it eventually
merged with Citicorp to form Citigroup. Bankers Trust was acquired
by Deutsche Bank in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley has never said why he believed Bankers Trust was going to
be bought by Travelers. Wednesday, he issued a statement saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am known for my detailed research and believe that I had a
reasonable basis for my opinion. The exchange obviously disagreed.
I decided to settle this matter to avoid the distraction and
expense associated with a protracted and drawn-out legal
proceeding. Having opinions is the job of a research analyst. I
look forward to continuing to provide clients with well-reasoned
research.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board charges said that Hanley did not have a reasonable
basis for the call, but did not accuse him of profiting from it in
any way. There was no mention of any trading by him in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   For Hanley, long one of the best-known banking analysts on Wall
Street, the Bankers Trust call appears to have been the worst one
he ever made, at least in terms of personal effect.
</P>
<P>
   In February of this year, he resigned from Warburg Dillon Read,
and has not yet taken another position. A spokesman for the firm
told Bloomberg News there was no connection between the
investigation and Hanley's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley, who previously worked at Salomon Brothers and First
Boston, has appeared on Institutional Investor's All-American list
of analysts from 1976 through 1999, including a string of 14
consecutive years when he was named the top analyst covering
money-center banks.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Hanley would have escaped discipline if he
had just said the prospective takeover was a rumor, but he did not.
Instead, he made it sound like he knew what he was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a world where analysts speculating on takeovers is a
daily occurrence, the discipline of Hanley raised some eyebrows.
``We were having merger mania and everybody was buying everybody
else,'' recalled Miles Seifert, the chairman of Gray Seifert, a
money management subsidiary of Legg Mason, of the atmosphere in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every analyst on Wall Street was saying somebody was going to
be bought by somebody else,'' added Seifert, who described himself
as a friend and client of Hanley. ``That seemed to be the job of
the analyst. I'm not sure what is different in this than in all the
other cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
