A7582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-M&AMP;M-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-28 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-M&AMP;M-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 ADVERTISING: ORIGINAL M&AMP;M'S RESUME THEIR MILK CHOCOLATE IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does the word ``plain'' insinuate? Dull, bland, simple,
ordinary, boring?
</P>
<P>
   That is how the marketing executives at M&AMP;M/Mars see it, anyway.
So, after 46 years, the company has decided to change the name of
its Plain variety of M&AMP;M's candy _ you know, the one without the
peanuts _ to what it hopes is a more appetizing moniker: Milk
Chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name change is a long time coming,'' said Michael
Tolkowsky, vice president for marketing and licensing at the
M&AMP;M's/Mars division of Mars Inc. in Hackettstown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all this time,'' he added, ``we've always internally sort
of felt like `Hey, that's not nearly the best way to refer to it.'
M&AMP;M's milk chocolate is too good to be called Plain.' ``
</P>
<P>
   To spread the word about the name change, M&AMP;M's/Mars is
introducing an ambitious multimedia campaign that begins this week.
The $10 million campaign, created by BBDO New York, carries the
theme: ``Same great chocolate. Much better name.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign takes the tongue-in-cheek tone that has recently
become a staple of ads for M&AMP;M's, which are centered on animated
anthropomorphic confectionery characters with contemporary personas
infused with attributes like sarcastic humor and sassy tongues. The
M&AMP;M's characters have been around since 1954, but they had
pleasant, passive personalities, all but begging consumers to eat
them.
</P>
<P>
   That went the way of the 5-cent candy bar in 1995 when BBDO New
York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group, was
awarded the M&AMP;M's account.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got the business, the characters were very appealing,
but they were somewhat two-dimensional,'' said Charlie Miesmer,
vice chairman and senior executive creative director at BBDO New
York, who oversees the M&AMP;M's creative effort along with Susan
Credle, a copywriter, and Steve Rutter, an art director. ``We've
made them somewhat irreverent kind of characters that are human.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So when the need comes five years later to announce a product
change,'' he added, ``you can do it in the context of that
background.''
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the campaign is to lampoon America's seeming
preoccupation with politically correct speech. In one spot that
mimics a public service announcement, to be shown on television and
in movie theaters, people describe their jobs with euphemisms like
``administrative assistant'' for secretary and ``domestic care
giver'' for baby sitter. They are followed by the Red M&AMP;M's
character, which declares, ``I am not a Plain M&AMP;M, I am a Milk
Chocolate M&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commercial features Patrick Warburton, the actor best
known for his role as Elaine's boyfriend Puddy in ``Seinfeld.''
Warburton, who has appeared in three other spots for M&AMP;M's, is seen
with Red looking up synonyms for ``plain'' in a thesaurus. As
Warburton rattles off several unflattering synonyms, Red asks, ``So
you think `plain' is a bad word?'' With restrained contempt,
Warburton looks at Red and says, ``Let's look up `stupid.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``His delivery is marvelous,'' Miesmer said. ``He has this
wonderful, restrained, laconic kind of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   A print ad features Red, with an unusually enlarged head,
growling to his fellow character Yellow, ``Whaddya mean this name
change has gone to my head?'' The ad will appear through early fall
in publications including Cosmopolitan, GQ, People, Rolling Stone
and Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of the campaign will include a satellite ``media
tour'' featuring the Red character and promotional tie-ins at the
Nascar Independence Race on Saturday in Daytona, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The name change takes the Plain variety back to its original
designation at its debut in 1941: The name was switched from Milk
Chocolate to Plain when the Peanut variety was introduced in 1954.
There have been other changes, like an updating of the logo and the
addition of pictures of M&AMP;M candy pieces, but the familiar
brown-and-white color scheme remains the same. M&AMP;M/Mars conducted
research among consumers to determine whether the name change would
be deemed confusing, Tolkowksy said, and found it would not be.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, though, agrees it's a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a bad case of what I call tinkering,'' said
Jack Trout, president of Trout &AMP; Partners, a marketing strategy
company in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's habits change so slowly,'' he added, ``and if that
has been called Plain, then it's Plain. I don't care what you call
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
