A7587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-0629-COX     06-28 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DECRIES ``BOGUS'' CHARGES OF WRONGDOING
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Wednesday that his personal
conduct in office is not the reason for Vice President Al Gore's
slump in the polls and he asserted that his administration has been
dogged by ``bogus'' allegations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging White House press conference, Clinton also
expressed frustration over the U.S. embargo against Cuba, which the
president said he had hoped to ease. He put the blame for
continuing the embargo on Cuban dictator Fidel Castro's 1996 orders
to shoot down two unarmed Cessna airplanes, killing four civilians
who flew from Florida to drop anti-Castro leaflets over Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deliberate decision to murder those people changed
everything,'' said Clinton. ``It made me wonder whether Mr. Castro
was hoping we never would normalize relations, so then he could use
us as an excuse for the failures of his regime.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said Israeli and Palestinian leaders cannot make peace
unless they sit down for hard bargaining in a Camp David-style
summit, the prospects for which he plans to discuss on Thursday
with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that they can resolve the final, most
difficult issues without having the leaders get together in some
isolated setting and make the last, tough decisions, or decide not
to make them, as the case may be,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some foreign policy problems, the answer is to kick the can
down the road and wait for them to get better and hope time takes
care of them,'' Clinton said. ``My own instinct is that the cluster
of problems here would be better off being resolved sooner rather
than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks during an hour-long appearance in the
ornate East Room, his first formal White House news conference in
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions about the recent spike in gasoline
prices, Clinton said consumer costs would ease somewhat as fuel
supplies strengthen later this summer. Clinton said the country has
been shortsighted in refusing to fully invest in energy-saving
technologies, however, and is paying the price for that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get more production on line, this present price crisis
will begin to abate,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will have fundamentally higher prices...until we make
up our minds that we are going to drive higher-mileage vehicles and
do other things that use less oil,'' he said. ``But we only get
interested in this when the price of gasoline goes through the
roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the news conference was centered on the presidential
campaign and the presumptive candidates, Gore and his Republican
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll taken last weekend showed Gore
trailing Bush by 13 points _ the Texan's largest lead since last
winter. The poll, which surveyed 560 likely voters nationwide, had
an error margin of plus or minus 5 percentage points. It showed 52
percent of voters favoring Bush versus 39 percent endorsing Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton predicted, though, that support for Gore would broaden
after each party holds its convention in August and he repeated his
contention that Gore is ``the best qualified person to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct is that people are still trying to figure out what
they think about this race,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Without specifically referencing the Monica Lewinsky scandal
that nearly brought down his administration, Clinton said the
public is not blaming Gore ``for anything I did that they didn't
agree with or that was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said on several occasions that he was wrong to have
an intimate relationship with Lewinsky outside of his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these other so-called scandals were bogus,'' Clinton
said, referring to inquiries into alleged wrongdoing by former
Cabinet members and to his speculation in the Whitewater resort
development before he came to the White House in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word scandal has been thrown around here like a clanging
teapot for seven years,'' Clinton said. Then, paraphrasing a
newspaper columnist, Clinton asked, ``Will no one ever stand up
here and say that a whole bunch of this stuff was just garbage, and
that we had totally innocent people prosecuted because they
wouldn't lie, we had totally innocent people's lives wrecked
because they wouldn't go along with this alleged scandal machine?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of charges by some Democrats that Bush
lacks the intelligence to lead, Clinton took a middle ground
position, saying there was more to the job of being president than
raw brainpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's so much a question of intelligence,'' said
Clinton. ``I think it's more a question of curiosity and
willingness to learn what you think is important...it's a deciding
job.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``No president can say, 'Well, it should be
enough for the voters if I get the best advisers in my party and
they come up with a position and I take it...because I think the
more you know, the better
</P>
<P>
   position you're in not only to draw your own conclusions, but to
take advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright was returning overnight from the Middle East, where she
huddled this week with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat over the prospects for a peace
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would discuss with her tomorrow the question of
how deeply divided the two men remain over issues of Palestinian
statehood, territorial disputes and the future control of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Clinton said, he would decide whether the time is right to
press for a peace summit between the two or to give lower-level
diplomacy more time.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be e-mailed at: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
