<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0629-COX     06-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush charges Gore's policies fueling gas prices
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND, Ohio _ Republican presidential candidate George Bush
came to Cleveland Wednesday to unveil a proposal for the disabled,
but used this Midwest visit to attack Vice President Al Gore over
high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused his Democratic counterpart of supporting higher gas
prices in the past as a way to curb oil usage. Bush also criticized
a Gore proposal that would let the nation's large oil companies
keep a tax break.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent is giving oil companies a huge tax break at a time
when gas prices are out of control,'' Bush said. ``Despite what
some have speculated in the national press, I am not the cause of
these high fuel costs.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't have a national energy plan, that's a big part of the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal Bush attacked would extend a moratorium on a
``royalty tax'' oil companies paid for drilling. The tax break was
established to encourage oil exploration, but it is scheduled to
expire in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gore officials _ who said the vice president supports energy
efficiency, not high gas prices _ say extending the tax incentives
for natural gas exploration in the Gulf of Mexico is designed to
increase domestic energy and cut energy prices for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments are ``a very clumsy attempt by the Texas oil man
to deflect his close ties to oil industry,'' said Douglas Hattaway,
Gore's national campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush clearly favors big oil at the expense of cheaper, cleaner
forms of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Bush has received $1.46 million in campaign money from
the oil industry, while Gore's campaign has gotten less than
$100,000, according to the Center for Responsive Politics, a
D.C.-based watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest gas prices continue to hover between $1.80 and $2.20 per
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   A couple miles away from Bush's event, motorists at a BP gas
station said they don't really care if Bush or Gore are blamed for
the high prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're worried about playing politics with these prices, but
what good is that doing me when I have to keep pulling out $40 to
fill up my truck?,'' said Ralph Jansen, a 34-year-old construction
worker from Parma.
</P>
<P>
   Before criticizing Gore, Bush toured Vocational Guidance
Services and met with several people who have significant
disabilities. The program employs 70 people who make some of the
uniforms worn by women in the U.S. Army and Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pledged to establish a five-year $100 million federal
matching grant program with local communities to help transport the
disabled to and from work. He also proposed using $45 million in
federal funds to set up 10 pilot programs in local communities that
would develop transportation plans for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore officials, however, again blasted Bush for his record on
supporting the rights of the disabled in Texas. Gore officials said
Bush fought against a U.S. Supreme Court decision favoring people
with disabilities who want to live in their own communities rather
than institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that he's running for president, he's changing his tune,''
Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   But in Cleveland on Wednesday, Bush was treated like a movie
star by the vocational program's employees, who crowded into a
small room to give him hugs and handshakes and to seek his
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a real nice guy, we don't get to meet people
like that everyday,'' said Ricky Banks, a 40-year-old who works in
the program from his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brief East Cleveland visit continued his trend of making
appearances in places where few Republicans have gone before. His
previous Ohio visits include stops in black and Hispanic
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Cleveland, Bush also attended a fund-raiser at
the Ritz Carlton Hotel that was expected to raise at least $200,000
for the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
