<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SCOUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS SCOUTS' RIGHT TO BAR HOMOSEXUAL LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Boy Scouts can exclude homosexuals from serving
as troop leaders, the Supreme Court ruled Wednesday, saying the
Scouts constitute a private group that can set its own moral value
system.
</P>
<P>
   For the Boy Scouts the ruling is a victory in autonomy, but gay
rights groups decried the decision as sending a message of
intolerance and as a setback for the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, delivered by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist,
overturned a New Jersey Supreme Court ruling that the dismissal of
a gay scoutmaster, James Dale, violated the state's
anti-discrimination law.
</P>
<P>
   While Rehnquist noted the court was not ``guided by our views of
whether the Boy Scouts' teachings with respect to homosexual
conduct are right or wrong,'' the majority said the law should
respect the codes set by the Boy Scouts, which members pledge to be
``morally straight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that homosexuality has gained greater societal
acceptance,'' Rehnquist said. ``But this is scarcely an argument
for denying First Amendment protection to those who refuse to
accept those views.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts took ``an official position with respect to
homosexual conduct and that is sufficient for First Amendment
purposes,'' he said for the majority that included Justices Sandra
Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's reasoning drew in part on a 1995 ruling regarding
Boston's St. Patrick's Day parade, allowing the organizers to
exclude a contingent from the Irish-American Gay, Lesbian and
Bisexual Group of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But the dissenting opinion, written by Justice John Paul
Stevens, said the Boy Scouts' ``policy statements fail to establish
any clear, consistent, and unequivocal position on homosexuality.''
Therefore, retaining Dale, despite his open homosexuality, could
not contradict the Scouts' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens in the minority were Justices David H. Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased,'' said Scouts spokesman Gregg Shields.
``It's going to allow us to continue our mission of providing
character-building programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale, the former Scout leader, said, ``I'm definitely saddened
by the decision. People don't join the Boy Scouts because they're
anti-gay. People join the Boy Scouts because they want acceptance,
they want community.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan Wolfson, Dale's attorney, said Wednesday's ruling left room
for interpretation, which could mean the exclusion would extend to
all Scouts, not just leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts ``won the right to declare themselves an anti-gay
group,'' Wolfson said. ``Now they have to live with that
discriminatory decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Carla Kerr, one of lawyers representing the Boy Scouts, said she
is confident the Scouts will not face that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many openly gay 12-year-olds do you know?'' she asked.
``The oldest (Scout) is 17. There has never been a situation of an
openly gay boy in the Scouts. The Boy Scouts will address the issue
when it comes up, and it hasn't come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ettelbrick, an attorney with the National Gay and Lesbian
Task Force Policy Institute, said, ``If the Boy Scouts are
celebrating today, what they're celebrating is their entitlement to
teach young men to be homophobic and that seems a little skewed.
It's a fairly narrow loss in many respects. It could conceivably
apply to the Boy Scouts and no one else.''
</P>
<P>
   The case began 10 years ago when Dale, now 29, filed a complaint
after being thrown out of the Boy Scouts when he was identified in
a newspaper as co-president of Rutgers University's Lesbian/Gay
Alliance. Dale began scouting when he was 8 and became an Eagle
Scout at 17 before becoming an assistant scoutmaster at 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that for 12 years they taught me to be honest
and open with my relationship with other people and to be
respectful to other people,'' said Dale. ``I didn't join the Boy
Scouts because I didn't like gay people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale hopes another group similar to the Boy Scouts will evolve
but without discriminatory policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there needs to be a program that takes the place of
this program,'' Dale said. ``The dinosaurs became extinct because
they didn't evolve, just as Boy Scouts are making themselves
extinct.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare in this report.)
</P>
