<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-ROCKER-TRANSIT-BOS &LR;      06-28 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-TRANSIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER'S RIDE ON THE NO. 7: A TOUR OF THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Here's some news for John Rocker: It may be safer
for you to ride the Number 7 train to Shea Stadium than to take the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who ride the Number 7 or live along it are like
Balinder Kumar, owner of Neena Sari Palace of Queens: Too busy
making their way in America to pay attention to a ballplayer's view
of their right to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know nothing of what you talk about,'' Kumar says, when
asked about the relief pitcher and his famous contempt for the
city's immigrants and minorities. Nothing about Rocker? Baseball?
the Braves?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, nothing,'' he says. ``I have work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So if Rocker really does ride the 7, he could safely get off at
a few stops along the route, look around, and discover it's a
pretty cheap way to tour the world.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker caused a stir last December in a Sports Illustrated
interview, when he compared the Number 7 to a ride through Beirut
and described its passengers as ``some kid with purple hair next to
some queer with AIDS right next to some dude who just got out of
jail for the fourth time right next to some 20-year-old with four
kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing I don't like about New York,'' he summed up,
``are the foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves in town to play the Mets Thursday, Rocker has
said he will pass up the team's bus ride out to Shea and _ against
the urgings of the mayor and the police _ take the 7 instead.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is right about one thing: There are a lot of foreigners
riding the 7. What he probably does not know is that the Number 7
line forms the crest of the biggest and broadest wave of
immigration New York City has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   The wave forms right along the 7 line _ which starts at Times
Square, goes east to Grand Central, then cuts a swath through
northwestern Queens. Each station-stop is like a different country.
</P>
<P>
   Get out at 74th St. in Jackson Heights, and you're in some
fusion of India and Pakistan. Go one more stop, to 82nd St., and
it's Argentina and Colombia. The next three stops, at Corona,
you're in Mexico, with sidestreet views of Ecuador, Peru, and
Uruguay. Go to the end of the line in Flushing, one stop past Shea,
and it's China with a bit of Korea around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first stop for many immigrants,'' says Andrew
Beveridge, a sociologist at Queens College. ``100 years ago, the
first stop was the Lower East Side of Manhattan. Today, it's west
Queens.''
</P>
<P>
   And as they come, they settle along the Number 7 line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 7 line was built in the 1920s to redistribute the crowded
immigration populations from Manhattan,'' said Illona Harlow, who
studies these groups for the Queens Council on the Arts. ``It
continues to play the role today. It's close to the airports, and
it's a fast commute into the city where people work.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one big difference: today's immigrants are far more
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, five countries _ Russia, Italy, Austria, Germany, and
Ireland _ provided three-quarters of this city's immigrants. Today,
you could add up the numbers from the top 25 countries and account
for just two-thirds of the immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 7.3 million people in New York City, over 2 million _
nearly one-third _ were born in other countries. Of the 600,000
people in western Queens, along the Number 7 line, over half are
foreign-born.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the story of 20th-century America will find
little new in these neighborhoods. Talk with Tomas Gonzalez, owner
of La Espiga bakery in Corona, and you hear echoes of the ambitions
of Italians, Greeks, or Jews who came to New York a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez came to Queens from Mexico in 1986, and sold tacos from
a pushcart on Roosevelt Avenue, just off the 7 line. He saved his
money, and when a Colombian bakery closed down a few blocks away,
took over the lease. Two years ago he expanded into a second
bakery, and gave the original to his son.
</P>
<P>
   The new La Espiga is a hang-out for many Mexicans in the
neighborhood. The jukebox plays popular tunes from back home. A
rooftop satellite-dish brings in TV Azteca. ``This Sunday,''
Gonzalez says, ``everybody will be in here, watching the Mexican
election returns.''
</P>
<P>
   This is another difference with the new immigrants. A century
ago, few could stay in touch with their homelands even if they
wanted to. Now there's satellite TV, airplanes, long-distance
calling-cards, newspapers in dozens of languages, and a cultural
environment that, far from pushing ``Americanization,'' celebrates
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   The 74th Street stop, where Balinder Kumar has his sari shop,
might jar Rocker the most. While most of the 7's neighborhoods have
overlapping languages and nationalities, this stop is almost
monolithically Indo-Asian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest Indian shopping district in America,''
Kumar says. ``Not just people who live here, but Indian, Pakistani,
and Bangladeshi people from all over the United States come here to
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, those three peoples have fought wars against one
another. Here, signs on restaurants advertise
``Indian-Pakistani-Bangladeshi cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehmod Syed, deputy manager of the Habib American Bank, just
down the street, says, ``There are no politics here, just business.
I am Indian,'' then, pointing to another bank officer, ``he is
Pakistani. There are no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Such assimilation of subcultures is common here. But more
striking is the sharp segregation of broad cultural groups into
station-stop continents.
</P>
<P>
   The Number 7 line explains this, too. It covers a vast stretch
of land; lots of groups have room to spread out. Yet the
station-stops provide natural points for clustering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's word of mouth,'' Syed explains. ``Someone from India
comes to this neighborhood. A relative back home joins him later.
Others follow, knowing the people here speak their language,
understand their culture.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it has always worked. Groups grow, reach a
critical-mass, then scatter as they become successful. New groups
come and replace them.
</P>
<P>
   Here, even as the immigrant population soars in diversity and
number, the second stage of assimilation has already started _ the
move to the suburbs. But areas like Jackson Heights preserve the
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant specialist Harlow once saw a woman on 74th Street
drive her car up to a pushcart selling kulfi, an Indian ice cream.
``She'd driven in from Long Island,'' Harlow remembers. ``She had
some ice in a big plastic bucket, and she filled the bucket with
kulfi for her kids. She grew up with kulfi back in India, and she
wanted her kids in the American suburbs to have this in their
childhoods, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
