<HEADER>
A7594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-1100(2T     06-28 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE SUMMER WARMS UP, THE BOX OFFICE COOLS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The summer movie season had started off so
promisingly. ``Mission: Impossible 2'' racked up $91.8 million in
American theaters on the long Memorial Day weekend, fueling a
record-breaking $171 million holiday and causing swoons of ecstasy
to ripple through the corporate corridors of major movie studios.
After that, who knew what the rest of the summer of 2000 might
bring? Perhaps there would be yet another bumper crop of $100
million movies, just like last summer. Some even predicted that the
hot months would see not just one, but two or even three $200
million blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   And then something happened.
</P>
<P>
   The horizon darkened. The engine began to make a funny pinging
sound. Slowly, silently, the air went out of the tires. And the
summer movie season of 2000 began to sink into the doldrums _ at
least compared with last year's.
</P>
<P>
   There were very few outright financial disasters among the films
released in the five weeks after Memorial Day, the biggest bomb
being the animated ``Titan A.E.,'' which cost more than $85 million
and is expected to bring in somewhere around a third of that,
causing 20th Century Fox this week to close the Phoenix animation
studio that created it. But even the movies that were opening well
(``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' ``Shaft,'' ``Me, Myself and Irene'')
didn't seem to be clicking with audiences with quite the intensity
that movies had exhibited in the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Take it weekend by weekend:
</P>
<P>
   On Memorial Day, strong holdover business from the hits of May
(``Gladiator'' and ``Dinosaur''), mixed with an explosive opening
for Paramount's ``Mission: Impossible 2'' and very promising debuts
for Disney's ``Shanghai Noon'' and DreamWorks' ``Road Trip,''
created a 29 percent increase from 1999s holiday box office, when
``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' was early in its
lucrative run. The next weekend, June 2 to 4, when only one major
Hollywood film opened, the Martin Lawrence comedy ``Big Momma's
House,'' there was again an increase, 23 percent, from the 1999
figure for the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But each of the next three weekends saw dramatically lower
receipts than the parallel weekends of 1999. On the second weekend
of June 1999, ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' earned
$54.9 million. This year on that weekend, the Nicolas Cage action
film ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' led the field with $25.3 million. On
the third weekend of June last year, Disney's animated ``Tarzan''
was the leader with $34.2 million. This year it was ``Shaft,'' with
$21.7 million. And last year on the fourth weekend in June, Adam
Sandler's ``Big Daddy'' was in first place with $41.5 million. This
year it was Jim Carrey in ``Me, Myself and Irene'' at $24.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with the grosses for most of these films _
``Shaft,'' for instance, showed much more strength on opening
weekend than most had expected and has been holding up well _ but
as a group they are just not generating as much box-office heat as
last year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the total weekend grosses for the top 12 films
paled in comparison with those of 1999 _ down 19 percent in the
second weekend in June, 21 percent in the third and 23 percent in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   And that's only part of the story, because the holdover business
_ the amount of money that movies make in their second, third and
subsequent weekends _ was also, in many cases, weaker than last
summer's, when even a movie like ``The General's Daughter,'' a
Paramount film that never rose to first place at the box office,
could go on to make more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the quality of the pictures,'' said Marvin
Antonowsky, a former studio marketing executive now working as a
freelance marketing consultant. ``There's only one film that's
going to do $200 million this summer, and that's `Mission:
Impossible 2.' You've got the Jim Carrey movie doing something like
half of what the Adam Sandler comedy did in the same weekend last
year. Category by category, from big action pictures to broad
comedies, the films are just not as strong. Last summer we had two
successful romantic comedies with Julia Roberts. This summer I
don't see any big picture for the female audience, no romantic
comedies at all. It's a very weak summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the summer of 1999 was something of an anomaly,
bracketed by the eagerly anticipated return of George Lucas' ``Star
Wars'' series and the unexpected successes of ``The Sixth Sense''
and ``The Blair Witch Project'' in the season's second half. But in
between, the summer also produced one $100 million success after
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been cautious in saying that this could be a record
summer because last year was just so amazing,'' said Paul
Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor Relations, a Los Angeles
company that monitors box-office performance. ``The bottom line is
that last year there were films that people really wanted to see
that were marketed brilliantly and followed on the momentum of
`Phantom Menace.' The whole situation just pushed up everything and
revved up audiences. And the strength of the holdover last year
told us that the word-of-mouth was very, very strong. Ultimately,
it comes down to the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Fellman, president of distribution at Warner Brothers,
attributed some of the lackluster box office to the scarcity of
PG-13 movies. Too many movies are R-rated, he said, and that's bad
for the summer, when studios are trying to draw more young people
into theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in a cyclical business, and you never really
know where your hits are coming from,'' he said. ``You have to take
the broader picture. Look at the year to date. It's already up 4
percent over last year for the whole year. If the summer comes up a
little bit flat, I think the prognosis for the fall and holiday
period looks absolutely terrific. I think we may end up the year on
a high note, beating last year's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Some object to comparing this year with last, saying that 1999
was not part of a continuing upward trend but highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was abnormally high,'' said Jim Tharp, head of
distribution at DreamWorks. ``I think if you look at an average of
three years or so, this summer probably won't be down quite so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Others point to what they say is a strong lineup of films
opening in the second half of the season as evidence that it is not
too late for the summer to turn around. Those films include ``The
Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps'' with Eddie Murphy, Robert Zemeckis'
``What Lies Beneath'' with Harrison Ford and Michelle Pfeiffer,
``The Hollow Man'' with Kevin Bacon, Bryan Singer's ``X-Men,'' the
slasher-spoof ``Scary Movie'' and Disney's ``The Kid'' with Bruce
Willis.
</P>
<P>
   But the turnaround had better begin quickly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Many think that if the summer season has any chance of shaking
off the doldrums, it is with this weekend's new batch of films for
the Independence Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I think this is a key weekend if we are ever going
to close the gap this summer,'' said Jeff Blake, head of
distribution at Columbia Pictures. Columbia's own picture, ``The
Patriot,'' starring Mel Gibson, opened on Wednesday. On Friday
Gibson will be joined by George Clooney in ``The Perfect Storm''
and Robert De Niro battling animated characters in ``The Adventures
of Rocky and Bullwinkle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What should help us,'' said Dergarabedian, ``is that this
year, with the holiday falling on a Tuesday, you have what amounts
to a five-day holiday weekend. Although you have two of the films
going after the same kind of audience, the action audience, there
is enough time in a long weekend for people to see more than one
film, and I believe they will. Then you have what could be
effective counter-programming with the third film, `Rocky and
Bullwinkle,' which is aimed at a family audience.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks also intends to capitalize on the generally glowing
reviews that greeted the release of its animated ``Chicken Run''
last week by expanding into several hundred more theaters. ``That
was always the plan, to build on word-of-mouth and be in a strong
position for the long holiday weekend,'' Tharp said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor working in this weekend's favor, as least as far
as a year-by-year comparison goes, is that last year's holiday
movie menu was not particularly strong. The top-grossing film was
Barry Sonnenfeld's ``Wild, Wild West,'' which earned $36.4 million
over the four-day weekend, followed by ``South Park: Bigger, Longer
and Uncut'' with $14.7 million. Given a full five-day holiday
weekend and the paucity of the competition remaining at the box
office, this year's holiday films have at least a shot at
attracting more people.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Friedman, vice chairman of the Paramount Motion Picture
group, said it was dangerous to take too narrow a look at the box
office because of the differences between specific weekends, or
even months, from one year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're comparing things to last year, it's a pretty
dramatic difference because it was an extraordinary year,'' he
said. Then, sounding a cautiously optimistic note, he added: ``That
being said, I think that, clearly, May of this year was probably as
big as or bigger than any May in history, and June is probably not
going to be as big. But if you're looking ahead to the Fourth of
July weekend, you have some really big movies opening, and my hope
is that it will drive the rest of the business. People like to go
to the movies, and they go more often when they see movies they
enjoy.''
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
