<HEADER>
A7598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS29-COX     06-28 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio minis
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino, Nick Tate, Shane Harrison and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``One Voice''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Gilman. Epic. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Nashville is talking about 12-year-old Billy Gilman,
the little boy with the big voice who blew away audiences at the
recent TNN/Country Weekly music awards show. Like LeAnn Rimes or
Brenda Lee, Gilman is indeed gifted with hornblast pipes in a Peter
Pan body, with the ability to interpret even the most adult of
tunes (a cover of Tammy Wynette's ``'Til I Can Make It on My Own,''
for example) like a seasoned, smoke-soaked lounge singer. But like
a two-headed calf at the fair, the young man's debut is more
sideshow than substance. It's not Gilman's fault. This debut CD,
produced by Blake Chancey (Dixie Chicks) is as studio slick as
anything coming out of Nashville. The boy's voice is extraordinary,
and shows great potential. But Gilman's age creates a curiosity
factor that erodes any lasting artistic expression in his music.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Billy Gilman:
www.nightsideentertainment.com
</P>
<P>
   /billygilman.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FOLK
</P>
<P>
   ``'Til We Outnumber 'Em ... the Songs of Woody Guthrie''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Righteous Babe. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that the song most closely associated with Woody
Guthrie, ``This Land Is Your Land,'' is often regarded as an
American anthem and not the protest song he intended. That's one
reason the clever retread of the song, overlaid with a famous
Guthrie tale of defiance, is such a satisfying highlight of this
marvelous tribute. Featuring a who's who of singer-songwriters,
``Outnumber'' excerpts a stellar 1996 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
concert that emphasized Guthrie's radical, political side. With
standout performances from Arlo Guthrie, Ani DiFranco and Bruce
Springsteen, who provides a riveting cover of ``Plane Wreck at Los
Gatos (Deportee),'' this is a classic musical toast to America's
foremost protest singer, complete with a folk hootenanny-style
closing singalong.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Woody Guthrie:
www.www.rockhall.com/hof/inductee.asp?id &QC; 115
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Fold Your Hands Child, You Walk Like a Peasant''
</P>
<P>
   Belle &AMP; Sebastian. Matador. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   You might want to keep a paperweight handy for this one. Like
the band's 1996 masterpiece, ``If You're Feeling Sinister,'' the
critically adored Scottish combo's fourth album is lighter than
air. It's quietly soulful and brimming with Burt Bacharach-style
strings and horns, but lacks ``Sinister's'' consistent melodicism
and melancholy charisma. ``I Fought in a War'' is as gorgeous as
anything the band's ever done and ``The Chalet Lines'' is a lyrical
marvel, but too much of it is uninvolving. While it's only
disappointing relative to the band's high standards, ``Fold Your
Hands Child'' feels like a minor work in the canon of a brilliant
band.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Belle &AMP; Sebastian:
</P>
<P>
   www.belleandsebastian.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome II Nextasy''
</P>
<P>
   Next. Arista. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   As Jagged Edge proposes marriage and Carl Thomas stakes his
claim as a new Mr. Romance, Next is happy being the unabashed R&AMP;B
act with its focus solely on the bedroom, baby. And the follow-up
to its million-selling debut is basically 13 inviting lures
(interludes excluded). A couple are both danceable and
complimentary (``Wifey''), one is delivered in the stop-start,
theatrical fashion of elder balladeer Gerald LeVert (``When We
Kiss'') and some are kind of clever plays on words (``Cybersex,''
``Jerk''). But thin-voiced crooners R.L., Tweety and T-Low get
overall creative points just for coming up with so many fun ways to
get, um, say one thing.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Next and Arista Records:
www.arista.com
</P>
<P>
   www.nextonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino, Nick Tate, Shane Harrison and Sonia Murray
writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
