A7599 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP29-COX     06-28 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salmon Pate uses what's likely on hand
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bernice Duthaler of Peachtree City asked readers for help
replacing her lost recipe for Salmon Pate using canned salmon,
Helen White of Winston sent hers. One of the great things about
this appetizer, to be served on wheat crackers, is that it can be
made using ingredients you probably have on hand. Our tester
recommended listing the anchovy paste as optional, according to
your preference.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Salmon Pate
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces cream cheese, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 inch anchovy paste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cocktail sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 (12-ounce) can salmon
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 hard-boiled egg, chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Combine cream cheese, butter, anchovy paste (if using), onion,
cocktail sauce, lemon juice, lemon pepper, horseradish,
Worcestershire sauce and salmon. Blend with a mixer until creamy.
Add salt to taste. Shape into a ball. In a shallow dish, mix
chopped egg and parsley; roll salmon ball in egg mixture until
completely covered. Refrigerate at least 2 hours or overnight.
Serve with wheat crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without crackers): 117 calories, 8 grams protein, 9
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 70), 1 gram carbohydrates, 50
milligrams cholesterol, 251 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Nicolson is looking for a dish made with eggs, cottage
cheese and dill, baked in a pastry shell. Her mother recalls having
it when growing up in a Hungarian community in Saskatchewan.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Classey of Atlanta is looking for a recipe for a good
oatmeal bread.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
