<HEADER>
A7601 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-DECALOGUE29-COX     06-28 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DECALOGUE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Decalogue' commands your attention
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you first commit to watching ``The Decalogue,'' its 10-hour
running length stretches before you like a prison sentence. But by
the time you reach the last of Krzysztof Kieslowski's masterful and
melancholy episodes, you won't want it to end. Inspired by the 10
biblical commandments, this urban epic of interlocked stories
absorbs you, becomes the atmosphere you breathe, makes you view
your own life and relationships with new eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Now available on VHS and DVD for the first time in this country
(on two disks or five tapes), this filmmaking milestone marked the
second collaboration of the director, who died four years ago, and
co-screenwriter Krzysztof Piesiewicz. They reteamed to make the
acclaimed French theatrical trio ``Blue,'' ``White'' and ``Red'' in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Centering on a massively bleak concrete apartment complex in
Warsaw, Poland, each of the hourlong episodes teases out sometimes
direct, sometimes elusive interpretations of the commandments.
They're meditations on morality. One of the work's many pleasures
is seeing how the filmmakers took each biblical injunction and
sifted it through the filters of contemporary, workaday lives in
the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   In the first (``I Am the Lord Thy God''), a professor's false
faith in his personal deities _ logic, mathematics and the computer
_ leads to tragedy involving his son. The literally chilly tone
(it's set in snowy wintertime) and slow pacing of this opener take
some getting used to, but it primes you for the deliberate,
intimate scale of all the films.
</P>
<P>
   The films hinge on small gestures, changing perceptions, quiet
conversations. But in their understatement and simplicity, they
create an immense emotional undertow for the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Number 5 (``Thou Shalt Not Kill'') is brutally simple in its
effectiveness. An unstrung young man loiters around a village,
hails a cab and pointlessly kills its driver in an extended,
real-time scene that's famous for its detailed, mundane horrors. In
turn, the killer is executed by the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Several episodes touch on more than one commandment. Number 3
(``Honor the Sabbath Day'') includes issues of adultery and false
witness as a married man leaves his family at home on Christmas
Eve, spending the night on a goose-chase with a former lover who
claims she's seeking her missing husband. Number 7 (``Thou Shalt
Not Steal'') is as much about honoring one's parents (or at least
enduring them) as it is about theft.
</P>
<P>
   Through ``The Decalogue,'' you see that no single rule of
conduct can exist without interacting with the others. Pull one
thread, and the whole fabric is imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the films end with a close-up of a single face,
locked in confusion, loss or a sudden bittersweet understanding. In
those moments, the camera seems to take us into the very souls of
the characters. It helps that the actors are uniformly excellent.
It's also a plus that their faces are unfamiliar to us; we seem to
be watching real people rather than actors.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken in Polish, with English subtitles, the movies aren't much
to look at. They tend toward the grainy and dark, but they're fit
for the small screen. After all, they were originally shot for
Polish television in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   That makes ``The Decalogue'' even more valuable these days, when
the closest American television comes to moral exploration is by
making something as dumb as ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Decalogue'' (unrated)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on Kieslowski:
www.dencity.com/metestudio/metekieslowski.htm
</P>
<P>
   Notable titles now on sale
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DVD: ``The X-Files Season One,'' seven-disc set, $149.98.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TV: ``The Simpsons Political Party,'' three tapes, two
episodes apiece, $24.98 gift set or $9.98 per tape.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
