<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A twisty, lovely look at la dolce vita
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ahandsome adaptation of novelist Patricia Highsmith's twisty
thriller. Matt Damon plays the title character, who travels to
Italy to bring back a rich man's son (the charismatic Jude Law, who
steals the movie). Once he begins to enjoy the Mediterranean dolce
vita, though, Ripley ends up adopting his lifestyle and plotting
murder.
</P>
<P>
   A wan Gwyneth Paltrow drifts through scenes as Law's girlfriend,
while Cate Blanchett turns in a hilarious caricature of a lockjawed
heiress taking a tour of the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   Director Anthony Minghella infuses the film with more overt
homoeoticism than ``Purple Noon,'' a less faithful but more
effective French version of the same novel. In the end, though, the
overt changes make this movie lovely to look at, but
psychologically questionable.
</P>
<P>
   `The Talented Mr. Ripley'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Consitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a review of ``Purple Noon'':
www.epinions.com/mvie-review
</P>
<P>
   -8B-12DCA15-38885B0F-bd1
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Runaway Bride'' (PG)does well by its intended audience,
i.e., anyone who wants to see Roberts galloping on horseback in
full wedding regalia. She's a bride who has already choked at the
altar three times and is about to try again; he's a cynical
journalist who's betting she'll run. Joan Cusack, Hector Elizondo
and Rita Wilson add spice in supporting parts. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hanging Up'' (PG) _ Breezily written by the Ephron sisters
and briskly directed by Diane Keaton, this movie's ads wanted you
to believe it's a side-splitting sibling comedy about three sisters
(Keaton, Meg Ryan and Lisa Kudrow) trying to connect. But it's
really a selfish aging parent/confused adult child story in which
Ryan tries to be all things to her dying dad (Walter Matthau). The
performances are fine, but the movie lacks the courage to be the
painful, genuine story it is.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
