<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYERS-EDGE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A festive fourth for under $100
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheers for the red, white and blue on the Fourth of July!
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans celebrate this all-American holiday with patriotic
programs, parties and, of course, the Peachtree Road Race. Food
celebrations range from picnics to buffets to sitdown dinners.
</P>
<P>
   If it's your turn to throw a firecracker of a party on Tuesday,
we'll show you how to do it, at the last minute, on a budget of
$100 _ with a minimum of fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Our choice? An informal neighborhood potluck at 5 p.m. for eight
people. Ask guests to bring a favorite cool summer salad _ who
wants to labor over a hot grill? _ and you spring for watermelon
for dessert. The late-afternoon start allows plenty of time for
food and conversation before everyone rushes off to see fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   We spent our money on such gotta-haves as festive tableware,
stemware, decorations, even edible party favors to savor at home.
Note: Beverages are not included in the cost, but a big pitcher of
lemonade or even a three-liter box of inexpensive wine won't
stretch the budget too much.
</P>
<P>
   To roll out the red, white and blue with gusto, we enlisted the
aid of Teri Craton, a certified meeting professional with Atlanta
Arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a fun, festive atmosphere to make your guests feel
welcome and comfortable,'' said Craton, whose day job is putting on
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``July Fourth is the perfect time for a nostalgic, rah-rah
party. And with a potluck, preparation time is minimal. Remember,
keep it simple and everyone, including you, can relax and
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   CREATING A FESTIVE TABLE
</P>
<P>
   For a bang-up look, Craton spread a white sheet (or use a blue
one) from her linen closet over the table. Next she placed two
striped banners lengthwise in the center to create a runner, thus
giving dimension and design to the white cloth. She used two pots
of white daisy mums, which she already had on her patio, and placed
them in colorful, Uncle Sam hats _ turned upside-down _ and used as
planters. As an accent, she placed an American flag in each pot and
added finely crinkled flag-colored crepe paper around the flower
stems.
</P>
<P>
   On each of the stars and stripes paper plates, she rolled a red,
a white and a blue fork, spoon and knife, plus a tiny flag, inside
a matching napkin and tied it with ribbon. Over the entire table,
she sprinkled star and flag-shaped confetti. Additional accents:
new candles in white and blue and a recycled red one from
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of plastic stemware, Craton found good-looking, cobalt
blue acrylic glasses and a matching pitcher _ the most expensive
items for the party. But think of it as an investment: You'll use
these again and again, for pool parties or picnics on the beach. To
serve the watermelon, she placed it in a basket (already on hand)
and tied the handles with wired patriotic-colored ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   For a take-home party favor, Craton put four mini blueberry
muffins in a plastic bag, tied it with shiny red ``star'' garland
and a miniature flag.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND TOTAL: $95.22
</P>
<P>
   What we spent and where:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Party City, $30.83: Two flag banners ($4.99 each); two Uncle
Sam hats ($1.29 each); eight tiny flags (69 cents each); two large
flags (two for $1.79); one package star and flag-shaped confetti
($3.59); plastic forks, knives, spoons ($1.19 each; 24 in each
bag); one package stars and stripes luncheon napkins ($1.65 for
16); one package stars and stripes paper plates ($2.15 for eight).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Michael's, $8: One blue and one white candle (each $1.50); two
spools of wired ribbon (two for $5).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Container Store, $4.98: Two containers of tiny plastic
bags (each container, $2.49, contains six).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden Ridge, $34.45: Acrylic pitcher ($7.97); eight matching
glasses ($2.97 each); one bag red, white and blue finely crinkled
crepe paper ($1.28); one roll shiny red star garland ($1.44).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Publix, $16.96: Three dozen mini blueberry muffins ($3.99 a
dozen); one watermelon ($4.99).
</P>
<P>
   LET'S PARTY
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Williamson, author of ``Entertaining for Dummies''
($19.95, I.D.G.) and consultant to Rich's, offers the following
suggestions on giving a successful July Fourth party:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There's absolutely nothing wrong with paper plates and
napkins, and plastic forks, spoons and knives. However, no drink
tastes good in a plastic cup or glass. Spend your money on acrylic
stemware.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use a white or blue sheet for a tablecloth. And, if you don't
use paper napkins, red/white or blue/white dish towels make
inexpensive napkins. Tie them with flag-colored ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If your party is in the yard, attach crepe streamers to trees
and to the serving table.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For flowers, use a bucket or a container you already own, such
as a pitcher, and fill it with posies from your garden, which might
be sunflowers, hydrangeas and zinnias. Or purchase pots of flowers
_ less expensive than cut ones.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red, blue and white candles add a festive note to tables. Use
saucers from your kitchen as candleholders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy CDs of John Philip Sousa's march music and play them
during the party. You might rent a movie and show ``Stars and
Stripes Forever'' or ``Yankee Doodle Dandy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take-home party favors might be classic blueberry muffins or
all-American chocolate chip cookies nestled in plastic bags and
tied with red ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
