r l BC-CHAIR-BACK29-COX     06-28 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAIR-BACK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Furniture details that draw second looks _ from behind
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   High Point, N.C. _ Reach back.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly run your hand along the row of buttons, the metal studs.
Gently caress the shoulders and curvaceous sides. Let your
fingertips dance along the treads of that long intriguing zipper.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, you've ``undressed'' the secret to designing
sofas and chairs for today's large rooms.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in the backs.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture, instead of hugging the walls, is ``floated'' more
often these days to the center of the room to form a cozy
arrangement conducive to conversation or watching the tube. As that
occurs, consumers are suddenly noticing bare backs and sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, you'd put a sofa table behind a sofa to soften it,''
said Atlanta interior designer Bill Stewart. ``But now, backs and
sides are becoming so much more expressive, whether it's the shape
of the piece, nail head trim, buttons, finishes, moldings.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers of contemporary furniture, especially Italians, have
always treated sofas and chairs as sculpture, taking into account
how they look from all sides, said Bryan Albrecht of Domus, an
Atlanta contemporary furniture store.
</P>
<P>
   But now, even traditional designs are embracing a mix of
materials, sensuous shapes and dressmaker kick pleats to put the
best face on a back. That much was evident at last spring's
International Home Furnishings Market in High Point, where
traditional styles reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backs of sofas and chairs used to be like the back of the
bed. Nobody saw them,'' said designer Larry Laslo, showing new
pieces for John Widdicomb Company. ``Now, they're looking at sides
and backs as well as the fronts _ still lean and clean but with
some decoration.''
</P>
<P>
   Makers of dining room chairs have always gotten it. The most
interesting part of the chair has always been the most visible _
the back _ since chairs are pushed under, more often than away
from, the table. But as rooms grow bigger and ceilings higher,
chair backs have gotten taller, said Atlanta interior designer
Charles Gandy.
</P>
<P>
   For occasional chairs, designers are crafting backs and sides
with open spaces, intricate hardware, raised panels and other
detailing.
</P>
<P>
   Sofas are rolling out of factories with rounded backs, heavy
seams, wood and metal accents.
</P>
<P>
   Even headboards, as beds get floated away from the corners of
rooms, are getting special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is just this big old slab to look at anymore,''
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it? Watch your back.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
