<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-SWEETTEA29-COX     06-28 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SWEETTEA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's an art to making sweet tea _ and it's being lost
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been said that in the South, you can't marry a man until
you know how his Mama makes sweet tea. Which is to say, folks
around here can be as particular about their sweet tea as they are
about their barbecue and corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   So the most avid fans of the house wine of the South have
created their ``perfect'' formula for the drink after years of
tinkering with tea making.
</P>
<P>
   But a dear friend recently asked me quite sincerely, ``How do
you make sweet tea?'' I was surprised, because he's from Kentucky
and has lived in Georgia for years. I guess I figured Southerners
just knew how to make sweet tea.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it makes sense that many of us don't anymore. That
space in the refrigerator where a pitcher of tea used to be is now
the home for soft drinks and other ready-to-drink beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Good sweet tea, it seems, is in peril in a world where there's
little appreciation for the joy of process _ even the short and
painless process of brewing a pitcher of tea. (Now, what is it
we're doing instead? Oh yes, making money and sitting in traffic
jams.)
</P>
<P>
   Even in restaurants, it's hard to get a good glass of sweet tea.
Where it's offered, it's often too weak or too sweet. And some
mimic restaurants outside the South and offer unsweetened tea only,
pointing to packets of sugar or artificial sweetener as the answer.
</P>
<P>
   It is not. Proper sweet tea must be sweetened when the tea is
still warm so the sugar will dissolve. There is one way to sweeten
already-cold tea, which I'll discuss, but the proper way is both
best and easiest.
</P>
<P>
   Ronni Lundy, author of ``Butter Beans to Blackberries: Recipes
From the Southern Garden'' (North Point Press, $30), provides a
good explanation of the process, starting with the tea.
</P>
<P>
   Plain orange pekoe is the best for iced tea. Lundy prefers
Luzianne; I've always used Lipton. For a 1 1/2-quart pitcher of
tea, use five regular-size tea bags of Lipton's or six of Luzianne.
Ice will weaken the tea, so it's good to start with a fairly hearty
brew.
</P>
<P>
   Put the tea bags in a pitcher _ Lundy recommends a heavy-duty
glass or thick stoneware pitcher. It must be sturdy enough to
handle boiling water. Plastic may melt; aluminum can absorb and
give off strange odors and flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a quart of water to a boil _ grabbing it off the burner
just when the bubbles start to burst through the surface. Pour the
water over the tea bags, soaking them through, and leave to steep
for about an hour. Anywhere between 30 minutes and an hour into
steeping, add about 1 cup sugar and stir. Yes, this is to taste.
Try it with a cup once, then adjust to your sweet tooth. After an
hour, remove the tea bags.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, add about 1 to 1 1/2 cups cold water and stir. Do not
serve the tea until it has cooled completely, Lundy warns. ``If
it's the least bit warm, it will melt the ice in the glass,
diluting the tea and making the drink tepid _ not what you want at
all.'' Fill the glass with ice cubes (crushed ice will melt) and
pour in the tea. A lemon wedge and sprig of mint make nice
additions, though I prefer mine straight up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you find yourself with a glass of brewed tea that is not
sweetened, there is one option for sweet success _ a simple syrup,
like that offered at the Blue Ridge Grill in small pitchers. Here's
my recipe.
</P>
<P>
   simple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Put 1 1/4 cups sugar and 1 1/2 cups water in a saucepan over low
heat. Bring to a boil, stirring constantly, until all the sugar is
dissolved. Remove from heat promptly. It should be clear, not
bronze. Let syrup cool, and then chill, covered. Use for up to two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
