r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE29-COX     06-28 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband enjoys Blue Bunny, a very healthy brand of ice
cream. But we haven't found it in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marissa McNeel, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: I scream, you scream, we all scream for . . . Blue Bunny Ice
Cream. This cool, reduced-fat treat (no sugar added) is available
at Wal-Mart Supercenter, 1436 Dogwood Drive, Conyers
(770-860-8544). A half-gallon is $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa-based Wells Dairy was founded in 1913 by Fred H. Wells.
He had the milk distribution route in La Mars, Iowa, as well as a
source of raw milk from dairy farmer Ray Bowers. Over the years,
Wells and his brother distributed ice cream all over Iowa. They
changed the name from Wells to Blue Bunny when a Sioux City man won
a ``Name That Ice Cream'' contest. He submitted his winning entry
after noticing how much his son enjoyed the blue bunnies in a
department store at Easter. The company also makes premium, premium
lite and fat-free ice creams as well as fat-free yogurt in a
variety of flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find Sunkist Fruit Gems _ a soft, chewy,
sugar-coated candy. These are especially good for someone who has
sworn off chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carol Hoefs, Tucker, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another sweet request: I am looking for a local store that
carries the candy Aplets &AMP; Cotlets. They are available by mail, but
the cost of shipping and handling, added to the price, makes a
somewhat daunting total.
</P>
<P>
   _ Frederick A. Pope, Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sweet tooths everywhere will appreciate this info. Sunkist
Fruit Gems are sold at Market Grocery, 16 Forest Parkway, State
Farmers Market, Building K, Forest Park (404-361-8620). A
3.15-pound plastic jar (144 pieces) is $5.45. We also spotted the
fruit gems (1-pound bag, $1.99) at Drug Emporium, 2320 Pleasant
Hill Road, Duluth (770-623-9444). These fat-free,
melt-in-your-mouth confections are made with fruit pectin and
contain no cholesterol or preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The other request, Liberty Orchard's Aplets &AMP; Cotlets, is
available at CVS, 3010 Centerville Road, Snellville (770-736-6512).
A 5-ounce box is $1.99. Manufactured in the Pacific Northwest for
80 years, these candies are made from the juice of Washington
apples, ripe apricots and English walnuts, and then rolled in
powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you find Advance Carpenter Ant Bait? It was mentioned in
a recent article in the newspaper. I have tried Home Depot,
Wal-Mart and Lowe's, but no luck.
</P>
<P>
   _ Winnie Tallant, Cumming, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Soon you will be able to give those pesky carpenter ants the
boot. We tracked down Advance Carpenter Ant Bait at U-Spray, 4653
U.S. 78, Lilburn (770-985-9388). A 2-pound jug is $70. You can
sprinkle the granular bait indoors or outdoors, wherever you see
the ants foraging. The worker ants take the bait back to the nest,
and it eventually kills the queen and the larvae and, finally, the
worker ants.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I can't seem to find Sweet Baby Ray's Barbecue Sauce in
Atlanta and would appreciate your help. They have a Web site,
www.sweetbabyrays.com, but only sell by the case. Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Todd Williams, Stockbridge, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Fire up that grill. Sweet Baby Ray's Barbecue Sauce is at Cub
Foods stores. An 18-ounce plastic bottle is $1.98. Publix has the
sauce, too. Two 18-ounce bottles are $3 at their stores. The sauce
is also available at Patton's Meat Markets, 3931 Peachtree
Industrial Blvd., Duluth (770-495-0077). An 18-ounce bottle is
$2.99. Dave Raymond and Mike O'Brien, owners of Illinois-based
Sweet Baby Ray's, describe their sauce as having ``a sweet tangy
flavor with a kick.'' Brush it on ribs, chicken or steak during the
last 15 minutes of barbecuing or broiling. And the company
philosophy? ``The Sauce is the Boss.''
</P>
<P>
   An update: Several readers called to say they can no longer find
Beemans, Black Jack and Clove gums. We reported last year that
Adams, the manufacturer, brought back these nostalgic brands for a
limited time. Alas, the gum did not click with too many customers,
so it's not being produced this year. However, if gum fans,
including reader Roger McDonald, want to call Adams _ a division of
Warner Lambert _ and ask it to reconsider making the gum again, the
number is 1-800-524-2854.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
