<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7608 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ELIAN-FAMILYFEUD-ABRI     06-28 2083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-FAMILYFEUD-ABRIDGED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANOTHER CUBAN FAMILY SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For immediate release.)  
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Now that Elian Gonzalez is on his way back to
Cuba, we call your attention to the following ``separate-buy''
article from The New York Times Magazine, which recounts how the
rift in the Gonzalez family developed -- both before and after the
tragedy that landed Elian in the United States and its court
system. For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ALSO INCLUDED: A FREE GRAPHIC of Elian's family tree, created in
Adobe Illustrator. It can be sent to you electronically. Simply
e-mail Peter Trigg, Communications Director, at
nytsf(AT)nytimes.com.
 &HT;    
 By TIM GOLDEN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    On Thanksgiving, three days after his ex-wife and son went
missing in Cuba, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, 31, received a call from
Miami relatives with the news that his 5-year-old son Elian had
been pulled from the waters off the Florida coast by a couple of
fishermen.
 &HT;    Later, after visiting the child at a hospital near Fort
Lauderdale, Juan Miguel's Uncle Lazaro called again to tell him
that the boy's mother Elisa had perished at sea in an apparent
failed flight from Cuba, but that Elian had survived the ordeal
astonishingly well.
 &HT;    The next day, TV news crews had already turned up at the
hospital, followed by the first Cuban-American politicians offering
their support.
 &HT;    With all the attention, Juan Miguel's Aunt Caridad in Miami had
begun hoping for a second small miracle to follow Elian's rescue:
that her brother (Juan Miguel's father) and his family might
finally have a reason to leave Cuba and join the rest of the
Gonzalezes in the United States ...
 &HT;    But, the story begins in Cardenas, the home of the Gonzalez
family on Cuba's north coast ...
 &HT;    The elegant colonial town built in the 19th century sits two and
a half hours east of Havana _ and due south of the Florida Keys, in
the path of currents that have carried wave after wave of desperate
migrants to the United States.
 &HT;    When Castro and his rebels overthrew Fulgencio Batista in 1959,
Cardenas was, for the most part, remote from the centers of the
uprising. Juan Miguel Gonzalez's grandparents, Luis and Georgina,
weathered the revolution relatively well; Luis kept his job as a
stevedore at the Cardenas port. The couple's nine children _ Juan
Miguel's father, aunts and uncles _ had a tougher time, and
struggled to find any work at all.
 &HT;    Uncle Delfin, then a dock worker in his early 20s, was among
those in the family with great hopes for the revolution. ``I think
I supported them for about a month,'' he said of the Communists.
 &HT;    On March 22, 1962, Delfin was arrested and charged with
subversion. He was sentenced to 10 years in prison. His devastated
mother Georgina, took down the large framed photograph of Castro
that she had put up on the living-room wall.
 &HT;    Later, several of Juan Miguel's aunts and uncles would remember
1962 as the year they began thinking about a new life outside of
Cuba.
 &HT;    For Caridad, whose husband had divorced her and hopped a boat
for Miami, America became a dream of opportunity, freedom and
requited love. When Castro announced in September 1965 that Cubans
with relatives in the United States would be free to leave,
Caridad, then a 35-year-old seamstress, boarded one of the
so-called freedom flights and flew to Miami.
 &HT;    Back in Cuba, Aunt Haydee got a job in a school cafeteria; Uncle
Manolo trained as a mechanic and found work repairing boat motors
for a fishing cooperative; Lazaro emerged as a talented young
gymnast just as Cuba began to pour resources into its sports
program; Juan Miguel's father, Juan, took a job as a police
investigator in the interior ministry, a career choice that not all
his siblings appreciated.
 &HT;    In 1979, with Caridad's help, Delfin got a visa and came to the
United States just months before his mother's death. Another of
Juan Miguel's aunts brought her family in 1983, and Luis, the
family patriarch, followed her the next spring. Manolo and Lazaro
took their families to Costa Rica in August 1984 and applied for
American visas there.
 &HT;    In Miami's Little Havana, the Cuban culture that received them
had begun to grow more diverse with the influx of the younger, more
liberal emigres. At the same time, older anti-Castro exiles were
coming into their own as an American political force.
 &HT;    But in Cuba, the next generation of Gonzalezes grew up seeing
the country differently. None of them knew a world before Fidel. In
the late 1960s and '70s, when some of Juan Miguel's uncles were
growing bitter, when his aunts felt like outcasts for going to
church, some of their children seemed to thrive.
 &HT;    Like thousands of other young Cubans of his generation, Juan
Miguel's eldest cousin, Jose Antonio, became the first member of
his family to attend college, earning a degree from the University
of Matanzas that led him to a job with the ministry of agriculture.
 &HT;    But if Castro had chosen among the cousins for one to champion
his crusade, he could not have done better than Juan Miguel.
Following in his father's path, Juan Miguel joined the Union of
Young Communists at 15 and threw himself into the duties it
presented.
 &HT;    In September 1984, he met Elisabeth Brotons at a birthday party
and the two soon fell in love. When they married, Elisa was just
shy of 16, Juan Miguel not yet 17.
 &HT;    At first, they lived with Elisa's mother, Raquel Rodriguez. Juan
Miguel left school after 10th grade and went to work in a paper
factory, training to become an electrician. Eventually, Elisa and
Juan Miguel went to night school to earn their high school
diplomas.
 &HT;    While he completed his three years of military service with an
army firefighting unit near Cardenas, she enrolled at a vocational
school in Varadero that prepared workers for jobs in hotels and
restaurants.
 &HT;    Varadero, a long ribbon of white-sand beach 10 miles west of
Cardenas, was becoming a centerpiece of Fidel Castro's reluctant
effort to attract foreign capital after the collapse of the Soviet
Union. Its hotels, many of them operated or partly owned by foreign
companies, offered some of the best-paying jobs in the country.
 &HT;    In 1990, Elisa went to work as a chambermaid at the newest
Varadero hotel. Juan Miguel also found a job in Varadero, and
eventually, he and Elisa did well enough to buy a creaky 1956 Nash
Rambler and to build a home for themselves next to his family's
house.
 &HT;    But Juan Miguel and Elisa struggled to have a child, eventually
losing seven pregnancies.
 &HT;    After several years of marriage, they started drifting apart.
Friends saw them as having less and less in common: she loved
clothes and perfume and romantic movies; he liked hanging out with
friends _ and began to go with other women.
 &HT;    Finally, in May 1991, they divorced. Then, several months later,
they were living together again. ``We had always wanted to have a
child,'' Juan Miguel said. ``We got together again to see if we
could do it. And finally we did.'' After months of bed rest and
prenatal checkups, Elisa gave birth on Dec. 6, 1993 to Elian, a
name made up from the first three letters of Elisa and the last two
of Juan.
 &HT;    But as much as Elisa cared for Juan Miguel, she was tired of his
running around. Juan Miguel, for his part, said he felt different,
too. ``She was like a sister to me,'' he said. In February 1997, 11
years after they were married and two months after Elian's third
birthday, they separated for good.
 &HT;    Still friends after the split, they shared custody of the boy
and Elisa remained close to her former in-laws.
 &HT;    Elisa's life began to turn on an evening in August 1997, when at
a Varadero nightspot with friends she met Lazaro Rafael Munero.
Within about two months, he went to live with her at Raquel's
house.
 &HT;    Elisa insisted she had found a good man. The son of an oil
worker, Munero had dropped out of school in 10th grade; at age 18,
he was imprisoned for more than a year for breaking into a hotel
room with a friend and stealing $236.55 from a German tourist. When
he met Elisa, he was 22; his steadiest job had been selling soft
drinks and beer to tourists on the beach in front of one of the
Varadero hotels. Mostly, he made his living as a taxi driver.
 &HT;    ``He would come by here sometimes to pick up the boy or drop him
off,'' Juan Miguel said of Munero. ``We got along with him all
right.''
 &HT;    Less than a year later, he left Cuba in a small boat with three
friends. Elisa's relatives say that he tried to persuade her to go
with him but that she refused.
 &HT;    Four months after his arrival in Florida, Munero bought a
motorized rubber raft to return to Cuba. He was picked up on Oct.
26, 1998 by the Cuban Coast Guard.
 &HT;    Munero spent the next two months there in prison. After his
release, he moved back in with Elisa at her mother's apartment.
Later they rented an apartment of their own and took Elian with
them.
 &HT;    Months later, they set off before dawn with friends and some of
Munero's family in a homemade boat with a balky 50-horsepower
motor.
 &HT;    Juan Miguel says that only in their first conversation after
Elian was released from the hospital did the boy ever speak about
what had happened.
 &HT;    ```Papa, my mama got lost in the sea,''' Juan Miguel remembers
his son saying. ``I told him: `Don't worry. You will be right back
here with me.''' Later that night, Juan Miguel said, his Aunt
Caridad called. ``She told me: `With all this, your life is set
here.'' Several of his other aunts and uncles called with similar
pleas.
 &HT;    ``Then Lazaro and Delfin called, and they started to offend
me,'' Juan Miguel said. ``They started telling me how bad the
government here is, all that. And me _ I have my ideals. They never
said a thing about the boy staying there _ they were just insisting
that we should go there.''
 &HT;    Two days later, the foreign ministry in Havana sent the United
States a diplomatic note seeking the boy's return.
 &HT;    Fidel Castro himself asked him how he felt about the situation
and what he wanted to do. ``He told me I could do what I pleased,''
Juan Miguel said. ``If I wanted to leave, I could leave.
Nonetheless, I told him no. My decision was clear.''
 &HT;    Castro was quick to recognize the episode's political potential:
an issue with the power to galvanize not only the party faithful
but also every Cuban parent and child and millions of people
abroad.
 &HT;    Within weeks of his rescue, Elian had become the biggest
revolutionary symbol since Che.
 &HT;    Castro's enemies were just as quick to recognize a poster child
when they saw one.
 &HT;    According to people working with the family, the cause has been
dominated by the Cuban American National Foundation, which has
sponsored most of the Gonzalezes political activities and advised
them on strategy.
 &HT;    As for Cuba, ``What is clear is that he is going to continue to
be a boy symbol, a boy hero,'' said Ricardo Chapelin, the Communist
Party chief -in Cardenas. ``This battle did not begin with Elian.
Our struggle has been one of challenging the government of the
United States for its attacks against our country. And we will
continue with this struggle, which is one that strengthens us in
every way.''
 &HT;    Elian has strengthened a lot of those who have fought over his
welfare. Fidel Castro hasn't looked so energetic in years. His
adversaries in Miami, while out of step with most Americans,
managed to seize hold of the presidential campaign, bring the U.S.
attorney general to their doorstep and reassert their once-fading
influence on Capitol Hill.
 &HT;    And Juan Miguel's uncle, Lazaro, is said to be weighing movie
and book deals of various sorts.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;     c.2000 Tim Golden  
