<HEADER>
A7609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRITNEY-SPEARS-ART-NY     06-28 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITNEY-SPEARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OOPS GIRL WITH THE BIG SMILE AND THE LITTLE VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JON PARELES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WANTAGH, N.Y. _ ``What you see is what you get,'' Britney Spears
sang at the Jones Beach Theater on Tuesday night. And what you get
from this 18-year-old singer is a big smile, a little voice, gushes
of sincerity, hardworking dance routines, shameless advertising and
a determination to play both sides of pubescence for all they're
worth. To an audience full of squealing little girls, Spears
previewed adolescent romance as a realm where all that matters are
a girl's feelings and her wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Spears, whose two albums have sold 16 million copies in the
United States, makes Madonna seem like a tortured artist. She is
eager to please and eager to sell both her music and her sponsors'
products. Her face on advertising posters greeted concertgoers at
the entrance; commercials were shown between sets. Since she is
sponsored by both a camera company and dairy farmers, fans could
have instant photos taken next to a Britney cutout with a milk
mustache.
</P>
<P>
   But her hits, which reached a nation of young mall shoppers,
were what brought the advertisers. Spears gets her best material
from a Swedish pop consortium led by Max Martin. Their songs chug
along in minor keys, pumped up with hard-rock guitar chords and
punctuated by throaty little moans. The lyrics switch between
promises of loyalty and pouty kiss-offs, growing marginally more
assertive on Spears' second album, ``Oops! ... I Did It Again.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs are often about being lonely or broken-hearted,
wishing a lost love would come back. Yet her show keeps her
surrounded with perky dancers who are as compliant as a high-school
clique, following her moves and sometimes raising her aloft. Her
voice, suitable for the lead in a road-show production of
``Annie,'' doesn't often stand on its own; it's carried by backup
singers and, possibly, prerecorded harmonies. But she does make
sure to moan.
</P>
<P>
   As scripted by the Swedes, Spears' main complaint is that people
keep telling her that her dresses are too short. Singing ``What U
See (Is What U Get),'' which insists that she's faithful even if
she likes to dress and dance seductively, she wore glittery jeans
and a halter top and clutched the kind of silver pole that
strippers use. When she reached the line, ``Take me as I am,'' she
twitched her hips in a clear bump and grind. Throughout the show,
she kept tearing away baggy clothes to wear navel-baring outfits
underneath. But she plays the good girl, not the vamp. The boy who
won a ``Meet Britney'' contest onstage got an arm's-length
handshake and a polite ``Nice to meet you.''
</P>
<P>
   With her long blond hair extensions, chesty figure and unfailing
smile, Spears has often been compared to a Barbie doll. During a
set that lasted slightly more than an hour, she went through enough
costumes and scenarios for a Mattel showroom. She was a little girl
in a bedroom full of teddy bears, a fairy tale princess, a
sailor-suited USO entertainer, a hippie goddess, a Catholic-school
cutup and a homecoming queen.
</P>
<P>
   Her finale, of course, was ``Oops! ... I Did It Again,'' about
coyly leading on a would-be boyfriend. Phallic red inflatable
columns reared all around her like avenging lip glosses. As she
sang its last, taunting line _ ``I'm not that innocent'' _ she
descended into a fiery pit, not to be seen again. Equating adult
sexuality with hellfire, she doesn't mind as long as it heats up
her career.
</P>
<P>
   Teenypop shows always have a gaggle of opening acts with taped
backups, and Spears brought along three warm-ups. No Authority,
four young men in tough-guy black T-shirts, had unctuous love songs
and half-hearted choreography; BBMak, who didn't dance, applied
1970s folk-rock strumming and high harmonies to protestations of
love. Innosense, a five-woman group, put the moves of a
cheerleading squad behind catchy, straightforward come-ons. The
tour continues Thursday night at Jones Beach and at the PNC Bank
Arts Center in Holmdel, N.J., on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
