<HEADER>
A7610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ROCKER-COMICS-COX     06-28 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-COMICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets undecided on giving away villain-laden comic book
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are superheroes powerful enough to save this
city from destruction, and only one person can stop them.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   A Mets official said Wednesday the organization still had not
decided whether to go through with a comic-book giveaway to kids 14
and under at Saturday's Braves-Mets game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll rely on the advice of our security people,'' said Dave
Howard, Mets senior vice president for business and legal affairs.
``If they recommend we don't do it, we'll defer to their
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the New York Post wrote that the Mets had
``commissioned a comic book featuring an out-of-town villain who
hates New York and wants to blow up the No. 7 train.'' The Post
described the villain as a ``purple monster.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 7 is the subway line that runs to Shea. Rocker told
Sports Illustrated in December that one was likely to end up
sitting beside an unwed mother or ``some kid with purple hair'' on
the No. 7. To many New Yorkers, the fictitious villain bore a
striking resemblance to the real-life Rocker. Too striking for even
some diehard Mets fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just hyping it up by doing that,'' said Jim Canavan,
34, from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous, because they're just reminding people of the
whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Howard said the Mets had picked the Saturday giveaway in
November ``well before (Rocker) made any statements to Sports
Illustrated.'' Besides, he said, the plot is about a ``typical
villain'' who wants to take over all of New York City - including
the Statue of Liberty and the subway system - not just the No. 7
train.
</P>
<P>
   A climactic fight between a group of Mets players who become
superheroes and the villain's robot gang does take place on the No.
7.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's because that's the line that goes to Shea
Stadium,'' Howard said. ``We wouldn't want to focus on, say, the
No. 4, because that's the line that goes to Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the focus is on whether 15,000 copies of a kids' comic book
could pose a security risk.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Howard said, ``We've definitely got a collector's item.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
