<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SISTERS ROLLING THROUGH WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A rental car was timidly approaching a
roundabout that must have looked like a death spiral to Richard
Williams in one of his first attempts at English driving rules.
Their eyes the size of bottle caps, an uneasy Venus and Serena
Williams tried to coach their dad from the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were having a little trouble, but now we're able to get to
the village without any accidents,'' said Serena, discussing the
2-mile radius of their rented home near the Wimbledon village.
``We're making it a little farther each day.''
</P>
<P>
   So get out of their way. Roads, lawns, nowhere is safe. Together
again, the sisters are barreling through the All England Club, with
horns blowing and their confidence on high beams. Just as they did
when they romped through the U.S. Open last summer, they are
healthy of body and full of enough verbal spirit to irritate
Martina Hingis _ once again. And if John McEnroe would rather the
duo try a dose of humility _ as listeners said he suggested on
television this week _ that's not their style.
</P>
<P>
   With a glittering, feathery bow in her hair from the Liberace
collection, eighth-seeded Serena Williams dominated Court 18 at
high noon with such powerful strokes that she all but left dimples
in the strings of the helpless Yvette Basting. In 35 minutes,
Williams wiped away the 186th-ranked woman in a 6-1, 6-0 warm-up
drill. An hour later, fifth-ranked Venus Williams flaunted her
speed and wingspan on Court 1 to chase down every angled shot off
the racket of 20th-ranked Ai Sugiyama for a 6-1, 6-4, victory in 65
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple and swift start to a third day of Wimbledon that
quickly underwent a gloomy and grumpy transformation. As if on cue,
a bank of clouds closed in on the sun. Suddenly, spats started to
erupt on the courts and darkness began falling on Pete Sampras'
half of the draw.
</P>
<P>
   As the top-seeded Sampras labored in pain but finally put away
Karol Kucera before nightfall, 7-6 (9), 6-3, 3-6, 6-4, his path to
Roy Emerson's Grand Slam record became easier.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, third-seeded Magnus Norman, sixth-seeded
Cedric Pioline and 11th-seeded Richard Krajicek had been upset. The
only seed left in Sampras' half of the draw is No. 9 Thomas
Enqvist.
</P>
<P>
   But can Sampras' body hold out? Wednesday, Sampras appeared even
more distressed than usual. In the fourth set, he played through a
suddenly inflamed foot, managing to hold his concentration with a
false alarm ringing in the background, all while Kucera was popping
a stream of unrelenting returns.
</P>
<P>
   For Sampras, every point was a chore. Even as he served for the
match at 5-4 in the fourth set, he squandered three match points
and double faulted twice before winning on a whistling second serve
down the middle that glanced off Kucera's racket.
</P>
<P>
   Wincing as he exited, Sampras left the grounds without talking
and went to a local hospital to have a magnetic resonance imaging
test on his left foot. Until a further evaluation on Thursday, it's
unclear whether he'll be ready for his third-round match on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While the men's draw is on the verge of disarray, the women's
draw is more intact. Hingis joined the Williams sisters by
advancing to the third round Wednesday with a 6-4, 6-1 victory
against Jing-Qian Yi. Although Anna Kournikova was not considered a
viable threat, a Clearasil-packing crowd of boys mourned the
instant she was aced by Anne-Gaelle Sidot on match point.
</P>
<P>
   At least the broken hearted were civil in their disappointment.
Elsewhere, tempers were heating up. After a five-set loss, the
prickly Jeff Tarango refused to shake the hand of fellow American
Paul Goldstein, and he later accused his opponent of faking an
injury. During his upset of Krajicek, Wayne Ferreira smashed his
racket in half over a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised by the weakness of my racket,'' Ferreira said.
``I was frustrated, I wasn't angry.''
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between real emotion and gamesmanship was
blurred Wednesday. It was particularly hard to separate sarcasm
from ego when the Williams sisters coyly answered their critics.
With their power and sculpted forms, some have wondered when
strategy will creep into their game plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have great bodies, yeah,'' Serena said with a
sly smile. ``Nice, slim, sexy bodies. They're right.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to go out the way Venus and I have and win a lot of
tournaments _ and have a Grand Slam between us _ I think we have
definitely grown in our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams also had her own clever way of addressing any
concerns about the sisters' humility. ``I believe that Serena and I
are very polite, because that's the way our parents taught us to
be,'' Venus said. ``But I believe that when Serena and I lose a
match it's because we beat ourselves, not because the other player
beats us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It's this kind of confidence that rivals that of Hingis, the
head honcho of self-esteem. Like Hingis, the Williams sisters have
no trouble being blunt about the force of their games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was popping it today,'' said Serena, who served up eight
aces. ``It was amazing. Sometimes, I had to pinch myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in their first Grand Slam together since the U.S. Open
because of injuries, the Williams sisters have a way of splashing
color on a gray day. Until Wednesday, Hingis has had little to say
about them. But in a news conference, she was told about Serena's
views concerning the dating scene around the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's a lot of action going on around the tour,''
Serena had said, taking note of the relationships between Jennifer
Carpiati and Xavier Malisse, Andre Agassi and Steffi Graf, plus
Hingis and Norman. ``Every day I see things, my eyes light up,
`Whoa, I didn't know.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm really focusing on my career. Basically, I'm
really trying to keep that No. 1 in life. It's really hard if you
get involved in a relationship. Next thing you know, your game goes
down, all kinds of things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis bristled at the idea that a boyfriend on the tour could
be an albatross to anyone's career. ``I don't know if she has had
any experiences, so how can she talk about that?'' Hingis said. ``I
don't think my game went down so far, so I'm doing pretty good. I'm
happy with my relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth is on. But it can only last for so long.
Venus, Serena and Hingis are on the same side of the draw. In the
finals, Hingis won't meet one of the Williams sisters and Venus and
Serena won't meet each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish my girls weren't in the same half of the draw,'' said
Richard Williams. ``I think one can make it, though. People forget
that this whole world is built on confidence. That's why Serena
says she should dominate this tournament. Venus and Serena, they're
race horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's best to get out of their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
