<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCULATIONS FOR A FLAGSTONE PATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stone is one of the oldest building materials. It is denser and
heavier than most others, and for this reason it is generally used
for smaller and simpler do-it-yourself projects.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is characterized by its shape. Ashlar is cut stone.
Flagstones are flat stones used for surfacing walls and paths.
Cobblestones are rounded stones, and fieldstones are stones found
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Laying down a flagstone path does not require any special skills
and only a few basic tools are needed, but it is still hard work.
You will have to move a lot of soil, carry buckets of sand and lift
heavy stones.
</P>
<P>
   Start by laying out the general outline of the path on the
ground with stakes and cord. Since flagstones are irregular in
shape, the path does not have to be perfectly straight or even a
consistent width.
</P>
<P>
   When you have the perimeters of the path staked out, you can
calculate its area and estimate the amount of material you will
need.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, you can lay flagstones directly on the ground
(after removing a few inches of topsoil so the stones are level
with the surrounding areas), provided the soil has good drainage.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be easier to level the stones and create better
drainage if you construct a sand bed first.
</P>
<P>
   To calculate the amount of sand needed, multiply the area of the
path (in inches) by 2 inches (the depth of the sand bed). This will
give the volume of sand (in cubic inches) that you will need.
</P>
<P>
   Calculating the amount of stone is more difficult because the
stones vary in size and shape.
</P>
<P>
   Flagstones are generally grouped according to thickness. Thicker
flagstones cost more than thinner ones, so you will get more
coverage for the money with thinner stones. But stones less than 1
inch thick break readily and are easily kicked out of place. So it
is best to buy stones at least 1 1/2 inches thick.
</P>
<P>
   You can find building sand, and flagstones at some larger home
centers and lumberyards, or look in the Yellow Pages under
``Landscape Equipment and Supplies'' and ``Stone, Natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Discuss your plans with the dealer to find out the amount of
stone needed. He can tell you roughly how many square feet of
coverage you will get from a particular type of stone and the cost
involved.
</P>
<P>
   After you have ordered your materials, excavate the path area
deep enough to accommodate the average thickness of the stones and
2 inches of sand. Check to make sure the depth is uniform by laying
a 2-by-4 across the path and measuring from the bottom edge of the
board to the scooped-out ground with a ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Next, lay landscape fabric on the ground. Landscape fabric is
made of plastic, not cloth.
</P>
<P>
   The fabric comes in a roll and is spread to create a barrier
between the ground and sand bed that will keep weeds from growing
up between the stones. If the fabric is too wide, you can trim it
with scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Use a bucket or shovel to dump sand on top of the fabric. Smooth
the sand into an even layer about 2 inches deep, then tamp it down.
</P>
<P>
   You can make a tamper by nailing a piece of scrap board (about
6-by-6 inches) to the end of a 4-by-4. Hold the 4-by-4 upright and
bring it down so the board on the end flattens the sand into a
compact layer.
</P>
<P>
   This technique works well for small areas, but for a large path
you may want to rent a power tamper from a tool store.
</P>
<P>
   When the sand bed is compacted, you can start laying the stones.
If you want your path to have neat borders, pick out stones with
straight edges and lay them along the edges then fill in the area
in between.
</P>
<P>
   Place each stone on the sand, then wiggle it back and forth to
seat it.
</P>
<P>
   Positioning the stones in a pleasing overall pattern will
require considerable trial and error because each stone has a
different shape.
</P>
<P>
   In narrow places you may have to cut large stones to fit, but it
is difficult to make precise cuts because flagstone is irregular in
composition and thickness.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to make a cut is by scoring a line on the stone
with a cold chisel. Place a metal pipe under the score line, then
strike the waste end of the stone with a heavy hammer. Be sure to
wear heavy-duty gloves and goggles while doing this.
</P>
<P>
   Once all the stones are in place, shovel sand over the entire
walk and sweep it into the cracks with a broom. Spray the walk with
a fine mist from a garden hose to dampen and compact the sand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
