<SLUG> BC-DOW0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fed leaves rates unchanged, but warns of inflation threat
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA, _ The Federal Reserve left short-term interest rates
unchanged on Wednesday, but its warning that inflation is still a
risk is expected to roil investment markets for ``the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy-making Open Market Committee ended a scheduled,
two-day session without changing the 6.5 percent target rate for
its federal funds, the rate banks charge each other for overnight
reserve loans.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed's post-meeting statement explaining its actions was
a good news/bad news document for Wall Street and for borrowers
generally, who have been suffering from rate increases already in
place.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that economic demand ``may be moderating,''
thanks mainly to productivity gains that have kept costs under
control despite slight increases in consumer prices during the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed also said that evidence of slower growth is still
``tentative and preliminary,'' and that tight labor markets are
still a problem.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Fed said there is still a risk that economic
conditions ``may generate heightened inflation pressures in the
foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst David Kim said the stock market's
attention now shifts to what the Fed will do at its Aug. 22
meeting, and that _ like the June session _ will depend on the
economic news between now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. financial markets are likely to lurch from one economic
release to another (indefinitely),'' said Kim. ``Next week's
release of the June purchasing managers' and payroll reports will
be the first notable reports.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market posted only subdued approval of the Fed's
action, which most analysts had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Except for small stocks, the market's initial buying spree was
followed by late selling that almost wiped out the gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average advanced only 0.2 percent for
the day and the broader S&AMP;P 500 index 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Nasdaq composite, which gained just over 2 percent on
buying of technology stocks, suffered a late sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Russell 2000 index of smaller stocks advanced all day
to close with a gain of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, analysts were also cautious in interpreting
the Fed's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the Fed left interest rates unchanged at their
June meeting should not be interpreted that they have finished
hiking rates this year,'' said First Union economist Mark Vitner.
``The Fed has clearly not fully bought into the slowdown
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   July, however, is likely to be a respite for the stock market,
as investor attention shifts toward second-quarter corporate
earnings reports _ which are expected to be strong.
</P>
<P>
   Charles L. Hill, research director of First Call/Thomson
Financial, said ``all the earnings indicators'' for the quarter are
more positive than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second-quarter final earnings results are likely to show a
year-over-year increase of 22 percent to 23 percent for the S&AMP;P
500,'' said Hill. ``That would be close to the six-year record of
23.6 percent in the first quarter of the current year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the earnings pre-announcements that companies make
prior to official reports, usually to warn of bad news, have been
``somewhat less negative than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
