<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LITTLE-ROCK-CULTURE-N     06-28 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-ROCK-CULTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS IN AMERICA: THE STAR OF LITTLE ROCK: AN ARTS FOUNDLING GROWS
UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE BARNES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Visitors to this small Southern city
(metropolitan population: 570,000) are often struck by the gap
between its reputation as an intellectual backwater and the reality
of its cultural offerings: A nationally recognized symphony, a
civic ballet, a comprehensive university fine arts department, two
repertory theater companies and a small but state-of-the-art
performance center.
</P>
<P>
   City officials seeking to recruit corporate and industrial
businesses always include a tour of the newly expanded Arkansas
Arts Center, which is now, more than ever, at the heart of Little
Rock's cultural life. A two-year campaign that ended in February
raised $22 million, which was used mostly to increase the center's
gallery and classroom space from 65,000 square feet to 100,000. On
a recent visit, President Clinton pronounced himself
``overwhelmed'' as he was led through the center's new two-story
atrium of blond wood and slate into a gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The center's permanent collection includes a Diego Rivera
painting, ``Two Women''; a Degas pastel, ``Dancing Trios Before
Class''; a Rodin bust of a young Balzac; and a Picasso oil, ``Still
Life With Red Bull's Head,'' among other works. There are works on
paper by Delacroix, Vuillard, Bonnard, van Gogh, Rubens and
Rembrandt, and sculpture by Louise Nevelson and Henry Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent collection is valued at $40 million, according to
Townsend Wolfe, the Arts Center's director and chief curator. Janie
Lee, a curator at large for the Whitney Museum of American Art in
New York, described the center's holdings as ``incredibly
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arts Center's first serious benefactor was Winthrop
Rockefeller, who served as Arkansas' governor. When he moved to the
state in the 1950s Rockefeller found Arkansas' cultural menu rather
skimpy. So he set about replacing the down-at-the-heels Museum of
Fine Arts, which by that point the townspeople essentially ignored.
He led a fund-raising campaign in Arkansas for a new arts center to
be constructed around the old, seeded the project with his own
money and coaxed more from his brothers Nelson, David, Laurance and
John.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win was the key man,'' recalled Jeane Hamilton, 74, doyenne of
the Little Rock arts community. ``The museum was a dead beast, and
the arts were something the people of Little Rock had not given a
lot of thought to. Without Win, we would have never got the center
off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Arkansas Arts Center opened in 1963, Rockefeller and
his wife, Jeanette, struggled to keep it afloat financially. The
center was started as a degree-granting institution with ambitious
programs in theater, sculpture and painting. Almost immediately, it
had staggering deficits, which Rockefeller absorbed for a while. In
its first four years it had five directors.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, a native of South Carolina, was recruited for the job of
director by and Rockefeller in 1968 from a teaching position at the
Wooster School in Danbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Win that I would take the job on condition that I run
the place with no meddling by others,'' Wolfe remembered. ``I said,
`If I'm going to be fired it's because I didn't do the job, not
because I let somebody else try.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, who was then 32, set about imposing order on the artistic
and administrative chaos he discovered in Arkansas. ``I tried to
figure out how they ran up those deficits,'' he said, ``and I never
could.'' He eliminated the degree programs, restricted performing
arts to a children's theater and, crucially, narrowed the center's
acquisitions focus to French, Italian and American drawings
``because it was something at which we could excel.''
</P>
<P>
   The passion of that era for paintings, Wolfe said, made the
acquisition of drawings easier and less expensive. ``Few
institutions and fewer people were collecting drawings back then,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he snatched up a Richard Diebenkorn watercolor for
$3,500 in 1973; today, Wolfe suggested, it might fetch $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people want paintings for their historical value,'' said
Lee, the Whitney curator, ``and drawings are of secondary
importance to them. Townsend had the courage to see beyond that, to
recognize that drawings aren't secondary. And the level of quality
he's maintained in Arkansas makes that collection very
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Werner Kramarsky of New York, a prominent collectors of works on
paper, described the Arkansas museum's holdings ``as one of the
most important contemporary drawings collections in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an almost immeasurable treasure, a superb example of
careful, connoisseur-based collecting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, the center took a gamble to broaden its financial base
by rejecting a bequest of $1 million from the executors for
Rockefeller, who died that year. ``People would have thought Win
was taking care of us from the grave,'' Wolfe explained.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Wolfe suggested that the trustees challenge the center
to raise $500,000 from local private sources with a 3-to-1 matching
provision from the Rockefeller estate. When Arkansans responded by
contributing $750,000 in two months, the Rockefeller family matched
the extra $250,000 as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Arkansas had to have title to it, had to feel
that it was truly theirs before the arts center could flourish,''
Wolfe said.
</P>
<P>
   The center continues to benefit from Rockefeller support
nonetheless. Lt.. Gov. Winthrop Paul Rockefeller, son of Winthrop,
is a contributor, and Abby Rockefeller Mauze, sister to the five
brothers, donated the Rivera. David Rockefeller donated a 1912 oil
by Redon, ``Andromeda.'' Laurance Rockefeller contributed 22
drawings and prints this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the center's latest, and largest, benefactors have been
homegrown. Jackson Stephens, a Little Rock investment banker,
contributed $5 million to the expansion campaign, then donated the
Picasso, the Degas and 13 other works from his private collection.
They include oils by Degas, Bonnard, Monet, Vuillard and Pissaro.
</P>
<P>
   Recently James Dyke, a local businessman, deeded to the center
his collection of 133 watercolors and sketches by Paul Signac. This
collection will tour Europe and stop at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art in New York before returning to Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   In Wolfe's 32 years as director the arts center's endowment has
grown from $34,000 to almost $23 million, and its holdings have
expanded from fewer than 800 works to more than 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people _ measured in contributions,
gallery visits, outreach programs and enrollment in arts classes _
are involved in the center, and its annual fund-raising dinner and
auction is the highlight of Arkansas' spring social season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started going to New York to buy things, the
reaction was, `Who is this sucker?''' Wolfe said.``I don't get that
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
