<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WestPoint Stevens to restructure
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WestPoint Stevens said it will take a $195 million
pre-tax charge in the second quarter to restructure operations this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The West Point maker of sheets and towels said Wednesday it will
consolidate manufacturing plants and get rid of some support and
administrative jobs as it tries to pay off debt.
</P>
<P>
   In its first public comments since a derailed plan to go
private, the company did not disclose which of its 29 plants would
be affected.
</P>
<P>
   The 186-year-old company said it will also import more goods in
every product category than it manufactures at its own mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, we're looking at doing more with less corporate
overhead,'' said Lorraine Miller, senior vice president of investor
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring will result in savings of $5 million this year
and $15 million next year, a WestPoint Stevens press release said.
After that, the company expects to save $29 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing debt is a priority for WestPoint Stevens. On Wednesday,
Moody's Investors Service downgraded the company's senior long-term
debt and said the outlook is negative.
</P>
<P>
   The lowered rating reflects a ``weak balance sheet,'' Moody's
said. Debt levels are approaching revenues of the West Point-based
maker of sheets and towels, Moody's noted, and the home furnishing
market is showing signs of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   Miller of WestPoint Stevens said the reorganization could lead
to sales growth of about 10 percent a year, up from last year's 6
percent growth. She projected long-term earnings growth of 20
percent and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get that kind of top-line growth, either they're going to
be selling higher-priced products. . . or they're going to make
some acquisitions,'' said analyst Kay Norwood of Wachovia
Securities. ``Acquisitions are likely because there are a lot of
companies out there that just aren't (big enough) to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens didn't offer many details on its new strategy
Wednesday. Norwood said she was looking forward to more particulars
when the company outlines the plan today at its annual shareholder
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market won't take to a huge restructuring charge like this
without the details on what they're doing,'' Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens stock has lost half its value this year. The
stock closed at $10.75 Wednesday, up 56 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In late March, Chairman and Chief Executive Holcombe Green Jr.
led a buyout team for the company shares they didn't already own.
But the buyout plan collapsed when rising interest rates prompted
an investor to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
