<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A CAMERA THAT PACKS ITS OWN CD-R DRIVE
</P>
<P>
   If anyone needs further proof that compact disc technology is
becoming as common as magnetic tape found in audio and video
cassettes, look to Sony's newest Mavica digital still camera.
</P>
<P>
   Its high-resolution pictures _ 2.1 megapixels _ are not stored
on conventional flash memory cards, nor on 3.5-inch floppy disks
like previous models, nor even on Sony's own MemorySticks. Instead,
the Mavica MVC-CD1000 carries a CD recorder that stores up to 160
snapshots on a recordable 3.5-inch CD.
</P>
<P>
   Sony executives said the $1,300 camera, expected to be available
in the United States in August, was the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are believed to use as many as 260 million CD or CD-R
drives on their personal computers, Sony estimates. By placing
pictures directly on small high-capacity CD-Rs, consumers can place
the discs _ about a third of the size of full-size CDs _ in
conventional CD-ROM and CD-R drives and view their pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-Rs can store up to 156 megabytes of digital information,
compared with a floppy disk that stores up to 1.44 MB and
MemorySticks that have a current capacity of 64 MB. Perhaps the
biggest benefit, Sony spokesmen said, is that the special CD-Rs are
relatively inexpensive, costing about $4 per disc.
</P>
<P>
   Storing pictures in the camera on a CD-R shortens recording time
in the Mavica, making it possible to shoot more images more rapidly
than models using other storage mediums, according to Sony
specifications on the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Like earlier Mavicas, the MVC-CD1000 includes optical zoom and a
digital image stabilization that eliminates unwanted shakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   MP3 PLAYER CLICKS WITH TECHNOLOGY FROM IOMEGA
</P>
<P>
   Iomega Corp., a maker of portable storage devices and media for
computers, announced this week that it was collaborating with
consumer electronics companies to produce a new kind of audio
player that uses its relatively low-cost, mechanical Clik drive.
</P>
<P>
   The the RaveMP 2300 digital media player, which is expected to
be in stores next month, may represent a breakthrough in permitting
users to cheaply store downloadable music and other audio files for
palm-size devices.
</P>
<P>
   Most devices, commonly referred to as MP3 players, use flash
memory cards that cost about $100 and store little more than 30
minutes of CD-quality music. The Clik disc, which holds 40 MB or
about 40 minutes of near CD-quality music, costs about $10 each.
There are other devices that are capable of storing hours of music,
but they have turned to much larger and heavier hard drives
commonly used in laptop computers to accomplish this.
</P>
<P>
   The RaveMP 2300 player, made by Sensory Science, has a slot on
top of its sleek body. A Clik disc, which is about 2 inches square,
fits into that slot.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Rathbun, director of Clik Original Equipment Manufacture
and channel product management for Iomega, said the Clik drives
(the only moving parts in the otherwise solid-state player) spin
only for a short time to transfer audio files to a memory chip
inside the device; the chip is then drawn upon to play audio
signals.
</P>
<P>
   The Clik drive does not make the player more susceptible to
skips when it is played on the go, Rathbun said. ``You can shake
and bake it as much as you want,'' he said of the Rave's stability.
</P>
<P>
   The RaveMP 2300 uses rechargeable lithium-ion batteries and has
an estimated 10 hours of continuous playback on a single charge.
The estimated price will be $299.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   FROM RAILS TO TRAILS, WITH MILES AND MILES TO EXPLORE
</P>
<P>
   More than 11,000 miles of abandoned railroad corridors have been
converted into public trails and greenways for activities like
walking, bicycling, horseback riding and cross-country skiing.
</P>
<P>
   The trails, which pass through urban, suburban and rural areas
for from two-tenths of a mile to more than 200 miles, can be found
on an online directory started by the Rails to Trails Conservancy
(www.traillink.com).
</P>
<P>
   There are also links, like one for the Virginia Creeper Trail,
which runs along the former right-of-way of the Virginia-Carolina
Railroad from Abingdon, Va., to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHELLY FREIERMAN
</P>
<P>
   AN E-BOOK READER PRICED FOR THE MASSES
</P>
<P>
   The e-book market got another boost this week as Franklin
Electronic Publishers unveiled the first hand-held reader to be
sold for less than $150. The slim, lightweight device, called the
eBookMan, will be sold in at least three versions this fall, with
prices starting at $129.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for people to spend $500 on a machine to read a $20
novel,'' said Barry Lipsky, Franklin's president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The machine will also function as an MP3 player, a listening
device for digital audio books, an address book, schedule keeper
and a repository for voice memos. It includes a stylus and is
designed to recognize handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive version, Lipsky said, will probably be
issued in a translucent blue. It will feature 8 MB of RAM, enough
room for about 20 novels. The $179.95 model has the same features
with a clearer screen, a back-light and a forest green shell. The
silver-colored model, for $229.95, includes all those options plus
16 megabytes of RAM. Each model includes a slot for a multimedia
card for extra memory.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin has years of experience in developing hand-held
electronic dictionaries and translators that sell for as little as
$15. Instead of having to dumb down a high-priced computer, Lipsky
said, Franklin was able to capitalize on its experience in the
low-end market.
</P>
<P>
   Prototypes of the eBookMan, shown at PC Expo in New York this
week, look like Palm organizers at first glance. They also come
with a cradle that plugs into a computer through a USB port. But
the screen is several inches longer and an inch wider than most
hand-held organizers.
</P>
<P>
   It is that extra size, said Peter Yianilos, the company's chief
technology officer, that makes reading Huck Finn an easier
experience than squinting to read it on other hand-held organizers.
For years, books, magazines and newspapers have been printing
columns of eBookman size. ``People are used to dealing with text of
that width,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
