<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International soccer notebook: France's `golden goal'
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``golden goal'' was priceless for France, which got a
penalty kick from Zinedine Zidane with three minutes to play in
overtime Wednesday to reach the finals of the European
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   And Portugal's artful, spectactular run to the semis culminated
in ugly fashion in Brussels as Austrian referee Gunther Benko
called a handball in the box against defender Abel Xavier.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Xavier, guarding the near post, did little
to move his left arm out of the way of a short shot by France's
Sylvain Wiltord on the touchline.
</P>
<P>
   Both before and after Zidane made the conversion for a 2-1
victory, angry Portuguese players charged Benko en masse, resulting
in a red card for striker Nuno Gomes. He had put Portugal ahead 1-0
in the 19th minute on a 20-footer that surprised French keeper
Fabien Barthez.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes into the second half, Thierry Henry drew France even
on a feed from Nicolas Anelka, and the match continued with the
same dogged, defensive shape it had taken from the outset. Neither
Zidane nor Luis Figo of Portugal, perhaps the two best players in
the tournament, got the kind of creative space to which they are
accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   The French can become the first team to win back-to-back World
Cup and European titles when they face either Holland or Italy
Sunday in Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's best international finish since losing in the Euro
'84 semis _ ironically to France by a 2-1 score in the last minute
of play _ also was the end of the line for coach Humberto Coelho,
who announced his resignation to reporters after the match.
</P>
<P>
   _Holland vs. Italy
</P>
<P>
   In today's other semifinal in Amsterdam, host Holland is favored
over defense-minded Italy. But the Dutch will be without left
fullback Arthur Numan, who has an injured foot, and goalkeeper
Edwin van der Sar isn't 100 percent, either. The Italians are
playing better than their pre-Euro form suggested. They have
conceded only two goals, although they haven't seen a team with the
offensive firepower of the Dutch. Patrick Kluivert, officially
credited with three goals in a 6-1 quarterfinal rout of Yugoslavia,
and Dennis Bergkamp are lethal on the attack, with Edgar Davids,
Marc Overmars, Philip Cocu and Boudewijn Zenden forming an
exceptional midfield behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Italy has some injury concerns as well, although defenders Paolo
Maldini and Fabio Cannavaro are expected to play. The unheralded
offensive trio of Stefano Fiore, Francesco Totti and Filippo
Inzaghi has performed admirably to get this far. Don't be surprised
if their best is enough to pull off an upset.
</P>
<P>
   _Germany: Daum job denied
</P>
<P>
   The Deutsche Fussball Bund, the German federation, is denying
media reports that Bayer Leverkusen manager Christophe Daum has
agreed to take over the national team. The Mitteldeutsche Zeitung
reported over the weekend that Daum would coach both teams until
after the 2000-01 Bundesliga season and then assume German team
duties full-time. Daum is one of the leading candidates, along with
Bayern Munich's Ottmar Hitzfeld, to succeed Erich Ribbeck, who
stepped down after Germany was ousted in group play in Euro 2000 in
its worst tournament showing in 16 years. Bayer management is
accusing the DFB of heavy-handed tactics in trying to lure Daum....
Sweeper Lothar Matthaus is claiming, after the fact, that teammates
Jens Jeremies, Markus Babbel and Dietmar Hamann were plotting a
coup to replace Ribbeck with Matthaus before Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _Boca wins Libertadores
</P>
<P>
   Defending South American club champions Palmeiras of Brazil were
dethroned 4-2 on penalty kicks last week in the finals of the Copa
Libertadores. Boca Juniors of Argentina won the title for the third
time. The teams played to a 2-2 aggreggate. Then, Boca goalkeeper
Cordoba stopped spot kicks by Faustino Asprilla and Roque Junior. .
. . Sao Paulo won its 18th Paulista state championship last week,
while Flamengo upset Vasco da Gama to take the Carioca title for
Rio de Janeiro state. . . . Argentina is at Colombia tonight in the
featured match as a full round of South American World Cup
qualifying continues. Paraguay travels to Chile and Peru is at
Ecuador. Brazil met Uruguay and Venezuela faced Bolivia late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _Transfer talk: Alfonso might stay put
</P>
<P>
   After starring for Spain in Euro 2000, striker Alfonso Perez
faces the prospect of playing second-division club soccer. That's
because Real Betis, relegated from La Liga, has no plans to ship
him off. And any suitors would have to pay $45 million, the cost of
the buy-out clause in his contract. . . . French striker David
Trezeguet is moving from first division champions AS Monaco to
Juventus. . . . Scottish Premier League player of the year Mark
Viduka, who scored 27 goals for Celtic, is set to transfer to
Leeds, where he will be reunited with fellow Australian Harry
Kewell. . . . After a season at Inter Milan, former Italian
goalkeeper Angelo Peruzzi is headed to Serie A champions Lazio,
which paid $28 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
