<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-ART-NYT &LR;      06-28 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRESS CONFERENCE, CLINTON TRIES TO BOOST GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER and MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton turned an hourlong news
conference Wednesday into an effort to bolster Vice President Al
Gore's campaign and to defend him from accusations of campaign
finance irregularities, saying Gore made ``a compelling case'' that
he did nothing wrong and arguing that the ``so-called scandals'' of
the past eight years ``were bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging discussion that ran the gamut from gasoline
prices to the death penalty to missile defense to Elian Gonzalez to
prescription drug coverage to how much brain power it takes to be
president, Clinton invoked Gore's name more than a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed polls showing Gore running behind Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas _ noting that this week alone one poll showed a
13-point lead for the presumed Republican candidate while another
indicated a virtual tie. The president said that once Americans
examine Gore's record, his economic policy and his understanding of
new technology, ``it's still more likely than not that he will
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not see a need for Attorney General Janet
Reno to appoint a special counsel to investigate Gore's involvement
in campaign fund raising, including his appearance at a Buddhist
temple in California in April 1996. He said she had already
considered, and rejected, an outside review and that ``the best
thing to do is for the American people to make their own judgments
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he seized the moment _ as he does increasingly often these
days _ to argue that his White House has been repeatedly vindicated
of wrongdoing despite a Washington ``scandal machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `scandal' has been thrown around here like a clanging
teapot for seven years,'' he said. And he quickly cited a
Washington Post column that he said concluded ``a whole bunch of
this stuff was just garbage, and that we had totally innocent
people prosecuted because they wouldn't lie.'' He cited numerous
investigations of his Cabinet members, and of his own financial
dealings in Arkansas, but never mentioned his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The president also plugged Gore when asked about the brain power
needed to be a good president and gently tweaked Bush, who has said
he plans to surround himself with the best advisers to compensate
for areas in which he is not an expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's so much a question of intelligence
generically,'' Clinton said in describing the qualities it takes to
be president. ``I mean, I think it's more a question of curiosity
and willingness to learn what you think is important,'' a clear
reference to suggestions that Bush often skims the surface rather
than delving deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I think that no president can say, well, it should be
enough for the voters if I get the best advisers in my party and
they come up with a position and I take it,'' he added. ``So what
the voters will have to analyze here is how important is the fact
that Al Gore spent 20 years working on arms control issues, for
example, and dealing with all these things?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent most of his time pressing the legislative agenda
for his last seven months in office. He urged Congress to take the
deal he offered this week: prescription drug coverage for senior
citizens, a longtime item on Clinton's list, in return for the
elimination of the ``marriage penalty'' in the tax system, a
longtime Republican desire.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the Senate to approve permanent normal trade relations
with China, as the House has already. ``I ask Congress, let's not
waste these precious weeks,'' he said. But his advisers acknowledge
that Clinton would be lucky to get one or two of his priorities
through an election-year Congress, and say he will focus instead on
negotiating an Israeli-Palestinian peace by September, and other
foreign policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about capital punishment, Clinton expressed concern about
racial disparities among those facing execution for federal crimes.
Seventeen of the 21 federal prisoners facing the death penalty are
members of minority groups. Clinton also said he was concerned that
prosecutors in a dozen Southern states have accounted for more than
half of the federal cases in which the death penalty has been
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments gave some hope to lawyers for Juan Raul
Garza, a migrant farm worker convicted of marijuana smuggling and
three drug-related murders who is scheduled next month to become
the first person facing a federal execution in nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged by the president's comments,'' said Gregory
Wiercioch, a lawyer with the Texas Defender Service who is
representing Garza and preparing to file a request for clemency.
``What President Clinton is realizing is that the Justice
Department's authorization is like a rigged lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's news conference came shortly after the Supreme Court
handed down a series of high-profile rulings, and Clinton fielded
questions on many of them, from the court's refusal to hear a case
dealing with Elian Gonzalez _ who left Washington for Cuba only
hours after Clinton spoke _ to its decision backing the Boy Scouts'
ability to exclude gay members.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wished the return of Elian to Cuba had ``unfolded in
a less dramatic, less traumatic way for all concerned.'' He made a
last-minute offer to the departing family: ``If he and his father
decided they wanted to stay here, it would be fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton signaled no major departure from the U.S. embargo on
Cuba, saying it would be up to Cuban President Fidel Castro to
reach out to the United States. He deflected comparisons to his
recent decision to lift the embargo of commercial exchanges against
North Korea _ despite the fact that the North Korean regime had
engaged in atrocities closely paralleling those he accused Castro
of committing.
</P>
<P>
   While he said he supported the notion of selling U.S. food and
medicine to Havana, the substance of a deal struck this week among
House congressional leaders, the president said he was concerned
about restrictions in the legislation on travel to the island.
</P>
<P>
   On the court's decision to permit the Boy Scouts to bar gays,
Clinton called the scouts, of which he is honorary president, ``a
great group.'' But he said he hopes the decision is ``just one step
along the way of a movement toward greater inclusion in our society
because I think that's the direction we ought to be going in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
