</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS DEVOTE HOURS TO CUBAN BOY'S DEPARTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CUBAN-BOY) 
 By BILL CARTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The departure of Elian Gonzalez for Cuba on Wednesday afternoon
received extensive live coverage from every television news
organization, with the all-news cable channels devoting most of
five straight hours to the story.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of the private jet taking Elian back to Havana was
covered by ABC News, CBS News and NBC News as well, all of which
interrupted regular programming for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The news coverage began shortly after noon, when the Supreme
Court announced that it had declined to intervene in the case. The
coverage included reports from Havana, Washington and Miami, where
Cuban-Americans were still protesting the decision that allowed
Juan Miguel Gonzalez to take his son back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   On the three all-news cable channels, CNN, MSNBC and Fox News,
the afternoon included a long period of live helicopter coverage of
the Gonzalez family in a white van heading for Dulles International
Airport near Washington. The coverage was visually similar to the
infamous white Bronco chase at the start of the almost
around-the-clock coverage of the O.J. Simpson murder case in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As one CNN executive put it, ``I don't want to call it a Bronco
but it certainly looked like a Bronco.'' Steve Capus, the executive
producer of special coverage for MSNBC, said, ``It was certainly
reminiscent of live events the country has watched in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Eason Jordan, the president of news-gathering for CNN, said,
``People expect us to be on top of every breaking story. This is a
story that involved President Clinton, Vice President Gore,
Attorney General Reno, Congress and the Supreme Court and has had
impact on Cuban-American relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Capus said MSNBC had devoted time to President Clinton's news
conference, as well as the Supreme Court's decisions on partial
birth abortion and gays in the Boy Scouts. But much of the day was
devoted to coverage of the Gonzalez departure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cable news business, a day like this is what we live
for,'' Capus said.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said CNN, the only news channel with a permanent bureau
in Havana, would continue to cover whatever developments took place
in Cuba. ``Elian Gonzalez is probably the most famous child on the
face of the earth,'' Jordan said. ``Beyond the policy issues it is
also obviously a great human interest story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
