<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0629-1STLD     06-28 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0629-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: small change in lede; new 4th, 5th grafs to update
with Elian's arrival in Havana . . .
 &HT;    ELIAN, FAMILY RETURN TO CUBA FOLLOWING MONTHS-LONG AMERICAN
ODYSSEY
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Nearly seven months to the day after he was plucked from
the sea, 6-year-old rafter Elian Gonzalez jetted home to Cuba with
his family Wednesday, ending a remarkable saga that tugged at
heartstrings and stirred intense political debate the world over.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear a legal
appeal by his Miami relatives who wanted to keep him in the United
States, Elian and his immediate family climbed aboard a small
chartered jet at Dulles International Airport outside Washington,
D.C. for their flight to Havana. The plane took off at about 4:42
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to be going home,'' Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, told reporters in broken English shortly before boarding
the jet with his second wife, infant son and Elian. ``I'd like to
thank the North American government for finally giving me my son
back after all my family's suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The jet arrived at Jose Marti International Airport in Havana at
7:45 p.m. ET. Stepping onto the tarmac, Elian was smothered with
hugs and kisses from grandparents and other family members as more
than 100 schoolchildren wearing uniforms cheered and waved Cuban
flags.
</P>
<P>
   Within 10 minutes, the family boarded a small white car and
drove away, with Elian waving out the opened window.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government _ which discouraged many U.S. journalists
from traveling to Havana to cover the homecoming _ insisted there
would be no large public celebrations, urging the Cuban people to
remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that the family would stay for several weeks
at a secluded diplomatic compound in the Havana suburb of Miramar.
Later in the summer, they will take a vacation and then return
their home in Cardenas, about a two hours from Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives made no public appearances Wednesday,
and angrily confronted a Miami television reporter who filmed them
outside a Coconut Grove Church shortly after the Supreme Court
decision was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are devastated that at this very moment, Elian is going
back to a country where he'll never be free,'' family spokesman
Armando Gutierrez said. ``This is a very rough time for us, but we
must obey the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian leaves behind a tangled legacy of warring lawyers, feuding
family members and hard feelings among Cuban exiles here, who
adopted his case as a symbol of their bitter hatred for Castro's
communist dictatorship. As Elian boarded the jet in Washington, a
few dozen somber Cuban exiles gathered outside the Little Havana
home where the boy lived for five months with his Miami relatives.
Many had tears streaming down their faces, while others held up
their hands in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came for the boy at gunpoint, that's the scary part,''
said Ruth Dupree, 27, a second-generation Cuban-American. ``This
family that did so much for him never got to say good-bye. It's
shaken my faith in America.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press briefing in Washington, President Clinton said he
regretted that the case became so politically charged, although he
said it would have been fine if Elian and his father had decided to
stay in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno _ who became a lightning rod of
criticism for her handling of the case _ applauded the Supreme
Court's decision not to hear the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All involved have had an opportunity to make their case _ all
the way to the highest court in the land,'' Reno said. ``I hope
that everyone will accept the Supreme Court's decision and join me
in wishing this family, and this special little boy, well.''
</P>
<P>
   With his impish grin and photogenic face, Elian captured the
hearts of millions, especially after they heard the harrowing story
of how his mother and 10 others drowned while trying to escape from
Cuba. Elian was found alone, floating in an inner-tube a few miles
offshore the Florida coast on Thanksgiving Day last year.
</P>
<P>
   With the initial blessing of his father and the U.S. government,
Elian was taken in by his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, a Little
Havana mechanic who left Cuba more than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the family's early relief that Elian had survived quickly
dissolved into acrimony over where the boy should live.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials took until early January to rule that Elian
should be returned to his father in Cuba, a decision that sparked a
day of angry protests in Miami. The Miami family quickly filed a
federal lawsuit aimed at winning Elian an asylum hearing and the
right to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, the boy's two Cuban grandmothers traveled to
the United States _ and briefly to Miami to see the boy _ in an
unsuccessful bid to take Elian home. Their visit only seemed to
feed the rancorous debate over the boy's future.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, Castro turned Elian into a cause celebre, staging
massive public rallies and marches that attracted hundreds of
thousands who chanted and sang for his return.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a Miami federal judge ruled that Elian should go home
with his father, triggering the Miami family's immediate appeal to
the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dramatic arrival of Juan Miguel Gonzalez from Cuba
in early April, sparking a new round of demands _ and a wave of
support from the American public _ that the boy be turned over to
his father pending the court appeal. After several weeks of
frustrating negotiations, Reno ordered a pre-dawn raid on April 22
to forcibly take the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The raid triggered outrage and a day of angry protests in Miami,
along with uneasiness among many Americans shocked by a news photo
of a terrified Elian being snatched by a gun-wielding agent.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling soon subsided, however, after Elian was reunited
with his father in the Washington area and subsequent photos of the
smiling boy were released. He spent the next two months living
mostly in seclusion, awaiting the outcome of the court case.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, the Atlanta appeals court ruled against the Miami
relatives; then reaffirmed its decision on June 23.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort, the Miami relatives asked the Supreme
Court to hear the case, but were rebuffed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the case that captured the attention of U.S. presidential
candidates and is cited as a factor in an apparent deal in Congress
to ease the embargo against Cuba is finally over.
</P>
<P>
   But it will clearly never be forgotten in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' said Ana Vega, 27, a Cuban-American
schoolteacher. ``It's just publicity for Castro. In his eyes, he
beat the American government. They gave in to that evil, horrible
man.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.canf.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
