<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7622 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEB-SITES-NYT &LR;      06-28 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-SITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET AS A FLEA MARKET OF IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMEWORK HELP FROM AN EXPERT  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When 9-year-old B.J. Pinchbeck could not find a good Web site to
help him with his science project, he and his father decided to
build one. Four years later, B.J. Pinchbeck's Homework Helper
(www.bjpinchbeck.com) has become an indispensable bookmark for many
middle-schoolers and their parents. The site, operated by
DiscoverySchool.com, has amassed more than 580 links organized by
subject and B.J. has become a kind of Stephen Jay Gould for
preteen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. is now 13, an age at which popularity can be a double-edged
sword. He receives between 20 and 40 e-mail messages a day asking
for help, even on days when he would rather be in-line skating or
playing Age of Empires online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard,'' he said. ``It's getting frustrating,
particularly in the summer.'' The reach of the Web means that he
now gets e-mail from countries where students do not get a
two-month vacation. His father reminds him, he is receiving a lot
more e-mail from American students in summer school. ``Yes,'' he
said a little wearily. ``That's another thing we have to
consider.''
</P>
<P>
   IT TAKES ONE TO TANGO ON THIS SITE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By day, Larry Carroll works as a software engineer at the Boeing
Co., putting animated figures through their paces in 3-D replicas
of cockpits and workspaces. But Carroll's heart belongs on the
dance floor. A longtime dancer, he saw his first tango class 11
years ago and, he says, fell in love. Four years ago, he wrote an
online manual
(home.att.net/(tilde)larrydla/basics(underscore)O.html) to teach
the tango to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tango is kind of like a polymorphic character that depends
on the viewers and what they want,'' he says. ``It can be very
technical, but it can also be very simple and intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, 58, grew up in Texas, where his uncle ran a honky-tonk:
``I learned swing, the two-step and the cowboy stuff at a very
early age.'' After the Air Force and an early career in television
production, his interest in software took him to NASA and then to
Boeing. Of course, he kept dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most good engineers also have a strong creative bent,'' he
says. ``Otherwise, they would just be plodders.'' He has just added
a new page to his site for people who want to learn the steps in
just one minute. He has called it, with an engineer's precision,
``0 to Tango in 60 Seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCIDENTAL JOURNALIST: A TEEN-AGER FINDS A VOCATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tameeka Mitchem remembers her first foray into journalism as
something of a disaster. In April 1999, she volunteered to work for
Harlem Live, a nonprofit Web site (http://www.harlemlive.org)
produced by New York teen-agers. When another reporter could not
make a scheduled interview at a local community organization,
Tameeka went instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous, and that's weird because I'm not a nervous
person,'' she said. ``I was reading the information in the cab on
the way over. I think I asked one question three times.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Tameeka was Harlem Live's editor in chief,
helping to manage the Web site's staff of more than 30. The site,
created in the mid-'90s, publishes news and features concerning
Harlem, mostly on community-based organizations that, she said,
``don't get all that much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Tameeka was not interested in being a reporter or an editor when
she joined Harlem Live. ``I was looking for something to put on my
college application,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. In a few months, she will leave the site to attend
college in Virginia. Her major: journalism. experiment with the Web
for exhibitions of non-commercial projects.
</P>
