<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7624 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-ABORTION-HNS &LR;      06-28 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT REJECTS NEBRASKA LAW BANNING LATE-TERM ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rekindling a bitter debate over women's rights to
end their pregnancies, the Supreme Court on Wednesday struck down a
Nebraska law banning late-term procedures that opponents call
``partial-birth'' abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In its most important decision on the subject in eight years,
the court ruled 5-4 that the law imposed an ``undue burden'' on a
woman's right to use the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer, writing for the court, said the state's
late-term-abortion law actually covers two types of abortion
techniques, both performed in the second trimester of a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The better known _ and more controversial _ is called dilation
and extraction (D&AMP;X), in which the fetus is pulled feet first
through the cervix and the skull is punctured and its contents
drained. The procedure is most often used between the 19th and 24th
week of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser known procedure, performed mostly between the 16th
and 22nd weeks, is called an intact dilation and evacuation (D&AMP;E),
in which fetal and placental tissue are dismembered and removed.
</P>
<P>
   It was the D&AMP;X procedure that the Nebraska legislature was
attempting to stop. But Breyer said the statute was so broad that
it also could be used to bar D&AMP;Es, which many doctors consider
safer.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said banning the D&AMP;E procedure could place a women's
health at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those who perform abortion procedures using that method
must fear prosecution, conviction and imprisonment (resulting in)
an undue burden upon a woman's right to make an abortion
decision,'' Breyer said. ``We must consequently find the statute
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Breyer were Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Sandra Day O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who supplied the critical fifth vote for striking down
Nebraska's law, wrote a concurring opinion that offered some
guidance on what type of late-term-abortion law might be
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ban on partial-birth abortion that only proscribed the D&AMP;X
method of abortion and that included an exception to preserve the
life and health of the mother would be constitutional in my view,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision produced both political and legal
shock waves.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the court decision ``was the only
decision that could be reached consistent with Roe v. Wade,'' the
1973 Supreme Court ruling that legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the next president is likely to choose two to four
Supreme Court justices and ``depending on who they are,'' abortion
rights are ``very much in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who has focused on the high court's
makeup as a key issue, said such ``razor-thin'' decisions could be
reversed if Texas Gov. George W. Bush wins the presidency and names
more conservative justices. ``The presidential election will decide
the future of the Supreme Court and that in turn will decide
whether or not we keep a woman's right to choose _ or see it taken
away,'' he said on a campaign stop in Blacklick, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, also campaigning in Ohio, said he was ``disappointed'' in
the ruling and that he felt states should have the right to pass
laws that ban the ``brutal practice of partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people can take steps to protect children who are
in the process of being born, and they should have that right,'' he
said in a statement. ``And, unlike Al Gore, I pledge to fight for a
ban on partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., hailed the decision as a major
victory for women's right to make ``private, personal'' decisions
about her body. ``Today women's health prevailed over extremism,''
Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican
Conference, said, ``I look forward to the day when a Republican
president will replace retiring liberals with justices who will
truthfully interpret the Constitution rather than impose their
activist views against states and the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the court's dissenters _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas
_ two questioned whether Nebraska and 29 other states with similar
statutes could rewrite their laws to conform to Wednesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a co-author of the last major abortion ruling in 1992
that upheld abortion rights but allowed some state restrictions,
wrote in a dissent joined by Rehnquist that ``Justice O'Connor
assures the people of Nebraska they are free to redraft the law.
The assurance is meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that including a ``health of the mother'' exception
to late-term abortion laws would award ``each physician a veto
power over the state's judgment that the procedures should not be
performed.''
</P>
<P>
   A late-term abortion bill is pending in the Republican-led
Congress, but Clinton has promised to veto it, as he did with
similar measures in 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's 1997 law was challenged as unconstitutional by Dr.
Leroy Carhart, one of only three doctors in the state known to
perform abortions and the only one who performed them after 16
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the court agreed that the law was too broad and placed
an ``undue burden'' on Carhart and his patients.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis
agreed, saying the law would result in banning a number of common
abortion techniques used in the second trimester. Similar laws in
20 other states have been struck down in federal courts as
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago upheld the
bans in Illinois and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the high court affirmed the decision of the 8th
Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Carhart, who sat in the high court chamber Wednesday, said
afterward, ``This is a victory for all Americans who believe that
the government must not be allowed to meddle in the private
decisions best left to women, their families and their doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   In another abortion-related decision, the court gave states
greater leeway to restrict anti-abortion demonstrations outside
health clinics
</P>
<P>
   Saying the right to avoid ``unwanted communication'' sometimes
outweighs free-speech rights, the justices by a 6-3 vote upheld
Colorado's limits on antiabortion protesters' so-called ``sidewalk
counseling'' of patients who coming to clinics where abortions are
performed. Dissenters were Scalia, Thomas and Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Colorado has enforced its ``bubble'' law that
prohibits people from counseling, distributing leaflets or
displaying signs within 8 feet of others without their consent
whenever they are within 100 feet of a clinic entrance.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
