<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-ANIMALS-NYT &LR;      06-28 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TV, IT'S RAINING CATS AND DOGS, NOT TO MENTION POTBELLIED PIGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newest crop of television stars are devoid of ego, blind
ambition and agents who request astronomical salaries. They don't
undermine their co-stars, and their so-called friends don't go
blabbing to the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   No, a new age of decorum has not dawned in the television world.
The new stars are animals: Dogs, cats, crocodiles, snakes, turtles
and even giant squid.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the animals play other animals (a dog named Howard is
the new Lassie). Others are on trial (like those on ``Judge
Wapner's Animal Court''). Others undergo surgery (on ``Emergency
Vets''). Many are just being themselves while being stalked by
indefatigable humans (``Crocodile Hunter'' and ``Jack Hanna's
Animal Adventures'').
</P>
<P>
   After years of relative scarcity, shows about animals are
multiplying: Some two dozen can now be found on television. And
they are being watched by ever larger audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started eight years ago, there were three or four
animal shows on television,'' Hanna said. ``Now _ golly day! It's
hard to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, two shows about extinct creatures on the
Discovery Channel have drawn the largest audiences ever for cable
programs other than sports or news. ``Walking with Dinosaurs,''
which used computer graphics to create the world of the dinosaurs,
was watched by 10.7 million people. ``Raising the Mammoth,'' a
documentary tracking an expedition that unearthed a wooly mammoth,
was watched by 10.1 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Planet, a cable network that features programs about
animals 24 hours a day, is the fastest-growing channel on cable
television, now reaching 60 million households, or 60 percent of
those with televisions. On a good night, its audience size is equal
to or greater than Larry King's on CNN. This fall National
Geographic will start up its own cable channel, with a large
percentage of its programming focusing on the animal kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, the majority of cable subscribers are offered
32 hours of animals. The Learning Channel, the Pax network and even
CNBC, the financial network, offer wildlife programs, as PBS has
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the genre has changed. In the 1960s and '70s nature
programming typically offered the heavy monotone of a narrator with
instructional shots from Africa, India or other faraway places, as
in ``Wild Kingdom'' and ``The Undersea World of Jacques Cousteau.''
</P>
<P>
   Later came programs centering on fights to the death _ in the
trade, ``fang television'' _ and offerings like the Fox network's
``When Good Pets Go Bad,'' which served up videos of snarling pets
turning on their masters.
</P>
<P>
   The new programs are livelier than the early vintage and less
violent than the fang-heavy ones. They feature colorful hosts and
include more close-up photography. They seek to educate and
entertain at the same time. And they are heavily promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the material has progressively gotten better,''
said Larry Gerbrandt, a media analyst with Paul Kagan Associates,
which follows programming trends. ``The footage has gotten more
exciting and networks like Discovery and Animal Planet have really
figured out how to generate ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Television programmers, media analysts like Gerbrandt and
academic experts attribute the resurgence to the expanding array of
cable channels; the relatively low costs of making wildlife
documentaries, which are now shot with vastly improved cameras; and
the growing adoration for nonhumans of every stripe.
</P>
<P>
   The animal genre ``couldn't compete in a network world,'' said
Jeff Sagansky, president of the Pax network, which recently added
reruns of Hanna's ``Animal Adventures'' to its daily schedule.
``But it can compete in more of a niche world,'' he said of the new
universe of cable, digital cable, satellite TV and smaller
broadcast networks like Pax.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller networks crave original programming that they can
call their own, but they do not have a lot of money for the
writers, producers, crews and actors. The wildlife shows require
only a small staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, these animals have not been signed by Aftra, so you
don't pay residuals,'' Sagansky joked, in a reference to the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   The programs are also attractive to parents troubled by
increasingly racy network shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a safe harbor on the dial,'' said Clark Bunting,
president of Animal Planet. ``People are looking for the
opportunity to do something as a family and not have the kids on
the computer, dad watching sports and mom watching something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunting said that the programs were also simply good television,
produced with the goal of entertainment. ``A typical show used to
be about lions in the Serengeti, and the story was about the alpha
male and the beta female and all that sort of thing,'' Bunting
said. ``Now, people have used elements of story to hook the viewers
and bring them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal Planet's No. 1 lure is Steve Irwin, host of ``The
Crocodile Hunter,'' the network's top-rated program, which is
regularly shown on Sunday and Wednesday nights and is watched in an
average of 400,000 households. Its popularity led Animal Planet
executives to run the show every night from June 18-24 in what was
heavily promoted as ``Croc Week.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two nights' programs brought Planet's highest
prime-time ratings ever. The June 18 edition of ``Crocodile
Hunter'' was watched by more than one million viewers, the largest
audience in the channel's four-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, known for his thick Australian accent and khaki outfits,
seems to regularly court death in the program as he roves the
swamps of Florida, the Australian outback and Sumatra in search of
crocodiles and any other large and dangerous animal he can come
upon.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent episode, he jumped into a river and wrestled a
``crocker'' into submission with his bare hands. In another, while
visiting the Komodo dragons of Komodo Island, Irwin wound up being
chased by one that bit into the back of his boot as he scurried up
a tree. He caught his breath and excitedly told the camera, ``This
is a great demonstration of how dangerous they are!''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has been the subject of a ``Saturday Night Live'' skit, is
negotiating a movie deal and will soon have his own action figure.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the nature genre as a whole is a new generation of small
video cameras that capture shots that would have been impossible
even a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Bunting said, ``you can fly in formation with Canada
geese, and your sense of perspective, as a viewer is you think that
you're a goose.''
</P>
<P>
   The network's other defining show, ``Emergency Vets,'' focuses
on the animals rushed to the Alameda East Veterinary Hospital in
Colorado. A typical scene: Zorro, a potbellied pig who rides a
skateboard in a traveling animal show, eats some plastic, which
causes an infection in an upper molar on the left side of his
mouth. The infection spreads to his sinus system and causes his
head to swell. The vets extract the tooth and give him antibiotics,
and Zorro is free to perform again.
</P>
<P>
   Akira Matsuka Lippit, a professor of cinema at San Francisco
State University, suggests that the current animal craze has a
broader explanation than intense interest in snakes and potbellied
pigs. He links it to a sweep of technological advances that are
distancing people from simpler ways of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a rapid increase in a kind of technologization of the
culture and there is perhaps a desperate attempt to reconnect the
human body and existence to a certain kind of animal, and natural,
state,'' said Lippit, author of the recent book ``Electric Animal:
Toward a Rhetoric of Wildlife'' (University of Minnesota Press).
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Rollin, a professor of philosophy and physiology at the
University of Colorado who has written extensively on the
relationship between animals and society, said the programs'
popularity might also be related to urbanization.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are fascinated by animals because we're removed from
animals,'' Rollin said. Such programs give humans a glimpse of
natural phenomena that their very distant ancestors lived with
every day, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Within the television industry, there is nonetheless a concern
that animal programming is reaching a saturation point. ``I'm sure
some of them are going to be weeded out,'' said Hanna.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he said, it will come down to the survival of the
fittest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
