<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN ANTONIO ARCHBISHOP KNOWN FOR OPEN-DOOR POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUDOLPH BUSH and JENNIFER DLOUHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Clergy members are called to reach out to the
troubled. Sometimes, it's a mission that puts them in danger as
they struggle to balance openness and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Recent high-profile violence aimed at religious centers,
including the September 1999 attack on a prayer service in Fort
Worth, Texas, and an August 1999 shooting rampage at a California
Jewish community center, has raised the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hostage situation involving Patrick Flores, the
Roman Catholic archbishop of San Antonio, is only the latest in
this series of violent acts that is prompting church officials to
take a look at safety. (The archbishop was released nine hours
after a man seeking help with a passport problem took him hostage.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We do wrestle with the issue of how do we keep our doors open
and how do we protect the lives of the people that work here,''
said Phil Raymond, president of the Alamo Chapter of the National
Association of Church Business Administrators. But though ``the
risks are greater today churches will always err on the side of
(openness).''
</P>
<P>
   The threats are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three decades ago, a man burst through the doors of the
Cornerstone Church in San Antonio and walked up the aisle, firing a
revolver at the Rev. John Hagee. Every bullet missed, and Hagee
credits God with saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in March 1999, a pipe bomb sent through the mail and
addressed to Hagee exploded en route from Dallas. No one was hurt,
but the attempt increased Hagee's wariness.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nobody visits his office without first being screened. He
worries, too, when he preaches to large crowds. But he doesn't let
the threats keep him from his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you allow one terrorist to stop you from fulfilling your
divine assignment, then he has been thoroughly successful,'' said
Hagee, an evangelical preacher whose sermons are broadcast on
television.
</P>
<P>
   A key tenet of most Western religions is evangelization, which
requires interaction between the church and potential converts. To
bar the gates would be against many Judeo-Christian principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not lock ourselves up permanently every time one
disturbed person creates an incident such as this,'' said Catholic
Bishop John McCarthy of the Austin Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi Bishop Edmond Carmody echoed McCarthy's vow to
remain accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot operate out of fear,'' Carmody said. ``Sometimes,
people can be very distraught, and no doubt, this man was very
distraught.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, though, openness has to give way to security.
Most chanceries in the country employ stringent security measures,
including magnetic door locks, monitoring systems and guarded
entrances.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Antonio chancery appears to be far less secure than
its counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of Flores' tenure has been accessibility, so
much so that the Catholic Chancery has no security officers or
sign-in process. Visitors can freely visit administrative offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been discussing the possibility of something like this
happening for maybe 10 years,'' said Carlton Brown, director of
management information systems at the chancery. ``The archbishop
didn't feel he needed security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants people to know that he is accessible to them,'' said
Monsignor Larry Steubben, vicar general of the San Antonio
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   The policies will undoubtedly be reviewed as a result of
Wednesday's incident, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of five ministers around the country who have had to go
to full-time body guards,'' said Max Lucado, pulpit minister of the
Oak Hills Church of Christ here. ``Maybe it's just a reflection of
the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
