<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSIC-SCULPTURE-NYT &LR;      06-28 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SCULPTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUND OF SCULPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL STRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ One of the more admirable qualities of the Experience
Music Project, the $240 million rock 'n' roll museum conceived by
Paul Allen, co-founder of Microsoft, is its commitment to local
musicians and artists. This is evident not just in its memorabilia
from artists like Nirvana, Jimi Hendrix, Heart and the Sonics, but
also in its centerpiece: A giant sound sculpture made up of 600
guitars strung along the branches of a metal tree rising more than
30 feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   On closer examination, little metallic centipedes seem to be
perched over the strings of several dozen of the instruments: These
are self-playing, self-tuning guitars that have been invented for
the project. Throughout the day, guitar picks on mechanical arms
strike the strings as computer-controlled dampers press down on the
frets, creating eerily beautiful music.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptor, inventor and composer behind this piece, titled
``If 6 Was 9'' (not just after the Jimi Hendrix song but also after
a ratio considered in developing the instruments), is a Seattle
resident who has spent his life outside the two local worlds the
museum represents: Rock and Microsoft. He is known as simply
Trimpin, one of Seattle's best-kept secrets, an excitable,
gray-bearded, German-born sound artist and recent recipient of a
MacArthur Foundation fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms observed during a recent visit to Trimpin's Seattle
studio were covered with the detritus of his more than 20-year
obsession with turning acoustic instruments into sculptures that
can be played by motors or by valves that release water, air and
even fire. In one corner stood a piano with pistons hanging over
each key. Upstairs was an old invention that combines a tuba and a
stand-up bass. Notebooks full of brightly colored, heavily
annotated diagrams and scores covered the tables. And on the walls
hung a dozen one-string prototypes of his mechanical guitar.
Trimpin tapped a key on his computer and the picks began clicking
over the strings, filling the studio with sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a 21st-century player guitar,'' said Trimpin, who
is known for his work with Conlon Nancarrow, the Mexico City
composer best remembered for creating compositions for player piano
too complex to be played by human hands. ``When I was asked to come
up with a proposal for the museum, I wanted to do something with
strings because I've never worked with strings. And I've never
worked with amplified sounds. I've always used natural sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture was built in just five months, with Trimpin
working 14 hours a day in his studio. ``I was dealing with hums and
interference, which I've never had to deal with before,'' he said.
``I had to build a completely different pick system, because a
normal pick has a higher impedance that picks up all the magnetic
noises. Then I thought that I could develop a fiber-optic pickup
that wouldn't have hums. But I didn't have time to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when you think back,'' he went on, ``the basic
loudspeaker design is 100 years ago. We have all these new digital
recording techniques, but we still need to use a loudspeaker with
this heavy coil and magnetic setup. I don't understand why that
still exists. I learned from this project that I'm not satisfied
with artificial, amplified sounds; when I work on my next project,
I want to change them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another inventor might run out and try to patent the player
guitar, the new picking system, the fiber-optic guitar pickup, and
the 21st-century loudspeaker. But not Trimpin. Though many of his
instruments, designs and ideas could make millions in the
instrument-manufacturing and even the toy world, he has never
applied for a patent or tried to mass produce anything.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is simply to combine sound, visuals and movement in new
ways and, in the process, modify instruments to extend their
repertory beyond human limitations. His guitars, for example, can
not only be played in configurations impossible for human hands
but, in the space it takes to get from one note to another, they
can also switch into a completely different tuning system.
</P>
<P>
   Trimpin says his interest in redesigning instruments comes from
his childhood in the Black Forest in Germany. ``When I got toys for
my birthday or Christmas, I had to take them apart first so I could
see what's inside and how it works,'' he said. ``And then I could
play with it. So there was always this curiosity of how mechanics
work.''
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, Trimpin was busy packing his fire organ so it
could be shipped for a performance at the Sound Symposium in
Newfoundland. It is a thermodynamic organ that uses a glass flame
in a Pyrex tube to produce sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal organ pipes use forced air to make the sound, but here
you get warm air rising, and at a certain temperature it creates a
much more beautiful, richer sound,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Trimpin eventually wants to incorporate the fire organ into a
multimedia piece that will also use cold water dropping onto heated
plates to generate pitch-specific hisses. In addition, the steam
that results will be used as a screen for projections.
</P>
<P>
   Trimpin said all of his ideas, even that one, evolve out of his
childhood experiences. ``The fire organ is based on a big bonfire
we had on top of a mountain after carnival every year in the
village where I grew up,'' he said. ``You'd put some square wooden
discs ... In a fire until they glowed, then slam them over a ramp
and they'd take off and howl into the air.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the village residents were watching these low-tech
fireworks, Trimpin was listening to the steam produced by the wet
discs and the whistling of their flight. ``I could always hear
choirs singing and whole symphony orchestras playing in the sounds
created by this tremendous heat,'' he said. ``I always looked
forward to going to the bonfire because I could listen to this
symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimpin turned back to his fire organ and continued packing,
trying to finish in time to hear another sort of symphony: He had
free tickets to James Brown that night. ``I like to go to concerts
and galleries and museums,'' he said, ``but when I go to the
junkyard I have the same experience because I can fantasize about
discovering things. So junkyards and museums and concerts are all
on the same level for me: There are inspirations to be found at all
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
