<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCHOOL-GRADUATION-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PRESCHOOL GRADS, THE FIRST DAY OF THE REST OF THEIR LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KATE ZERNIKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTSDALE, N.Y. _ Lia Cupani tugged at the corsage on her wrist
as the other graduates pinned on their mortarboards. Gabriel
Levine, this year's student speaker, scanned his note card one last
time before the strains of ``Pomp and Circumstance'' rose up.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my mommy and daddy!'' whimpered Hunter Smaldone.
</P>
<P>
   You could hardly blame him. He is 4 years old. Yet there he was,
along with his classmates at Creative Beginnings Children's Center,
about to celebrate what has become a milestone in this season of
commencements: the preschool graduation.
</P>
<P>
   In Westport, Conn., the Landmark Academy Preschool gave awards
not only for ``Always says please and thank you'' but also for
``Best rester.'' In Mineola, on Long Island, the Tutor Time Child
Care center even put out a yearbook for its young graduates. And
suggesting how seriously some take all of this, one preschool in El
Paso had to call in the police to control a crowd of parents trying
to squeeze into a graduation ceremony in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   No one, yet, has invited Alan Greenspan to speak. But still,
preschool graduations are taking on all the trappings of similar
events on college campuses _ the caps and gowns, the diplomas, the
grandparents flying in from overseas, the triumphant bubble-blowing
at festivities' end.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when pressure to achieve comes younger and younger _
parents compete to see who walks first, who reads first, who gets
into Harvard early _ it only makes sense that each step, no matter
how early, takes on more moment. As transitions go, the one to
kindergarten might not seem so rough. But preschools across the
country say they want to ease it by marking all that has come
before _ even if all that's come before is block building, song
singing and the ABC's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition is a grown-up thing, but it also gives a child
an acquaintance with what is next,'' said Vicki Folds, vice
president for early childhood education at Tutor Time, a company in
Boca Raton, Fla., that operates 204 preschools nationwide. ``We
can't just throw them into a new environment. We have to tell them
they are ready for it, they are going to succeed. A stressful child
can't learn as well as one who's confident.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hartsdale, Creative Beginnings held several dress rehearsals
to prepare the 4- and 5-year-olds for the big day. Teachers tied
1,000 bright blue balloons into an archway over the blacktop
playground behind the school and roped off the surrounding grassy
area for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   As parents warmed up their camcorders outside on the lawn, the
graduates showed off their finery back in the classroom _ a pink
tulle dress for Lia, a tuxedo for Daniel Berle. The pint-sized
mortarboards came with elastics to fasten under the chin, but no
one, sighed Josephine Covais, a teacher, wanted to wear them.
Elastics are so preschool.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, the graduates were feeling cocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're free play!'' hollered Emily Mancuso, 5, throwing her
fists in the air. ``WE get to make the rules!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to have snack?'' asked Lia, whose teachers voted
her most likely to become a congresswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looks like she's going to a wedding,'' one little girl
blurted as Emily Hsu flounced in wearing a poufy white dress.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers here chose Gabriel to deliver the message from the
graduates because he could read, and so he dictated a few brief
sentences expressing the graduates' thanks to the school.
``Remember,'' his teacher, Covais, whispered into his ear as he
reviewed one last time, ``Periods mean `stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   As the graduates lined up for the procession, their teachers
reminded them to wait for the music to begin, and advised the girls
to hold up their dresses as they walked up the grassy hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just have fun,'' Covais advised. ``Remember, those are only
your mommies and daddies out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The underclassmen marched in first, tied together by a rope. The
parents burst into applause, some clapping around bags of Cheerios
brought along to calm cranky younger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dress down now!'' a teacher hissed at Emily Hsu, still
carrying the bustle of her dress like a bag of groceries in front
of her.
</P>
<P>
   The graduates sat beaming and more still than any of their
parents could ever remember seeing them, as Gabriel read his
speech, enunciating syllable by syllable (but remembering to stop
for periods). Walking up one by one, they took their diplomas with
their right hand and shook the hand of the director, Susan
Stevenson, with their left.
</P>
<P>
   Like most graduations, this one stretched on too long, with four
speakers, including two alumni, now elementary school students, who
offered wise words about the good and bad things that happen to you
after preschool. (Good things: No naps in kindergarten. Bad things:
You get homework.) The graduates amused themselves by finding uses
for their rolled-up diplomas, as telescopes or bats to hit one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after Susan Stevenson, the director, bid them ``a great
time in kindergarten,'' the graduates rushed into the waiting arms
of their parents, greeted with bouquets and shouts of ``We did
it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It squishes your heart,'' said Lia's mother, Imre Cupani,
wiping her eyes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
