<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-PRESCHOOL-GRADUATION-     06-28 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCHOOL-GRADUATION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HARTSDALE, N.Y.: her eyes.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much of the effort was for the parents, as Emily's mother, Karen
Hsu, acknowledged. A chiropractor, she had canceled all her
appointments for the afternoon. ``My clients don't understand,''
she said, ``but I'm really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she knows the significance,'' Hsu added,
watching her daughter. ``She just knows she's getting big and she's
going to go on the bus. She's excited about getting big, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   If all this seems to be taking preschoolers a bit too seriously,
those who organize the graduations say the ceremonies work to the
opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   Parents have become so competitive, and are so bombarded by
advice on how their children should be developing, said Folds at
Tutor Time, that they sometimes worry too much if their children
are not achieving enough at a young age. The graduation, she said,
is a way of recognizing that every child has achieved. After all,
everyone graduates cum laude from preschool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are looking for children to do more, sooner,'' she
said. ``This helps recognize the positive things that are
happening. We applaud the joyfulness of the child. We don't want to
lose sight of that. We don't want to turn them into adults too
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, Craig Cupani, Lia's father, could only sigh wistfully
from behind his camcorder. ``It's the first big step in life,'' he
said. ``Then elementary school, junior high, high school, college.
Then she's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
