<SLUG> BC-HINCKLEY-VISITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL REVERSES ITSELF ON HINCKLEY VISITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: St. Elizabeths has no apostrophe)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Washington psychiatric hospital reversed itself on Wednesday
and withdrew its recommendation that a court permit John W.
Hinckley Jr. to leave the hospital for unsupervised weekly visits
with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley, who was found not guilty by reason of insanity in the
1981 shooting of President Ronald Reagan and three others, has
argued for years that he should be permitted more freedom. He has
argued that his mental health has improved since he attempted the
assassination to prove his devotion to the actress Jodie Foster.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal by the hospital, St. Elizabeths in Washington,
followed court filings on Tuesday in which prosecutors said
Hinckley had deceived his psychiatrists this spring and had
``continual interest in violently themed books and music.''
</P>
<P>
   At least twice before, St. Elizabeths has reversed itself after
urging more freedom for Hinckley. After a recommendation in 1987 in
which the hospital said Hinckley was no longer a danger, government
investigators found 47 photographs of Foster under Hinckley's
mattress.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley could continue to seek the unsupervised visits, but the
hospital's backing had been expected to be influential with the
judge, June L. Green, of the U.S. District Court in Washington.
Since last July, Hinckley, 45, has been permitted occasional visits
to malls, restaurants and bookstores in the Washington area but
only when accompanied by hospital employees.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors did not identify the books or music Hinckley had
obtained but said that after the hospital recommended the
unsupervised visits last March, he had told his treatment team
about the materials. Hinckley also acknowledged that his fiancee,
Leslie deVeau, had helped him keep the materials secret from the
hospital, the prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that deVeau had purchased certain books for him,
brought them to St. Elizabeths, given them to him and taken them
back once Hinckley had read them,'' said the filing by the federal
prosecutors, Robert R. Chapman and Thomas E. Zeno.
</P>
<P>
   DeVeau's telephone number is unlisted, and she could not be
reached on Wednesday. Hinckley's lawyer, Barry Levine, did not
respond to telephone calls, but The Washington Post reported on
Wednesday that Levine had said on Tuesday that the prosecutors'
assertions were a smokescreen to distract attention from the
remission of Hinckley's psychiatric illness.
</P>
<P>
   DeVeau and Hinckley met while she was in the same hospital after
being acquitted by reason of insanity for killing her 10-year-old
daughter. She was released in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   St. Elizabeths' director of forensic services, Dr. Raymond
Patterson, declined to discuss Hinckley's case but said the
hospital would typically withdraw a recommendation for unsupervised
visits if it acquired new information.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley's efforts to win more freedom have often been
frustrated by disclosures. Once it was found that he had written to
the serial killer Ted Bundy and once that he had sought a nude
drawing of Foster. There has also been evidence that Hinckley
developed an obsessive interest in a female pharmacist at the
hospital in the mid-1990s and that he expressed admiration for the
serial killer Charles Manson.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 ruling on one of Hinckley's requests, Green said
Hinckley had often deceived those treating him. The judge quoted
from a 1987 diary entry by Hinckley. ``Psychiatry is a guessing
game, and I do my best to keep the fools guessing about me,''
Hinckley wrote. ``They will never know the true John Hinckley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
