<SLUG> BC-GORE0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore announces plan to save energy and cut taxes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Vice President Al Gore, campaigning in Columbus
on Wednesday, unveiled a proposal to give tax credits to people who
buy energy-efficient cars and homes and announced a $10 million
expansion of an administration program that encourages business
development in distressed areas.
</P>
<P>
   He also said recent 5-4 Supreme Court decisions on
abortion-related matter underscore the importance of the
presidential choice this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One vote on the wrong side of the issue would change the
outcome, and a woman's right to choose would be taken away,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To highlight his energy proposal, Gore praised Joshua Homes, a
Columbus company that builds energy-efficient houses, and traipsed
through a muddy construction site, to tour the environmentally
friendly home of Amy and Brian Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   He said his tax-cut plan is designed to promote saving energy.
Under the plan, people buying fuel-efficient cars would be eligible
for a tax credit up to $6,000; those upgrading home insulation or
heating and cooling systems would could qualify for a credit up to
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get the tax incentives, then it becomes too good of a
deal to pass up,'' he said. ``There's no doubt that we can save the
environment and thus reduce pollution dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crosbys' decision to build an energy-efficient home was
mostly based on finances, Brian Crosby said. The couple paid about
$1,000 additional for an energy saving furnace and air conditioning
system, but Crosby expects it to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically going to pay for itself on the savings we'll
get on our electric bills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, Vivian and Chuck Stuart, offered support. Vivian
Stuart said her apartment's gas bill averaged $260 in the winter,
compared to the monthly $63 she and her husband pay now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got twice the square footage and one-third of the gas
bill,'' her husband said.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners like the Stuarts are helping out the environment
while keeping bills low, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get rid of the debt of pollution that we shouldn't
pass on to the next generation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Gore shifted his focus from middle class
suburbs and environmental awareness to distressed communities in
need of economic growth and resources.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing conference on community empowerment, he announced the
adminstration's Community Empowerment Fund would receive $10
million in new funding. He said he would expand the Clinton
administration's empowerment program that helps local leaders start
up, attract and keep businesses in underdeveloped urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly was addressing a friendly audience. When Nancy
Santana, a Pennsylvania woman who started her own cleaning business
with the help of the empowerment program, introduced him _
apparently by accident _as the next president, people stood and
cheered.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
