<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-RATES-1STLD-WRITE     06-28 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED DECIDES TO LEAVE INTEREST RATES UNCHANGED, AT LEAST FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: rewritten with additional information; story grows by about
700 words)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve voted Wednesday to leave
interest rates unchanged, giving itself more time to determine
whether the series of rate increases it has imposed over the last
year are slowing the economy sufficiently to avoid an upturn in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank warned that it could start raising rates
again as soon as its next meeting, on Aug. 22. Analysts said the
Fed would probably tighten policy in August unless economic
indicators in coming weeks provide assurance that the red-hot pace
of economic growth earlier this year has given way to a more
sustainable path that reduces the threat of an inflationary spiral
in wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's decision had been widely anticipated by
economists and investors, and Wall Street took the news largely in
stride. The Dow Jones industrial average climbed more than 100
points but fell back after the Fed announcement to close at
10,527.79, up 23.33 points for the day. The Nasdaq composite index
rose 81.38 points, to 3,940.34.
</P>
<P>
   In calling a time out Wednesday in its campaign of rate
increases _ six over the last year, pushing its benchmark federal
funds target rate up by 1.75 percentage points, to 6.5 percent _
the Fed acknowledged that there has been some evidence that the
economy is cooling off. And the central bank noted that while
inflation by some measures has been accelerating, price pressures
are being held down by continuing improvements in productivity, a
measure of the economy's ability to produce more for less.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank's policy-making Federal Open Market
Committee suggested that it remains unconvinced that the economic
slowdown is for real. And it stressed its continuing concern that
the current low rate of unemployment _ 4.1 percent in May _ could
lead wages to rise so fast that companies would be forced to jack
up their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of moderating growth ``are still tentative and
preliminary, and the utilization of the pool of available workers
remains at an unusually high level,'' the committee said in a
statement released at the conclusion of a two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, the statement said, ``the committee
believes the risks continue to be weighted mainly toward conditions
that may generate heightened inflation pressures in the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the wording of the statement was intended in part
to keep investors off balance and keep stock prices from surging on
the assumption that the Fed was finished or nearly finished raising
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said there was a good chance that the Fed would push
rates up by another quarter of a percentage point in August, but
that the decision would be driven by the economic statistics that
come out between now and then.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're back on data watch,'' said Ian Morris, an economist at
HSBC Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Economists pointed to Wednesday's report on orders for durable
goods as evidence that some of the weakness exhibited by the
economy in the last few months might have been temporary. Orders
for durable goods in May rose 6 percent, to $218.89 billion, more
than reversing a 5.7 percent decline in April, the Commerce
Department reported. Analysts had expected an increase of less than
3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big increase in durable goods today is telling you that
this slowdown is going to be just moderate, that we're not going to
have an extremely sharp slowdown,'' said Maury N. Harris, an
economist at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said other important indicators in coming weeks could
follow a similar pattern, with chances good that both job creation
and average hourly earnings will rebound in June after being
depressed in May.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects the Fed to raise its federal funds target
rate on overnight loans among banks by a quarter of a percentage
point, to 6.75 percent, in August, and then to push the rate up
again to 7 percent by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert V. DiClemente, an economist at Salomon Smith Barney, also
said he expects the federal funds rate to rise to around 7 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that current financial conditions are not going to
prove sufficiently restrictive to keep demand moving back into
line,'' DiClemente said in a report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining its decision to leave rates unchanged, the Fed
suggested that it remains ambivalent _ or perhaps divided _ over
the potential for inflation to take root.
</P>
<P>
   The open market committee's statement gave equal emphasis to two
competing ways of assessing the outlook. One view, often emphasized
by Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, is built on the idea that an
acceleration in productivity growth is likely to continue, holding
down costs and tempering any inflation pressures that might result
from rising wages.
</P>
<P>
   In this view, the goal of monetary policy is to bring economic
growth down to ``a pace closer to the rate of growth of the
economy's potential to produce,'' as Wednesday's statement put it.
The economy grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate in the first quarter,
and most Fed officials put the non-inflationary growth rate at
between 3.5 percent and 4 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in expressing concern that the low unemployment rate could
ignite inflation, the statement recognized a position advocated by
a number of other Fed officials, including Laurence H. Meyer, a Fed
governor. Meyer believes that with unemployment around 4 percent,
even 3.5 percent annual growth might be enough to generate
inflation pressures.
</P>
<P>
   He has raised the possibility that the Fed might need to push
growth below 3.5 or 4 percent for some period and allow the
unemployment rate to rise to 5 percent or higher in order to
squeeze inflation pressures out of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan works to bring consensus to policy making within the
Fed, and the lines between the two camps are not firmly drawn. But
even if the Fed agrees that tighter monetary policy is beginning to
bite, it could still face a debate over how much further it needs
to go in slowing the economy.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
