<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ POST BIGGEST GAIN IN 7 SESSIONS; DOW HOLDS NARROW GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq composite index had its biggest gain in
seven sessions Wednesday as investors flocked to technology shares
while shunning most blue-chips.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index jumped 81.38 points, or 2.1 percent,
to 3,940.34, its best advance since June 19. Major contributors
were the four Nasdaq stocks that Lehman Brothers selected as
``uncommon values'' that would outperform the broad market over the
next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Juniper Networks surged 10, to 136 7/16; BEA Systems 7 3/64, to
45 63/64; Tellabs 5 5/16, to 68; and Gemstar International 4 1/2,
to 54 3/8. Of the six other Lehman picks also advanced _
Hewlett-Packard rose 7 1/16 to 123 11/16, Agilent Technologies rose
4 5/16 to 79 3/4, Cendant rose 1 3/8 to 14 1/4, Eli Lilly rose 2
3/8 to 87 1/8, and Nortel rose 7/8 to 67 7/8. Micron Technology
slumped 1 7/16, to 88 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which at one stage was up
nearly 116 points, managed to hold on to a gain of just 23.33
points, or 0.2 percent, to 10,527.79.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 4.27 points, to
finish at 1,454.82.
</P>
<P>
   All major gauges gave ground after the Federal Reserve warned of
a continued inflation risk even though, as expected, it took no
action to raise short-term interest rates further. Analysts said
they found nothing in the central bank's statement to dispel the
belief that at least one more rate increase, probably at the Aug.
22 meeting, was likely, barring convincing evidence that economic
growth had slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cloud is still going to be hovering over the party,''
said James Paulsen, chief investment officer for Wells Capital
Management.
</P>
<P>
   But he also pointed to the next wave of corporate earnings,
which will start being announced next month and which should be
about 20 percent higher than in the second quarter of 1999. And if
this coincides with perceptions of an economy that has moved from
unsustainably rapid growth to one headed for a so-called soft
landing, then that ``could be a dynamite combination'' for stocks,
Paulsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed basically said there are still inflation worries,''
said Kenneth Sheinberg, head of listed trading at SG Cowen. Sixteen
of the Dow's 30 stocks fell Wednesday, but hefty gains by
Hewlett-Packard; IBM, up 3 7/8 to 113 5/8; and Coca Cola, up 2 1/8
to 60, kept the average in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices fell Wednesday after the Federal Reserve
decided to leave interest rates unchanged but left the door open
for a rate increase in August. The price of the 30-year Treasury
bond fell 7/32, to 104 5/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from the price, rose to 5.95 percent from 5.94
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year Treasury note increased 4/32, to 102 29/32. The
note's yield declined to 6.10 percent from 6.08 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In corporate finance, the German telephone giant Deutsche
Telekom sold $9.5 billion of dollar-denominated bonds Wednesday as
part of its record $14.6 billion global bond sale. The dollar
portion was increased 90 percent from an original $5 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
