A7657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ABORTION-RULING0629-C     06-28 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-RULING0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supreme court's ruling a setback for abortion opponents
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida's ban on so-called ``partial birth''
abortions was put in jeopardy by the U.S. Supreme Court Wednesday
in a 5-4 decision making it nearly impossible for states to outlaw
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents decried the ruling. Supporters were
cautiously pleased, but worried about the close vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's action is imponderable. It is incomprehensable.
This is a damaging blow to the pro-life movement,'' said state Rep.
Randy Ball, R-Titusville, one of the authors of Florida's law
banning this type of abortion. ``We will continue this fight and we
will win this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   James Bopp, a lawyer for the National Right to Life Committee,
called the decision ``a radical expansion of the abortion right.''
Clarke Forsythe of Americans United for Life added: ``It's the most
extreme decision on abortion ever issued by the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Closing out its 1999-2000 term with some of the most divisive
rulings in years, the court added a further setback for abortion
opponents by ruling 6-3 that laws forbidding protesters from coming
too close to people entering clinics are not a violation of their
First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won this time but the battles are far from over,'' said
Lillian Tamayo, chief executive officer of Planned Parenthood of
Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast. ``The fact is that this
was a 5-4 decision. What is going to happen the next time an
abortion issue goes before the court?''
</P>
<P>
   Calling it an ``undue burden'' on women's rights, the Court
found unconstitutional a Nebraska law banning partial-birth
abortions, known medically as dilation and extraction, or D&AMP;X. The
procedure involves partially extracting a fetus, legs first,
through the birth canal, cutting the skull and draining its
contents.
</P>
<P>
   A more common procedure is dilation and evacuation, or D&AMP;E, in
which an arm or leg of a live fetus may be pulled into the birth
canal during the abortion operation.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the Nebraska law, while purportedly aimed only at
the D&AMP;X method, could criminalize the more common D&AMP;E method as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The law's other big flaw, Justice Stephen G. Breyer wrote for
the court, was that it lacked an exemption that would allow the D&AMP;X
procedure if a doctor concluded it was the best way to preserve a
woman's health. Florida's law allows the procedure when the woman's
life is in danger, but lacks the exemption for a woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   Abortions opponents are especially concerned about Breyer's
conclusion that the law ``must contain a health exception.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an unexpected setback for the pro-life movement,''
said Ball. ``The health exception is a broad loophole that allows a
doctor to just say a woman is stressed and use that as the
exception.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, chastised
the majority for viewing ``the procedures from the perspective of
the abortionist, rather than the perspective of a society shocked
when confronted with a new method of ending human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's law, passed during this year's legislative session, is
already being challenged in federal court in Miami. Earlier this
month, Judge Joan Lenard barred the state from enforcing the law
until the Nebraska case was decided by the Supreme Court. She is
expected to overturn the law and her decision is likely to be
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that the Florida law is constitutional and can
withstand a Supreme Court challenge,'' said state Sen. Anna Cowen,
R-Leesburg, who helped write the legislation. ``We were aware of
the Nebraska case when we wrote the law and I think we have a good
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 84-32 and the Senate voted 30-10 to ban partial
birth abortions in Florida. Gov. Jeb Bush signed the bill into law
on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Breyer in the court majority were Justices John Paul
Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, David H. Souter and Ruth Bader
Ginsburg. Dissenters were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Antonin Scalia, Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, supporters of school vouchers got what they
believe is good news in a Louisiana case in which the court ruled
that the government can provide computers to religious schools as
long as it is done in a ``secular, neutral and nonideological,''
way.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 ruling was praised by supporters of private school
tuition vouchers who believe the same criteria can be used to make
voucher programs constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the majority of the court has signaled that school
vouchers are constitutional,'' said Matthew Berry, a lawyer with
the Institute for Justice. He defended, among other programs being
challenged in lower courts, Gov. Jeb Bush's statewide plan to give
parents of poor children money for private schooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Removing the constitutional cloud from school choice will
encourage more legislatures to support such programs,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the ruling is ``a resounding victory.'' He said the
state's voucher plan meets ``the court approved principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agreed that the Court ruling helps supporters of
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court certainly took a sledgehammer to the wall of
separation between church and state today,'' said the Rev. Barry W.
Lynn, executive director of Americans United for Separation of
Church and State. ``The silver lining is that this decision gives
no aid or comfort to voucher supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas wrote the decision joined by Rehnquist, Scalia and
Kennedy. O'Connor and Breyer voted with them but in a separate
opinion they said the other four were too expansive in their
willingness to allow government aid to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The three dissenters were Souter, Stevens and Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling on abortion clinic demonstrations, the justices
decided the right to avoid ``unwanted communication'' sometimes
outweighs free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 vote upheld Colorado's limits on ``sidewalk counseling''
of patients who show up at clinics where abortions are performed.
</P>
<P>
   The state since 1993 has enforced a ``bubble'' law that
prohibits people from counseling, distributing leaflets or
displaying signs within 8 feet of others without their consent
whenever they are within 100 feet of a clinic entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens wrote for the court that the law is not aimed at the
content of someone's speech but only at where, when and how a
message is delivered.
</P>
<P>
   In his dissent, Kennedy complained that the decision
``contradicts more than a half century of well-established First
Amendment principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
