<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHINA-GAMESGEEK-N     06-28 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHINA-GAMESGEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S FORBIDDEN VIDEO GAME AND WEB PARLORS FLOURISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER 8. LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ 3 a.m. on a summer Friday here. A smoke-filled room is
packed with men, faces lighted by computer monitors, adrenaline
running from online combat. Bicycles clutter the alley outside the
door under the sign that reads NG Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   The men are muttering into their headsets, discussing attack
strategies with teammates seated only a few computers away. Brown
and green scenes of soldiers, terrain and tanks scroll rapidly
across the screens. A mobile phone rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' a man snaps at the caller who interrupted him. ``I'm
playing computer games.''
</P>
<P>
   NG Cafe is a net cafe, or a wangba, the businesses that serve as
late-night entertainment sites for hundreds of Beijing residents.
The putative reason the wangbas operate is to provide online
access. But the global scope of the Internet seemed to be mostly an
afterthought in a room where 18 of the 20 computers were engaged in
electronic warfare with opponents sitting nearby. To many Chinese
men, the emergence of the networked computer has less to do with
e-commerce than it has with e-battle.
</P>
<P>
   Six juniors from nearby Peking University have come for an
all-night session of Starcraft, a popular multiplayer computer
game. One of the students, Simon Zhang, said that his economics
professor had joked that Americans routed the Iraqis in the Gulf
War because they had more experience playing video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some logic to his joke,'' Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the room is male, a demographic reflected in the
fact that the bathroom has only a urinal. Everyone else is directed
to a brick hut across the alley. Most of the men, mainly students
and professionals who work nearby, arrived around midnight, and
many will not leave until dawn.
</P>
<P>
   One man has fallen asleep, his head collapsed against the table.
Another is asleep, sprawled across three chairs. An orange sign on
the wall reads: ``Loud Yelling is Prohibited''; it was prompted by
the frequent over-exuberance of players in the throes of victory or
defeat. Smoke burns their eyes, and some computer keys are charred
from errantly placed cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the government considers the playing of computer
games in wangbas illegal has not stopped thousands of them, and
their cousins, the game parlors (which typically do not provide
Internet access, just locally networked computers) from springing
up across China. The term cafe seems excessively elegant for the
one-room hovels heated by coal stoves that are NG Cafe's lower-end
counterparts and where customers generally pay about 50 cents an
hour and play for hours on end.
</P>
<P>
   But the proliferation of wangbas and game parlors in the last
three years has vexed a government that aspires to monitor social,
political and economic trends. Wangbas, the government believes,
have the potential to alter all three.
</P>
<P>
   When the Internet came to China about five years ago, observers
around the world thought that it would help reshape the politics
and economics of the country by introducing residents to ideas and
ways of life that the government had tried to restrict.
</P>
<P>
   When NG Cafe opened, its owners predicted that most of the
business would come from people seeking Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But Wang Peng, who works nights at the cafe, said that in the
seven months since the NG Cafe opened, game playing had grown to
about 70 percent of business. Visits to wangbas and game parlors
from Kashgar to Kunming to Kaifeng revealed similar ratios. Some
wangbas, particularly those near universities, have customers who
mostly use the computers for e-mail messaging, chatting or surfing
the Web, but the further the cafes are from educated, affluent
areas, the more computer games take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Computer games are to Chinese men what pick-up basketball games
are to American men. Instead of going to the neighborhood court,
Chinese men head to their neighborhood wangba. Here, those who are
most savvy on the battlefield earn the respect of their peers and
engage in the digital equivalent of trash talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a social activity,'' Zhang said. ``Playing a game on the
Net is very different from playing a game on a machine because you
can feel other people's hearts beating during the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He typed in a message to his teammates in Chinglish, a
Chinese-English hybrid: ``go zhou. wo dian ta.'' (Go attack Zhou,
I've electrified him.)
</P>
<P>
   Zhang's roommate, Otto Hua, 21, said there were some weeks when
he played multiplayer games for more than 20 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the government prohibited the playing of computer games
in wangbas, a restriction that has been sporadically enforced. The
regulation still permitted Wangbas to provide Internet access, just
not for playing games.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the government reiterated the restriction as part of a
collection of regulations that also prohibited wangba customers
from engaging in activities endangering national security and
disrupting public security and order.
</P>
<P>
   Editorials published in The People's Daily depict wangbas, game
parlors and computer games as a ``plague'' and ``poison.''
Newspapers and television broadcasts regularly report on students
addicted to computer games who do not return home for days, steal
money from their parents and give themselves to the wangbas in
indentured servitude to pay their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Wangba owners must now go to their local public security bureau
to register within 30 days of receiving a business license. In the
last several months, government enforcement has become stricter.
Several hundred unregistered wangbas and game parlors in Beijing
were closed in March, and several hundred wangbas and game parlors
in Shanghai were raided last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some wangbas have responded to the clampdown. Feiyu, a wangba
chain south of Peking University, has restricted game playing. But
other wangba owners are resisting limits on their lucrative
businesses. Last year, a wangba owner in the province of Zhejiang
challenged the restrictions in court saying that despite its social
harm, computer gaming has the potential of aiding development of
information technology in China. In February, the courts rejected
the claim, citing wangbas' societal harm.
</P>
<P>
   By 4:30 a.m., the sky over NG Cafe is light. Zhang and his
classmates leave at 5:30 a.m. after five hours. By 8 a.m., most of
the older customers have left and another wave of players, mostly
younger, arrives, ignoring the sign that prohibits elementary and
middle school students from entering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid of the regulations,'' said Zhang Shi Miao,
13, a student at a middle school. ``The government is overreacting.
Most people don't become addicted to computer games. It's just for
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Many customers are unaware that playing computer games in
wangbas is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know about these rules. Therefore the responsibility
is not on us,'' said Zhang, when told of the regulations. ``If they
don't strictly administer the law, then we can still go on
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was unlikely that the government would suddenly
strictly enforce the prohibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many interests in computer-game playing for that
to happen,'' he said. ``In America you would call it lobbying. In
China we call it bribery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
