<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE OUTLINES PROPOSALS ON ENERGY, ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKLICK, Ohio _ Vice President Al Gore wants more Americans to
drive to work on electric power and sleep under roofs latticed with
solar panels, and Wednesday he explained how he would nudge them in
that direction: with lucrative tax credits of up to $6,000 for
buying energy-efficient cars and up to $2,000 for buying houses
that met certain energy-efficient standards.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals boiled down to a philosophy that says that if
the federal government wants Americans to live and transport
themselves in a fashion less dependent on oil and kinder to the
environment, it should make it worth their while. As president,
Gore said Wednesday, he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get the tax credit, then it becomes too good of a
deal to pass up,'' Gore said as he sat on a stack of drywall in the
back yard of a house in this suburb of Columbus that was being
built with an array of energy-saving devices. ``Hopefully, over
time, that will change the pattern of practice so that these
energy-saving options begin to be just the normal way we do things
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that we can save on energy _ and thus reduce
pollution dramatically _ by giving these tax cuts to Americans who
want to take advantage of them,'' Gore added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides said that the tax incentives that the vice
president outlined Wednesday would represent about $48 billion in
lost federal tax revenue and spending over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gore had proposed a 10-year, $75 billion package of
tax breaks and other measures to motivate utility companies and
other manufacturers to explore and implement more energy-efficient
methods to reduce the country's dependence on oil. The vice
president was expected to make additional proposals on Thursday
that would bring the 10-year price of what he described as a new
energy and environmental initiative to much more than $125 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore's critics in the past have painted him as a
tree-hugging extremist or a starry-eyed idealist when it came to
the environment, the vice president has seized on sudden concerns
over the country's dependence on oil as an opportunity to dream big
environmental dreams. Gore had described this moment as ``an echo''
of the energy crisis of the late 1970s in remarks at a fund-raiser
in Washington late Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore spoke Wednesday not only in a swing state for the
general election, but in also in a region of the country hit
particularly hard by high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign and the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas have spent much of the last week trading bitter accusations
that resemble the schoolyard chant, ``I know you are, but what am
I?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his aides have asserted that Bush, as a former oil man
who has received large sums of campaign money from oil and gas
companies, would be unable to stand up to oil-industry interests.
And Bush's aides, in turn, have combed through the vice president's
proposals and statements over time for suggestions or evidence that
Gore at times supported higher fuel prices and had his own cozy
ties to the oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bush's aides complained that the ideas that Gore was
promoting were recycled, unimplemented proposals by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just adding more money,'' said Dan Bartlett, a
spokesman for the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That was true of some of Gore's proposals Wednesday, but not of
others. Gore's plan included a tax credit of 20 percent of the cost
of building equipment that did not rely on oil, like electric heat
pumps, hot water heaters and natural gas heat pumps; a tax credit
of up to $1,000 for the purchase of solar water heating systems and
$2,000 for solar electricity systems; an unspecified tax credit for
consumers who choose utilities in their areas that use cleaner
energy sources, and financial help for low-income families so that
they could better ``weatherize'' their homes and save on energy.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest tax credits for individual consumers were those for
the purchases of automobiles that ran at least partly on
electricity or dramatically maximized fuel efficiency in other
ways. These credits ranged from $4,000 for fuel-efficient pickup
trucks to $15,000 for fuel-efficient 18-wheel cargo trucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
