<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New AirTran ads spoof tyranny of `big airlines'
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Are cheap airfares in the same league with famous
victories over tyranny?
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Airways suggests they are _ in a lighthearted way _ in
new television ads debuting next week.
</P>
<P>
   The discount carrier also is rolling out a new slogan, ``Your
airline has arrived.'' It replaces the 2-year-old tagline ``It's
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   One AirTran TV spot shows a lone business traveler on an airport
tarmac facing a jetliner. The plane moves left, the traveler moves
to block its path. The plane moves right, the traveler moves again.
He finally puts down his briefcase and takes a stand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a takeoff on the historic image of a Chinese student facing
down a tank during the Tiananmen Square demonstrations of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to take a stand'' against the tyranny of unnamed
``big airlines,'' the voice-over implores.
</P>
<P>
   A second TV spot also plays off a historical image. It shows a
couple in New York's Times Square locked in a kissing embrace, a
re-creation of Alfred Eisenstaedt's famous VJ-Day shot at the end
of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is over,'' the voice-over says, touting AirTran's lack
of Saturday night stay restrictions. ``Now there's an airline that
lets you come home when you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ads are filmed in black-and-white, an attention-getting
device. They were produced by Chicago agency Cramer Krasselt.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran's ads follow a new campaign rolled out earlier this year
by its larger Atlanta rival, Delta Air Lines. AirTran is unveiling
the campaign today with a public rally at Lenox Square.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran's advertising has become more sophisticated in the past
year or two. Last fall it issued an innovative movie-trailer style
spot _ still in use in some markets _ touting the arrival of its
first Boeing 717 jets. The spot shows a military radar room, with
controllers panicking at the sight of unidentified planes. The
punchline comes when a senior officer staring helplessly at the
bogeys murmured, ``Oh, Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline, created by the 1997 merger of Atlanta-based ValuJet
and Orlando-based AirTran, struggled to survive initially but has
had five straight quarterly profits. It's recently been in talks
about a possible combination with TWA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're at a point where we're more confident and
credible in selling ourselves,'' marketing director Tad Hutchison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
