u a BC-CHESAPEAKE-COMPACT-NY     06-28 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHESAPEAKE-COMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENTS TIGHTEN GOALS FOR RESTORING CHESAPEAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSE HAVEN, Md. _ A toughened Chesapeake Bay restoration pact
aimed at a tenfold increase in oyster production and a 30 percent
drop in land lost to suburban sprawl was signed on Wednesday by
state and federal officials who hailed it as an environmental model
for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing else like it,'' said Carol M. Browner,
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency, in praising
the pact's inclusion of the anti-sprawl pledge by the governors of
Maryland, Virginia and Pennsylvania. ``This is the first-ever
federal-state-local agreement to have that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The revision of the 18-year-old multigovernment pact was
announced in a ceremony here on the bay's western shore. Speakers
celebrated the slow mending of the bay's tattered ecology and the
innovative standards set for further cleansing the vast bay
resource, which covers 64,000 square miles and serves 15 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement's most ambitious goal is the anti-sprawl
commitment, which would mean a 30 percent reduction in the
projected loss of the bay's farm and forest land to development by
2012. This would spare an estimated 30,000 acres a year if the
state governments lived up to that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first quantitative target of its sort that one of the
nation's regional water body cleanups has adopted,'' said Michael
Hirshfield, vice president for resource protection at the
Chesapeake Bay Foundation, a watchdog group of scientists and
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprawl has been discussed for years, and enough people felt
this new agreement had to take it on, so it does,'' Hirshfield said
in an interview while praising the separate commitment to
permanently preserve 20 percent of watershed land from development
by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
   While the agreement sets voluntary goals, over the years state
and local governments, prodded by environmental groups, have slowly
enacted laws to meet many of the escalating goals of the pact.
These have produced such successes as the resurgence of rockfish
and the flourishing of pelicans. But progress is offset by the
effects of pollution runoff from farms and suburbs and wetland loss
through development.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also includes a pledge to protect and revive the
devastated blue crab population, with the first cautious harvest
goals to be set across the next year. More promising is the
commitment to a tenfold increase in oysters, one of the crucial
food-chain creatures needed for filtering impurities from the bay.
</P>
<P>
   If met as promised by 2010, this goal would mean a restoration
to about 15 percent of the output of the bay's oyster heyday a
century ago, when 20 million bushels were harvested annually and
the bay was one of the world's premier seafood resources.
Development and pollution devastated the bay and reduced the take
to less than 500,000 bushels. But scientists have developed a
promising technique of recreating the oyster reefs of a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the bay shimmering in the background, Gov. Parris N.
Glendening of Maryland recalled ``the darkest of times'' two
decades ago when the bay's vitality was sapped and the first
uncertain agreement was pledged. He noted the firmer political
commitments that grew to support the pact. This year, his state
earmarked $25 million for the oyster program, and Virginia declared
a vast swath of the bay off-limits to commercial crabbing so female
crabs would be protected and the population might rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agencies spend about $150 million a year on
programs devoted to reducing pollution, restoring underwater
grasses and reviving waterway passages for migratory fish, a prime
barometer of a healthy bay. Progress against nutrient pollution has
included a drop of 6 million pounds annually in phosphorus and 42
million pounds in nitrogen, but has come with a warning that
expected population growth will intensify the problem.
</P>
<P>
   For all the optimism of the Chesapeake Executive Council, which
includes the District of Columbia as well as the three states,
members noted that the overall goal of seeing the bay removed from
the environmental agency's list of ``impaired waters'' remained
unmet. Among other problems, the bay, including its tidal rivers,
does not meet standards for dissolved oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists expressed disappointment that the pact
did not ban the dumping of dredge spoil in the bay or address
problems like nitrogen pollution from cars and power plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But overall,'' Hirshfield said, ``compared to other areas of
the country I'm familiar with, in terms of specific actions, this
stacks up very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
