<SLUG> BC-INTERNET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET REGISTRAR ORGANIZING USERS FOR BOARD ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 CITIZENS-NYT   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to raise public awareness of an
international election to help administer the Internet, public
interest groups on Wednesday announced a voter registration and
education campaign to recruit what it called cybercitizens.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign urges Internet users to join the Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers, which was selected in 1998 to take over
administration of the network's addressing, or domain name system.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit group is holding its first global elections this
fall. Anyone age 16 or older with an Internet address is eligible
to join the group. Those who register on ICANN's at-large
membership Web site (http://members.icann.org/) by July 31 will be
able to vote in the first election.
</P>
<P>
   The public-awareness effort was announced by the Center for
Democracy and Technology, Common Cause and the American Library
Association, three groups that have been working with Icann to try
to ensure that individual Internet users are properly represented
on ICANN's board.
</P>
<P>
   While representatives of business and technical groups have
already elected nine board members, ICANN this fall will hold
elections for the first five of what ultimately will be nine
at-large members, who will represent Internet users in general.
</P>
<P>
   Although ICANN defines itself as a standards-setting body with a
role limited to the technical functions of the Internet, it has
already made rules to protect trademark interests from so-called
cybersquatters, or domain name speculators. And in its next
meeting, scheduled to begin July 13 in Japan, the group is expected
to begin moving on plans to add new top-level domains to supplement
the popular .com, .net and .org suffixes.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Berman, executive director of the Center for Democracy and
Technology, said the goal of the campaign is to educate Internet
users about ICANN and how the group's decisions can effect them.
</P>
<P>
   He compared ICANN's role to one of being able to ``rearrange the
streets of a city, because they are registering our identity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are essentially effecting what is going to be a critical
identity and property right of every person in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Democracy and Technology, Common Cause and the
American Library Association said they would be alerting their
members about the campaign. Berman said that any company or group
wanting to post information on the campaign is welcome to copy the
information on the ``Become a CyberCitizen'' page on the Center for
Democracy's Web site, www.cdt.org.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the American Library Association said it will be
urging librarians around the country to post the campaign
information on the first page that Internet users see when using
public computers.
</P>
<P>
   Although ICANN's relationship with the three groups has been
contentious since they issued a report that forced the board to
make the at-large elections more open, ICANN's president, Mike
Roberts, said ICANN welcomes help with outreach.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said about 20,000 people have already registered, and
updated numbers with country-specific information should be posted
on the ICANN Web site this week
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
