<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-MISSILE-3     06-28 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-MISSILE-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND RUSSIA PLAN JOINT EXERCISE OF MISSILE DEFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a effort to broaden their military cooperation,
Russia and the United States are planning to conduct a joint
exercise of their defenses against short- and medium-range
missiles, a senior U.S. official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to rehearse the procedures for coordinating Russian
and U.S. theater missile defenses against a common foe, U.S.
officials said. The exercise is likely to take place at Fort Bliss,
a U.S. Army post in Texas, before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Theater defenses are anti-missile systems like the Russian S-300
or the U.S. Patriot that are intended to counter short- or
medium-range missiles _ typically missiles with ranges between a
few hundred and a few thousand miles _that could threaten U.S.
troops abroad or endanger the United States' allies.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for the joint exercise does not mean that Moscow has
dropped its opposition to the Clinton administration's grander
proposal to erect a missile shield over the United States. Russia
still fears that the administration plan, which is intended to
counter intercontinental-range missiles, would give the United
States a strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But theater systems have emerged as the one missile defense area
in which Washington and Moscow seem able to cooperate. It is kind
of a lowest common denominator, where each side is prepared to work
with other, albeit for their own reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are resuming our longstanding cooperation in theater
missile defense,'' a senior U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the exercise were discussed in talks in Washington by
senior Russian and U.S. defense officials. The broad aim of the
talks is to restore the cooperation between the two militaries that
existed before NATO's war with Yugoslavia. The two sides, for
instance, discussed a plan to have Russian peacekeepers from Kosovo
train U.S. soldiers for that mission at the United States' military
training center in Hohenfels, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian motivation to cooperate on theater missile defense
is clear. Moscow sees the Clinton administration's plan for a
national missile defense as a threat and is energetically
advocating theater missile defense as an alternative.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In meetings with U.S. officials, President Vladimir Putin of
Russia has asserted that theater defenses could be used to shoot
down enemy missiles immediately after launching, an approach that
is known in the United States as a ``boost phase'' defense. This,
the Russians suggest, could protect the United States and Europe
from threats from states like North Korea, dispensing with the need
for the administration's system, which involves the deployment of
20 missile interceptors and a battle-management radar in Alaska by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has a different motivation in seeking to cooperate
on missile defense. U.S. officials are also eager to draw the
Russians into a discussion of potential missile threats and ways to
counter them in the hope that the Kremlin' s opposition to national
missile defense might eventually wane. And they want to learn about
Russian technology.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperation itself involves a ``command post'' exercise at
Fort Bliss, the El Paso home of the 32nd Army Air and Missile
Defense Command, according to a United States official. That means
that Russian and U.S. officers would practice the procedures that
are needed to track enemy missiles and then coordinate and fire
Russian and U.S. anti-missile defenses. No ``enemy'' missiles would
actually be launched or shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Russians and U.S. officers have been involved in two previous
exercises _ in Moscow 1996 and in Colorado Springs in 1998 _ but
they have essentially been computer simulations. Another round of
Russian and U.S. talks is planned before the date of the command
post exercise is formally set; it is expected to be held in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an attempt to move out of institute and simulations
into the field,'' said a U.S. official said. ``It is still a
simulation but under more realistic field conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a lawmaker influential on missile
defense, said the Pentagon had been too slow to cooperate with the
Russians on theater defense, in part because the administration was
initially opposed to the idea of a national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have been doing this all along,'' Weldon said in a
telephone interview. ``We have sent the wrong signals to the
Russians, and now they wonder why we want to get them involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon recently met with Russia's deputy defense minister,
Nikolai Mikhailov, who told him that Moscow was interested in
working with the Americans in developing a new system, the S-500.
But Mikhailov did not describe that system in any detail.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Russians and the Americans discuss cooperation on
theater systems, Russia's generals have insisted that their
opposition to national missile defense will not recede. They have
publicly threatened to undertake a variety of countermeasures if
the Clinton administration moves ahead with plans for a missile
shield. These include putting multiple warheads on their new Topol
long-range missile, withdrawing from the treaty banning
medium-range missiles and suspending inspections of other arms
accords.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. national defense ``could lead to the tearing up of all
treaties and the withdrawal from joint inspections of nuclear
weapons,'' Col. Gen. Vladimir Yakovlev, the commander of Russia's
strategic rocket force, wrote in the government newspaper
Rossiiskaya Gazeta. ``Isn't it useful for Americans to note what is
going on here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
