<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-DETECTIVES-     06-28 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-DETECTIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE HIRED A DETECTIVE AGENCY TO INVESTIGATE MICROSOFT'S ALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD SHORES, Calif. _ In a raucous news conference on a
sprawling Silicon Valley corporate campus affectionately dubbed
Larryland by its inhabitants, Larry Ellison, the chairman and
founder of Oracle Corp., Wednesday defended his company's yearlong
spying operation against Microsoft Corp. as a ``civic duty''
similar to investigative reporting by the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was to try to take information that was hidden and
bring it into the light,'' Ellison said. ``I don't think that's
arrogance. That's a public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison's remarks came a day after Oracle acknowledged hiring a
detective agency in Washington, D.C., to document ties between
Microsoft and three advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference, at the end of a previously scheduled
product announcement, was marked by Ellison's determined defense of
his business ethics and of his company's behavior as an appropriate
method for combating Microsoft's business tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The hour-long session took on a surreal quality as questions
about whether Ellison's behavior was ``Nixonian'' were interspersed
with inquiries about Oracle's products, principally related to
databases, and the company's market share in the Internet software
business.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison repeatedly asserted that the spying operation was
justified by Microsoft's own tactics, which recently led a federal
judge who heard the antitrust case against the company, Thomas
Penfield Jackson, to rule that Microsoft should be broken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're alone in this,'' Ellison said. ``The
Justice Department felt the need to investigate this company,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old software entrepreneur, whose wealth has come
close in recent months to rivaling that of Bill Gates, the chairman
of Microsoft, said his company had done nothing wrong in
commissioning the investigation, which came to light this month
after a failed attempt by the detective agency to buy the trash of
the Association for Competitive Technology, a Washington-based
lobbying firm favoring Microsoft ally.
</P>
<P>
   Two other groups backing Microsoft in the antitrust case, the
Independent Institute and the National Taxpayers Union, were also
targets of the Oracle-sponsored investigation, which began last
June. Documents showing Microsoft's financial support for those
groups were later cited in articles in The New York Times and The
Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging on Tuesday that it had paid for the
investigation, Oracle declared, ``Left undisclosed, these Microsoft
front groups could have improperly influenced one of the most
important antitrust cases in U.S. history.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ellison said he accepts complete responsibility
for the effort, but added that he had not known until Tuesday about
the tactics involved or even the name of the detective agency. The
agency, Investigative Group International, is headed by Terry
Lenzner, a former Watergate investigator who has also worked for
President Clinton's lawyers and the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't spend a lot of my time planning the
investigation,'' Ellison said. ``We have a group in Washington that
looked after that. Believe it or not, I spend most of my time
worrying about our e-business suite, our applications server and
our database server.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who has long deflected controversy with combative
humor, insisted that he had nothing to hide. And he challenged
Microsoft to undertake its own investigation of Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will ship them our garbage,'' he said. ``We will ship our
garbage to Redmond, and they can go through it. We believe in full
disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Microsoft headquarters in Redmond, Wash., were
quick to rise to the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing more disturbing than Oracle's behavior is their
on-going attempt to justify these actions,'' Microsoft said in a
statement. `` Ellison now appears to acknowledge that he was
personally aware of and personally authorized the broad overall
strategy of a covert operation against a variety of trade
associations.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's statement noted that Oracle had financed its own
share of lobbying groups, including ProComp, the Progress and
Freedom Foundation, the Software and Information Industry
Association and the Computer and Communications Industry
Association _ all of which have taken stands against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Microsoft's top executives, including Gates and
CEO Steve Ballmer, were in an all-day executive retreat and were
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The verbal fencing between Oracle and Microsoft is only likely
to sharpen as they compete with increasingly parallel industry
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Microsoft introduced its vision of Internet-based
computing that it called its Microsoft.NET strategy. Gates said it
would take years for all the products in the strategy to reach the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle executives responded Wednesday by saying that their
company already had a complete line of software for Web-based
computing. Both Ellison and his chief marketing executive, Gary
Bloom, said Microsoft's strategy should actually be called
Microsoft.NOT, as in ``not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison said he did not communicate frequently with either Gates
or Ballmer. He showed a particular dislike for the two Microsoft
executives and the company they have built into the world's largest
independent software developer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
