<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-ABORTION-HNS &LR;      06-28 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT RULES AGAINST BAN ON `PARTIAL-BIRTH' ABORTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in a split vote, struck down a
Nebraska ban on so-called ``partial birth'' abortions, stirring up
a near decade-old debate that immediately spilled into the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a 5-4 ruling, said the Nebraska law placed an
undue burden on a woman's right to end a pregnancy. About 30 states
have laws prohibiting the practice. Texas, which has no such law,
had filed a legal brief with the justices urging them to uphold
Nebraska's prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also decided in a separate case to uphold a
Colorado law that restricts protests near medical clinics. The
court said the statute, designed to stop abortion protesters from
closing in on visitors to the clinics, did not violate abortion
opponents' free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League and
other supporters of abortion rights hailed the decisions.
Opponents, such as the Family Research Council and the National
Right to Life Committee, decried the rulings as unjust.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the courtroom, the court's pronouncements reflected the
raging national disagreement over abortion rights as justices
forcefully expressed their views during an emotionally charged
final public day of their 1999-2000 term.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer and John Paul Stevens, who wrote the
majority opinions in the two cases, called the differences between
abortion-rights supporters and opponents irreconcilable.
Nevertheless, they asserted that the Constitution gives women the
right to choose abortion free of undue legal burdens and harassing
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia, who oppose a
constitutional right to abortion, took the unusual and deeply
symbolic step of reading portions of their dissents from the bench.
Justices recite dissents only in cases in which they have profound
philosophical differences with the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Scalia each took the court to task for ignoring the
rights of abortion protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The court's 5-4 decision striking down the Nebraska law marked
the justices' first consideration of the controversial
partial-birth abortion procedure. The rare surgery involves
partially removing a fetus, legs first, from the womb into the
birth canal, where its skull is pierced and its contents drained.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of abortion rights first dubbed the procedure
``partial-birth,'' but the term has gained wide use, even by
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has twice passed legislation calling for a ban on the
practice, but President Clinton has vetoed those measures.
Republican House leaders vowed to keep pressing for a federal
prohibition, despite the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee
for president, said he was disappointed with the court's decision
and vowed to fight for a federal ban, if elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``States should have the right to enact reasonable laws and
restrictions, particularly concerning the brutal practice of
partial-birth abortion,'' Bush said. ``The American people can take
steps to protect children who are in the process of being born, and
they should have that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, an abortion-rights supporter and Bush's
likely Democratic opponent, hailed the court's decision but said a
single vacancy on the court could change things. The next
president, in the likely event that a vacancy occurs, could tilt
the direction of the court by appointing a new justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential election will decide the future of the
Supreme Court and that in turn will decide whether or not we will
keep a woman's right to choose or see it taken away,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a supporter of abortion rights, lauded the court for
striking down Nebraska's prohibition, calling it ``the only
decision it could reach consistent with Roe vs. Wade,'' the 1973
decision that gave women the constitutional right to choose
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in ruling against the Nebraska statute, did not
address the constitutionality of the procedure. Rather the
justices, in an opinion by Breyer, said the Nebraska law was so
broadly written that it criminalized not only the controversial
surgery but more conventional procedures protected under the
court's prior abortion decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result is an undue burden upon a woman's right to make an
abortion decision,'' Breyer said. ``We must consequently find the
statute unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who performed abortions in violation of the Nebraska law
could have been sentenced to prison for up to 20 years, fined up to
$25,000 and have their state medical licenses revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Breyer's opinion in Stenberg vs. Carhart were Stevens
and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, David H. Souter and Ruth Bader
Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, in his vociferous dissent before a hushed courtroom,
publicly assailed the court's decision as ``indefensible'' as he
likened the partial birth abortion procedure to infanticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion is a unique act, in which a woman's exercise of
control over her own body ends, depending on one's view, human life
or potential human life,'' Thomas said. ``Nothing in the federal
Constitution deprives the people of this country of the right to
determine when the consequences of abortion to the fetus and to
society outweigh the burden of an unwanted pregnancy on the mother.
Although a state may permit abortion, nothing in the Constitution
dictates that a state must do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Thomas' dissent were Scalia and Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, an abortion-rights
supporter, wrote a separate dissent in which he said the
partial-birth abortion procedure does not interfere with a woman's
constitutional right to terminate pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, the court upheld, 6-3, Colorado's statute
restricting protests within 100 feet of medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, people cannot come within 8 feet of another
person to engage in ``protest, education or counseling'' without
that individual's consent. Violators can be fined $750 and
imprisoned for up to six months, though no one has been prosecuted
under the 1993 statute.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in an opinion by Justice John Paul Stevens, called
the law a legitimate exercise of the state's ability to set neutral
criteria for the time, place and manner of public protest while not
trampling on the constitutional right of people to express their
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute's restriction seeks to protect those who enter a
healthcare facility from the harassment, the nuisance, the
persistent importuning, the following, the dogging and the implied
threat of physical touching that can accompany an unwelcome
approach . . . by a person wishing to argue vociferously
face-to-face and perhaps thrust an undesired handbill upon her.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens' opinion in Hill vs. Colorado were Rehnquist,
O'Connor, Souter, Ginsburg and Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   In dissent, portions of which he read to a hushed courtroom,
Scalia assailed the court's ``remarkable'' conclusion that the
Colorado law is not intended to silence abortion protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is before us, after all, is a speech regulation directed
against the opponents of abortion, and it therefore enjoys the
benefit of the ad hoc machine that the court has set in motion to
push aside whatever doctrines of constitutional law stand in the
way of that highly favored practice,'' Scalia wrote in a dissent
Thomas joined.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow dissenting Justice Kennedy, who also read from the bench,
said the court was shortchanging the free-speech rights of abortion
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
