<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-PROVIDIAN-FRAUD-560&AMP;A     06-28 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-FRAUD-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT CARD ISSUER AGREES TO DEMAND TO REPAY MILLIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Va.)  By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the nation's large credit-card companies
agreed Wednesday to a demand from bank regulators to reimburse its
customers at least $300 million for misleading and improperly
billing them.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators accused the Providian Financial Corp., the
nation's seventh-largest issuer of credit cards, of misleading
hundreds of thousands of consumers, many of them with credit
problems, with phone calls and mass mailings full of confusing
sales pitches. As a result, people paid annual fees when they had
been told there were none, received credit cards they did not know
they had signed up for and were subjected to higher interest rates
than the company had advertised, according to the government, which
conducted a yearlong investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Providian signed a joint agreement with the federal comptroller
of the currency, the attorney general of California and the San
Francisco district attorney's office, in which it agreed to halt
the practices objected to by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 million of Providian's 13 million customers are likely
to receive reimbursement checks later this year, regulators said.
In addition to the $300 million in reimbursements, which regulators
called a minimum, Providian will pay a $5.5 million fine to the San
Francisco district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the $300 million in restitution was one
of the largest they knew of in a case involving consumer deception.
It is 10 times larger than the amount Wall Street analysts had
expected and, after taxes, will wipe out the equivalent of more
than one-third of Providian's 1999 profits.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which is based in San Francisco, was the nation's
fastest-growing issuer of credit cards over the 12 months ended
March 31, increasing the size of its portfolio _ which is chiefly
credit card debt _ by 54 percent, according to Friedman Billings
Ramsey, an investment banking firm in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Providian focuses its marketing on the growing number of
Americans who have credit problems, and is known for its
sophisticated use of databases in singling out potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which regulators said began because of complaints from
Providian customers, also offers the latest evidence of a growing
consumer backlash against credit card companies struggling to
maintain their profit margins. So many consumers have complained
about receiving their bills too close to the payment deadline to
avoid a late fee, for example, that the comptroller began an
investigation into the practice earlier this year. Bank One's giant
First USA credit card unit has received the most complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providian has engaged in a pattern of abusing consumers by
misleading them,'' said Daniel P. Stipano, the director of
comptroller's enforcement and compliance division.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, Providian, whose credit card operation
is led by David R. Alvarez, neither acknowledged nor denied
breaking the law, but did agree to change its practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we thought seriously about fighting'' the government,
Shailesh Mehta, Providian's chief executive, said Wednesday in a
conference call with reporters. ``This was purely a business
decision'' based on the calculation that litigation would have cost
more than the settlement, Mehta added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent months, the number of consumer complaining to the
comptroller's office about Providian's practices has declined
significantly, Mehta said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes as bank regulators, state officials and
members of Congress are vowing to look more closely at predatory
lending, particularly to people with a bad credit history or low
income.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an historic occasion,'' said June D. Cravett, the head
of the consumer and environmental protection unit of the San
Francisco district attorney's office, because it indicates that
federal regulators are now concerned with the banks' treatment of
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the current government efforts against this sort of
fraud focus on confusing, high-interest home-equity loans that are
pitched to people who often have few other lines of credit open to
them and can lose their houses if they default. In 1994, Congress
passed a law to stop banks from offering the deceptive loans, but
regulators have since warned that the law has had little effect.
The Federal Reserve recently formed a multiagency task force that
is studying ways to curb predatory lending.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the Providian settlement showed that
home-equity loans were not the only worrisome practice in the
so-called subprime lending market. ``People who don't have good
credit are preyed upon in all sorts of areas _ when they try to get
a credit card, when they try to get a home-equity loan, when they
try to get a mortgage on a house,'' said Frank Torres, the
legislative counsel at Consumers Union, an advocacy group that
publishes Consumer Reports. The case also reflects a new level of
aggressiveness among bank regulators, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Te government's agreement with Providian is the first time
regulators have punished a company by using the Federal Trade
Commission Act, Stipano said. The act gives the government wider
latitude to investigate marketing practices, as opposed to solely
the details of a written contract, than the laws regulators have
traditionally used.
</P>
<P>
   In its agreement with Providian, the comptroller described
selling pitches that one regulator compared to a Catch 22.
</P>
<P>
   In one pitch, Providian boasted of charging no annual fee but
then required customers to pay $156 a year for credit protection,
the government said. If, after seeing the charge, they asked not to
receive the protection, they were then charged an annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   In another, Providian telemarketers, working from scripts,
refused to tell people what interest rate they would receive no
matter how many times they were asked. Instead, the employees would
repeat, using slightly varied language, the idea that Providian
would significantly beat a consumer's current interest rate. In
fact, the difference was usually slight and, because of the
complicated rules, often ended up being higher, Stipano said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the payments to customers, Providian said it would use
$36 million of cash reserves and take a $163 million charge.
Because restitution is tax deductible, it will not show up as a
$300 million loss on the company's earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Providian announced the likely size of a
settlement, its stock fell more than 10 percent. Wednesday, it
gained $2, to $85, as investors were cheered by the news that the
case is now largely over, said Todd Pitsinger, an analyst at
Friedman Billings Ramsey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
