<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVESTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER RUSSIAN ENERGY CONCERN MOVES TO KREMLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A battle over Unified Energy Systems, Russia's
electricity monopoly, intensified on Wednesday after a group of
foreign investors who oppose a plan to overhaul the company took
their case to the Kremlin. The government controls more than half
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors representing about 15 percent of the company's stock
met with Alexander Voloshin, the Kremlin chief of staff. Voloshin,
an important figure in President Vladimir Putin's administration,
is also chairman of Unified Energy's board.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came a week after disenchanted investors asked Putin
to stop the restructuring plan, which they say would destroy the
value of their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Unified Energy, the most actively traded stock
in Russia, is seen as a test of the new Putin administration's
attentiveness to foreign investors as well as its commitment to
strengthening Russia's power resources.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring plan would break up Unified Energy's vast
network of generating stations and distributors into companies that
could then be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The government has yet to formulate a position on the plan. But
its opinion is important, since it is the single largest
shareholder in Unified Energy, with a 53 percent stake. Its vote is
crucial to the fate of the plan and in any move to overrule the
plan's author, Anatoly B. Chubais, the company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute pits investors against Chubais, architect of
Russia's privatization program and previously a favorite among
foreign investors because of his pro-Western views.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investors are criticizing Chubais for pushing ahead with a
plan they say will allow powerful local business groups to buy up
power industry assets at bargain prices. They say he has ignored
their proposals to alter the plan. In an open letter to
shareholders posted on Unified Energy's Web site Wednesday night,
Chubais replied directly to those concerns, saying, ``I am
listening, but are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Voloshin, an opponent of Chubais', wields vast power in the
Kremlin and the government. He was surprised by how strongly the
investors felt about the restructuring, a person close to the
situation said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Voloshin's position is still unclear, government
opposition could halt Chubais' plan, or more seriously, threaten
his position in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais presented a revised plan last week, but investors say it
was little changed from an earlier version. They say the plan is
still too vague on how regional energy companies will be split off
from the main grid. Investors want regional companies merged and
sold as larger units.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais does not need the approval of shareholders to begin
carrying out the plan, although he has pledged to show it to
investors first.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, shareholders amended the company charter to require a
75 percent vote to oust Chubais, who became chief executive of the
company in 1998. Investors have threatened to call an emergency
shareholders' meeting in July and possibly attempt an ouster. The
government and foreign investors together represent more than 80
percent of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Unified Energy stock is trading about 11.5 cents a share, down
about 40 percent since the end of March, just before Chubais first
formulated the restructuring plan. Russia's benchmark stock index
is down about 24 percent over the same period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2121EDT &QL; 
