<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-NYT &LR;      06-28 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDCOM AND SPRINT NOW SEEN AS TAKEOVER TARGETS FOR RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON   and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint Corp. have not yet called off their merger,
but already the rumors are swirling about who might try to buy
either company.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, no doubt telecommunications executives around the
globe huddled with their advisers to figure out what the Justice
Department's opposition to the WorldCom-Sprint merger might mean
for them.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, all they can do is wonder.
</P>
<P>
   By contract, neither Sprint nor WorldCom can talk to other
parties until their merger agreement is terminated or unless both
companies agree to third-party discussions. Neither Sprint nor
WorldCom would comment Wednesday, but after the Justice Department
filed suit on Tuesday to block their merger, it is widely assumed
that the companies will call off the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability is high,'' said a person close to the two
companies' discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, too, are betting that the deal will fall apart.
WorldCom's stock price was up $4.875, to close at $44.5625
Wednesday. Sprint's stock fell $5.625, closing at $52.75.
</P>
<P>
   And while Sprint, in particular, is seen as a potential takeover
target, ``no one is entirely safe,'' said Adam Quinton, a
telecommunications analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``The evolution of the
industry is that if it was compelling to hook up 12 months ago, it
is even more so now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean competitors are ready to rush in just yet,
though. Executives close to Atlanta-based BellSouth, the regional
phone company that lost a bidding war to WorldCom for Sprint last
October, said that BellSouth was sitting tight for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the world looks different than it did last fall.
BellSouth, for one, now has a joint venture with SBC Communications
to combine their wireless operations. Such a deal, analysts said,
makes it less pressing for BellSouth to own Sprint's wireless
operations. And BellSouth, primarily a local telephone company,
does not yet have approval to sell long-distance service _ another
drawback.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect BellSouth to wait to see if a foreign buyer,
particularly the cash-rich Deutsche Telekom of Germany, makes a run
at either Sprint or WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sommer, Deutsche Telekom's chairman, said two weeks ago that
he expected to have a war chest of about $100 billion to pay for
his entry into the United States. Just this week, Deutsche Telekom
raised $14.5 billion in the largest corporate bond offering ever.
Recently, Deutsche Telekom's Internet arm, T-Online, had an initial
public offering in which it raised more than $30 billion. And the
parent company plans to issue an additional 1.5 billion shares in
the next five year to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom failed to secure an American beachhead earlier
this year when talks between it and Qwest Communications
International Inc., the Denver-based telecommunication carrier,
collapsed. The talks hit a snag when US West, which was in the
midst of closing its own merger with Qwest, objected to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   US West did not like the fact that its shareholders would have
received a significantly lower premium for their shares than
shareholders of Qwest. The Qwest-US West merger received approval
from the Federal Communications Commission on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Deutsche Telekom said the company might be
particularly interested in Sprint, in which it already owns a stake
of about 10 percent, because the deal would give the German company
both a fixed-line and wireless network in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts have pointed to Sprint's wireless network as its
crown jewel, and possibly a property that could be sold
independently of Sprint's fixed-line business, executives close to
several major European telephone companies mulling an offer for
Sprint disagreed. These executives said that Sprint was more likely
to be acquired whole because of the increasing importance placed on
a strategy that combines both businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom wants to make an acquisition United States by
the end of the year, according to executives close to the company,
and the company has held internal meetings in the last week to
discuss their options now that WorldCom's acquisition of Sprint
looks doomed. If the German company goes after Sprint, Qwest's
lingering hopes of an eventual combination with Deutsche Telekom
would be dashed.
</P>
<P>
   But if Deutsche Telekom decides not to make a play for Sprint,
executives close to the company said it might return to the
bargaining table with the merged Qwest-US West, or possibly look at
Global Crossing Ltd., an undersea fiber optic cable operator with
which it has already held informal talks. An executive close to
Deutsche Telekom said it was just a matter of time before the
company pounced _ with the only question being in which direction.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom is also seen as a
formidable overseas contender to acquire either WorldCom or Sprint,
although again Sprint is the more realistic target. WorldCom's size
is such that if it merged with France Telecom, or even Deutsche
Telekom, WorldCom might end up with the controlling interest.
</P>
<P>
   Like Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom already owns approximately
10 percent of Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom has its own ambitions to do business in the
United States, although analysts said it might not have the cash or
stock to unilaterally make a deal. But Sprint is particularly
attractive to France Telecom, which recently acquired Orange,
Britain's third-largest wireless telephone company. Orange,
combined with Sprint, could become a worldwide brand.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to France Telecom also said the company had
recently analyzed the feasibility of making a bid for AT&AMP;T, whose
stock is slumping. The French company went so far as calculating
what the value of AT&AMP;T might be if it were broken up, this person
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts see Nippon Telegraph and Telephone of Japan as another
possible bidder. It has the money and its wireless arm operates
I-mode, the most advanced wireless network in the world, which
might make Sprint an attractive potential fit.
</P>
<P>
   Any foreign effort to acquire Sprint or WorldCom could meet
political resistance in this country. But analysts predict that
regulators would not block a deal soley on foreign-ownership
grounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2123EDT &QL; 
