<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-SCHOOLS-(TRIMS     06-28 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SCHOOLS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT BACKS U.S. FINANCING OF RELIGIOUS SCHOOLS' EQUIPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Overturning two of its own precedents that had
limited public aid to religious schools, the Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday that a federal program that placed computers and other
``instructional equipment'' in parochial school classrooms did not
violate the constitutional separation between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision was not supported by a single majority opinion:
a far-reaching opinion by Justice Clarence Thomas that would have
made ``the principles of neutrality and private choice'' the only
touchstones for channeling aid to religious schools was supported
by three other justices but was qualified by Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor's insistence in a concurring opinion that public aid may
supplement but must not supplant money that the religious school
could otherwise spend on its own programs.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the decision appeared likely to provide momentum
for the drive to legalize the use of vouchers for religious-school
tuition and provide ammunition for the legal argument that as long
as aid is distributed even-handedly, it cannot be said to be
impermissibly favoring religious recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see six potential votes for school choice,'' said Clint
Bolick, litigation director of the Institute for Justice, a leading
advocacy group on the issue, on Wednesday. His count included
Justice Stephen G. Breyer, who voted with O'Connor, as well as the
three who voted with Thomas: Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, although the voucher debate was quite obviously in
the justices' minds, that outcome remained in the realm of
potential, given O'Connor's observation that in the case before the
court Wednesday, no government funds ``ever reach the coffers of a
religious school.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Barry Lynn, director of Americans United for the
Separation of Church and State, said in an interview that ``in the
case of vouchers, the money goes directly to the school's coffers''
even though it first passes through the hands of parents. ``The
parents can do nothing with the voucher except spend it for
tuition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration supported the program that was upheld
Wednesday and appealed a decision from a federal appeals court in
New Orleans that declared it unconstitutional. Dating originally to
1965, the law, now known generally as Chapter 2, has evolved from
providing video filmstrips and similar material to a vehicle for
accomplishing the administration's goal of wiring every classroom
in the country for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, federal money flows through public school
districts, which are obligated to buy the equipment and distribute
it, technically as loans, to all schools within the district's
geographic boundaries, public, private and parochial, based on
their enrollment. Three taxpayers in Jefferson Parish, La., brought
suit in 1985 to challenge application to religious schools in the
district on the ground that there was no way of preventing the
schools from using the equipment in support of their religious
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The case had a tangled history, leading eventually to a 1998
ruling by the 5th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in New Orleans,
that the program was unconstitutional under two Supreme Court
precedents from the mid-1970s. Those decisions, Meek vs. Pittenger
and Wolman vs. Walter, held that the government could provide
textbooks but not other instructional materials to religious
schools, the premise being that textbooks could be vetted in
advance to make sure they did not advance the schools' religious
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The six justices who voted in the majority Wednesday to overturn
the 5th Circuit's decision all agreed that the earlier decisions
should be overruled. Thomas said the decisions were
``irreconcilable'' with other decisions in this area that came both
before and after them, most recently the court's ruling three years
ago in Agostini vs. Felton. In that decision _ which also
overturned an earlier precedent _ the court held that it did not
violate the Constitution for public schools to send teachers into
parochial schools, under a federal program, to provide remedial
classes.
</P>
<P>
   As these decisions indicate, the court's jurisprudence on the
subject of permissible public aid to religious schools has been in
turmoil for years. Wednesday's case, Mitchell vs. Helms, No.
98-1648, was by far the oldest case on the court's docket, having
been argued Dec. 1, and the failure of the justices to settle on a
single majority opinion after seven months shows that the turmoil
is likely to continue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reflecting on historical anti-Catholic sentiment in the late
1800s, Thomas said that ``hostility to aid to pervasively sectarian
schools has a shameful pedigree that we do not hesitate to
disavow.'' He said that ``nothing in the Establishment Clause
requires the exclusion of pervasively sectarian schools from
otherwise permissible aid programs'' and the cases that supported
such exclusion, ``born of bigotry, should be buried now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that government programs should be upheld on ``the
principles of neutrality and private choice,'' meaning that if the
government ``offers aid on the same terms, without regard to
religion,'' no impermissible religious purpose can be attributed to
the government. That was especially true, he said, when individuals
can make their own private choices on how to use the aid.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this point that O'Connor and Breyer expressed their
unease with what O'Connor called the ``logic'' of Thomas' opinion.
``The plurality opinion foreshadows the approval of direct monetary
subsidies to religious organizations, even when they use the money
to advance their religious objectives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In his dissenting opinion, Souter, joined by Stevens and
Ginsburg, said Thomas' opinion represented a fundamental break with
the court's precedents. He said it threatened the court's long-held
distinction ``between indirect aid that reaches religious schools
only incidentally as a result of numerous individual choices and
aid that is in reality directed to religious schools by the
government or in practical terms selected by religious schools
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, in her concurring opinion, explained her reasons for
agreeing that the court should overturn the precedents that limited
aid to providing textbooks. ``Technology's advance,'' she said, has
made the distinction between textbooks and other materials ``more
suspect'' than ever. ``Computers are now as necessary as were
schoolbooks 30 years ago, and they play a somewhat similar role in
the educational process,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      06-28 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN ELECTION TAKES A NASTY TURN NEAR THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Standing above an immense crowd in Mexico City's
central square recently, Francisco Labastida, the governing party's
presidential candidate, kept giving his followers, over and over, a
single message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to win,'' Labastida intoned. ``We are going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is not clear, just days before the vote on Sunday,
that Labastida, the candidate of the long dominant Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, is going to win, although he may.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that big rally, his supporters were oddly dispassionate.
Most had been brought in from out of town by bus and hurriedly left
after he spoke, even skipping a free concert by Juan Gabriel, one
of Mexico's most popular singers.
</P>
<P>
   The final opinion polls, published last week, show Labastida in
a tie with Vicente Fox, the right-of-center opposition candidate.
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist contender, was trailing well behind,
and millions of voters were still undecided. By law, campaigning
ended on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks PRI leaders, sensing this softness in their once
rock-hard support, have mobilized all their machinery and myriad
links to the government in a blistering campaign against Fox,
accusing him of taking illegal campaign donations from foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how the voters will react to the nasty turn in the
campaign. Never before have Mexicans faced a such a close contest
under an election agency with enhanced powers to ensure an accurate
tally.
</P>
<P>
   Enrique Jackson, a leading PRI lawmaker, electrified a
congressional hearing on June 21 by displaying a series of checks
that he said proved that Fox had received donations from people and
companies in Belgium and, far worse, the United States, Mexico's
historical adversary. Campaign laws prohibit funds from businesses
and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the checks showed that Fox was backed by ``powerful
foreign groups that have an appetite for our country.'' In fact,
the checks did not indicate the money trail from overseas to the
Fox campaign that he described. One was written a year ago, before
the campaign was officially under way.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Hakim, a businessman whose company was said to have made
contributions, produced documents to show that his transactions
were not donations to Fox. Fox filed a defamation suit on Tuesday
against the PRI, but his denials have been less potent in the press
than Jackson's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI came down hard on Ramiro Berron Lara, an engineer from
Petroleos Mexicanos, the state-owned petroleum company better known
as Pemex. He complained in the press that his superiors had tried
to make him campaign for Labastida during working hours.
</P>
<P>
   At a new conference, the director of Pemex, Rogelio Montemayor,
a PRI politician, denied that the company had leaned on any
employee to back Labastida. He described Berron as a problem
employee who was facing disciplinary action for ``distributing
pornography'' on the company's Internet network.
</P>
<P>
   Berron responded by showing a list on which he had been assigned
to register 10 Pemex employees to vote for Labastida. He said the
``pornography'' was a joke that a friend had sent on the Web and
wondered aloud why his superiors were reading his e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days, workers at one Pemex refinery complained
to the newspaper Reforma that they had been required to present
current PRI party credentials and pledge help for Labastida to
ensure their jobs and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring by the Federal Elections Institute, the government
agency that is organizing the election, showed that the broadcast
media had shifted sharply in favor of Labastida at the end of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While the two major national television networks remained more
balanced, elections officials said, the news media in the
provinces, where the hottest battle between Labastida and Fox is
being waged, strongly colored the news to benefit the PRI
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases coverage of Fox's campaign faced suppression.
Josh Tuynman, the national editor of Mexico City's English-language
newspaper, The News, said he resigned last week in protest over
instructions from the pro-PRI publishers to play down any stories
about Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Castaneda, an adviser to Fox, ended his regular
commentaries on Televisa after news officials there said he should
not continue because he had publicly suggested that they might
release inaccurate polls on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's campaign has galvanized a diverse range of Mexicans who
want what they refer to, with near-religious fervor, as ``the
change,'' an end to the PRI rule. His followers' vigor showed at
the huge rally that Fox held last weekend in that same vast plaza
in downtown Mexico City. His campaign slogan is a simple ``Now!''
describing the time when his voters want to be finished with the
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox has made problems for himself. He raised doubts about
his qualities as a statesman with a show of stubbornness in a
discussion with the two other leading candidates on live television
in May, a day his supporters call ``Black Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably his most serious error was his failure to lure more
support from Cardenas, who opposes the PRI from the left. Fox grew
impatient with Cardenas' resistance to his overtures and has lashed
him a number of times with his country-talking tongue, making it
more difficult for Cardenas' voters to cross over.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, in his own teeming closing rally in the Mexico City
square last Sunday, echoed the PRI's accusations about Fox's
campaign finances and called him a liar and an ``electoral
delinquent.'' He said hardly an unkind word about Labastida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
