<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7693 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-CARGO-THIEVES-LATINTR     06-28 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARGO-THIEVES-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORT STINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives ANA PENA in
New York at 212-499-3333 or fax at 212-499-3382; or KARL HORWITZ in
Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; or New
York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH WEYDERT at
1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``f''
financial and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By MICHAEL FABEY 
 c.2000 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MIAMI _ The port of Miami once shone like a beacon for
hijackers, thieves and cargo rustlers. Now it has smugglers headed
for the rocks.
 &HT;    New X-ray machines screen containers for drugs and other
contraband. Shipyard trucks pass through rigorous checkpoints.
Customs inspectors are more zealous than ever. At a time when cargo
crime is up nationwide by about 20 percent to nearly US$12 billion
annually, Miami is cracking down.
 &HT;    ``The port is much better than it used to be,'' says John Hyde,
the head of security for Maersk-SeaLand, one of the leading
shipping lines for the Latin American trade lanes and one of the
leading customers at the port. ``Miami is much improved.''
 &HT;    It has to be. Many drug traffickers, FBI Special Agent Tracy
Reinhold says, are switching to cargo crime because they can make
just as much money with a lot less risk. Indeed, the penalties are
not as stiff for a container of stolen microchips compared to a
container of cocaine.
 &HT;    The entry of drug traffickers and other sophisticated criminals
_ combined with an increase in the shipping of smaller and more
expensive items, like electronic equipment _ has helped change the
face of cargo crime. It is now increasingly organized and
sophisticated. Whereas before the biggest problem was pilferage
from the back of trucks (or, in rare cases, a hijacking), current
schemes include infiltrating trucking companies to create phony
invoices or bills of lading and emptying and refilling containers
in warehouses.
 &HT;    ``It's a very liquid business,'' Reinhold says. ``They steal it
one day and it's sold within the next 72 hours. It's a constant
problem, especially for major cargo hubs, like New York, Memphis
and Miami.''
 &HT;    The increased vigilance at Miami, the busiest container U.S.
port for Latin American cargo, comes amidst a national crackdown on
cargo crime. About a year ago, the FBI started Operation Sudden
Stop, which combines the efforts of 36 task forces in 29 field
offices across the United States. The agency recently came through
with 400 arrests and indictments. ``In the early 1990s, we shifted
our efforts from property crimes to gang-related crimes,'' Special
Agent Reinhold says. ``Now we are switching back to property.''
 &HT;    Last year, federal, state and local authorities busted eight
people on charges of running an international cargo crime ring. The
group allegedly stole computer parts on demand in the Miami area
and then exported them to Latin America.
 &HT;    Despite its progress, Miami is still a hot spot for cargo theft.
That's not terribly surprising. Most cargo theft occurs during the
shift of boxes from one mode of transportation to another; Miami,
as an air, land and sea transfer point, offers more opportunities
than many other gateways. That's why Miami has to work so hard to
prevent these crimes. It operates three checkpoints that truckers
must clear before they can get their cargo, and the port takes
pictures of the drivers with the paperwork.
 &HT;    But the new watchfulness carries a price. Greater vigilance has
increased delays in moving cargo through the port. Truckers,
already riled by congestion backups and rising fuel prices,
complain that the additional slowdowns cost them cargo runs and
money _ many are paid by the number of trips they make in the port.
 &HT;    Port Director Charles A. Towsley says the facility is working on
cutting down the delays and devising ways to reimburse the trucking
companies for lost time or revenue.
 &HT;    The real key, law enforcement officials say, is getting
businesses to take more firm steps to protect against cargo crime.
They need to do a better job screening employees and tracking their
cargo, from the time it leaves the plant to the moment it reaches
its destination.
 &HT;    The FBI achieves its most effective results, Reinhold says, when
the Bureau and industry work ``hand in glove.'' Indeed, that may be
best way to keep thieves' hands off cargo.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Latin Trade 
