<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PINEBEETLE0629-COX     06-28 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINEBEETLE0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's party time for pine beetles
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EATONTON, Ga. _ The voracious Southern pine beetle threatens to
lay waste to thousands of acres of Georgia's drought-stressed pine
forests, state and federal foresters warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Loblolly and short-leaf pines weakened by two years of drought
have become especially vulnerable to the insect no larger than a
grain of rice, the foresters said. The beetle infestations also are
occurring at the peak of a natural cycle in which the insect's
populations rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trigger is cocked for one of the worst pine beetle
outbreaks we've seen in years,'' said Terry Price, an entomologist
with the Georgia Forestry Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Price and other foresters are predicting the infestations this
year will be just as bad or worst than the massive outbreak during
the drought of 1988, when pine beetles killed tens of millions of
dollars worth of pines and literally changed the landscape of
portions of North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Drought makes the trees more susceptible to the beetle because
it lowers their natural defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of beetle infestation were especially heavy on Wednesday
in the 115,000-acre Oconee National Forest in Middle Georgia, where
more than 300 stands of dead pines _ known as ``pine beetle spots''
_ have been found since April. The spots range in size from less
than an acre to several acres.
</P>
<P>
   When foresters find at least one beetle spot for every 1,000
acres of pine forests, they declare a pine beetle epidemic for the
region. ``We've certainly got an epidemic here,'' said Ron
Stephens, acting district ranger at the Oconee forest.
</P>
<P>
   Inspections of several dead pines in the forest on Wednesday
revealed the backside of the bark riddled with thread-like tunnels
_ mute evidence of the pine beetle, which strikes a tree's cambium
layer that lies just below the bark and transports water and
nutrients throughout the tree. Infected pines are killed within two
to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After laying eggs in the tunnels, the beetles emerge from the
trees and spread to other pines in the area. Immediate removal of
infested trees is necessary to prevent the larvae from further
spreading the infestation when they develop into adults.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists are especially concerned that the loss of trees in
the Oconee forest, which is about 72 percent pine, will further
imperil the red-cockaded woodpecker, considered to be Georgia's
most endangered bird. The Oconee forest is home to one of the last
remaining red-cockaded populations in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The bird is the only woodpecker that makes its nest in a living
pine _ in particular mature pines that have a wood softening fungus
that makes it easier for the tiny birds to peck out a cavity to
raise their young.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the trees that the beetles are going after,'' said
biologist Liz Caldwell of the Oconee forest. ``Every tree lost here
is a setback for these birds.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Oconee National Forest, which includes large
portions of Jones, Jasper and Putnam counties, other Georgi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
