<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ARCHBISHOP-FLORES0629     06-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP-FLORES0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flores described as ``a very kind human being''
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Priests, bishops and lay people throughout Texas
prayed Wednesday for San Antonio Archbishop Patrick Flores, the
43-year Catholic cleric who has dedicated his life to promoting
peace, caring for immigrants and taking on Latino concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, the highest-ranking prelate in Texas, is known
internationally as a champion of Latinos and has created programs
for immigrants, refugees and Mexican-Americans that are considered
models across the country. He also put together an archdiocesan
television station that broadcasts Masses in Spanish throughout the
Western Hemisphere from the historic San Fernando Cathedral in
downtown San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the archbishop has lobbied heavily for anti-violence
measures, including gun control, and is an outspoken critic of the
state's concealed gun law.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, the first Mexican-American bishop in the United States,
is described as a gentle, compassionate soul who shunned security
at the the archdiocesan offices because he felt it should be open
and accessible to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in San Antonio loves him,'' said the Rev. Edward
Maddox of Sacred Heart Catholic Church in Austin. ``He is one of
the greatest representatives for the Mexican people.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores was held hostage in the chancery Wednesday, the
archbishop's administrative headquarters where he leads his flock
of more than 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Stella Trevino of Austin was in San Antonio to see
Flores realize a dream. He hosted an archdiocesan-wide Eucharistic
Congress, which featured an array of speakers talking about the
meaning of Holy Communion. ``He always wanted to do that,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was packed,'' she said of the gathering at Joe and
Harry Freeman Coliseum. The Roman Catholic Church is celebrating
the Year of the Eucharistic, and Flores seized the opportunity to
put together the gathering in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the archbishop received a standing ovation when
he was introduced by local Bishop John McCarthy at the Austin
diocese's confirmation celebration at the Frank Erwin Center.
Flores celebrated the first of two Masses on Pentecost Sunday where
more than 3,000 teen-agers received the Catholic sacrament that is
a rite of passage to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Austin and the state's 13 other dioceses are part of the
Catholic Province of San Antonio, of which Flores is the head.
Flores' archdiocesan territory includes 23 Texas counties that
stretch from Hill County, north of Waco, to the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, 70, is the seventh of nine children born into a migrant
farm-working family from Ganado, north of Victoria in Jackson
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew what it was to get up and ride the truck to sugarbeet
fields in Minnesota and Wisconsin,'' said McCarthy, who was a
seminary classmate with Flores.
</P>
<P>
   Flores dropped out of school in the 10th grade and was working
in a Texas dance hall, cleaning up the after-hours detritus, when
it came to him that perhaps there was a better path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking _ not having any visions or anything like
that _ but I said I should not go to work for smoke and stench,''
Flores said in a 1996 interview. ``That day the thought hit me
about being a priest.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished his high school education and went into the seminary
in 1949 _ the same year as McCarthy. The two were ordained into the
priesthood together in the Galveston-Houston diocese in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Flores was named auxiliary bishop in San Antonio _ the
first Mexican-American bishop. He went on to become the bishop of
El Paso in 1978 but returned to San Antonio a year later when he
was named archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage situation Wednesday wasn't Flores' first scrape with
danger. In 1976, he was attending a conference in Riobamba,
Ecuador, when armed soldiers stormed the retreat house, arresting
the 90 bishops, priests, religious and lay people attending the
event.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, believing the retreat was some kind of clandestine
meeting to take over Ecuador's government, forced the Catholics
into army buses, driving them eight hours to the country's capital
of Quito. There, Flores and the others were detained in Army
barracks until the next day when the U.S. Embassy intervened and
got 50 foreigners released.
</P>
<P>
   Flores and the four other Americans among those were ``invited
to leave'' the country, said Tom Quigley, policy adviser on Latin
American affairs for the U.S. Conference of Catholic Bishops in
Washington, D.C., who chronicled the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Flores was one of four U.S. bishops selected to attend
a special meeting of bishops at the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years before Pope John Paul II made his historic visit
to Cuba, Flores visited the Communist country in 1985 and again in
1986. The following year, Flores welcomed the pope to San Antonio.
The pontiff stayed with Flores at his residence, located on the
same chancery grounds where Flores was taken hostage Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy Wednesday described Flores as ``a very kind human
being. You can't imagine him saying anything uncomplimentary about
a person.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Flores gave $100,000 of his money to restore San
Fernando Cathedral. ``I don't have a family to support so my
expenses are not as great as yours,'' he told the congregation,
many of whom are poor immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The donation was in keeping with Flores' personal motto: ``I
will work not for myself but for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
