<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MINORITIES-HOME-OWNER     06-28 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES-HOME-OWNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES STILL LAG IN HOMEOWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Fla., Ga., Ore., Wash., Calif., Mass.)   By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the United States roars through the Year 2000 still in the
midst of the longest housing boom on record, there are disturbing
signs that minorities remain at the bottom of the homeownership
gap, according to a report issued this week by the Joint Center for
Housing Studies at Harvard University.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report found that although government loan programs directed
toward minorities have increased significantly, a greater
percentage of whites than blacks own homes, creating a gap of 25.8
percent, about the same as in 1994. Hispanics, who are fast
becoming major players in the country's housing market, still fall
23 percent below whites in terms of homeownership. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Especially in such prosperous times, these problems of
affordability are ``deeply troubling,'' said Nicolas P. Retsinas,
the center's director. ``The signs are that, yes, the gap will keep
getting bigger. The history is that in good times the gaps narrow.
But in these good times _ about the best we know of _ they have
not.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, minorities are becoming a larger part of the
population. While today 75 percent of households are white, that
number will shrink to 71 percent by 2010. There will be nearly 12
million more households, and minorities _ classified in three
groups, as black, Hispanic, and Asian and others _ will make up
nearly two-thirds of that growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard study noted that rising housing costs create pain
for everyone, regardless of race and income. Rents have risen
across the country, significantly in the Northeast and the West
where Portland, Seattle and San Francisco have posted record rents.
</P>
<P>
   Homes cost more, and so do mortgages. Adjusted for inflation,
mortgage costs rose nearly 5 percent between 1998 and 1999. Down
payments rose 3.5 percent, for an average increase of $442. House
prices hit record highs in 15 of the nation's 39 biggest cities:
only Buffalo, Miami and Rochester saw a decline in prices. But the
study found disproportionate impacts on the poor.
</P>
<P>
   As house prices and mortgage costs rise, the poor are
experiencing increased difficulty in finding homes, not only to buy
but also to rent. Ninety-thousand federally subsidized housing
rental units have been lost since the early '90s, as landlords have
opted out of federal programs, in many cases because they want the
freedom to raise rents to market levels. Housing authorities are
also demolishing public housing projects without replacing them in
equal numbers. The stock market has made fortunes for many people.
But the biggest investment for most Americans is their home. This
is especially true among homeowners who are black or Hispanic.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the face of these statistics, Darren Walker, the chief
operating officer for the Abyssinian Development Corp., which
builds housing in Harlem, says he finds it incomprehensible that
the largest lenders in New York are not writing more loans for
African-American applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The study reported that many minorities were taking out more
expensive loans _ called subprime _ which are geared to home buyers
with poor credit. The Harvard study found that such high-interest
loans had risen fivefold from 1993 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Walker contended that minority homeowners in Harlem are the
focus of intense advertising efforts by the subprime lenders;
often, home buyers _ even those with excellent credit _ do not
realize they must pay higher interest for these subprime loans than
what would be offered by a mainstream bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers reinforce our contention that the mainstream
lenders have still not fully embraced the minority communities,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said that subprime lenders, whose interest rates are
currently 1 to 3 percentage points higher than the prevailing 8\
percent home mortgage rate, at least ``allow people who wouldn't
otherwise own a home to be able to swing it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The annual Harvard report, ``The State of the Nation's
Housing,'' poked holes in the belief that home buyers and renters
alike are increasingly drawn to center cities. While some
households choose lofts and condominiums downtown, the report found
that Americans still prefer the suburbs, often with good reason:
from 1990 to 1997, jobs in the lower-density fringes of
metropolitan areas grew 19 percent, compared with only 4 percent in
the urban core.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the report said, most minority and low-income buyers
chose the suburbs. In the Northeast, a full 72 percent of
low-income buyers bought in the suburbs, compared with 60 percent
in the West. Hartford, Atlanta and Miami were the most unpopular
cities among home buyers: 85 percent of low-income borrowers in
those markets chose not to live in their downtowns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
