<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-GAYSCOUTS-HNS &LR;      06-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GAYSCOUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY SCOUTS CAN KEEP GAYS FROM BEING SCOUTMASTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a setback for gay rights advocates, a divided
U.S. Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that the Boy Scouts of America
has a First Amendment right to bar homosexuals from serving as
scoutmasters.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision, announced on the last public day of the
court's term, said New Jersey's goal of enforcing its civil rights
laws and preventing discrimination against gays is trumped by the
Scouts' constitutional right to free association and free
expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forced inclusion of an unwanted person in a group
infringes the group's freedom of expressive association if the
presence of that person affects in a significant way the group's
ability to advocate public or private viewpoints,'' Chief Justice
William Rehnquist wrote for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   While Rehnquist said the court was not endorsing the Scouts'
anti-gay views, he said making the group accept a gay Scout leader
would unfairly ``force the organization to send a message, both to
the youth members and the world, that the Boy Scouts accepts
homosexual conduct as a legitimate form of behavior.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The ruling reversed a unanimous decision by the New Jersey
Supreme Court, which found that the Scouts illegally fired
assistant scoutmaster James Dale, an Eagle Scout, when it
discovered through a newspaper article in 1990 that he is gay. That
court said Dale's expulsion from Troop 73 in Matawan, N.J., was
based on prejudice and was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts appealed, saying that allowing an openly gay troop
leader would undermine the group's rules calling for members and
their leaders to be ``morally straight'' and ``clean.'' But Dale
argued that he never tried to express his views on homosexuality
and pointed out that the Scouts allows pro-gay rights heterosexuals
to serve as Scout leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Dale, 29, expressed his disappointment during a news conference
in New York, where he works as an advertising director for POZ, a
magazine targeted at readers who are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I learned anything during my years as a Scout, it was to
believe that justice will prevail,'' he said. ``America realizes
that discrimination is wrong, even if the Boy Scouts don't know
that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale's lawyer, Evan Wolfson, from the New York-based Lambda
Legal Defense and Education Fund, said the Scouts had won ``the
dubious right to be bigoted and exclusionary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have convinced the highest court in the land, and have
shown the rest of the country, that they stand for
discrimination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gay and Lesbian Task Force also criticized the high
court's decision, which it said ``should lead no one to believe
that discrimination against gay, lesbian, bisexual and
transgendered people is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We renew our call on the (Scouts) to model `moral
straightness' by ending its shameful exclusion of youth and adults
who are different,'' said Elizabeth Toledo, the group's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   But the Scouts and other groups hailed the court's decision as a
victory for the First Amendment and for private organizations
seeking to maintain control of their membership criteria and
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe an avowed homosexual is not a role model for the
values espoused in the Scout Oath and Law,'' the Irving,
Texas-based Boy Scouts said in a statement posted on its Web site.
``We respect other people's right to hold differing opinions and
ask that they respect ours.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It is not the role of government to decide who should share a
pup tent with the Scouts, who is fit to be a scoutmaster, and what
message the Scouts should deliver about homosexuality,'' said Jan
LaRue, senior director of legal studies for the Family Research
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Supreme Court had ruled the other way, it could have
forced the NAACP to accept a Ku Klux Klan member, the B'Nai Brith
to accept Catholics, and the Knights of Columbus to accept Jews as
members and leaders,'' she added. ``Every private association would
have had to look like and believe whatever the government said.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Shackelford, chief counsel of the Liberty Legal Institute,
which filed a friend-of-the-court brief in the case, said Americans
are ``safer and freer'' now that the court has ruled in the Boy
Scouts' favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Boy Scouts were not able to define themselves by their
own moral constraints,'' he said, ``then neither could any other
private association, including religious denominations and
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   In deciding the case, Rehnquist, who was joined by Justices
Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony Kennedy and Clarence
Thomas, invoked a 1995 decision permitting organizers of Boston's
privately run St. Patrick's Day parade to exclude a gay rights
group from marching.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice John Paul Stevens, who dissented along with Justices
David Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer, said the case
was more analogous to the court's decisions requiring civic
organizations such as the Rotary Club and Jaycees to include women
members.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens wrote that the New Jersey law ``does not impose any
serious burdens'' on the Boy Scouts, ``nor does it force (the
Scouts) to communicate any message that it does not wish to
endorse.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that homosexuality has gained acceptance in the
United States in recent years. Rehnquist agreed, but said that's
even more reason to protect groups such as the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment protects expression, be it of the popular
variety or not,'' the chief justice wrote. ``And the fact that an
idea may be embraced and advocated by increasing numbers of people
is all the more reason to protect the First Amendment rights of
those who wish to voice a different view.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who is honorary president of the Boy Scouts,
said during a news conference at the White House that the Boy
Scouts are ``a great group.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the country should continue to move toward greater
inclusion of gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the country has moved a long way, and I'm proud
of the things that we've been able to do, and I'm disappointed we
haven't been able to do more in some areas,'' he said. ``But I
think we're moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, spokeswoman for George W. Bush, who was on the
presidential campaign trail in Ohio, said the Texas governor
supports the decision because it is consistent with his belief that
private organizations should be able to set their own standards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Houston Chronicle reporters John Henry and Julie Mason contributed
to this story. &UR; )
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
