<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MARCHING-BANDS-2TAKES     06-28 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARCHING-BANDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING OOMPAH IN THE KEY OF WHATEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A memorial service for a famously self-destructive
performance artist is about to start, and out on the sidewalk on
the Lower East Side of Manhattan, the sousaphone player for the
Hungry March Band is teaching the tenor saxophonist a new song. No
sheet music is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to repeat five notes,'' Scott Moore, the man with
the big horn, tells Emily Fairey. ``The first three notes everybody
drew out of a bag, different notes for everyone. The fourth note is
a collective B flat. The fifth note is your choice. It's sort of a
tribute to his idea of random chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairey nods like a veteran pitcher. ``Got it.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, the band files out of the community center,
trailing mourners. The new song, powerful as it is simple, seems to
hold the sunlit air still _ three slow chords, noirish and
Mingus-y, rising to the clear, piercing B flat, improbably heroic,
then dissolving into the final random chord, dense and mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   The band strikes up an improvised funeral march, greasy and
soulful, something out of New Orleans by way of Eastern Europe, and
steps off in no particular formation. Up Eldridge and onto Houston,
children cling to fences to watch the motley band go by, young
couples stare down bemused from tenement windows, and hipsters
slurping iced cappuccinos sway in front of cafes. Everyone smiles.
Everyone loves a parade.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-20th century, outdoor bands, whether marching or
stationary, played a vital role in American civic life, adding
celebratory notes to every public ritual from a judge's
installation to a saloon opening. Bands still roam the streets in
places like India and Peru, but outside of Louisiana, professional
marching bands have all but vanished from the American landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a passe thing,'' said Joe Losh, an 81-year-old trumpeter
who leads the John Philip Sousa American Legion Post Band in
Manhattan and who recalled running from one parade to the next on
the day Franklin D. Roosevelt announced the National Recovery Act.
``The old guys don't want to march anymore. The young guys are into
rock 'n' roll; they don't want to march. All you got left is the
high school bands, and once they graduate they give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Siegel, a band leader active in Local 802 of the American
Federation of Musicians who is sometimes asked to put together
marching bands for parades, could not name a single year-round,
semi-stable professional marching band in the city. There was, he
and Losh said, simply not enough work anymore to keep a marching
band busy.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungry March Band, a quasi-anarchist collective of 10 to 25
musicians, dancers and twirlers of widely varying abilities from
the arty streets of the Williamsburg neighborhood in Brooklyn, beg
to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always someone who needs a marching band,'' said
Theresa Westerdahl, 28, one the band's four drummers and its de
facto manager.
</P>
<P>
   In the three dozen or so shows _ about 15 of them paid _ that
the band has played in the last year, it has led a pet store's
parade of dogs, marched naked across a long white table at a
dot-com mogul's millennium party in TriBeCa, serenaded marathon
runners and commandeered subway trains at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The band marches mostly in its own community and in the
radical-friendly East Village and Lower East Side. But it has also
done the twist in Times Square to protest the city's restrictive
cabaret laws, blessed a church's Thanksgiving feast in Queens, and
rallied anti-World Trade Organization troops in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The band will play for just about anyone. Last fall, the day
after providing sonic support at a Manhattan demonstration against
the homogenizing forces of Starbucks and Disney (purse: $200), the
band played the opening of a mini-mall in Williamsburg ($400). The
mall is no Wal-Mart _ its boutiquey shops are all owned by locals _
but band members were amused to hear themselves accused of selling
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the political stuff the band does tends to be a
little shrill, so it was kind of nice to be able to do the opposite
and not be so partisan,'' said Jon Lewis, 36, an artist who plays
the marching mellophone, a sort of trumpet-shaped French horn.
</P>
<P>
   The band's music is a strange blend. Into it go the mixed
musical resumes of its members _ lapsed school band nerds, a jazz
trumpeter who has played at the Blue Note, a drummer for a
hard-core punk band, veterans of New York's experimental-noise
scene, and a few near-beginners. Out flows a ragged but usually
coherent sound, full of passion and surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all these kinds of personalities rubbing up against each
other, and this is what happens,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The dress code is similarly loose. A few members wear actual
marching-band uniforms scavenged from thrift shops, but they are
just as likely to parade in purple robes or white skullcaps or
feathers. The band's only nod to militarism is its ever-present
flag, depicting an ear above a crossed knife and fork.
</P>
<P>
   Jenneth Webster, the producer of Lincoln Center Out of Doors,
who has booked the band for opening day on Aug. 5, compared Hungry
March to the Arkestra, the band led by the late cosmic jazz genius
Sun Ra, who claimed to have descended to Earth from Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that every musical ensemble is unique, but they're
really unique,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the band's shows evolve into audience participation
events. At a march against trash transfer stations in Williamsburg,
an old man abandoned his walker and pounded on a piece of sheet
metal that was being carried in front of the band. At a winter
celebration in the East Village in January, someone in the crowd
handed out sleigh bells.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People love the marching band,'' said Sasha Sumner, a soprano
saxophone player. ``No matter what we're doing you have a big group
of people who want to join in just from hearing it for a second.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the results can be disorienting. But the music seems
able to accommodate a lot of chaos.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so public that you can't really tell people they can't
play,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   The band, originally a four-piece, formed in 1997 to play the
Coney Island Mermaid Parade, one of the city's freakiest annual
public spectacles. (The name, bestowed by a departing founding
member, refers both to the band's will-play-for-food business
strategy and to a deeper hunger for something raw and real.)
</P>
<P>
   Then in the spring of last year, an opportunity arose for the
band to play at a sex-industry convention at the Javits Center.
Westerdahl, a massage therapist by day, put up recruitment posters
around the neighborhood to fill out the sound.
</P>
<P>
   The selection process was simple. ``Whoever kept coming got to
stay in the band,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Javits Center gig fell through, but the band took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would do clandestine marches in the neighborhood,'' said
Moore, a 40-year-old carpenter with a linebacker's build and an
Amishman's beard, ``just to take it to the South Side,'' the still
largely Hispanic section of Williamsburg. ``To see the smiles on
people's faces, the little tykes, the tough guys on the corner
digging it, too, really made me take notice of what a generous
thing this was, and that's when practices got regular.''
</P>
<P>
   Practices are happenings in themselves. Sunday afternoons,
members gather on an enormous concrete slab overlooking the East
River in the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn, set in a marsh
dotted with Stonehenge-size chunks of bulldozed industrial
buildings. (If it rains, they adjourn to a spot under the
Brooklyn-Queens Expressway.)
</P>
<P>
   A few Sundays ago, two teen-age boys hacked their way through
the weeds and watched two women in midriff-baring T-shirts juggle
flaming torches while a tumbler practiced splits on the
glass-strewn concrete. A stranger wandered past playing bagpipes,
and Sumner and one of the trombonists tootled over to check him
out.
</P>
<P>
   A Hasidic family walking down by the pier made a detour up onto
the concrete, drawn in by the snaky, vaguely klezmer-like strains
of a waltz, ``Whack Clown,'' which Lewis wrote for the memorial of
the performance artist Mark Ashwill.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the band improvised everything, but it found that
structures somehow emerged and congealed. Soon members were writing
tunes on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with the presence of songs,'' Moore said, as if
discussing an infestation.
</P>
<P>
   The band even plays a couple of non-original numbers, though
neither is a staple of the American band repertoire _ a World War
II Italian Partisan anthem, ``Ciao Bella,'' and an Indian movie
soundtrack hit called ``Disco Bhangra.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every performance is stellar. At a recent Sunday march
through the East Village, starting at 10 a.m., the band, including,
for the first time, Fairey's 3-year-old son, Sammy, on toy trumpet,
sounded peevish, a brown stew of blats and thumps. The bass
drummer, Doug Anson, walked close to cars and banged loudly,
setting off their alarms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little early in the morning for us,'' Sumner conceded
afterward.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The band has faced other problems. One time, Moore's spats got
hooked together and he fell horn first into Avenue A. As he lay
helplessly tangled, all his change spilled out of his pockets and
children descended on him and stole it.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at a Halloween parade in the East Village, he got
tangled in his spats again and fell onto Jeremy Obviren, the snare
drummer. Fortunately, Obviren was wearing a foam praying mantis on
his head.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, though, things turn out as they did on the
day of the memorial service for Ashwill last month. When the band
reached Tompkins Square Park, three kindergarten-size girls emerged
from the crowd and started dancing and jumping in time to the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ashwill's former dance partner, DD Dorvillier, walked
up and thanked the band tearfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard them I thought they were really fruity,
really crazy,'' she said later. ``But today, as soon as I heard
those chords in the brass I started to cry. That piece was like
digging your heels in the dirt to take a big shovelful of dirt and
throw it over your shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed them to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
