<HEADLINE>
IBM SUPERCOMPUTER WILL PUT MORE BANG IN NUCLEAR TESTING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LETITIA STEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A supercomputer three times faster than any to date
and with a footprint the size of two basketball courts is on its
way to the Department of Energy to make possible nuclear testing
without so much as a bang.
</P>
<P>
   The ASCI White supercomputer, unveiled by IBM Wednesday, is
capable of processing 12.3 trillion calculations per second. It
would take someone 10 million years to do that number using an
ordinary calculator.
</P>
<P>
   And chess players beware: ASCI White is 1,000 times more
powerful than ``Deep Blue,'' the computer that beat World Chess
Champion Gary Kasparov in a highly publicized 1997 match between
man and machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant development in pushing forward the
technology, and we view this as just a step,'' said Jim Jardine,
IBM program manager.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight trucks are transporting the ASCI White system _
which weighs as much as 17 adult elephants _ to the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratories in California, where it will be
used simulate the explosions of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ASCI White was developed through the Department of Energy's
Stockpile Stewardship Program. The $110 million supercomputer is
part of a series of ever-faster computers the program needs to
monitor the aging of nuclear weapons without underground testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see whether or not it actually goes boom'' using computer
simulations, said David Cooper, chief information officer at the
Livermore lab.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a computer as powerful as ASCI White over 20 days
to perform the calculations necessary to simulate the detonation of
a nuclear weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The department hopes to have the technology to simulate the
entire aging process of stockpiled nuclear weapons by 2004, when a
computer eight times as powerful as ASCI White is slated for
completion.
</P>
<P>
   While ASCI White will be limited to classified usage, its
unprecedented computing power is expected to lead to advances in
other fields _ such as weather forecasting, biological engineering
and drug design _ as IBM makes the technology available for
commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the computer community must learn how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Computer science professor Ken Kennedy, director of the Center
for High Performance Software Research at Rice University in
Houston, cautioned that ASCI White's mega-fast processing
capabilities are only as powerful as the software it runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real achievement here is making a machine that is actually
balanced in a way that can run applications efficiently,'' he said,
referring to the common problem of not having the software needed
to take advantage of a supercomputer's power.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he expressed optimism that the technology will one day
let scientists simulate physics at its highest complexity, from
studying water tension on the surface of an aircraft to the folding
of protein structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to mean better science, better engineering and, in
the end, a better life,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
