u f BC-GANNETT-CENTRALNEWSPA     06-28 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANNETT-CENTRALNEWSPAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANNETT BUYS CENTRAL NEWSPAPERS FOR $2.6 BILLION IN CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gannett Co., whose stable of newspapers is already the
largest in the country, announced Wednesday that it has agreed to
acquire Central Newspapers Inc., the owner of The Arizona Republic
and The Indianapolis Star, for $2.6 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   That price tag makes the deal the second largest in newspaper
history, after the recent purchase of the Times Mirror Co., which
publishes The Los Angeles Times, by the Tribune Co., which owns The
Chicago Tribune, for $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition marks the end of the long reign of the Pulliam
family, the descendants of Central's founder Eugene Pulliam, a
conservative publishing clan whose members include Dan Quayle, the
former Republican vice president. The family has long been a
political force in Indiana and Arizona _ one investment banker
pointed out that neither state observes Daylight Savings Time
``because Eugene Pulliam always refused to change his clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Weil III, chairman and chief executive of Central, said
last night that the sale to Gannett is an acknowledgment that
Central simply lacked the scale necessary to be successful in
today's market of large media properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were too big to be small and too small to be big, as a
public company,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas McCorkindale, president and chief executive of Gannett,
said in a statement that the company expects to operate Central's
newspaper properties ``in keeping with the high standards
established by the Pulliam family.''
</P>
<P>
   To effect the deal, Gannett is offering to buy all of Central's
publicly traded Class A stock for $64 a share. The stock, which has
risen 118 percent since the company put itself up for sale three
weeks ago, closed Wednesday at $64.25, up 12.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, which is based in Arlington, Va., is also offering to
purchase Central's Class B shares for $6.40 a share. A Pulliam
family trust, which owns just under 83 percent of those shares and
thus controls approximately 78 percent of Central's shareholder
votes, has granted Gannett an option to purchase its shares. The
remaining 17.2 percent of the Class B shares are owned directly by
members of the Pulliam family.
</P>
<P>
   Under Indiana law, which governs in this case, a shareholder
meeting will not be necessary if at least 90 percent of each class
of stock is tendered to Gannett, explained Eric Tooker, Central's
general counsel. If a shareholder meeting is necessary, the Pulliam
trust's shares alone are sufficient to ensure that the merger will
be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett already publishes 89 daily newspapers worldwide,
including USA Today, the nation's largest-selling weekday
newspaper. It announced on June 8 that it plans to acquire 21
additional daily papers in Louisiana, Maryland, Ohio, Wisconsin and
Utah from the Thomson Corp. for $1.125 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett also operates 22 television stations, including KPNX-TV
in Phoenix, where both Central's home office and one of its key
properties, The Arizona Republic, are based. According to Gannett,
the transaction does not involve the transfer of any broadcast
licenses, and therefore does not require the approval of the
Federal Communications Commission. However, if the federal
cross-ownership rules, which govern the ownership of multiple media
outlets in a single market, have not been modified before KPNX's
license is up for renewal in October 2006, Gannett would need a
waiver from the F.C.C. to continue owning both the television
station and the Phoenix newspaper, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett's share price has slipped in recent days amid
speculation that it would be bidding for the Central properties,
which had become increasingly expensive as Central's stock
strengthened. Market analysts speculated that investors feared
Gannett would pay too much for the Central properties.
</P>
<P>
   The price Wednesday is roughly 11.8 times Central's expected
earnings in the current year, before interest, taxes and
depreciation, only slightly higher than the value given to the
Times Mirror's earnings in the Tribune Co. deal. If Gannett is able
to trim costs _ by eliminating Central's corporate overhead, for
example _ the price would represent an even better value, one
analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is an excellent one for Central's shareholders, said
Thomas Russo, a partner in Gardner Russo Gardner, which is listed
as Central's second largest institutional shareholder. ``But my
dream outcome would have been to get Gannett stock at this price,''
said Russo, who said he thinks the purchase ``doesn't change the
bright prospects for Gannett.''
</P>
<P>
   Central was advised in the deal by Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. advising the Pulliam family trust.
Gannett did not employ an investment banking firm for the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
