<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CANADA-CARS-ONLINE-NY     06-28 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CARS-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD AND TOYOTA TEST THE SALE OF CARS ONLINE IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Canada has become a laboratory for the automobile
industry's experiment with selling cars to consumers over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian subsidiaries of Ford Motor and Toyota Motor have
established test Web sites to let consumers in three regions of the
country log onto the Internet to buy vehicles _ tests that could
foreshadow the companies' global strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Though all automakers maintain Web pages for product and other
information, car buyers in Canada can use the Toyota site to
compare brands, pick the model and options they want, get a price
for their trade-in vehicle, arrange financing and place an order
through a participating dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians who have tried the test Web sites seem to like
them, at least partly because there is no bargaining with a
showroom salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a haggler, and I don't like to feel that I'm being
taken advantage of,'' said Kathryn Tessier, a 38-year-old
chiropractor in Brandon, Manitoba, who bought a new Toyota Solara
coupe in March through the Web site. ``This way, there's a
bottom-line price _ it's the same deal for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   An appealing feature, Tessier said, was the ability to see how
different options affected the price. That led her to buy a coupe
instead of her original choice, a convertible. She was also able to
compare financing plans easily. She then took a test drive at a
local dealer, Precision Toyota in Brandon. ``I had to see the
car,'' she said. ``I just couldn't order it over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although car manufacturers are venturing into Internet sales
slowly, the idea is nothing new. E-commerce car-dealer specialists
like CarsDirect.com and carOrder.com have expanded quickly in the
United States, and cars4u.com is about to begin operations in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Online sales of new and used cars in the United States amounted
to $19 billion last year, about 3 percent of the total market,
according to Gomez Advisors, a research firm in Lincoln, Mass. But
it says that by 2002, Internet auto purchases will exceed $140
billion annually, almost a 20 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   Such a potentially huge increase in sales is an important reason
why the automakers are at least testing the business of selling on
the Internet, in cooperation with conventional dealers who feel
threatened by their online competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car companies control the market through dealers, and as
Internet players gain more control of the purchasing process, it
will be tougher for dealers to maintain their profits and their
relationships with buyers,'' said Dennis DesRosiers, a
Toronto-based automotive consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Internet car dealers do not see it that way. Barry Shafran,
president of cars4u.com, said the automakers' programs would appeal
to ``consumers who are not educated _ it's still the dealers who
are setting prices.'' Internet car retailers, he pointed out, need
to own dealerships themselves to buy new vehicles from automakers.
And orders placed through manufacturers' Web sites are routed
through a dealer, usually one selected by the buyer. Someone from
the dealership also has to make one house call to get a signature
on an order form and perhaps another to deliver the car.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. of Canada Ltd. recently began a larger test
program than Toyota's, with 24 participating dealers. It is selling
only three brands online _ Focus, Taurus and Windstar _ in two
regions of Ontario: the populous Niagara Peninsula in the south and
around the federal capital of Ottawa in the east. Toyota is selling
in one region, the area around Winnipeg, Manitoba, with eight
dealers participating.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford contends that its BuyerConnection program is the
only ``direct-order-to-the-manufacturer automotive Web site
available today,'' it, too, is set up for sales through dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that Canadians spend as much time on the Internet
as Americans do but that they are more timid online shoppers and
that 80 percent of those who buy cars hate dickering over price.
The Ford and Toyota Internet projects eliminate price negotiations.
Participating dealers provide what are described as discounted, or
competitive, market prices.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the manufacturers expect many more shopping visits
than buying visits to their Web pages. ``But by the time they
arrive in the dealer's showroom they are going to be pretty well
armed with information about the vehicle they are going to buy,''
said Stephen Beattie, a spokesman for Toyota in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're modernizing the way we do business,'' he said. ``We're
not trying to move to direct sales. But consumers want more
information up front, and this is a tool for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford says its program is an ``integration of the bricks and
clicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Total activity on Toyota's Web site increased 40 percent in the
first month of the Internet sales test, Beattie said. It will
probably become available across Canada in the fall. In the United
States, Toyota Motor Sales has begun a similar test project in the
Seattle-Tacoma area, with 19 dealer participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
