<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-UGANDA-POLITICS-ART-N     06-28 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UGANDA MUST CHOOSE POPULAR AUTOCRAT OR DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9-11 were sent on June 27 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda _ Once there were few places in Africa as grim
as Uganda, now there are few as hopeful. The man who claims the
credit is campaigning hard for voters to reward him in perhaps an
odd way: He wants them to admit that Uganda is still backward and
not yet ready to open up to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   President Yoweri Museveni is balder and bulkier than when he was
a bush fighter, his once-brilliant reputation dulled recently at
home and abroad. But he is still the man who brought Uganda back
and did so with a certain steady charm _ on full display the other
day when a group of college students heckled him for more than 20
minutes as he tried to give a speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a chance to talk,'' he said. He leaned back and
scratched his nose patiently, waiting for quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not how democracy works,'' he lectured the hecklers
here at Makerere University. ``Democracy works by hearing and then
deciding in a calm way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few months Museveni, 56, has been lecturing not
only students but also all Ugandans on his version of democracy.
And on Thursday voters will decide between two political systems:
whether to continue with the ``Movement,'' which Museveni
champions, or switch to a multiparty system, outlawed since
Museveni fought his way to power in 1986 after two violent decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Movement is what Museveni calls a no-party state. It is an
umbrella group with the goal of uniting all Ugandans (its symbol is
a big yellow bus) and to which all Ugandans theoretically belong.
His argument is that political parties divide Ugandans by tribe and
religion -_and that those splits gave rise to leaders like Idi Amin
and Milton Obote, whose reigns ended the lives of tens of thousands
of Ugandans. Now, even after 14 years under his rule, Museveni says
Uganda has still not matured enough politically or economically for
the return of political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried having a lot of parties but we failed,'' he said in
Luganda, the language of Uganda's largest tribe, the Baganda, at a
recent campaign rally just outside Kampala. ``We messed up with bad
leadership. It's up to you people to decide whether you want to
move with the Movement or move with the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But a growing column of opponents say the Movement is becoming a
one-party state in disguise. Some go so far as to call Museveni its
new-style dictator. Under law, political parties can exist in name,
but they cannot hold rallies or conventions or field candidates for
office. Real democracy, opponents say, requires more than one
political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excuse, a pretext,'' said Paul Ssemogerere, leader of
the Democratic Party and a former presidential candidate against
Museveni. ``You have ethnic divides in America. When Dukakis ran
for president, the Greek community was enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have WASPs, the Jewish vote, the Latino vote, the black
vote,'' he added. ``But is that an argument against democracy? If
anything, it is a point for democracy that you are able to give
voice to all communities. That is the beauty of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt how this referendum will turn out.
Ssemogerere and other leading opposition figures have called for a
boycott, and their rallies are filled with people who say they will
not vote. So it seems certain that the Movement _ headed by a
still-popular Museveni _ will win.
</P>
<P>
   But with elections for president and Parliament coming next
year, the real questions will be Museveni's margin of victory and
the percentage of Uganda's 9.6 million registered voters (the total
population is about 23 million) who come out to vote. The results
will give both Museveni and his opponents vital clues for the
national mood as they focus on the contests next year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the referendum comes at a telling time for Uganda and in
some ways Africa itself. To the nation's credit, foreign diplomats
and other observers say, the peaceful campaign in Uganda contrasts
sharply with Zimbabwe, led by a long-serving former guerrilla
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time of so much pessimism about conflict and corruption
around Africa, Museveni has been campaigning as his image abroad _
and with many of his own constituents _ has hit a low because of
his nation's participation in the war in Congo. Museveni has for
years been considered one of Africa's most progressive leaders. He
liberalized the economy, invested in the infrastructure and in
education and stressed African self reliance. He stood first among
a ``new breed'' of African leaders praised several years ago by
President Clinton (all of whom subsequently dragged their nations
into war).
</P>
<P>
   But in August 1998, he and his neighbor to the south, Rwanda,
supported rebels seeking to overthrow Congo's president, Laurent
Kabila. Even if Uganda can convince the world that its reasons are
good _ rebels who attack Uganda are based in Congo _ it has been
harder to justify its behavior. Soldiers are accused of rank
profiteering, dealing in diamonds, timber and gold.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, troops from Uganda and Rwanda have themselves clashed
three times in the Congolese city of Kisangani _ most recently this
month when both sides rained down shells indiscriminately, killing
what aid groups said was at least 600 people, mostly civilians.
Even the United States, often accused of being too lenient with
Uganda, strongly condemned Museveni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congo has to some extent caused his performance to be
re-evaluated,'' said one Western diplomat here, who asked to be
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Though the result of the referendum does not seem in doubt,
Museveni has been campaigning ferociously. He has visited nearly
all of Uganda's 45 districts and recently has spent hours on radio
programs answering call-in questions.
</P>
<P>
   While the referendum is supposed to be between two systems,
Museveni has made it very much about himself and his performance.
He reels off the accomplishments not of a political system but of
his government: providing more electricity, making primary
education essentially free, opening the economy to foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
   He jokes that life has improved so much that poor farmers use
mobile phones while hoeing their fields. He says that the work is
far from done, and that continuing the Movement is the only way to
keep improving.
</P>
<P>
   But his opponents say that the glass of Uganda is really half
empty. Poverty and unemployment remain high. The Congo war is
unpopular. Museveni, they say, gets more autocratic each year (he
may run for only one more five-year term). He seems tolerant, they
say, but that disguises a harder side. Several protesters at
Makerere were arrested and beaten up.
</P>
<P>
   From students in Makerere to clerks in small towns, Ugandans
themselves do not seem excited about the referendum, now that the
nation has become accustomed to voting. Turnout to civic education
classes has been low. Many Ugandans do not see their choice as
clear as either Museveni or his opponents portray it.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally for the Democratic Party, Edith Namutebi, 22, said
she liked Museveni but not the Movement, which she said is not open
enough. So she will not be voting. A few feet away, Mbuya Faisal,
26, said he was not voting, but gave an opposite reason: He agrees
with Museveni that multi-parties will divide the nation by tribe.
After 14 years, he is merely tired of Museveni and thinks he should
not make the mistake of so many African leaders _ staying in power
too long.
</P>
<P>
   For many young people like them, the evils of Uganda's past are
only a hazy memory, and as time goes on, it will become harder to
sway voters based on that. Just shy of half all Ugandans are under
the age of 15, nearly all born since Museveni became president. l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7724 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-RELIGSCHOOLS-H     06-28 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RELIGSCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SCHOOLS WIN ROUND BEFORE SUPREME COURT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday allowed the federal
government to continue providing computers to religious as well as
public schools, saying the national program does not violate the
constitutionally mandated separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a 6-3 decision, said the Education Department's
effort to ensure that all students have computers is a neutral
program under which the federal government neither endorses nor
repudiates the sectarian messages taught at parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling clears the way for the federal program to
continue unimpeded in Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi. The 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers the three states, had
ruled in 1998 that the program violates the First Amendment clause
prohibiting the government from endorsing religion.
</P>
<P>
   Americans United for Separation of Church and State said the
court ``took a sledgehammer'' to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based group said the ruling means that taxpayers
will continue to support federal assistance to religious
institutions, a governmental use of revenue that the First
Amendment was designed to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in Supreme Court history that the
justices have allowed a resource to be given to parochial schools
that can readily be diverted to religious purposes,'' said Barry
Lynn, the group's executive director. ``At public expense,
religious schools can now have students surf the Internet to read
the bible in religion classes ... or download crucifixes as screen
savers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Family Research Council praised the court's decision,
saying that fairness dictates that all students, even those in
religious schools, be provided with computers and other secular
materials that aid in their education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government does not have to discriminate against religion
in order to satisfy'' the Constitution, said Jan LaRue, senior
director for legal studies at the Washington-based council.
``Taxpayer dollars should be distributed equally among all
schoolchildren, regardless of what their religious beliefs are.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they upheld the program, the six justices in the majority
could not agree on exactly how much assistance government officials
can provide to parochial schools without violating the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the justices said officials should have wide latitude to
provide learning devices to all educational institutions on an
equal, ``neutral'' basis. Justice Clarence Thomas expressed this
view, in an opinion joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But the two other justices in the majority, Sandra Day O'Connor
and Stephen G. Breyer, said their colleagues'
governmental-neutrality test for upholding parochial-school
assistance programs was too broad, potentially enabling the
government to assist sectarian study unconstitutionally.
</P>
<P>
   For example, religious-school teachers, under the relaxed
neutrality standard, would be able to use the government-supplied
computers in teaching expressly religious courses, O'Connor wrote
in an opinion Breyer joined.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the religious school uses the aid to inculcate religion in
its students, it is reasonable to say that the government has
communicated (an unconstitutional) message of endorsement,''
O'Connor added. ``Because the religious indoctrination is supported
by governmental assistance, the reasonable observer would naturally
perceive the aid program as government support for the advancement
of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   To be constitutional, the governmental aid program to parochial
schools must have safeguards such as official overseers to ensure
that the computers are not being used for religious education,
O'Connor said. She added that the Education Department's program
provides such protection.
</P>
<P>
   In dissent, Justice David H. Souter said the federal program
should be struck down because, contrary to O'Connor's view, no
adequate safeguard exists to ensure that teachers at parochial
schools will not use the computers for sectarian study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where religious indoctrination pervades school activities of
children and adolescents, it takes great care to be able to aid the
school without supporting the doctrinal effort,'' Souter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joining his dissent were Justices John Paul Stevens and Ruth
Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling marked a defeat for public-school parents in
Jefferson Parish, La., who had challenged the constitutionality of
the government's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit had agreed with the parents, saying that the
government's provision of computers unconstitutionally assisted
parochial schools in their religious mission. But the federal
government and religious-school parents successfully appealed to
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
