<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS GORE HAS HIS OWN OIL CONNECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Who is more tarred by the big oil companies and
therefore more responsible for the high price of gasoline? That was
the burning question in the presidential contest on Wednesday as
both Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore campaigned in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The latest accusation came from Bush, who said that although
Gore had accused him of cozying up to big oil, it was really Gore
who was doing so because he had proposed extending a tax break to
the industry for deep-water drilling in search of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp replied that this was a foolish accusation, and
that the tax break provided an incentive for natural-gas
exploration, which could help increase domestic supplies, reduce
dependence on foreign oil and thereby cut energy prices for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was the latest in an escalating back-and-forth as
each candidate tried to paint the other as less likely to fight to
reduce the price of gas at the pump. Polls show that gas prices
remain Americans' No. 1 concern as they take their summer
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   The prices have risen most sharply here in the Midwest, in the
states most up for grabs in the presidential election. Both
candidates have encouraged a federal investigation into gasoline
prices, which have exceeded $2 a gallon in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would encourage the foreign oil producers to
increase the supply of crude oil and the domestic industry to
increase exploration, including in the Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge. Bush also wants to deregulate utilities to spur demand for
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore laid out a sweeping plan on Tuesday to reduce dependence on
foreign oil. It would provide more than $125 billion in tax breaks
over 10 years to businesses that provide cleaner forms of energy;
one proposal would extend the moratorium on royalties paid by
natural-gas companies while they drill under the Gulf of Mexico.
The moratorium is scheduled to expire in November.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop here on Wednesday, Bush, a former oil
executive and the recipient of $1.5 million in campaign
contributions from the gas and oil industries, told reporters: ``My
opponent is giving major oil companies a huge tax break. I believe
a royalty moratorium ought to happen when the price declines. We
ought not to have moratoriums when the prices are high.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore, said that the tax breaks
would help bring down the cost of fuel and that Bush's position
showed his true colors because it aligned him with the oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This policy provides an incentive to increase domestic energy
production, reduce our dependence on foreign oil and cut energy,''
Hattaway said. ``Bush clearly favors big oil at the expense of
cheaper, cleaner forms of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has received less than $100,000 in contributions from
oil and gas interests, has been casting Bush as the darling of big
oil and more likely to look out for the industry than for the
average consumer. So it was with some zeal that Bush and his aides
seized on the chance to portray the vice president as the one
giving the industry a break.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush went further. He suggested that the oddity of the vice
president's call for tax breaks for the oil industry was emblematic
of a candidate who would ``say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush used both a sledgehammer and a scalpel to make his point.
</P>
<P>
   First, the sledgehammer: ``Al Gore yesterday apparently said he
never made comments about raising prices of gasoline, yet in his
book, `Earth in the Balance,' he advocated higher taxes on fuel use
and he supported a B.T.U. tax, which would raise gasoline prices on
people,'' Bush said. ``When you tax energy, it raises the cost. He
advocated it, strongly advocated it, two such measures, and now
that the political heat is on he's changing his tune. Changing his
tune. He advocates for raising taxes, raising gas prices, and he
denies he ever did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the scalpel: ``This is another example where he doesn't
know the meaning of `raise,''' Bush said. This was a reference to
Gore's quibbling over the definition of the word ``raising'' _ as
in money _ in his April 18 sworn testimony about his fund raising.
</P>
</TEXT>
