<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM IKE TO CLINTON, KNIGHT KEEPS WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The winner, and still champion . . . Helen Knight.
</P>
<P>
   El Caballero's remarkable 70-something has done it again,
winning the women's championship at the Tarzana country club for
the 38th time in 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   This time she won the four-week, four-round gross tournament by
14 strokes, pulling away in the final round despite opening play
that day with a triple bogey.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth consecutive title for Knight, who won her first
El Cab championship in 1956 _ that victory launching a string of 32
straight titles. Not bad staying power for someone who took her
first golf lesson from Tommy Armour as a University of Michigan
student during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' said Knight, whose title tenure has extended
through the administrations of 12 presidents. ``I had two good
rounds and one round that was not so good. But everybody else had
more than one not-so-good round.''
</P>
<P>
   Others will speak more for the modest but extremely hard-working
Knight:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of new lady members and it seemed she might have
a battle this year,'' longtime El Cab member Gene Cofsky said.
``But you have to see the way Helen works. She's so dedicated. She
plays Tuesdays, practices Wednesdays and Saturdays, plays Thursdays
or Fridays, plays Sundays . . . and I'm not so sure when the course
is closed on Mondays she doesn't go somewhere else to play. Not
many have her dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's amazing,'' said head pro Mark Taylor, who said Knight's
strengths are accuracy, wedge play and consistency. ``She can go
out there and shoot 85 every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Others speak as supportively with their actions. The El Cab
women honored Knight this year by initiating the Helen Knight
tournament. That net-score event was held the week before the club
championship _ which for nearly a half century has been the
unofficial Helen Knight tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting harder,'' said Knight, whose stretch of club
championships has brought her a letter of congratulations from
Arnold Palmer. ``I'm getting older and they're getting younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, as famous at El Cab for her work ethic as her
championships, is not content just to repeat a swing that has
proven a winner. She continues to fine-tune her game and has been
working recently with North Ranch teaching pro Laura Hurlbut, a
former LPGA Tour member who has helped simplify Knight's swing.
</P>
<P>
   I feel my swing is more consistent,'' Knight said, ``not based
so much on timing. I'm really excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret to her success?
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice and play,'' she said. ``It's the only way you can do
it. You can't eliminate one of those steps and keep your game
intact.''
</P>
<P>
   How long can Knight stretch this remarkable run of club
championships? She said she doesn't really think about it, focusing
instead on the game at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just keep plodding along, do the best you can and try not
to make any dramatic errors,'' she said. ``I was thinking this year
there are younger people coming in and I'm getting older, but you
just keep trying. The worst that can happen is you lose. That's not
so bad. I've had a good run.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The name sounds familiar: The new head pro at Burbank's De
Bell GC is former Notre Dame High star Scott Scozzola, 24, son of
longtime De Bell head pro Phil Scozzola, who is now the club's
Director of Golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grooming him to take over,'' said the elder Scozzola, who
has been at De Bell since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who went on to New Mexico State to study professional
golf management, has since done stints at Oakmont and Saticoy
country clubs before joining his father at the hillside course in
Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   __ Knights to remember: Scott Scozzola is one of two former
Notre Dame golfers making a move upward in their profession. Kyle
Kovacs, Scozzola's teammate on the Knights in 1993 and now a
playing pro out of Tierra Rejada, has a first and four seconds in
six minitour tournaments this month.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tiger tickets: Tickets are now available for the Williams
World Challenge, featuring Tiger Woods and 11 other PGA Tour
players in a 72-hole tournament at Sherwood Country Club, Nov. 27
through Dec. 3. Prices range from $65 for a tournament-long pass to
$10 for day passes. Information: (714) 816-1806.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keeping it in the family: Scott Golditch won this year's
men's championship at El Cab, his second and the third for his
family in four years. Brother Todd won in 1998, the year after
Scott's first club title.
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Brian Edick, who just completed his
sophomore year at Hart High, shot 38-33_71 in the opening round of
the American Junior Golf Association's Langdon Farms Junior
Classic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
