<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-SFCHRON-COLUMN </SLUG>
  
Select Examiner Staffers to Be Answering Questions for a Change &HT;     By DAN FOST  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A select group of reporters and editors at the
San Francisco Examiner will be hearing soon from investigators
hired by the Hearst Corp. to look into whether the paper
compromised its coverage to further Hearst's interests.
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein said yesterday that the
investigators submitted a list of names to Hearst officials in New
York, and Hearst gave the names to Bronstein.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst announced the investigation in May, after Examiner
Publisher Tim White testified during an antitrust trial that he had
offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable treatment on the paper's
editorial pages in exchange for the mayor's support of Hearst's
efforts to buy The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Although White almost immediately recanted his testimony, it
caused an uproar in journalism circles and Hearst hired former
federal Judge Charles Renfrew to conduct an ``unlimited'' inquiry
into the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein said he will not be involved in the investigation and
does not expect that his staff will withhold information from
investigators just because he and other higher-ups know that
they're on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I know everybody who is on the list,''
Bronstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the fact that there's an initial list suggests
the scope or number of people being interviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   A journalism professor said yesterday that such a list does not
necessarily mean the investigation is compromised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally understandable that you would think it might
taint the investigation,'' said Jack Doppelt, a lawyer and an
associate professor at Northwestern University's Medill School of
Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is a recognized prosecutorial technique: You go to
everybody and you make it known, we want everybody to come to us
knowing that the boss is not going to get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein _ who, according to White's testimony, was at the
fateful lunch with White and Brown _ said he expects to be
interviewed. ``My bosses know I'm an interviewee, and that's not
going to stop me from telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had agreed last August to buy The Chronicle for $660
million. That agreement was due to expire yesterday if the deal had
not been consummated, but because the antitrust trial had delayed
the closing, Hearst and Chronicle Publishing Co. said they will
extend the deadline to August 31.
</P>
<P>
   THE GATE OPENS UP: Here's a novel effort at employee retention:
double pay.
</P>
<P>
   SFGate.com, the online arm of the San Francisco Chronicle, is
offering its 40 workers a bonus if they stick with the company
until its eventual merger with the Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Each week that the deal doesn't close, an
amount equal to that worker's pay for the week is placed into
escrow. If the employee is still around at the time the merger is
consummated, the employee gets the entire sum.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA29 (104109 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  If the merger isn't complete in December, everyone gets a check,
and the plan gets re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Examiner is offering its employees a cash
incentive to stick things out. Bronstein confirmed the deal, but
not the amount, said to be $2,000 for full-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   John Coate, general manager of SFGate, confirmed the arrangement
at his company. ``The competition for talent has never been
greater, that's for sure,'' Coate said.
</P>
<P>
   POST-POSTHOC: Posthoc, an irreverent, lively Web guide to San
Francisco, is holding a wake tonight to mark its second anniversary
_ and the end of production. But don't buy it a plot in the dot-com
graveyard: Posthoc isn't a failed business.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it wasn't a business at all. The site was an
all-volunteer, no-advertising labor of love launched by Susan
MacTavish Best out of her Pacific Heights home two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still run on a clunky old computer, Posthoc _ the name is Latin
for future _ attracts 6,000 to 10,000 unique visitors each day.
</P>
<P>
   Best, 26, quit her job at a public relations agency, took a
class in Web publishing at San Francisco State University, found
five volunteers, and Posthoc was born.
</P>
<P>
   The site offered reviews of restaurants, bands, plays, movies
and more, generally giving a fresh, real-person's view of what to
do in the city. It also featured a range of eclectic writing,
everything from an essay on how to blow the perfect bubble to humor
columns by former Herb Caen pal Strange de Jim. It grew to 100
contributors _ all unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, ``I need to take a little rest,'' Best said. ``I
woke up the other morning and thought, for something that's started
as a hobby, it's gotten huge and out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Best will move the content to another still-unnamed site and try
to figure out a way to use the Posthoc domain to create a viable
business.
</P>
<P>
   She'll be bringing people together at 6:30 tonight at Backflip,
601 Eddy St., San Francisco. But in the Posthoc tradition, it's not
a typical Silicon Valley party: ``We are certainly not paying for
your drinks,'' Best said. ``You can go schmooze off another
dot-com.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SKINNY ON SKINNY: I was on the prowl. I had already noticed
on my own that Skinny DuBaud, the _ dare I say? _ fictitious gossip
columnist on Cnet's News.com, had ceased his frequent updates and
was only dishing his Silicon Valley dirt roughly every other month.
</P>
<P>
   Then I got the tip: Cnet was looking for new writers to give
voice to Skinny. I talked to News.com Editor Jai Singh and his
sidekick, Executive Editor Jeff Pelline, but they stuck to the
story that Skinny was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   So I sent an e-mail to Cnet reporter Paul Festa, who rumor had
it was Skinny's alter-ego. It would be natural that Festa doesn't
file many Skinny columns; he's a part-timer who writes about
hackers and viruses.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MEDIA29 (104109 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  I wanted to ask Festa himself, but he was, suspiciously enough,
on an actual vacation. So I waited for his return.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Skinny surfaced. His latest column didn't
mention me by name, but I knew it was me, all right, when he griped
about ``one of those old-media types ( &LR; peskius &LR; 
 &LR; paleojournalist &LR; )'' who had been nosing into his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I waited. Finally this week, Festa returned. I e-mailed
my question: What have you done with Skinny?
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is preposterous on its face,'' Festa replied.
``Skinny is perfectly able to take care of himself, even if his
fondness for Scotch whisky and Cuban cigars occasionally prevents
him from meeting his deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please also keep in mind that while I am the designated
assistant to his secretary Trixie Pixel, everyone on the News.com
staff helps Skinny out with tips and items.''
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE, GARY: Gary Brickman, a journalist who helped pioneer
the use of video on the Internet, died in his sleep at his San
Francisco home last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Brickman, 38, worked for NBC Internet in San
Francisco as managing editor for broadband. Brickman was a fixture
on the tech scene, arriving in his wheelchair and getting at the
personalities behind the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drove this beat-up old van all over the Bay Area and went
to every event and every trade show,'' said Jeff Pundyk, who was
his editor at CMP Media's Internet publication TechWeb. ``He knew
everybody. He was such a distinguished figure _ he was one of the
most recognizable personalities in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to  &LR; fostd &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of MEDIA29 (104109 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
