<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PCEXPO-SFCHRON &LR;      06-28 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCEXPO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   Breakthroughs to help those who need portable power &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a schlepp being a road warrior. But life is
about to get easier for mobile professionals, if some of the new
technologies on display here at PC Expo live up to their promise.
</P>
<P>
   Ultralight notebooks with an astonishing eight hours of battery
life and wireless Internet access that's three times faster than
56K dialup are two breakthroughs that could transform being a
digital nomad.
</P>
<P>
   The notebooks are the first to use the new low-power Crusoe chip
from Santa Clara, Calif.'s Transmeta Corp. Running at speeds up to
700 MHz, Crusoe is more power-efficient than other microprocessors,
as well as cooler so it doesn't require a built-in fan, according
to Transmeta.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, Hitachi, Fujitsu and NEC all showed technology demos of
Crusoe-based laptops in Transmeta's shipwreck-themed booth. None
are yet committing to when _ or whether _ they will deliver laptops
with the technology, although they acted coyly optimistic about
their lightweight (3.5 pounds or less) prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   IBM showed a version of its ThinkPad 240 with a 600-MHz Crusoe
chip. While the current model, which is now based on a 500-MHz
Pentium III or Celeron 450, gets four hours of battery life with
standard business applications, the Crusoe prototype is getting
more than seven hours, according to David Nichols, manager of IBM
Mobile Computing.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said it is likely that IBM will come out with a Crusoe
notebook in the second half of the year. Pricing would be
comparable to that of the current ThinkPad 240, which is $2,399.
</P>
<P>
   But IBM would market the Crusoe laptop to the entrepreneur and
education markets, rather than the much &LR;   &LR; larger corporate world.
That's because the Crusoe chip achieves its low power consumption
by moving some functions to software, rather than hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nichols said IBM's testing has not shown any
compatibility problems, he thinks corporate users would be
concerned about whether the new approach would adversely affect
legacy applications.
</P>
<P>
   Bob O'Donnell, an analyst with research firm IDC in Mountain
View, Calif., agreed. ``Corporate IS managers are extremely
conservative and I think they'll be very hesitant to jump to a
whole new processor architecture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even AMD had a hard time trying to make any inroads, and AMD
is directly derivative (of chip leader Intel).''
</P>
<P>
   And Intel, which had a mammoth booth right next to Transmeta's,
isn't standing still. Last week, it announced the Mobile Pentium
III, a chip that will directly compete with Crusoe.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Sony and Toshiba are already shipping laptops
based on the new chip. A lightweight Sony notebook is getting five
hours of battery life, an Intel representative said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PCEXPO29 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But at Toshiba's booth, Steven Andler, vice president of
marketing for portables, said the new Intel chip extends battery
life by only about 15 percent. Toshiba's Portege 3480 gets three
hours of battery life using the new chip.
</P>
<P>
   Transmeta may have an edge over Intel for at least one market:
Linux enthusiasts. Linux guru Linus Torvalds is an executive with
Transmeta. Although all the prototype laptops were Windows systems,
theoretically they could run Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Crusoe isn't just for laptops. Transmeta is pitching it for
``information appliances'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   It showed off sleek prototype Web pads, similar to those Gateway
and America Online might produce under their recent deal with
Transmeta.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of options for staying connected on the road,
most of them mediocre. Users who want full-speed Internet
connections can seek out phone lines and dial up to nationwide
ISPs, which will get them online at 56 Kbps.
</P>
<P>
   Those toting personal digital assistants, two-way pagers and
cell phones can tap into wireless networks at speeds under 8 Kbps,
adequate for sending and receiving e-mails, sans attachments and
browsing simplified text-only Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Some airports and hotels are beginning to install wireless
Ethernet connections that in turn connect to high-speed options
like T-1 lines, a great solution for the lucky folks who visit
those particular airports and hotels and who have wireless Ethernet
cards.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Gatos firm Metricom says it may have a better idea. For
five years, the company has offered a radio-based network called
Ricochet in the San Francisco Bay Area, Seattle and Washington,
D.C., operating at about 28.8 Kbps, half the speed of a dialup
modem. It's drawn 30,000 users, many of them devotedly loyal to the
service that unleashed them from their offices.
</P>
<P>
   Now Metricom is spending $1.5 billion to roll out its Ricochet
wireless network in 46 cities _ at a speed of 128 Kbps. In demos,
Ricochet's service allowed video and animations to play smoothly,
and Web searches to return quick results. Since 56K dialup
connections actually achieve throughput of about 40 Kbps, Metricom
says its solution is three times as fast.
</P>
<P>
   Ricochet users will enjoy ``an office experience untethered from
the office,'' said Timothy Dreisbach, Metricom's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The service will roll out in Atlanta and San Diego by the end of
July. An additional 19 communities will get coverage before the end
of the year. The Bay Area should be up and running with 128K
Ricochet by September. Metricom said 25 more cities will have
coverage by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage isn't just for the core cities; it's averaging
1,000 square miles in each community. In the San Francisco Bay
Area, coverage will encompass six counties that ring the bay:
Alameda, Contra Costa, San Francisco, San Mateo, Santa Clara and
Marin. The service area will stretch as far north as Vallejo,
Calif., and as far east as Antioch, Calif., and down to the
intersection of highways 101 and 85 in the South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Users will have to pay for the convenience. Modems are likely to
be about $250 to $300; monthly fees will range from $60 to $100 for
unlimited usage.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Metricom installs shoebox-size microcell
radios on lightpoles throughout its service area; about three to
five per square mile. It has wired access points, essentially big
routers, installed in every few square miles. Laptop radio modems
communicate with the poletop boxes, which in turn send packet-based
data to and from the wired boxes, which make the connection to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of PCEXPO29 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  For now, Metricom is the fastest mobile wireless solution.
Cellular companies are eager to get in on the data act. They
already offer wireless Web access, but at pokey speeds. They hope
to upgrade their networks to handle fast data traffic; the question
is how fast they can do it and what speed they can achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Metricom's service will be available through various partners,
such as MCI WorldCom and Juno Express, Juno's high-speed service.
</P>
<P>
   Metricom has a hefty war chest to help in its efforts. Last year
it landed $300 million each in backing from Paul Allen's Vulcan
Ventures and from MCI WorldCom. It raised an additional $900
million in February from public equity and debt offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Chipmaker National Semiconductor is now designing a special
Ricochet chipset that will allow devices ranging from PDAs to
laptops to come with built-in Ricochet capability.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, users can buy external modems about the size of a
pack of cigarettes, or PC Card modems that slide into a laptop
slot.
</P>
<P>
   With Ricochet, ``you can surf the Web or check your e-mail while
you're sitting in a meeting,'' said Gail Bronson, a senior analyst
at IPO Monitor in Palo Alto, Calif., and a Silicon Valley startup
executive. ``It lets you multitask without a connection.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said it's too bad that Metricom has stopped selling
its older modem. The current 28K service is only $30 a month; the
faster service's price ``will be a little dicey for a certain group
of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Donnell said, ``For a mobile professional, it's a dream
come true. One twenty-eight always on, that's a great way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of PCEXPO29 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
