<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
BofA Exec Announces Early Resignation &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The last top-ranking executive from the old Bank
of America resigned yesterday, turning the reins of the bank's
corporate and global banking unit over to his successor-in-training
more than a year early.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murray, who weathered the takeover by North Carolina's
NationsBank, will leave his post as president of Bank of America
Global Corporate and Investment Banking on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Brown, the division's deputy head, will succeed Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said the timing of his announcement _ he wasn't expected
to leave the bank until late 2001 _ had to do with both personal
and professional reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Brown took on more responsibility this summer as part of a
transition plan outlined in January. As that happened, ``I realized
it's not in my ability to be happy and functional as a fifth
wheel,'' Murray said. ``And I know if I was taking over (the
division) I wouldn't want me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 56, said family commitments also played into his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year banking veteran said he will spend time replanting
his Sonoma vineyard and ``enjoying eating my own cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray downplayed the fact that his departure is the beginning
of a new era for the bank, which was taken over by NationsBank,
based in Charlotte, N.C., 19 months ago. Murray joined BofA in
1994, when the company bought Chicago's Continental Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new company, and the new company is going to continue
to change and evolve and this is part of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BOFA29 (42141 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Murray was the last remaining executive from the original Bank of
America, based in San Francisco. After the acrimonious NationsBank
takeover, many San Francisco executives, including chief executive
David Coulter, were forced out.
</P>
<P>
   Murray insisted that the same fate hasn't befallen him.
</P>
<P>
   But one industry watcher was more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``NationsBank is an organization that has a pretty significant
old boys network associated with it, and obviously, as part of Bank
of America, Mike wasn't part of that,'' said Lawrence Cohn, an
analyst at the New Jersey brokerage Ryan Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his outsider status at the combined bank, Murray's unit
thrived.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the corporate bank earned $2.6 billion of the bank's
total $8.2 billion in profits _ a solid 18 percent return on
equity. In the first quarter of this year, the division earned $960
million, a 26 percent return on equity.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said the unit's headquarters will remain in San
Francisco. The division employs about 4,400 in the San Francisco
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn said he didn't expect Murray's resignation to have any
sizable impact on the bank.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``It will have an effect on morale in that
unit. Mike was a popular guy who was well respected and well
liked.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BOFA29 (42141 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
