A7733 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON &LR;      06-28 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
Providian to Return Millions &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Credit card giant Providian Financial Corp.
agreed yesterday to pay more than $305 million to settle charges it
cheated customers, a devastating rebuke to one of San Francisco's
biggest and fastest-growing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the San Francisco district attorney's office,
the California attorney general and federal bank regulators ends a
yearlong probe of the company that uncovered ``a web of deceptive
and misleading business practices,'' District Attorney Terence
Hallinan said in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, as earlier reported, Providian will set
aside a minimum of $300 million to repay customers who were fooled
into buying products they didn't want. The nation's sixth-largest
bank credit card issuer will also pay the city a $5.5 million fine.
The company didn't admit wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most significant consumer recoveries in the
history of the United States,'' said California Attorney General
Bill Lockyer, whose agency signed the agreement though it wasn't a
party to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   For the federal Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the
agency that supervises nationally chartered banks, the case
represented a bold assertion of its authority over consumer
matters. The agency cited for the first time federal trade laws
barring unfair and deceptive practices as the basis for its action,
taking it beyond the narrowly drawn consumer regulations it has
traditionally enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're utilizing a tool nobody has used before,`` said First
Senior Deputy Comptroller Julie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Providian agreed to make a sweeping series
of changes in its direct mail and telemarketing sales techniques
over the next 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company will have to describe how products such
as credit protection work before it enrolls customers, not after it
has signed them on. Providian's credit protection program lets
customers skip payments if they lose their jobs or become disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, prosecutors and regulators from the Office of the
Comptroller of the Currency must approve certain Providian sales
scripts for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Providian officials said the company settled the case to remove
a cloud that has hung over it since the district attorney's
investigation came to light more than a year ago. Prosecutors said
they began their probe after receiving hundreds of customer
complaints about Providian's sales tactics.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters, Chief Executive Officer
Shailesh Mehta said the company has already put in place
wide-ranging changes in its sales methods.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PROVIDIA () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Providian's willingness to accept harsh sanctions was ``a
business decision,'' Mehta said. He said the company didn't do
anything wrong, but ``needed to lay this matter to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming to terms ``was a very tough decision for me,'' he added.
``I wanted to fight it. I had to let go of my emotional side.''
</P>
<P>
   The company still faces consumer lawsuits in state and federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement mainly covers alleged deception in the sale of
two products: credit protection and balance transfers from other
card issuers.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who believe they were victimized won't have to contact
the company. Under the supervision of prosecutors and bank
regulators, Providian will have to identify and compensate clients
who may have been harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's legal woes mark the biggest challenge the company
has faced since it was spun off in 1997 by its former parent, a
Kentucky insurer also known as Providian. Since the spin-off,
Providian has been one of the area's fastest-growing nontechnology
companies, specializing in extending credit to customers who have
scant or troubled borrowing histories.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company's earnings zoomed 85.6 percent to $550.3
million as it nearly doubled revenue. Much of those gains came from
peddling fee-based products, such a credit protection. Providian
operates huge call centers in Pleasanton and other locations where
batteries of telemarketers use hard-sell tactics to pitch products
such as credit protection.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's backers have said the company's sales methods
weren't any worse than those used by many other banks and card
issuers.
</P>
<P>
   The company was a Wall Street favorite until news of the
district attorney's investigation caused the stock to plunge. It
has never fully recovered. The company's shares rose $2.07
yesterday to $85.07, well below the high of $131.62 posted last
year.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts said the restrictions on Providian will have
little affect on its profits, others insisted the company will be
handcuffed in the marketplace. The company may sell fewer products
such as credit protection if customers have a chance to think about
what they are buying, the analysts warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe they will be able to sustain the rate of
growth they've had,'' said Kathleen Shanley, a credit analyst with
the firm Gimme Credit, which rates corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PROVIDIA () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
