<HEADER>
A7735 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-ARCHBISHOP-HOSTAGE-TE     06-28 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP-HOSTAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHBISHOP RELEASED AFTER NINE HOURS AS HOSTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The archbishop of San Antonio, Texas'
highest-ranking Roman Catholic, spent nine hours as a hostage
Wednesday before being freed unharmed by a man facing deportation
and claiming he carried a live grenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``God came down with a smile on his face for us today,'' San
Antonio Police Chief Al Philliphus said in announcing the release
of Archbishop Patrick Flores and the arrest of his captor shortly
after 7 p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, 70, who suffers from chronic back pain, was placed on a
stretcher and taken to a hospital for observation.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-taker was identified as Nelson Antonio Escolero, 40,
who also goes by the name of Carlos Cruz. He was booked into jail
pending a variety of charges, including terroristic threats,
unauthorized detainment and possible weapons charges, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The grenadelike device he threatened to detonate was confiscated
and was being examined Wednesday night to determine whether it was
real.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of deportation apparently stems from Escolero's
criminal past, which includes marijuana possession, burglary of an
automobile and unauthorized use of a motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Escolero, whose wife and three children were on the chancery
grounds throughout the ordeal, was described as distraught over
possible deportation and said he chose to take Flores hostage
because of the archbishop's sympathy to human rights causes,
Philliphus said.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in the negotiations came when authorities
obtained documents related to the case and faxed them, as
instructed, to the archbishop's office, Philliphus said.
</P>
<P>
   Flores then explained them to Escolero, and the man kept his
promise to release him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no desire to hurt the archbishop,'' Philliphus said.
</P>
<P>
   The police chief praised Flores as courageous and a skillful
negotiator who participated in talks with hostage negotiators
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty smooth today,'' Philliphus said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, believed to be from El Salvador, took Flores and his
secretary hostage about 10 a.m. but released the woman about two
hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Catholics mingled outside the chancery throughout the
day, praying nonstop for the safety of the country's first
Mexican-American Roman Catholic bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the sake of his sorrowful passion, have mercy on us and on
the whole world,'' they repeated in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Pytel, an office manager in the chancery, was among the 100
or so people evacuated at 10:15 a.m. She stayed nearby all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were determined to keep the vigil and support our
archbishop,'' Pytel said. ``We waited, we watched, we prayed and we
hoped. And we were so relieved that it all ended peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of police, FBI agents and SWAT officers surrounded the
chancery shortly after Flores and his secretary, Myrtle Sanchez,
were taken hostage. About 100 employees of the chancery were
quickly evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Before Flores' release, Kenneth Thompson, executive director of
the San Antonio Community of Churches, prayed for the man to
release the archbishop unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken hostage the man who probably cares the most and
is most willing to listen,'' he said. ``One of his known strengths
is his ability to stay quiet and to listen. He is a humble person
and he is willing to sit there and listen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he wants this to end very peacefully,'' said the Rev.
David Garcia, an associate of the archbishop since 1970, when
Flores came to San Antonio as an auxiliary bishop. Garcia said.
``He probably wouldn't even want the man arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said Flores will be 71 on July 26 and is in good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``His only complaint are some lower back problems,'' Garcia
said.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop was among several American and Latin-American
Catholic clergy detained in 1976 by military leaders in Ecuador.
Flores was placed under house arrest with the others.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Eddie Bernal is a San Antonio native who grew up a
half-mile from the scene of yesterday's crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been very accessible, very kind and very
compassionate,'' Bernal said of the archbishop. ``He will give
anybody an audience at any time he is available. He will continue
that practice, God willing. I don't see him changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of the archbishop's release was met with cheers and
tears among onlookers at the chancery, many of whom had been there
throughout the 90-degree afternoon heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is proof that the miracle of prayer works,'' said
Louisette Zuritha, 25, a San Antonio Catholic school music teacher.
``We are all so relieved. He is a wonderful, wonderful man.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, negotiators reported that they could hear
Flores ``in the background'' as they chatted with his captor.
</P>
<P>
   Although the man claimed to be armed with a grenade, Sanchez saw
only what she could describe as a weapon, said Monsignor Larry
Stuebben, who spoke to the woman after her release.
</P>
<P>
   Flores and his secretary were taken captive when a man entered
the archbishop's office on the third floor to discuss an
immigration problem in Spanish, said Richard Yzaguirre, general
manager of Catholic Television.
</P>
<P>
   While the man did not raise his voice, he ``was pretty insistent
he wanted him to help him with this problem,'' Yzaguirre told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The man was ``very frustrated by the way he's been treated, and
wants the archbishop to help him,'' Stuebben said Sanchez reported
shortly after her release.
</P>
<P>
   Stuebben quoted Sanchez as saying, ``He said only that he wants
a great variety of papers saying he has been mistreated by various
segments of government.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancery office complex serves as the diocese's local
headquarters and sits on about 40 acres that includes Assumption
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II stayed at the complex when he visited San
Antonio in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Leticia Nieto, who lives near the chancery, watched the drama
from a front stoop with her mother, Kata Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done so much to help this community, and not just the
Catholics,'' Nieto said. ``He helped fund music programs for
inner-city kids and sports programs and all kinds of things. He is
an amazing man.''
</P>
<P>
   Kata Flores described the archbishop as humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not put himself above you,'' she said. ``He will meet
with you at your level.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
