<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-NYT &LR;      06-28 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A SELECTION': A DANCE OF SURREAL IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Japan)   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alas, the first program in Pilobolus Dance Theater's
new season at the Joyce Theater is more or less a bust. The
exception among the four pieces on Tuesday night was ``A
Selection,'' created last year in collaboration with Maurice Sendak
and Arthur Yorinks, directors of the Night Kitchen, a children's
theater company.
</P>
<P>
   As an artist, Sendak has contributed not only a backdrop (a town
aflame in the scary but compelling style of his book illustrations)
but also an outside eye. ``A Selection,'' a phantasmagoria on a
Holocaust theme, was commissioned by the American Dance Festival,
which just awarded the company its Samuel H. Scripps-American Dance
Festival Award for achievement in modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   The piece is full of enigmatic images with surreal and
fearlessly tossed bodies. They are stunningly rendered by the
troupe, especially Otis Cook as the rubber-legged personification
of evil. Above all the work does not share divorce between ideas
and movement as evident in the rest of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tsu-Ku-Tsu,'' a New York premiere, had all the earmarks of a
work created on assignment. The springboard was a match between
Pilobolus and Leonard Eto, a Japanese musician who takes a
contemporary approach to the taiko drums, which are familiar from
tours of Kodo drummers. Eto had approached the Dance Umbrella,
producer of experimental dance in Boston, for a collaborative
project and was commissioned to work with Pilobolus.
</P>
<P>
   This was not an outlandish choice: one of the group's early and
best duets was ``Shizen,'' accompanied by the haunting melody of a
Japanese flute. But Alison Chase, who choreographed the new piece
with help from the dancers, was faced here with percussion and
rhythm. The beat and reverberation at the core of Eto's complex
performance onstage are too dominant for the Pilobolus style.
</P>
<P>
   This is movement that usually banks on the linkage and leverage
of bodies, which are reduced here to an image to two mini-sumo
wrestlers locked in a hold. Elsewhere the choreography tends toward
mere gymnastics without the metaphoric dimension one expects from
Pilobolus.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of transformation nonetheless informs the initial image
after Eto raises an arm to strike a big hanging drum before he
moves on to the small drums. As Steven Strawbridge's lighting
changes from near-obscurity, three crouched figures in Angelina
Avallone's short kimonos are revealed to be six dancers (three on
the backs of three others).
</P>
<P>
   A faster beat sends them rolling and tumbling on the floor.
Springs in the air, cartwheels and dives precede the sumo duet for
Cook and Gaspard Louis. Matt Kent and Benjamin Pring are part of
some entangled clusters: Rebecca Anderson and Josie Coyoc, first
leaning head to head, arch into backbends that leave them legs up.
</P>
<P>
   Some might see their grouping as a plant. Objectively, it is one
of several isolated episodes. The end recalls the old nightclub
acrobatic adagio acts: upright performers supported in a fanny lift
by a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Femme Noire,'' choreographed by Chase in collaboration with
Anderson and Rebecca Stenn, was a sketch on an
angst-behind-the-glamour theme. Anderson, as a fashion model doing
the backstroke on the floor and playing with a picture hat, did her
best with a minimum of material.
</P>
<P>
   The sincerity behind ``Gnomen,'' a male quartet, is not in
doubt, but neither is its sanctimonious tone. Cook, Kent, Louis and
Pring each took turns as the protagonist either succored or stoned
by the others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
