<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7745 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CUBAN-BOY-CUBA-1STLD-     06-28 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-CUBA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DECISION PERMITS ELIAN GONZALEZ TO RETURN TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2nd graf to correct ``schoolmates'' to ``schoolchildren'')  
(EDS: This replaces the earlier CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU and is
now the A1 story.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ with LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Hours after the U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear any
more arguments in the Elian Gonzalez case, the 6-year-old left
behind seven months of contention, conflict and court battles, and
returned home to Cuba Wednesday with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian arrived to the embrace of relatives and the excited cheers
of hundreds of flag-waving schoolchildren. A crowd of students
hurriedly bused in from their hometown of Cardenas waved flags and
chanted: ``Elian! Elian!''
</P>
<P>
   They arrived just in time to meet the two planes that ferried
Elian, his father and other friends and relatives from Washington.
Moments later, his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, carried the boy
off the plane and into the arms of his grandparents, including his
two grandmothers, who had made an unsuccessful journey to reclaim
the boy in January.
</P>
<P>
   As the boy was swept up in the arms of his grandfather, his
schoolmates began singing the Cuban national anthem, as the
television announcer described the scene
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the torture they said Elian would be subjected to,''
the announcer said, referring to the claims by Cuban-Americans that
the boy was being returned to a grim fate. ``That is passion. That
is affection.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the excitement of the small crowd at the airport, Elian
was quiet, waving at times to his friends. No public remarks were
made, and Cuban officials did not plan any news conferences or
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   President Fidel Castro did not greet the child at Jose Marti
International Airport, being represented instead by Ricardo
Alarcon, the president of the National Assembly, who has guided the
campaign for Elian's return. The airport ceremony lasted only 10
minutes before the child and his entourage were whisked off in a
caravan to an undisclosed location for a long-awaited reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The homecoming was subdued, with no other rallies or marches
taking place in the city. But Cubans were reminded of the
importance of Elian's return, much the same way that Castro had
seized on it as a case of national respect, and a way to win points
in his long battle with the United States. In countless past
rallies, the case had been used to criticize the trade embargo, the
conservative Cuban American National Foundation and the Cuban
Adjustment Act, which grants asylum to Cubans who reach U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   As national television broadcast the caravan leaving the
airport, the voice of Elpidio Valdes, Elian's favorite cartoon
character, took over the narration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome, Eliancito,'' he said. ``Now we have to keep the
battle against the Cuban Adjustment Act, the blockade and the
foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian, his father, his stepmother, Nersy, and his half brother,
Hianny, left Dulles International Airport in Virginia at 4:41 p.m.,
just hours after the Supreme Court declined to hear arguments
presented by lawyers for Elian's relatives in Miami that the child
had been denied a right to an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   As Elian and his family made their way to the airport,
television viewers watched a strikingly familiar scene from the
vantage of helicopters as the motorcade snaked its way along
traffic-free highways, a white Suburban in the lead. The coverage
was reminiscent of the white Bronco chase at the start of the O.J.
Simpson murder case in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a failed crossing from Cuba drowned Elian's mother
and 10 others and left the boy floating alone in an inner-tube off
the Florida coast. The Supreme Court's decision Wednesday was the
final development in a series of court challenges brought by
Elian's Miami relatives, who cared for the boy after he was rescued
last Thanksgiving until immigration agents reunited him with his
father in late April.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the announcement in Washington Wednesday that
Elian could go home, Cuban radio and television interrupted their
programming to proclaim the boy's impending arrival once the
injunction that kept the child and his father in the United States
expired at 4 p.m. All day, announcers praised Elian as a heroic boy
and model child, whose father showed courage and dignity throughout
the custody battle. Pastoral music played softly in the background
as images of Elian hugging his father or frolicking with his
friends in a pool slowly dissolved on the screen, giving way to an
image of the Cuban flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian had to return,'' said Roberto Perez Martinez, who was
drinking a beer with some friends in the Playa section of Havana.
``When a child is caught in the middle, people get upset. At 17 if
he wants to go on a raft, it does not matter. But today he must
come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was to go from the airport to a reunion with relatives and
friends at an undisclosed location. From there, he would go for an
undetermined period to a special school in Havana, where teachers
and psychologists would prepare him for his return to Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the airport, Elian's father, said in brief
remarks that his experience in the United States had been a good
one. He said he hoped Cuba and the United States would strengthen
their ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all my family's suffering, I think that this has
allowed me to meet very beautiful and brilliant people in this
country,'' Gonzalez said. ``And I hope in the future, this same
impression I took from this country, can become true between Cuba
and the United States.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, asked at a news conference whether he had any
reservations about Elian's return home and his administration's
role in the outcome, said Wednesday that he had replayed it all in
his head many times, and concluded that his administration did the
proper thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I wish it had unfolded in a less dramatic, traumatic way
for all concerned?'' Clinton asked. ``Of course, I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, he said, is the father's right to be with his
child, and the fact that Gonzalez was found to be a ``good'' and
``loving father.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's rescue and the attempts of his Miami relatives to keep
him in the United States unleashed an international drama that
complicated the United States' relationship with Cuba. In the end,
the drama embroiled the White House, stirred up the presidential
campaign, revitalized Fidel Castro and tarnished the standing of
the politically powerful Cuban-American population in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   And in a twist that few could have anticipated, the case, and
its handling by Cuban-Americans, helped galvanize support in the
United States for more relaxed ties to Cuba. On Tuesday, Congress
negotiated a deal to permit food sales to Cuba, with restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami Wednesday, supporters of the Miami relatives gathered
outside the Little Havana house to mourn Elian's return to Havana.
A few lashed out at reporters and cursed the Clinton
administration. Many praised the Miami relatives for their
persistence, and expressed disbelief that most Americans believe
Elian belongs in Communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are devastated that at this very moment Elian's going back
to live in a country where he'll never be free, to a country where
his father will simply not be allowed to give him the freedom that
his mother, Elisabeth Brotons, wanted so desperately and died for,
to a country of tyranny and dictatorship,'' said Armando Gutierrez,
the spokesman for the boy's Miami relatives. ``But we must obey the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who had tried to persuade the Miami
relatives, face to face, to turn the boy over, wished Elian well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This little boy now knows that he can remain with his
father,'' Reno said in a statement Wednesday. ``All involved have
had an opportunity to make their case _ all the way to the highest
court in the land. I hope that everyone will accept the Supreme
Court's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department spent at least $1.8 million through June
11 on reuniting Elian with his father, assigning scores of
officials and negotiators to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The legal challenge began in Miami, where Lazaro Gonzalez,
Elian's great-uncle, petitioned the courts for custody and for the
right to request an asylum hearing for the boy. That was denied,
and Gonzalez carried out a series of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In Havana Wednesday, there were few joyous outbursts, in
contrast to the huge public rallies that had taken place across
Cuba calling for Elian's return.
</P>
<P>
   A few people sported worn-out Elian T-shirts that were worn by
hundreds of thousands at past rallies. The sprawling seaside plaza
that was specially built in January to hold demonstrations in front
of the offices of the U.S. government here was unusually empty.
</P>
<P>
   Many people quietly expressed relief that the boy was returning
after months of what they said was manipulation by Cuban-Americans
in Miami, whom they faulted for having tried to sway the child with
gifts, favors and the promise of a better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time he came back to be with his family, his people,''
one woman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
