<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RX-DRUGS-HNS &LR;      06-28 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RX-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES GOP PRESCRIPTION DRUG BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders on Wednesday pushed a Medicare
prescription drug bill through the House that has little chance of
becoming law because of opposition from President Clinton and the
health insurance companies it would rely on to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Republican members hailed the bill's passage,
217-214, as ``a red letter day'' for seniors who would benefit from
their plan to provide subsidies to insurance companies that
voluntarily offer drug coverage plans for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, however, used words such as ``sham'' and
``fraud'', to describe the plan, which was written by Rep. Bill
Thomas, R-Calif., following an intense lobbying campaign by
pharmaceutical companies designed to prevent a more generous but
more costly Democratic substitute from reaching the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic members stormed out of the House Wednesday when
Republicans adopted a rule that made the Thomas proposal the only
bill in order for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the rain under yellow and red umbrellas that read
``shame,'' the Democrats accused Republicans of trying to pull a
``hoax'' on the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are going to allow debate on only one opinion,''
said Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas. ``We will talk about nothing else
because they are afraid ... that too many of their Republicans may
side with too many of the Democrats in putting a real prescription
drug plan under Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders did lose 10 of their own on the final vote,
which was twice as many as they gained from the Democratic ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stall passage of the GOP measure, the Democrats
employed a number of parliamentary maneuvers in addition to their
walkout that delayed the final vote until late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accused them of playing election-year politics with
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them stall, let them dilly-dally,'' said Rep. Deborah
Pryce, R-Ohio. ``Americans can see through it.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also weighed in at a White House news
conference, threatening a veto if the GOP bill manages to pass the
Senate in its present form.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to consider a different drug benefit bill
in the coming weeks, and may allow some debate on a Democratic
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ``an empty promise'' to seniors who struggle to pay
the high cost of prescriptions, Clinton said the Thomas bill ``puts
special interests above the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a private insurance plan that many seniors and people
with disabilities simply won't be able to afford. Insurers
themselves say the Republican plan won't work,'' Clinton said,
citing criticism of the proposal from the insurance industry, which
has labeled it ``unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The president accused Republicans of taking up the banner of
prescription drug benefits only because their narrow six-seat
majority hold on Congress is in danger in this fall's elections.
The vote among seniors could determine the outcome in several key
races.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders stood in the way of attempts last year by
Democrats to force a vote on the issue. But during last summer's
congressional recess, while trying to sell a tax cut plan, they
found that most Americans put a higher priority on providing a drug
benefit for low-income seniors and paying down the debt than
receiving a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Republicans have been pushing debt reduction as a
priority issue and floating ``public-private'' proposals that call
on insurance companies to voluntarily provide affordable drug
benefit plans for seniors. In return, companies would receive a
subsidy paid out of a Medicare funds to help them offset the rising
costs of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Thomas plan, Medicare beneficiaries would have to pay
the insurance premiums, depending on the kind of coverage provided.
The companies would be free to set the premiums at different levels
for different parts of the country. But they would be encouraged to
provide at least two coverage choices. Thomas predicted that
premiums would average $35 to $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the bill, however, world force pharmaceutical
companies to reduce the price of drugs sold to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The Thomas plan would cost an estimated $40 billion over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Thomas plan and the Democratic alternative would pay on
average up to 50 percent of annual drug costs for seniors. But the
Republican measure would force them to spend more out-of-pocket
than the Democratic proposal, which would cost an estimated $100
billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   For catastrophic or terminal illnesses, the Thomas bill would
pay all drug costs above $6,000 a year, while the Democratic
proposal would assume all costs above $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan, which would be administered directly
through the Medicare program with the help of insurance companies,
would also establish a basic set of guaranteed benefits and costs
that would be uniform throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, attacked the
Democratic proposal as a ``one-size-fits-all'' bureaucratic
approach to curbing high drug costs for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll offer seniors only a single government-run plan and
seniors will have to take it or leave it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But one of his Texas colleagues, Democrat Gene Green, accused
Republicans of trying to promote ``a gimmick'' that appears to
provide help for seniors but really doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be putting the benefit in the hands of senior
citizens and not insurance companies,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
