<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON JUMPS TO GORE'S DEFENSE, SLAMS `BOGUS' SCANDALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton rejected assertions Wednesday
that his administration has been plagued by scandals, calling them
``bogus'' and saying the myriad investigations should not taint
Democratic candidate Al Gore's bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping to his vice president's defense, Clinton expressed
doubts that voters would penalize Gore for the legal problems that
have dogged the president, his wife, aides, Cabinet members and the
Democratic Party since he took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `scandal' has been thrown around here like a clanging
teapot for seven years,'' Clinton said angrily, waving his arms
during a White House news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these ... so-called `scandals' were bogus,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whitewater thing was bogus from day one,'' Clinton said,
referring to the five-year investigation _ still going on _ into
Arkansas business dealings in which he and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had nothing to do with the official conduct of the
administration anyway,'' the president said testily.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed out that former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy
was acquitted on charges of accepting illegal gifts from
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cisneros thing was a tempest in a teapot, totally
overdone,'' Clinton said, referring to the case in which former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros pleaded guilty to lying about
payments he made to a woman with whom he was having an affair while
mayor of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention investigations that yielded no
prosecutions against Labor Secretary Alexis Herman or Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt. Likewise, Clinton did not mention his
efforts to cover up his sexual misbehavior at the White House or
how it led to his impeachment and almost ended his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Gore has been implicated only in ``this
campaign finance thing,'' referring to fund-raising abuses in 1996
that so far have resulted in prosecutions against 21 people
associated with the administration and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   A top Justice Department prosecutor early this month recommended
that Attorney General Janet Reno appoint a special counsel to
examine what role Gore played in the fund-raising and whether he
lied under oath when questioned by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has rejected earlier recommendations that she seek an
independent investigation and has not acted on this latest one.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed assertions that Gore's recent drop in public
opinion surveys was linked to the specter raised by the possibility
of a deeper investigation into 1996 fund-raising excesses. One
recent poll showed Gore trailing Republican George W. Bush by 13
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of volatility in these polls,'' the
president said during his hourlong news conference in the East Room
of the White House. ``My best judgment is that people are still
trying to figure out what they're going to do, and sooner or later
they will.''
</P>
<P>
   When they do, voters will like what they see of Gore's record
and vision for the future, Clinton said. ``It's still more likely
than not that he will win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
