<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, JUNE 28
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(sb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CALIF-EDUC-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 25
about how the booming economy is helping California improve the
national ranking of its schools misstated the size ranking of
California's coastline (in a reference to how the state compares to
other states). Its coastline is the second longest among the 48
contiguous states, not the longest. Florida's is the longest.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GPS-UPDATED-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June 14
about the improved accuracy of the Global Positioning System
described the orbits of G.P.S. satellites incorrectly. Their
orbital positions are very precisely known, but they are not in
geosynchronous orbits (maintaining a fixed position relative to the
earth).
</P>
<P>
   The article also mischaracterized the number of satellite
signals that can be used by a G.P.S. receiver to determine
location. Four is the minimum number that can be used, not the
maximum.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
