u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-28 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FROWNING ON BRAVES' NEW FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Mets fans greet the dawn of a new day
Thursday morning with a rush of anticipation of a big showdown.
They open a four-game series with the Atlanta Braves in what can
safely be called the first critical series of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of important games coming up,'' Mike Piazza
said Wednesday. ``We're not going to put a do-or-die perspective on
this series, but this is a huge series.''
</P>
<P>
   More than the New York Yankees, more than any other National
League team, Atlanta is a franchise that has defined the Mets in
recent years; it is the franchise against which the Mets measure
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the terms of the competition are different. This
time the competition has a face, a name, a personality. The new
face of the Atlanta Braves belongs to John Rocker, the relief
pitcher whose anti-gay, anti-ethnic anti-New York comments in a
magazine article last year earned him a fine and suspension, as
well as a notoriety that has made him something of a pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is a product of the dot.com age of information, in which
every word, every image, is captured by a widening range of news
media. Devoured.
</P>
<P>
   In the long, meandering history of the Braves _ from Boston to
Milwaukee to Atlanta _ the face of the franchise has often been a
player: Warren Spahn, the Hall of Fame pitcher; Hank Aaron, the
career home run leader. During the last decade the face of Atlanta
has been its three All-Star pitchers: Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and
John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Then John Rocker decided to go off on his own and grab the
marquee billing: like Gladys Knight and the Pips, or Diana Ross and
the Supremes, it's now John Rocker and the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was stunning last season and suffocated the Mets. Near
the end of National League Championship Series the Mets began to
reach Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Harris said he believed that Rocker lost more that a few
games with his statements. He lost part of that mantle of a
closer's invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he feels Rocker may have lost some face. ``We used
to look at him: `Man, here comes Rocker. This guy, he's tough to
hit.' Then next thing you know, he comes out with something like
this. You say, `Aw man, this guy is silly. He doesn't know what
he's talking about.' He's lost some respect; he's lost a lot of
points out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw I was going to face John Rocker, I'm like, this
dude here is pretty bad. I've really got to let him make a mistake
before you can beat him. Now you're like, `forget it,' at the
plate. `I'm going to try to kill this guy.' I still feel like what
he said _ calling his teammate a monkey _ wasn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Rocker is dragging his teammates into a fray they didn't
want to be in. The team and Rocker will be protected like a
visiting premier or minister during their four-day stay in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a distraction for that team,'' Harris said. ``You
can tell by the comments his teammates make from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta with Rocker has become like a traveling medicine show,
with a beefed-up news media asking the same questions, dredging up
the same history. Rocker, attempting to hold true to character, is
still running to the mound, still pumping his fists and assuming
the bravado of the conqueror.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is how will this affect the standings. Will the
Mets lose or gain from Atlanta's distraction?
</P>
<P>
   The Rocker of this season is hardly the Rocker of old. He has 12
saves, but his control has been so inconsistent _ why isn't that
surprising _ that he was sent down to the minors earlier this month
and was brought up after a brief stay. He'll be tested as never
before during Atlanta's four games in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be exciting baseball, like a playoff
atmosphere,'' said Piazza, the Mets catcher and top hitter.
``There's going to be a lot of reaction. But we're not going to go
into this series and lose our focus on baseball. We can't worry
about one guy. You got Greg Maddux, you got Tom Glavine, Andruw
Jones, Chipper Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, unlike Harris, said he doesn't this think more or less
of Rocker as a player because of what he said as a civilian. ``I
always try to humanize my opponents,'' Piazza said. ``I've never
built anybody up, I don't build up these huge confrontation because
I get too wired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, frustrated by Atlanta for the last three seasons, must
overcome history to overcome Atlanta. Atlanta's problem is much
more deep seated. John Rocker's Braves not only need a new
personality they desperately need a face lift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
