<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ARCHBISHOP0629-COX     06-28 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Archbishop released uninjured
 &HT;    By Stephen Scheibal and Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ An armed San Antonio man fearing
deportation released one of Texas' top Catholic Church officials
Wednesday evening, ending nearly nine hours of a police standoff
and community vigils.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Patrick Flores, 70, head of the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of San Antonio, was reportedly uninjured after he was
released around 7 p.m. from his office by Nelson Antonio Escolero,
40, an immigrant from El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Escolero took Flores and his long-time secretary, Myrtle
Sanchez, 74, hostage around 10:30 a.m. Wednesday at the archdiocese
chancery, just northwest of downtown. Sanchez, who has worked with
Flores for about 30 years, was released unharmed within three
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Escolero, a legal resident of the United States, was upset over
his possible deportation for driving with a suspended license,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, after authorities faxed Escolero immigration status
papers he had requested, he allowed Flores to go free, San Antonio
police chief Al Philippus said, then placed a grenade-like device
on a table and walked out. Escolero was taken away in handcuffs and
was being held Wednesday night on two counts of aggravated
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Police later said the device was a fake grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Previous criminal convictions for Escolero, also known as Carlos
Cruz, were nonviolent: two charges of possession of marijuana,
burglary of a vehicle, unauthorized use of a motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The chief said the archbishop was tired but relieved the
situation had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Philippus said Escolero pushed Flores down early in the day, the
only physical contact between the two. Flores was taken to Christus
San Rosa Health Care hospital to be checked for possible back
problems, but otherwise seemed fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're very pleased with the outcome of this,''
Philippus said. ``God came down and really smiled on us and wrapped
his arms around the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Escolero, who has a wife and three children in San Antonio,
reportedly met Flores on the ground floor of the San Antonio
Archdiocese Chancery Wednesday morning and accompanied the
archbishop to his third-floor office. During various phone calls
during the standoff, he railed to authorities about his immigration
problems, fears of deportation, and current unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations, Escolero also raged about other
different subjects, including the return of Elian Gonzales to Cuba.
During negotiations, police brought Escolero's wife and at least
one of his children to the chancery, where officers passed messages
back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who was not available for comment Wednesday evening,
remained calm throughout the ordeal and played a key role in his
own release, Philippus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty smooth today,'' Philippus said of Flores.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who has headed the 23-county San Antonio archdiocese
since 1979, is the only archbishop in Texas. He is also head of the
Catholic Church's Texas province and oversees all the dioceses in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jimmy Drennan, who spoke on behalf of the archdiocese,
said the archbishop was in good condition physically and
emotionally late Wednesday. Drennan, pastor at St. Paul's Catholic
Church in San Antonio and a former San Antonio police officer, rode
to the hospital with Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed a lot of concern for the man and said his faith in
prayer and God and his love for life got him through it,'' Drennan
said. ``He saw himself as a pastoral agent even to him
(Escolero).''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Rosa hospital administrator Cary Fox said the archbishop
would remain at the hospital overnight for observation. He was
undergoing a number of tests Wednesday night to determine his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   A group of San Antonio police officers were questioning Flores
about the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, Escolero simply wanted to bring
attention to his concerns, officials said, and chose Flores because
of the archbishop's long support of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he got a lot of attention today,'' Philippus said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippus said police did not make any guarantees to Escolero.
Escolero and his family were forced to leave their San Antonio home
on Elvira Street about a year ago when they were unable to pay
their property taxes, said a former neighbor who asked that her
name not be used. Other neighbors said Escolero rarely socialized
with them and often worked on cars in his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the standoff, police evacuated the chancery of its
roughly 100 employees and allowed them to retrieve cars from the
parking lot about five at a time. But many of the archdiocese
employees went across the street and began a vigil on the
residential lawns facing the chancery, a light brick building with
two red columns sitting atop a grassy hill several hundred yards
from the street. Others left their keys in the building and could
not get back into their cars.
</P>
<P>
   About a half dozen people began reciting the rosary toward the
building. The crowd on the lawns swelled over the afternoon, with
concerned Catholics and other area residents.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Monod, director of the archdiocesan Office of Social
Concerns, said the crowds on the lawns reflected the love that
Flores, who faces mandatory retirement in two years at age 72, has
in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just reaches out to people,'' Monod said. ``He always wants
to help people whenever he can.''
</P>
<P>
   That openness may have helped cause the crisis. Several
employees described Flores' open-door policy in which people
sometimes could literally walk off the street and knock on his door
unquestioned. That policy has led to some debate in the past, said
David Garza, rector of the San Fernando Cathedral in San Antonio
and a long-time friend of Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's extremely accessible, which is something people have
criticized him for,'' Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   Flores has devoted his ministry to helping the poor,
particularly reaching out to Latin American refugees, immigrants
and Americans of Mexican heritage. The archdiocese freely welcomes
illegal immigrants, many of whom make San Antonio their first stop
after crossing the southern Mexico-Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio churches help them with food, water, and clothes.
Some move on to other cities, but many decide to stay because of
the large Hispanic culture and the array of ministries to help them
get on their feet offered through the archdiocese and its churches.
In many ways, the archdiocese is an international sea of Latinos _
helping people from El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras, and a host of
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Fernando Cathedral, the archbishop's home church,
about 175 parishioners erupted with shouts of joy shortly after the
7 p.m. Mass began.
</P>
<P>
   Archdiocesan officials received word about two minutes into the
service that the archbishop had been released unharmed. For them
the release was a statement on the power of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it with God's help,'' said church member Janie Cauazos.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Wednesday, hundreds of people visited the
cathedral for prayer, church officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Other churches in the area also scheduled special prayer
services Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Following the service at the cathedral, parishioners once again
began clapping, cheering, hugging and crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the Lord would take care of him,'' said worshipper
Eloise Cortez. ``All of San Antonio and the U.S. and world were
praying for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
