<SLUG> BC-GLADIATOR-DEMOCRATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEMOCRATS LOOK TO FILMS FOR INSPIRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority
leader, has an unusual motivational tool for his rank and file: the
magic of the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Girding for Wednesday's showdown on the House floor over a
Republican-sponsored bill to expand Medicare coverage to include
prescription drugs, Gephardt showed Democrats clips this week from
the films ``Gladiator'' and ``Apollo 13'' to rouse his troops to
fight together against the Republican legislation. Ultimately,
however, the Republicans prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Tuesday of the 211 House Democrats, Gephardt dimmed
the lights in a Capitol conference room and rolled a scene from
``Gladiator'' in which a band of warriors led by the film's hero,
played by Russell Crowe, prepares to battle better-armed gladiators
in the Colosseum. (Subtext: The House Democrats are the underdogs;
the Republicans are the evil gladiators, Democratic aides said.)
</P>
<P>
   In the part of the film viewed by the Democrats, Maximus, the
hero, implores his men to fight with him and says, ``Whatever comes
out of these gates, we have a better chance of survival if we stick
together.'' When the underdogs win, the room full of Democrats
burst in wild cheers and applause, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gephardt showed Democrats a clip from ``Apollo 13''
that includes the line, ``Failure is not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Gephardt has used movie clips to rev
up the minority. Last August, he showed Democrats a clip from
``Braveheart'' before the summer recess as part of Democrats'
strategy to fight for more teachers. They won that fight, though
their ``Gladiator''-inspired effort against the Republicans'
Medicare legislation was much more of an uphill battle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2320EDT &QL; 
