A7892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-MISSILE-NYT &LR;      06-28 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MISSILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE PROPONENTS URGE CLINTON TO DELAY ANTI-MISSILE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A group of more than 40 U.S. scholars on China and
former diplomats is urging President Clinton to delay a decision on
whether to build a national missile defense, arguing that the
proposed system may do more harm than good to American economic and
military interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that a precipitous decision to deploy would
adversely affect U.S. relations with China,'' the group says in a
letter to be issued on Thursday, ``by unnecessarily increasing
tensions between the two countries and provoking a series of
negative steps by China that would undermine American security.''
</P>
<P>
   Those signing the letter, which was to be delivered to the White
House, include an ambassador to China under President Ronald Reagan
as well as China specialists from around the country. Signatures
were gathered by the Council for a Livable World, a private group
in Washington that lobbies for nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Strong political momentum has gathered for construction of a
limited missile defense system intended to protect against a
missile attacks from rogue states like North Korea or Iraq. Clinton
is supposed to decide this summer, after a key test on July 7,
whether to begin construction of radars in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   But many foreign policy experts, scientists and former security
officials have questioned the plan on technical or strategic
grounds, and it has been strongly opposed by Russia, China and even
American allies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that the plan will raise the stakes in the arms
race by stimulating the Chinese and others to make more missiles,''
said one signer of the letter, Arthur Hummel Jr., who was
ambassador to China from 1981 to 1985. ``Second, I have grave
doubts about whether it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a silmilar plea for delaying the
anti-missile program came from a group of former top officials,
including retired Gen. John Shalikashvili, who was chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff; former Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, who had
served as chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee; and
William Perry, a former defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed system, the first stage of which involves 100
missile interceptors based in Alaska, would violate the
Antiballistic Missile Treaty signed with the Soviet Union in 1972.
The administration has tried, without success, to persuade Russia
to agree to treaty revisions, arguing that limited defenses would
not undermine the value of Russia's large nuclear forces.
</P>
<P>
   But China's objections run deeper. Officials here say that in a
showdown with the United States, the deterrent effect of China's
small nuclear force, which includes perhaps 20 long-range missiles,
would be vitiated by the American plan. Officials warn that China
will be forced to build far more missiles or develop decoy
measures, and say the U.S. plan will set off a global arms race.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials respond that China plans to improve its missile
forces anyway, and that the proposed defenses are not intended to
offset Chinese power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
