u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     06-28 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDIAN PAYS $300 MILLION TO CUSTOMERS
</P>
<P>
   Providian Financial, the nation's seventh-largest issuer of
credit cards, agreed to a demand from bank regulators to reimburse
its customers at least $300 million for misleading and improperly
billing them.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 million of Providian's 13 million customers are likely
to receive reimbursement checks later this year. Consumer advocates
said the $300 million in restitution was one of the largest they
knew of in a case involving consumer deception.
</P>
<P>
   GANNETT BUYS CENTRAL NEWSPAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, whose stable of newspapers is already the largest in
the country, agreed to acquire Central Newspapers, the owner of The
Arizona Republic, The Indianapolis Star and four other daily
newspapers, for $2.6 billion in cash. The deal is the second
largest in newspaper history, behind the Tribune Co.'s acquisition
of the Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   TYCO BUYS MALLINCKRODT
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International agreed to buy Mallinckrodt, a health care
company, for $3.24 billion in stock. Tyco said it would also assume
nearly $1 billion in Mallinckrodt debt. With the acquisition of
Mallinckrodt, Tyco's health care business would become the leader
in bulk analgesic pharmaceuticals and a leader in the fast-growing
respiratory care business. Shares of Mallinckrodt rose $2.59375, to
$31.34375. Tyco fell $2.3125, to $45.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY SHARES RALLY
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index jumped 81.38 points, or 2.1 percent,
to 3,940.34. The Dow Jones industrial average edged up 23.33
points, to 10,527.79. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed
4.27 points, to 1,454.82.
</P>
<P>
   RUMORS FOR WORLDCOM AND SPRINT
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint have not yet called off their proposed
merger, but already rumors are swirling about which companies might
try to buy one of them.
</P>
<P>
   FEDEX PROFIT BEATS EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   FedEx said its fourth-quarter profit rose 11 percent, to $245
million, or 85 cents a share, compared with $221 million, or 73
cents a share, in the period a year earlier, on a rebound in United
States shipments. Analysts had expected 81 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN INVESTORS PETITION KREMLIN
</P>
<P>
   A battle over Unified Energy Systems, Russia's electricity
monopoly, intensified after a group of foreign investors who oppose
a plan to overhaul the company took their case to the Kremlin.
Investors representing about 15 percent of the company's stock met
with Aleksandr Voloshin, above, the Kremlin chief of staff who is
also chairman of Unified Energy's board. The meeting came a week
after investors asked President Vladimir Putin to stop the
reorganization plan, which they say would destroy the value of
their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN FOR AN INTERNET ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   Public interest groups announced a voter registration campaign
to recruit what it called cybercitizens and raise public awareness
of an international election to help administer the Internet. The
campaign urges Internet users to join the Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers, which was selected in 1998 to take over
administration of the network's domain name system.
</P>
<P>
   2 MODELS FOR PREDICTING ELECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Economics now offers two distinct approaches to predicting
election outcomes. One has its roots in macroeconomics, examining
how national economic performance affects voting. The other is
grounded in microeconomics, using a real financial market in which
participants can place their bets on the results. Hal R. Varian:
Economic Scene.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
