<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL BLINK FIRST, THE YANKS OR CUBS?
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ If the Sammy Sosa deal is going to be finished,
somebody is going to have to give it a good shove. Maybe that will
be George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, who is eager
to make a big deal. Maybe it will be the Cubs, faced with the
possibility that the Yankees' current offer might be the best they
can get.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs executives are waiting for the Yankees to cave in to their
demands. Yankee executives are weighing the huge cost, in prospects
and dollars, of acquiring Sosa, and are exploring other modest
improvements, like trading for Oakland's John Jaha or San Diego's
Ed Sprague. The stalemate continues.
</P>
<P>
   According to a person with knowledge of the trade talks, this is
the Yankees' current four-player offer: the Cubs will receive the
Double-A outfielder Jackson Melian, the Triple-A pitcher Jake
Westbrook, outfielder Ricky Ledee and a choice of two minor league
infielders _ either Alfonso Soriano, who is one of the Yankees' top
prospects, or D'Angelo Jimenez, a touted infielder who has been out
all year after breaking a bone in his neck in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs want more; they want five players. They want Melian,
Ledee, Westbrook and both Soriano and Jimenez, or one of those two
and pitcher Alex Graman, a 22-year-old left-hander with Single-A
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been pretty much there all week, and they are at an
impasse,'' said a person with knowledge of the talks. ``But sides
appear to be pretty well entrenched. Nothing has changed these last
couple of days. There has been no progress. It doesn't look like
there's going to be any change.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, is said to be very
reluctant to surrender such a significant package of prospects,
knowing that the cost will be double edged. The Yankees will have
to give Sosa a four- or five-year extension for something in the
range of $17 million to $20 million a year, and in addition, the
Yankees would suffer for all the low-priced talent they would give
away. Soriano, Melian, Westbrook and the others could serve the
Yankees for the next half-decade for bargain basement salaries, and
the Yankees might have to acquire older, more expensive players
instead.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees are looking at other ways to improve and keep
their prospects. They know they need pitching, like Francisco
Cordova or Jose Silva of the Pirates, or the Rangers' Esteban
Loaiza, with Ramiro Mendoza and Roger Clemens currently on the
disabled list and little talent ready for the major leagues at
Triple-A Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have had fruitless talks with the Baltimore Orioles
about B.J. Surhoff so far. The Orioles have asked for Ledee and
Melian, but the Yankees have had more promising discussions with
the Athletics about the 34-year-old Jaha and with the Padres about
Sprague, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Jaha hit 35 homers for Oakland last year, but he has been
battling injuries this season and only recently has returned to the
lineup, batting .178 with 1 homer in 26 games before last night.
Jaha is adept at working the count and drawing walks. Even with his
low batting average, he has accumulated a .429 on-base percentage,
and is averaging 4.72 pitches per plate appearance, at a time when
3.7 pitches per plate appearance is considered average.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, which is loaded with first base/designated hitter types
like Jaha, has talked with the Boston Red Sox about the slugger as
well. The Yankees could probably get Jaha for a good, but not
great, prospect or a serviceable relief pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague was hitting .274 with 10 homers in 117 at-bats before
last night's game for the Padres, who have been devastated by
injuries and are looking to trade the veterans for young players.
He hit 22 homers last year, and has 8 homers in 74 at-bats this
year against left-handed pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could use Jaha or Sprague against lefties, mix one
of them in at first base and DH, the way they wanted to do with Jim
Leyritz before it became clear that Leyritz's diminished bat speed
rendered him ineffective early in the season. The Yankees would
like to acquire Jaha or Sprague, regardless of whether they make
the Sosa deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' losses keep mounting, however: 26 defeats in the
last 41 games, a 37-35 record over all. ``The only thing that's
helping us,'' David Cone said after Tuesday's 7-6 defeat, ``is that
there is consistent mediocrity in the division. That's what is
keeping us in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, executives say, is angrily pressuring Cashman to
make a big deal. The Cubs, on the other hand, do not appear to have
much of a market for Sosa, with few teams willing to dump a
truckload of prospects and then have enough money to negotiate a
new deal with Sosa, who can veto any trade possibility.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a nudge from either side, the deal can be finished,
Sosa would be in pinstripes and Ledee would face the unhappy fans
in Wrigley Field. But that nudge is required. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
