<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MOVES TOWARD DISLOSURE REQUIREMENTS FOR NONPROFIT GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress moved decisively on Wednesday toward
enacting the first major change in the nation's campaign finance
law since 1979, closing a loophole through which millions of
dollars have secretly flowed. President Clinton strongly supports
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday morning, the House overwhelmingly approved
bipartisan legislation to require a growing number of shadowy
tax-exempt groups that raise and spend money on political advocacy
to disclose their activities and donors. The vote was 385-39.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders who had fought the measure conceded
that the Senate would approve the House bill. After a brief debate
Wednesday night, a final Senate vote was scheduled for Thursday.
The outcome is not in doubt. Three weeks ago, the Senate passed
virtually the same measure, 57-42. ``This will pass
overwhelmingly,'' said one senior Senate Republican aide.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the last 24 hours were a major victory for Sen.
John McCain, R.-Ariz, who made overhauling campaign finance law a
centerpiece of his failed presidential bid this year, and his
bipartisan allies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But their bill to constrain the undisclosed political activities
of nonprofit groups is far less comprehensive than the legislation
to overhaul the election laws that McCain has tried to push through
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote represented a stern rebuke to House and Senate
Republican leaders who had tried to kill the measure by offering a
much broader bill, only to see that effort backfire. By clamping
down only on the tax-exempt groups, the leaders hope to dilute
support for more extensive measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a remarkable first step, but I don't think
anyone is expecting a major bill beyond it this year,'' said Larry
Makinson, executive director of the nonpartisan Center for
Responsive Politics, which tracks money in politics. ``There will
be calls for stronger reform, but not until 2001, after the
excesses we're sure to see this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin T. Meehan, D-Mass., and Christopher Shays, R-Conn.,
told reporters that they would continue their fight for broader
campaign finance legislation to restrict issue advertisements and
ban unregulated donations called soft money. ``We're not going to
let this go,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are scores of tax-exempt groups formed under Section
527 of the Internal Revenue Code. These groups raise money for
polling, advertising and other political activities but do not have
to disclose contributors, as long as they do not back candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The committees span the political spectrum. One group,
Republicans for Clean Air, ran $2.5 million in advertisements
attacking McCain and praising Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in the
Republican primaries. Liberal groups, like the Sierra Club, also
have Section 527 committees.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed by the House and before the Senate would
require the 527 political groups with annual gross receipts of more
than $25,000 to follow federal campaign law and file tax returns.
They would have to disclose contributors who gave more than $200
and report expenditures of more than $500. A violator would face a
35 percent tax on all contributions and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The groups would have to report their donors and spending to the
IRS every three months in an election year. The information would
be posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Senate endorsed the measure sponsored by McCain and
Senator Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., Senate and House Republicans
have tried to dilute its impact by offering a competing bill
expanding disclosure requirements to labor unions, business groups
and trade associations.
</P>
<P>
   But critics complained that this approach was overly punitive
toward the unions, while letting corporations off the hook. In
recent days, traditional Republicans allies like the Christian
Coalition and National Right to Life Committee balked at the
disclosure requirements, and House Republican leaders relented.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to be perceived as backing up their support for
disclosure, all senior House Republicans except the House majority
whip, Tom DeLay of Texas, who is closely allied with a 527
organization, joined this morning's lopsided vote in favor.
</P>
<P>
   After that show of strength, top Senate Republicans were in no
mood on Wednesday to block the popular measure. ``Senator Lott is
not putting his body on those railroad tracks,'' said John
Czwartacki, spokesman for Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the two presumptive presidential nominees, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore, applauded the
House vote and urged Senate passage.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Congress moved to close one area of campaign abuses,
lawyers and other campaign finance experts predicted that the 527
committees would receive a flood of donations before the law took
effect. They also said it was likely that many groups would try to
change to another nonprofit status to avoid the disclosure
requirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
