<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON UNAPOLOGETIC ABOUT ADS ATTACKING LAZIO IN SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton defended her two-week-long
wave of attacks on Rep. Rick Lazio Wednesday, asserting that she
was simply trying to highlight contrasts between the two candidates
for Senate, and disputing Lazio's contention that she was
orchestrating a campaign based on fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the congressman has anything to fear from me; I
think the only thing he has to fear is his own record,'' Clinton
said, emerging from an hour of mostly gentle questioning on ``The
Early Show'' on CBS. ``I'm going to keep on demonstrating as
clearly as I can to New Yorkers what his record is, what his
positions have been, and how many times he has voted against the
interests of New York. I think that's information that the voters
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that she had no apologies for either the remarks
she had made about Lazio in speeches and news conferences, or the
five advertisements her campaign has run attacking his record.
Though it is unusual for a candidate in the early stages of a
campaign to begin attacking an opponent, particularly with
television ads, in this case, it reflects an attempt by Clinton to
use selected votes by Lazio to present him as more conservative
than most voters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns are about information,'' Clinton told Bryant Gumbel
on the program, broadcast from the CBS affiliate in Syracuse. ``I
don't think giving information is negative; I think it's
informative. From my perspective, there's going to be a lot of
contrast in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the theme at a news conference after her television
appearance, Clinton said: ``Part of my campaign is to draw
contrasts between me and my opponent. Because I believe the people
upstate and the people in the rest of the state deserve to know
where we stand on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's summertime, and we've only got, what, four months left
before the election,'' she said. ``I have run for nearly a year
against another opponent. And I have a new opponent, and it's a new
campaign. And there are some people who say, you know, he's a more
traditional Republican opponent and there are many differences
between us on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks were in response to Lazio's assertion that she
was distorting his views with advertisements highlighting votes he
had cast, for example, against Democratic legislation that would
allow patients to sue their HMOs. Lazio complained that the
advertisements were ``about fear'' and predicted they would stir
distrust of her among New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's spokesman, Dan McLagan, described Clinton's remarks as
``a smoke screen to hide the fact that she has no record whatsoever
of ever lifting a finger for New York or New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange between the two candidates over campaign tactics _
there was little talk of policy differences Wednesday _ comes at a
time when Clinton has been making a concerted effort to raise
questions about Lazio's political views and credentials. There has
been no evidence, in the form of polls, to suggest what effect, if
any, of Clinton's attacks .
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even some of Lazio's supporters said that the
attacks appeared to have put him off-balance and forced him to
devote time to dealing with them rather than laying the foundation
of his campaign. And Clinton left no doubt Wednesday that she would
continue a line of attack that her aides have concluded is
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are real differences,'' she said. ``I am not calling him
names, or engaging in the kind of activities that I don't approve
of. That's not the kind of campaign I'm running.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-00 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000628.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7909 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DRUGS-MEDICARE-1STLD-     06-28 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-MEDICARE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AGREES TO REPUBLICANS' PRESCRIPTION PLAN FOR ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Inserts list specifying 5 Democrats voting for and 10
Republicans voting against bill in bottom 2 grafs) By ROBERT
PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House passed a bill Wednesday offering
prescription drug benefits to 39 million elderly and disabled
people on Medicare, but only after a day of pitched battle in which
frustrated Democrats walked off the House floor at one point.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was passed by a vote of 217-214, with five Democrats
voting for the measure and 10 Republicans voting against it. Though
the bill would expand Medicare more than any other measure passed
in the 35-year history of the program by offering coverage for drug
costs to all beneficiaries, it now goes to the Senate, where its
fate is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote came at the end of a day of high drama and
political high jinks as each party tried to outdo the other in
proving its zealous commitment to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they championed a major extension of Medicare coverage,
Republicans found themselves on the defensive throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing the Republican bill as a sham, a hoax, bad medicine
and a risky scheme that would ``privatize'' Medicare, the
Democratic minority used a variety of parliamentary and procedural
tactics to delay the work of the House. The Democrats also
expressed their frustration at being unable to get a full debate on
their proposal to establish much more extensive drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans shot back that the Democrats were throwing temper
tantrums and were engaged in political grandstanding, stunts and
shenanigans to scare the elderly and win votes in this fall's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said, ``Democrats are
standing in the way of progress.'' President Clinton threatened to
veto the House Republican bill, which he denounced as an empty
promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts special interests above the public interest,'' Clinton
said at a White House news conference Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican bill, the government would pay subsidies to
insurance companies to encourage them to offer a product that does
not now exist: insurance policies covering drug costs of the
elderly and disabled. The policies would not cover any other
medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats strongly support Medicare drug benefits, but want a
larger role for the government and a smaller role for the insurance
industry. Under the Democratic bill, premiums and benefits would be
the same for virtually all beneficiaries in all parts of the
country. Under the Republican plan, the government would describe a
model or standard policy, but premiums, benefits and co-payments
could vary from one private drug plan to another, so long as the
overall value was equivalent to that of the model policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan appears to be more generous than the
Republicans' standard policy. Monthly premiums would be $25,
compared with $37, there would be no deductible and the
beneficiary's maximum out-of-pocket costs would be $4,000 a year,
compared with $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, Medicare generally does not cover drug costs
for people outside the hospital. One-third of Medicare
beneficiaries have no insurance to help pay such costs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans won a majority of the elderly vote in elections for
the House two years ago, and Democrats see the prescription drug
issue as an opportunity to regain their advantage with the elderly,
and their majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., criticized the Republican measure,
saying: ``This bill does not provide prescription drug coverage to
senior citizens. It provides political cover for Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last week rejected the Democratic approach to
Medicare drug benefits when it came up suddenly and unexpectedly on
the floor. The Senate Finance Committee is working on drug
legislation and may vote on it soon.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the House Rules Committee at 2:30 a.m.
Wednesday, Republicans set highly restrictive rules for floor
debate later in the day. The rules were narrowly approved in the
full House on a largely party-line vote of 216-213.
</P>
<P>
   The rules allowed the Democrats only 10 minutes at the end of
the day to propose an alternative to the House Republican bill.
Democrats wanted to offer a measure costing $100 billion over five
years, but House Republican leaders insisted that the Democrats
could not offer anything costing more than $40 billion, the cost of
the Republican bill.
</P>
<P>
   To show their displeasure, Democrats forced the House to take
nine roll-call votes before the House even began debating the
substance of the Republican bill.
</P>
<P>
   Just before final passage of the Republican bill, the House
Wednesday night rejected a scaled-down version of President
Clinton's plan to offer drug benefits through Medicare. The vote on
the measure, which came in under the $40 billion limit set in the
rules, was 222-204.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the day's political in-fighting, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the
Republican whip, said, ``The Democrats have been planning this
circus for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Deborah Pryce, R-Ohio, said: ``The Democrats are throwing a
temper tantrum to divert attention from the merits of our bill. In
walking out of the House today, they walked out on America's
seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   After marching out, Democrats held a news conference on the east
steps of the Capitol, then returned to the House floor a half-hour
later.
</P>
<P>
   The AARP, formerly known as the American Association of Retired
Persons, did not endorse or oppose either bill.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Congress, Horace Deets, the group's executive
director, said, ``We are pleased that both the House Republican and
Democratic bills include a voluntary prescription drug benefit in
Medicare _ a benefit to which every Medicare beneficiary is
entitled.'' But Deets expressed concern that ``many beneficiaries
may elect not to participate'' in the Republican plan. People with
low drug costs may not view it as a ``good buy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Senior Citizens Law Center, which represents many
Medicare recipients, opposed the House Republican bill, saying
subsidies would be ``grossly inadequate'' for many of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House Republican plan, a widow with income of $13,000
a year and drug expenses of $4,800 a year would have to spend
nearly one-third of her income on drugs and insurance if she bought
the standard coverage. She would have to pay $4,194, or 87 percent
of her drug costs, out of her own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In this example, the widow would pay $37 a month, or $444 a
year, in premiums, plus the $250 deductible and half of the next
$2,100 in drug expenses, or $1,050. The insurance policy would pay
the other half. The beneficiary would have to pay the remainder of
her drug expenses, $2,450.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their bill was superior to the Democrats'
because it would let elderly people buy policies tailored to their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, the Texas Republican who is chairman of the
Ways and Means Committee, said: ``Democrats offer no choice to
seniors. They offer only a single government-run plan. Seniors will
have to take it or leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Rick Lazio, R-New York, said: ``Our bill will improve
the lives of millions of Americans. It relies on a public-private
partnership model that has proven successful in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader,
said: ``Instead of making prescriptions more affordable for all
seniors, the Republican bill hands a huge subsidy to the insurance
industry. Republicans are forcing seniors to deal with private
insurance companies, which have said they will not offer
prescription coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats repeatedly quoted Charles Kahn III, president of the
Health Insurance Association of America, who has said his members
are not interested in selling drug insurance of the type envisioned
in the House Republican bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tammy Baldwin, D-Wis., said the Republican bill ``throws
money at special interests and allows pharmaceutical companies to
continue price-gouging.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans countered that their bill, by pooling the
purchasing power of older Americans, would allow them to get
discounts of 25 percent off retail drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who voted for the bill on final passage were Reps.
Ralph Hall of Texas, Jim Maloney of Connecticut, Matthew Martinez
of California, Collin Peterson of Minnesota and James Traficant Jr.
of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 Republicans who voted against the bill were Reps. Helen
Chenoweth-Hage of Idaho, Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, Greg Ganske of
Iowa, John Hostettler of Indiana, Ernest Istook of Oklahoma,
Constance Morella of Maryland, Ron Paul of Texas, Mark Sanford of
South Carolina, Bob Schaffer of Colorado and Nick Smith of
Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
